<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOTCOM-ADS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: FEW ADS FOR ONLINE RETAILERS ARE AIMED AT MAINSTREAM
USERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON BARNHART  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) At a time when Y2K looms smaller by the day, it looks
as if the really big deal will be 1999.com.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers that sell on the Internet _ or dot-coms, to use the
imprecise shorthand _ have lately been all over your television
dial: Egghead.com, Toys.com, Monster.com, DSports.com, Ditech.com
and 800.com, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   And, like Santa's elves, they've been busily creating almost a
subgenre of television advertising _ a recognizable,
loaded-with-attitude blizzard of pitches, the most notable of which
may be the 30-second messages from our friends at Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe what you hear in the business media, these
dot-coms are part of the new economy of e-commerce. Soon, we are
told, all of America will be shopping on the Internet. Whether it's
for cat food, computers, stocks, a new job, DVDs, BVDs ... if
you're not buying these things on the Web by now, it's easy to feel
as if you're the only one who is not.
</P>
<P>
   That's a myth, of course _ plenty of shoppers are still crowding
the malls, spurred on by tradition and mild weather. But the
dot-coms are spending furiously on advertising to make you think
otherwise. By the end of 1999.com, these companies will have
shelled out $2 billion on television advertising, or 15 times what
they spent last year, according to PaineWebber Group.
</P>
<P>
   And on Sunday, Jeff Bezos, the Amazon.com founder whose company
_ while losing millions of dollars _ has helped foster the
point-and-click revolution that is changing the way Americans shop,
was named Time magazine's person of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever a dot-com chief executive makes an appearances on one
of those financial talk shows, the interviewer always asks about
the company's marketing strategy, or the ``growth potential'' for
the next quarter, or what dot-com his or her dot-com is going to
acquire. But never does anyone ask the basic existential questions
a lot of us would like to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Namely: Why is this company in business? And why should we care?
</P>
<P>
   Dot-coms never give us answers to such obvious questions. In
their TV advertising, they give us comedy routines instead.
</P>
<P>
   One current commercial shows a guy dropping his cellular phone
into a urinal while he's, uh, multitasking. Then we're told you can
buy a hands-free cellular phone online. (OK, but what if you're not
an idiot?)
</P>
<P>
   Outpost.com, a computer and software store, uses even less
subtlety in its ad, which made its million-dollar debut in the
Super Bowl. A well-dressed man sits in a comfortable chair and
explains that the company thought the best way to get viewers'
attention would be to show a marching band being hunted down by
jackals. With that, we cut to a few seconds of something that looks
sort of like the promised melee.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes. Bob Newhart plays a nervous company chief
mailing out recall notices with Stamps.com. Wacky product testers
try out wacky products for Gifts.com. Something called a ``fogdog''
howls at the end of the ads for Fogdog.com. (Here's a quiz for you
couch potatoes: What does Fogdog sell?)
</P>
<P>
   The use of edgy humor and the nearly nonexistent sales pitch has
defined dot-com ads in 1999. But once everyone starts using the
same approach, its distinctiveness vanishes, as does viewer recall.
(Answer to above pop quiz: Sporting goods.)
</P>
<P>
   That is why Amazon.com's spirited and joyfully retro holiday ad
campaign is such a revelation. Instant classics when they hit the
airwaves last month, the Amazon ads sing their way into viewers'
hearts and carry with them a powerfully simple message.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon, a veritable granddaddy among Internet companies, created
five 30-second spots based on the TV variety shows of days gone by.
In their use of color, wardrobe, casting and music, these ads look
and feel as if they came right out of a time capsule buried in the
Kennedy administration.
</P>
<P>
   We watch an all-men's chorus, decked out in sweater vests,
cheerfully belting out tunes to a bouncy polka beat. The lyrics are
flashed on the bottom of the screen in primitive TV letters. All
that's missing is Mitch Miller.
</P>
<P>
   And what songs they sing:
</P>
<P>
   I spent two minutes
</P>
<P>
   Two whole minutes
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes shopping for your gift
</P>
<P>
   And it was so pleasant
</P>
<P>
   Getting credit for a present
</P>
<P>
   That was really super easy to give
</P>
<P>
   The commercials are mesmerizing. The songs are hilarious, with
enough squaresville in them to stand apart from the rest of the
dot-com pack.
</P>
<P>
   (Another song, extolling the joys of being done with Christmas
shopping, includes the lines, ``Nothing else to do today//But worry
about Y2K//Soaking in a bubble bath//With 15 days to go.'')
</P>
<P>
   Amazon chose this campaign because it appealed to audiences of
all ages and because it invoked an earlier time when _ true or not
_ people seemed to be less hassled during the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think shopping online is becoming a new tradition,''
explained an Amazon spokesman. ``It saves time, and you have more
time to do things that the holidays are traditionally all about.''
</P>
<P>
   The Amazon campaign assumes that viewers are intimidated by
online shopping. To these people, Amazon offers an oddly comforting
incentive: Shop with us and you'll be offline in no time. Just two
minutes, two whole minutes, and you're done, the phone line is
free, and you're in the next room styling homemade Christmas cards
with glitter and glue.
</P>
<P>
   No one doubts that eventually e-commerce is going to be, as
William Shatner tells us in those Priceline.com ads, ``big, really
big.'' But it isn't now. According to figures from Jupiter
Communications, a research firm specializing in e-commerce,
consumers will spend $6 billion online this holiday season, a
fraction of their offline purchases. Four out of five persons who
have Internet access won't go near an online mall this season.
</P>
<P>
   Far from changing these consumer attitudes, the rash of
look-alike dot-com ads may have the opposite effect. With their
sneering, hipper-than-thou approach, they make the Internet seem as
cluttered and uninviting as ever to mainstream users. With Amazon
as the notable exception, it's hard to see how the dot-coms will
have much to show in January for their holiday spending spree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
