<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWHAMPSHIRE-DECISIONS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL STATE'S DECISIONS LOOM LARGE ON POLITICAL LANDSCAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ Inside Poor Pierre's Restaurant on Main Street,
the coffee is steaming hot, the windows are fogged from the
December chill and the little boxes of cornflakes behind the
counter are stacked in a neat pile.
</P>
<P>
   The political landscape, however, in this presidential
bellwether state is not quite so orderly.
</P>
<P>
   With almost six weeks to go before New Hampshire holds its
first-in-the-nation presidential primary, front-runners have become
underdogs and yesterday's underdogs now lead the pack. But that's
in keeping with New Hampshire voters' rich tradition of rattling
front-runners and winnowing the political field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's so much that we like to knock off
front-runners,'' said Don Mayo, a Nashua insurance agent, as he
buttered a grilled blueberry muffin. ``New Hampshire voters may be
more selective as to who they believe to be the best.''
</P>
<P>
   For so small a state, New Hampshire voters exercise an influence
far greater than political logic dictates. For instance, California
is bigger and more diverse politically, ethnically and economically
_ a much more accurate microcosm of America. But candidates often
don't get farther west than the Vermont border if they can't
survive New Hampshire's scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Its voters have always been conservative, but probably are less
so lately because of the influx of younger, better-educated and
more-affluent families to the bedroom communities in the south,
near the Massachusetts high-tech corridor.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, recent surveys have shown that more registered
Republicans who plan to vote in the primary are moderates rather
than conservatives on issues such as gun control, abortion and
campaign-finance reform. Polls also show that independents, the
largest voting bloc at about 37 percent, may split evenly this time
among Democratic and Republican candidates; in 1996, Democrats
captured only about a third.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the voters have long been romanced as flinty and
independent.
</P>
<P>
   The reality probably is that New Hampshire voters just pay
closer attention. ``We're immersed in it,'' said Kathy Sullivan,
the state's Democratic chairwoman. ``We've been living with it for
months, and the intensity keeps increasing.''
</P>
<P>
   They have a history of thumping the front-runner, the way they
did to then-Sen. Bob Dole in 1996 when they awarded the state to
GOP rival Pat Buchanan, and to Democrat Walter Mondale in 1984 when
they gave the nod to Gary Hart.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting President Lyndon Johnson got fewer votes than expected
in 1968, and later chose not to seek re-election. The state also
proved fatal to the efforts of top contenders Edmund Muskie in 1972
and Paul Tsongas in 1992. And they even won the state's primary.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, George McGovern, with 35 percent of the Democratic vote,
was all set to give a concession speech on primary night in 1972
until his aides convinced him that Muskie's 44-percent victory did
not meet expectations. Muskie was soon out, and the little-known
McGovern went on to win the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing can still be winning if you make it a close second and
exceed expectations,'' said Dante Scala, who teaches politics at
St. Anselm College in Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   Decisive political moments are a staple in New Hampshire too.
Muskie's notorious tear on the cheek (or was it a snowflake?),
Dole's snappish retort to President Bush in 1988 to ``quit lying
about my record'' and Gennifer Flowers' public declaration of an
affair with Bill Clinton all occurred there.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many front-runners have limped out of New Hampshire to
oblivion,'' said Dave Carney, a Republican strategist from the
state who worked for Dole, the 1996 GOP nominee. ``The momentum in
a campaign can change overnight. It can change drastically and can
change dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Democratic contenders Vice President Al Gore and
former Sen. Bill Bradley are trading the lead back and forth. Among
the Republicans, Sen. John McCain of Arizona has surged ahead of
Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly a week goes by without a motorcade rolling through some
town. And there are rallies, town meetings and makeshift parades as
candidates and their entourages sweep into town and crowd into
diners and Dunkin' Donuts to talk to voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Primary,'' said a retired man at the counter at Poor Pierre's.
``It's spelled C-I-R-C-U-S.''
</P>
<P>
   It also doesn't take a game of six degrees of separation to find
someone _ it may be a relative or a neighbor _ who has been called
by a presidential candidate, his campaign or a pollster.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Lajoie, a Nashua electrician, said he had been asked in
1992 by the local Democrats to work for then-Gov. Bill Clinton of
Arkansas. ``I said I wouldn't work for anybody unless I met him
face to face,'' said Lajoie, a coffee cup in one hand, an unlighted
Marlboro in the other.
</P>
<P>
   So he met Clinton at the local Holiday Inn, agreed to help his
campaign and has gotten a Christmas card from him every year since.
</P>
<P>
   While the closest encounter most Americans have with a
presidential candidate is seeing him on television, about 30
percent of New Hampshire's voters meet one face to face for more
than five minutes. That's what Dayton Duncan, who wrote a book
about the 1988 presidential primary, found based on his experience
as a press aide to Democratic then-nominee Michael Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   ``That 30 percent is just phenomenal,'' said Duncan, who lives
in New Hampshire. ``That simply doesn't happen anyplace else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
