<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAHAWKS-BRONCOS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS AT A LOSS TO EXPLAIN LATEST COLLAPSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The pain of the Seahawks' latest loss was evident in
the way Sean Dawkins buried his face in his hands as he sat
silently in front of his locker.
</P>
<P>
   The frustration of the team's fourth loss in a row was obvious
as Jon Kitna fought back tears as he tried to explain how the
Seahawks had rallied to score 10 points in the final 1 minute, 47
seconds of regulation only to lose on a bizarre play in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The utter disgust of watching Broncos linebacker Glenn Cadrez
return a fumble 37 yards to give Denver a 36-30 victory was
apparent from the sour looks that covered the faces of several
players as they tried to explain how the Seahawks had found yet
another way to let yet another game slip away.
</P>
<P>
   What was a once seemingly insurmountable three-game lead in the
AFC West is now a one-game deficit, as the Seahawks prepare for
what they have been talking about during their month of losses _ a
matchup next week against the division-leading Kansas City Chiefs
in the Kingdome that has become the equivalent of a playoff game of
the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   The 8-6 Seahawks still can win the division if they beat the 9-5
Chiefs on Sunday and then beat the New York Jets on the road on
Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our playoffs have started,'' Kitna said. ``We've been asking
for a playoff game around here for 10 years. Our playoffs have
started. It's do-or-die. When the playoffs come around, it's all
about survival. We're in the playoffs now. So it's about survival
and whatever it takes to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the Chiefs have helped the Seahawks fritter away
their three-game lead by winning four in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Going down ...
</P>
<P>
   Second floor, er, place: Blown opportunities. Massive
misfortune. Dropped passes. Missed tackles. Self-doubt.
Second-guessing. And an wide array of wouldas, couldas and
shouldas.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Seahawks can even entertain realistic thoughts of
beating the Chiefs, they must find a way to stop their fall down an
elevator shaft.
</P>
<P>
   It was no different Sunday, on a bitterly cold afternoon at Mile
High Stadium where the wind-chill was 10 degrees at kickoff and
closer to zero by the time the 3 hour, 28 minute game had ended.
</P>
<P>
   The defense allowed season-highs of 36 points and 430 yards _
including 260 yards rushing that was their worst performance by 93
yards; 183 of those by Broncos rookie Olandis Gary.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna lost two fumbles that led to nine points by the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   The special teams got the snowball rolling in the wrong
direction by allowing Broncos rookie Chris Watson to return the
game's first punt 81 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   And everyone, it seemed, contributed to the Seahawks being
penalized 12 times for 118 wrong-way yards _ both season highs. Or
is that lows?
</P>
<P>
   In looking for a quick-fix that can stem this self-destructive
tidal wave before the Chiefs show up for the showdown, where do the
Seahawks even begin?
</P>
<P>
   As guard Brian Habib said, ``It's not one specific thing. It's
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Seahawks took losing to a new, historic level. This
was only the second overtime game in NFL annals to end on a fumble
return for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the hardest way to lose, probably,'' Kitna said. ``We
still control our own destiny _ and that's a good thing. But until
we learn how to win games, that doesn't do us any good.''
</P>
<P>
   For two never-say-die minutes Sunday, it appeared the Seahawks
had remembered how to win _ and how to make the plays they were
routinely making during their five-game winning streak that staked
them to that three-game lead in the division.
</P>
<P>
   After Kitna found Derrick Mayes with a 36-yard touchdown pass
with 54 seconds remaining to cut the Broncos' lead to 30-27, the
Seahawks executed a text-book on-side kick. Todd Peterson topped
the ensuing kickoff and safety Kerry Joseph made a leaping grab of
the ball just as it had traveled the required 10 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph's look-what-I-found play gave the Seahawks the ball at
the Seattle 42-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna then found Dawkins with a 26-yard pass at the Broncos' 32.
After three incompletions, Peterson kicked a 45-yarder to tie the
score and send the game into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming back from a 10-point deficit with a minute-something to
go, that's the determination of a team that knows it's not out of
it,'' said defensive end Phillip Daniels, who sacked Denver
quarterback Brian Griese twice.
</P>
<P>
   What followed was even more encouraging, as the defense turned
in its first three-and-out of the game to open the overtime period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we go that three-and-out, I really felt like we were
going to win,' Daniels said. ``A lot of strange things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what happened on the play that ended the game,
which followed a play when Kitna overthrew a wide-open Joey
Galloway at the Broncos' 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks were in their five-wide receiver set that has
produced some big plays in recent games. Kitna had two option
routes on either side and was just about to unload the ball to Mike
Pritchard when Broncos cornerback Ray Crockett unloaded on Kitna.
</P>
<P>
   Crockett came free on a blitz, as the Seahawks were left with
only five linemen to block and no back in the backfield to pick up
blitzers. Crockett drilled Kitna, who fumbled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great call,'' Crockett said. ``We ran a zone blitz.
It was my call, time for me to make a play.''
</P>
<P>
   Crockett made his play, and Cadrez finished it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both came on blitzes from the outside,'' Cadrez said. ``I
heard the hit, and I turned around to look for the ball and there
it was.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, here the Seahawks are _ out of first place for the
first time since Oct. 17, when they were 3-2; and facing a must-win
against the Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The season's not over,'' coach Mike Holmgren said. ``But
bouncing back from a loss like this is a challenge. But you find
out what you're made of in situation like this.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Clare Farnsworth can be reached at 206-448-8016
</P>
<P>
   or clarefarnsworth &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
