<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3900 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-JETS-HNS &LR;      12-20 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-JETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
IRVING _ All season, the Cowboys have been telling themselves they
are better than their record indi-cates.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A successful field goal here, a completed pass there, one less
injury _ and they might lead the NFC East.
</P>
<P>
   But after another loss to a non-playoff team, the Cowboys are
starting to realize they are exactly what their record shows _ a
.500 team in serious danger of having the season end in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   This time it was the New York Jets coming from behind for a
22-21 victory. But like no other this season, this defeat came at
Texas Stadium before 64,271 disillusioned fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we are again after seven losses saying what we could do
and how good we can be,'' running back Emmitt Smith said. ``Who are
we kidding?''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys were well aware of the situation when Sunday's game
started.
</P>
<P>
   NFC East rivals Washington (8-6) and the New York Giants (7-7)
had lost before the Cowboys kicked off. Had Dallas won, it would
have pulled into a tie for the division lead and _ because of a
pair of victories over the Redskins _ would lead the division.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Cowboys remain tied with New York, a game out of
the lead. Even if the Cowboys win their final two games _ Christmas
Eve in New Orleans and Jan. 2 at home against the Giants _ the
Redskins must lose once if Dallas is to win the East.
</P>
<P>
   Washington plays at San Francisco a week from today and hosts
Miami on Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had everything sitting just like we wanted it, but we
didn't take advantage,'' Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, the Cowboys are a .500 team. That means win
one, lose one. And since they beat the Philadelphia Eagles last
week, it wasn't too shocking that the Cowboys found themselves on
the losing end this time.
</P>
<P>
   After all, this team hasn't put up back-to-back wins since
starting the season 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it says about this team,'' quarterback Troy
Aikman said.
</P>
<P>
   One thing it says is that this team can't hold a lead when it
matters. Though they trailed early after the Jets kicked a pair of
field goals, the Cowboys controlled play in the second quarter and
early in the third to take a 21-13 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But they let the Jets score the final nine points while picking
up just three first downs on their last six possessions.
</P>
<P>
   At 6-8, the Jets are last in the AFC East. At 7-7, the Cowboys
are smack in middle of the NFC playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to be 7-7 and think of ourselves as a playoff
team,'' Aikman said. ``But we still could be.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Cowboys had a shot at being 8-6.
</P>
<P>
   After New York went on top 22-21, the Cowboys started at their
16 with 1:35 remaining, and Aikman immediately passed to Rocket
Ismail for 23 yards. Thirty more yards, and the Cowboys had a
chance for a long field goal. Forty yards, and three points would
have been almost certain.
</P>
<P>
   But they went no further.
</P>
<P>
   Jets cornerback Aaron Glenn broke up another attempt to Ismail.
A second-down pass aimed at Chris Brazzell was nearly intercepted.
A third-down try for Eric Bjornson was knocked away by Victor
Green, and a fourth-down try for Ismail was underthrown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we could get in a position to get a field goal, but
we failed to do that,'' Aikman said. ``I failed to do that, and I
take responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   He failed more than he succeeded Sunday, managing only 158 yards
in the air on 12-of-28 passing. He was picked off twice. More
significant, the Cowboys converted only three of 12 third-down
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like we always play just good enough to win,''
Brazzell said. ``But when you play just good enough, you sometimes
don't pull it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there were moments. For one six-play drive in the third
quarter, the Cowboys looked like a playoff team.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys ran the ball on five of six plays, something they
thought would be nearly impossible against the Jets' tough run
defense. Smith carried for 13, 10 and five yards. Robert Thomas
gained 10, and the Cowboys found themselves at the New York 27.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail then went left on an end around and sprinted untouched
into the end zone. That score put Dallas ahead 21-13 with 11:18 to
play in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   And it was the offense's last gasp. The final six possessions
ended in two interceptions, three punts and Aikman's final four
misfires. The Cowboys averaged four plays per drive on their final
six possessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating to go from good to bad in the game,'' said
Smith, who accounted for 110 of Dallas' 195 rushing yards. ``We
make plays at times, and at times we don't.''
</P>
<P>
   On this day, the Cowboys scored three touchdowns, though special
teams played major roles in the first two.
</P>
<P>
   The first came after Deion Sanders returned a punt 26 yards to
the New York 41 early in the second period. The Cowboys then
sprinted to the end zone on four plays, all involving Smith, who
carried three times for 27 yards and was on the receiving end of a
14-yard touchdown pass in the right flat.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Dallas led 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   The second TD was a special-teams highlight.
</P>
<P>
   After a five-play drive stalled at the New York 20, the Cowboys
set up for a field goal. Bjornson, the holder, took the snap and
sprinted down the right sideline, scoring easily.
</P>
<P>
   In between, cornerback Kevin Smith was flagged for a 34-yard
interference penalty on Dedric Ward, setting up the Jets' first
touchdown. The penalty moved New York to the Dallas one, and
quarterback Ray Lucas passed to fullback Richie Anderson for a 13-7
New York lead.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas moved his team into contention, marching the Jets 62 yards
on seven plays early in the third quarter. He passed to Blake
Spence for a two-yard touchdown but failed to run in the two-point
conversion, leaving the Cowboys up 21-19.
</P>
<P>
   It stayed that way until the Jets' 11-play drive that ended in
John Hall's 37-yard field goal with 1:35 remaining. Curtis Martin
was the workhorse, carrying on nine plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 7-7 and on the verge of not making the playoffs,''
Emmitt Smith said. ``I thought we were a better ballclub than what
we showed today, but we showed today we're not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
