<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3901 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      12-20 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAWKS DON'T KNOW HOW TO HANDLE SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The NFL recently banned the throat-slash gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Seahawks, the prohibition did not also
include the choke.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks have a solid grip on their own windpipes. There is
no sign of let-up.
</P>
<P>
   In a four-week period that borders on the astonishing, the
Seahawks have gone from darkhorse contenders for the Super Bowl to
longshots to get out of their own way.
</P>
<P>
   It's strictly mental. No team is 8-2 in the NFL without having
considerable talent and a substantial plan. But the head game is
crucial, especially in December. And the Seahawks are a month into
one apparently endless concussion.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks have taken that 8-2 record and worn it like an
anvil strapped to a piano. Sunday, they came into their old
nightmare shack, Mile High Stadium, in a complete role reversal _
they were the AFC West co-leaders and the 4-9 Broncos were out of
playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing changed. The Seahawks played like losers and the Broncos
like winners, prevailing in overtime 36-30 in as screwball a finish
as the worst Leslie Nielsen movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brutal,'' guard Pete Kendall said. ``We overcame everything
that came our way, and they just made one more play than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the game ended,'' safety Merton Hanks said, ``was
extremely bitter.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks were consumed with the freakishness of the final
play _ Denver linebacker Glenn Cadrez's 37-yard touchdown run with
a fumble from sacked quarterback Jon Kitna _ which allowed them to
ignore the events that made them vulnerable to the improbable.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks can say they scored 30 points at Mile High Stadium
on a day colder than a mean preacher's stare.
</P>
<P>
   They can say that in scoring 10 points in the final 1:47 to tie
the game, they showed heart.
</P>
<P>
   They can say that they were screwed multiple times by poor
officiating, and that a lucky bounce of the ball led to the second
overtime loss by fumble return in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   All true.
</P>
<P>
   So what?
</P>
<P>
   Playoff-caliber teams overcome. They get in the last punch. They
have a trick left. Somewhere in the sleeve, vest or fedora, there
is an ace.
</P>
<P>
   The first 10 weeks, the Seahawks displayed a few of those. Now,
they are played out. Spent. Consumed with their own shortcomings,
unable to conduct themselves with a division lead.
</P>
<P>
   Dramatic as was their late comeback to force overtime, it was no
more representative of their level of play than was Cadrez's fumble
return representative of the Broncos defense.
</P>
<P>
   What was truly representative of the Seahawks' play in the last
month happened after cornerback Willie Williams' interception set
up the offense on the Denver 47-yard line with 8:40 left in
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   After four plays, the Seahawks had a first down at the 12. On
three of the next four snaps, they committed five-yard penalties:
</P>
<P>
   -- False start on right tackle Grant Williams;
</P>
<P>
   -- Illegal shift (two men in motion);
</P>
<P>
   -- Delay of game.
</P>
<P>
   The officials missed another obvnalty: a team SAT in
single digits.
</P>
<P>
   The three penalties were part of a season-high 118 yards in
punishments, and forced the Seahawks to take a field goal when a
touchdown would have given them a 24-23 lead. They even had that
TD, an endzone catch by Sean Dawkins, but it was wiped out by the
delay penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The three drive-killing penalties were a hallmark of a team
unsure of itself in a pressure situation. In the run to 8-2, there
was relatively little pressure, because the Seahawks used the
entirety of the expiring decade to beat down expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But expectations blossomed, inspired by the previously golden
touch of the new head man, Mike Holmgren. But there are things in
sports that can't be taught, only experienced.
</P>
<P>
   A group of players who had never been there before began to
swoon from the heights. A month later, the only thing that might
save them is a call to NASA for some heat-resistant tiles from the
space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   The dive has been so precipitous that the uninitiated tend to
drift toward explanations involving the fates and the supernatural.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in jinxes, necessarily,'' Holmgren said.
``Games are decided by the way this one was.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Kitna: ``That's garbage. I don't believe in stuff like
that. It's not hocus pocus. It's not magic.''
</P>
<P>
   They're right. Tempting as it is to believe that the Kingdome
was built on an Indian burial ground, and that Ken Behring is still
haunting the halls in Kirkland, the pragmatic explanation is that
these Seahawks can't take the pressure of success.
</P>
<P>
   All they have to do to disprove it is beat the most resurgent
club in the NFL. In beating the Chiefs 31-19 earlier in Kansas
City, the Seahawks have established they have talent to do so;
Sunday it comes down to guts.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
