<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3904 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-REDSKINS-COLTS-HN     12-20 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REDSKINS-COLTS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
INDIANAPOLIS _ The Indianapolis Colts have become the kind of
warm-hearted Christmas story even Scrooge would love.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite back-to-back records of 3-13, the Colts began the season
hoping to prove they were merely leasing the AFC East basement. Few
took their worst-to-first goal seriously, because they play in the
NFL's best division, which sent four teams to the playoffs last
season.
</P>
<P>
   But to see the Colts is to believe in them. Their transformation
from frogs to princes became official Sunday when they beat
Washington 24-21 to clinch the AFC East title, securing a
first-round bye and a second-round game at the RCA Dome, where
57,013 cheered Indianapolis' first division crown since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   After the Colts defeated NFC East leader Washington to elevate
their winning streak to 10 games and to improve their record to
12-2, quarterback Peyton Manning led them out of the dressing room
and back onto the field for a curtain call in front of thousands of
fans who continued to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans have been a big part of our success,'' said Manning,
who threw two touchdown passes. ``This was our chance to thank them
for supporting us. There's no question that crowd noise is a factor
for every team that comes here, and as a team we certainly
appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   While Manning and his teammates circled the field signing
autographs and shaking hands, his father, Archie Manning, stood in
the tunnel watching his son lead his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had any idea they'd come this far this fast,'' Archie
Manning said. ``I was one of those 8-8 guys. I'm excited for Peyton
and the team because they've played hard, and they've played well
against a real tough schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie running back Edgerrin James scored their first and last
touchdowns on a 37-yard catch and a two-yard run to help the Colts
improve their record to 6-1 against teams in or tied for first
place. They are now 7-2 against teams with winning records.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a fast turnaround, definitely faster than we
expected,'' Peyton Manning said after completing 23 of 37 passes
for 298 yards. ``We were confident we'd be good, but we didn't know
we'd be this good.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best division in football, and we've beaten a lot
of good teams. But this is just another step to a higher goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colts want to win Super Bowl XXXIV, but the road to Atlanta
may go through Jacksonville for any AFC team. If the Colts continue
to play as they have been, there may be no stopping them.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins resisted until the end. They led 10-7 in the first
half and 13-10 in the fourth quarter, despite losing running back
Stephen Davis, their leading rusher and scorer who aggravated an
ankle injury in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the game's last two minutes, the Redskins scored a
touchdown, added a two-point conversion and recovered an onside
kick to leave them a field goal from overtime. But quarterback Brad
Johnson's fourth-down pass from their 47 was incomplete, leaving
Washington with an 8-6 mark and a trip to San Francisco and a home
game against Miami left on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game was ours to control at the end, but we didn't make
the plays,'' Redskins defensive tackle Dan Wilkinson said. ``I
never feel good about losing, and this one hurts. The bottom line
is that we've got to win our last two games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins, who didn't commit a turnover, will never know if
they could have pulled this one out if Davis had stayed healthy.
</P>
<P>
   After James made a fingertip catch on Manning's 37-yard pass for
a 7-0 lead, the Colts fell behind 10-7 when Brett Conway kicked a
23-yard field goal and Albert Connell caught a 48-yard touchdown
pass for Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Vanderjagt's 43-yard field goal made it 10-10, but Conway
countered with a 32-yarder and the 13-10 halftime lead for the
Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Before Davis left, he had 70 yards rushing. The Redskins
finished with 151 yards rushing compared to Indianapolis' 88, but
no one provided the kind of game-breaking weapon Davis has become.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made a big difference when we lost Stephen,'' receiver
Michael Westbrook said. ``We lost a lot of momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, the Redskins forced three turnovers and
limited the Colts to 19 yards rushing, but Indianapolis didn't
change its game plan at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the best things we do offensively is to run the ball,''
Colts coach Jim Mora said. ``I have to credit (offensive
coordinator) Tom Moore and the offensive coaches. They've got
patience.''
</P>
<P>
   James rebounded from his 19-yard performance in the first half
for 70 more in the second. And he got them the hard way, by
breaking tackles and moving the piles.
</P>
<P>
   James' 20-yard run to the Washington one set up Manning's
one-yard touchdown pass to tight end Ken Dilger that gave the Colts
a 17-13 lead early in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins retaliated by moving to the Indianapolis 31.
Conway's 49-yard field goal was blocked by Jason Belser. The Colts
responded with another scoring drive that James finished with a
two-yard touchdown run to make it 24-13 with 5:57 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins made it interesting by going 66 yards in seven
plays. Brian Mitchell scored on a six-yard run, and Johnson threw
the two-point conversion pass to Westbrook, putting Washington
behind 24-21 with 1:24 left.
</P>
<P>
   Washington receiver James Trash controlled Conway's onside kick
at the Washington 46, but the Colts' defense allowed only one net
yard in four plays to seal the win.
</P>
</TEXT>
