<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-EAST-CAROLINA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER THE FLOOD: EAST CAROLINA RISES ABOVE ADVERSITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Jeff Kerr plays in a linebacker's violent
world. East Carolina's second-leading tackler has no compassion for
the opposition and when he sees tears, he wants them spilling from
the eyes of smacked-down running backs. With a tree-trunk neck, at
6-foot-4 and 235 pounds, he's not accustomed to being knocked down.
</P>
<P>
   A natural disaster, a relief shelter and a destitute woman
changed that.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates were visiting people who were displaced by the
flooding caused by Hurricane Floyd in September. It was a few days
after East Carolina had dispatched the Hurricanes from Miami,
27-23, in one of the most inspiring victories of the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This woman came up to me and told me she had lost
everything,'' said Kerr, a native of Salisbury, N.C. ``She looked
me right in the eye and said, `Thank you. Thank you for that game.'
And her eyes were filled with tears. She said, `These aren't tears
of sadness, these are tears of happiness.' That's something I'll
always take with me.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the Pirates' Mobile Alabama Bowl game with TCU on
Wednesday, even if a season-ending loss makes them 9-3, won't
matter as much. At a time when the people of Eastern North Carolina
were suffering from floodwaters left by the hurricane, they
provided a ray of sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a flood of Biblical proportions,'' said East Carolina
chancellor Richard Eakin, noting that the Tar River crested at 30
feet, 17 feet over flood stage. ``When the game ended, I don't
think there was a dry eye in the house. And certainly not mine. I
just realized I had seen something pretty miraculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team probably gave more hope and more realization there
is a tomorrow and the sun will shine tomorrow than anything else
could have done for Eastern North Carolina.'' \Nsubheds:Pride is
back The sun is shining again here. Life appears close to normal.
Holiday shoppers fill the parking lot at The Plaza Mall.
Greenville, home of East Carolina University, appears to be a
typical college town. But the scars are still apparent.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles out of town, nearly 100 displaced families are
living in a makeshift trailer park. Half a mile away, Joseph C.
Randolph is plowing fields of ruined bean and cotton crops. Even
now, nearly three months after Floyd's monsoons, the ground is
still saturated. The tractor's wheels bog down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was rough, rough,'' Randolph said of Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Floyd was blamed for 51 deaths in North Carolina. The
damage is estimated at more than $6 billion. More than 48,000
people were forced into shelters.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent recruiting trip, East Carolina coach Steve Logan
said he passed ``thousands'' of trailers and campers that are
housing people who lost their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over,'' he said. ``This disaster blasted this culture
and it's not going away any time soon. It altered peoples' lives
permanently.''
</P>
<P>
   This is an area accustomed to tough times. Logan and others
describe the inhabitants as having chips on their shoulders. This
is tobacco and hog-farming country. To the west, there's Raleigh,
Durham, Chapel Hill, Greensboro, Charlotte _ cities of technology,
medicine and culture.
</P>
<P>
   Greenville mayor Nancy Jenkins grew up in Raleigh and attended
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all very arrogant and probably thought there was
nothing east of Raleigh,'' said Jenkins, who has lived in
Greenville for 37 years. ``Now, we're the mecca of the east. We
used to be called a sleeping giant. We're no longer asleep, we're
alive and thriving.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is such pride, purple pride, in the university. It's
given us a reason to be proud.''
</P>
<P>
   East Carolina's football program has fueled that pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to tell people we're the only football school in
North Carolina,'' said Pirates defensive back Kevin Monroe, a
Greenville native. ``All those ACC schools are basketball
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   And on Sept. 25, playing in North Carolina State's stadium
because they had been displaced by the disaster, the Pirates
spotted Miami 20 points. In shelters in Greenville, the refugees
listened on radios, rode the roller coaster to the valley of an
apparent loss, then rejoiced in the euphoria of triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time East Carolina wins, it gets your spirit up. And
beating a team like Miami ... '' Randolph said. ``It's like your
car breaks down, the guy right behind you stops and gives you his
car. It just picks your spirit right back up. People were worrying
about how much they lost, what they were going to do. Winning that
game just seemed to give people a boost.''
</P>
<P>
   A hand-painted sign hanging from a campus window seemed to
capture the spirit of the region. ``We're Making It A Habit Of
Beating Hurricanes.'' \Nsubheds:Magic dust The prelude for East
Carolina's inspiring defeat of Miami came with its game at South
Carolina. The Pirates left for Columbia, S.C. on Sept. 17. They had
a police escort out of town. They needed help to find a way out of
town to avoid the rising flood waters.
</P>
<P>
   After beating the Gamecocks, 21-3, Logan told his team the bad
news: The flooding was getting worse. The campus was without
electricity and water. The Pirates would not make it back home for
awhile.
</P>
<P>
   The team stayed in Columbia, S.C. The players had brought just
one change of clothes, so the hotel where they were staying
provided a daily laundry service. The Carolina Panthers donated
practice equipment. South Carolina allowed use of their film rooms.
Weightroom work was done at a Gold's Gym. The Pirates prepared for
the Sept. 25 Miami game by practicing at a local high school. There
was no scout team, so the first-team offense practiced against the
first-team defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly, we were thinking about home,'' Monroe said. ``When we
were on the field, we thought about football; that was the only
time things were normal. We couldn't use the phones in our rooms
because it was some sort of NCAA violation, so we had 10, 12 guys
in line using three pay phones.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates were preparing for a game they weren't sure they
would play.
</P>
<P>
   The Monday before the Miami game, there was no water and no
electricity in the East Carolina athletic offices. Some people felt
that athletic director Mike Hamrick and the school's administration
were in the dark when they decided to play the game, but moved its
location to North Carolina State's Carter-Finley stadium in
Raleigh, about 90 miles to the west.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a controversial decision,'' Hamrick said. ``We're in
the midst of the worst disaster ever, we're moving it out of town
and costing us millions of dollars. And we had some second
thoughts. We were getting ready for a game here with porta-potties
and generators.''
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 20,000 was expected; 45,900 showed up. Some fans
drove north into Virginia, making it a three-hour excursion to
reach the game. Some ticket holders donated their tickets to people
in shelters, who then were bussed to the game. The purple-clad
crowd started to roar in pregame warmups and it didn't end until
they tore down both goalposts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What helped us the most was the fans,'' Kerr said. ``We'd just
make a routine tackle and they'd roar, go nuts. We saw the
enthusiasm ... we played 89 snaps on defense and during the game,
because of the fans, I didn't get tired. Once it was over, I just
collapsed.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamrick remembers a full moon in the September sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started to come back, it was like somebody had thrown
magic dust on the field,'' Hamrick said. ``If we had not played
that game, we would have let the disaster defeat us. We would have
sat around and felt sorry for ourselves. Instead, we went over and
beat the nation's No. 9 team, on national television, in our
arch-rival's stadium, our fans tear the goalposts down. Hollywood
wouldn't believe it. If you made a movie or wrote a book about it,
it would have to be fiction.'' \Nsubheds:Football as poetry
Columbine High wins the Colorado state championship six months
after a murderous shooting spree. Texas A&AMP;M defeats Texas after the
bonfire tragedy. And East Carolina gives hope to flood victims who
lost everything. Football, a ``game,'' can provide a unique healing
agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing these people had to hope for was for a football
team to beat a nationally ranked, powerhouse football team,'' Kerr
said. ``About all that's in this community is this university. For
a lot of people, the football team is important and that game
turned out to be really special for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Logan has received hundreds of letters _ and they're still
arriving _ from people effected by the flood. The themes are all
the same: ``I lost everything ... The football team gave me
something to look forward to ... The football team showed me what
perseverance and faith can accomplish. ... If you guys can come
back from being down 20-0, I can come back from this flood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing else you could conjure up to give these people
an emotional lift,'' Logan said. ``Nothing, other than a dramatic
victory as an underdog, would have been more perfect. There was a
poetry to it. It was a mountain-top experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``College football has its warts and stupid people do stupid
things. People say college football is out of control. But in its
inception, it was meant to be something for people to rally behind.
In our case, it's an entire region. This whole thing was college
football at its finest.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 0059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
