u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-EAGLES-B     12-20 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-EAGLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS' PLAYOFF HOPES END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Pete Carroll stood near the door to the visiting
coaches' office at Veterans Stadium, looking out on his team's
locker room, his eyes red and tears welling up.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Sunday's humiliating 24-9 loss to the Eagles
that, coupled with the Buffalo Bills' victory over the Arizona
Cardinals Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, ended his team's playoff chances, the
Patriots coach surveyed the room for a moment, then retreated to
his office.
</P>
<P>
   Was he looking for answers? Looking for a reason why his players
couldn't find it in themselves to beat, in Willie McGinest's words,
``one of the worst teams in the league''? Or looking for an escape?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick about what we did,'' said Carroll, who said his team
``squatted'' on the field. ``I can't imagine we would do what we
did. Obviously, y'all saw that. Where that came from . . . that's
as ugly of a performance as you can imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Owner Robert Kraft visited Carroll in the office after the game.
Speculation will abound about Carroll's future with the team, and
perhaps this was the last straw.
</P>
<P>
   After starting the season 6-2, the Patriots dropped to 7-7 and
saw their streak of three consecutive playoff appearances come to
an end. Even if the Patriots finish 9-7, they'd lose tie-breakers
to all wild-card contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a team playing for nothing except pride, and they
kicked our ass,'' said Troy Brown, who was the only Patriots bright
spot with five catches for 105 yards and a 32-yard punt return.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to make any sense out of this one. The Eagles
started their third-string quarterback _ Koy Detmer _ and, by and
large, he looked like a third-string quarterback. The Patriots
played without cornerbacks Steve Israel and Ty Law, and both of
their replacements, Kato Serwanga and Tebucky Jones, were burned
for touchdown passes.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Bledsoe continued to be a mystery. He was 23 of 49 for 331
yards, but had four interceptions, no touchdowns, two fumbles
(losing one), and was sacked six times. Bledsoe was blitzed to
death by the no-name Eagles defense, and the offensive line
provided little resistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the coach, the quarterback, or the offensive
coordinator, but there just seems to be no rhyme or reason to why
we call certain plays,'' said veteran tackle Bruce Armstrong, who
gave up three sacks to former Boston College end Mike Mamula.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're going to blitz, what are the good plays against the
blitz and what are the bad plays? Why does it seem we're always in
bad plays against the blitz? I don't know the answer. I just know
in the past we knew we were going to be successful. Now we call the
plays and come to the line with fingers crossed.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the play-calling was questionable, it's pretty hard to
win when you turn the ball over seven times (four interceptions,
three fumbles). Tony Simmons set the tone when he fumbled the
opening kickoff, with the Eagles recovering at the Patriots 24.
That led to a Norm Johnson 43-yard field goal and a 3-0
Philadelphia lead.
</P>
<P>
   Remember those red zone problems in Indianapolis last week? The
Patriots added a new twist on their first drive Sunday. After they
marched from their 30 to the Eagles 17, Terry Allen fumbled on a
hit by tackle Hollis Thomas and Philadelphia recovered at the 5.
</P>
<P>
   The hapless Eagles didn't do anything with their good fortune
and gave the Patriots a gift when Detmer was hit by Lawyer Milloy
as he released the ball, throwing it into the open arms of Tedy
Bruschi at the Eagles 20. After Allen recovered his own fumble and
Bledsoe was sacked by Mamula for an 8-yard loss, the Patriots
quarterback tossed an interception to Jeremiah Trotter,
underthrowing Shawn Jefferson by a mile.
</P>
<P>
   With the ball at midfield, Detmer followed with one of his
shining moments _ a 50-yard touchdown pass to Torrance Small, who
ran a corner post and left Serwanga on the rug.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the second quarter, the Patriots' struggles were
exemplified by one play. Larry Whigham blocked a Sean Landeta punt,
but with Whigham still on the ground, Philadelphia's Mike Caldwell
picked up the loose ball and ran down the left sideline, eluding
Jerry Ellison for the first down. But the Eagles could not pad
their lead.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the quarter, after a 23-yard field goal by Adam
Vinatieri made it 10-3, Bledsoe threw it long to Jefferson, who had
put a great fake on Al Harris at about the 25. But Jefferson was
off balance as the ball arrived and went out of bounds at the
Eagles 7 for a 31-yard gain. But again, the Patriots fizzled and
had to settle for a 43-yard field goal by Vinatieri.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of day. It seemed whenever something good
happened, it was negated by something bad shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   On the kickoff following Vinatieri's second field goal, Brown
recovered a fumble at the Eagles 28. But that merely led to an
interception of Bledsoe by Harris and an 84-yard return that
included a fumble recovered by teammate Brian Dawkins at the 11.
From there, Detmer hit Small for a touchdown and 17-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Before the half ended, the Patriots had one more embarrassing
moment when Vinatieri's 56-yard field goal attempt fell short and
was returned 74 yards by Allen Rossum before Mike Bartrum made a
saving tackle at the 26.
</P>
<P>
   All the Patriots could muster in the second half was a 46-yard
field goal by Vinatieri with 10:17 left in the third quarter. The
Eagles scored again with 1:08 remaining in the third when Detmer
hit former Patriot Dietrich Jells with a bomb. Jones was beaten on
the play, but help was late in coming from Chris Carter, who was
slowed by a hamstring problem but played the whole game anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The second half was an act in offensive futility for the
Patriots, resulting in two punts, two interceptions, a fumble, and
a hail of dropped passes.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots looked like a Triple A affiliate, with nobody ready
for prime time and everyone now primed for a lot of down time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of losing,'' said McGinest. ``I'm tired of losing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
