<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG CAN'T BEAR TO WATCH 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ A 34-year-old man who has played for a 1-15 team
might rightfully assume he had endured the worst, but when a player
spends his entire career with the tragi-comedic pigskin troupe
known as the New England Patriots, there is always a new and
shocking surprise in store.
</P>
<P>
   It is bad enough that over a four-season stretch his team has
regressed from being an honorable participant in the Super Bowl to
being a point away from the AFC Championship Game to a first-round
loser in the playoffs to being out of the playoffs entirely. So how
could it get any worse? Is that what you're saying?
</P>
<P>
   Here's how. You can't get into the end zone. Ever. That's how.
</P>
<P>
   ``You explain it to me,'' said 13-year veteran Bruce Armstrong,
who is now fully aware that nobody is ever around this organization
long enough to state with assurance that he has seen everything.
``With the offensive players we have on this team, how can we not
be scoring any points?''
</P>
<P>
   Your New England Patriots have become the Chicago Bulls of the
NFL. Sunday's losing score to the Eagles was 24-9, and in case you
haven't been keeping the weekly tally, be advised that Your New
England Patriots have now scored no touchdowns in the past two
games, two touchdowns in the past four games, and seven touchdowns
in the six games since the bye week that has marked the dividing
line between Hope and Despair for Pete Carroll's demoralized bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Is it time to bring back the quick kick?
</P>
<P>
   Drew Bledsoe Sunday threw for 331 yards, but who cares? You
don't win on base hits, field goal percentage, or total yardage.
You don't win very many with a field goal subsistence diet, either.
You win on touchdowns, and if you'd like to pinpoint the reason why
the Patriots can all have their SUVs, pick-up trucks, and campers
packed and ready to go on Jan. 2, it's because they have proven
incapable of scoring touchdowns since the midway mark of this
perplexing season.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure we're all gifted with 20-20 now. We can all say how
deceptive and synthetic those wins over the Jets, Giants, Browns,
Dolphins, Broncos, and Cardinals were, and how anybody who knew
anything about pro football realized that the Patriots were living
on the edge, taking reasonable advantage of a favorable first-half
schedule. And the truth is that a lot of people did feel nervous
about what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, well, OK. But who foresaw the nature of their stunning
second-half collapse? Who stepped up on Nov. 15 and declared that
over the next six weeks the Patriots would treat the end zone as if
it had been mined? You could see some 31-24 or 28-21 losses, but
17-7? 20-15? 24-9? Even the only victory since the bye was by the
none-too-inspiring score of 13-6. The once-feared New England
Patriots have become the very parody of a professional football
team, at least when those dreaded moments come when they are
actually in possession of the football.
</P>
<P>
   The dreamer in Armstrong suggests that his chances of playing on
a championship team in a Patriots uniform are not completely gone.
He talks about free agency and salary caps and the general
year-to-year volatility of the league, and he can make it all sound
very rational. But the realist in him knows the truth. That
proverbial window of opportunity that was thrown open in 1993 when
Bill Parcells accepted James Busch Orthwein's offer to tinker with
this jinxed franchise has been jammed shut with the toughest nails
money can buy.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the headstone:
</P>
<P>
   CHAMPIONSHIP QUALITY PATRIOTS &QC; 
BORN 1993. DIED 1999 &QC;
</P>
<P>
   It's over. Bruce Armstrong knows it and he just doesn't
understand why it has to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is as bad as I've ever felt,'' he said. ``I have
absolutely no answers. We start out 6 and 2 and we come out in the
the second half and we are not able to get anything done. In my 13
years this is as bad as I've felt. I don't have the answers. Maybe
you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Drew Bledsoe does. ``Whether it's me, the offense, or the
entire team,'' the quarterback said with a sigh, ``we're just not
very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in football there are a lot of ``we's.'' There's the
offense. There's the defense. There are the various special teams.
There is the quarterback. There are the running backs. There are
the wide receivers. There are the offensive linemen. There are the
defensive linemen. There are the linebackers. There are the
defensive backs. And, of course, there are the coaches. There are a
whole lotta ``we's'' who must do their jobs in order for a football
team to win, and no one man can speak for the entire group.
</P>
<P>
   The most Armstrong can speak for is the offense, and he admits
to a feeling of near helplessness that begins with some of the
plays that are being sent in by offensive coordinator Ernie
Zampese.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a bad, bad feeling when plays are called in the
huddle and you just don't have a great feeling about them,'' he
said. ``There used to be times when plays would be called and you
know they'd be successful. Now plays are called and you head to the
line of scrimmage with your fingers crossed. I can just tell you
that there isn't a feeling of flow in the offense. Sometimes you
feel you're just running (pause) plays. We're running a lot of
different people in with a lot of different formations. When it
works, you're a genius. When it doesn't . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe was blitzed the entire game, and he was sacked six more
times. Drew Bledsoe being sacked is no longer news, and it would be
nice if somebody could figure out a way to prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know they'e going to blitz,'' Armstrong said. ``You watch
the films all week, and you know. So you ask yourself this
question: If you know they're going to blitz, and there are plays
you can run against the blitz and plays you can't run against the
blitz, how come we seem to be sending in plays that don't work
against the blitz?''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong is not claiming infallibility. He admits he'd sure
like to have back a certain sequence in which he was beaten by Mike
Mamula. And he knows very well that plenty of good plays were
called, and that, as is the second-half norm, assignments were
blown and passes were dropped and players spoiled all the best
situational coaching expertise by their own atrocious play.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Armstrong knows that there never is one answer when things
deteriorate so completely. ``I'm sure there is enough blame to
spread around,'' he said. But if anyone has a right on this team to
be frustrated, angry, and morose, it is Bruce Armstrong. The
playoffs are out of the question for this year, and he knows that
by the time a Patriots team returns to the Super Bowl he'll be
working on some joint replacement.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is there are two more irrelevant games to play. ``At
this stage of my career,'' he said, ``playing games just for the
sake of playing games is something that wasn't in my plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Let him vent. He's earned the right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
