r s BC-FBC-TCU-MOBILE-BOWL-T     12-20 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-MOBILE-BOWL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QB SYSTEM AT TCU PRODUCED STUDENT-TEACHER RELATIONSHIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Arthur Garcia 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOBILE, Ala. _ They share the same position and a room on the
road, but on the surface, those are the only similarities between
TCU quarterbacks Casey Printers and Patrick Batteaux.
</P>
<P>
   Printers is the confident freshman starter and Batteaux the cool
senior backup, and despite their roles, both figure prominently in
the Horned Frogs' plans for Wednesday's Mobile Alabama Bowl matchup
with No. 20 East Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and Casey provide different things for this offense,'' said
Batteaux, the starter the first two games of the season. ``He's
more of a passing-type quarterback and I'm more of a running-type
quarterback, but we both can do it. He can run the ball and I can
pass it, so we give a little mixture of things to provide the
defense different looks. Having that two-quarterback rotation keeps
defenses on their toes.''
</P>
<P>
   Printers is the prototypical signal caller, a 6-foot-3,
190-pounder with a rocket right arm. The true freshman, a highly
touted recruit from DeSoto last year, spurned programs such as
Notre Dame, Texas A&AMP;M and Arizona State to sign with the Horned
Frogs.
</P>
<P>
   One of only two members of the 1999 recruiting class not
redshirted, Printers went 7-2 as a starter, passing for 1,213 and
eight touchdowns. He was also named one of the 10 best true
freshman in the country by ``Sports Illustrated''.
</P>
<P>
   Batteaux found his way into the offensive backfield quite
differently. The 6-footer came to TCU as receiver in 1996 and
played that position for two seasons, leading the team with 27
catches in '97.
</P>
<P>
   Batteaux moved to quarterback in '98 with the arrival of coach
Dennis Franchione, who wanted a player with Batteaux's speed and
intelligence to run his option-based offense. Not only did Batteaux
combine to run and throw for nearly 1,000 yards, he also led TCU to
a Sun Bowl victory over Southern Cal.
</P>
<P>
   Printers and Batteaux routinely go over game plans in their room
on the road, and the freshman has tried to learn as much as
possible from his backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great deal for me as a true freshman,'' Printers said.
``Patrick is a senior who has been through a lot. Every time I made
a mistake, he would tell me what I did wrong and how I could
correct it. There were definitely more pluses to having Patrick
around then just going out there by myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Having Printers and Batteaux on the field in different
situations helped spark the Frogs during the season-ending
four-game winning streak. Though Printers has started since the
third game at Arkansas State, Batteaux has continued to contribute.
He finished second on the team with 333 yards rushing and passed
for another 243. In games against UT-El Paso and SMU, the senior
was in the field to start the second half and the Frogs took
control of both games in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won a lot of games down the stretch for us,'' Printers
said. ``I always liked Patrick's poise. He's poised in every
situation, and that's the main thing I can learn from Patrick.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Batteaux of his late-season play: ``I was just happy to be
in the games playing. It's the last couple of games of my career,
and I just wanted to be prepared to take advantage of my
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-quarterback system sometimes took shape within a drive.
For a change in tempo, Batteaux would replace Printers to run the
option for a few plays before giving way to the freshman on obvious
passing situations. But even more nerve-racking for the defense,
Batteaux might let loose a pass downfield or Printers might take to
the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against Hawaii, for example, I did my passes and then Patrick
came in and ran a few options and then he threw a long pass,''
Printers said of the key 34-14 victory that started the winning
streak. ``We kept teams off-balance and guessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Franchione has his starting QB coming back, he'll miss
the experience and steady hand of Batteaux. ``Our Casey
Printers-Pat Batteaux change-up hitter had been a great deal for
us,'' Franchione said. ``That'll be hard to replace.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
