<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3909 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     12-20 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRING LINE A LONG ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Memo to Robert Kraft: Fire whomever you'd like.
</P>
<P>
   Fire a few of them. Fire the lot of them. Fire at them if you
want.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing else to say after Sunday's sorry effort by the
New England Patriots, a group of 53 men purporting to be a
professional football team. The only thing professional about them
is that Kraft will be forced by law to hand them paychecks this
morning for what they did at Veterans Stadium. What they should be
handed is subpoenas.
</P>
<P>
   But in the firings, do not stop at the front office or at the
coach's office. Go to the source of the Patriots' problems. Go to
the players' office.
</P>
<P>
   Go to the locker room because the people who populated it Sunday
should be ashamed of themselves. They not only lost to the lowly
Eagles, 24-9, to embarrass themselves and virtually end their phony
playoff hopes (Buffalo sealed the deal Sunday &UR;  &LR; night), but they
quit. Play after play after play, they quit.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again half or more of them stood around at the end of a
play, hands on hips, and watched someone else try to do their job.
Not all of them, but too many of them. Way too many of them.
</P>
<P>
   Not Troy Brown, who played so ferociously right to the final
play, and not aging Bruce Armstrong, and not many of the defensive
players, and frankly not the quarterback you love to hate, who kept
getting up off the ground (6 sacks, 14 hurries, 7 knockdowns, 8
drops) and still threw what should have been two touchdown passes
except that Shawn Jefferson ran out of bounds on one instead of
into the end zone and Terry Glenn dropped the other when the ball
hit him in his expensive pair of hands in the end zone when he was
wide open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just went out there and squatted,'' a disgusted Pete
Carroll said. ``We got dominated today. It was a disgrace. That's
what it was.''
</P>
<P>
   For once the carefully selected words were gone and what was
laid bare was that Pete Carroll saw everything the rest of the
football world saw. No rose-colored glasses anymore. No political
statements. No effort to put the best face on a gargoyle.
</P>
<P>
   This time he didn't see effort, at least not enough of it. He
didn't see preparation, at least not enough of it. He didn't see
urgency or desire, at least not enough of it.
</P>
<P>
   What he saw was what we all saw: a team with everything to win
playing like it had nothing to lose, including its pride.
</P>
<P>
   What happened Sunday, despite all the talk of the many talented
players supposedly in their locker room, is that the Patriots were
beaten by a better team. A better team that was 3-11 when the game
began. A better team that thought its bye week was next Sunday but
found it came a week early.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can beat anybody,'' the denizens of the Patriots' locker
room have said time and time again this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can win them all,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do this,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   But they can't and they didn't and they couldn't and the reason
is not schemes and coaches, it is overrated talent and personnel
mistakes and misjudgments by people in charge about who had
character and who did not, and a repeated inability to stand up for
themselves when it was most necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``God forbid we played somebody trying to get into the playoffs
because we would have lost by 40 points,'' said Brown, who is one
of the few who should be re-signed this morning for whatever he's
asking because if Kraft is looking for the definition of a football
player it's not based on size or speed or ability to negotiate the
shuttle run.
</P>
<P>
   A football player is Troy Brown, and there are precious few like
him in the Patriots' locker room these days. There will be one
fewer after free agency begins in March if Kraft doesn't lock Brown
up instead of wasting millions on bigger, faster guys who act like
they're doing him a favor by taking his money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete warned us Saturday,'' Brown said. ``He said he saw a lack
of focus. It showed today from the opening kickoff.'' That's when
Tony Simmons, a second-round draft pick, fumbled after running into
his teammate, a play that was the highlight of his day as he went
without a catch for the third straight game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to get myself ready to play and I hope everybody else
is,'' Brown said. ``This is our profession. You're accountable. The
coaches can only tell you what to do so many times. If you still
don't know what to do, you need to take yourself out of the game.
Fact is, we've been playing like a bunch of front-runners. That's
the bottom line. Like a bunch of front-runners.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, they're not front-runners any more. They're what so many
people said they were back in August, when they acted so deeply
offended that anyone might suggest this football machine was the
fourth best team in the AFC East.
</P>
<P>
   Today they are barely that, just as they are barely a .500 team
after a 6-2 start that convinced them they were more than they
appeared to be.
</P>
<P>
   Since that time this talented team has gone 1-5 and scored seven
touchdowns in the last six games. It has not scored more than 17
points since Halloween, which is also the last time it scared
anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Such a record is the essence of being a front-runner. When the
going gets tough, the tough get going. When the going gets tough
for the Patriots, they go home. Which is where they'll be when the
playoffs begin in three weeks and rightfully so because despite all
their bluster, when it was time to play this year, they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly didn't look like we were fighting for anything,''
Jefferson said. ``This one was the worst and I'm embarrassed by it.
I would have bet my house this team couldn't come out and manhandle
us, and they did. It was like they were playing for something and
we were playing for nothing. It was embarrassing to be involved in
a game like this. Now all the world will find out what we're made
of.''
</P>
<P>
   Memo to Shawn Jefferson: We already know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 0126EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
