<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3910 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-MIC     12-20 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC UPSETS MICHIGAN 
</HEADLINE>
 COLLEGE-MICHIGAN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It wasn't close at halftime. It wasn't close at the
end. Michigan at Boston College. You know the outcome, right?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you know Michigan came into Sunday's game at Conte Forum
with a 6-1 record, which included a win over Georgia Tech and a
7-point loss to Duke.
</P>
<P>
   You probably know BC was 5-2, but with few credentials _ five
wins against mid-major competition, and two losses, to UMass and a
bad defeat to Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   So you see the final score _ 89-71 _ and you see a 41-37
rebounding advantage, and you think this is another blowout win for
the Big Ten.
</P>
<P>
   Think again. BC 89, Michigan 71, which was a fair indication of
the way the game went all afternoon for coach Al Skinner's Eagles,
who Sunday &UR;  &LR; night got on a plane bound for Puerto Rico, where they
will meet Tulsa Tuesday in the first round of the Puerto Rico
Holiday Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's win _ in which the Eagles took a 40-30 halftime lead,
squandered it in the first 10 minutes of the second half, then went
on a 27-8 romp to break the game open _ was both satisfying and
significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, it's the happiest moment we've had in
basketball,'' said BC athletic director Gene DeFilippo, who has
been at The Heights for three years. ``It shows everybody around
the league that basketball here is headed in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   For third-year coach Skinner, it was the highlight of a young
season, not his BC career. ``To me, the most satisfying win was our
first league win (against Notre Dame last season) and it always
will be,'' said Skinner, who seemed to enjoy the game as much as
the rest of the surprisingly noisy Conte Forum crowd of 7,223.
Freshman point guard Troy Bell poured in 28 points, forward Xavier
Singletary added 16 points and seven rebounds, and Jonathan
Beerbohm came off the bench with 14 points and 11 boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a quality win,'' Skinner said. ``A feel-good win. It
was an indication of the potential we can find. It might not be
there every night, but it is there.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a far different BC team than the one that lost a home
game to Harvard last December and prayed it would win any game,
much less one against a talented, although young, team like
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a big statement game for us,'' said Bell, who is
having a remarkably smooth freshman season. ``After that loss to
Penn State,'' an 85-57 rout, ``we wanted to show people we can play
at this level against big-time teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Wolverines weren't _ and now won't be _ ranked,
they came in as perhaps the biggest name nonconference team ever to
visit Conte Forum. They also brought a starting lineup of three
freshmen and a sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   ``BC came in ready to play,'' said Michigan coach Brian Ellerbe.
``They had the complete package today. They scrapped and played
better.''
</P>
<P>
   No question about it. From the opening 20 minutes, when
Beerbohm, the 6-foot-7-inch junior forward nearly had a
double-double in the first half with 8 points and 10 rebounds, the
Eagles established control of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan made a run in the second half and tied it, 55-55, on a
layup by LaVell Blanchard, who scored a team-high 25 points.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bell was fouled on a 3-point attempt and made all three
foul shots, and BC led by at least 3 the rest of the way. The
Eagles' advantage swelled as high as 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a turnaround in a year,'' said DeFilippo. ``From losing
to Harvard, to this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
