<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURNS PUZZLED BY ALLISON'S BEHAVIOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Win one, lose one.
</P>
<P>
   Play inspired some nights, play like dead men skating the next
night.
</P>
<P>
   Score goals one night, can't put the puck in the ocean the next
night.
</P>
<P>
   Show some fight one night, show nothing at all the next night.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Bruins should consult Sherlock Holmes. Maybe he
could unravel the mystery of the team's multiple-personality
disorder.
</P>
<P>
   The most disturbing sign of all in Saturday's astonishing 4-0
loss to the Blues in St. Louis is what happened with center Jason
Allison. As recently as last Monday, he said his right forearm felt
great. He hadn't been taking faceoffs, save for a precious few,
until that point, and it was obvious his game suffered as a result.
However, against the Coyotes, he said he was ready, willing, and
healed enough to go back to taking them.
</P>
<P>
   That lasted three games. Then Saturday night, in a contest
against one of the premier teams in the league, Allison couldn't
take them.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns said if Allison's availability is tenuous, the
team has to make a decision. Burns made it clear he wants Allison
either to play all facets of the game or sit out until he can. But
Allison is the focal point of the Bruins' offense, and his
inability to do what they expect throws everything off.
</P>
<P>
   When he wasn't able to take the faceoffs, Allison said he didn't
think he was playing as poorly as his coach did. The fact was,
though, he wasn't the same player. He said taking faceoffs got him
more into the game, got him out on the ice in more situations, and
made him feel an important part of things. That all seemed very
true, particularly against the Coyotes a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Blues, perhaps because he wasn't able to take draws,
Allison was completely ineffective. Burns said he didn't even know
Allison was unable to take the faceoffs until Anson Carter skated
into position. That handcuffed the coach, because he has to have
two other players on the ice who can take draws in case one of them
gets kicked out of the circle.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are too thin at the center position, so to have
Allison unable to participate in such an important facet of the
game is alarming. Not only that, but Allison, one of the most
outgoing players on the team, politely but grimly declined comment
after the game. He did so again Sunday as the team prepared for its
annual family skating party at the FleetCenter. Allison having no
words is like Bill Gates having no money. That indicates something
is definitely wrong.
</P>
<P>
   To add insult to injury, Tim Taylor, the center the Bruins let
walk away for nothing, is the second-leading faceoff man in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   By no means should all the blame be laid at Allison's feet.
There is plenty to go around.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Rob DiMaio was visibly upset after the game, saying it
was the players' fault, and the coaches didn't deserve to take the
heat for this puzzling situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unacceptable,'' he said. ``We, as players, know it,
and we tell each other that between periods that this just can't
happen, but then we go out and do the same thing. It's a shame,
because the coaches know exactly what to say and when to say it and
how to win. We go out and are on our own program some nights, and
it's got to stop. This is nuts. Us, as players, we have to stop
this. It's not acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio said they played well for the first few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look what happened,'' he said. ``They just turned the game
into a one-sided show and dominated us. We're better than that. We
keep telling ourselves that, but we don't seem to do anything about
it. This has to stop. We play one good game, and then we come back
the next night in a very important game against a very good team
that we should be prepared for, and all the right things are said,
and then we go out and put on a performance like that. I wish I had
the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One answer the team most likely will get shortly is whether
forward Joe Murphy will be sitting out a 10-game suspension for
leaving the bench to jump Blues' left wing Tyson Nash. After
battling with Ray Bourque along the boards, Nash charged Bourque,
and Murphy left the bench to pummel Nash. Leaving the bench to
start or join an altercation carries a multiple-game automatic
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said it was a normal line change, and he doesn't believe
he deserves any supplemental discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything will happen,'' he said. ``(Steve)
Heinze was changing, and I came on and was just involved in the
play. He was coming to the bench to change, and I was up to go and
he was coming off. I came on, and that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said he was offended by Nash running Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody can take advantage of our captain,''
said Murphy. ``Ray's our best player, and he plays the most
minutes, and guys can't be taking runs at him. It's not right.
We're a team here, and we have to be all together, sticking up for
each other and going to battle for each other. Guys can't be doing
that to our captain.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy had best be hoping the NHL's dean of disclipine, Colin
Campbell, is in the Christmas spirit. Otherwise, there's big
trouble on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The only Bruin who skated prior to the skating party Sunday was
defenseman Mattias Timander. Timander, who is coming off a shoulder
separation, is coming along slowly. It was tough to be out there
alone. ``Yeah,'' joked Timander. ``I'm out here skating with all my
buddies.'' . . . Not so for center Shawn Bates. Bates was sporting
a cast on his left arm that started at his hand and covered his
biceps _ all because of a sprained wrist. ``The doctor felt there
was instability,'' said Bates, ``and he thought this was the way to
correct it. It's a nightmare.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
