<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO GET BACK TO BASICS FOR CELTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Five games. Five losses. This was to be a revealing
week for the Celtics, with their first extended foray on the road.
</P>
<P>
   What did they show us? They showed us they miss Paul Pierce. And
they showed they still are a flawed team that can't win on the
road. They played stretches of tantalizing basketball and stretches
of incomprehensible basketball. This past week, it was more of the
latter.
</P>
<P>
   The last defeat, a 100-94 setback Saturday night in Houston,
could well have been an early watershed win. Coming home with a win
after four tough losses, and with an 11-12 record rather than a
10-13 record, would have been much different, especially with the
rest of the month looking equally grim.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 10-13 and with two difficult home games this week (LA
Sunday night, Atlanta Wednesday), the Celtics face the prospect of
sinking even lower. (Their 10 road games are still the fewest in
the conference.) They are still without Pierce (the Celtics are 0-7
in games he has missed), and they need more than white uniforms and
friendly faces to turn it around.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Pitino looked especially exasperated after the Houston
game, sitting on a table in the training room, alone, his tie loose
around his opened white shirt, staring at the final box as if
extended looks might change it.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a young basketball team,'' he said, ``scoring can't
dictate the mentality of how you play this game. That goes for all
12 members. Scoring dictates how they play all other phases of the
game. If they score, they play good defense. They offensive
rebound. Scoring can't dictate how you play this game. It just has
to be a physical battle every possession on defense and has to be a
work of art on offense with passing. Unfortunately, our young
basketball team is not grasping those concepts.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited mental lapses, such as fouling good free-throw shooters
instead of bad ones at the end, or not blocking out to retrieve a
missed free throw. Simple things to a coach. Easy things.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not being down or up. It's understanding how to play
basketball,'' he said. ``If you're missing your jump shot, then
offensive rebound. Get to the line. Run the lanes and get a break.
Get a steal. Play all phases of the game of basketball so you're
well-rounded . . . You put all those simple things together.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Celtics didn't do that. They made it hard. Too hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made up my mind this year I'm not going to get upset at
anything,'' Pitino said after the Houston game, when he was clearly
upset about a lot of things. ``Even this type of basketball is not
going to break me.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of his many concerns:
</P>
<P>
   Team defense: The Rockets were the latest team to exploit the
soft underbelly of the Celtics' half-court defense. Only two teams,
the Nets and the Bulls, are allowing opponents to shoot a higher
percentage. The five teams the Celtics played this week averaged 49
percent shooting; the first three, New York, Utah and Cleveland,
each shot 50 percent or better. The Spurs and Rockets were all
close to 50 percent until they slipped in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Falling behind: At least they didn't blow any leads. But how
hard is it to win when you're on the road and trailing after three
quarters by 12 (New York), 16 (Cleveland), 15 (San Antonio), or 10
(Houston)? Or, to look at it another way, the biggest lead the
Celtics had in any of the five games was 9 points _ early in the
game at New York. In their last four games, the biggest lead the
Celtics had was a 6-pointer at Houston in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Free throws: This figure is somewhat inflated due to deliberate
fouls, but the Celtics allowed an average of 38 free throws a game.
The Celtics shot an average of 23 a game. That's a potential swing
of 15 points. (And with Shaq here Sunday night, that margin is
unlikely to change.) But fouling is one thing. Pitino was mystified
as to why the Celtics fouled 85 percent shooter Cuttino Mobley down
the stretch in Houston when two clangers, Kelvin Cato and Kenny
Thomas, were on the floor. The differential also signals a lack of
aggressiveness at the other end. Once again, the Celtics are below
the 26-a-game average for free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Antoine Walker: Pitino didn't single him out in his post-Houston
rant, but he could have. Walker turned in a 19-minute stink bomb in
the first half, going 1 of 7 and not managing to get a single
rebound. He turned it around with an active, involved second half
(20 points, 7 rebounds). Walker had one excellent game this week
while the other four were classic Walkerian. In those games, he
averaged 16.8 points, 6.8 rebounds, 1.3 assists, and 2.5 turnovers,
and he shot 32 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Rebounds: The Celtics outrebounded the Knicks by 18 and still
lost. When is the last time that happened? The rest of the week,
they were manhandled by every team but Utah. The loss of Danny
Fortson hurts here, but they haven't had him all year and were the
top defensive rebounding team in the league at the start of the
week. Adrian Griffin, a 6-5 swingman, remains their top rebounder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
