<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREDICTABLY, IT'S QUITTING TIME 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ A top Philadelphia Eagles executive had a
quizzical look on his face in a rather subdued winning locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the worst any team has played against us in the last
two years,'' he said. ``I've never seen some of our coaches so
confident before the game. They really had a good feeling about
this one.''
</P>
<P>
   What does that say about the Patriots?
</P>
<P>
   The 4-11 Eagles, following their 24-9 victory, were not talking
about how good they were, but about how bad the Patriots were. And
rightly so.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the front seven of the defense, the rest of the
Patriots should have been forced to walk back to Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them not only played badly but gave up for the first
time this season. There were a bunch of guys in New England
uniforms who put out minimal effort, which is a tough way to win a
game in the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   For the sixth straight game, the New England offense was
pathetic. In the past, one could make excuses, as the Patriots were
playing against defenses with some muscle.
</P>
<P>
   But the Eagles do not have that reputation. Their defense ranks
23d in the league while playing in the NFC East, which has a host a
terrible offensive teams, such at the Giants, Cardinals, and
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   But this normally weak crew dominated the Patriots offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles have a fine defensive coordinator, Jim Johnson, who
enjoys a fine reputation. Johnson was with Indianapolis a few years
ago under Ted Marchibroda, and the Colts always gave the Patriots a
hard time.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday Johnson outguessed the Patriots on almost every play.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were one step ahead of us almost all the time,'' said
backup quarterback John Friesz. ``There were a lot of times they
brought more guys rushing than we had blocking. There were times
when they gave us a fake look, and then came the other way. One
time we had maximum protection, eight guys protecting, and they
still got through to Drew (Bledsoe) and hit him just as he was
throwing the ball. That was the interception in the end zone when
he was trying to throw to Shawn Jefferson. If he had time, I think
it would have been a touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' midseason crash has followed a consistent flight
pattern. They do not score touchdowns in the first half. In fact,
in the first three quarters of their last four games, they have no
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   With the Patriots playing from behind, the opposition knows two
things:
</P>
<P>
   1. New England will stop running the ball.
</P>
<P>
   2. The Patriots will spread the field with three or more wide
receivers looking for a big pass play, leaving Bledsoe vulnerable
to the blitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our (offensive philosophy) seems to be that we will give up
the hit on the quarterback trying to make the play,'' said veteran
tackle Bruce Armstrong. ``We see the defense, we set the
protection. We know how to block it. But then they rush six guys
and we have just five blocking, so he (Bledsoe) has to get the ball
out before that open guy gets there or he's going to get hit.''
</P>
<P>
   You could not point the finger at any one person on offense
Sunday. They all had a hand in the self-destruction, with the
exception of Troy Brown, who played so well some of his teammates
should be embarrassed to sit in the same meeting room with him
Monday watching the game films.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe didn't throw well. The blockers didn't block. The
receivers, especially Terry Glenn, dropped passes and made
half-hearted attempts at others.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Patriots played well, with the exception of
free safety Chris Carter. There was some question whether Carter,
who has a sore hamstring, would play at all. He shouldn't have. He
simply didn't have the speed to get to the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles had only two big offensive plays all day. Koy Detmer,
the third-string quarterback, threw 50 yards to Torrance Small for
one touchdown, and 44 yards to Dietrich Jells for another. On both
plays, Carter should have been in coverage in the middle of the
field but couldn't help the cornerbacks who thought he was covering
the receivers to the inside.
</P>
<P>
   Detmer completed just 10 of 29 passes for 181 yards. More than
half his yards came on two plays. Yet his team won by 15.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles had just three sacks in their previous four games.
They had six Sunday. Mike Mamula came in with 4 1/2 sacks all year.
He had three Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' offense is suffering from what is called
``overload,'' a blitzing scheme in which the defense puts extra men
to one side of the field and rushes them all. This maneuver has
absolutely been killing the Patriots. They can't handle it. They
can't block it, and Bledsoe and the receivers can't beat it.
</P>
<P>
   The overloading has caused a short circuit, shutting down the
entire Patriot system.
</P>
<P>
   The pregame message on the bulletin board in the Eagles'
defensive locker room was simple.
</P>
<P>
   Physical. Finish.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles were physical, and they finished. And they finished
the Patriots in the process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 0133EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
