<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3914 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BLEDSOE-     12-20 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BLEDSOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE LEFT HELPLESS, HOPELESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Apologies were in order, but this time Drew
Bledsoe should have been on the receiving end _ which was more than
could be said for most of his passing targets Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in the wake of a deflating 20-15 loss at Indianapolis,
Bledsoe had issued a mea culpa to Patriots owner Bob Kraft for his
ineffectual performance. Gallant gesture. Disingenuous, too.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, Kraft, his administration and his offense _ with
the notable exception of Troy Brown _ should be begging Bledsoe for
forgiveness for what they've put him through during this season's
second-half nightmare. While the Patriots have been busy turning a
6-2 start into a 7-7 visit to oblivion, the quarterback has served
as the fall guy, both physically and metaphysically, for an offense
that has been as feckless as it has been clueless.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was able to start tending to the rug burns he'd
absorbed on the Veterans Stadium carpet in a 24-9 humiliation by
the supposedly wretched Eagles, Bledsoe knew that not even Santa
Claus could give the Patriots a playoff berth this year.
</P>
<P>
   By then, he probably had more modest Christmas requests in mind,
anyway _ such as survival.
</P>
<P>
   This debacle was a microcosm of the Patriots' demise. Bledsoe
wound up completing only 23 of 49 passes for 331 meaningless yards,
no touchdowns, and four interceptions. The more pertinent
statistics were these: 6 sacks, 14 hurries, 7 knockdowns, and 8
dropped passes, including one in the end zone by Terry Glenn on
fourth and 3 from the Philadelphia 6 with 5:55 left in the fourth
quarter when the Patriots could have made it a one-score game.
</P>
<P>
   This was a true indication of the siege Bledsoe endured all
afternoon as the Eagles' piledriving defense and the Patriots'
passive blockers combined to leave him at constant risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sending nine people,'' said Eagles cornerback Troy
Vincent. ``If you can't get pressure with nine people, there's
something wrong. A lot of times, we were sending more people than
they could block.''
</P>
<P>
   That was gruesomely manifest on two second-quarter plays that
helped take the Patriots out of contention.
</P>
<P>
   New England faced third and goal at the 6 after a 4-yard loss by
Terry Allen when Bledsoe dropped back. And back. And back. Safety
Brian Dawkins burst through the Patriots' line as if it were an
open wound and drove Bledsoe back 19 yards for a sack that forced
New England to settle for a 43-yard Adam Vinatieri field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that pulled the Patriots within 10-6, and they seemed in
golden shape when Allen Rossum fumbled the ensuing kickoff and
Brown covered it at the Eagles 28. From there, Bledsoe went for the
kill but emerged as the victim. Looking for Shawn Jefferson in the
end zone, he was crunched by linebacker William Thomas as he
released the ball, which floated into the hands of Al Harris
downfield and was returned a mere 84 yards to the New England 11.
On the next play, Koy Detmer and Torrance Small showed the Patriots
what a touchdown connection is, and the Eagles were winging away,
17-6.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's later drop in crunch time was merely another statistical
insult for Bledsoe, who again showed he lacks one talent. Pointing
fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't know what happened to us,'' he said. ``It's not a
good sign, and this has been going on for a while. (The game) was
certainly one to forget. If we could have taken away those three
turnovers in the first half and the points off the board, we would
have been right in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bledsoe well knows there are no givebacks in the NFL, just
giveaways _ of which the Patriots totaled seven. In other words, it
was business as usual for them, though they won't have a chance to
employ it much longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're done,'' said Bledsoe. ``Obviously, it's hard to put
into words how disheartening this is. We were playing from behind.
They blitzed us the entire game, and we just weren't prepared for
it. I don't have the answer for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes he does.
</P>
<P>
   He's just too classy _ or shellshocked _ to acknowledge it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
