<HEADER>
A3915 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-EAGLES-DETMER-BOS     12-20 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-EAGLES-DETMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETMER MANAGES PASSING GRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ All day long, it seemed, his passes were hitting
either paydirt or dirt. There was no happy medium for Eagles
quarterback Koy Detmer, no semblance of consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, that was perfectly understandable, because there was
no frame of reference, either.
</P>
<P>
   A bona fide journeyman, Detmer had spent the first 14 games of
the season entrenched as the Eagles' third-string quarterback. The
disaster quarterback, in NFL parlance.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of disasters, he had watched the two men ahead of him
in the pecking order, Doug Pederson and No. 2 overall draft choice
Donovan McNabb, guide Philadelphia to a 3-11 record. And since both
were sidelined for Sunday's game against the Patriots at Veterans
Stadium, disaster became calamity as Detmer became, for all intents
and purposes, the one and only quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Having seen no action since the first exhibition game _ and no
official action since he started the last five games of the 1998
season _ Detmer was admittedly covered with rust, as reflected in
his final numbers: 10 for 29, 181 yards.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to an even more inexperienced New England secondary,
he also found his receivers uncovered often enough that his
performance had to be adjudged a success, as reflected in these
final numbers: Eagles 24, Patriots 9.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Detmer wound up enjoying a career day. Granted, it's
been a modest career for the three-year veteran from the University
of Colorado, but three touchdown passes _ 50 and 11 yards to
Torrance Small and 44 yards to Patriots castoff Dietrich Jells _
were nothing to sneeze at.
</P>
<P>
   ``Koy came out and rose to the occasion,'' said Eagles coach
Andy Reid, ignoring the fact that the New England offense (seven
turnovers) sank to the occasion, allowing the Philadelphia defense
to hand Detmer prime opportunities all day. ``He did a nice job.
He'd be the first to tell you he was inconsistent, but that's to be
expected in a situation where he's had so few reps.''
</P>
<P>
   But Patriots cornerbacks Kato Serwanga and Tebucky Jones had
even fewer reps before they were shoved off the bench to replace
injured starters Steve Israel and Ty Law.
</P>
<P>
   And Detmer took advantage to find Small on a corner post pattern
from midfield on which Serwanga got lost in a zone defense in the
first quarter. Just when the Patriots seemed to be threatening,
pulling within 10-6 in the second quarter, Detmer hit Small on a
crossing pattern on which the receiver made a one-handed catch for
the score and a 17-6 halftime spread. Both plays came immediately
after the Philadelphia defense bequeathed the ball to Detmer in
scoring territory with interceptions of beleaguered Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man-to-man, we knew they had some new corners,'' said Detmer,
``and we wanted to take a shot at them, see what they could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Not much, as Jones proved with 1:08 left in the third quarter
when he was left flatfooted at the line of scrimmage by Jells, who
hauled in a Detmer strike over the middle and slanted into the end
zone for the coup de grace.
</P>
<P>
   Detmer, an excitable boy whose celebratory histrionics had
prompted criticism last year, commemorated his highest TD output
ever with a dance in front of the Eagles bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a high-energy kind of guy,'' said Reid, who had cautioned
Detmer to tone it down _ on the off chance he had something to
revel in _ before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about all that stuff,'' said Detmer. ``The main deal
was he didn't want it to be overzealous. He knows I like to be
emotional out there.''
</P>
<P>
   That was obvious earlier in the third quarter when Detmer rolled
and writhed in seeming agony after taking a straight-on shot from
Patriots linebacker Tedy Bruschi. Observers were counting Detmer's
body parts when he was finally helped off the field, but after a
one-play hiatus in favor of Pederson, he was back in the huddle.
The grave diagnosis: The wind had been knocked out of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know you're going to be all right,'' said Detmer, ``but
your family and everybody are worried. You feel like a sissy,
flailing around like that when there's really nothing wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Flailing also described his performance for much of the
afternoon. ``It was one of those games when I was up and down,''
said Detmer, speaking figuratively despite the Bruschi smash.
``Offensively, we didn't play terrible and we didn't play great.''
</P>
<P>
   Which qualified as a smashing success against the obliging
Patriots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
