<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-CHARGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI'S REVERSAL OF MISFORTUNE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ This was the wild and woolly week that was for the Miami
Dolphins:
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, Miami suffered its third consecutive loss in a
horrendous setback, 28-20, to the host New York Jets. Coach Jimmy
Johnson criticized quarterback Dan Marino for not taking better
care of the football. Then the Dolphins' anemic running game was
dealt another blow when Cecil Collins, a recalcitrant rookie
running back on the mend after breaking his left leg Nov. 14, was
arrested on two counts of burglary for breaking into a woman's
apartment early Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth-round draft choice who had run afoul of the law at
McNeese State and Louisiana State, Collins was released on $10,000
bail and placed on the inactive list, but he was arrested again
Friday for extradition to Louisiana, where he is expected to face
parole violations.
</P>
<P>
   That same day, troubled rookie defensive lineman Dimitrius
Underwood _ who survived an apparent suicide attempt three months
ago in East Lansing, Mich. _ was reported missing from a
psychiatric care facility into which he had voluntarily admitted
himself in nearby Sunrise, Fla. Underwood showed up at the Dolphins
training complex, met with Johnson, and was released from the team.
</P>
<P>
   So how did the Dolphins cap off the week?
</P>
<P>
   Miami engaged the San Diego Chargers in a tractor pull between
red zone-challenged offenses Sunday and snapped its three-game
losing skid with a redemptive 12-9 victory before a Pro Player
Stadium crowd of 73,765. The game, however, wasn't decided until
San Diego kicker John Carney bounced a game-tying 36-yard field
goal attempt off the left upright with 10 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins (9-5) got all 12 of their points on field goals by
Olindo Mare, who converted kicks of 32, 21, 30, and 31 yards, the
last coming off a Rich Owens forced fumble and Brock Marion
recovery that enabled Miami to break a 9-9 tie with 3:22 left in
the game. Mare, as a result, established a club scoring record with
133 points and tied the NFL single-season record for field goals
with 37.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won the game, and that's what matters,'' Mare said.
``There's more pressure in kicking a field goal to try to break a
tie for the win than there is trying to break a record.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Miami won a game without scoring a touchdown was
last Oct. 25 in a 12-9 victory over the Patriots. But when Carney,
who converted kicks of 23, 22, and 31 yards, lined up for his
fourth and final attempt, Mare was so certain it would be good he
began warming up for overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a quick story for you,'' Mare said. ``I went to kick
with Carney out in San Diego with a group of guys (during the
offseason) . . . And we kicked out there and kind of goofed around
and had a little competition. Carney was probably about 35 yards
away from a telephone pole, and we just sat back there and said,
`First one to hit it wins.' He went first and hit it, and I never
got to kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a year ago, and I'm thinking this guy's a real
professional and I'm just a kid trying to learn,'' he added.
``Believe it or not, it helps you out with little things watching
something like that. But you never even consider or think of
something like that when it happens. You just feel for the guy. I
probably feel for him more than anybody in here, but I'm happy to
win a game, too.''
</P>
<P>
   And though Miami's offense had to settle for field goals on four
red-zone opportunities, there were no arrests afterward. Johnson
released no players. And for the time being, there was no whining
on the airwaves about Jimmy and Danny and Danny and Jimmy.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the distracting events of the past week, Marino, who
completed 22 of 36 passes for 241 yards, chose to skirt the issue
during his postgame press conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``What events?'' was Marino's sharp retort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it was like a soap opera, man,'' admitted linebacker
Zach Thomas. ``You can get caught up in those distractions. You
know, everything happened this week. I'm so glad that we got that
out of our heads, because it can hurt you as a team. The Dolphins
are here to play football and not to (generate) all this negative
publicity. It can bring down your whole organization . . . It was
great to win again. It tops everything, and hopefully we can get on
a roll and get a little confidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
