<HEADER>
A3917 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-RAPTORS-LA     12-20 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-RAPTORS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS BEAT RAPTORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ So much seemed familiar Sunday as the Los Angeles
Lakers dueled the Toronto Raptors _ and that wasn't necessarily a
good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Lakers frittered away a huge lead.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, they ditched a methodical offense in favor of
too-fancy or too-rushed plays that turned into fast breaks in the
other direction.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, there were thinly veiled jabs at the Lakers' eager
young superstar for failing to stick to the game plan.
</P>
<P>
   But then, no one was complaining too loudly about any of it
because the most familiar sight of all Sunday afternoon was a
Lakers victory, 94-88 over the Raptors at the sold-out Air Canada
Centre.
</P>
<P>
   That's six wins in a row, 13 in the past 14 games and a 3-0
record on the road trip that concludes today in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased, we're very pleased,'' coach Phil Jackson said,
without sounding the part.
</P>
<P>
   Locker-room hand-wringing overshadowed any sense of
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: a 19-point, third-quarter lead that was chopped to
four points by the final minute of play _ caused in part, but not
solely, by Kobe Bryant's wildness with the ball as he tried to
outduel fellow phenom Vince Carter.
</P>
<P>
   It's a familiar issue, one Jackson discussed at length with
Bryant on Saturday during a long wait at Canadian Customs at the
Toronto Airport.
</P>
<P>
   And it will be discussed again. Though Bryant led the Lakers
with 26 points, he was 1 for 5 with a turnover in the final 10
minutes. That _ along with turnovers by Ron Harper and Rick Fox and
1-for-5 shooting by Shaquille O'Neal _ contributed to a breakdown
in the offense and 14 fast-break points for Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pleased with Kobe's effort for the first three
quarters,'' Jackson said. ``I thought that he felt like he had to
do something special at the end of the game.... It wasn't
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant admitted to getting a little caught up in a tit-for-tat
circus act with Carter, forgetting for a time the lecture Jackson
delivered 24 hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pick your spots,'' Jackson recalled telling him. ``Know the
whole team aspect rather than the individual aspect of what the
game situation is, the clock situation is. Look for your
opportunities to run, but then don't force it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant agreed with the sentiment, both before and after the
game. It was during that caused problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers took a 17-point lead into the fourth, having held the
Raptors to 35-percent shooting through three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   It was 81-66 with 7:23 to go. But Fox lost the ball on one
possession and missed a shot on the next. Then Bryant missed. Then
he tried to dunk between Davis and Kevin Willlis but got the foul
and hit his free throws.
</P>
<P>
   But then Bryant missed another long jumper (Carter dunked at the
other end). Fox bricked from 3-point range (Muggsy Bogues hit a
jumper). Harper traveled. Tracy McGrady stripped Bryant in the key.
O'Neal missed three of four free throws. Davis blocked Harper.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's free throws made it 84-80 with 1:23 left. Bryant atoned
with a jumper, and the Raptors turned to fouling (with O'Neal
safely on the bench). The Lakers survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some times a couple players got carried away out
there,'' Harper said without naming names. ``They start doing their
own thing, they get out there, dribbling the ball in between their
legs and doing their own thing. There's a time for that. There's a
time we need to learn, we need to sit down and play basketball and
put a team down and just hold them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said his chat with Jackson was positive, and said he
understands the need to show restraint. ``Oh, absolutely,'' he
said. ``I mean, there's no question about it. The better I get at
it, the better we get at it, the better we're going to be at key
situations during the contest. I'm going to get better at it, no
question....
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to get caught up in a one-on-one competition,
especially against this team, but my job on this team is to dissect
them, and find out which way we need to go in certain situations.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense again revolved around Glen Rice (22 points), Bryant
and O'Neal (24 points), but O'Neal was stewing about the final 12
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we wore down, it's that we were taking
ill-advised shots,'' he said. A problem that needed to be fixed?
``I guess.'' And was it being fixed? ``I guess. I have no idea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
