<SLUG> BC-BKW-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT-SHOOTING BC RIPS NORTHWESTERN 
</HEADLINE>
 COLLEGE-NORTHWESTERN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Once again, the Boston College women's basketball team
rolled over its opponents. And once again, the Eagles brought in
all 12 of their players as they trounced Northwestern, 86-55,
Sunday before 731 at Conte Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Five BC players scored in double figures, but it was senior
point guard Cal Bouchard who led the charge as she racked up a
season-high 25 points, including a perfect 5 of 5 from behind the
3-point line and 6 of 6 from the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   BC improved its record to 8-3, while Northwestern, which has now
lost four games in a row, fell to 2-6.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome was similar to BC's 88-52 blowout over Dartmouth
last Sunday, although it looked as if BC would have a harder time
against the Big Ten team when the Wildcats marched out to a 7-4
lead and the Eagles missed their first four shots. But then BC went
on an 11-2 run to give the Eagles a 15-9 gap and a lead they would
never relinquish.
</P>
<P>
   BC, which finished with 11 steals to Northwestern's four, had a
play worthy of a highlight film in the first half. Kim Mackie, BC's
6-foot-3-inch forward, harassed Northwestern's Tami Sears as she
threw an inbound ball. Mackie intercepted the pass and threw the
ball to BC forward Alissa Murphy, who fed it to Bouchard, who
connected for a 3-pointer to put the Eagles up by 11, 27-16.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats refused to let the Eagles have the last word,
though, and at 3:41 in the half, they went on an 11-2 run of their
own to close the gap to 30-27. But Mackie drove for a layup as the
clock wound down, and BC took a 32-27 lead at the intermission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we had a little bit of a mental breakdown, and we had
to make some adjustments,'' said BC coach Cathy Inglese.
</P>
<P>
   One of those was to have Bouchard take over the point guard
spot, which Brianne Stepherson (11 points) had assumed until she
went to the bench with four personal fouls at 15:11 in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I moved to point, and I think that freed me up to make more
shots,'' said Bouchard, who hit 14 in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when the Eagles came back after the break, they made the
first half look like a dry run and went on a 21-6 tear that put
them up by 20 at 53-33.
</P>
<P>
   Northwestern coach June Olkowski said she wasn't surprised by
BC's dominance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston College has the outside-inside punch, and they have the
attitude,'' she said. ``There is no self-doubt, there is no team
doubt, and when you have that and good coaching, you have the
winning combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Northwestern forward Leslie Schock finished with a team-high 15
points.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy added 11 points for the Eagles, and center Jamie
Cournoyer contributed 10, but the real surprise was 5-11 shooting
guard Nicole Conway, who had been averaging 13 minutes and 2.5
points a game this year. She finished with 24 minutes and a
season-high 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   Conway saw a lot of action last year when Bouchard was
sidelined, and she admitted she's had to adjust to getting reduced
playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working hard to get myself back to where I was last
year, confidence-wise,'' said Conway. ``But after I hit my first
two shots, I just went from there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
