r s BC-HKN-KINGNOTES-LADN     12-20 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURRAY ON A STAR SEARCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Three games, 23 goals-against and three losses
have brought questions about whether this Los Angeles Kings team is
any different than years past.
</P>
<P>
   It's also brought rookie coach Andy Murray his first full-blown
crisis, and Murray is leaning on the Kings' stars to pull the team
out of a disastrous funk.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Kings practiced Sunday at Staples Center, Murray
pulled Rob Blake, Garry Galley, Sean O'Donnell and Luc Robitaille
in for individual meetings to discuss the psyche and direction of
the club. After practice, Murray spoke with the remaining players
individually.
</P>
<P>
   Murray challenged the Kings' marquee players _ primarily Blake,
Robitaille, Ziggy Palffy and goalie Stephane Fiset _ to carry the
Kings out of this three-game slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trusting each other,'' Murray said. ``It's the way
we've lost them that's been alarming for us. We think our system of
play execution has been our first problem, and trusting each other
in that system of play. The second point is that our key players
have to play good. It's difficult for our other players, who are
role players, to be effective if our key players are not playing
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The third thing is we've taken a lot of pride to be tough to
play against. We're not being tough to play against right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings still have two more days of practice before playing
Wednesday at San Jose, but fundamental breakdowns in forechecking
and defensive zone coverage resulted in losses to New Jersey (7-1),
the New York Rangers (8-3) and Chicago (8-4).
</P>
<P>
   In those games, the Kings were outscored 13-1 in the first
period. It's in direct contrast to the first 30 games, in which the
Kings started strong and went 16-8-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the system that's letting us down, it's the
players,'' Blake said. ``Our game against San Jose is magnified
way, way more than if we would have won those three games. You have
to be able to stop it. In the past we haven't stopped it, and
that's what killed us during seasons. You work that hard for 30
games, you don't want to let that slip. We let it slip far enough
in three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't let it slip anymore. That's why there's meetings and
that's why there are practices.''
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel return?: After skating on the Kings' first line with
Robitaille and Vladimir Tsyplakov during practice, center Jozef
Stumpel said he expected to play against San Jose. Stumpel has been
out since Nov. 4 because of sports hernia surgery. He was supposed
to miss eight to 10 weeks but has worked his way back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel maybe I need to get a little more in game shape, but
the only way to do that is to play games,'' Stumpel said. ``Maybe
the first game I'll be great and then struggle for a couple.''
</P>
<P>
   Also: At 12:01 this morning, rosters froze for a week, so the
Kings met into the evening to discuss their plan. They are expected
to announce they have placed Galley (post-concussion syndrome) on
injured reserve and sent Dan Bylsma to Long Beach of the IHL. They
are expected to activate Stumpel and add tough-guy Bill Huard, who
is at Lowell of the AHL.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Palffy (back) and Jason Blake (post-concussion
syndrome) both received treatment rather skating in practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
