<HEADER>
A3921 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN     12-20 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN HEIRS IN WAITING STRUT THEIR STUFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The game within the game Sunday was, in a manner of
speaking, the Battle of the Heirs.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant of the Los Angeles Lakers and Vince Carter of the
Toronto Raptors, both young, athletic, superbly gifted, versatile
and charismatic, both possible heirs to Michael Jordan went head to
head for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The lockout-shortened schedule prevented a meeting last season,
Carter's first in the NBA. Bryant's broken hand prevented a matchup
in November. When they finally did go head to head, it was hardly
by design.
</P>
<P>
   Carter plays small forward, not shooting guard, and Lakers coach
Phil Jackson didn't intend for Bryant to guard him as much as he
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kobe just gravitated over there,'' Jackson said. ``I
wanted to go with Kobe on Carter at one point in the ballgame, and
I did make that change. I think Kobe liked the challenge and took
it (further).''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's team won behind his 26 points on 9-for-20 shooting.
Carter scored a game-high 29 on 11-for-28 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The smack talk was a draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit his shot and I'd say, `Aw that was a B.S. shot, and I
come down and hit a shot and he says, `Aw, that was a B.S. shot,''
Bryant said. ``We just go back and forth, just talk and have a good
time. ... Definitely, you like to talk a litle bit. Him, J.R.
(Rider) and a couple other guys that I know and I'm familiar with,
I like to talk to them sometimes. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just pure competition, that's all. I wanted to see what
he got, I'm sure he wanted to see what I got. Just playing him,
denying him the basketball, making him do something else. It was
just fun. I mean, we're going to be in this league for a long, long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant was asked what Carter brings to the court. ``He's got
some game.'' And Bryant? ``I got a lot of game.''
</P>
<P>
   Weary: The Raptors' late charge Sunday prevented Jackson from
resting his starters, and the Lakers showed some signs of fatigue
after playing their third game in four nights. But they can sweep
the road trip with a win over the Boston Celtics tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of got the idea of playing well together on the road
and feel confident about what we're doing,'' Jackson said. ``It's
just that right now we're playing a little bit in fits and spurts
and we've got to get a little more smooth in our overall game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics, though sub-.500, present a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that's going to be a pressing, trapping, up-tempo
(team), and we're going to have to be very strong,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
