<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSIDERING PARITY IN THE NFL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's parity-free edition of The Sporting Muse:
</P>
<P>
   To the NFL, parity is a good thing. To many fans, it should be
one of comedian George Carlin's seven nasty words.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of an upside-down NFL was kind of cool at
mid-season. Didn't we all snicker at a thought of a Rams-Colts
Super Bowl showdown? But now that December is here, that matchup
may be the best prospect, and the only thing inspiring laughter are
the playoff dreams of bluebloods like the Cowboys and Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Teams like the Cowboys, Redskins, Dolphins and Seahawks are
still alive according to the league's coroners, but they are merely
postponing the inevitable. Anyone believing the Dolphins are on
track for a Dan Marino Super Bowl appearance has been watching
``Ace Ventura'' too much. ...
</P>
<P>
   Here's how things will likely shake out:
</P>
<P>
   AFC: Indy (12-2, East), Jacksonville (13-1, Central) and
Tennessee (11-3, wild card) are in. Buffalo and Miami, both 9-5,
look safe as wild cards. That leaves Kansas City (9-5) and Seattle
(8-6) to settle the west next week.
</P>
<P>
   Caveats to this: Miami, the worst 9-5 team ever, has to play the
Jets this week and Washington next. Buffalo has the Colts in their
finale. Seattle holds a tiebreaker edge if they tie with K.C.
Tennessee- Jacksonville play for show this week. K.C. shouldn't
test fate with a finale scheduled against the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   NFC: St. Louis (12-2, West) is on the pole. If this was the
Kentucky Derby, everyone else would be a field horse.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay (9-5, Central) controls its fate, but has the Packers
and Bears left. The Lions (8-6) are hanging on, but have the
Broncos and Vikes left. The Packers (7-6) need tonight's game more
than the Vikings (7-6), since the Vikes should win their last two
(Giants, Lions left.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the NFC East is the Big West of pro football.
Washington (8-6, East) has the 49ers and Dolphins left. A split
won't win them the division if Dallas (7-7, Saints and Giants) wins
out, but it would be enough if the Giants win out (Vikes, Cowboys).
Carolina (7-7) should finish 9-7 with the Steelers and Saints left,
but most of the tiebreakers work against them. They need several
teams to fall apart. ...
</P>
<P>
   Ruminations after 15 weeks:
</P>
<P>
   Miami is the worst 9-5 team ever, and they're also schizoid. Six
of their nine wins have been by a touchdown or less. They've scored
30 points or more four times, but 17 points or less in six of their
last nine games. Jimmy Johnson was warned before taking the job
that he and Marino couldn't co-exist, and the '99 season proves it.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore has won five of its last seven, and the two losses
were to the Jags. They started their run too late to earn a playoff
spot, but they're definitely a team to watch in '00. Think
Cleveland regrets not hiring Brian Bilick? The Ravens coach is
winning with Tony Banks.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams may be this season's version of NFL serendipity. More
than one person close to the organization confides that the players
were split over Dick Vermeil at the beginning of the season, and
that no one had a clue Kurt Warner would play like this.
</P>
<P>
   Banks and Steve Beuerlein are Exhibits 1 and 1-A in the case for
keeping veteran quarterbacks handy. And I guess Jon Kitna isn't the
new Brett Favre, either.
</P>
<P>
   Al Davis would be crazy to fire Jon Gruden, which is a rumor
around the league. The '99 Raiders haven't been able to finish
games, but Gruden has the team playing hard and with better
fundamentals in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   And anyone who was around the Raiders when Gunther Cunningham
was defensive coordinator isn't shocked to see the Chiefs where
they are. Cunningham is as tough as he is bright, and he sold the
Chiefs on his macho philosophy. The only hedge is that macho
tactics often have a short lifespan. ...
</P>
<P>
   I have less of a problem with UCLA getting soundly beat by
Gonzaga than the Bruins putting the Morgan State's of the
basketball world on their schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Games like those are of little value to anyone. Where's the
test? It's impossible to judge a team's progress against an
outclassed opponent like that. All it did was fed the ego of Steve
Lavin's young team and create an unreasonable expectation once they
met a good team, like Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   The DePaul win was a good win. But the Bruins haven't shown
anything that makes one believe they can beat Stanford and Arizona.
This team is a year older, but it still plays young. ...
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Jason Kapono will be a force this year, and the Bruins
depth will improve once JaRon Rush and Matt Barnes get cleared to
play. But center Dan Gadzuric will define the Bruins' success. If
he's healthy and plays strong inside, the Bruins can play deep into
the tournament. ...
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Morgan's 49ers are never going to play pretty basketball,
but then there's not a whole lot of beauty in the sport these days.
Basketball has become a tug-o-war; he who holds tightest and grunts
the loudest wins.
</P>
<P>
   The win over USC came on the backs of the 49ers stubborn inside
game -- Mate Milisa is looking like a first-round NBA pick, and
James Williams has been a great addition -- and Morgan's good
fortune in having a fleet of guards to rotate and wear down
opponents. ...
</P>
<P>
   Getting to the Final Four a year after saying goodbye to Misty
May almost says more about the state of Brian Gimmillaro's program
than any of their three national titles. The 49ers never rebuild,
they just reload. ...
</P>
<P>
   Today's question du jour: The only endeavor in which screaming
is considered an effective tool is in the military. So why do so
many basketball coaches scream at the top of their lungs? It can't
always because of the din of the crowd, because I see coaches
scream in huddles.
</P>
<P>
   I can't ever remember hearing John Wooden, Red Auerbach or Bill
Sherman scream during a game. ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
