<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS HAVE HIT A ROAD BLOCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 30 games the script was perfect. An embattled hockey team
moves into a state-of-art arena and is reborn. Instead of being the
butt of jokes, it becomes the talk of the town. The more it plays
the more it convinces people it's for real.
</P>
<P>
   At one point the Kings led the NHL in points, and despite the
loss of Luc Robitaille, Jozef Stumpel and Stephane Fiset for
extended periods of time they were still riding high in the Pacific
Division and Western Conference standings as recently as six days
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Murray was a leading coach of the year contender, Rob Blake
was being touted for his second Norris Trophy and Zigmund Palffy --
well, maybe he wasn't Wayne Gretzky, but to Los Angeles'
star-starved fans he was close.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, however, the positives seem like distant memories
after a disastrous three-game stretch that made one realize that
the Kings are still the franchise that probably lost a Stanley Cup
title because of an illegal stick, made an artform of trading away
high draft choices that other teams turned into stars, and one that
had only 11 .500 or better finishes in its first 32 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings took their league-leading road show -- they still have
the NHL's best road record -- to the New York area last week and
their act was off off-Broadway in less than 48 hours as they were
routed by good New Jersey team, 7-1, on Tuesday and then humilated
by a bad Rangers team, 8-3, a night later.
</P>
<P>
   And just when when it didn't seem like it could get any worse,
they brought their pathetic act back home and were embarrassed by
Chicago, 8-4, in front of a sellout crowd at Staples Center on
Saturday. The same Blackhawks team that barely managed a scoring
chance in a 2-0 loss to the Mighty Ducks on Friday, a Chicago team
that had only 22 points (third worst in the league) heading into
the game.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a shocking turn of events for a team that looked
poised to turn things up a notch with the return of Blake, Palffy,
Robitaille and Fiset to the lineup. Losing three games in a row is
one thing, but not being competitive is another, especially for a
team that had outscored its opponets 95-73 in the first 30 games.
</P>
<P>
   It's even harder to understand when one realizes the Kings
haven't been playing the NHL's offensive elite. No, it hasn't been
Jaromir Jagr, Teemu Selanne, Paul Kariya, Eric Lindros and Pavel
Bure who have been lighting the lamp. No, it has been guys like
Todd Harvey (3 goals this season), John MacLean (3), Kevin Stevens
(3), Jean-Pierre Dumont (7), Doug Zmolek (2) and Dave Manson (1)
who have seemingly destroyed the Kings' confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who admits his team has ``reached rock bottom'' now
faces his biggest challenge yet -- restoring the confidence of a
team that looked shaken to the core Saturday night. Three games
certainly don't make or break a season, but three embarrassing
losses can send a team into a downward spiral that take a long,
long time to pull out of. And no team in the Western Conference can
afford an extended slump, especially one that has qualified for
postseason play only once in the last six seasons. &QL; 
--
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, down in Orange County the Ducks are very slowly, but
surely, beginning to believe they might be more than just a .500
team. Heading into Sunday's game with old nemsis Detroit the Ducks
were three games over .500 and spirits were high among a group that
at times had looked surprisingly uninspired this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had our ups and downs this season, but the rewards are
starting to come,'' said Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg, who has
defended his team all along, saying it was going through a learning
process. ``We know we are on the right track and the guys are
excited about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are having a lot more fun that six weeks ago and we just
have to keep plugging away, keep progressing.''
</P>
<P>
   One area in which the Ducks have certainly progressed in is
defense. Anaheim came into Sunday's game as the NHL's third best
defensive team, allowing (2.18 goals a game).
</P>
<P>
   Despite the presence of Selanne and Kariya the Ducks don't score
a lot (2.5 goals a game), but Hartsburg has convinced even his
biggest stars that they must play both ends of the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are starting to play the way Craig wants us to play and
that's why we are having success,'' said Kariya, who was second in
the league with a plus-21 rating going into the Detroit game.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne, who scored 76 goals as a rookie, hasn't been a scoring
machine this season (14 goals going into Sunday's game), but he was
among the league leaders as well with a plus-17 rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should always win when we limit teams to two goals or
less,'' said Selanne. ``We are playing smart defensively and our
line has to be the example.''
</P>
<P>
   The third member of the Ducks' No. 1 line is also doing a lot of
little things right. Steve Rucchin was plus-12 and leads the league
in faceoffs won.'' &QL; 
--
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt that Jagr is most talented player in the
NHL. His totals of 25 goals and 53 points in 29 games speak for
themselves. But you can't help but wonder about his priorities
sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr recently won the war with former coach Kevin Constantine
when owner Mario Lemieux and GM Craig Patrick fired the man who
somehow kept the Penguins together, and more than competitive, the
last two seasons as the franchise struggled through bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr, it seems, wasn't happy with the defensive-minded system
that Constantine used, and he was more than willing to air his
opinions in public.
</P>
<P>
   Not wanting their meal ticket to be unhappy, Pittsburg hired
Herb Brooks, he of ``Miracle of Ice'' fame. The former U.S. Olympic
coach may employ the wide-open system that Jagr favors, but don't
expect any miracles in Pittsburgh come playoff time. Like it or
not, teams have to play defense to win Stanley Cup championships
these days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
