<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS QUICK TO COME TO EACH OTHER'S DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Paul Kariya and Chris Chelios, buddies from
Chelios' days in Chicago, got together several times in Sunday's
game. This time it was the Ducks captain who seemed to get under
the Detroit defenseman's skin.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya, who is more and more to defend himself, appeared to get
away with a high stick in the second period and Chelios responded
by taking a roughing penalty. At the end of the period the two went
at it again lios took a run at Kariya and put a hard, clean
check on him. But the Ducks quickly came to Kariya's aid and
Chelios and Jason Marshall were both assessed 10-minute misconducts
following the scrum that once again involved Teemu Selanne.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne and the rest of the Ducks are very quick to come each
other's defense these days, no matter who is involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend a lot of time together and we are becoming a very
close-knit team,'' said Kariya. ``Not every team has to be close to
be successful, but when you care about the guy next to you, you
want to play hard for them.'' &QL; 
--
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks have avoided major injuries to their so-called core
players. Among the group of Selanne, Kariya, Guy Hebert, Steve
Rucchin and Oleg Tverdovsky, only Kariya (1) and Selanne (3) have
missed time due to injury.
</P>
<P>
   But the Ducks' role players have been hit hard with injuries and
suspensions and it has tested Anaheim's questionable depth.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim went into Sunday's game minus forwards Antti Aalto and
Mike Leclerc and defensemen Pavel Trnka and Pascal Trepanier. Aalto
has missed six games with a strained elbow and isn't expected back
until after New Year's. Leclerc, who had elbow surgery and missed
12 games earlier this season, reaggravated the elbow last Friday
and is out idefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Trepanier suffered a concussion Friday when his head hit the ice
after running into Chicago's Tony Amonte. Trnka is close to
returning, but he has missed the last five games with a groin
strain.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Kevin Haller and forward Jim McKenzie are back, but
both have missed considerable time. Haller has missed 13 games due
to knee problems and McKenzie was out nine games with a broken hand
and also served a four-game suspension early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Trepanier has missed four games due to suspension and Ruslan
Salei was suspended for 10 games. &QL; 
--
</P>
<P>
   Marty McInnis, like the most of the Ducks, has had his share of
ups and downs, but like the rest of the team he has been on the
upswing recently.
</P>
<P>
   The winger had a career-high three assists in Sunday's game and
has seven points in seven games after having only two in the
previous 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim power play came into the game ranked 26th in the
league, but like the team it's getting better. Kariya's power play
goal in the second period extended the unit's scoring streak to a
season-high four games. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
