<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 03:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3942 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-GAYS-CAMPAIGN-SFCHRON     12-20 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-CAMPAIGN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ANALYSIS: ON CAMPAIGN TRAIL, GAYS STILL VIEWED AS LIABILITIES  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is the best and worst of times for gay politics
on the presidential campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   For all their softened rhetoric on homosexuality, Republican
presidential candidates remain opposed to virtually every piece of
legislation important to gay groups. Democrats, who are openly
jostling for gay support, refuse to even consider the notion of
same-sex marriage.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy for advocates of gay causes to get lost in their
successes. Everyone agrees that this field of presidential
aspirants accepts gays more than ever before and that gay issues
have assumed a more prominent role than in any previous
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the limits to what politicians will support
have never been more noticeable. The concerns are especially acute
in regard to the Republican field, where no candidate endorses
basic gay causes, such as a ban on job discrimination or passage of
a hate-crimes law. But even the Democrats appear fearful of too
tight an embrace with a group that has been ostracized for
centuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rhetoric has become more benign, but the serpents are live
and well below the surface,'' warned Elizabeth Birch, executive
director of Human Rights Campaign, the nation's largest gay
lobbying group, quickly adding that her greatest fears involve GOP
front-runner George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic issues that affect gays and lesbians have moved like
a rocket ship in this decade ... but we still have a long ways to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the issue was the military's policy of permitting
homosexuals to serve as long as they do not disclose their
sexuality. Vice President Al Gore, following the lead of first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton, characterized President Clinton's ``don't
ask, don't tell'' policy as a failure and called for its
elimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gays and lesbians should be allowed to serve their country
without discrimination,'' Gore said, as campaign aides e-mailed
news clippings to reporters showing that the vice president has
opposed the policy all along.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore, like his Democratic rival Bill Bradley, believes that
while the military should be open to gays, marriage should not.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; A Different Category
</P>
<P>
   The vice president ``supports domestic partnerships, (but) we
don't think they should be put in the same category as traditional
marriages,'' said Gore spokesman Chris Lehane.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who speaks passionately on the stump about ending
discrimination against gays, agrees that the line should be drawn
at marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just been my view that there is a sufficient body of
religious opinion that marriage is a sacrament,'' Bradley explained
in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The position rankles some gay leaders, who understand the
political necessity of opposing gay marriage but see no
intellectual honesty to their argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take a very courageous politician to lead the way,''
said Rebecca Isaacs, political director for the National Gay and
Lesbian Task Force. ``We don't have that person yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Isaacs and other gay leaders say there is a world
of difference between Democrats _ who support domestic
partnerships, hate-crimes legislation, more AIDS funding and
federal protection against job discrimination _ and Republicans,
whose party has a legacy of hostility toward gays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the perception eight, even four years ago, was that
you could gay bash and that it would be a plus. I don't think
that's working today,'' said Rich Tafel, executive director of the
gay Log Cabin Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best illustration of the low expectations for
Republicans among some gay groups is the almost gushing support for
Arizona Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   McCain impressed some gays for his successful efforts in the
Senate to kill legislation sponsored by former Orange County Rep.
Bob Dornan that would have forced anyone with AIDS out of the
military. He also has stood up for openly gay staff members and
endorsed gay candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain rejects nearly all of the legislative proposals
advocated by gay leaders. His biggest difference with Bush is
simply his willingness to sit down and talk with gay Republicans
and ask for their support, despite his refusal to endorse their
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am unashamed, unembarrassed and proud to work with you,`
McCain told the group, according to participants in the meeting
that was held last month.
</P>
<P>
   McCain told the group that he would work to eliminate prejudice,
but when asked the next week by a reporter how he would do so, he
provided few details.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to enforce existing laws and pursue programs (to
eliminate discrimination),'' he said. ``I also think the president
can use his bully pulpit to appeal to our better angels.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush prompted an angry response from gays for his refusal to
meet with the Log Cabin Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a person's sexual orientation is their personal
business and should not be politicized,'' Bush explained earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why then he agreed to meet with a Jewish Republican group
days before, he hardly budged from his original answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I meant to say personal and private,'' Bush said. ``It's
private as far as I'm concerned. I don't want to politicize
someone's private life.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Mixed Signals
</P>
<P>
   Gay critics point with alarm to Bush's support for Texas
legislation that would have banned gay adoptions and his failure to
support a state hate-crimes bill. Bush has also caused concern by
giving mixed signals on gay political appointments. After saying in
a newspaper interview that he would not discriminate, he reportedly
told religious leaders in a meeting that he would not appoint
anyone who is openly gay.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, by contrast, criticized his Senate colleagues for taking
so long to confirm San Francisco philanthropist James Hormel, who
is openly gay, as ambassador to Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their differences with the gay community, Bush and
McCain are seen as the tolerant edge of the GOP field. Their
rivals, with the exception of Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch, have toed a
much harder line against gays.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes said he would allow gays in his administration, but
added: ``If a person wants a job to make a statement, they won't
get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, only partly tongue-in-cheek, said he cannot imagine
why anyone who is gay would ever want to serve in his
administration, and said he would worry about their mental health
if they did. Alan Keyes refers to homosexuality as ``an
abomination.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At least Bradley and Gore are coming out into the sunlight,''
Birch said. ``The Republicans are caught somewhere back in a
depressing rain shower.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 0331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
