<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 03:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3943 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     12-20 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BREAKING NEWS FROM THE ZOOKEEPER AT SFO  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's a busy time at good old SFO (Sardines
Freaking Out), so busy that airport manager Kim Dickie doesn't have
time to translate her thoughts into standard bureaucratese.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a zoo,'' Dickie said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But every time I go to the zoo, it's uncrowded and
peaceful, the animals are calm and playful and well-fed, and
nobody's weeping or swearing.
</P>
<P>
   Although I do remember one time when the zoo was very crowded,
tempers were short and nerves frazzled, and I heard one monkey tell
another, ``Man, this place is an  &UR; airport.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Dickie also said of SFO (and stop the presses), ``There are tons
of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means, you travelers, that you've been eating way too much
of that sumptuous airport food.
</P>
<P>
   If it's any consolation to folks lost in the SFO Triangle, it's
nice to reflect on the continuity of mankind's adventures. We came
into the 20th century struggling to fly, and we're going out the
same way.
</P>
<P>
   OUT OF HER TREE: Congratulations to Butterfly, who came down
from her perch in a redwood tree named Luna in Humboldt County,
Calif., and now that tree can be turned into newsprint for this
column praising her. The circle of life.
</P>
<P>
   Could be a trend. What if one of the fur-coat protesters at
Neiman Marcus were to climb the giant N-M atrium Christmas tree and
camp out at the top? What if Terence Hallinan and Bill Fazio were
to camp together at the top of the Union Square Christmas tree to
protest the slow vote count?
</P>
<P>
   But seriously, what Butterfly did was amazing. I hope the
Pacific Lumber people honor their agreement to change the company
name to Pacific Serial Tree Murderers &AMP; Land Rapists.
</P>
<P>
   YOU CAN'T put your kids in the front seat of the car, because
they'll be injured by air bags. Now a study shows that they're not
safe in the back seat, either, because they can get injured by the
front seat.
</P>
<P>
   New best option: roof racks.
</P>
<P>
   I AM TIBURON, hear me roar: An item last week told of the
opening of an In-N-Out burger palace in Tiburon, the suburban
enclave north of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong on several counts.
</P>
<P>
   Error I: In-N-Out isn't a restaurant, it's a religious shrine.
I've witnessed miracles at In-N-Out, like opening the bag and
finding it filled with exactly what I ordered.
</P>
<P>
   Error II: This particular In-N-Out isn't in Tiburon, after all.
It's between Mill Valley and Tiburon in an unincorporated place
known as Strawberry. Every person in Tiburon e-mailed or phoned me
to alert me to my stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   Error III: This isn't the only In-N-Out without a drive-thru
window. There's one in Placentia.
</P>
<P>
   Error IV: Tiburones would  &UR; never  &LR; allow an In-N-Out on their
soil. Their policy on such matters is NIMBY (Not In-vicinity-of My
Big Yacht). If a tacky burger franchise muscled its way into
Tiburon, the citizens would commit mass suicide by jumping into the
bay from the roof of Sam's Anchor Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, I sense a strong undercurrent of inter-village
hostility. Tiburones are peeved at being mistaken for their tacky
neighbors, and Strawberrians feel they got stuck with a busy, noisy
burger barn that is now being frequented by smug Tiburones.
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned, it could get ugly.
</P>
<P>
   THOUSANDS DIE every year in veterans hospitals around the
country due to goofs.
</P>
<P>
   The mistakes, according to the news story, include ``surgery on
the wrong body part or wrong patient,'' and ``therapeutic
misadventures.''
</P>
<P>
   This story has TV sitcom written all over it. High concept: a
cross between ``ER'' and ``Pardon My Blooper,'' to be called
``ERR.''
</P>
<P>
   KIDS UNDER 10, please skip this item. (But thanks for reading
this far.)
</P>
<P>
   Barring political intervention, Santa Claus will be fried in an
electric chair Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   There's a new high-tech horror revue opening at the Union Square
Playhouse, ``Squished Eyeball Theater.'' It includes the world's
only simulated electric-chair execution, the guillotining of an
audience member and Elvis rising from the dead (I know he's not
dead, but use your imagination).
</P>
<P>
   Sure to be the feel-good entertainment hit of the winter.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa bit is just a cheap publicity stunt. Producer Bob
Pritikin is hoping Willie Brown or one of the two DA candidates
will come on over and ``pardon'' Old Saint Nick.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a wise political move to me. Then maybe the pol can
get naked and take a shower with the exhumed Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   AND THIS is spooky: You mention Elvis in one item and boom, he
pops up again in the next item.
</P>
<P>
   In the Carmel, Calif., Pine Cone's police and sheriff's log,
this entry (spotted by Daryl Glen): ``Woman reported someone
entering her locked car in the Lodge parking lot, without force,
and removing an Elvis cassette. When asked to check her car again
to look for the cassette, she found it in the cassette deck, but
assured the deputy that it had not been there before. Nothing
further.''
</P>
<P>
   That is truly eerie. Sounds like a case for Scully and Mulder.
Or Toody and Muldoon. Ooh! Ooh!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
