<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Trouble in the back seat
 &HT;    (For release Dec. 22, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This subject should not be treated lightly but it is a
head-scratcher. It is, in the coinage of the recently late Joseph
Heller, a Catch-22. It is about where in automobiles children ought
to be sitting _ or, rather, where they should not be sitting.
</P>
<P>
   For some time, it was judged that children should not be sitting
in the front seat because of erupting air bags in an accident. Now,
according to a study done by the Los Angeles Times, they also
should not be sitting in the back seat, this based on unsubstantial
front seats that pitch backwards.
</P>
<P>
   If we are to accept both cautions, then where are the kids going
to sit?
</P>
<P>
   In earlier years, with four children, there have been
aggravating times when I conjured stashing them in the trunk, but
eventually dismissed it because of a lack of air holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every action there is always opposed an equal reaction,''
Sir Isaac Newton told us hundreds of years ago. It didn't take an
apple hitting me in the head to recognize the genius of Newton's
observation.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly anything happens today where someone or something else
does not counter with an equally plausible theory.
</P>
<P>
   The study of children in automobile back seats certainly ranks
there.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety reported
that properly restrained children in the back seat have the lowest
crash death rates. And likely that remains accurate.
</P>
<P>
   But just when you were beginning to think your kids were safe,
they aren't _ as least not according to this study. While including
a caveat that the back seat still is the safest place in the car,
statistics are presented that show the danger of putting your child
there.
</P>
<P>
   The Times found at least six children in the 1990s who were
killed while seated _ and restrained _ in the back seats of
automobiles. They were victims of front seats collapsing backwards
in accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``While federal authorities issued air bag warnings in 1995
after the deaths of eight children,'' wrote the Times, ``it has not
notified consumers about the back seat hazard.''
</P>
<P>
   Factory-made warnings are posted on the sun visors of my
late-model automobile, to wit: Children under 12 can be killed by
air bags; they should be in the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who are safety-conscious have banned children from
the front seats in response to the warnings. But now comes a
warning from the back.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, there are collisions where neither front seat nor
back is safe, either for children or adults, but given the small
fender benders or rear-enders, the driving public ought to feel
safe.
</P>
<P>
   The matter of a collapsing front seat is both a bureaucratic and
industry lapse. For 33 years, federal motor vehicle safety
regulations have not been adequate to prevent seat collapse. The
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration has conceded that
but done nothing about it.
</P>
<P>
   Some auto manufacturers have reacted by strengthening their
front seats and the bolts that hold them to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   A susceptible public becomes bleary under the weight of the
endless studies that tell us that what was good for us then is not
now or what was not good for us then isn't so bad compared to the
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Good parents want their children safe. They'll put them anywhere
in the automobile that assures that. As a result of this recent
study, there is no such place. It's another classic example of
choosing one's poison.
</P>
<P>
   If it is true that automobile manufacturers can remedy the back
seat problem by making better and stronger front seats, then let
them voluntarily choose to do it. Failing that, the federal
regulations need to be revamped and imposed on them.
</P>
<P>
   Parents forever will be taking their children somewhere, to
school, to church, to the movies, to grandma. We need to know they
will be safe, not victimized by an air bag or a collapsing front
seat.
</P>
<P>
   Is that too much to ask?
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
