<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The U.N.'s anti-Israel slant
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The United Nations has no standing in the Israeli-Syrian or
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks but there's a way the U.N. could be
helpful even so. It could get off Israel's back.
</P>
<P>
   In more diplomatic but still firm language, that was the message
from U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan in a recent speech. Annan
was repeating, with new emphasis, a point he first made on a visit
to Israel last year.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. effectively created Israel by partitioning the old
Palestine Mandate into predominantly Arab and predominantly Jewish
parts in 1947. Israel was an enthusiastic participant in the world
body until Soviet Cold War politics, in trouble-making cahoots with
Arab and Muslim animus, turned a U.N. majority against Israel after
it won the 1967 Six-Day War, the second of three that Arab states
launched trying to destroy Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, U.N. majorities have pounded on Israel like a manic
drummer.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has tried to force Israel to settle with the
Arab states on Arab terms. It annually passes old and new
resolutions favoring Palestinian interests and condemning Israeli
actions and positions.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. has provided a willing forum for vicious anti-Semitism,
like the 1991 claim there by the Syrian ambassador that Jews kill
Christian children to use their blood in making matzoh or the
charge in 1997 by the Palestinian representative that Israel was
injecting Palestinian children with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for 16 years, until it repealed the notorious resolution
in1991, the U.N. offically declared Zionism a form of racism and
only last year did it finally recognize anti-Semitism as a human
rights offense. U.N. ``Special Committees'' and ``Palestinian
Units'' still churn out and distribute anti-Israel propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   Crucially, alone of all member nations, Israel has been denied
membership in any of the U.N.'s five regional groups.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, it is barred from participating and voting in most
major U.N. organizations and from being elected as a non-permanent
member of the Security Council. Israel has always been shut out of
the Asian group, which includes all other Mideast states, and now
its bid to join the European group is on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has a government keen to do deals with Syria and the
Palestinians. Negotiations on both fronts are at critical stages,
with the best chance yet that each might come to fruition. For that
to happen, however, Israel will have to make painful and, to a
degree, even risky decisions about ceding buffering territory. And
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has said he will submit any
Syrian treaty to a referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The issues will be settled _ if they are setttled _ by hard
negotiations, not good vibes. But the atmosphere for making
compromises and especially for public endorsement of the
compromises would be helped if, as Annan has urged, the U.N.
stopped indulging gratuitous grandstanding against Israel and
admitted Israel to full United Nations participation.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
