<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIG-MOON21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big, bright moon to welcome new year
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In recognition of Western civilization's
frenzied quest to find a divine _ or, at least, cosmic _ sign that
the end of the millennium approaches, try this:
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is alight with e-mails declaring that Wednesday
night's last full moon of the millennium will be the brightest
first night of winter in 133 years, perhaps portending disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Startlingly bright,'' said Jack Horkheimer, director of the
Miami Space Transit Planetarium. ``The moon will be brightest at
midnight almost directly overhead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Biggest, brightest and baddest,'' joked Erich Landstrom,
director of astronomy education at the South Florida Science Museum
in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Remember what happened the night of Dec. 21, 1866: Crazy Horse
and the Lakota Sioux took advantage of the bright moonlight to
ambush and kill 80 U.S. soldiers in the Wyoming territory.
</P>
<P>
   A moon so bright that in the snow-covered north, car headlights
won't be needed.
</P>
<P>
   A moon so close that the Old Farmer's Almanac warns of
abnormally high tides and coastal flooding.
</P>
<P>
   All the result of a cosmic triple coincidence of perigee,
solstice, syzygy and near perihelion _ that is, when the moon and
earth are closest, on the first day of winter, in a straight line
with the sun and when the earth is almost at its closest to the
sun.
</P>
<P>
   But not so fast, say astronomers and meteorologists.
</P>
<P>
   The millennium moon is not don't-stare-directly-at-the-moon
bright and most folks won't be able to discern that it's larger
than July's full moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is the width of a small fingernail held at
arm's length,'' Landstrom said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell if you could get two full moons side by side
but that doesn't happen very often,'' said Geoff Chester of the
U.S. Naval Observatory in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what will happen Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   The winter solstice occurs at 2:44 a.m., when the North Pole
tilts the farthest away from the sun, marking the beginning of
winter in the northern hemisphere and the shortest daylight of the
year. The moon will travel almost directly overhead.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:55 a.m., the moon reaches perigee in its elliptical orbit
around the earth _ its closest approach of the year to the earth at
220,000 miles, thereby causing its greatest effect on the tides.
The moon will be 14 percent closer to earth than in July, when it
is at its apogee, or farthest distance from the earth.
</P>
<P>
   At 12:31 p.m., the moon becomes full and at syzygy (SIZZ ah
gee), meaning the earth is sandwiched between the sun and moon in a
nearly straight line, also causing the highest and lowest tides of
the month. Wednesday night is when you will see the full moon.
</P>
<P>
   Perihelion occurs Jan. 3, when earth is closest to the sun, 91.4
million miles, increasing the sunlight reaching the moon by 7
percent over July.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a cool combination of things, and the poet in me loves
it,'' said Sten Oldenwald, an astronomer at the Goddard Space
Flight Center in Maryland. ``But it is not particularly rare.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the happenstance hasn't happened on the same day in 133
years, it happens within 24 hours about every 19 years or so. It
last occurred in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   MOON VISIBLE FOR 13 HOURS
</P>
<P>
   The difference between low and high tides Wednesday and Thursday
will be about 4.1 feet, the widest range of the year, said Jim
Lushine of the National Weather Service in Miami. The typical range
is about 3 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who have to worry are boaters who might bottom out
or get stuck on shoals at low tide,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The shortest day of the year means the longest night. The moon
will be visible for nearly 13 hours, from 5:49 p.m. Wednesday to
6:46 a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real wow factor is when the moon rises above the horizon,
that's when it looks the largest,'' said Chester of the Naval
Observatory. ``It's an optical illusion. It looks large in relation
to other objects on the horizon.''
</P>
<P>
   For chroniclers of millennium events, the millennium moon isn't
one. ``It's not even the end of the millennium,'' said Chester.
</P>
<P>
   That's next year, when a a partial solar eclipse on Christmas
Day closes the year 2000 and the true end of the millennium is
marked. But that's another story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
