<HEADER>
A4023 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-LANE-COLUMN21-COX     12-20 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The hole in the comics page
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ It is still difficult for me to imagine a
newspaper without ``Peanuts.'' But that's probably because I don't
want to.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schulz recently announced he will no longer draw the
strip. He is 77, battling cancer and has drawn round-headed
children for a half century. His decision should be no surprise.
But it is.
</P>
<P>
   Schulz's work ethic and sense of craft were such that he drew
his strips himself and still has enough to last until Jan. 3. This
gives people time to get used to the idea. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   I look at the comics page and feel like an old fart. I see past
the tiny panels to what used to be there. ``The Far Side,''
``Calvin and Hobbes,'' ``Bloom County'' and others you probably
don't remember or haven't heard of. That's not counting the ones
long gone. Artifacts of ancient graphic history: ``Pogo'' _
``Pogo'' most of all _ ``Steve Canyon,'' ``Terry and the Pirates,''
``Dick Tracy'' ... .
</P>
<P>
   Comic strips insinuate themselves into your life. They are not
like other entertainments. Television series run a few months or a
year or two. You expect them to come and go. Comic strips don't
work that way.
</P>
<P>
   They are so much a part of a day's routine, so personally
comforting that even in the unsentimental newspaper business, we
expect them never to die. Each casualty is a shock and readers
write in protest.
</P>
<P>
   Immortality is a bad thing in humor. I give Schulz huge credit
for forswearing it. He won't allow anyone to take over his comic.
After he stops, his syndicate will rerun his old strips rather than
passing the franchise to less devoted hands.
</P>
<P>
   I usually skip over immortal comic strips. They exist not
because they are funny, but because they vaguely remind people of a
time when they used to amuse.
</P>
<P>
   When new artists take over a strip, it's a lot like new owners
taking over a beloved old landmark house. One of three things
happens. They will remodel and jazz it up past recognition, adding
stucco, tile roofs, satellite dishes and picture windows to a
Victorian
</P>
<P>
   exterior.
</P>
<P>
   Or they treat it like a historic site. One of those places that
look as if they were hit with a neutron bomb after everyone had
cleaned up for company. Everything looks grand but there's no life
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Or, saddest of all, they just let it slowly fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   Second-, third- and fourth-generation strips are updated in ways
that make no sense, treated as period-piece gag machines or are
simply passed hand-to-hand to artists who are successively less
interested in the job.
</P>
<P>
   It's instructive to find some of the oldest ones reprinted in
books. How strange to discover they possessed a life. That they
once were funny. It's like finding out your grandfather had a
girlfriend. And she looked hot.
</P>
<P>
   I doubt I would be writing for a newspaper were it not for the
comics page. They were what first fooled me into thinking that this
is an exciting, romantic enterprise. I started reading the comics
and only gradually got snagged into reading the rest.
</P>
<P>
   I even read the serial strips, an endangered species hardly
sighted any more except in degraded form.
</P>
<P>
   Readers are no longer assumed to have the patience, regular
habits, time and memory to follow a strip with a yearlong plot
line. Our loss.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many products of our culture, cartoons are marketed to
death. The strip that appears in the newspaper often is a mere loss
leader. More important are posters, books, TV specials, key chains,
toys, video games, cards, stickers and product endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder if a strip with the subtle, sweet-natured, beating
heart of ``Peanuts'' would make it past the gauntlet of marketing
advisors, focus groups and concept engineers that inhabit modern
media. Too low concept. It targets no identifiable demographic
segment. The gags are wistful, not yuk out loud. If submitted now
instead of in 1950, it would never fly. Every smart guy in the
building would agree.
</P>
<P>
   Without ``Peanuts,'' I worry about the comic page. Even more
than when those other strips left. Sure, the comics page still will
keep company with my cereal. But with Charlie Brown gone, I'll be
even more uncertain of whether I've gotten bigger or the page has
really gotten that much smaller.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.) News-
</P>
<P>
   Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
