<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A friend and a role model
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANDWICH, Mass. _ I have an old friend who lives in a
gray-shingled house on Cape Cod, that arm of land flexing upward
into the Atlantic just off the Massachusetts coast, its finger
pointed toward Boston. She builds garden furniture from fallen tree
limbs and has meaningful conversations with her plants.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in Gail's formative years, vowels and consonants
became confused, which explains why she calls her friends
``Ahh-thuh'' and ``Riter.'' ``Cuber'' is an island where Castro
reigns, and ``baahking'' is what the neighbor's dog does when the
``gaahbage'' truck rumbles around. Every evening for supper, she
has brie cheese on crackers, a shrimp cocktail, and just a drop or
two of pinot grigio for her stomach's sake, naturally.
</P>
<P>
   Gail and I have been friends since 1976, when we met at a
needlework school in East Townsend. I remember she had a bad
headache and missed class one day. She remembers that I neglected
to bring a long gown for our graduation dinner and so as not to
look out of place around the table, chose to wear my bathrobe _
with pearls of course.
</P>
<P>
   Gail and I have been friends through three husbands (her two, my
one) and four children (her three, my one). Now she has two
grandchildren and I have a daughter-in-law. It's been a long time
since either of us has thought about having a husband.
</P>
<P>
   Our families have been spending holidays together since the
children were small. Gail is the one who taught me to make scratch
pizza crust one snowy evening as one daughter banged noisily on the
old upright piano and the other bathed Toots the turtle in the
kitchen sink. The two boys were busy stoking a roaring blaze in the
fireplace she'd had built right after her first husband died.
</P>
<P>
   Between us we've weathered failed marriages, bouts of
self-employment, college (ours and our kids'), school teaching,
boyfriends, and sagging body parts _ not always good-naturedly, but
never without our homegrown variety of wicked humor where we can
giggle like crazy women over the latest basement flood or boyfriend
defection. Laugh or die was our motto.
</P>
<P>
   Gail paints birdhouses and substitute teaches. I write. Neither
of us understands a budget. All we know is, when we don't have it
we can't spend it. We've both been there and done that.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't bother Gail when her paintings hang crooked. I'm the
screwball who straightens pictures in public waiting rooms. We are
the original ``Odd Couple'' _ I'm Felix, she's Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   Gail's house is loaded with neat stuff _ tons of it. That's how
I learned that lavender objects placed in a southwest corner will
attract money. ``Feng shui,'' she told me, the ancient Asian folk
belief that suggests the careful arrangement of objects in a room
brings good fortune. When she was visiting last month she nestled a
sprig of lavender, a polished purple stone, and a tree
</P>
<P>
   ornament on the bookcase in the corner of my bedroom. I added a
hunk of amethyst my son had brought from Colorado. I'm not sure how
long it takes to work.
</P>
<P>
   Gail's home is filled with books and plants, and lace hanging
over the lampshades. She works jigsaw puzzles on the dining room
table and watches birds from an easy chair beside the kitchen
window. She needlepoints Christmas stockings and buys two of every
storybook _ one for the grandchildren and one for herself so she
can read to the kids over the phone while they follow along.
</P>
<P>
   Gail has always been a risk taker. She's had the courage to jump
up and bite life on the backside, and the spunk not to apologize
when she flops on hers.
</P>
<P>
   I want to be just like her when I grow up.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett (AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
