A4036 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-REPORT21-COX     12-20 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    64 Net-related business plans will be whittled to one winner
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Despite record online sales, few people except the
ones who run the pornography sites are making much money selling
stuff on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Still, venture capitalists are lending millions of dollars so
college graduates, and sometimes college dropouts, can test
e-commerce business plans.
</P>
<P>
   How can you tap that?
</P>
<P>
   Hummer Winblad partners, one of Silicon Valley's most respected
venture capital firms, is holding a business plan contest modeled
on one of our nation's greatest sports events: March Madness, the
NCAA basketball tournament, where 64 teams play their way down to
one champion.
</P>
<P>
   The contest, online at winbig.humwin.com, is soliciting business
plans from any student at any accredited school. The 64 best plans,
one per school, get to compete. The 16 finalists will have a chance
to present their plan to the Hummer Winblad folks March 23. The
winner will be named March 24.
</P>
<P>
   The idea must be Internet-related.
</P>
<P>
   THE MILLENNIUM AFTER NEXT
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago we had pretty clear ideas about what we thought
life in the 2000s would be like. The Jetsons pretty well nailed it:
cars that fly, robots that clean and meals that come in the form of
pills. None of which is all or even some of the rage yet.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe we can get better. One Web site,
www.brainticklers.com, is all about guessing what life will be like
in 3000.
</P>
<P>
   The site poses questions on issues divided by category,
including: our bodies, our cells; our planet; money and power;
technology; energy and travel; inner life; family life.
</P>
<P>
   You can search by topic, read a question and pose an answer that
stays on the site. That's one of the nicer things about the
Internet: Thanks to chat groups and message boards, the random
brilliance or random stupidity of people is given a kind of
permanence.
</P>
<P>
   One recent Q and A:
</P>
<P>
   Q: From mead to coffee, business beverages have gone from merry
to performance fuel. What will we drink at business meetings in
3000?
</P>
<P>
   A: Water.
</P>
<P>
   The site was started by Elizabeth Arnold, an entrepreneur,
writer, executive coach and feng shui consultant; and Rod
Beckstrom, chairman of a financial risk management systems company.
</P>
<P>
   A list of best of this and best of that sites
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo Internet Life has ranked the 100 best Web sites for the
new year.
</P>
<P>
   The January 2000 issue broke the sites into categories.
</P>
<P>
   The entertainment and sports rankings included:
</P>
<P>
   _ Best movie site: The Internet movie database, www.imbd.com,
now part of Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best television hub: TV Guide online, www.tvguide.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best TV network, PBS Online, www.pbs.org.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best music reference site, All Music Guide, www.allmusic.com.
</P>
<P>
   The best shopping sites included:
</P>
<P>
   _ Best place to buy event tickets, www.ticketmaster.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best job-hunting tutorial, www.rileyguide.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best place to research potential employers, www.hoovers.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best technology business news, The Industry Standard magazine
online, www.thestandard.com.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best health and fitness sites:
</P>
<P>
   _ Best medical hub, www.cbs.medscape.com. Also, www.drkoop.com
received mention.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best fitness hub, www.women.com. Also, www.phys.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best alternative medicine hub, Ask Dr. Weil, www.drweil.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best pharmaceutical index, RxList: The Internet Drug Index,
www.rxlist.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best online pharmacy, Drugstore.com, www.drugstore.com. CVS
Pharmacy's site, www.cvs.com, also was mentioned.
</P>
