<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-INNOVATION21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Software helps stockbrokers catch false claims in e-mail
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A sure thing!
</P>
<P>
   A guaranteed winner!
</P>
<P>
   100 percent safe!
</P>
<P>
   These words make frequent appearances in spam, the junk e-mail
we hate to get, usually followed by some supposedly unbeatable
offer to invest in a stock. Often, it's not clear where the
messages come from.
</P>
<P>
   But for reputable stockbrokers, they are words to avoid. In
fact, it is illegal for registered representatives of brokerage
houses to use phrases such as ``a sure thing'' in cyberspace,
according to the Securities and Exchange Commission and the
National Association of Securities Dealers, which last year issued
a notice to that effect.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers, who have been notoriously slow to accept the influence
of the Internet on their business, now have a huge burden: watching
e-mail to make sure the wrong words aren't delivered into a
client's inbox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, the (regulators) have said, `You've got to watch
over e-mail,''' said Edward Pecelli, a broker with Horner, Townsend
and Kent, a 1,400-representative brokerage in Horsham, Pa. ``You've
got to put a surveillance process into place.''
</P>
<P>
   That burden has become an opportunity for Amicus Inc., an Austin
software company that designs Web-based tools for financial
services companies, especially independent brokerages. Packaging
them with extranets, Amicus began selling a surveillance system
that throws up virtual red flags when noncompliant language appears
in an e-mail from a representative to a client.
</P>
<P>
   While Amicus has sold the application to only about a half-dozen
of its roughly 30 clients, the company is predicting it will become
more popular as more companies are faced with audits of their
communications by the SEC. Bigger investment houses have charged
their internal information technology departments with developing
similar applications.
</P>
<P>
   But the independent broker-dealers that are Amicus' customers
often can't afford a big outlay to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``They now get stuck with a job they weren't prepared to deal
with,'' said Dennis Passovoy, chief executive of Amicus. ``When
they get audited, they get told, `Figure out a way to deal with it.
Either come up with a manual system or come up with an automated
system.' That's when we get the phone call.''
</P>
<P>
   Misrepresentations by salespeople were the most common cause for
complaints that investors made to the SEC last year, and electronic
misrepresentations are becoming increasingly common.
</P>
<P>
   But for years, e-mails from brokers to clients were not governed
by the same rules that prohibit written statements that claim a
guaranteed return on investment. Typically, brokers submit copies
of letters to their compliance departments to ensure they are not
violating rules that forbid promising that a risky investment will
pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Amicus' ToolBelt 98-11 _ named for NASD Notice 98-11, which
alerted the securities industry to the rule change _ uses a search
engine to look for about 600 problem words, such as ``guarantee''
and ``promise,'' in outgoing e-mail from a company's system.
</P>
<P>
   With ToolBelt, noncompliant messages automatically come to the
attention of administrators before they are sent, avoiding rule
violations but without the need for a time-consuming physical
review of messages. The system can also create an archive of
messages for up to seven years that can be examined randomly or
specifically for noncompliance.
</P>
<P>
   Pecelli said the extranet that Amicus established for his
company two years ago also gives his brokers an opportunity to draw
on the firm's resources remotely at any time.
</P>
<P>
   A common characteristic of Amicus' customers, which make up
about 10 percent of all independent brokerage houses, is a thin
operating margin that doesn't allow for large-scale computing
applications.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a perfect market for the type of out-source technology
that we provide, in part because their margins are so thin, they
don't have the resources to develop these technologies
themselves,'' said Passovoy. ``Under their own power they're not as
able to adopt technologies as fast as other industries.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
