 &HT;    Makings of a frugal funeral offered on Web
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   www.webcaskets.com _ We know, we know _ what kind of person
comparison-shops for a funeral? Well, according to this site, a
smart and frugal one. According to the site's frequently asked
questions, consumers routinely spend too much on funeral
arrangements. ``Be wary of funeral homes that do not have any
caskets priced below $2,000. This is a sure sign you are paying far
too much,'' webcaskets.com warns. Shop here to make quick shopping
out of an eternal resting place.
</P>
<P>
   MUST BUY: The Lone Star Art Casket, a casket emblazoned with a
picture of mesas, cacti, bluebonnets, the state flag and the Alamo,
$2,575 with shipping. Simply to die for. www.bn.com _ Most people
who buy books over the Internet have a preference: Amazon.com or
Barnes &AMP; Noble's Web site. But Barnes &AMP; Noble is upping the stakes
by offering one-day delivery in Manhattan, using courier and
hand-delivered services at no extra charge. While that doesn't mean
a whole lot right now, the experiment may spread to some of the
chain's 500 other locations, including Austin. So check out the
site now and start doing some comparison shopping in case that
happens.
</P>
<P>
   MUST BUY: ``Memoirs of a Geisha'' in softcover, $11.20 plus
shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
