<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forecast is for better weather sites
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's a reason everyone talks about the weather.
It's one of the things we all have in common.
</P>
<P>
   Weather sites on the Web are among the most frequently
bookmarked. And Atlanta's own Weather Channel has one of the most
popular sites in the nation. But since weather sites are one of the
largest categories on the Web, there are plenty of choices. With
icy and snowy weather probable in the next few months, this is a
good time to see what's out there.
</P>
<P>
   Since Weather.com (www.weather
</P>
<P>
   .com) is the king of the hill, we'll start there. Since most of
us tend to check the weather in the same cities each time _ your
hometown, where you live now, places where relatives live, cities
you visit _ a long-standing feature of the site makes a lot of
sense. You can customize the start page so that every time you
visit, you'll get the weather for cities you select (other features
can be customized, too, but this is the most useful one).
</P>
<P>
   One good change at this site is the completeness of the weather
report. Frankly, the information was once a little skimpy _ the
day's weather was reduced to little more than an icon that showed a
sunny day, or cloudy one, etc., and the predicted highs and lows.
There's more detail now, and that's helpful. Even more detail would
be better. It exists, but you have to select the ``detailed
forecast'' link to get it.
</P>
<P>
   Another excellent source of weather information comes from that
Web standby, Yahoo. Just go to weather.yahoo
</P>
<P>
   .com, and checking the local forecast is easy. Simply type in
the ZIP code (or the name of the city) and you'll get a complete
summary (furnished by Weathernews Inc.).
</P>
<P>
   A standout feature of this site can be tested by following the
link to the long-range forecast. You'll be taken to www
</P>
<P>
   .weatherplanner.com/ (or you can bypass the Yahoo site and go
there yourself) and be able to get a 30-day forecast for your area.
That's a pretty ambitious goal (for instance, the weather for my
neighborhood says that Christmas Day will be clear with highs in
the 50s to 60s. But it's at least as good as guessing and sort of
fun).
</P>
<P>
   The Weather Underground (www
</P>
<P>
   .wunderground.com) site offers some of the most complete weather
information on the Web. If you want to know absolutely everything
about the weather in a city _ literally down to the phase of the
moon, dew point and visibility _ this is a good place to bookmark.
</P>
<P>
   Another unique feature of the site is its ability to translate
the weather news into more than 40 languages. So whether you want
to read the Des Moines weather in Arabic, Afrikaans or Korean, it's
as simple as just using the pull-down menu to change the language.
</P>
<P>
   You can't talk about weather forecasts without considering the
nation's prime source: the National Weather Service. The Weather
Service is, of course, represented on the Web. You'll find it
(among other places) at www.wrh.noaa.gov
</P>
<P>
   /wrhq/nwspage.html.
</P>
<P>
   From that page, you can select from a long list of links that
will take you to various regional centers and also to some of the
Weather Service's specialized weather centers. For instance, you
can go to the National Hurricane Center, various maritime and
aviation centers and the Storm Prediction Center. A serious student
of the weather, or just a person who enjoys knowing more than is
needed, can spend hours here.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
