<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PC World has primer on finding lost data
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Have you ever turned on your computer and _ after
moments of clicking and grinding _ found yourself facing a blank
screen or a frightening error message?
</P>
<P>
   More and more of our lives _ everything from banking records to
personal correspondence _ is stored on that computer hard disk.
That's why the January 2000 issue of PC World is worth checking
out. You'll find tips on what to do ``When Good Data Goes Bad.''
The magazine covers various methods for recovering data from a
dying hard disk, as well as recovering corrupted files.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have a friend who is new to the computer world, or is
expecting his or her first computer as a holiday gift? Pick up the
special holiday issue of Family Circle/PC World Computers Made
Easy. This issue is aimed at novice computer users. Even for
veterans, there are articles of interest, including ratings of the
best PCs in the low-price range, last-minute holiday gift
suggestions and ways to keep your information private when you surf
the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ON CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular basketball games in the computer world
is ``NBA Live'' from EA Sports. A new edition of that game _ ``NBA
Live 2000'' _ is just out. It's available for PlayStation and
Nintendo 64. Some of the nifty new features include the ability to
challenge Michael Jordan for a little one-on-one. You'll also be
able to customize the on-screen players _ almost a build-a-person
kit _ changing the way a face looks, altering hairstyles and skin
color, and even changing eye colors.
</P>
<P>
   Also new on shelves is ``South Park, Chef's Luv Shack,'' for PC
systems. This game from Aklaim is based on the popular TV show.
Parents should note that _ as is true in the TV show _ the content
may be objectionable for some. But if the TV show is on your
family's approved list, the game should be fine, too. You'll need a
Pentium II running at 233 megahertz with 64 megabytes of RAM to
enjoy the game, although it should run on systems as sluggish as a
Pentium166.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever received an e-mail and wanted to find out a little
more about the source? One way is to look up the domain name.
Finding out where the originating site is located can help. There's
a Web site at dedicated
</P>
<P>
   .rapidserver.com/whois.html that can provide some of this
information.
</P>
<P>
   Also, if stuff like anonymous e-mail is driving you crazy, maybe
you should drop in at www
</P>
<P>
   .allhealth.com/onlinepsych/. Besides some psychological mind
games, you'll also find various tests to check out your
personality, or lack of one.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
