<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IBM's 1480 ThinkPad puts whistles atop bells
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I'm writing this on the finest laptop computer I've
ever used, but curiously a lot of the high-end bells and whistles
built into IBM's Model 1480 ThinkPad don't have anything to do with
computing.
</P>
<P>
   The 1480, apparently, has reached the limits of the mobile
computing envelope. Oh, I'm sure that you can get plenty of laptops
that run a little faster _ the 1480 is, after all, running on an
Intel Celeron chip of a mere 466 MHz _ but you'd be hard-pressed to
notice it.
</P>
<P>
   It's got a 6-meg hard drive, 14.5-inch LCD display with an ATI
video card that has 4 megabytes of RAM, 64 megs of memory, and a
DVD drive along with a floppy drive.
</P>
<P>
   The modem is a Lucent Technologies V.90 model that achieved 48k
and better on my telephone line.
</P>
<P>
   None of that constitutes bells and whistles; it's just good
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the bells and whistles, my favorites first:
</P>
<P>
   On the edge of the lid, there's a little light. Turn it on in
the daylight, and you won't even see it. But turn it on in the
dark, and it provides just enough light to let you read the
keyboard. Now, you might think that's silly, and I probably would
have agreed a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   But this past summer I had to write an article on deadline in
the passenger seat of a car flying down Interstate 85 in the dead
of night. No problem, I suppose, for an accomplished typist, but
I'm not one of those, and I doubt a lot of laptop users are. The
National Security Agency would have been hard-pressed to decode the
results of that adventure. This little light would have been a
blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Next is the Internet scroll bar, a big paddle kind of thing
right behind the small paddle things that serve as mouse buttons on
the deck in front of the keyboard. You can use this paddle in
conjunction with the mouse stick to scroll through Web pages
without having to stay on the scroll bars. That's very nice, but
why not extend it to internal applications as well?
</P>
<P>
   Then you've got the four color-coded buttons above the keyboard.
These are preset to use various functions of the Web services IBM
and Lycos have created, but you can customize them to do anything
you wish.
</P>
<P>
   There's a built-in microphone, and also a microphone jack.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the flashy stuff.
</P>
<P>
   At the front of the deck, protrudinga bit so it can still be
used when the computer is turned off and the lid is closed, are
controls and a little window to let you play music disks, or even
DVD movies, through the S-video output to a television set. Oh,
wow.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, at extra cost but what the heck, you can buy
optional covers for the 1480 in seven different colors, not all of
which, one assumes, are blue.
</P>
<P>
   Along with all of these wonders, of course you have the
inescapable evils of all laptops: disagreeable cursor control
devices and a cramped keyboard. The video display can be viewed
quite well from any angle in any light. However, the brightness and
contrast controls had little, if any, effect on it.
</P>
<P>
   As mentioned, IBM has opted for the mouse stick in the middle of
the keyboard instead of the little trackball or the little panel
you diddle with your finger. I don't like any of these. There is,
of course, a standard mouse port for those situations in which you
can use one.
</P>
<P>
   The keyboard is less cramped than many, and most of the keys are
where you expect to find them. And, of course, you can plug in a
standard keyboard when you wish.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you have the price _ $2,200 _ which is roughly twice
what you might pay for the same features in a desktop, but about
half what a top-of-the-line laptop would have cost a couple of
years ago. Computing on the go will always command a premium, I
suppose.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
