<HEADER>
A4060 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NFK-FEATURE-CANAL21-C     12-20 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-CANAL21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Panama to take control of its biggest asset _ the Panama Canal
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After 85 years of running the Panama Canal, the United
States will turn over the keys to the giant waterway. The country
of Panama will officially take control on Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The canal is considered one of the major engineering
achievements of the 20th century. It slices across the 50-mile-wide
land bridge _ or isthmus _ that connects Central and South America.
</P>
<P>
   Ships save thousands of miles by taking a short-cut through the
canal. The canal connects the Caribbean Sea and the Pacific Ocean.
Before the canal opened, they had to sail all the way around the
tip of South America, making their journeys much longer and more
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   A ship traveling from New York to San Francisco saves 8,000
miles by taking the canal short-cut.
</P>
<P>
   The French were the first to try to build a canal. They were led
by Ferdinand de Lesseps, who became a legend after he constructed
the Suez Canal. The Suez Canal connected the Red Sea and the
Mediterranean Sea in 1870.
</P>
<P>
   But the French effort in Panama collapsed in 1889 due to poor
financial management and Panama's disease-ridden swamps. Some
20,000 workers died of malaria and yellow fever.
</P>
<P>
   The United States wanted to take up where the French left off.
But Panama was then part of the South American country of Colombia.
Colombia refused to sign a canal treaty with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In 1903, the people of Panama revolted from Colombia _ some say
with help from the United States _ and quickly signed the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. President Theodore Roosevelt was among the canal's
strongest backers. The ``big ditch'' took 10 years and employed
50,000 workers at the height of the job. It was finished in 1914.
</P>
<P>
   About 5,000 workers died in accidents or of disease. But a
famous American doctor named William Gorgas managed to wipe out
most of the tropical diseases that plagued the French. He did this
by controlling the mosquitoes that spread malaria and yellow fever.
</P>
<P>
   After the canal opened, Panama and the United States often
bickered over its control. In 1977, U.S. President Jimmy Carter _
who once served as Georgia's governor _ signed two treaties turning
the canal over to Panama at the end of this century. Carter felt it
was important to let the Panamanians control the most important
piece of property in their own country.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans oppose the treaties, fearing the canal might be
poorly maintained or even fall under the control of a hostile
nation. But the proud Panamanians insist they will run the canal
safely and fairly.
</P>
<P>
   The giant ditch is still a vital trade link today, carrying
about 5 percent of all the world's shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Some 13,000 ships pass through the canal each year. They carry
everything from cars and television sets to raw materials like
petroleum, ore and lumber.
</P>
<P>
   The ships pay a total of about $600 million per year in tolls to
use the canal.
</P>
<P>
   FACTS ABOUT THE PANAMA CANAL:
</P>
<P>
   Length: 50 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Maximum ship size: 106 feet wide by 965 feet long with a draft
of 39.5 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Canal work force: 9,000 workers, 95 percent of them Panamanian.
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   Cost in human life: Estimated at 25,000, including 20,000 during
the French effort who died mostly of malaria and yellow fever.
</P>
<P>
   Panama Canal Zone:10 miles wide, it once included 12 U.S.
military bases and 7,000 buildings. All have now been turned over
to the Panamanian government.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
