<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Attacking `soft money'
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Presidential candidates Bill Bradley and John McCain
pledged last week not to use ``soft money'' in their campaigns if
they are chosen as their parties' nominees. Bradley is a Democrat
and a former New Jersey senator. McCain is a Republican and an
Arizona senator.
</P>
<P>
   To help keep a presidential election fair, there are rules about
how much money a person can give to a candidate. Companies and
labor unions are not allowed to donate money directly to a
candidate, explains Sharon Snyder of the Federal Election
Commission. The commission regulates how money is spent during
elections.
</P>
<P>
   However, a person or company can give an unlimited amount of
money to a political party, such as the Democrats or Republicans.
That money given to a political party is called ``soft money.''
Although soft money can't be spent directly on a presidential
candidate, those candidates can reap benefits from it. For example,
the party can run ads for a particular issue a candidate supports,
like the environment. The party also can run ads to encourage their
party members to vote.
</P>
<P>
   There are many people who would like to see soft money banned in
elections because they think it allows rich companies and rich
people to influence our leaders.
</P>
<P>
   PHONEY-MONS CAN FOOL YOU
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon card traders beware! If Pikachu looks a little funny,
you might have purchased an impostor.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials and Nintendo of America, the producer
of the cards and toys, say counterfeiting has become a problem,
especially during the holiday season. People are selling fake cards
and plush toys.
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo officials suggest you hold the cards up to the light to
make sure they're real. If you can see through to the other side,
they're probably fake. In addition, counterfeit cards are often
printed on cheaper, thinner paper that bends or ``crinkles.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTRE DAME ON PROBATION
</P>
<P>
   For the first time ever, Notre Dame's football team was placed
on probation because of gifts, money and trips given players by a
former booster.
</P>
<P>
   The National Collegiate Athletic Association stripped the team
of two scholarships and put it on two years' probation.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame remains eligible for postseason bowl games. Its
multimillion-dollar TV contract with NBC is not affected.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA announcement ended an almost two-year investigation
into the relationship between a former booster and up to a dozen
players. The booster has admitted spending some of the more than
$1.2 million she embezzled from her former employer on players.
</P>
<P>
   The university did not have a comment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
