</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: My boyfriend wants an alarm clock for
Christmas that displays the time on the ceiling. His grandmother
used to have one. He is not sure what brand his grandmother's was
or where she got it. I remember seeing these some years back but
have not been able to find one. I hope to put this in his stocking
for Christmas _ do you have any suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   _ Stephanie Bertagna
</P>
<P>
   A: Hammacher Schlemmer stocks ceiling projector clocks ($59.95)
that run on batteries. Call (800) 233-4800 to order, or shop from
your keyboard at www.hammacher.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have some relatives in Minnesota who want me to send them
barbecue from Kreuz Market in Lockhart. Unfortunately, the folks at
Kreuz do not ship, so I am trying to figure out how to safely ship
barbecue up to the frozen northland. Can you help?
</P>
<P>
   _ Dan Kinnunen
</P>
<P>
   A: When your taste buds crave Kreuz's, nothing else will do.
Here is the preferred packing method from Kay Welch, owner of
Mailboxes Etc., who has shipped everything from a frozen coiled
rattlesnake to a 44-inch Spanish sword: Wrap the barbecue in foil.
Freeze it solid. Enclose in sealable plastic bags (two if
possible). Pack in a Styrofoam cooler with a small amount, about 5
pounds, of dry ice. Pad with packing peanuts and overnight the box.
The overnight charge on a 10-pound box will be expensive (but for
your relatives, why not?). Q: I bought a Reed &AMP; Barton bell in 1979
for my wife during the holidays. It had ``Christmas 1979'' engraved
on it. Who handles these bells and where can I order one? My wife
wants one dated 1999 since it is 20 years since we got married, and
I would like to give her one. Merry Christmas. _ T.C.
</P>
<P>
   A: What a nice gift! Try silversuperstore.com or (800) 426-3057.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it considered poor taste to invite people to a shower who
will not be invited to the wedding service and reception? _ B.B.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Only those invited to a wedding are eligible for shower
invitations. Many wedding books agree, including ``The Knot's
Complete Guide to Weddings in the Real World'' by Carley Roney.
Exception? If the wedding is an immediate family affair on Nevis
and showers are the only way to include friends in the nuptial
festivities. It is the bride's duty (one of many) to approve all
invitation lists so guests will not think they have only been
invited to give great gifts. Invitations should be spread around _
so no one is over- or under-invited.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Help me find a recipe for Amish Friendship Bread. It is made
with an old-fashioned starter that undergoes a 10-day process of
sitting, stirring, and adding a cup each of milk, sugar and flour
on certain days. I've misplaced my recipe (which ironically had
instant pudding in the final mix). I have no idea where to
``start.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jennifer Clitheroe
</P>
<P>
   A: Start with a batch of starter: This recipe is courtesy of the
Bon Appetit Cooking School: Use equal parts flour, sugar and milk
(1 cup each, for instance). Let set at room temperature in a jar
three times larger than the amount of mixture. Cover with
cheesecloth and stir with a wooden spoon once a day. Let sit for
one week before you use it. Do not use metal spoons or containers
and don't refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
