<SLUG> BC-SAVING-FEET-OF-WORLD-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUCKNER'S ANATOMY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE B&AMP;W SLIDE and THREE COLOR SLIDES are available FREE OF
CHARGE to purchasers of this article. The art can be sent
ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please specify that you want the art when
you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By BILL HIVELY  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Jan Bruckner, a professor of physical therapy at Thomas
Jefferson University in Philadelphia, heads across campus for a 10
a.m. appointment at the Human Performance Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   There, Gary Sylvester, one of Bruckner's students, nervously
waits. He has responded to her standing offer to examine any pupil
who complains of foot pain.
</P>
<P>
   Bruckner begins the evaluation by asking his age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-three,'' he announces.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of 23?'' says an older woman being treated for a serious
foot problem in the same lab. She listens jealously as Sylvester
explains that he runs 15 miles a week. His feet rub inside his
shoes, get raw around the toes and develop blisters.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvester is far from alone. After years of clinical practice,
anthropological research and pioneering studies, Bruckner has
concluded that, biomechanically speaking, there's no such thing as
a normal human foot.
</P>
<P>
   Instead there is a spectrum of variations. Biologically, the
foot remains a work in progress, and it needs a lot more help from
the shoe industry than it's getting.
</P>
<P>
   If Sylvester hadn't bothered to show up today, his blisters
