<P>
   FILIPINO-VET (San Francisco) _ Having been on this earth for 85
years, Ernesto Fajardo's thoughts have turned to his funeral
arrangements. Sensing the end is near, Fajardo received the good
news last week that President Clinton had signed legislation
allowing Filipino veterans of World War II who receive Supplemental
Security income (SSI) to return to the Philippines and still get 75
percent of those monthly payments. By JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   BABY-NAMES (San Francisco) _ The king of baby names has been
deposed. After a 45-year reign, Michael has finally been forced to
turn over his title to Jacob,
</P>
<P>
   which emerged as the most popular male baby name in 1999,
according to Social Security records compiled by the San
Francisco-based BabyCenter.com, the national baby resource
organization. The top girl's name for the year was Emily, popular
throughout the decade. By MARSHA GINSBURG.
</P>
<P>
   CHALUPA (San Francisco) _ It's worth remembering, says the
president of the Popular Culture Association, that there was a time
_ precisely three
</P>
<P>
   months ago _ when no one in the history of planet Earth had
</P>
<P>
   heard the phrase, ``Drop the Chalupa.'' Or knew what it meant.
Now, spawned by a Taco Bell commercial featuring an officious
Chihuahua, Chalupas are on our collective tongue. By ELIZABETH
FERNANDEZ.
</P>
<P>
   CASHMERE-CRAZE (San Francisco) _ A glut of cashmere fiber _
stockpiled by herdsmen during _ the past two years after demand had
fallen in economically
</P>
<P>
   depressed Asian countries caused prices to drop to historic
</P>
<P>
   lows. Thus, mass market retailers in the United States could
</P>
<P>
   offer the luxury product, industry experts said. But the
widespread availability of cashmere has caused some consumers to
question the price and quality. By VANESSA HUA.
</P>
<P>
   SF-MAYOR (San Francisco) _ Anyone wondering whether Willie Brown
was humbled after being forced into last week's runoff election
should know that
</P>
<P>
   the victorious mayor's ego is healthier than ever and his
</P>
<P>
   sense of humor is firmly intact. By ANASTASIA HENDRIX.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e``category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-LEILA (Undated) _ There's never been a more
shockingly insubordinate
</P>
<P>
   mother-in-law than the one who wreaks conjugal havoc in
``Leila.'' Her shrill sitcom sisters have nothing on the
relentlessly selfish harridan pulling the strings in Iranian
director Dariush Mehrjui's devastating account of an infertile
bride poisoned by devotion to a tradition not even her loving
</P>
<P>
   husband supports. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HEADHUNTER-VERDICT (San Francisco) _ A high-powered executive
recruiter who lost her ability to do high-pressure work on deadline
after a rear-end auto wreck
</P>
<P>
   has won a $19,million award from the owner of the truck that hit
her. By LANCE WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS (Charlotte, N.C.) _ While two games remain in the
worst
</P>
<P>
   49ers season in two decades, the club is already beginning to
</P>
<P>
   look ahead to the offseason, a time whust address its
</P>
<P>
   biggest problem among a long list of deficiencies: Horrendous
pass defense. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PERSONAL-BEHAVIOR (Charlotte, N.C.) _ Long ago but not so
far away,
</P>
<P>
   we had a college professor who claimed sports simply mirrors
society at large. If so, the mirror in which we look is cracked.
Here in Charlotte, former Carolina Panther Rae Carruth is accused
of first-degree murder, the first active NFL player so charged. He
typifies a spate of personal problems in the
</P>
<P>
   over-hyped world of sports. Athletes seem to think they are
immune from the consequences of their actions. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-STANFORD (Stanford, Calif.) _ Stanford University's Rose
Bowl experience is about to begin. And remember: It's not just a
game, it's an adventure. By the time the Cardinal line up across
from Wisconsin on New Year's Day, while the viewing public splashes
Visine into its bleary eyes, Stanford could be coping with its own
hangover. Answer this: Can one football team possibly have too much
</P>
<P>
   fun? By MARK FAINARU-WADA
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ We peered over the top of the
duck blind, largely concealed by eucalyptus branches spread across
its top, and watched Moto
</P>
<P>
   Duck do its thing. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ If Lucy McKnight had ever been
certain of anything, she was certain she'd been wronged. She'd been
working for the New York State Dormitory Authority. An active
Democrat and an African American, she'd been hired during the Cuomo
administration. After George Pataki and his Republicans took over
New York state government, Lucy McKnight suffered health problems
and missed some work. When she was fired, she noted that a number
of white folks with similar absences hadn't been discharged. So,
Lucy McKnight filed suit against the dormitory authority alleging
racial discrimination. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
