<HEADLINE>
HIGHER RETURN REQUIRES ASUMING MORE RISK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 62 and retired. My combined pension and Social Security
give me $21,000 a year. My wife, who doesn't plan to retire, has a
part-time job earning $12,000 a year. Combined, this is enough to
live on, since we own our home and take only one mini-vacation a
year. I currently have an IRA CD at 5.5 percent worth $90,000 that
will mature in two months. I would like to transfer this to my IRA
account at Schwab, which now consists of $5,000 in Janus Balanced
and $5,000 in American Century Growth. My plan is to divide the
money evenly among Janus Balanced, American Century Growth, and a
GNMA fund. I will not need any of this money for at least five
years, since I have $55,000 in savings bonds for any emergency. I
am a cautious investor, but can I realize a safe return of 7
percent to 9 percent with little risk, or should I put the entire
$90,000 in a GNMA fund and take the safer yield?
</P>
<P>
   J.C., East Boston, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It's hard to give you an answer without coming to an
understanding of risk. What you're proposing is dividing that
$90,000 just about evenly between stock market and fixed-income
investments.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever you are dealing with the stock market, you can't make a
projection of growth and categorize it as safe or having little
risk. This is particularly true now, when the stock market has been
spurting ahead at nearly unprecedented levels for half a decade;
the prospect for a cooling off seems almost inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   So if the operative words in your letter are conservative, safe,
and little risk, then your plan is probably too aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Why not consider as an alternative putting half of the money
into the GNMA fund (and I would counsel the Vanguard GNMA as the
fund of choice in this category) and then divide the rest of the
money between American Century Growth and Janus Balanced or another
balanced fund.
</P>
<P>
   I say another balanced fund because Janus Balanced isn't your
run-of-the-mill balanced fund. Although Morningstar rates it
average for risk, it also terms its portfolio quirky and notes a
dominance of expensive growth stocks and high-yield (or junk)
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   It wins four stars, for an above-average overall rating from
Morningstar, as can be attested to by its 19.44 percent
year-to-date return as this is written.
</P>
<P>
   If you want a more conservative balanced fund, you might
consider Vanguard Balanced Index, which also wins an above-average
overall grade from Morningstar.
</P>
<P>
   But the fund analysis company says the fund doesn't take a lot
of chances. It's year-to-date return stands at 11.23 percent, but I
suspect the situations would be reversed in a sour market.
</P>
<P>
   With the toned-down portfolio, I think the prospect for average
annual returns in the 7 percent to 9 percent range are quite good _
but again, since you would have 37.5 percent to 40 percent stocks,
it wouldn't be reasonable to use either the words safe or little
risk in connection with it.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce risk still further, you might cut the position in the
growth fund to 15 to 20 percent, increasing either the GNMA or
balanced fund position. But of course as you reduce the level of
risk, the prospects of getting closer to the 9 percent range of
your projected returns decreases.
</P>
<P>
   One final thought. If you could arrange your affairs so that you
wouldn't need to draw upon the IRA account for a longer period of
time _ say until you reach the age of mandatory withdrawals after
70 1/2 _ your original proposal looks a good deal safer. The longer
your investment time frame, the higher level of risk you can
prudently take.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a 50-year-old recent widow and I make $40,000 a year and
rent a modestly priced but nice apartment. Beginning in January, I
will fund my 401(k) account with 15 percent of my earnings, and my
employer will match 4 percent. I will continue at the same levels
until I am 60, during which time I anticipate my salary will
increase at a rate of 3 percent a year. I am in the process of
selling my home in Maryland, from which I will net $150,000. I also
have $30,000 that I inherited from my late husband's IRA. As a
widow, at age 60 I will be able to draw Social Security against my
husband's earning record, and at 62 or 66 I can switch to drawing
against my own record. I enjoy the relatively high wages of
Southern California, but since real estate here is so expensive,
when I retire I plan to move to Albuquerque, where the cost of
living is much lower _ I could buy a very nice house there for
$100,000 in today's dollars. My goal at age 60 is to buy two
mortgage-free houses in Albuquerque: one to live in and one to
rent. I have a fairly simple standard of living and believe I will
be able to live quite contentedly on my Social Security plus rental
income. Does this sound realistic? Where should I invest my 401(k)
funds? What should I do with the $180,000?
</P>
<P>
   J.J., Orange, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Let's start with the 401(k). If you invest the money in a
balance of conservative growth and balanced funds, you might expect
average annual returns of 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With total contributions between yourself and your employer of
14 percent of your earnings (which would increase from $40,000 to
$52,188 based on your projection) you would accumulate a total of
$128,419 after 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   During that period, the monthly contributions from yourself and
your employer would slowly grow from $633.33 in the first year to
$826.31 in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   If your $30,000 in the IRA account were similarly invested, you
could expect an accumulation of $64,767.
</P>
<P>
   And if the $150,000 were similarly invested, this time in index
funds _ which tend to be fairly tax-efficient _ you might attain
after-tax returns of about 6 percent and therefore amass $268,627
in that account.
</P>
<P>
   (One way to improve the overall tax situation would be to put
$2,000 of your taxable money _ that $150,000 pool _ into a Roth IRA
each year, thus entirely sheltering that money from future
taxation.)
</P>
<P>
   The upshot would be that you would have plenty of money
available to buy real estate in Albuquerque. If the price of
Albuquerque real estate advances at a 3.5 percent rate for the next
10 years, a house that costs $100,000 now would cost $141,059 then.
</P>
<P>
   I don't question that it would be a nice thing to buy yourself a
house at that point, but I suggest you think carefully about the
idea of a rental property.
</P>
<P>
   If you put the $141,059 that a rental house would cost into a
fixed-income mutual fund yielding 6.5 percent, it would bring you
an income stream of $9,168 a year, or $764 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The question I would then ask is this: Are you sure that after
paying for insurance, taxes, maintenance, repairs, and facing the
countless unforeseeable headaches that can go with being a
landlord, do you think you could net as much as $764 a month
through renting the property?
</P>
<P>
   True, one advantage of a rental property is that you can
increase the rental level to offset the effects of inflation;
equally true, there's a reasonable chance that the property will
gain in value, provided you carefully maintain it.
</P>
<P>
   But one advantage of a position in a GNMA fund is that you
wouldn't have to worry about sloppy tenants, deadbeat tenants, new
furnaces, property tax increases, and so forth, on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, unless you have a lot of experience in real estate
and know all of the ins and outs of that business, I would think
that investing the money would yield you a more certain, and
perhaps higher, income stream.
</P>
<P>
   As for target investments, I would put all of the money in
conservative but growth-oriented stock and balanced funds. With
your 401(k) you will be limited by the options presented in the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   For your own investments, I'd suggest a mixture of
value-oriented large-cap stock funds such as Vanguard Windsor II or
Vanguard Index Value, and balanced funds, which divide their assets
among stocks and bonds. Good examples in the same family are
Vanguard Balanced Index and Vanguard Star.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Correction: There have been an enormous number of mergers in the
mutual fund industry, but in last Monday's column I inadvertently
included one that hasn't happened. The American Fund family and the
American Century group are entirely different mutual fund
companies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
