<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4209 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-CLINTON-AMBASSADORS-B     12-20 1365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AMBASSADORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMBASSADOR UNDER FIRE IN STATE DEPARTMENT REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They called themselves Friends of Bill, the cadre
of people around the country who had met Bill Clinton, liked Bill
Clinton, and proudly wore big ``FOB'' buttons announcing their
loyalty during Clinton's 1992 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years into Clinton's presidency, the FOBs have gotten
their reward, and many now call themselves ambassadors to European
and Caribbean posts.
</P>
<P>
   Of 170 current ambassadors, 61 are political appointees, the
largestpercentage in recent history. Not since the tenure of Ronald
Reagan has the percentage of political appointees _ 36 percent _
been so high. Nor does the Clinton count include political
appointees to sunny posts such as Bermuda, where the United States
has a representative _ in this case, former New Hampshire
Democratic fund-raiser Robert Farmer _ but no ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   While even career foreign service officers admit that certain
political appointees serve with distinction, many worry about the
damage that can be done when the chief United States representative
to a foreign nation is not a practiced diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   In a blistering internal State Department report, James C.
Rosapepe, the US ambassador to Romania and a Clinton supporter, is
accused of failing to inform Washington of key developments in
Romania, giving too much weight to the domestic Romanian agenda,
and pressuring US agencies and contractors to hire people he
selects.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most important functions of a US embassy is to keep
the State Department posted on a country's internal politics and
trends. But Rosapepe's reporting is so inadequate and ``slanted''
that ``we really have no idea what is going on there,'' said an
official quoted in the report, prepared by the department's
inspector general and obtained by the Globe last week.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials have been forced to rely on their
personal Romanian contacts to find out what is really happening in
the politically and economically volatile nation. ``Those who need
to keep up on Romanian events have developed their own sources, and
the embassy is not first among them,'' said the inspector general's
report.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Romania, Rosapepe, a former Democratic state legislator
from Maryland, has displayed a lack of diplomatic discretion, the
report indicates. The ambassador includes Romanian nationals in
many embassy meetings, has discussed US budget figures with
potential contractors, and sometimes brings only a Romanian embassy
employee and not a US Foreign Service officer to high-level
meetings with the Romanian government, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Rosapepe, reached in Bucharest, said it would be improper for
him to discuss the report. But allies of Rosapepe's in the
diplomatic corps defended Rosapepe's general performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has done a great job . . . in a difficult situation,'' said
Richard Schifter, special assistant to the secretary of state for
Southeast Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find him to be energetic, innovative, flexible and highly
respected by the folks he deals with in Romania,'' Richard Sklar,
US special representative for the Southeast European Initiative,
said by telephone from Rome. But, Sklar added, ``I know nothing
about the report and it is none of my business.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosapepe is hardly the first US ambassador to be criticized. But
the fact that he is a political appointee makes his case
noteworthy, as critics complain that Clinton has been overly
generous in handing out plum ambassadorships to friends and
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as this administration has used the Lincoln Bedroom as a
little prize for funders, it has given out ambassadorships in the
same manner,'' said Larry Birns, head of the Council on Hemispheric
Affairs, a liberal foreign policy group.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials defended the practice of making
political appointments. ``I really believe that for key jobs in
dealing with important governments, you want someone who has had
experience outside government,'' Schifter said.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, political appointments are made to posts that are
pleasant places to live, such as Western Europe and the Caribbean.
Currently, every European ambassadorship except two is held by a
political appointee; posts in difficult or dangerous places, such
as the Balkans and most of Africa, are almost universally held by
career diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   New Englanders who have received ambassadorships based on their
relationship to the Clinton administration include Jean Kennedy
Smith, former ambassador to Ireland; New Hampshire Democrat George
Bruno, formerly ambassador to Belize; and former Boston mayor
Raymond F. Flynn, who was ambassador to the Holy See. Current
ambassadors from the region include former US representative
Richard Swett of New Hampshire, now ambassador to Denmark; Boston
civil rights activist Charles Richard Stith, ambassador to
Tanzania; and New Hampshire lawyer Edward E. Shumaker III,
ambassador to Trinidad and Tobago.
</P>
<P>
   Saving the cushier posts for friends and supporters of the
president ``has a long-term effect on morale'' in the foreign
service, said Marshall Adair, president of the American Foreign
Service Association, which represents career employees. ``It's hard
to build and maintain an effective professional diplomatic service
if people don't believe they have a chance of getting the top
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress has politicized the process as well. The chairman of
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, Jesse Helms, Republican of
North Carolina, has held up numerous Clinton appointments, often
because of an unrelated foreign policy disagreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress needs to impose some discipline on itself . . . and
the administration has to exercise some control in giving out
assignments as a way of paying back good contributors,'' Adair
said.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official who asked not to be named said that
it was ridiculous to try to set an arbitrary limit on political
appointees ``because it all comes down to the individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosapepe's assignment was unusual in that Romania is considered
neither a comfortable posting nor a stable nation. Just last week,
the Romanian government slipped into crisis when the president
fired the prime minister, who then refused to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts describe Romania as a nation on the brink of
prosperity, which may eventually join such exclusive clubs as NATO
and the European Union, but also in danger of falling into the
economic morass and political upheaval of other post-communist
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Romania has lagged in the region in economic reform, and suffers
from the brutal legacy left by former dictator Nicolae Ceaucescu,
whom the Romanians executed on Christmas day 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``Romania has wonderful potential, but it is an unfortunate
position right now,'' said George Handy, an Eastern European
specialist at the Center for Strategic and International Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain diplomatic posts that you just don't hand
out to cronies or fiscal sluices, and Bucharest is one of them,''
Birns said.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of the political appointments say the non-career
ambassadors often bring solid managerial skills to the job, and
that their posts benefit from the ambassador's personal
relationship to the White House. In some cases, such as the United
Kingdom, the selection of the US ambassador is less crucial because
Clinton speaks directly to British Prime Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
   Tales of unliked political appointments are legendary. One
ambassador to Sri Lanka during the Eisenhower administration was
unable to name the prime minister of Sri Lanka during a
congressional hearing, recalled a former career diplomat. An
ambassador to Jamaica once assigned each embassy employee an
animal, and communicated with his staff by stamping an image of the
animal _ for example, a drawing of a chicken _ onto correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some outstanding (non-career) ambassadors,'' said
the former career ambassador. But there are some exceptions, and
``it's up to the system to find the counter-balance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
