<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4216 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GENETIC-ENGINEERING-L     12-20 1656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENETIC-ENGINEERING-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS PUSH GENETIC ENGINEERING TO NEW LEVELS
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes color photos of biologist with a test tube, and a
petunia)
 By RON MATUS 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By transferring a gene from a common weed into a petunia,
biologist David Clark can make the flower's bloom last a couple of
weeks longer.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't care to make them plastic,'' says Clark, 33, a
molecular biologist and horticulturist at the University of Florida
in Gainesville. ''We just want them to last so the growers can
expand their market and the consumers can enjoy them longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving genes from one species to another used to be science
fiction. Now it's routine, as scientists push genetic engineering
to new levels.
</P>
<P>
   Transgenics is big stuff, on a par with the emergence of the
Internet and the last ''green revolution'' in agriculture in the
1950s and 1960s. Supporters are counting on high-tech horticulture
to develop crops that will feed a hungry planet.
</P>
<P>
   Making pretty flowers bloom longer, Clark says, is just the
''icing on the cake'' of agricultural achievement. Transgenic
research already has created sweeter fruits and vegetables, higher
yielding crops and pest- and disease-resistant plants.
</P>
<P>
   But critics warn of ''Frankenfoods'' and ''superweeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental activist Jeremy Rifkin claims scientists are
''reseeding the planet with a second Genesis.'' Protesters in
Europe have ripped up transgenic crops in the field and sent
tremors of a trade war back across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   For universities who are major players in transgenic research,
such as the University of California at Berkeley, the University of
California at Davis, and the University of Florida, it makes for a
daunting public relations challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a Jurassic Park mentality out there,'' says Mike
Martin, UF's vice president for agriculture and natural resources.
''We have to educate the public and then proceed carefully. If we
don't do it, it will be done elsewhere _ and not as well.''
 &UR; PICK A TRAIT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Genes _ which are made up of DNA _ are the blueprints for life.
And considering how fast, how often and how far they're being moved
around in labs now, the reference to Jurassic Park may be apt.
</P>
<P>
   No longer are scientists limited to finding the traits they want
in individual members of certain species _ say, sweetness in
tomatoes _ and then slowly breeding those traits into others so
they become commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   Now researchers can take the desired traits from one species and
engineer them into the species they want to ''improve.''
Furthermore, genes can be drawn from any species and implanted into
any other: Bacteria. Viruses. Plants. Animals. People. There are
millions of combinations from which to choose.
</P>
<P>
   This may sound futuristic, but man has been altering genes in
plants through traditional breeding and selection for centuries,
said Karen Marshall, a spokeswoman with the St. Louis-based
Monsanto, a company that makes nutritional, pharmaceutical and
agricultural products. ''Corn would be a cereal grass with a little
nub on the end of it without man,'' Marshall says.
</P>
<P>
   Monsanto has developed dozens of new crop varieties either by
itself or in conjunction with university researchers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't call it a revolution. I call it evolution,'' Marshall
said. ''You pick the trait you want. You insert it. We may do
10,000 plants before we find the one that's perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are working with genes in animal species, too,
mapping them, cloning them, transferring them. But it's with plants
that scientists have most quickly taken the new tools and put them
to widespread use.
</P>
<P>
   A CHANGED LANDSCAPE
</P>
<P>
   This advanced technology has altered a lot of landscape,
physically and culturally, in a short time. Monsanto made the first
transgenic plant, a petunia with a marker gene from a bacteria, in
1983. The first transgenic crop to be sold commercially, a
slow-ripening tomato, hit grocery stores in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In three years, the number of acres of transgenic crops planted
in the United States has gone from zero to tens of millions.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are using biotechnology to make rice with extra iron
and beta carotene. They've engineered potatoes with bits of virus
gene to fight diarrhea in Third World countries. They've even found
a novel use for tobacco: Fitting it with a bacteria gene so it can
break down explosive chemical residues left in soil _ a consequence
of TNT production.
</P>
<P>
   Corn, soybeans, cotton, potatoes and other crops have all been
engineered with a bacterial gene that contains a natural pesticide.
Insects that munch on the pesticide-infused plant die.
</P>
<P>
   Other crops have been ''wired'' with herbicide-resistant genes
from bacteria. Farmers can more efficiently apply weedkiller
without fear of killing the crop.
 &UR; A SECOND GENESIS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But in Europe, a lot of people don't want potatoes engineered to
kill the bugs that eat them.
</P>
<P>
   And they don't want frostproof oranges, rot-resistant melons or
anything else researchers might be working on, either.
</P>
<P>
   Great Britain's Prince Charles is one of them. The prince, a
longtime organic farmer, is an opposition leader in England.
</P>
<P>
   ''Are we going to allow the industrialisation of life itself,
redesigning the natural world for the sake of convenience?'' he has
written on his Web site. ''Or should we be adopting a gentler, more
considered approach, seeking always to work with the grain of
nature?''
</P>
<P>
   Activists in Europe have made up their minds. They've defined
the debate with a catch-phrase: ''Frankenfoods.''
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, so far there hasn't been much of an
outcry. Biotech supporters say it's proof that the public is happy
with the new foods. Opponents say it's proof the public is
clueless.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to look at the scale of what is happening,'' writes
activist Rifkin, a longtime critic of the biotech industry. ''In
the next 10 years, the major companies hope to introduce thousands
of gene-spliced organisms over millions of acres of land and even
into the water. They will reseed the planet with a second
genesis.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not just the next step in plant breeding, Rifkin says _
it is a heart-stopping leap. One that has already resulted in
unexpected outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, scientists announced that pollen from
genetically engineered corn can kill Monarch butterfly caterpillars
that eat it. The corn produces a natural pesticide designed to kill
a major corn pest, the European corn borer.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also say that a handful of big agribusinesses, such as
Monsanto, are making huge profits through rapid development of
transgenic species. The faster a company can get a new crop variety
to market, the faster it can cash in. Safety checks, they fear, are
bypassed in the race for money.
</P>
<P>
   Even university research teams in biotech fields are viewed with
a suspicious eye, since they rely more and more on private, and
often corporate, research dollars.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FORGING A BETTER WORLD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Researchers agree that there are potential pitfalls and ethical
questions to be confronted. Some also agree with critics who demand
labeling of transgenic products.
</P>
<P>
   But, they counter, there is potential for so much good: By
moving genes, researchers have made corn with bigger kernels and
wheat that grows 30 percent bigger. They're on the hunt for
virus-resistant oranges and grapefruit that aren't bitter.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important crops will emerge, such as
''nutriceuticals'' and ''farmaceuticals'' _ produce with
disease-fighting antibodies.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought this was cool, this was something I had to do,''
said University of Florida Professor Harry Klee, 46, who began
working on transgenic plants after earning his doctoral degree in
biochemistry in 1980. ''Without this (technology), the world's
population is going to exceed its capacity to make food.''
</P>
<P>
   Klee was a researcher for Monsanto before coming to the
University of Florida, where he and his assistants are working on
everything from more productive cotton plants to melons that stay
ripe longer.
</P>
<P>
   All that work doesn't come cheap. It's not unusual for
university researchers such as Klee to corral several hundred
thousand dollars worth of grants each year. Klee says about half of
his money comes from the federal government, half from agricultural
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Klee hopes a new, sweeter variety of tomato he has developed
with the help of a corn gene will give tomato farmers an edge to
win back markets they lost because of the 1994 North American Free
Trade Agreement. But even after research and development, getting
transgenic fruits and vegetables to market is a costly endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   It cost Monsanto $2 million to maneuver an engineered tomato
through stiff regulatory hurdles designed to protect consumers and
the environment. ''We had to show that in every way, shape or form
that this was a tomato,'' Klee said.
</P>
<P>
   As money from government sources gets tighter, university
researchers look to industry to pick up the slack.And with so many
crops, so many potential transformations and so many genes to
choose from, industry researchers alone can't keep up.
</P>
<P>
   ''For every success story,'' said University of Florida
professor Curt Hannah, who has developed new varieties of corn,
''there's a thousand things that didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ron Matus writes for The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun). &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
