<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4217 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-EAST-COMMUNISM-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     12-20 1808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAST-COMMUNISM-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 SOFIA, Bulgaria: ... for them.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Singer acknowledges that life has become harder for some, but
says he believes that the free market provides the best standard of
living for the most. Last year, Singer had 15 people working for
him. Today he has seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to shed people,'' he said. ``I'm not here to keep people
employed. I'm here to make a profit.''
</P>
<P>
   Such cold, bottom-line thinking is unfathomable to Vrtic. For 17
years, he worked at the Poldi steel mill, as did about half of the
adults in Kladno, a town of 75,000. Ten years ago, some 22,000
people worked at Poldi. But after it was privatized, the staff
shrank to 6,000. Two years ago, the plant closed.
</P>
<P>
   Communist poets used to wax lyrical about the red haze that hung
over Kladno, a product of Poldi's furnaces. But economists say it
had to be shut down because it operated in the red.
</P>
<P>
   Vrtic says he believes Poldi was closed for political reasons.
He says its workers were punished for being supporters of the
communist system. He and other steel workers say they did not have
skills that could be transferred to other emerging industries, and
that the government has not retrained them.
</P>
<P>
   Vrtic and other laid-off workers, such as Jiri Nohejl, 55, say
that they have been turned away when looking for work in Prague by
people who sneer at ``Red Kladno.''
</P>
<P>
   The steel mill did more than provide jobs. It paid for nearly
all of the social activities in town, including the youth hockey
program that produced Jaromir Jagr, the Pittsburgh Penguins star.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poldi was the lifeblood of the community,'' said Vaclav Kalla,
49, chairman of the district council. ``Poldi organized vacations
for workers and their families, meals for the elderly. It was like
a big brother, overseeing everything in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Vrtic, who has two sons, has scraped by with odd jobs, most
recently as one of the 100 security guards who patrol the idle
steel mill. He makes about 60 percent of what he used to make.
</P>
<P>
   Vrtic has continued to vote for communists, and recent polls
show that more than 20 percent of Czechs would vote for communists,
making them nearly as popular as the governing, coalition-leading
Civic Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Poldi mill closed during its 100th anniversary. A huge
bronze statue near the factory gates that pays homage to the
worker, the backbone of the communist state, is overgrown with
brush now.
</P>
<P>
   Vrtic carries in his wallet one of the razor blades made at
Poldi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of our tradition,'' he said. ``But memories won't
help.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rise of nationalism
</P>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Kosovo _ Shortly after NATO troops had sent Yugoslav
troops packing, Ilir Demiri, 19, infiltrated a press conference
here and listened as British Lieutenant General Michael Jackson,
who led the liberation forces, asked ethnic Albanians not to
retaliate against the Serb minority left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Demiri, an ethnic Albanian who said several of his family had
been killed by Serb forces, snickered as he listened to what he
considered Jackson's naive plea for tolerance, one repeated by
President Clinton last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does not understand this place,'' Demiri said. ``This is
our country. The Serbs do not belong here.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last seven months, Kosovars who think like Demiri have
taken their vengeance against Serbs and gypsies who are seen as
collaborators in Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's attempt to
ethnically cleanse a part of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Under communism, overt nationalism was suppressed. Now it is
emerging, often expressing itself as xenophobia and sometimes as
violent racism directed at anyone not perceived as being native.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic and Yugoslavia provide a case study of post-communist
nationalism. Under Josip Broz Tito, Yugoslavia's communist leader
from 1945 until his death in 1980, a more pragmatic form of
communism gave people a higher standard of living than those in the
Soviet bloc. Tito's federal political system was aimed at keeping
the nationalism of the region's various ethnic groups in check.
</P>
<P>
   Once a fervent communist, Milosevic reinvented himself as a Serb
nationalist when communism collapsed. The ethnic quilt that Tito
held together tore apart, as nationalism fed wars and led to the
founding of independent countries in Slovenia, Macedonia, Croatia,
and Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
   While Yugoslavia is the most obvious example, extreme
nationalism, from the neo-Nazis in the depressed corners of the
former East Germany to the skinheads in Slovakia who beat up
foreigners, has become a problem in virtually all parts of Central
and Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Velvet Divorce'' of the Czech Republic and Slovakia is
held up as an example of cooler heads prevailing in the face of
polarizing nationalism. But each country has its own troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomatic immunity is supposed to protect foreign officials
from the vagaries of laws in countries where they are not
nationals. But the skinheads who stalk the streets of Bratislava,
Slovakia's capital, have created their own menacing concept:
diplomatic vulnerabilty. Being a foreign diplomat, or a foreign
anything, increases the chances of getting attacked. Last summer, a
Chinese diplomat was badly beaten by a gang. A few weeks later,
Libyan diplomats complained that their sons had been attacked by
skinheads.
</P>
<P>
   John Sanchez Bendezu, a 26-year-old graduate student from Peru,
decided he had seen enough. When he saw three skinheads close in on
a Korean student, he intervened. The skinheads turned on Bendezu,
beating him severely. When police arrived, they were more
interested in demanding the identity cards of the foreigners than
finding the culprits.
</P>
<P>
   Bendezu got off lightly. Last year, in Prague, skinheads were
chasing a Gypsy when they stumbled across a Sudanese student. The
skinheads abandoned their intended quarry and settled for the black
youth, stabbing him to death. The murder was shocking, even more so
because it took place in a city that is considered the most
enlightened capital in Eastern Europe, the home of writers like
Vaclav Havel, now the Czech president, who inspired the Velvet
Revolution 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Few have suffered more than the Roma, or Gypsies, an estimated 8
million of whom live in Eastern and Central Europe. Gypsies had
jobs in the Soviet bloc, and they say the suppression of
nationalism by the communist regime kept racists at bay. Now,
Gypsies are routinely beaten, and sometimes murdered, by racists
even in the countries considered most progressive.
</P>
<P>
   Josef Facuna, a Gypsy leader in Ostrava in the Czech Republic,
said he and other Gypsies prefer the certainties and safety of
communism to the supposed freedom under democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least during the totalitarian regime, I knew that I would
work eight hours, come home, and go wherever I wanted. But not
now,'' he said. ``Now I'm afraid that someone will beat me up.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Confronting the past
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN _ As the 10th anniversary of the collapse of the Berlin
Wall approached, the thirst for nostalgia was insatiable, and
Guenter Schabowksi relived his 15 minutes of fame.
</P>
<P>
   It was Schabowski who, as chief spokesman for East Germany's
Politburo, garbled the regime's plan to save itself by loosening
travel restrictions. As almost an afterthought, and because he had
not read a briefing paper thoroughly, Schabowski announced on live
television on the night of Nov. 9, 1989, that the border was open.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds gathered at the wall in East Berlin and, after meeting
muted resistance from guards who had not been given any
instructions, began streaming into West Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   The Berlin Wall had collapsed, Germany was free, and Schabowski
was its unwitting liberator.
</P>
<P>
   Schabowski's almost comic role in the collapse of the wall, and
the subsequent collapse of the Soviet bloc, was recalled here so
often and with such fondness that it came as a shock to many that
on Nov. 8, just as the limousines carrying former President George
Bush and former Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev rolled into Berlin
for the 10th anniversary gala, Schabowski was ordered to serve
three years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Schabowski and two other Politburo members, including Egon
Krenz, the last communist leader of East Germany, were convicted of
manslaughter for giving the orders to border guards who shot and
killed more than 900 people who tried to escape over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev, who was hailed as a hero and made a citizen of
Berlin, criticized the decision to imprison Schabowski and the
others as ``victor's justice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We should put this all behind us,'' said Gorbachev. ``We
should look to the future instead of holding witch hunts.''
</P>
<P>
   For Falco Werkentin, however, and many of the 250,000 people who
were political prisoners of the Stasi, the East German secret
police, this is not about vengeance but justice. Werkentin, now the
deputy in charge of Stasi files in Berlin, says too few of those
who used violence and repression to prop up the regime have been
imprisoned, because too many people, especially West German judges,
want to forget the past and move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the heroes of the fall of 1989, there was no place in the
judicial analysis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Romania, those who brought on the counterrevolution a decade
ago wasted little time in apportioning blame. They put the
communist dictator Nicolae Ceaucescu and his wife up against a wall
and shot them.
</P>
<P>
   But throughout the rest of the former communist bloc, it is only
now that the ghosts of the past are being confronted, that those
who used the repression needed to maintain a totalitarian society
are being held accountable.
</P>
<P>
   In Hungary, four men accused of opening fire on demonstrators
during the failed uprising of 1956 are on trial for murder in a
case that has opened old wounds. In Warsaw, the Polish supreme
court last month ordered the trial of the former communist leader
General Wojciech Jaruzelski and nine other communist officials
accused of ordering police to shoot workers who rioted in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Some countries prefer to let the past lie. Czech President
Havel, who has hosted a series of conferences aimed at remembering
the communist era and learning from it, says his country has failed
to confront its past. His desire for a truth and reconciliation
commission is not shared by many of his fellow Czechs. Havel
complains that communism spread responsibility so widely that it is
difficult to fix blame, and so, many would prefer not to try.
</P>
<P>
   Confronting the past does not mean simply holding the former
regime accountable. In Poland, dozens of people who were raised as
Roman Catholics have over the past decade learned they were born
Jewish, part of an identity switch meant to save them from the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
