<HEADLINE>
WHY ARE SUNSET TIMES DIFFERENT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. At 9 p.m. in Portland, Ore., it was very light. A day later
in San Francisco at 9 p.m. it was dusk. Why are sunset times
different?
</P>
<P>
   D.R. Stoneham, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The answer lies in your longitude and latitude. Though the
earth isn't a perfect circle, it's divided up that way for
navigational and time setting purposes. Longitude runs vertically,
up and down between the poles. Latitude is horizontal, like the
equator. It may help to remember that latitude, which runs across,
has an ``A'' in it.
</P>
<P>
   Both measurements are carved up in degrees (360 of them in a
circle), minutes (60 per degree) and seconds (60 per minute).
</P>
<P>
   Time zones are 15 degrees across, since the 360 degree circle of
the earth, divided by 24 hours, equals 15 degrees of longitude per
hour. So at Boston's latitude, 42.4 degrees North (above the
equator, which is designated 0 latitude), one degree is 49 miles
across and the time zones are 735 miles wide.
</P>
<P>
   But where you are in the time zone, not the clock, determines
the actual time the sun sets. Since Portland is east of San
Francisco by 13 minutes of longitude. Same time, different sky.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just a question of east-west longitude. Portland is
also eight degrees, one minute latitude north of San Francisco. The
earth's axis tilts over the course of the year, with the north pole
tilting toward the sun in the summer, away from it in the winter.
The moment when it stops tilting one way and starts tilting back is
the Winter Solstice, Latin for ``suns stands still'' This year it
occurs at 2:44 a.m. December 22nd in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In the winter, the further north you are, the lower the sun is
on the horizon to the south during the day, and the later it rises
and the earlier it sets. So differences in latitude also affect how
dark or light it is at different places in the same time zone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write to
How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
