<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4224 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CENTURY-RELIGION-BOS &LR;      12-20 1792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-RELIGION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SPIRITUALITY INSPIRED BY EASE AND ESTEEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   God may have had the first word, but he sure isn't having the
last one. As we round the corner into the 21st century, Americans
have shrugged loose the strictures of Scripture and are busy
remaking the religious rules _ and even the nature of faith itself
_ to their own liking.
</P>
<P>
   We have discarded both the devil and details of religion,
consigning the Holy Spirit to symbolic status, insisting that
heaven isn't just for believers anymore, and dismissing the
once-powerful concept of hell as all but irrelevant. Traditional
worship in church or synagogue must now vie with a variety of
alternatives, from home services to mega-churches, from
cyber-services to new age fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a time of spiritual exploration that makes us
question, and in some cases be uncomfortable with, traditional ways
of doing church or religion,'' says David Roozen, director of the
Hartford Institute for Religion Research at the Hartford Seminary,
an interfaith institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of free-floating religion and a lot of
experimentation going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, for traditionalists, there is some good news: Basic faith
is strong, though doubt creeps upward.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, when the University of Chicago's National Opinion
Research Center polled Americans about their beliefs, 63 percent
said they had no doubt that God existed. A decade later the
response was the same.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of disbelievers _ although still small _ had
doubled, from 1 percent to 3, while the number who said they
believed in a higher power, but not a personal God, increased from
7 percent to 10. Other categories also show encroaching doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at all the categories, you could say there is an
increase in disbelief,'' said Tom W. Smith, director of the study,
which is called the General Social Survey.
</P>
<P>
   Still, what those and other, similar surveys show is that a
strong majority of Americans have a basic belief in God and an
afterlife and say religion is important in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   But just as plain chant gave way to polyphony, Americans seem to
be playing jazz with traditional teachings _ and the change in tone
is coming more from the pew than the pulpit. The story of how some
of that change was discovered is as interesting as the attitude
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the widespread view was that, despite the
turbulent '60s, the questioning '70s, the materialistic '80s, and
the complacent '90s, Americans remain as churched as ever over the
last half-century.
</P>
<P>
   That, after all, is what a number of Gallup opinion polls have
shown. In 1947, 41 percent of Americans surveyed told the Gallup
poll they attended religious services regularly. These days, 40
percent say they were in a house of worship on the previous Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   That statistic has led many to proclaim that God is still in his
heaven, his flock still loyally in his house.
</P>
<P>
   But when a trio of skeptics employed a number of sociological
research methods to double-check those self-reported contentions,
they discovered that a goodly part of that worship was imaginary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that about half the people who said they were there
actually attended services on a given weekend,'' said Mark Chaves,
associate professor of sociology at the University of Arizona. ``So
we look a lot less religious than it seems when you use the
standard self-reported survey stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean that people regularly lie to pollsters? Chaves is
circumspect. ``I don't like to use the word lying,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, he says, they interpret the question as asking if they
think religion is important and they want to answer in a way that
says yes. Or perhaps they intended to go to church.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, of course, it was well known that the road to
hell was paved with good intentions. But at a time when no less an
authority than the pope has said that hell isn't really a pit of
torture and despair of the sort depicted by painter Hieronymus
Bosch, but rather only the absence of God's grace, the penitent in
the pew has taken things much further.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is there neither fire nor brimstone, but the idea of
heaven's gate as a portal narrow as a needle's eye seems to have
gone the way of Joe Camel. These days, heaven is seen more as, say,
a celestial community college: inclusive, receptive to all creeds,
and with all-but-open admissions.
</P>
<P>
   And forget Pascal's famous formulation of belief in God as a
self-interested wager that cost little if you were wrong and won
you an afterlife if you were right. No need to ante up in the new
theology, where many people believe that if there is a heaven,
simply living as a good person will be enough to get you in.
</P>
<P>
   That's hardly the only heterodox view that Americans hold when
it comes to religion, says George Barna, president of the Barna
Research Group, a Ventura, Calif., firm that regularly surveys
Americans about their religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Although 58 percent say they believe the Bible is totally
accurate in its teaching, they hold views divergent from what the
good book teaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``A majority say that when it comes to personal salvation, it is
either based on belief in Christ or just being a good person, as
though it is multiple choice,'' says Barna.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, 6 out of 10 Americans say there is no such thing as
the Holy Spirit, though this third member of the trinity is
supposedly fundamental to the Christian faith that 84 percent of
Americans embrace. (Curiously, 55 percent of born-again Christians
don't believe in the existence of the Holy Spirit.) It's perhaps
less surprising that 72 percent say the devil doesn't actually
exist, but rather is only a symbol of evil.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have a basic belief in God or a basic belief in some
sort of higher power, but they take it upon themselves to determine
the nature of those deities,'' Barna said. ``What we have is a
nation where everyone is his own favorite theologian.''
</P>
<P>
   Another way in which loosening of traditional theological
understanding is seen is the giving way of strict religion to
gauzier notions of spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't restrict your definition of religion to what happens
in that big stone building,'' argues historian Mark Silk, director
of the Center for the Study of Religion in Public Life at Trinity
College in Hartford. ``Religion has migrated in some parts of the
country into nontraditionally religious institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Silk cites such activities as tai chi, the Chinese martial arts
movement sometimes called moving meditation, or Falun Gong, the
Chinese spiritual movement with roots in Buddhism and Taoism, and
even ardent environmentalism, as examples of that migration.
</P>
<P>
   From there, of course, it's a short step to religion as little
more than a personal chat with God. Which is the approach that
popular author Neale Donald Walsch has taken in his best-selling
books, ``Conversations with God'' (three volumes) and now,
``Friendship with God: an uncommon dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   As Walsch tells it in this last book, God speaks to him in
friendly conversations, little epiphanies that seem to pop into his
head much like an instant message on a computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   He writes: ``I heard God's voice whisper: `Neale, your
relationship with Me is no different from your relationship with
each other. You begin your interaction with each other with a
conversation. If that goes well, you form a friendship. And if that
goes well, you experience a sense of Oneness _ communion _ with the
other person. It is exactly the same way with Me.' '' (God's
italics)
</P>
<P>
   This is not the stern figure of the Old Testament. He is not
even a Dutch uncle-type deity. We're talking a thoroughly
easygoing, ``I'm OK, you're OK,'' type, a God whose standards are
as flexible as our desires, one who believes that ``There are no
cans or cannots here. There are no shoulds or shouldn'ts. You may
do as you wish. Every decision is a statement of Who You Are.''
That, at least, is the gospel according to Walsch.
</P>
<P>
   Now, this sort of new age God is famously easy to get along
with. No need to tremble or quake, nor is self-abnegation or
humility required. He's not ``our father who art in heaven'' so
much as an indulgent friend, always ready to enable us.
</P>
<P>
   One objection to that sort of theology is obvious: It's the
Church of the Wholly Convenient. The theology is too easy, and in
its ease, it appropriates religion into the soothing,
self-therapeutic impulse that so characterizes today's culture.
</P>
<P>
   Is a spiritual Sunday walk on the beach easier than church? Why
not make it a stroll on the golf course and kill two birds with one
stone? God wants you to do what you want.
</P>
<P>
   ``One wonders about the extent to which there is really a depth
in contemporary spirituality,'' says Roozen, of the Hartford
Seminary, who calls it a compartmentalized religion ``of partial
commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush may testify to the way his faith has changed his
life _ as he noted anew in last week's GOP debate in Iowa _ but
theological conservatives wonder if America's ever-more-casual
theology truly carries the power of improvement any longer.
</P>
<P>
   Two centuries ago, Voltaire said that society needed religion to
keep the servants from stealing the silver. No one would phrase it
quite that way today, but theologians do worry about the loss of a
more demanding moral sense in American life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real concern for that moral loss,'' says Eddie
Gibbs, a professor of religion at Fuller Theological Seminary in
Pasadena. ``Where do we base values that have traditionally come
out of religious convictions?''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder fin de siecle faith frustrates the traditionalists,
who feel theology should establish unwavering standards of belief
and conduct, not ones that evolve with the times.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear the Catholic bishops saying they are not sure that
what goes on in Catholic colleges is really Catholicism, you hear
the conservative Christians saying the liberal religions are not
really Christianity, you hear Orthodox Jews saying that Reform Jews
are not really Jewish,'' says Alan Wolfe, director of the Center
for Religion in American Public Life at Boston College. But though
the changes may mortify some, in a country where persuasion is
increasingly the pulpit's only tool, there's little stopping the
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans reinvent everything. We are a very inventive
people,'' says Wolfe. ``And you can't have an old-fashioned
religion in a modern country. The only thing that surprises me is
that people are surprised by this reinvention.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Scot Lehigh is The Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
