</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETERINARY-HOLDUPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG THIEVES HIT VETERINARIANS FOR `SPECIAL K' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOIS R. SHEA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUDSON, N.H. _ A gunman walked over the stenciled pawprints and
up the front steps of the Lawson Veterinary Hospital one afternoon
last month.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't want money. He wanted an animal anesthetic called
ketamine, or, as it's known on the street, ``Special K.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hudson stickup was the most brazen in a recent string of
drug-related burglaries that has veterinarians and police officials
on alert. Two Woodstock, Vt., vet clinics were broken into last
month. Since August, New Hampshire has seen more than a dozen
similar break-ins. Maine reports about the same number over the
past two years.
</P>
<P>
   The growing popularity of Special K as a party drug has turned
the vet clinics into targets. People who take the anesthetic _
intended for dogs, cats, and horses _ go into a demobilized,
trance-like state called a ``K-hole.'' The drug, and the trances,
have become standard components of ``raves,'' all-night dance
parties.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the break-ins have taken place after-hours, the
late afternoon armed robbery in Hudson has veterinarians
particularly concerned. Suddenly, working at the local vet clinic
feels a little like the overnight shift at the Store 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``Damn fools are getting buzzed on it,'' said New Hampshire
state veterinarian Clifford McGinnis. ``It's been kind of a problem
now for three or four years _ it just seems (recently) it has just
broken out and become a continual rash of break-ins. . . . It's
gotten out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Some veterinary clinics, particularly in New Hampshire, are
starting to tighten security. They're installing new locks and more
secure safes. Some have considered removing the drug from clinics
each night and, borrowing from the Store 24 approach, posting signs
that say: ``No drugs on the premises.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being a bank teller,'' McGinnis said. ``It's got to
be quite a shock to have somebody come in with a gun and ask for
something. I am so upset and I can't believe what's happening _ my
God.''
</P>
<P>
   The Plymouth Animal Hospital in Plymouth, N.H., was burglarized
twice this fall, said receptionist Kary Tobine. Another attempted
break-in failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took everything,'' she said. The drugs had been secured
in a safe, which the thieves broke open with what must have been a
crowbar, Tobine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've put on new doors and deadbolt locks,'' said Tobine.
``And of course the drugs are locked in a better vault than what we
had before.''
</P>
<P>
   The damage done by the break-ins can extend beyond the vet
clinic walls.
</P>
<P>
   Ketamine is increasingly known as a ``date-rape'' drug. Billy
Yout, special agent in charge of the Drug Enforcement
Administration in New Hampshire, said that ketamine can render
victims unconscious and vulnerable to sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing would be that they have no control over
their faculties _ that's what makes it so very, very dangerous,''
said Yout.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can see what's going on, but they can't move, they really
can't function at all,'' said Mike Gosselin, the Hudson detective
investigating the Nov. 22 armed robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Ketamine is addictive. And it can be lethal.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other parts of the country it's a tremendous concern,''
said Yout. In the past few months, break-ins have been reported at
vet clinics from Worland, Wyo., to Tammany, La.
</P>
<P>
   Hardest hit in New England have been New Hampshire and Maine.
There were only a few similar break-ins reported in Vermont before
the two last month. And while the break-ins have been cooling off a
bit in Maine, New Hampshire is on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Grasso, the chief compliance investigator of the New
Hampshire Board of Pharmacy, said the number of break-ins since
mid-August could be higher than the 12 to 15 he knows about, since
some of them may not have been reported, especially repeat thefts.
</P>
<P>
   Drug-seeking thieves broke into the Riverside Animal Hospital in
Boscawen, N.H., three times. The first time, thieves triggered the
alarm, which is wired to the police department, and fled, said Dr.
Brad Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, they were back. They broke a window, Taylor
said, and ``took ketamine, and were gone before the police could
get here, so they did the whole thing with the alarm going off in
their face.'' When the thieves returned for a third try, Taylor
said, ``We had everything locked up so tight that they couldn't get
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very disconcerting,'' said Taylor, who said veterinarians
are worried that animals could be harmed in a break-in. ``We take
it personally when somebody starts messing around with our
patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Police believe the armed thief in Hudson was a teenager; that's
also been the case in many of the other ketamine thefts.
</P>
<P>
   If there are signs of a slowdown in the number of break-ins in
Maine, it's not yet being felt on the streets. ``We are seeing a
steady increase in (ketamine) possession cases and particularly in
the Portland area,'' said James Cameron, drug prosecution
coordinator for the state attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, a Portland nightclub raid led to a number of
ketamine possession charges, Cameron said, and some Portland-area
concert-goers were recently caught with the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron said that he suspects the ketamine being sold in Maine
is coming from out of state.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Zuckerman, a senior assistant attorney general in charge of
the criminal justice bureau in New Hampshire, said Special K is not
nearly as prevalent as the other rave drug of choice, ecstasy. But,
he said, ``who knows what these break-ins mean. Maybe that will be
changing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sergeant Bruce Hansen of the Nashua Police Department said the
drug has been turning up there at raves. ``Oh, absolutely,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire last year stiffened the penalties for possessing
and selling ketamine, classifying it as a Schedule Three drug. A
first-offense charge of possession or sale of the drug can carry a
maximum seven-year prison term and fines of up to $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts, too, has strengthened laws against possession and
sale of ketamine, making it, like heroin, a Class A drug.
Possession and sale of the drug in Massachusetts can carry a
maximum prison term of 10 years and a $10,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Maine has not followed suit; possession of ketamine there is
still a misdemeanor, Cameron said, punishable by up to six months
in jail and a $1,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   But, said Cameron, ketamine is ``a very dangerous drug. People
think of it as a party drug, but it's a lot more serious than
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
