<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4234 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-WORCESTER-HOMELESS-BO     12-20 1799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORCESTER-HOMELESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROAD TO TRAGEDY FOR WORCESTER PAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ She has the face of a child _ still full with
youth, her lips pressed into a permanent pout _ and a childlike
need to be liked and to belong.
</P>
<P>
   He has sunken cheeks, small eyes, and a manner that friends say
can swing between docility and rage: calm unless provoked, quiet
until he drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Separated by a generation, shaped by troubled pasts and
shattered families, Julie Barnes, 19, and Tom Levesque, 37, found a
connection in Worcester's streets. On and off for about a year,
they huddled together in shelters and nestled in vacant buildings,
nurturing a volatile, sometimes violent love.
</P>
<P>
   According to their friends and acquaintances, the shelter
denizens who knew them, the couple bickered constantly and
occasionally came to blows. They lost a child to miscarriage and,
three months ago, conceived another.
</P>
<P>
   After one heated squabble, Barnes asked for a restraining order.
A judge denied it the same day for reasons that remain unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a few forays into court, Levesque and Barnes lived what
one local priest calls a ``subterranean'' existence: shadows of
lives the rest of the world rarely sees.
</P>
<P>
   He rummaged through trash bins for cans. She spent hours in
MediaPlay, a local music store. They were fixtures in downtown
Worcester, but often barely noticed.
</P>
<P>
   That changed after their last fight on a chilly Friday night
more than two weeks ago, in their makeshift home in the vacant,
heatless Worcester Cold Storage &AMP; Warehouse Co. building.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of an argument, a candle fell over, starting a
fire they couldn't put out.
</P>
<P>
   Six firefighters died in the blaze, a fire so intense it burned
for a week before finally going cold. And Levesque and Barnes, who
had slipped away before the fire trucks arrived, were arrested for
involuntary manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Now their names and faces are fixed in the collective conscience
of Worcester, as objects of anger, or sympathy, or wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the homeless people who dot the city's streets, there are
always stories, tales of dead ends and hardships, said Liz Dicenzo,
supervisor at Public Inebriate Program, the Worcester shelter where
Levesque and Barnes were known to stay, and where some residents
know Dicenzo as ``Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's at the PIP shelter because they want to be here,''
Dicenzo said. ``They're here because they have to be. They have
nowhere else to go.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The children at Worcester East Middle School and North High
School had a litany of derisive nicknames for Julie Barnes when she
was their classmate: ``scrub,'' ``loser,'' ``dirty slut,'' and
``Downtown Julie Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   Teenagers can be cruel, even proudly so, to people who are
different, and in the cutthroat world of Worcester public schools,
Barnes did not fit in. She dropped out in the 11th grade.
</P>
<P>
   Her former classmates say she seemed slow, had been held back a
year, and was enrolled in some special education classes. She wore
clothing that was dirty or ripped, or too-small pants that stopped
just above her ankles. Her hair hung stringy and greasy. She
carried cats to school in her backpack. Her classmates teased her
mercilessly.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, she lingered around them, several North High students say,
trying to strike up conversations, brag about her boyfriends, or
pay misplaced compliments (``I really like your chapstick,'' she
once told a girl).
</P>
<P>
   She laughed, even when the jokes were about her.
</P>
<P>
   If the teasing became too intense, someone in the crowd usually
stepped in and told her tormenters to ``back off,'' said a onetime
classmate, 18, who called himself Alex. But there were many more
times when no one intervened.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was there to laugh at,'' said Alex, who still attends
North High. ``She was, like, one sandwich short of a picnic
basket.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems a constant in Barnes's life that even those who care
about her, and sympathize with her, speak about her cruelly, and
that her relationships with her closest relatives often have been
strained.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, a cab driver named Kevin Castonguay, told the
Worcester Telegram and Gazette that he and Barnes's mother, Evelyn
Menard, split up in the early 1980s. Barnes and a sister, now 21,
lived with Menard and their stepfather for a time, Castonguay said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the state Department of Social Services intervened in
the mid-1980s after reports of sexual abuse and neglect.
</P>
<P>
   The department ``does not have an open case'' on Barnes, a
department spokesman said, but he would not give specifics.
</P>
<P>
   Castonguay took custody of the girls in 1992, he told the
newspaper, but he had a hard time with Barnes when she turned 16.
She was belligerent, stole things, and sometimes slipped away from
home to stay at shelters. When she was 18, she moved out for good.
</P>
<P>
   After she started to spend time on the streets, a friend named
Virgil Larose, a self-described biker, took her in. He called
Barnes ``my little granddaughter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's called me Grandpa and I've protected her, watched over
her, and I won't let nobody hurt her,'' Larose said outside a
Worcester courthouse after a hearing this week. Barnes could not be
guilty of manslaughter charges, he said, because she was too
helpless to be held responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``That little girl don't have the brains to do something like
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to friends, Barnes and Levesque met when Levesque was
living with her aunt, Norma Barnes. He was the father of Norma
Barnes's twin children.
</P>
<P>
   Levesque, who wandered in and out of temporary jobs, was also
the product of a troubled home; one friend recalled that he talked
about being thrown out by his mother when he was about 10 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   Though he has never been convicted of a crime, Levesque had been
arrested on charges that were later dismissed: in 1993, for assault
and battery against a girlfriend, who claimed he punched her; and
in 1994, for disorderly conduct. Two former girlfriends received
restraining orders against him in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1994 request, Kelly Marie Johnson said Levesque
``threatened to do something to me and my husband. He also
threatened to kill me and beat me up,'' the Telegram and Gazette
reported. And in a 1995 request, Norma Barnes, wrote that Levesque
``has threatened to come after me if I don't let him see his
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who knew him said Levesque has a jealous streak that often
spun him into a rage, but others said he also could be quiet and
calm.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Joe Coonan, pastor of a local Catholic church that aids
the homeless, remembered Levesque wheeling a shopping cart through
the neighborhood, searching for cans in church trash bins,
sometimes coming to the rectory for aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``When asking for food, he was almost shy, and very passive and
polite,'' Coonan said.
</P>
<P>
   Levesque made connections among Worcester's homeless, and was
loyal to his friends, one man said. ``Unless you got him riled or
if he started drinking, he was a good guy,'' he said. ``He'd go out
of his way for you.''
</P>
<P>
   But alcohol was a problem for Levesque, friends and
acquaintances said _ though he sometimes tried to break free of the
cycle. Nearly a year ago, he was enrolled in a detox program at
Public Inebriate, and seemed to do well for a time, working in the
shelter kitchen, and taking medication, said Barry Bennett, 37, who
was in the program with him.
</P>
<P>
   Levesque could lash out violently when provoked, residents of
the Public Inebriate Program said, and his relationship with Barnes
seemed, at times, a constant provocation.
</P>
<P>
   The pair argued constantly: about where they would sleep, what
they would eat, why he worked such long hours.
</P>
<P>
   Levesque tried to control Barnes's friendships, said Norma
Johnson, 49, a homeless woman who befriended them. He even took her
along when he went to find work.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes could hold her own in a fight, Norma Johnson said; she
would swing at him and pelt him with her high-heeled shoes.
</P>
<P>
   But there were times when they were quiet, too.
</P>
<P>
   Often, they would sit together in the shelter and play with the
kitten Barnes carried in a red fanny pack. They looked after the
cat, taking care that it didn't get on the floor, so it wouldn't
run away.
</P>
<P>
   The shelter for the Public Inebriate Program was one of
Worcester's few safe havens for homeless people, a place many
return to again and again when they're down on their luck.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are reasons why some homeless people choose not to
live in shelters, those who know and help them say. Some are HIV
positive, and fear they could contract illnesses from another
resident. Some are wary of other people, afraid of getting into
fights. Some prefer to stay outside and drink.
</P>
<P>
   Levesque might not have had a choice; three or four weeks before
the fire, he was kicked out of the shelter, apparently after an
altercation with the staff. It was then, shelter residents said,
that he moved into the Worcester Cold Storage building.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear how often Barnes joined him there, but the pair had
been there long enough for local business owners to know about
their presence. On the night of the fire, the owner of a diner
across the street told firefighters there were homeless people
inside.
</P>
<P>
   According to the story Barnes told Larose, the fire broke out
after she and Levesque got into a fight. She said Levesque slapped
her, and she stood up in reaction, knocking over a candle they had
lit.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the fire caught onto clothing and papers, and
quickly spread out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Levesque and Barnes were arrested four days later. They were
charged with six counts of involuntary manslaughter, and bail was
set at $1 million each.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Levesque is undergoing a psychiatric evaluation in
Bridgewater. Barnes was interviewed by a court psychologist who
reported that she was of ``less than average intelligence,'' but
was competent to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Barnes are likely to argue that she and Levesque had
no legal obligation to report the fire, or to tell anyone that they
were not in the building.
</P>
<P>
   As Barnes awaits another hearing, she is sad, remorseful, and
confused, said her attorneys, Michael Wilcox and Louis Aloise. She
has had a string of visitors, they said: her mother, her
stepfather, her father, Larose.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the state Department of Correction will offer
prenatal care for her unborn child, said Aloise. If Barnes is still
in prison when she gives birth, the state will take custody of the
child, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The child could be sent to foster care, or to live with Barnes's
mother. It's a decision for another day, another life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
