A4238 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-EAST-COMMUNISM-3RD &LR;  &UR; T     12-20 1946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAST-COMMUNISM-3RD </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 SOFIA, Bulgaria: ... the Holocaust.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the former East Germany, where it is estimated that about 5
percent of the population of 17 million supplied information to the
Stasi about relatives and friends, people are only now getting
access to the Stasi files. CIA analysts have picked over the files
for a decade, but now ordinary people are learning who informed on
them.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say these disclosures will tear families apart and turn
neighbor against neighbor needlessly. In what was East Berlin,
Klaus Himmel, a retired baker, says he has no interest in finding
out if he has a Stasi file.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past is the past,'' he said, sitting in a Turkish coffee
shop. ``People here spend so much time worrying about the past that
they ruin the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Werkentin, the deputy in charge of Stasi files, says that unless
the past is confronted, there is no future.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The status of women
</P>
<P>
   DUBI, Czech Republic _ Afternoons are slow here. So there are
only a few dozen hookers lining the roads of this gloomy town on
the German border.
</P>
<P>
   At night, however, it becomes surreal, with hundreds of women
dressed in short skirts and high heels, some of them flashing their
breasts at passing motorists. Inside the seedy hotels and bars that
line the E55 highway, there are even more women who can't work
outside because they were smuggled here from other parts of Eastern
Europe by gangsters.
</P>
<P>
   The booming sex industry of Dubi is a product of the free-market
economy that is struggling to find its feet in the old Soviet bloc.
Women in more legitimate areas of employment are not doing as well
as the hookers of Dubi.
</P>
<P>
   Under communism, women were, in theory, the equals of men. They
worked alongside men in jobs considered nontraditional in the West.
But since the collapse of communism, women have suffered
disproportionately.
</P>
<P>
   In a report released in September, UNICEF found that the living
standards of women and girls throughout the former Soviet bloc had
deteriorated. Of the 25 million jobs lost since the collapse of
communism, 14 million were held by women.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the transition to a market economy, the status of women is
eroding further,'' said Carol Bellamy, UNICEF's chief.
</P>
<P>
   In 16 countries UNICEF studied, the life expectancy of women had
gone down, due mostly to increases in smoking and alcohol
consumption, drug abuse, and the unsafe sexual activity that has
proliferated in places like Dubi.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, UNICEF found there were about 30,000 cases of
HIV in the former Soviet bloc. By last year, that number had
climbed to 270,000.
</P>
<P>
   Under communism, women were better represented in politics, even
if it was a one-party system. Women used to make up about a third
of communist lawmakers, but now account for about 10 percent of
those in the parliaments of fledgling democracies in the East.
</P>
<P>
   Blatant sexism and discrimination are tolerated throughout the
region. Want ads in newspapers, even in places considered
progressive, such as Prague, ask for ``attractive'' women to fill
secretarial jobs. Some ads say that anyone over a certain age is
not welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone is welcome in Dubi. German men flock here. The hookers
of Dubi charge about $35 for a half-hour, about half the price of
German prostitutes. The E55 in Dubi is also lined with open-air
markets run by Vietnamese, where people load up on cheap beer,
booze, and clothing, much of it bootleg designer wear.
</P>
<P>
   Jana, a 20-year-old Czech, insists that working in Dubi is not
so bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work for myself,'' she said, standing on the side of the
road, trying to make eye contact with male drivers. ``This is
better than working in a bar.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Jana's claims, men still take a disproportionate amount
of women's earnings. Without a pimp in Dubi, a prostitute doesn't
last very long. Serbian gangsters operating out of the Hotel Bihac
treat the young women they smuggled here from Ukraine and Bulgaria
like indentured servants.
</P>
<P>
   While Jana talks about being empowered by being able to take to
the streets, many other women tell of feeling systematically
hampered. Anna Buresova, 34, is typical. Before the Velvet
Revolution of 1989, she worked as a translator at a
state-controlled press agency in Prague.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, the agency was liquidated and we were thrown out,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   She got married and had two children, but when she tried to get
back into the job market she found that the child care that was
standard under communism was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one would hire me because they didn't want anyone who had
children,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When her son developed pneumonia and she got sick taking care of
him, her husband stayed home for three days to care for them. The
trucking company he worked for fired him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That never would have happened under the old system,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   After seven years of trying to find work, she recently got a job
as a police investigator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sought a job in the public sector because the private sector
will not accommodate working mothers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some argue that women have opportunities today they would
never have under communism. Nela Vamporova, 24, a student in Sofia,
says women were never the equals of men under communism.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother worked at a factory just like my father, but when
they came home my father sat on the couch and my mother had to make
dinner and take care of us kids,'' she said. ``It wasn't the
feminist ideal some people talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Not far from Dubi, at the orphanage in Teplice, half of the 70
beds are occupied by babies born to prostitutes. Dr. Jirina
Rejtrova, who runs the orphanage, says most of the babies arrive
without names or identity papers. Their mothers drop them off and
head back to the E55 in Dubi. They've got to go to work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clear and present danger
</P>
<P>
   KOZLODUY, Bulgaria _ When the Soviet bloc collapsed, one of the
first things the West pledged to do was clean up and close
high-risk nuclear plants in Central and Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The meltdown at Chernobyl in 1986 offered incentive, and, with
the cash pipeline to Moscow cut off, the governments of former
Soviet satellites were anxious to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   But 10 years later, only Chernobyl's Unit 4, where the disaster
struck, has been closed. There are at least 26 nuclear reactors
considered by Western specialists to be in the high-risk category
for an accident, including the plant in Kozloduy. Those specialists
consider four of the six reactors here to be among the most
dangerous and prone to accident in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But nuclear power provides Bulgaria with nearly half of its
electricity _ compared to less than 20 percent in the United States
_ and the cash-strapped government in Sofia has found it cheaper
and easier to upgrade the plant than put it in mothballs.
</P>
<P>
   This is, according to some specialists, a dangerous gamble, one
taken not only because the Bulgarian government lacks the money and
the political will, but because the European Union and the G7 group
of industrialized nations, including the United States, failed to
follow through with pledges of aid.
</P>
<P>
   Antony Froggatt, a London-based nuclear power analyst and author
of ``EU Accession and Nuclear Power,'' said the West sent
conflicting messages about how serious it was about closing
high-risk nuclear reactors. He said a 1992 study by the G7
estimated that between $18 billion and $24 billion was needed to
either upgrade existing plants or replace them with alternative
energy sources by 2000. He said the West has donated about $2
billion, including $500 million from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is supposed to be a priority, it's not a good
record,'' he said. ``The main problem is there hasn't been a
unified message from the West on what to do. Some say close them
down, while Western business is saying we can patch them up. The
dilemma is, if you invest in the facilities, these countries turn
around and say they are safe and won't close them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Froggatt points to Kozloduy as the prime example of a confused
policy. It was the first plant to receive Western funds meant to
ease its reactors into retirement, but today there is no agreement
to close it down.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his office here, Kozloduy plant manager Krassimir
Nikolov insists his plant is safe. Nikolov bears a resemblance to
Clinton, and shares the president's gift for charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The upgrading has been made and we are approaching Western
standards of operation,'' he said. ``Kozloduy will never be the
next Chernobyl.''
</P>
<P>
   Nikolov says he believes it is politics, not science, that is
behind the push by the West to close down the plant. He was in
Ukraine, less than 200 miles from Chernobyl, when the disaster
occurred. He remembers seeing people fleeing the area around
Chernobyl, their heads shaved to get rid of the radioactive
particles. Nine years after the accident, he went to Chernobyl and
saw ``a large city so empty.''
</P>
<P>
   But that experience has strengthened his resolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of nuclear safety is much higher than 13 years
ago,'' he said. ``There are many victims of car accidents, but
nobody has given up driving. This is the way of technological
progress. The other way is back to the caves.''
</P>
<P>
   The plant here employs 6,600 people, and it is keen on its
image. Promotional material says the power it produces is
``reliable, nature friendly, necessary.'' A banner hanging across
the main street of the town proclaims that the plant has provided
``25 Years of Energy and Clean Nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivancho Guergov, a shift unit supervisor, says workers see
claims from Western specialists that Kozloduy is an accident
waiting to happen as unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is safe,'' he said. ``There is more radiation on
the streets of Sofia than here.''
</P>
<P>
   But such pledges did not completely reassure Dimitar Lozanov,
10, when he and his classmates toured the plant recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a program about this on the Discovery Channel, and they
talked about radiation all over Europe,'' the boy told Geurgov,
citing a source of information that didn't exist here 10 years ago.
``If they blow up, the whole country would blow up.''
</P>
<P>
   As she shopped in the town market with her 7-year-old daughter
and 4-year-old son, Julia Dimitrova said she knew no one who
worried about the plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother works there,'' she said. ``There's never been a
problem. I was worried during the war in Kosovo, because some
missiles landed in Bulgaria. But I don't believe people who say
Kozloduy is the most dangerous in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   The EU has given Bulgaria until 2005 to close the reactors. But
Nikolov says his plant made it possible for Bulgaria's application
to join the EU to be accepted this month. To qualify for EU
membership, countries must keep inflation and borrowing in check.
Nikolov says cheap power has helped in both areas.
</P>
<P>
   A small group of activists led by those belonging to Za Zemiata,
an environmental group, appear to be the only people in Bulgaria
who want the reactors shut down. Polina Kireva, Za Zemiata's
nuclear project head, says support for nuclear power is a hangover
from communism.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are pronuclear because the Kozloduy plant is a
socialist success story,'' she said. ``The plant's backers have
been able to convince most people that attempts to close the plant
are part of a conspiracy theory, to deny Bulgaria one of its great
successes, and so other countries can cash in and sell us power.''
</P>
<P>
   Kireva says changing attitudes will, like the demolition of
Georgy Dimitrov's mausoleum, take time and patience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
