<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ORLANDA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PSYCHOANALYST-NOVELIST NOT AFRAID TO PLAY ON WOOLF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CLEA SIMON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ORLANDA 
By Jacqueline Harpman (translated, from the French, by Ros
Schwartz) 
Seven Stories Press, $22, 224 pp., $22 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reworking Virginia Woolf has come into vogue recently, with
books like Michael Cunningham's Pulitzer Prize-winning ``The Days''
reconsidering the author's stories from alternate viewpoints.
Belgian author and psychoanalyst Jacqueline Harpman does Woolf one
better though, in her 12th novel, the newly translated ``Orlanda.''
In this brief, light read, winner of France's Prix Medicis, Harpman
not only updates Woolf's ``Orlando,'' the tale of a gender-shifting
protagonist, she also makes her protagonist a literary scholar, one
who is deeply critical of Woolf.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Harpman's take on Woolf's classic is a direct parallel.
Rather than having one character shift sexes, as Orlando does,
Harpman's heroine, Aline, splits to live simultaneously in the
original female body and in that of a young man, Lucien, whom Aline
briefly, nearly unconsciously, admires in a train station. As
befits the creation of a psychoanalyst's mind, Aline's male persona
(who renames himself Orlanda) is really the rambunctious youthful
part of herself that she repressed upon hitting the latency period
that precedes adolescence. That this splinter personality decides
to take up residence in a handsome young man, 20 years old to
Aline's 35, is a result of society and convenience. Orlanda knows
that in a man's body he/she will be more free to play and to
experiment sexually. Perhaps more important for the impulsive
10-year-old spirit, the male ``host'' was there, sitting beside the
heroine in the station _ a place of transition _ at just the right
time.
</P>
<P>
   No, Aline does not have a multiple-personality disorder. Harpman
plays her story very straight, a metaphor that comes to life as
Aline works on an analysis of the Woolf original, which she
initially dreads. As if disowning the magic in her otherwise
realistic novel, Harpman occasionally inserts herself as a third
voice: a narrator who washes her hands of her errant characters as
they defy nature and personal boundaries to follow their own whims.
Her narrator's air of bemusement colors the entire book, and
actually makes the more far-fetched parts seem feasible. ``I think
he reminds me of a love affair that I did not have, because I was
too young or too silly,'' she writes about her newly emerged
Orlanda, and muses further: ``Unfortunately, I did not have the
presence of mind to turn into a boy and become adventurous.'' In
general, her breezy style works, making what could be a too-clever
work amusing and, at times, beautiful. ``Let us listen too for a
while,'' she writes of a concert attended by Orlanda. ``Time kills
us, second after second, and we fools continue to be impatient.''
</P>
<P>
   However, this same air of detachment also shackles Harpman's
story. On occasion, she skims too lightly, risking superficiality
with observations like: ``Where is my sense of propriety . . . to
my utter amazement, I see that she is smiling. Orlanda's influence
has really transformed her!'' Besides, its lighthearted approach
makes a deep connection to these characters' emotional lives
difficult; it's hard to feel that the entire book is anything but
an intellectual conceit. ``I have no blood on my hands, just a
little ink,'' Harpman herself admits, dismissing final
responsibility for her characters _ and perhaps for the work. For
all its spots of glory, as well as its occasional insights into the
older work, ``Orlanda'' remains a pleasurable pastime, an amusement
of the ``what if'' sort, but one a disciplined academic like Aline
would likely dismiss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 1403EST &QL; 
