<SLUG> BC-CASHMERE-CRAZE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GLUT OF CASHMERE LEADS TO LOWER PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VANESSA HUA  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A glut of cashmere fiber, stockpiled by herdsmen
during the past two years after demand had fallen in economically
depressed Asian countries, has caused prices to drop to historic
lows.
</P>
<P>
   Mass-market retailers in the United States have been able to
offer the luxury product at unusually low prices, industry experts
said.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the hardy goats from the high mountains and plateaus
of China, central Asia and India each produce just four to six
ounces of cashmere fiber each year. The manufacturing process also
is time-consuming.
</P>
<P>
   To collect the fiber, workers brush or shear the goats, then
separate the soft underdown from the coarse outer coat. It takes
cashmere fiber from four goats to make one woman's sweater. The low
yield and production costs make cashmere costly _ until this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the widespread availability of cashmere has caused some
consumers to question the price and quality.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Miller, 30, of San Francisco, spent hundreds of dollars
on her cashmere sweaters and paid to have them repaired when moths
chewed through the fine knit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get a good wear out of it,'' said Miller, who
considers cashmere an investment and said she was suspicious of
this year's lower-priced offerings.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``pashmina'' (shawls made from a blend of cashmere and
silk) also has created some confusion among shoppers and retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pashmina is a rare cashmere that comes from the underbelly of
Himalayan goats,'' said Ken Seiff, chief executive officer of
Bluefly.com, an on-line retailer that sold out its stock of
pashmina several times this season.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, scoffed officials at the Cashmere and Camel Hair
Manufacturers Institute in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pashmina is just a fancy word,'' said institute President Karl
Spilhaus. The institute's examination of pashmina under a
microscope found it was no different from other cashmere fiber, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The move of cashmere into the mass market may not last. Next
year, prices for cashmere and other items are expected to be much
higher, with high demand and a smaller supply already doubling the
price of raw materials.
</P>
<P>
   The wholesale price of white cashmere used in knitwear rose from
$60 to $120 per kilo, said Alex Shlomm, purchasing manager for New
York-based manufacturer Amicale Industries, which buys and spins
goat hair into yarn in Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The farmers and merchants get excited and keep jumping the
price up,'' Shlomm said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 1404EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4242 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-LEILA-HNS     12-20 0305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-LEILA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE MOTHER-IN-LAW FROM HELL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There has never been law than the one who wreaks conjugal havoc
in ``Leila.'' Her shrill sitcom sisters have nothing on the
relentlessly selfish harridan pulling the strings in Iranian
director Dariush Mehrjui's devastating account of an infertile
bride poisoned by devotion to a tradition not even her loving
husband supports.
</P>
<P>
   Leila and Reza (Leila Hatami and the great Ali Mossaffa) agree
that her inability to conceive will not be a barrier to their
happiness as a couple. But once it becomes clear to his family that
she can't have children, his mother plants this meddling seed in
Leila's head: Let Reza have a second wife so my son can have the
family I deserve.
</P>
<P>
   Like the transfixing films of his countrymen Abbas Kiarostami
and Mohsen Makhmalbaf, Mehrjui (``The Cow'') dares to draws his
culture's social politics on emotional terms.
</P>
<P>
   Leila is a woman in turmoil long before she serves as a
metaphor. By the time she tells Reza that she thinks he ought to
consider taking on another woman, she has already forced herself
into the shadows and spends the remainder of this willfully
infuriating film similarly self-effaced, resigning herself to the
guest room of her marriage. Repeatedly Leila is told to pray, but
she doesn't need Allah, she needs a therapist. But as written by
Mehrjui with Mahnaz Ansarian and eloquently acted by first-timer
Hatami, Leila is a tragic ball of confusion that any other
mother-in-law could love.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
