<HEADER>
A4243 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;  &UR; NEW     12-20 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
    NEW YORK'S CASES OF RACIAL INJUSTICE  
 Commentary    (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH    c.1999 Albany Times Union   ALBANY, N.Y. _ If Lucy
McKnight had ever been certain of anything, she was certain she had
been wronged. She had been working for the New York State Dormitory
Authority. An active Democrat and an African-American, she had been
hired during the administration of Mario Cuomo. After George Pataki
and his Republicans took over New York state government in 1994,
McKnight suffered health problems and missed some work. When she
was fired, she noted that a number of white folks with similar
absences hadn't been discharged. So McKnight filed suit against the
dormitory authority alleging racial discrimination. When the suit
finally made it to federal court a few weeks back, McKnight was
appalled to discover that all 100 people who made up the jury pool
were white. There would not be a single black face on the jury that
would hear her case. There's a reason for that. The federal court
district covering the northeastern portion of this sprawling,
50,000-square-mile state constitutes a part of the world where
black folks make up less than 3 percent of the population. Plus the
federal jury pool is culled from voter rolls and New York State
Department of Motor Vehicle records. Statistically,
African-Americans are less likely than whites to be voters,
licensed drivers or car owners. McKnight lost her case. She
believes firmly that if the jury had contained even one member who
had had a gut sense of what racial discrimination feels like, she
would have won. That may or not be true, but the intensity of
McKnight's conviction in this matter is only one more indication of
the stunning gulf that stretches between whites and minorities on
issues like this. Now, in this town, we're about to see another
illustration of just how immense that gulf can be. We'll see it
when four New York City police officers go on trial, probably late
next month, for the shooting death on Feb. 4 of a black West
African immigrant in the Bronx. Amadou Diallo, an innocent man, was
standing in a darkened doorway late at night. Four officers hunting
a rape suspect approached him, guns in hand. What happened next
will be the crux of this murder case against the cops. Diallo
either did something to lead the cops to believe mistakenly that he
was reaching for a weapon or they behaved with criminal
recklessness when they fired 41 slugs into that vestibule. This has
been a huge and heavily publicized case in New York City. In the
spring, the Rev. Al Sharpton led daily protests outside police
headquarters in Manhattan. More than 1,700 people, many show
business celebrities and prominent politicians, managed to get
themselves arrested at the demonstrations. Now an appeals court has
ruled that New York City media coverage has been so feverish that
the cops could never get a fair trial there. Instead, the cop will
be tried in Albany, the closest New York jurisdiction of any size
that doesn't watch New York City television stations. The Bronx
district attorney will prosecute this case. But instead of the jury
being chosen from a pool in the Bronx, where whites constitute a
distinct minority, this jury instead will be drawn from Albany
County, where the jury pool is 92 percent white. It should be
remembered, too, that the last time police officers went on trial
in this town charged with excessive violence against a black
arrestee _ just a few months back, in the infamous, foul-smelling
Jermaine Henderson case _ an all-white jury found the police
officers not guilty. Henderson had alleged, in rather plausible
terms, that the cops had beaten him while he was in handcuffs. But
the Albany County district attorney's office _ apparently eager to
take a dive that even Greg Louganis would have envied _ had
threatened to prosecute him for perjury if he testified in open
court because of inconsistencies in his grand jury testimony.
Henderson stayed away from the trial, and the cops walked. This
Diallo disaster will be a huge, hot case in Albany. The courthouse
is bound to be encircled daily by protesters bussed up from New
York City. Sharpton is sure to be at his loudest and least
responsible. Meanwhile, Lucy McKnight and other African-Americans
all over New York will be watching closely, as will most white
people, too. Each from their own side of that yawning gulf we were
talking about.    (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times
Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
