<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keep Windows 2000 in mind when buying or upgrading
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ While normal people are getting ready for the
holidays, the real geeks and wireheads among us have started
thinking about getting home computers ready for Windows 2000, the
coming edition of Windows that should be released early in the new
year.
</P>
<P>
   I've been using beta copies of 2000 for several months now. It's
not really fair to critique Windows based on test copies, since the
whole idea of a beta test is to find problems and bugs in the
software. But, all in all, it seems as if it will be (and it should
be) better than Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   Based on my experience, here are some things that will help you
get ready for Windows 2000 if you're thinking of buying a new
computer or upgrading the one that you have.
</P>
<P>
   Memory: Windows 95 and 98 used memory a lot better than Windows
3.1, but both are still flawed. For technical reasons that would
take too long to explain, some computers running these versions of
Windows actually slowed down after much more than 64 megabytes of
RAM were installed. Windows 2000 is built on the more robust
backbone of Windows NT (the industrial strength version of Windows)
and handles memory a lot better. It also seems to need more memory.
I'd suggest 128 megabytes of RAM.
</P>
<P>
   Accessories: Not every accessory that you are now using with
Windows 95 or 98 will work with Windows 2000. That applies even to
brand-new devices. For instance, just weeks ago I got a demo
version of a new game controller that plugs into the joystick port.
It won't work with Windows 2000. A smart buyer would know in
advance, since the package clearly stated that the controller
wasn't compatible with Windows NT (and, as I said, that's the
framework Windows 2000 is built on). So if you're shopping for
accessories, check the package to make sure that they'll work with
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Software: It's the same story here. Not all of your software
will work with Windows 2000. When you install 2000, the program
does a good job of identifying the programs on its list of
incompatible programs.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a tip, though. Many of the programs that 2000 flagged as
incompatible ran just fine, so don't delete those old programs
without actually trying them. And when you buy new software, look
on the package to make sure that it's Windows 2000 compatible.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the important ``gotchas'' to think about. But there
are some other things to keep in mind. These apply to any computer
running Windows.
</P>
<P>
   USB: That stands for universal serial bus port. Windows 98 and
Window 2000 support this technology, and it's a vast improvement
over the way things used to be. It's much easier to install new
equipment on a computer equipped with USB. You simply plug it in,
and it works. You can plug and unplug the device while the computer
is running, without a bunch of rebooting and reconfiguring. I've
literally never had a moment's trouble installing a USB device. You
can be sure that your new computer will have USB ports. I highly
recommend that _ when you're buying a new scanner, printer or other
device _ you get the USB version.
</P>
<P>
   Video cards: Most people don't know what computer gamers have
understood for a long time. A good video card can speed up your
computer at least as much as going to the next-fastest processor
chip. Even if you're not a gamer, make sure the next video card you
buy has at least 16 megabytes of onboard RAM. My own video card has
32 megabytes of RAM and _ even on my now-antique 350-megahertz
Pentium II machine at home _ things fly.
</P>
<P>
   One last thing to keep in mind. Windows 98 will be around for a
while. There is no law that says you have to buy and install
Windows 2000. But, since most of us probably will move to it
someday, it's smart to keep its requirements in mind when you buy a
new computer or upgrade the old one.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
