<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LEGEND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIDE-SCREEN BIOGRAPHY DETAILS JOHN FORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
PRINT THE LEGEND 
The Life and Times of John Ford 
By Scott Eyman. Simon &AMP; Schuster. 
656 pp. Illustrated. $40. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Ford didn't invent the Western. He could barely stay on a
horse (one longtime sidekick earned his wrath by saying Ford looked
like a sack of onions in the saddle). But the tall, lanky,
red-headed Irishman _ born John Martin Feeney in Portland, Maine,
in 1894, and known as Jack from childhood _ went west to become one
of the giants who invented and transformed movies. Before his 30th
birthday, he was mythologizing the West in ways that stretched and
defined the genre and America's way of thinking of the frontier
experience, of itself, and of its relation to the rest of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The title of this admirably thorough biography by Scott Eyman
comes from the last Western Ford made that can be thought of as
great, ``The Man Who Shot Liberty Valance'' (1962). In that rueful
meditation on the mythifying process of which Ford was so much a
part, a frontier newspaper editor says, ``This is the West, sir!
When the legend becomes fact, print the legend!'' The monumental
job facing Eyman was separating one from the other. This bountiful
study fills many a gap in previous books, supplying not just
on-the-set anecdotes, but descriptions of the shoot, including
finances. Possibly Eyman was aided by the fact that Ford died in
1973, before Eyman began the book. Ford was as great a storyteller
off-camera as on, and wasn't always the best source of fact about
his own life. We know too much about the last part of Ford's life,
not enough about the early days, and Eyman rights the imbalance.
</P>
<P>
   Ford was a closed book for most of his life. He
self-protectively hid his artist's soul behind a rough crust of
meanness. He dominated his sets in often bullying ways. For years,
he belittled two ex-football players turned actors and Ford
regulars _ John Wayne, who took Ford's abuse and became a good
actor, and Ward Bond, who also took it, but was rather more
successful as a McCarthy-era Red-baiter. Yet Ford wasn't always a
tyrant. He didn't say much on his sets, where he would spend a lot
of time chewing on a handkerchief balled up in his fist. But on
more than one occasion when he would see a young actor having
trouble, he'd walk over and murmur the one word that would be the
key to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the answer was to resist his bullying altogether.
Thomas Mitchell, the ex-newspaperman turned actor, once found
himself on the receiving end of Ford's barbs. ``I saw `Mary of
Scotland,' '' Mitchell said, silencing Ford by citing one of his
flops (although it led to a tempestuous relationship with its star,
Katharine Hepburn). Truculence was part of Ford's makeup. So was a
romantic streak. He went West under the shadow of his older
brother, Francis, an actor who employed Jack as a carpenter, stunt
man, editor, assistant director, actor. The Ford brothers were
loyal to each other, but also hard on each other. Once an explosion
on a set put Jack in a hospital for weeks with a broken arm. ``That
was close,'' Frank said. ``Another second and audiences would have
realized I was using a double.''
</P>
<P>
   In a few years, they underwent reversals of fortune. Frank ended
up playing drunks in Jack's Westerns. Their brother, Eddie, worked
for both of them off-camera. Jack and Eddie had fistfights well
into their 40s. But Jack wouldn't have dreamed of not giving Eddie
work.
</P>
<P>
   Ford was famous for his grudges long before he became famous for
his movies. Eyman does the moviegoing world a service by reminding
us that though Ford seemed to arrive full-blown as the foremost
director of Westerns in 1939 with ``Stagecoach,'' he had begun
making them as early as 1917. His admitted influences were the
best: D. W. Griffith, F. W. Murnau. Once, in the 1940s, someone
marveled at Ford's ability to shoot a Western in eight weeks. ``I
spent 26 years learning how to make a picture in eight weeks,''
Ford growled.
</P>
<P>
   Among his contemporaries, only Howard Hawks rivals Ford's
stature as a director of Westerns, and Hawks made far fewer of
them. Ford's first epic Western was a silent, ``The Iron Horse''
(1924). You can bracket the arc of the Western with two shots of
John Wayne's face _ open, hopeful, and energized in ``Stagecoach''
(1939), twisted by hate and alienated from civilization in ``The
Searchers'' (1956), arguably Ford's greatest Western because it
strips away any hint of bonhomie that sentimentalizes the racist
violence behind the so-called winning of the West.
</P>
<P>
   Critics who feel closer to the iconoclastic thrust of Sam
Peckinpah's ``The Wild Bunch'' than to Ford's output would do well
to reexamine not only ``The Searchers'' but also ``My Darling
Clementine'' (1946). Ford's retelling of the story of Wyatt Earp
and Doc Holliday and the Gunfight at the OK Corral marked the
genre's turning away from heroics toward melancholy introspection,
a quality to be found as well in ``Fort Apache'' (1948) and ``She
Wore a Yellow Ribbon'' (1949).
</P>
<P>
   ``My Darling Clementine'' and ``The Searchers'' seem less a
double-barreled broadside against imperialism than a reaction to
the depleting of American optimism by the horrors of World War II.
Like his contemporaries Frank Capra and George Stevens, Ford found
his worldview darkened by his experience making wartime
documentaries. If the detective story turned into film noir, Ford's
Westerns turned fatalistic. Still, Ford has always been more than a
little misunderstood. Because he has so closely been identified
with Wayne and Wayne's politics, and loved strutting around in his
Navy uniform, Ford has been thought of as a right-wing
propagandist.
</P>
<P>
   Although he embraced Nixon at the end, he voted for Kennedy in
1960, had supported Truman in 1948, and was a big fan of FDR's
progressive politics. In a highly theatrical and totally effective
way, the canny Ford, whose patriotism was beyond question, routed
the Red-baiters who tried to take control of the Directors Guild in
the blacklist days. His Westerns were never about heroic loners
(contrary to the image Wayne was made to stand for, especially
later in his career). They were more about communal energies. In
``Stagecoach,'' Ford clearly sides with the tarnished proles over
the stuffy respectable hypocrites.
</P>
<P>
   His sympathies become clearer in light of the communal values in
his best non-Westerns: ``The Grapes of Wrath'' (1940), ``The Long
Voyage Home'' (1941), ``How Green Was My Valley'' (1942), ``They
Were Expendable'' (1945), even his idealized Irish idyll, ``The
Quiet Man'' (1952). Ford saw films in his head, painting with the
camera, finding and pouncing upon humanizing detail. He began by
making up films as he went along, only later devising scripts, and
only because studio executives demanded them. Colleague after
colleague tells how Ford had whole sections of films in his mind
before shooting even began. As the years went by, his shooting
style became simpler, sparer, until the end, when his energies
flagged and he produced long, slack films like ``The Long Grey
Line'' (1955) and ``Cheyenne Autumn'' (1964).
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he was most comfortable in mostly male societies heavily
populated by cronies he could boss around. His shoots in Monument
Valley were, psychically speaking, little Western expeditions of
escape and exploration with people he knew and with whom he kept
repeating the experience. Some the public never saw _ like Danny
Borzage, director Frank Borzage's brother, whose job for decades
was to hang around the set playing Ford's favorite songs on the
accordion (a device many silent movie directors used to get the
right mood on set). By the standards of the day, he treated the
Navajos of Monument Valley well. They made him an honorary Navajo,
gave him blankets and keepsakes, which he kept in his bedroom in a
Los Angeles home he often fled to be alone on his yacht, Araner _
his one luxury.
</P>
<P>
   Like many an artist, he was not a sterling family man. Making
films was his thing, not being a husband or father. Even if the
city of Portland hadn't gotten around to erecting a statue of Ford
a few years ago, his place in history would be assured. Given
access to family records and documents, Eyman has diligently sorted
out fact from fiction, including the travails Ford experienced as
an artist trying to make his own films his own way. Today Ford
would thrive as an independent. Had his health and energies held,
he might have done more TV, to which he was ideally suited, given
his background in quickly and cheaply grinding out two- and
three-reelers. Of course, he never would discuss his films or his
methods in terms of art _ only craft, and not much of that. In a
country of immigrants reinventing themselves, Ford sometimes was
his own best creation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
