<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-HARBISON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARBISON'S `GATSBY' A LONGTIME LABOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Like many people of his generation, John
Harbison read ``The Great Gatsby'' when he was in high school, more
than four decades ago. Unlike some of his classmates, Harbison read
F. Scott Fitzgerald's novel because he wanted to, not because an
English teacher assigned it. ``All of my friends were reading the
book,'' Harbison recalled last week, sitting by the fire in his
kitchen. ``So I read it too. Also my father taught at Princeton,
and the Princeton-Fitzgerald connection was still very strong in
those days.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gatsby'' has stayed with Harbison ever since. He has always
wanted to be an opera composer in a world where that is a very
difficult ambition to fulfill, and ``Gatsby'' has always been an
opera he wanted to write. But the rights to adaptations were tied
up by Fitzgerald's literary executors, so Harbison composed two
other operas first, ``Winter's Tale,'' after Shakespeare, and
``Full Moon in March,'' after Yeats. There were a couple of other
operatic projects that didn't come to fruition, though Harbison
continued to compose prolifically for solo and choral voices, as
well as in just about every other genre of music. By 1985, Harbison
had given up on ``Gatsby,'' but he bade an elegant, eloquent, and
engaging farewell to his ambition by putting some of his musical
thoughts about the book into an overture, ``Remembering Gatsby.''
That piece has become one of his greatest hits; even the Boston
Pops has played it.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later Harbison made an ``innocent discovery'' _ he
did the math and discovered that the novel was about to enter
public domain, and his projected opera became a possibility again.
Harbison forged ahead, though two prominent composers serving on a
panel with him told him they had tried to wrestle it onto the
Broadway stage and determined that ``it can't be done.'' Ultimately
the Metropolitan Opera commissioned Harbison's opera to commemorate
the 25th anniversary of the debut of James Levine, and so Levine
will conduct the world premiere of ``The Great Gatsby'' at the Met
on Monday night _ coincidentally Harbison's 61st birthday _ with a
prestigious cast headed by Dawn Upshaw as Daisy, Jerry Hadley as
Gatsby, Susan Graham as Jordan Baker, Lorraine Hunt Lieberson as
Myrtle, Dwayne Croft as Nick, and Mark Baker as Tom Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Harbison composed the score between June 20, 1995, and Dec. 20,
1996, in a variety of venues _ Cambridge; his wife's family's farm
in Wisconsin; Sand Point, Idaho; Martha's Vineyard; Italy. Before
he started composing, he drafted his own libretto. (He found one of
two surviving copies of a once-popular 1926 stage version, but
found it unhelpful.) Harbison's solution to the problem of the
novel's indirection was to put its narrative line onto the stage
and its indirection into the music, which warms up some of
Fitzgerald's unpleasantly hedonistic characters and makes them more
interesting and better company. (Harbison's mother had said to him,
``What do you want to write an opera about so many disagreeable
people for?''). Harbison the composer found Harbison the librettist
``compliant'' in a way that some composers have not found their
librettists, and as he worked, he changed some of the libretto to
follow where the music was leading. ``One amazing thing about the
human voice,'' Harbison says, ``is that it is impossible to be
unsympathetic to someone who is singing.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Harbison's important pre-compositional decisions was not
to rely on period pop music to do a lot of the work of creating
atmosphere, which is the route most dramatizations of ``Gatsby''
have taken. Harbison began by writing 13 '20s-style pop songs that
would thread through the score; after struggling with trying to
write period lyrics, he sent six of the songs out to Murray
Horwitz, who knows the turf (the others are heard as instrumental
numbers, for which Horwitz has supplied lyrics not heard in the
opera). The pop songs contain within them the motives and harmonies
of the rest of the score, so that Harbison could ``glide in and out
of them, seamlessly,'' coming up, he hopes, with a new solution to
an age-old dilemma of how to integrate songs and arias into
theatrical exposition. ``Mozart solved this problem, and so did the
Fred Astaire/Ginger Rogers pictures. The songs in `Gatsby,' I hope,
will help some people find their way into the opera; more analytic
members of the audience will recognize how the same music runs
throughout. Every era has to dicker with the recognition of what
`melody' is.''
</P>
<P>
   Harbison certainly knows the musical turf as well as Horwitz
knows the lyrics of the period. His father was a dance-band leader,
and he says he wrote ``Remembering Gatsby'' as an opportunity to
see his father tuxed up again. He himself started playing in a
Dixieland band at 11, and the music of Louis Armstrong, Wild Bill
Davis, and Max Kaminsky is something he has known his whole life.
What he didn't know as well was the music of the social milieu of
``Gatsby,'' so he put himself through a course of Bix Beiderbecke
and Paul Whiteman in order to reproduce some of the characteristic
sounds of the period. He's grateful to some historically informed
jazzmen in the Met orchestra who have improved on his own knowledge
_ he had scored for high-hat cymbals, for example, but a player
told him that they hadn't been invented by the early '20s, and the
player showed him how '20s musicians created what sounds like
high-hat work on period recordings.
</P>
<P>
   The soprano sax is heard in the ``Gatsby'' orchestra, and so is
the banjo; there is also an ``ahuugah'' horn of a Stutz Bearcat in
the music, and a couple of wandering stage bands, which during the
party scenes create layers of texture like the ones in the finales
of Mozart's ``Don Giovanni.''
</P>
<P>
   As Harbison worked, casting fell into place. Dawn Upshaw was in
from the beginning; the others came later, and by the time Harbison
was composing the second act, everyone was in place. ``It was very
good to have images of the performers, aural and visual, as I
worked. I found myself expanding the character of the working-class
Myrtle, who is a kind of downscale Gatsby, filled with the same
kinds of inchoate longings. I tried to give her a different class
of music, and with a wide range of emotions in it. You don't have
Lorraine in mind without thinking of a wide range of emotion. Mark
Baker I saw as the Drum Major in `Wozzeck,' the best I ever saw,
and so that may have entered into my thinking. The Met saw Gatsby
as a baritone, a specific baritone, but I always thought of him as
a lyric tenor, with Tom as a heavy, Wagner kind of tenor.''
</P>
<P>
   One fringe benefit that came to Harbison was to attend many Met
performances as he composed. ``I saw all the standard pieces like
`Aida,' `Carmen,' and `Butterfly,' and I kept going back to pieces
I love, like `Eugen Onegin.' And I went to all the 20th-century
operas the company was doing _ `Wozzeck,' `Moses und Aron,' `A
Midsummer Night's Dream,' and `Lady Macbeth of Mtsensk.' This I
found very useful, particularly hearing how different sizes of
voices projected over different kinds of orchestration in the large
theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, there was a reading of two scenes at Emmanuel
Music, where Harbison serves as principal guest conductor; later
there were readings of other scenes by students at Aspen under the
direction of David Zinman. Harbison found these readings immensely
helpful, and he made some changes as a result; at the request of
the Met technical staff, he rewrote an orchestral interlude because
they told him the scene change the interlude was covering was
impossible without additional music.
</P>
<P>
   Once the opera was out of his hands and into those of the Met,
Harbison found himself delighted, sometimes bewildered, sometimes
amazed. Opera on the Met scale is a complex mechanism involving
hundreds of people and many individual efforts that do not coalesce
until the last moment _ Harbison says he sometimes felt like the
proverbial blind man with his hand on the hide of an elephant.
``Some pieces you know, but you have to figure out how they fit
with others that you don't know. It is absolutely amazing how any
opera ever gets put on; a tremendous number of people have to
function at a very high level.''
</P>
<P>
   Harbison is full of praise for the direction of Mark Lamos, who
directed the world premiere of ``Winter's Tale'' in San Francisco
in 1970; for the efforts of the cast; for the design team _ he
shows you Jane Greenwood's spectacular costume designs with as much
pleasure as if he had drawn them himself. And being Harbison, he
has found something to learn in every part of the experience. (``I
didn't understand that if a set design looks terrific, you're
probably in trouble; the set has to work together with the
costumes.'')
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Harbison is full of admiration for Levine. ``His
theory of conducting is unique in the present day, I think; he
wants the orchestra and the music to come to him. He transfers a
lot of the responsibility for interpretation to the players, so he
looks like a throwback to the era of Pierre Monteux, Bruno Walter,
Fritz Reiner, or George Szell. It is all centered in what he is
doing, with such tremendous economy and authority _ totally
different from so much conducting today which cries `wolf' so many
times that it wears out its authority. In rehearsal, he will
sometimes let things swim for a while, so that the players can
learn with their ears why and how it happened; the final result is
playing of the highest standard. The players are not peons but
participants in the performance. Their mandate is to offer detail;
his is to stay calm and out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, ``Gatsby'' is already securely in the composer's
past _ the premiere comes exactly three years after he put down the
last note. He has since written a major work for the Chicago
Symphony, and he is working on a concerto for orchestra for the
Minnesota Orchestra; an orchestra/choral work for the Boston
Symphony; and some chamber-music projects, including a song cycle
on poems by Elizabeth Bishop and a piece for flute and strings for
Randolph Bowman, the former Boston freelancer and principal flute
of the Cincinnati Symphony whose performance of Harbison's flute
concerto blew the composer away.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he hopes the Met audience will take out of the
theater with them, Harbison says, ``I hope people will be haunted
by some aspect of it _ the way I am haunted by other operas I have
seen. What you see in a opera is very preoccupying, but you also
carry out of the theater a sense of musical space, and the rhythm
of the piece, its musical and psychological content. This is an
opera about yearning and longing, like `Tristan und Isolde,' or
`Eugen Onegin,' from the feminine side _ but yearning of a
particularly American kind. Opera haunts people more than concert
music does; that's because purely musical impressions are mingled
with other kinds of experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
