<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4252 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-JORDAN-BOS &LR;      12-20 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-JORDAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN TAKES A GAMBLE WITH GRAHAM GREENE'S `AFFAIR' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it was published, in 1951, Graham Greene's ``The End of the
Affair'' was hailed by such literary luminaries as William
Faulkner, who anointed the book ``one of the most true and moving
novels of my time,'' and Evelyn Waugh, who considered the novel
``singularly moving and beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Neil Jordan has always considered ``The End of the Affair,'' a
book he first discovered as a young man in his native Ireland,
``one of the most frank and moving books about a love affair that
I've ever read.'' But Jordan, the writer-director of such films as
``Mona Lisa,'' ``The Crying Game,'' and ``Michael Collins,'' also
believes the book is ``very plotty,'' and its conclusion
``absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone once said that story is where the characters do what
they want to do, and plot is where the characters do what the
author wants them to do,'' said Jordan, over a recent breakfast at
a Boston hotel. ``And the book seemed to me very plotty. I thought
the author was very intrusive, especially at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   So in his adaptation, Jordan resolved to make bold changes that
would, in his words, ``let the characters breathe. The changes I've
made, I think, make the story more real and more poignant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The End of the Affair,'' which opens Christmas Day, stars
Ralph Fiennes, Julianne Moore, and Stephen Rea. As the film begins
it is 1946, and Bendrix (Fiennes) is still tied in knots over the
abrupt end of his affair with Sarah (Moore, resurrecting the
British accent that served her so well in ``An Ideal Husband'') two
years before. Without explanation, Sarah suddenly walked away from
Bendrix, vowing to see him no more. She returns to life with her
husband, Henry (Rea, appearing in his eighth Jordan film), a kind,
but achingly dull civil servant. A chance meeting between Bendrix
and Henry pushes Bendrix to discover why he was unceremoniously
dumped by Sarah.
</P>
<P>
   It is a love story, yes, but it is also a deeply spiritual tale
about the profound sacrifice one may be willing to make for someone
he or she loves. ``The End of the Affair'' is considered Greene's
most autobiographical novel; it was based, in part, on his own
affair with a married woman.
</P>
<P>
   When he read the novel again five years ago, Jordan immediately
thought ``it would make a lovely movie,'' he said. There was
already a film version, a poorly received 1955 adaptation that
starred Deborah Kerr as Sarah, the decidedly un-British Van Johnson
as Bendrix, and Peter Cushing as Henry. Greene is said to have
hated the film, directed by Edward Dmytryk; Jordan took his own
look shortly before beginning his version.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not very good,'' he said in his soft Irish accent. ``It's
just one of those very pedestrian adaptations they made in the '40
and '50s. They made (Bendrix) American so it didn't make sense at
all. And they couldn't show any of the sexuality, so you couldn't
really tell what was going on. The social context was lost, and
that was confusing.''
</P>
<P>
   That Dmytryk film, Jordan said, became a heavy-handed morality
tale undermining the sensuality of Greene's love story. He wanted
to restore those emotions, and highlight the book's central event _
a bombing during the Blitz that marks a dramatic moment for both
lovers, but especially for Sarah, who makes a desperate deal with
God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it important that this event be seen from many
different angles,'' Jordan said. ``I thought it could be filmed to
show the actual meanings of these particular events in these
people's lives. I think it's a timeless story. The dilemma Sarah is
put in is a terribly human one, and one I could understand now.''
</P>
<P>
   What didn't work for Jordan was the novel's later chapters, and
that is where his film differs most markedly from the novel. The
death of a major character, which occurs about two-thirds of the
way through the book, comes near the conclusion of Jordan's
adaptation. That structural change, Jordan maintained, does right
by Greene's characters in a way that perhaps the author himself
could not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't believe'' some of the events in the book, said
Jordan, who was himself a novelist before he became a filmmaker.
``Greene's a bit like Thomas Hardy in that he tends to manipulate
his characters toward the positions he wants them to hold. You can
feel him pushing the characters in those directions. So I tried to
allow the stories and the characters to breathe a little bit more,
allow them to exist, and allow the ideas to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Graham Greene was a really messed-up British Catholic, and I
wanted to make the explanations far more ambiguous,'' he said. ``In
the end, I didn't want to explain whatever was happening.''
</P>
<P>
   If Greene purists are disturbed by the liberties Jordan has
taken _ and they likely will be _ the director is undaunted. He's
been down this path before, having stared down bloodthirsty Anne
Rice devotees when he cast Tom Cruise as the vampire Lestat in his
1994 ``Interview with the Vampire.'' Rice herself was among the
most vocal, complaining that Cruise ``is no more my vampire Lestat
than Edward G. Robinson is Rhett Butler.'' (She later praised the
finished film, which went on to earn more than $100 million.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I was unprepared for that because I didn't know the enormous
reputation the book had in America,'' said Jordan, recalling the
barrage of criticism he endured while adapting Rice's novel. ``But
we had a clear mind about what we wanted to do,'' he said, ``and I
suppose in a strange way all the public fuss about it drew us
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Jordan, Greene has been dead for eight years _
not that Jordan believes the writer would have necessarily
objected. As for disgruntled fans, Jordan said, ``I think it's
their problem, I honestly do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's an incredibly powerful story, and Greene became
overwhelmed by ideas. That's one of the reasons I wanted to make
the movie,'' he said. ``I thought his philosophical concerns were
destroying the very beautiful human story he told.''
</P>
<P>
   At 49, Jordan has had a varied, see-saw career. There have been
highs such as ``Mona Lisa'' and ``The Crying Game,'' for which his
original screenplay won an Academy Award in 1993; and lows such as
``We're No Angels,'' which managed to make both Robert De Niro and
Sean Penn look bad, and ``In Dreams,'' a godawful psychological
thriller starring Annette Bening and Robert Downey Jr. earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even sure I should be making films in the United
States,'' he said with a laugh, admitting his American films have
tended to be his least successful. ``I can make `Mona Lisa' in
England, and understand the context; I can make (``The End of the
Affair'') in Britain, and understand the context. Obviously, I can
make any Irish movie because I know the characters,'' said Jordan,
who lives in Ireland. ``But over here, I just don't know, say, how
a father and daughter in Massachusetts would instinctively relate
to each other. I don't know all that stuff people just breathe over
here. So it's probably better for European directors like me to
make European films, although that doesn't mean I won't be offered
American films.''
</P>
<P>
   And while he still wants to make films in America, he's happy to
steer clear of the noisy, megabudgeted action films Hollywood's
most famous for these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``'I don't think, unless you're Jim Cameron or Steven Spielberg,
those big huge movies really belong to the director,'' he said.
``Besides, I'm sure there are people who can do those much better
than I can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
