<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4253 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-ROCKS-BOS &LR;      12-20 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ROCKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD-FASHIONED LOVE STORY OF SCARLET LETTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
FORTUNE'S ROCKS 
By Anita Shreve. 
Little, Brown. 453 pp. $24.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Otempora, o mores! Back in the days of carriages and
shirtwaists, when men were men and women were girls, physical
passion was not a force one unleashed lightly. Surrendering to it
outside the strictures of society's blessings could ruin your life,
particularly if you were a young woman of a particular class who
was supposed to marry well. But desire still lurked among the
shoals, as we know from the opening lines of Anita Shreve's
full-frontal novel. The first paragraph of ``Fortune's Rocks''
contains the words ``licks,'' ``pink,'' ``naked,'' and ``shudder,''
and that's just the description of a girl walking barefoot in the
sand.
</P>
<P>
   So you get the sense fairly quickly that this will not be a
novel of ideas; in fact, ``Fortune's Rocks'' is a bodice-ripper
with a mission. For all its sultry attention to the breathtakingly
doomed romance between a 15-year-old girl and a man nearly three
times her age, it also borrows from the conventions of Dreiser,
Dickens, and Hawthorne, both in its overtones about oppressive
morality and in its revelations about the haves and have-nots. With
its token bow to ``Sister Carrie'' and ``The Scarlet Letter,'' this
is a big, old-fashioned novel with its heart in the right place,
even if its sensibility lies somewhere between heavy breathing and
a heavy hand.
</P>
<P>
   I devoured it shamelessly, despite initial misgivings (that
opening paragraph) and making snippy margin comments. Certainly
Shreve is beloved by readers for earlier works, especially ``The
Pilot's Wife'' and ``The Weight of Water,'' and this story contains
the same combination of narrative scope and tension that has served
her in the past. But it is the unalloyed character of Shreve's
young protagonist, Olympia Biddeford, that gives the story its
staying power. Following her heart into dangerously deep waters,
she will spend most of her life trying to rectify her early
impulsiveness. Still, Olympia is no ninny and even turns out to be
a lousy martyr. She has good sense, and the emotional posture of a
woman who knows how to care for herself, whether out of
self-respect or sheer instinct for survival. And the little world
that has witnessed her downfall seems hellbent on robbing her of
both.
</P>
<P>
   The only child of a well-heeled Beacon Hill literary editor,
Phillip Biddeford, and his neurasthenic wife, Rosamund, Olympia has
accompanied her parents as they flee the Boston heat for their
house in the summer community at Fortune's Rocks, on the New
Hampshire seashore. It is 1899, and Olympia is under the tutelage
of her father, an intellectual and progressive whose love for the
girl is revealed through rigorous instruction. One day he gives her
a collection of essays by a physician who runs a clinic in the
nearby mill town of Ely Falls; the fellow is coming to visit,
Biddeford counsels his daughter, so she might as well familiarize
herself with his work. This is the first Olympia has heard of John
Haskell, who is 41, with a wife and four children. By the time the
two are finished shaking hands a few days later, destiny and
longing is written all over them both.
</P>
<P>
   So: She's a girl on the verge of becoming a woman, beautiful and
smart and already accustomed to admiring older men. He's on the
verge of life's mid-afternoon, but he's also swimmingly masculine,
passionate about caring for the poor, and has a close-focus
charisma that, to a 15-year-old, must be as blinding as the sun.
There are a few noble attempts to keep their desire at bay _ she
accompanies him to attend a breech birth; he insists during
emotional moments that this connection is all they can ever have _
but within a few weeks they are wildly in love, or in something.
Much running up and down the beach for Olympia, who lies to her
father and then takes flight for the hotel where Haskell awaits
her. Much hand-wringing for Haskell, who knows better, flings
himself between torment and lust, then risks everything anyway.
</P>
<P>
   This cannot last, of course, and the scandal, when it becomes
public, is devastating. Poised in that hinterland between want and
wisdom, Olympia foresees what lies ahead _ ``that she has forfeited
her future'' _ just before the bough breaks. Disgraced, Haskell
loses his family as well as his practice. Olympia, having torn her
father's heart out, returns to the Biddeford home in Boston, where
the following spring she will have a son, taken from her in the
first moments of life. Banished to a female seminary in Western
Massachusetts, Olympia could well go on to live a life of piety and
mourning, but some semblance of core strength propels her toward
another course of action.
</P>
<P>
   And all this in the first half of the novel! Relying upon a few
aged but sturdy conventions _ desire under the elms, tragedy,
penance, redemption _ Shreve has written a period piece of a
certain predictability, but she has tried to imbue it with moral
authenticity, and that effort mostly succeeds. Her worst error
regarding the doomed lovers concerns Olympia's continual insistence
that she hasn't been seduced _ a protestation that at first seems
lead-footed, then shrill (on Shreve's part, not her character's),
and does little to redeem Haskell in the reader's eyes. The only
feat which accomplishes that is his own suffering; as with
Hawthorne's Arthur Dimmesdale, his measure of nobility is hardly a
match for the likes of Hester Prynne.
</P>
<P>
   And this Hester, too, will have her day. I was surprised to care
as much for Olympia Biddeford as I came to through the course of
her sodden story: not for her blunders and sorrows, which are those
any girl could claim, but for her mercy _ her strength and kindness
in the face of despair. Shreve has woven fine and elaborate cloth
around her heroine, giving the 19th-century communities of
Fortune's Rocks and Ely Falls historical accuracy as well as
evocative detail. Her attention to the opposing social milieus of
the summer rich and the mill workers, a tension that will figure in
Olympia's plight, has done her story a world of good, opening it up
beyond a romance cum morality tale to greater narrative sweep. She
can be an impatient writer _ tidying up a disaster, she might go
from rubble to repair in a couple of sentences _ but her gifts as a
storyteller have to do with a kind of prime-time realism. Having
set up that dependable formula of windswept heartbreak in the dunes
(O mores! O moors!), she knows precisely when to cut and when to
fade.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is the chief book critic of The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
