<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Anne Morrow Lindbergh'' by Susan Hertog (Nan A.
Talese/Doubleday, $30). In search of a living moral example, the
biographer finds a woman who married the century's dominant public
hero but who craved privacy and silence. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Flu'' by Gina Kolata (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $25). A
masterly recounting of medical history, and a good mystery story
about the pandemic of 1918-19. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeats's Ghosts: The Secret Life of W. B. Yeats'' by Brenda
Maddox (HarperCollins, $32). How the spirit world, and a spirited
woman, aided the great Irish poet. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Rembrandt's Eyes'' by Simon Schama (Knopf, $50). A lively and
wide-ranging biography/appreciation of the original Dutch master. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Voyage'' by Philip Caputo (Knopf, $26). Three boys from
Maine on a sailing ship, bound for the Caribbean. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Test: The Secret History of the American Meritocracy''
by Nicholas Lemann (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $27). How the SAT
became the preeminent standard for college admission.
</P>
</TEXT>
