<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !! ``American Movie'' Chris Smith's documentary about a
desperate amateur filmmaker in Wisconsin trying to will a grade-Z
horror movie into being. At first, it seems like campy Americana,
but then it veers uncomfortably into geek-show territory. (R) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   !!! ``Anna and the King'' This handsome, intelligent retelling
of the story of the British teacher who aided the King of Siam's
policy of education and enlightenment in the 1860s is inevitably
old-fashioned, despite a few tweakings for the sake of political
correctness. But it's more than carried by the character in Jodie
Foster's Anna and Chow Yun-Fat's progressive king. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   !! 1/2 ``Bicentennial Man'' Robin Williams goes the touchy-feely
route again, this time as a sensitive robot who prospers, acquires
some reprogramming, and falls for the granddaughter of the family
that bought him, thinking he was no more than a snazzy household
appliance. (PG) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BS)!! 1/2 ``The Cider House Rules'' The best film yet of a John
Irving novel. It's built around the surrogate father/surrogate son
relationship between Michael Caine's saintly orphanage doc and
Tobey Maguire's innocent, which lasts even after the boy departs to
taste of the tree of knowledge (via a job on an apple farm) in the
1940s. Lasse Halstrom bolsters the rich characters with sensitive
and lyrical direction. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``Ride with the Devil'' Ang Lee's historical romance reminds us
that the Civil War was fought with particular savagery in Kansas
and Missouri, where pro-slavery planters and abolitionists were
neighbors. But most of the film focuses on the lulls between the
bloody outbreaks, and on how the loosely organized Confederate
forces known as Bushwhackers survived. Intelligent and absorbing,
it requires patience, but repays it with nuanced performances from
Tobey Maguire, Skeet Ulrich, Jeffrey Wright, and Jewel. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``Stuart Little'' Serviceable rather than magical, this
retelling of E. B. White's classic story of a spunky mouse who
refuses to think small has warm performances, the most up-to-date
computer-generated mouse Hollywood can buy, and a scene-stealing
Noo Yawk voice from Nathan Lane as the Little family's resentful
cat. But it never charms us out of an awareness that we're watching
a manufactured object. (PG) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! 1/2 ``The War Zone'' Tim Roth's first outing as a director is a
harrowingly courageous film about incest in a claustrophobic
British family in Devon. In its uncompromising choice of subject
matter and its go-for-broke (yet never falsely sensationalized)
execution, it's an extraordinary piece of work. Lara Belmont makes
an unforgettable acting debut as a troubled teenager. (Unrated) &QL; 
 &QL; 
! 1/2 ``Where's Marlowe?'' Not here. This lame effort can't make up
its mind whether it wants to spoof private eye noirs or independent
filmmaking cliches. It fails at both as it takes the ungainly form
of a mockumentary about a couple of filmmakers who find themselves
bailing out a struggling LA detective agency headed by Mel Ferrer's
gumshoe hooked on Sam Spade and Philip Marlowe. (R)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 1415EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
