<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISAPPOINTED COUPLE WANT REFUND ON RING BOUGHT IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL AND PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a stop in Cozumel on a Caribbean cruise last month, Michael
and Nancy Greco paid $2,400 for a tanzanite and diamond ring that
their Mexican jeweler appraised at $6,530.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tremendous bargain, and normally the type of savings
that would make the couple from southeastern Massachusetts wonder
whether something was amiss. But the Grecos had been reassured by
representatives of their cruise line, Celebrity Cruises, a division
of Royal Caribbean Cruises Ltd., that everything was on the up and
up.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Grecos say cruise line representatives gave a
lecture before the ship docked at the island off Mexico's Yucatan
Peninsula, telling guests that they would be able to buy jewelry
for far less than in the United States and receive a guarantee of
quality and value as long as they shopped at specific stores. The
guarantee was contingent on an appraisal by an independent
gemologist within 30 days of the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we went there,'' said Nancy Greco, referring to the
jeweler Rachat &AMP; Romero. ``We wouldn't just go to anybody,
particularly in Mexico. The cruise line went out of its way to say
how great they were.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Grecos returned from their cruise, Michael Greco had
the ring appraised, but discovered that finding a gemologist with
no ties to any store was not so easy. But he kept searching, and
eventually had the ring appraised for a fee of $100 by Arthur
DeMello Jr. of National Gemological Laboratories in New Bedford,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   When the appraisal arrived in the mail, the Grecos were shocked.
The ring that Rachat &AMP; Romero had appraised at $6,530 was appraised
by DeMello for $1,900, a difference of $4,630. DeMello told us
appraisals are not a ``black and white science, there's always a
gray area. But the gray area doesn't overlap from $2,000 to
$6,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the Grecos' jewelry bargain began to look a lot like a
scam. The Grecos said that instead of paying far less than they
would have paid in the United States, they paid more.
</P>
<P>
   Antoinette Matlins, a gem and jewelry specialist from South
Woodstock, Vt., who has written a number of jewelry buying guides
for consumers, said she could not vouch for the accuracy of the
Grecos' appraisal. But she said jewelry fraud is rampant abroad,
and she described cruise ship passengers as lambs being herded to
slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``These stores are taking advantage of the fact that people are
looking for bargains,'' Matlins said. ``Everyone wants a memento of
their trip and, for women, jewelry is one of the favorite
mementos.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the cruise line's guarantee, she said it was the first
she had ever heard of it. ``But it's an easy promise to make since
most people, quite frankly, don't bother to check out anything when
they get home,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Liz Jakeway, a Celebrity Cruises spokeswoman, said the in-port
shopping program is handled by a subcontractor called Onboard
Media. Hugh Treadwell, a vice president with Onboard, said that
participating retailers agree to repair or replace any
unsatisfactory item. ``It's not a price guarantee, and it's not a
guarantee of future value,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Rachat &AMP; Romero, the Cozumel jeweler, officials described the
Grecos' complaint as a ``misunderstanding.'' The store's customer
service manager, Leslie Pubols, said the jeweler does a ``huge
business'' with cruise line passengers and insisted such problems
are rare.
</P>
<P>
   She said the appraised price that the Grecos received from
Rachat &AMP; Romero was more like a suggested retail price, even though
it was identified as an appraised price on a document entitled
``certified appraisal.''
</P>
<P>
   To clear up the misunderstanding, Pubols originally offered
Michael Greco $400, then raised the offer to $500, the difference
between his $1,900 appraisal and the $2,400 he paid. When he
demanded more, she offered to reimburse the entire $2,400 if he
returned the ring to Rachat &AMP; Romero's Florida supplier.
</P>
<P>
   Matlins said full reimbursement is customary when a dispute
about the value of jewelry arises. Treadwell called the jeweler's
offer ``extremely diplomatic'' and not required by the guarantee.
He said he would have asked for a second appraisal.
</P>
<P>
   But Greco said that agreeing to a refund would be letting the
cruise line and the jeweler off too easily. ``They're basically
saying, `You caught us at fraud so what we'll do is give you your
money back.' I think that stinks. How many other people are they
ripping off?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Greco said the $2,400 he paid for the ring was 37 percent of the
Rachat &AMP; Romero appraised price. He said he would be satisfied if
he paid 37 percent of the $1,900 appraisal, which would mean Rachat
&AMP; Romero or the cruise line would have to refund him $1,697. He
also wants them to pay the $100 cost of his appraisal.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides currently are at a standoff. Pubols has refused to
offer anything more than a refund, and Greco, who paid for the ring
with a credit card, is disputing the charge and refusing to pay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Odds &AMP; Ends
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Wrong year on personal checks. As the 2,000th year approaches,
a reader said she is puzzled about how to fill out the dates on her
personal checks, all of which are preprinted with the year 19--.
Should she cross out the first two digits and write in 2000? That
indeed is the answer to this millennium issue, but it is not worth
fretting over. Robert Fichter, spokesman for the Massachusetts
Bankers Association, said the official date is the one stamped by
the bank, not the one scribbled by the check-writer. He said people
ought to be more worried about possible Y2K scams, such as
strangers, posing as government or banking officials, calling up
and asking for bank account or credit card information.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(We want your consumer ideas and tips. Please call (617) 474-2510
or e-mail Mohl at mohl(at)globe.com or Wen at wen(at)globe.com.
Their address is PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
