u l BC-CHRISTMAS-CHICKEN-BOS     12-20 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-CHICKEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE LAUGHTER NEVER STOPPED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By P. CLEMENT HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was not an auspicious start to the Christmas vacation in my
senior year so long ago. Fifty years to be exact, but the memories
have burned into my soul.
</P>
<P>
   I had just come home for a two-week stay. The family was there.
Everyone, including Mac, the cat. It should have been wonderful,
except I ruined the first day by prowling around the house wringing
my hands and just not sitting still.
</P>
<P>
   I was a nervous wreck, due mainly to an out-of-control
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Exasperated, Ma asked, ``What is the matter with you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing,'' I replied, resuming my pacing.
</P>
<P>
   Ma didn't take kindly to that lame excuse, so she asked again,
using as strong a language as she ever did: ``What in heaven's name
is the matter with you? You're driving us all nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm in trouble,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, God, he's got some girl pregnant,'' Ma said, as big sis
and big bro looked on, all ears and giggles.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I wailed. ``Worse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then out with it,'' Ma yelled as her voice cracked. That
usually happened when she yelled at me. Frequently.
</P>
<P>
   So word by word, misery by misery, the story was wrenched from
my miserable body. It gets better, too, because as I groaned out
the story, my brother laughed so hard he nearly fell down, laughing
even more as the story became more and more ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   My big brother loved to tell the story in later years, but
never, never finished it because he got laughing; you know, the
tears rolling down his face and sheer inability to go on.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, this didn't bother me, maybe because the more I told
the story and the more my siblings laughed (even Ma had a giggle or
two, although as the lady she was she tried not to laugh), the more
I realized how dumb the story was and I had nothing to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   But not at the time. It has to do with a chicken, or half a
chicken. It could have been a turkey, but I was the turkey, a
Christmas turkey.
</P>
<P>
   It was a great lunch, a roasted half-chicken that my girl's
folks gave me to take home and enjoy. I did just that, took it back
to my rooming house and enjoyed it.
</P>
<P>
   There is a rule at the rooming house that no food is allowed in
rooms. I broke that rule, then wondered how to get rid of the
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Several days later, as the eaten carcass got riper and riper, I
had to do something. So, one cold midnight, I went out of the
house, ready to toss the carcass on the unvirsity coal pile next
door. Just a quick walk, a short toss, and I was home free.
</P>
<P>
   But then, I was caught in the act, in the headlights of the
hated campus cops.
</P>
<P>
   The cops didn't say, ``Hold it right there!'' They didn't have
to; I was still holding that ripe chicken carcass in its cardboard
box.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you doing?'' one of the cops asked. ``Just taking the
air,'' said I (it was freezing).
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh huh,'' said the cop. ``What have you there?''
</P>
<P>
   ``My lunch,'' said I, getting in deeper and deeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see it,'' said the cop, taking a whiff as I handed it to
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not lunch,'' said the cop, handing it back, gingerly.
</P>
<P>
   To the rescue of his partner with the puckered up nose, the
other cop asked, ``So what were you doing out here at midnight with
a rotten chicken?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had lunch at my friend Paul's house where we were studying,
and it got late and I just wanted to get home,'' I said, as visions
of prison cells danced in my head.
</P>
<P>
   The big problem, and the reason I was so worried, is that I
mentioned my friend Paul's last name, and was afraid the cops would
check with Paul and find that everything I said was a lie.
</P>
<P>
   And that is when my siblings had to leave the room because they
were laughing so hard.
</P>
<P>
   After this everything got blurry. I know the cops let me go and
I got back to my cozy bed, where, as in Dylan Thomas's ``A Child's
Christmas in Wales'' I said few words to the holy darkness and
slept.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, nothing ever came of the incident, and I was
able to relax for the rest of the vacation. I will never forget the
story, but I don't remember what happened to the chicken.
</P>
<P>
   And my brother never stopped laughing. Not at me, but with me.
</P>
<P>
   His death last month at the age of 78 stopped the laughter, but
I, with the love that only a brother can give and receive, will
never stop smiling.
</P>
<P>
   You might wonder about that strange twist to the handyman's
byline. It is my real name, put there in honor of Clement C.
Moore's ``A Visit from St. Nicholas.'' It's appropriate, too, since
my big brother's name is Nicholas.
</P>
<P>
   And, amid the laughter and tears, we wish everyone a happy
holiday, and many more, and a handy (of course) new year.
</P>
<P>
   Exit laughing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Peter Hotton writes the Globe's handyman column.)
</P>
</TEXT>
