<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 15:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4323 &Cx1f; sci-z
u v BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-     12-20 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, Dec. 21:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANCIENT-FLOWERS (Undated) _ A trove of fossils in
Sayreville, N.J., reveals what plant life was like when dinosaurs
roamed New Jersey. Researchers say the findings are turning
botanical lore on its head, by revealing that the great
diversification of flowering plants, the most species-rich and
important group of plants on earth, took place at least 90 million
years ago, some 30 million years earlier than previously suspected.
By Carol Kaesuk Yoon. (1250 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-CANCER (Undated) _ Seeking to better understand the
origins of breast cancer, researchers have begun to look as far
back as the womb to identify prenatal factors and childhood
experiences, including birth weight, diet and exercise patterns,
that may affect a woman's risk of developing breast cancer. By Jane
E. Brody. (1900 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NUKE-LABS (Undated) _ The indictment of Dr. Wen Ho Lee has
cast a pall over scientists and others in and around Los Alamos.
And some foreign scientists, whose expertise is needed, are staying
away from the lab. By William J. Broad. (1900 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PLANT-DNA (Undated) _ Biologists have decoded a large part
of the DNA of a plant, affording the first glimpse of the genetic
programming of the plant world. The plant, known formally as
Arabidopsis thaliana and informally as ``the weed,'' is studied by
nearly a thousand laboratories around the world as a model plant.
By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GOULD-NATURE (Undated) _ A conversation With Stephen Jay
Gould, the noted evolutionary biologist, who gives his views on
creationists and the movement, neo-Darwinism and the joys of
writing. By Claudia Dreifus. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: items on eyes
of the giant squid, atomics clocks and eclipses, and haze over
China. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FULL-MOON (Undated) _ High tides, not cosmic levels of
illumination, may be the most noticeable effect tomorrow night when
an unusual combination of celestial events will produce one of the
largest and brightest full moons in recent memory. By Robert A.
Saar. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BETHLEHEM-STAR (Undated) _ The Star of Bethlehem has been
called many things by many people: a comet, a conjunction of
planets, a supernova, a miracle, a myth. With just one biblical
account, in the book of Matthew, of the star and how it caused the
wise men to come to Judea in search of the newborn Jesus, exactly
what it was, if indeed it was anything at all, remains an open
question. That question has attracted yet another answer, one that
is gaining attention from historians of astronomy for its unique
approach. Dr. Michael R. Molnar, an astronomer and physicist and
former teacher at Rutgers University, proposes that the star was
the planet Jupiter, seen in the constellation Aries, the ram. By
Henry Fountain. (850 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EYE-CANCER (Undated) _ Terry Hoddinot, 36, has been blind
since the age of 3. His son, Riley, 3{, lost his left eye a month
ago. And the same rare eye cancer, retinoblastoma, was diagnosed in
his baby daughter, Katie, while she was still in the womb. But
doctors say there is a good chance that they may have saved Katie's
vision with a bold new procedure: delivering her prematurely, then
treating the affected eye before the cancer had a chance to grow
and blind her. The approach has important implications for the
treatment of retinoblastoma, a potentially fatal genetic disorder
that afflicts 1 in 20,000 North Americans. By Mark Bloom. (1100
words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BARBIE-ENVIRON (Undated) _ Barbie is about to become
environmentally correct. Her creator, Mattel Inc., the world's
largest toy maker, announced last week that its most popular doll
would henceforth be made with organic, biodegradable materials
instead of the petroleum-based polyvinyl chloride, which has been
linked to an assortment of environmental and health problems.
Environmental and consumer groups say the announcement marks a
significant break with industry practice. But it only partly
quieted an angry controversy that surrounds a host of plastic toys.
By Holcomb B. Noble. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Personal Health: Lurking in the
guts of many pets and people is a sneaky parasite that may well be
the most common cause of gastrointestinal distress in this and many
other countries. The organism, a protozoan called giardia, is easy
to acquire but hard to diagnose and often difficult to treat
effectively. It can cause no symptoms at all or it can turn its
host into one sick puppy suffering from abdominal cramps, diarrhea
and weight loss. It may even result in food allergies. By Jane E.
Brody. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-YOGA-FITNESS (Undated) _ The Novice: Learning to do Bikram
yoga, less formally known as hot yoga and conducted in rooms heated
to 100 degrees. The heat enhances flexibility. By Vicky Lowry.
(1250 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CONTACT-LENSES (Undated) _ Buying contact lenses has never
been easier. Besides the traditional outlets, like optometrists'
offices and mail order stores, they can be found on hundreds of Web
sites and even at beauty salons and local flea markets. But now
authorities are cracking down on those sold without prescriptions.
By Susan Gilbert. (860 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on health and
fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ A newly redesigned Web site aims to make cancer survival
easier for the growing number of Americans who are being
successfully treated for it. (210 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Canadian researchers report that after studying a variety of
alcoholic beverages, they found that the martini scored highest for
its antioxidant properties, which researchers believe may help the
body fight everything from cancer to cataracts. (320 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Gay men are almost twice as likely to smoke cigarettes as men
over all, a new study finds. The study was done by researchers at
the University of California at San Francisco, and looked at 2,600
men who described themselves as gay or bisexual. About 48 percent
reported smoking, compared with about 27 percent of all American
men. (200 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Perhaps the only thing more frustrating for diabetes experts
than the number of patients who lose their vision is that in many
cases, the problem could be prevented with relatively basic eye
examinations. (290 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Some elderly people who are given diagnoses of voice or speech
disorders may simply be showing ordinary signs of aging, scientists
say. (200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science question answered: What is the
difference between dentists with D.D.S. after their names and those
with D.M.D.? (425 words)
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   Some ScienceTimes stories are available to international clients
only by special arrangement, and are so marked. Asian and European
points: contact Karl Horwitz in Paris for details and prices
(Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX: 47-42-80-44). Latin American points:
contact Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX:
310-996-0089).
</P>
