<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4328 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-MILLENNIUM-PARTY-MAIN     12-20 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-PARTY-MAIN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT TOO LATE FOR A COZY MILLENNIUM BASH
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL BIDWELL 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So you're not going to Las Vegas and dropping big bucks to party
with people you don't know ... not going to New York to see the
ball drop in Times Square ... not dancing till dawn buoyed by
rivers of the finest champagne.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean you're stuck solo on New Year's Eve with a
frozen pizza and a bottle of $3 wanna-be champagne, either.
</P>
<P>
   It's not too late to plan an elegant, intimate gathering to
welcome in 2000. All it takes is a bit of organization, a
willingness to be flexible and a bunch of compatible people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people have realized that this is a once-in-a-lifetime
event, and rather than spend it with a bunch of strangers at a big
party, they're looking for something more personal, a time of quiet
reflection with friends,'' said Bob Klingensmith of Chatsworth, at
a Canoga park liquor store. He was picking up a few bottles of
Irish whiskey he'll share with friends on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Party planners suggest you first decide whether you'll have a
sit-down dinner, a wander-around buffet or a casual, grab-a-bite
evening around the TV. The kind of party you choose will suggest
the size of your guest list: Dozens may be able to mingle through
your small apartment with chips full of dip, but your dining table
can just seat so many.
</P>
<P>
   Don't have enough glasses or chairs, and your china is old
Melmac from the thrift store? Although the best of the rental
merchandise has already been spoken for, it's not too late to look
into renting even the basic necessities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of wonderful things available in rental today,
things that are like the finest heirloom china and the finest
crystal,'' said Joann Roth-Oseary, president of Someone's in the
Kitchen catering in Tarzana.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can make do with what you have, using the most mundane
materials to make your party setting sparkle, said
party-planner-to-the-stars Colin Cowie, who has operations in Los
Angeles and New York.
</P>
<P>
   A bedsheet or a shawl can be a tablecloth, and lighting bunches
of inexpensive votive candles can provide a romantic setting.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent dinner he threw for friends, he had big pieces of
mirrored glass cut to fit a long, narrow table for a sit-down
dinner. As a centerpiece, he used ball-shaped white candles set
into a meandering river of snowy rock salt; when lit, the candles
shimmered and the tabletop reflected the light.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very simple to do and it didn't cost a lot,'' Cowie
said. ``Money has nothing to do with style, or with having a great
party. A formula for a good party is a great guest list, a
well-stocked bar, a delicious dinner and wonderful music. You can't
go wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowie suggests a cold seafood buffet and bottles of bubbly for a
group if you've got a healthy bank balance, or a pot of stew and
pitchers of martinis if your cash isn't flowing quite as freely as
you'd like. Or maybe it's time to whip up a pot of your special
chili or a big pan of lasagna.
</P>
<P>
   Don't cook? Ask each of your guests to bring a dish to share. Or
check out the deli and takeout sections of your supermarkets; most
offer party trays of cold cuts and cheeses and even entire holiday
meals, if you order in advance. And some caterers, even though
they're busy organizing big New Year's Eve bashes, will cook extra
for your small party. Just be prepared to pick up the food yourself
on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Or you could serve an all-desserts buffet, with your guests
awash in a sea of chocolate and whipped cream, either homemade or
purchased. But do desserts go with champagne, the traditional drink
as the calendar rolls over to next year?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing goes better with champagne than more champagne, or
maybe some strawberries or raspberries,'' said Dan Whittemore,
owner with wife Linda of Dandy Don's Ice Cream Sundae Bar catering
in Van Nuys. ``If you have a $30 bottle of champagne, you don't
want anything to interfere with the delight of the champagne.''
</P>
<P>
   If you plan to buy champagne, better buy it soon, advises David
Breitstein, owner of the Duke of Bourbon in Canoga Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not running out yet,'' he said. ``But there's definitely
more of a demand for champagnes and sparkling wines now than at any
time in history. But, you know, you don't have to buy the most
expensive champagne. You just have to share it with someone special
to you.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 1501EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
