<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-LA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIZMOS, GAMES HIGLIGHT THE SEASON
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(David Bloom's weekly Digital L.A. column on the intersection of
technology and entertainment.) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As you stock up on computers, video game consoles and DVD
players this digital Christmas, you'll need something to actually
play on your new gizmos. Here are some last-minute arrivals worth
your attention.
</P>
<P>
   Some titles are available on more than one platform, and are so
noted with the following abbreviations: PlayStation (PSX), Nintendo
64 (N64), Sega Dreamcast (DC), Windows-based computer (PC), Apple
Macintosh computer (Mac), Game Boy/Game Boy Color (GB). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
DVDs &QC;
</P>
<P>
   I concentrate here on some recent animation and fantasy titles
that may work for both little ones and grownups. As with most DVDs,
these titles often have lots of extras beyond the film itself.
</P>
<P>
   Disney is issuing its first nine DVD titles, starting with
``Pinocchio.'' You also may find ``The Wizard of Oz'' in a
resplendent digital reissue. But for more out-of-the-way goodies,
try these:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nuttiest Nutcracker'' is a fabulous-looking 3-D computer
animation based loosely on ''The Nutcracker'' story line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iron Giant'' was a box-office bust but critical fave with
its Atomic Age in-jokes, deft combination of classic and computer
animation and story of a boy and his giant robot. Warner Bros. has
loaded the disc with other features.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wall'' is Pink Floyd's Orwellian movie/album, completely
remastered for 5.1-channel surround-sound and high-definition
video. Throw in a second documentary and much else and you have a
showpiece.
</P>
<P>
   For a quick tour of English animation highlights of the past
three decades, start with ``Yellow Submarine,'' reissued in
glorious fluorescent colors with all that gorgeous Beatles music
sounding better than ever.
</P>
<P>
   You can see the movie's influences stretched beyond 1969 with
``Monty Python's And Now for Something Completely Different,''
which is laden with fun from the loony British comedy troupe that
gave us John Cleese, Graham Chapman, Michael Palin and Terry
Gilliam.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, over the past decade or so, the great Nick Parks has
been crafting a series of much-loved, stop-motion clay animation
shorts about a wide-mouthed Brit and his eyebrow-arching dog. The
``Wallace and Gromit'' disc contains three of these wonderful
stories, along with some other odds and ends about Parks' career. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sports games &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Basketball season is well under way, with some decent titles on
every platform. One of my favorites is Midway's NBA Showtime: NBA
on NBC (DC, PSX, N64). It's the roundball equivalent of the
company's over-the-top NFL Blitz. Anything short of physical
assault is legal, with plenty of fun moves and dunks possible. This
is a great game on the Dreamcast and N64 because four people can
play in the two-on-two game.
</P>
<P>
   For more extreme winter sports, try Sled Storm (PSX), a somewhat
unlikely but fun snowmobile-racing game, or Cool Boarders 4 (PSX),
the latest in a line of great snowboarding titles. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Looking back &QC;
</P>
<P>
   For your clan's nostalgic gamers, I'd suggest several revived
classics mined from 1980s-era arcades and given a heavily revamped,
3-D version as well as their ``classic'' modes. They aren't all
worth the treatment, but I liked the revived Centipede game (PSX,
DC), the Next Tetris (PSX, N64) and Space Invaders (GBC, PSX).
Blessedly, Pac Man and Ms. Pac Man are also back, as part of the
Namco Museum Collection. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Multi-platform &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Rayman 2: The Great Escape (N64, PC) The limbless hero hops to
N64 with a great new adventure that's a blast to play for any age,
and looks even better on PC, in one of the better games of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Toy Story 2 (PC, N64, PSX) comes from the same people who made
last year's ``Bug's Life'' title so fun. Buzz Lightyear makes his
way through a series of buildings, much as in the hugely successful
film, to rescue Woody and others. A nice adventure for anyone 8 or
so and up. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
PlayStation &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Spyro 2: Ripto's Rage is the sequel to last year's breakout
adventure hit, Spyro the Dragon, and every bit as much fun. Younger
children will love it, but so will more grown-up ones.
</P>
<P>
   Crash Team Racing is also a sequel of sorts, with Crash
Bandicoot now driving. I don't like it as much as Hot Wheels Turbo
Racing (also on N64), but both are good. But if you want a real
racing experience, look for Gran Turismo 2, the massive sequel to
the best driving simulator ever.
</P>
<P>
   For more mayhem in your driving, look for Twisted Metal 3 and
Vigilante 8: Second Offense (also DC), or the truly politically
incorrect Grand Theft Auto 2. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Nintendo 64 &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo's secret weapon is Rare and other in-house studios,
which are responsible for both Donkey Kong 64 and Jet Force Gemini.
</P>
<P>
   DK64 is the latest from one of Nintendo's signature franchises,
and is a colorful, complex and fun title. But it's a bit too
challenging for players younger than 8 or so.
</P>
<P>
   Jet Force Gemini is also for older gamers, a space adventure
that involves killing a lot of big, well-armed ant creatures and
rescuing ewok-like villagers. There's a two-person cooperative
mode, a four-player battle mode, and an excellent story line. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dreamcast &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The new guy has already sold more than 1 million machines in
less than three months, in part because of great titles such as NFL
2K and NBA 2K. I also love the Sega Bass Fishing game, which is
ridiculously addictive.
</P>
<P>
   Soul Fighter is another handsome entry in Dreamcast's seemingly
inexhaustible array of fighting games, though Soul Calibur remains
the champ. And in the racing genre, Sega Rally Championship is a
near-perfect arcade transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Toy Commander, which lets you direct toys against each other, is
a fun alternative to the Toy Story 2 universe, while Rippin' Riders
and Trick Style should sate the family extreme sportster. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
PC &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Quake III Arena is the ultimate blast-fest but relies largely on
tournament modes instead of what made the first two Quakes go. It
looks fabulous, plays wonderfully but is strictly for
testosterone-ridden older gamers (on Mac too).
</P>
<P>
   Amerzone is a handsome, Myst-like adventure, with you playing a
journalist trying to return mystical white eggs to a Central
American tribe. Good for gamers who prefer a slower ride.
</P>
<P>
   Panzer General 3-D Assault is a turn-based-strategy game set on
World War II's Western Front, with nifty 3-D graphics for units and
terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Command &AMP; Conquer Tiberian Sun nicely extends the real-time
strategy genre its predecessor started, with much better graphics,
fun new units and cool terrain effects.
</P>
<P>
   Lego Friends is a great game for youngsters of both sexes. You
help an all-female music group create multiple tracks of music, tie
it to backdrops and lighting, then watch the group perform. Highly
recommended.
</P>
<P>
   Legacy of Kain Soul Reaver and Shadowman are somewhat similar
horror adventures that will have you working this world and the
afterlife to clean out the bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   Mob Rule is a very funny, very politically incorrect take on the
SimCity genre. Build up your gang of criminals through graft,
corruption and other unsavory tactics. For a more upstanding pair
of simulations, try out Roller Coaster Tycoon or Sim Theme Park,
both of which let you build and run your Disneyland-like
operations. Tycoon is the more detailed one, but cartoonish Sim
Theme Park even comes with a camcorder view to let you see
firsthand what a ride looks like. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Gear &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I'd suggest a couple of computer accessories from
Saitek, whose nifty little $20 joystick, the ST-110, makes a great
stocking stuffer. You can also try its more expensive _ and
endlessly configurable _ cousin, the Cyborg 2000.
</P>
<P>
   I also like the Pool Shark, which lets you play virtual pool
games using a real cuestick. It even comes with a pool cue and a
game, Ultimate 8 Ball. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 1509EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
