<HEADER>
A4350 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BABY-NAMES-HNS &LR;      12-20 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-NAMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACOB DISPLACES MICHAEL AS THE NAME FOR BABY BOYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARSHA GINSBURG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Michael, the king of baby names for 45 years,
has been deposed.
</P>
<P>
   Jacob became the most popular baby name among boys in 1999,
according to Social Security records compiled by the San
Francisco-based BabyCenter.com, and Internet baby resource
organization.
</P>
<P>
   The top girl's name for the year was Emily, popular throughout
the decade. Last year's favorite, Kaitlyn, might have been a fad,
because it plummeted to seventh place on this year's top 10 list.
Other favored girls names after Emily were Sarah, Brianna,
Samantha, Hailey and Ashley.
</P>
<P>
   Following Jacob and Michael this year were Matthew, Nicholas,
Christopher and Joshua, Babycenter announced Monday. The Internet
company provides information, support and products for parents.
</P>
<P>
   Names that have climbed onto the top 100 list as 2000 approaches
include Austin, Isaiah and Jack for boys; Emma, Cloe and Sophia for
girls. As technology brings the world closer, expect Americans to
look overseas for names, and even more traditional last names to be
used as first names _ Riley, Taylor, Morgan, Tyler and Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   How was Michael squeezed out?
</P>
<P>
   Baby name specialist Cleveland Evans of Bellevue University in
Omaha, Neb., said society ushered out the popular ``J'' names of
the '80s _ Justin, Joshua, Jason, Jeremy _ but still liked the
sounds of them. In Jacob, a classical biblical name, they found a
friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``There finally comes a point where something new comes up and
people don't realize it's so popular, so it can sneak in,'' said
Evans, a psychology professor who studies fads and fashions in
names.
</P>
<P>
   Jacob has plenty going for it, as names go. BabyCenter.com says
a survey of 22,000 parents found that half call their children by a
nickname _ Jacob's would be Jake. And Evans said names with long
``a'' vowels are popular lately, for boys and girls. Some examples:
Haley, Bailey and Caitlin.
</P>
<P>
   And if you think society is entering a new century of
enlightenment, consider this: one-third of parents said they picked
boys names based on whether they would look good on resumes and
bring success.
</P>
<P>
   But with baby girls, parents are more likely to take a chance
that a name winds up being a fad.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (parents) don't project her as much into the future,''
Evans said. Therefore, cuteness and youth often prevail _ names
like Christy, Brianna or Ashley, which was the No. 1 girl's name of
the decade, according to BabyCenter.
</P>
<P>
   So are baby girls taken less seriously?
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it is psychological and part of it is biological,''
Evans said. ``Women are supposed to be young. Young is good for
women. It's good for men, but it's not a requirement.''
</P>
<P>
   Names, he said, tell more about parents than children.
</P>
<P>
   Upper middle-class families from old money like antiques,
classical music and also like names traditionally applied to the
upper-crust, such as Emma, Henry and Eleanor. But blue-collar
families say the past has not been all that good for them, Evans
said, and they want to focus on emerging names. Hence, Cheyenne and
Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael, a Catholic name, wasn't used much in colonial New
England because Protestants thought it sacrilegious to name a child
after an angel. But Michael, and other Catholic names like Patrick
and Christopher, later gained popularity, especially with Irish
immigration.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, people began naming children after adored stars,
such as Gary for Gary Cooper and Gregory after Gregory Peck.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Deborah Kerr and Debbie Reynolds, some variation of
the names gained ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those who wanted the girls perky or sophisticated, the
name got hit from both sides,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   Not every star was copied. Few followed Warren Beatty, whose
name was commonly associated with older men, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And few name their son after Brad Pitt because Brad is already
too common.
</P>
<P>
   But Evans said the same year Pitt's movie ``Legends of the
Fall'' (in which Pitt plays a character named Tristan) came out,
there ``were little Tristans all over the place.'' Ditto for Dylan
and Brandon in Beverly Hills 90210.
</P>
<P>
   Evans said parents should think about the values their baby's
name is expressing and then decide if those are the values they
want to reflect.
</P>
<P>
   BabyCenter.com found that 90 percent of parents in their survey
picked a name before the baby was born, and that their primary goal
was to pick a unique name.
</P>
<P>
   And for those of you about to give birth and planning to come up
with a common name with an uncommon spelling, please think again,
Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That drives me up the wall,'' he said, pointing out the
popular Caley is now Kaylee, Kaley, Kayleigh and Kaylie, and goes
on ``ad nauseum.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's counterproductive. The kid isn't going to have any
advantages. They're going to go through their whole life spelling
it for people,'' he said. ``And people won't think it's creative.
They'll think the parents were illiterate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 1510EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4353 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-20 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEASTLY BIAS OF BANKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At a structured discussion about banks last summer
in a politically hip place called Iowa, a dozen or so Republicans
were asked which animal banks reminded them of.
</P>
<P>
   The answers opened a window on an issue that never goes away _
the way credit is dispensed in a society that needs it to grow and
prosper, and the continuing, strong public perception that this
crucial dispension remains rooted in unfairness and discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The perceptions both mirror and clash with changing realities,
notes John Taylor, the Massachusetts activist who heads the
National Community Reinvestment Coalition, which coordinates the
activities of those battling for a level playing field.
</P>
<P>
   But down deep, adds the Boston-Washington commuter, ``The
American public believes that race and gender bias exist in the
banking industry, and in fact that is true.''
</P>
<P>
   Back to the animals.
</P>
<P>
   Said two women in the Iowa discussion group, banks are lions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think lions tend to think of themselves as king of the
jungle, controller of all,'' one said. ``I think when you generally
deal with a bank, that's a lot of times the feeling that you get.
And then again, the intimidation thing, the charges that we have no
control over, kind of like the smaller animal being eaten by that
lion.''
</P>
<P>
   Another GOP voter, male, picked an elephant: ``They're just very
big and don't pay attention to the smaller ones.''
</P>
<P>
   The discussion or focus group (one of four the coalition held
around the country this year, including in equally pivotal
Manchester, N.H.) was part of a national study of public attitudes
toward banks that also included a polls of 800 voters, with
additional surveys of 200 African-Americans and 200 Hispanics. The
study was bipartisan, coordinated by Republican pollster Frank
Luntz and Democratic consultant Jennifer Laszlo, and consistently
revealing.
</P>
<P>
   The general public attitudes of intimidation and mistrust were
complemented in the polling results. Remember, they come just two
years after a federal study found blacks twice as likely as whites
to be turned down for loans without regard to income, with similar
research showing patterns of discrimination toward other minorities
and women. Some highlights:
</P>
<P>
   --Some 15 percent said they themselves or someone they know has
been discriminated against in applying for a loan.
</P>
<P>
   --Among blacks, the number was nearly twice that, or roughly
one-third. Of those who had personal or second-hand experiences to
relate, two-thirds said it was race, and not gender or income or
credit history, that was the cause.
</P>
<P>
   --73 percent of the whites said they had never been turned down,
almost a 20-point difference from Hispanics (52 percent) and blacks
(58 percent).
</P>
<P>
   --And by 5-1, white males were believed to have an absolute
advantage in the bank loan system. When asked if a white man and a
minority with the same credit history apply for a home mortgage or
small business loan, roughly half overall said they believe the
white male would be favored, while reverse discrimination believers
did not get outside of single digits. Needless to say, the results
were much more pronounced among minorities.
</P>
<P>
   --The poll also disclosed equally strong perceptions about
gender discrimination. Among whites, for example, voters by 60-8
percent believe that with two loan applications at issue, the male
would be more likely to get the dough. Elements of these
perceptions could also be found in attitudes about single-parent as
opposed to two-parent families.
</P>
<P>
   As a man in a Texas focus group put it, ``We really tend to look
at men as business people and women as cooks.''
</P>
<P>
   John Taylor's remark that a lot of these perceptions are at
variance with reality is instructive here. Ticking some of them
off, he noted that a person with a job has got huge odds in his or
her favor of getting credit. It's also true that the working poor
now have statistically documented, excellent track records in
making their loan payments; indeed, some in the industry believe
that good payment records vary inversely with income.
</P>
<P>
   It is further the case that the credit industry has been and is
changing rapidly for the better. There is much more sophistication
about loan products, about the potential of low-income people and
neighborhoods. And the smart institutions are becoming
astonishingly aggressive in their outreach.
</P>
<P>
   But there is still discrimination, a lot of it. Taylor believes
its roots are to be found in the same perceptions among lenders
that afflict the rest of the society _ the idea that there is
something negative associated with nonwhites, with women on their
own, with the foreign-born.
</P>
<P>
   At the national level, the recent rewrite of the banking laws
included a lease on life for the basic law in this area, the
Community Reinvestment Act. But the new law will also relax that
data collection requirements that have given responsible activists
like the NCRC the ammunition to demand change.
</P>
<P>
   The study released last week reminds us all that the battle
against discrimination and bigotry never ends, because the
conditions that breed it survive. It is encouraging and troubling
at the same time, and food for activism as well as thought.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 1510EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4355 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-CENTURY-ARTS-2TAKES-B     12-20 1578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-ARTS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISUAL ARTS: DEFINING THE LIMITS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a long-running show in London's West End, ``The Complete
Works of William Shakespeare (Abridged),'' which squeezes all the
Bard's plays into 97 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the equivalent condensation of 20th-century visual arts.
In the beginning, Paris ruled. Impressionism had paved the way for
other groundbreaking movements. Picasso and Matisse, titans who
remain unsurpassed in the century's painting, emerged, along with
Cubism and Fauvism.
</P>
<P>
   Europe retained a shaky sort of supremacy during and after World
War I, inventing Dada and Surrealism to deal with the unreality of
life. But the next conflagration left that life a complete
shambles. After World War II, the capital of the art world moved
from Paris to New York; some of Europe's leading avant-garde
artists had already made the leap. By 1950, Greenwich Village had
become what Montmartre had been half a century before. Abstract
Expressionism, Pop, and other modes were born and bought, the lag
time between the two steadily shortening, until, in the craziness
of the '80s, millionaires were putting themselves on waiting lists
for paintings by recent art-school grads.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last couple of decades, the notions that the art world
has a single capital and that art is based on a neat succession of
styles have faded. Diversity _ in geography, in media, and in just
about everything else _ is held up as the new god.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us up to now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Art is unavoidable
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of alternative histories, of course. (That's
what keeps the art book business booming.) Another way to look at
20th-century art is through the sheer proliferation of images. In
centuries past, you could avoid art. All you had to do, if you were
an average person without a private collection, was stay out of
museums and churches and away from the fancier areas of town where
you'd be confronted with sculpture in parks and plazas, and you'd
be safe.
</P>
<P>
   In the 20th century, that changed. Endlessly reproduced, art is
now unavoidable. Monet and King Tut turn up on tea towels and on
the sides of buses, advertising the blockbuster shows that, like
the image glut, represent one of the radical shifts of the
20th-century art world. Mass market imagery goes beyond reproducing
masterpieces, though. Posters, billboards, and magazine ads became
as visually innovative as ``high'' art in the 20th century, and the
distinction between ``high'' and ``low'' has been worn down almost
to the point of meaninglessness.
</P>
<P>
   With advanced technology, the distinction between authentic art
and imitations has also blurred. The scariest example is the
Polaroid Replica, a substitute for real brand-name art for those
who can't afford it _ i.e., almost everybody. The Polaroid
duplicates the scale and even the texture of the original. One of
the things traditionally prized about a painting is its uniqueness;
does cloning devalue it? What's sad about Polaroid Replicas is that
for the same amount of money, you can go to an art-school sale and
buy something created by a human hand, head, and heart.
</P>
<P>
   Art now invades your home via the Internet, where you can
purchase paintings without having seen them in the flesh, or check
out a museum Web site that allows you to rotate a piece of
sculpture 360 degrees, viewing it from all sides. CD-ROMs have made
accessible some art that you can't really see even in situ. The
installation at Pennsylvania's Barnes Foundation, for instance, is
so eccentric that some paintings _ those hung high over doorways,
for instance _ are better seen on a computer screen, where you can
also enlarge and home in on details. Art created for the computer
screen is still in its infancy, though; maturity will have to wait
for the next century.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shifting definitions
</P>
<P>
   For most of our century, there was faith in progress in art just
as there was in progress in the American economy. One thing would
always lead to another, and things would always get better. That's
the way art and art history were taught. Then, with the Vietnam
era, those certainties eroded.
</P>
<P>
   Definitions and demarcations began to shift. With the Happenings
of the 1960s, performing and visual arts merged _ an extension of
their joint ventures earlier in the century, under the auspices of
the impresario Serge Diaghilev. Multimedia collaborations among
giants such as John Cage, Merce Cunningham, and Robert Rauschenberg
constituted some of the most exciting art of the day. With
performance art, the boundaries between disciplines blurred
further, until you couldn't say who was the choreographer and who
designed the decor. Everybody tried everything.
</P>
<P>
   By the '60s, visual art was no longer a tidy progression of
styles in painting and sculpture. Painting in oils and sculpture in
bronze or marble weren't necessarily where the action was anyway.
In 1917, Marcel Duchamp had decreed that a urinal he dubbed
``Fountain'' was in fact sculpture; more recently, there has been a
flood of bathroom art, including Robert Gober's sinks and Kiki
Smith's crouching female urinating glass beads. Any material can be
made into art, and any subject can as well.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most ambitious categories of art in the second half of
the century was the Earthwork, which attempted nothing less than
altering the topography of the planet. Robert Smithson's 1,500-foot
black basalt ``Spiral Jetty,'' which curls its way into the Great
Salt Lake, is a tangible epic, an homage to myths about the lake's
origins, and an on-again, off-again presence, depending on the
rising and falling of the water. Is a work like ``Spiral Jetty''
really new? It's not much of a stretch to trace Earthworks back to
Stonehenge and before.
</P>
<P>
   Sculpture in neon, video, and light itself is another important
development of the late 20th century. Some work based on new
technology initially looked like science projects run amok, carried
away with whizbang gimmickry. A lot of it matured most
gratifyingly, though. Video artist Bill Viola, for instance, has
conquered technical difficulties to create grand-scale, weightless
images of birth and death, fire and rain, the elements of
existence. Bruce Nauman, who has worked in many media, including
himself, bathes those who venture into his quirky spaces in neon
light. James Turrell has spent more than two decades reshaping
Roden Crater, an Arizona volcano, into a place that frames and
concentrates light from sun, moon, and stars.
</P>
<P>
   There's an idealism in Turrell's megaproject, which no one will
ever buy. But the century has also seen plenty of art greed. The
art market boiled over in the 1980s, the hysteria exemplified by
the fate of van Gogh's ``Irises,'' sold at Sotheby's in 1987 for a
then-record $53.4 million. The buyer was Australian entrepreneur
Alan Bond, who, it turned out, couldn't afford the painting.
Sotheby's, which had lent him half the money in a move denounced as
ethically dubious, reclaimed it and sold it once more, this time to
the Getty Museum in Los Angeles. The world's richest museum, the
Getty can afford anything _ although, of course, not everything is
for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Collecting in the 20th century has been degraded by the
commodification of art. Gone are the days when
collector-intellectuals such as Gertrude Stein and her clan from
America, and the Shchukin and Morozov families from Russia,
converged on Paris to compete for still-wet canvases by Picasso and
Matisse. Now we've got buyers like British ad tycoon Charles
Saatchi, who scoops up a museum's worth of new art only to dump it
on the market a few years later, sending some of the artists into
spirals of depression.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The photo revolution
</P>
<P>
   The granddaddy of the technology that is revamping art on what
seems an almost daily basis is photography, a 19th-century
invention that continued to change visual experience profoundly and
permanently through the 20th. Photography revolutionized the
practice of art history, through the color slide. It led to one of
the century's biggest publishing phenomena, the lavishly
illustrated coffee-table art book. Aerial photography helped free
painters from the horizon line. And photography brought other media
to broad public attention: Hans Namuth's photographs of Jackson
Pollock dancing around his studio splashing paint helped build the
legend of ``Jack the Dripper.''
</P>
<P>
   From Edward Steichen to Cindy Sherman, photography in the 20th
century grew from an art that imitated painting to one capable of
all kinds of tricks painting couldn't perform. Photography entered
the unlimited realm of ``mixed media.'' The pristine print was no
longer the goal. Artists once hand-colored black-and-white
photographs to make them look ``real''; now they paint them for
other reasons, and even bend them into sculpture. The 20th century
has also seen the development of play-acting in photography, from
F. Holland Day posing as the crucified Christ at the beginning of
the century to the contemporary Japanese artist Yasumasa Morimura
inserting his obviously Asian face into reproductions of paintings
by Titian, Rembrandt, and van Gogh. Photography made bigger strides
in the 20th century than either painting or sculpture, pace the
advent of abstraction. (The abstract photograph came along, too.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 1512EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4357 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-CENTURY-ART-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     12-20 1391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-ART-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... along, too.)  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Abstraction is what many would cite as the defining feature of
20th-century art as we know it in the West. But that's murky
territory: Islamic painting, for instance, has been abstract for
centuries. The identity of the painter of the first completely
nonrepresentational canvas in the West in the early years of the
20th century is uncertain. It may have been the Russian Kasimir
Malevich, or the American Arthur Dove. What is clear is that
paintings that confined themselves to a single hue or geometric
motif opened the floodgates of possibility: Art was no longer tied
to observable reality; color and shape could exist independently.
</P>
<P>
   Abstraction also opened the floodgates of ridicule. People had
lampooned Impressionism in the 19th century. But in the 20th, the
divide between advanced art and the general public widened. There
were loads of ``You-call-that-art?'' controversies, centered around
religion, sex, or even, in the case of Damien Hirst's pickled
sharks and goats, accusations of cruelty to animals. There were
jokes about the ``hoax'' of Minimalism, a '60s style that has worn
better than anything else in the second half of the century. It's
Minimalism's contemporary, Color Field Painting, that, at century's
end, looks like just so much wallpaper.
</P>
<P>
   Hostilities between the art world and a skeptical public
escalated through the 1900s. Never before had ordinary people in
such large numbers felt so alienated from art, felt they didn't
``get'' it. This happened, ironically, even as the art world
increasingly co-opted ordinary people's turf. Consider Warhol's
soup cans.
</P>
<P>
   Another way visual artists have edged closer to everyday life is
to design functional, albeit often utopian, environments: Examples
are Andrea Zittel's ``Living Units'' and ``Pit Beds'' and Joep van
Lieshout's mobile homes that range from decadent to austere. Many
artists who yearn to be useful work in traditional ``craft'' areas.
There's been a late-century resurgence in glass, ceramics, and
handmade furniture, some by ``crossover'' artists trained in
``fine'' art. Their work answers a craving, in an age of
mechanization and mass production, for the handmade and unique.
</P>
<P>
   Scale became a signature of modern art. Early in the century,
Monet's paintings blanketed whole walls, as Abstract Expressionist
canvases did 50 years later. Later, art got even larger, whether it
was Christo wrapping the Reichstag, the vast Cor-ten steel
sculptures of Richard Serra, Rauschenberg's ``The 1/4 Mile or 2
Furlong Piece,'' or Maya Lin's haunting Vietnam War memorial, a low
black granite wall snaking its way into the earth. Lin's 1980
monument acts as balm on a century's worth of angry political art,
from Leon Golub's brutal paintings of torturers and their victims
to the Socialist Realism imposed on artists in Communist countries.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The blockbuster exhibition
</P>
<P>
   Art on a huge scale, and the advent of the blockbuster
exhibition that drew huge numbers, were dual impetuses behind the
20th century's museum-building boom. Existing art museums sprawled
ever larger, adding new wing after new wing. The truism about
architecturally splashy new museums is that the building counts as
the biggest work in its collection.
</P>
<P>
   Museums were relatively staid places before the advent of the
blockbuster, epitomized by the 1972 ``Treasures of Tutankhamen'' at
New York's Metropolitan Museum, staged by that great showman Thomas
Hoving. A quarter-century later, the appetite for big-budget
big-name shows had increased to the point that tickets for a
particular time of day had to be ordered in advance. Impressionism,
Egypt, ancient gold from practically anywhere, all are reliably big
at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   Blockbusters can be cynical displays of whatever museum
development departments think the public wants to see. Or they can
be breathtaking, bringing together works that will never, within a
single lifetime, share the same space again. The 1995 Vermeer show
organized by the National Gallery in Washington, D.C., and the
Mauritshuis in The Hague is a case of the latter, with most of that
master's slim output under one roof for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeer became an art star only in the 20th century; before
that, he'd been a ``lost'' painter, then a rediscovered one. The
notion of an art star is largely a 20th-century invention, with
Picasso the brightest in the firmament. Later artists, including
Warhol and Jeff Koons, made stardom a primary goal; art was merely
a means. They themselves became art.
</P>
<P>
   The museum building also achieved celebrity status. Projects
like the Grand Louvre in Paris or the vast branch that London's
Tate Gallery will open in a former power station on the Thames next
spring make headlines. Frank Gehry's Guggenheim Bilbao in Spain is
a twirling titanium pirouette that has quickly become the city's
symbol. Richard Meier's Getty Center is an arrogant, austere,
off-putting, off-white pile overlooking Los Angeles. I. M. Pei's
Miho Museum in Shiga, Japan, is the best thing he's ever done, and
one of the most humble, most of it built underneath a national
park. Stephen Holl's Kiasma museum in Helsinki is a curvaceous,
futuristic masterpiece for the electronic age. Thousands of people
make pilgrimages to these buildings; many go with little thought of
what's inside.
</P>
<P>
   Museums are being designed to accommodate not only existing
collections and new ones, but also the rewriting of art history.
African or Native American art that once was relegated to the
dioramas of ethnographic museums is now entering museums of fine
arts. Museums that once smugly identified themselves as
``encyclopedic'' are realizing they're not, and hastening to
acquire, say, South American art.
</P>
<P>
   There are endless curatorial debates over how to display and
categorize art that plays by different rules than those that
prevail in the West. Some African cultures, for instance, value
tradition and continuity over innovation and artistic ``progress,''
so a 100-year-old object will look like one made today. How does a
museum convey that idea? Should contemporary Asian art go in a
department devoted to contemporary art from around the world, or in
one that traces the development of Asian art from its origins to
now? Should departments be divvied up according to geography, era,
or medium? Defining ``contemporary art'' has proven particularly
tricky. And a few years back, museums with departments of
20th-century art started nervously looking ahead to the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The canon is expanding _ and fast. The standard joke about
``Outsider Art,'' subject of a slew of museum shows in the past
decade, is that it's now ``In.'' Since its first publication in
1962, H. W. Janson's ``History of Art,'' the premiere college text
on the subject, has undergone regular revisions, most notably to
add women and African-American artists. Those two groups, and
minorities in general, are still pitifully underrepresented in
museum collections and in high-profile exhibitions, though. We're
not yet over the cult of the Dead White Male.
</P>
<P>
   While Western museums scramble to acquire art from corners of
the world they didn't used to consider, some of those corners are
developing into important centers themselves. Sao Paulo,
Johannesburg, and Istanbul now hold respected biennials. There are
pockets of cutting-edge artists all over the globe; in countries
where governments still dictate art's content and style, some
survive underground. Some Western governments, most notably ours,
have little power to control art because they're unwilling to fund
it. For the most part, art in America has to pay its own way: Hence
the $17.50 ticket to the blockbuster show.
</P>
<P>
   The world's museums are winding up the century with a lot of
apologies for housing Nazi loot, and art whisked out of Third World
countries under dubious legal circumstances. There's a lot of
defiance, too. War and Colonialism mixed up what went where.
Sorting it all out is impossible; making the effort is a moral
imperative. At the beginning of the 19th century, the seventh Earl
of Elgin brought great marble figures from the Parthenon to
Britain. At the close of the 20th, a leading British newspaper, The
Guardian, has broken ranks and called for their return.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
