<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4358 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-20 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS  
 NEW YORK'S CASES OF RACIAL INJUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ If Lucy McKnight had ever been certain of
anything, she was certain she had been wronged.
</P>
<P>
   She had been working for the New York State Dormitory Authority.
An active Democrat and an African-American, she had been hired
during the administration of Mario Cuomo. After George Pataki and
his Republicans took over New York state government in 1994,
McKnight suffered health problems and missed some work. When she
was fired, she noted that a number of white folks with similar
absences hadn't been discharged. So McKnight filed suit against the
dormitory authority alleging racial discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   When the suit finally made it to federal court a few weeks back,
McKnight was appalled to discover that all 100 people who made up
the jury pool were white. There would not be a single black face on
the jury that would hear her case.
</P>
<P>
   There's a reason for that. The federal court district covering
the northeastern portion of this sprawling, 50,000-square-mile
state constitutes a part of the world where black folks make up
less than 3 percent of the population. Plus the federal jury pool
is culled from voter rolls and New York State Department of Motor
Vehicle records. Statistically, African-Americans are less likely
than whites to be voters, licensed drivers or car owners.
</P>
<P>
   McKnight lost her case. She believes firmly that if the jury had
contained even one member who had had a gut sense of what racial
discrimination feels like, she would have won. That may or not be
true, but the intensity of McKnight's conviction in this matter is
only one more indication of the stunning gulf that stretches
between whites and minorities on issues like this.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in this town, we're about to see another illustration of
just how immense that gulf can be. We'll see it when four New York
City police officers go on trial, probably late next month, for the
shooting death on Feb. 4 of a black West African immigrant in the
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Amadou Diallo, an innocent man, was standing in a darkened
doorway late at night. Four officers hunting a rape suspect
approached him, guns in hand. What happened next will be the crux
of this murder case against the cops. Diallo either did something
to lead the cops to believe mistakenly that he was reaching for a
weapon or they behaved with criminal recklessness when they fired
41 slugs into that vestibule.
</P>
<P>
   This has been a huge and heavily publicized case in New York
City. In the spring, the Rev. Al Sharpton led daily protests
outside police headquarters in Manhattan. More than 1,700 people,
many show business celebrities and prominent politicians, managed
to get themselves arrested at the demonstrations. Now an appeals
court has ruled that New York City media coverage has been so
feverish that the cops could never get a fair trial there. Instead,
the cop will be tried in Albany, the closest New York jurisdiction
of any size that doesn't watch New York City television stations.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx district attorney will prosecute this case. But
instead of the jury being chosen from a pool in the Bronx, where
whites constitute a distinct minority, this jury instead will be
drawn from Albany County, where the jury pool is 92 percent white.
It should be remembered, too, that the last time police officers
went on trial in this town charged with excessive violence against
a black arrestee _ just a few months back, in the infamous,
foul-smelling Jermaine Henderson case _ an all-white jury found the
police officers not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson had alleged, in rather plausible terms, that the cops
had beaten him while he was in handcuffs. But the Albany County
district attorney's office _ apparently eager to take a dive that
even Greg Louganis would have envied _ had threatened to prosecute
him for perjury if he testified in open court because of
inconsistencies in his grand jury testimony. Henderson stayed away
from the trial, and the cops walked.
</P>
<P>
   This Diallo disaster will be a huge, hot case in Albany. The
courthouse is bound to be encircled daily by protesters bussed up
from New York City. Sharpton is sure to be at his loudest and least
responsible. Meanwhile, Lucy McKnight and other African-Americans
all over New York will be watching closely, as will most white
people, too.
</P>
<P>
   Each from their own side of that yawning gulf we were talking
about.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
