<HEADER>
A4377 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-HEADHUNTER-VERDICT-HN     12-20 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEADHUNTER-VERDICT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RECRUITER WINS $19 MILLION JURY VERDICT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LANCE WILLIAMS  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A high-powered executive recruiter who lost her
ability to do high-pressure work on deadline after a rear-end auto
collision has won a $19 million award from the owner of the truck
that hit her.
</P>
<P>
   In a verdict reached Friday in San Francisco Superior Court, a
jury ordered Winterland Productions to pay the larger award to
Janis Zivic, 56, a former city library commissioner and
$600,000-per-year ``headhunter'' with the Spencer Stuart executive
search firm.
</P>
<P>
   Zivic suffered brain injuries when her BMW sedan was hit from
behind in a chain-reaction accident on an exit ramp of Interstate
280 in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A Mack Truck owned by Winterland caused the wreck when it
careened out of control on the exit ramp and rammed another car,
which then struck Zivic's auto, the jury found.
</P>
<P>
   Zivic was partially paralyzed and had to have emergency brain
surgery, said her lawyer, James S. Bostwick. But she made a
remarkable recovery and eight months later was back at her job.
Problems quickly became evident, the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is very intelligent, and when you meet her you would never
know it, but she has serious problems with recall and memory,''
Bostwick said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a very high-pressure, high-level job (in which) you've
got to do what you do very fast, remember details, do about six
things at once,'' he said. ``And now, if somebody interrupts her,
she can't keep her train of thought. ... She can't do two things at
once.''
</P>
<P>
   In a two-week trial before Judge John Munter, medical experts
testified that Zivic had lost her ability to perform ``higher-level
executive functions,'' especially on deadline.
</P>
<P>
   In its verdict, the jury found that Zivic could still do
less-demanding work, and might well bring in as much as $70,000 per
year for it.
</P>
<P>
   But jurors agreed her head-hunting days were over. Of the award,
$17 million was largely to compensate Zivic for lost earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Zivic, the daughter of former welterweight boxing champion
Fritzie Zivic, was a Pittsburgh schoolteacher when she moved to San
Francisco and landed a job in the personnel department at
Crown-Zellerbach. She won a series of promotions and better jobs,
eventually going to work for Spencer Stuart's San Francisco office,
where she specialized in recruiting top-tier executives for big
companies.
</P>
<P>
   She also served for six years as president of the San Francisco
Family Services Agency and was named to the Library Commission by
then-Mayor Frank Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, she earned more than $600,000, most of it commissions,
according to evidence in the case. The year of the accident she had
already earned $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   The accident occurred while Zivic was stopped in traffic on the
Embarcadero. Truck driver Larry Randolph said he plowed into the
line of cars after his brakes failed on the off-ramp. Zivic said
she hopes to use the award to set up a foundation to promote early
childhood education programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
