<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAYS-POLL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEASON EVOKES MIXED EMOTIONS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL BIDWELL 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What really matters to Americans during the December holidays?
According to a nationwide Lutheran Brotherhood survey, Americans'
favorite holiday activity is celebrating with their families, and
shopping is the necessary evil of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Almost three-quarters (70 percent) of the 1,000 adults surveyed
by telephone said being with family and friends is their favorite
part of the holiday season. It is also their favorite holiday
memory from childhood (74 percent).
</P>
<P>
   While only 3 percent selected shopping as their favorite
activity, almost one-third (30 percent) said if money were no
object, they would spend a lot more on gifts than they currently
do.
</P>
<P>
   Almost two-thirds of those surveyed (61 percent) said the
December holidays have less religious significance now than when
they were growing up, and more than half (54 percent) blame the
decline on pressure to buy and give expensive gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, 62 percent said they really don't like shopping for,
wrapping or assembling gifts. A distant second (11 percent) said
sending and receiving holiday cards is their least favorite holiday
task.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
