<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4411 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     12-20 1334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUST READ NEW BOOK ON FIRST AMENDMENT AND CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c. 1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a new book out on the First Amendment that ought to be
given as a holiday gift to every library and school board in the
nation _ Robert S. Peck's ``Libraries, the First Amendment, and
Cyberspace,'' published by the American Library Association.
</P>
<P>
   If board members of our public libraries and public schools were
to read it, in all likelihood there would be fewer of those
sweeping-but-futile restrictions adopted to limit Internet use.
Consequently, there would be fewer successful lawsuits against
schools and libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Peck is a well-respected First Amendment scholar, who teaches
constitutional law at American University in Washington, D.C. He
was a judicial fellow at the U.S. Supreme Court and is now senior
director for Legal Affairs and Policy Research for the Association
of Trial Lawyers of America.
</P>
<P>
   In writing this book, Peck researched all the relevant U.S.
Supreme Court cases and federal appellate cases that address the
First Amendment rights of public school students and the patrons of
public libraries _ as well as the free speech obligations of both
public institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Peck gives citations for the court decisions quoted so that
attorneys and interested readers can look up those rulings and read
them for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   However, this book is written for the layman, in a clear prose,
not legal jargon, and should be understandable by anyone who can
read at a high school level.
</P>
<P>
   It also contains appendices that include the Library Bill of
Rights and its interpretation in regard to issues like challenged
material, restricted access, building diversity of opinion in a
collection and library initiated programs.
</P>
<P>
   One appendix gives guidelines for developing a public library
Internet-use policy consistent with First Amendment jurisprudence
and the Library Bill of Rights.
</P>
<P>
   The book opens with a valuable question and answer section that
both clarifies legal concepts in First Amendment law and in broad
terms clarifies how they apply to public libraries and public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Peck ferrets out the questions often asked and answers them
briefly: ``Does the First Amendment include the right of access to
information?''; ``Do children have lesser First Amendment rights
than adults?''; ``What has the Supreme Court said about the First
Amendment's treatment of the Internet?'' The chapters that follow
answer those same questions and many more in greater detail.
</P>
<P>
   In answer to the question, ``What is the constitutional status
of libraries?'', Peck devotes a portion of his response to the
public school library: ``The Supreme Court has called the school
library a place where students may `test or expand upon ideas
presented ... in or out of the classroom' and a venue for
`self-education and individual enrichment that is wholly optional'
and without the restraints that may be placed on students in the
`compulsory environment of the classroom.''' The high court
decision Peck quotes is Island Trees Union Free School District No.
26 vs. Pico (1982) _ a decision significant to all public school
libraries, school librarians and our children.
</P>
<P>
   The second chapter describes basic freedom of speech and free
press principles and shows how those principles apply to libraries.
Public libraries are state, county, parish or city governmental
agencies; therefore, the Supreme Court has held them to the same
First Amendment prohibitions that are imposed on the federal
government: ``Congress shall make no law ... abridging the freedom
of speech, or of the press ....''
</P>
<P>
   Peck outlines the scope of the First Amendment by quoting
several Supreme Court decisions: ``Our commitment to free speech,
in one of the court's most classical formulations, anticipates
`uninhibited, robust, and wide-open' debate that `may well include
vehement, caustic, and sometimes unpleasantly sharp' language. It
embraces the notion that `above all else, the First Amendment means
that government has no power to restrict expression because of its
message, its ideas, its subject matter, nor its content.'
</P>
<P>
   Further, Peck notes, ``And it extends to the notion that `the
right to receive ideas is a necessary predicate to the recipient's
meaningful exercise of his own rights of speech, press, and
political freedom.' Thus in addition to protecting the rights of
speakers, `the First Amendment protects the public's interest in
receiving information.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the conclusion of the chapter, Peck warns, ``It is inevitable
that speech will be controversial and that libraries will become
embroiled in those controversies. It is critical that libraries
recognize their custodianship of intellectual freedom and remain
vigilant of these liberties even in the face of severe criticism
for the books, materials, and access they provide.''
</P>
<P>
   The book includes a chapter titled, ``Children, Schools, and the
First Amendment.'' It should be required reading for all high
school students, teachers and principals. Far too often, we short
change our youth in regard to their free speech rights. Peck
reviews for the reader all the pertinent case law regarding
children's First Amendment rights in the public school setting.
</P>
<P>
   Peck writes at the end of this chapter, ``Most importantly, the
courts have recognized that schools and school libraries should
serve a goal of open inquiry and further the exploration of ideas,
and objective that is palpably consistent with the philosophy
underlying the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``For that reason, any removal of school library books will
receive such heightened judicial scrutiny that the removal is
unlikely to survive the constitutional objection.''
</P>
<P>
   The final chapter is the key chapter for those concerned with
Internet access: ``Cyberspace _ The Last Frontier.'' Peck has
researched all the Supreme Court decisions regarding other media
and communications systems -- newspapers, books, radio, television
and the telephone. The high court has noted that the differences in
the media require different First Amendment standards. The print
media has traditionally received the greatest First Amendment
protection.
</P>
<P>
   Peck analyzes the high court's decision in the Communications
Decency Act case. A unanimous high court found the CDA
unconstitutional because it was not narrowly tailored to protect
minors from harmful materials.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the act would have suppressed speech that adults have a
constitutional right to receive. This case is pivotal to all
restrictions on Internet access by government agencies. In its
decision the Supreme Court granted the Internet the same high level
of First Amendment protection as that of the print media.
</P>
<P>
   Peck concludes: ``Any policy on Internet access that a public
library adopts cannot adversely affect adult access to protected
speech, must respect the rights of access of both older minors and
younger minors who have a right to access protected speech and some
speech that parents could find troubling but have serious value for
youth, and must respect the rights of parents who choose to permit
their children to access sites that others might deem appropriate
only for more mature individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Peck has done us all a great service in writing this book now
during the height of the controversies over Internet access and the
concern over children seeing pornographic Web sites. His book
offers insights into what can be done and still be within the legal
constraints of the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   (Charles Levendosky is a member of the Freedom to Read
Foundation Board of Trustees, the litigating arm of the American
Library Association.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 1540EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4423 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-WOODY-ALLEN-LADN     12-20 1780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-WOODY-ALLEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `LOWDOWN' ON WOODY ALLEN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The conundrums about Woody Allen, his films and his life, are
pretty well summed up when he describes his primary artistic
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tough part is being able to be funny and to get the dark
side in as well,'' the filmmaker says. ``It'a a hard thing to do.
If you miss the balance, as I sometimes do, you get something
that's too light and doesn't really say what you want; or, worse,
too dark, and then nobody wants to see it. That happens to me. It's
not an exact science.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not. But at least on the screen,
writer-director-frequent star Allen has gotten it right more often
than most of his contemporaries. Of course, the fact that, at age
64, he's long been America's most prolific filmmaker (averaging at
least one feature per year since 1984) gives him more chances.
</P>
<P>
   But when you really consider it, who else has consistently
pumped out a pretty great film every couple of at-bats for three
decades? Allen's honor roll includes such early '70s satires as
``Everything You Always Wanted to Know About Sex'' and ``Sleeper,''
grows through the Oscar-winning ``Annie Hall'' and matures into the
more rueful, semi-comic character inquiries ``Manhattan,'' ``Hannah
and Her Sisters,'' ``Crimes and Misdemeanors,'' ``Husbands and
Wives'' and ``Deconstructing Harry.''
</P>
<P>
   In between there have been less successful straight dramas,
conceptual comedies of varying mirth and, perhaps most
delightfully, a series of show-biz subculture studies (``Broadway
Danny Rose,'' ``Radio Days,'' ``Bullets Over Broadway'') that have
affectionately captured past eras and their attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweet and Lowdown,'' Allen's latest release, combines a light
tone and an ulikable protagonist, then sets the mixture in a
low-rent, 1930s jazz milieu. It's kind of everything the artist and
his art _ Allen is, after all, a dedicated amateur clarinetist with
a less-than-pristine track record with women _ is about.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't tell him that. True to his renowned kvetchiness,
Allen takes issue with most attempts to pigeonhole or explicate
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two things people always do with my films are make comparisons
and try to find me in there someplace,'' says Allen, a small,
fragile figure in nondescript green sweater, corduroys with
rubbed-out knees and his trademark black-framed glasses. ``I'm not
blaming them for it; there have been films where, clearly, there
are hints of myself in them. But many times, not at all; it's like
they're trying to find the Ninas in the Hirschfeld drawings.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Caine, one of many actors whom Allen has directed to
Academy Awards (for ``Hannah and Her Sisters''), is among the
sizable number of associates who in fact believe that the best way
to understand Woody is through his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to know him more making the picture than I did for the
20 years we'd been acquainted before that,'' Caine reveals. ``And
not through personal contact, but through the screenplay, which was
autobiographical.''
</P>
<P>
   Draw your own conclusions about the ``Sweet and Lowdown''
parallels. As with the director's ``Zelig,'' it's a
pseudo-documentary about a legendary guitar genius, Emmet Ray, who
never existed (Allen appears briefly as a modern-day commentator,
as do several real-life jazz experts). Played by Sean Penn, Emmet
supposedly was an egotistical, irresponsible gambler, drunk,
sometime pimp and full-time womanizer who, nonetheless, made the
most beautiful guitar music in the world this side of Django
Reinhardt (in whose presence Emmet faints dead away). Less a
traditional musical than even Allen's oddball ``Everyone Says I
Love You'' from a few years back, ``Sweet'' is gaga with great
tunes and lovingly re-created period detail. But Emmet is a
complete creep, especially in his treatment of an adoring young
woman, Hattie (the young British actress Samantha Morton), whom he
realizes too late is his mute muse.
</P>
<P>
   Allen claims that he just wanted to make a film about a
musician. But there is something about Emmet that, he admits, comes
from inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known so many jazz musicians, and there are other artists
like this, who play so beautifully that you think they're just full
of sensitivity and they could not be any other way,'' he reveals.
``Then, when you meet them, they're self-centered and nasty,
egotistical braggarts and insensitive to people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Sean could play that because he's got a real
ferocious side,'' Allen adds. ``But he's a very, very sensitive
person, really. He couldn't give those kind of performances, like
in `Dead Man Walking,' if he wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Penn has his reputation for trouble, though one quite
different from Allen's. And, refreshingly, the outspoken,
rebellious actor brought none of the director's neurotic screen
mannerisms to the role, avoiding a trap that caught John Cusack in
``Bullets Over Broadway'' and Kenneth Branagh in ``Celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hear Woody when I read the script,'' Penn explains.
``And if I had, the thing going against playing it that way is that
people have been so saturated with it. I have modeled some
performances on directors, but in this case I would probably not do
that because, one, then he should play it, and also because I just
didn't hear this character in that way.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Penn did find consistent between ``Sweet'' and Allen's
other films was the quality of the script.
</P>
<P>
   ``To begin with, in the world that I'm growing up in as a movie
actor, there is writing in them,'' Penn says. ``Which is a big
departure from most of the things that come around. I think most of
us celebrate this guy as an important writer who knows how to press
the buttons. You read or see his stuff and it moves you, with
uncommon views on common matters that are provocative. And he's
such a perceptive observer of people; it's exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen, naturally, shrugs off such praise. Real film artists, he
reckons, are guys like his European idols Ingmar Bergman and
Federico Fellini (he also dismisses comparisons between ``Sweet''
and its obvious influence, Fellini's ``La Strada'') _ not some
pampered Manhattanite who refuses to inconvenience himself for the
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do all my films in a very lazy way,'' he points out. ``I do
them near where I live. I don't like to travel, I don't like to
make sacrifices, I don't like to work a long day. Now, when I first
started in the business, you're so thrilled that they're letting
you make a film that you're up at 5 in the morning, working fast
and shooting in freezing weather and flying to Budapest 'cause it's
cheaper there. Then, after a couple of films, I stopped and said
this is ridiculous. Films are not my top priority; my life is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to eat leisurely at lunch. I want to come home at 6
o'clock at night, not at 10 o'clock. If the choice was between
doing another angle on a shot and getting home in time to watch the
Knicks on television, I go home. If you notice, so often over the
last 20 years I do everything in one shot. People have said that
it's a style, but it's not; it's laziness. Somebody else would
shoot your closeup and yours and yours, two-shots and
over-the-shoulders, they'd take three days on each scene. But I
just don't have the patience for that; they have more dedication to
the process than I do.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Allen is unabashedly dedicated to, off and on
throughout his work and certainly in ``Sweet,'' is recapturing the
flavor and attitudes of the past on film, informed by his decidedly
downscale Brooklyn youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a great attraction for the past in terms of
storytelling,'' he admits. ``When I used to go to the movies, it
was always a treat to see something like `My Fair Lady' that
projected back into Victorian England or somewhere. It's fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the subcultures are really the cultures that I know. I
come from a lower, lower-middle-class family, and the people I grew
up with were not high-tone people. They were little managers like
Broadway Danny Rose, with jugglers they would try to book
someplace. They were musicians who were not in symphonies, but guys
who hustled for jobs in the mountains. My father was a cab driver,
ran a pool room, was a bookmaker for a while ... So that's what I
grew up knowing. And I always found those characters funny and
likable and basically honest _ within certain parameters.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he's long been a member of New York's creative elite,
some feel that Allen operates outside all parameters. Now married
and the father of a year-old daughter, few can forget that Allen's
wife, Soon-Yi Previn, was the adopted daughter of his former
girlfriend (and mother of his other child), Mia Farrow.
</P>
<P>
   Allen acknowledges that the disappointment he feels when beloved
artists don't live up to his personal expectations reflects how
many others feel about him. And he insists, as he always has, that
he couldn't care less.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's of no interest to me how I'm regarded,'' he contends.
``Though I am, in actual fact, quite the opposite of the hero of
this movie. I'm actually a very sweet person who is not a profound
artist. But I do have a personality that has its advantages and
disadvantages. I am very, very focused, and it can be read that
this guy's aloof, doesn't care about anything and just does his
work, is isolated or insensitive. On the other hand, the advantage
of it is that you can work. In a crisis or any other kind of
situation, you're focused and you don't get distracted off the main
point, you don't waste a lot of time on nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other wrong impressions Allen says people have of him:
that he doesn't like to act in other directors' films (he just
finished one, ``Picking Up the Pieces''); that he knows all there
is to know about such complicated subjects as philosophy and
psychology (``I've made very little headway in understanding life's
big questions''); and that he doesn't like L.A.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never felt bad about L.A.,'' he insists. ``It's not where
I would want to live because I like a much more hectic urban
center. L.A. is more rural for me, but I enjoy coming here. My wife
loves it, and seeing her enjoying it is pleasurable for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've teased L.A. a lot, and because of that, people think I
hate the place,'' concludes the ever-misunderstood Allen. ``But
I've teased my parents a lot over the years, and psychoanalysis.
You know, you can only really make jokes about things that you have
some feeling for. If you hate a thing, you have no detachment, and
if you write about it, it comes out very unentertaining.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 1548EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4431 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-MATT-DAMON-IN-THE-TAL     12-20 1402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATT-DAMON-IN-THE-TALENTED-MR-RIPLEY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD WILL HAUNTED: THE TALENTED MATT DAMON TESTS HIS DARK SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Matt Damon with Gwyneth Paltrow in a
scene from ``The Talented Mr. Ripley.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Talk about feast or famine.
 &HT;    While filming ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' in Italy, newly minted
superstar Matt Damon spent his days portraying Tom Ripley, a deeply
solitary figure with no self-esteem. Then he'd emerge from his
trailer to the screams of gaggles of young Italian girls shrieking,
``Matt Damon! Matt Damon!''
 &HT;    ``I never really get used to it,'' says Damon, who _ along with
pal Ben Affleck _ swept to fame in 1998 on the Oscar-winning ``Good
Will Hunting'' juggernaut.
 &HT;    ``When Ben and I went to shoot `Dogma' (1999), it was the night
after the Academy Awards,'' he recalls. ``We had to fly to
Pittsburgh, and there were about 10 people waiting at the airport,
which was really strange _ nothing like that had ever happened to
me before.
 &HT;    ``We got off the airplane and we were signing autographs and
taking photos with people,'' he says. ``There was this whole fever
pitch, and then someone from `Dogma' showed up and said, `Let's get
these guys through!' And it seemed almost mobbish for a second.''
 &HT;    The affable Damon, sitting in a suite at Los Angeles' Four
Seasons hotel, shakes his baseball-cap-covered head in lingering
disbelief.
 &HT;    He and Affleck, still trailed by those 10 fans, walked a
quarter-mile to a tram that would shuttle them to the airport's
main terminal, he adds.
 &HT;    ``We got on the tram and these people had to get on the tram,
too,'' Damon says bemusedly. ``By the time we got to our cars, they
were just talking and were not even interested in us anymore.''
 &HT;    He laughs.
 &HT;    ``It's this situation that's perpetuated by circumstances,'' he
says thoughtfully. ``When those circumstances are manipulated and
what's normally a 30-second experience turns into a 30-minute
experience, it becomes, `All right, see you, guys!'
 &HT;    ``It was a really interesting study of that whole phenomenon.''
 &HT;    Perhaps coincidentally, ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' _ which will
open nationwide on Christmas _ is itself an exploration of the
nature of idolatry, taking it to a jarring, disturbing extreme.
 &HT;    Written and directed by Anthony Minghella, who made the
Oscar-winning ``The English Patient,'' and based on the novel by
Patricia Highsmith, the film casts Damon as Tom Ripley, a
chameleonesque, gay nobody in 1950s New York. The tragic story line
gets underway when a wealthy shipbuilder (James Rebhorn) hires
Ripley to bring home his wayward son Dickie (Jude Law), who, along
with his girlfriend Marge (Gwyneth Paltrow), has been leading the
lush life in Italy.
 &HT;    Dickie's elegant lifestyle so fascinates Ripley that he decides
to achieve it for himself, first by worming his way into Dickie's
favor and then ... well, by any means necessary.
 &HT;    ``We all project a certain amount of happiness on somebody
else's life and make assumptions about other people,'' Damon says.
``I'm certainly guilty of doing it. `Ripley' is a riff on that, but
we play it all the way out.
 &HT;    ``When you start to root for a guy like Ripley,'' he adds, ``and
some people do, you've got to think to yourself, `Well, what does
that say about me?'
 &HT;    ``Hopefully, that question will stay with people after the
lights come back on in the theater,'' Damon says. ``Hopefully,
people will take away the feeling that they're implicated in it
all.
 &HT;    ``In that sense, `Ripley' is a cautionary tale.''
 &HT;    But, since Damon admits that even he started to root for Ripley,
what does that say about him?
 &HT;    ``Exactly,'' he says, breaking into a toothy grin. ``That's why
I had to do the movie. That's why I felt `Ripley' was important, in
terms of the way it goes against the grain of the way movies are
made nowadays.
 &HT;    ```Ripley' really says something,'' the actor adds, ``and its
tone is so original. It was exciting, because I hadn't seen
something like `Ripley' in a long time. Our hero is a very complex
antihero.''
 &HT;    And, it should be noted, Damon delivers a very complex
performance, a well-calibrated one that smartly plays off his
youthful good looks and aw-shucks charm. It's as if the Devil rose
from the pits of Hell and was reborn as the boy next door.
 &HT;    Damon doesn't consider Ripley a despicable character, however.
It's a subtle distinction, but he thinks of him as a guy who
commits despicable acts.
 &HT;    ``The whole challenge of the movie was to keep the audience with
Ripley, not in the sense that they're sympathetic, but in the sense
that they understand what he does,'' the actor says. ``They can
disagree with what he does, but they understand it because they
know where it's coming from, which is this deep loneliness that
this guy (feels).
 &HT;    ``He's so desperately trying not to be alone,'' Damon says,
``and you see that he has this incredible capacity for love, I
think, and sensitivity. He's really far more good to the people
around him than Dickie is.
 &HT;    ``Dickie is very careless, but he just has this incredible
charisma and can leave people totally gobsmacked,'' he adds. ``He's
like the sun, with everyone orbiting around him, but he's totally
oblivious to it. Tom would never treat people that way if he had
Dickie's life.''
 &HT;    Damon's own life has not been the same since ``Good Will
Hunting'' became an unexpected breakout hit a couple of years ago.
The actor, in fact, has spoken often of how he lives out of two
duffel bags that he's dragged from set to set.
 &HT;    After ``Good Will Hunting,'' Damon turned up in ``Rounders''
(1998), then the current ``Dogma'' _ in a role even darker than
Ripley, since he plays a casually murderous renegade angel. Several
other films are already shot, including ``All the Pretty Horses,''
directed by Billy Bob Thornton, and ``The Third Wheel,'' a romantic
comedy, starring Denise Richards and Luke Wilson, which is produced
by Damon and Affleck, who make cameos.
 &HT;    Just completed is ``The Legend of Bagger Vance,'' a Robert
Redford-directed ``fairy tale'' about a golfer (Damon) who has lost
his soul and must be redeemed by a mysterious caddie (Will Smith).
 &HT;    As the holidays approach, Damon is at last slowing down and
catching his breath. At home in his Manhattan apartment, he'll
unpack those well-traveled duffel bags and squeeze in some quality
time with his girlfriend, actress Winona Ryder.
 &HT;    And, despite the high price of fame _ most notably the loss of
anonymity _ Damon intends to count his blessings as the new year
begins. He has no film about to go into production, and he and
Affleck are only now beginning their next script.
 &HT;    ``I'm looking forward to getting a little time to reflect on
everything that's happened to me, because I haven't had that yet,''
he says softly. ``I'll have six months off, and all I'm planning on
doing is writing a script. I think it'll be a good time for me to
reflect and spend time with my family and friends.
 &HT;    ``But I can't think of anything I'd want to be different right
now.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
