<HEADER>
A4435 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-MATT-DAMON-IN-THE-TAL     12-20 1402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATT-DAMON-IN-THE-TALENTED-MR-RIPLEY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD WILL HAUNTED: THE TALENTED MATT DAMON TESTS HIS DARK SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Matt Damon with Gwyneth Paltrow in a
scene from ``The Talented Mr. Ripley.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Talk about feast or famine.
 &HT;    While filming ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' in Italy, newly minted
superstar Matt Damon spent his days portraying Tom Ripley, a deeply
solitary figure with no self-esteem. Then he'd emerge from his
trailer to the screams of gaggles of young Italian girls shrieking,
``Matt Damon! Matt Damon!''
 &HT;    ``I never really get used to it,'' says Damon, who _ along with
pal Ben Affleck _ swept to fame in 1998 on the Oscar-winning ``Good
Will Hunting'' juggernaut.
 &HT;    ``When Ben and I went to shoot `Dogma' (1999), it was the night
after the Academy Awards,'' he recalls. ``We had to fly to
Pittsburgh, and there were about 10 people waiting at the airport,
which was really strange _ nothing like that had ever happened to
me before.
 &HT;    ``We got off the airplane and we were signing autographs and
taking photos with people,'' he says. ``There was this whole fever
pitch, and then someone from `Dogma' showed up and said, `Let's get
these guys through!' And it seemed almost mobbish for a second.''
 &HT;    The affable Damon, sitting in a suite at Los Angeles' Four
Seasons hotel, shakes his baseball-cap-covered head in lingering
disbelief.
 &HT;    He and Affleck, still trailed by those 10 fans, walked a
quarter-mile to a tram that would shuttle them to the airport's
main terminal, he adds.
 &HT;    ``We got on the tram and these people had to get on the tram,
too,'' Damon says bemusedly. ``By the time we got to our cars, they
were just talking and were not even interested in us anymore.''
 &HT;    He laughs.
 &HT;    ``It's this situation that's perpetuated by circumstances,'' he
says thoughtfully. ``When those circumstances are manipulated and
what's normally a 30-second experience turns into a 30-minute
experience, it becomes, `All right, see you, guys!'
 &HT;    ``It was a really interesting study of that whole phenomenon.''
 &HT;    Perhaps coincidentally, ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' _ which will
open nationwide on Christmas _ is itself an exploration of the
nature of idolatry, taking it to a jarring, disturbing extreme.
 &HT;    Written and directed by Anthony Minghella, who made the
Oscar-winning ``The English Patient,'' and based on the novel by
Patricia Highsmith, the film casts Damon as Tom Ripley, a
chameleonesque, gay nobody in 1950s New York. The tragic story line
gets underway when a wealthy shipbuilder (James Rebhorn) hires
Ripley to bring home his wayward son Dickie (Jude Law), who, along
with his girlfriend Marge (Gwyneth Paltrow), has been leading the
lush life in Italy.
 &HT;    Dickie's elegant lifestyle so fascinates Ripley that he decides
to achieve it for himself, first by worming his way into Dickie's
favor and then ... well, by any means necessary.
 &HT;    ``We all project a certain amount of happiness on somebody
else's life and make assumptions about other people,'' Damon says.
``I'm certainly guilty of doing it. `Ripley' is a riff on that, but
we play it all the way out.
 &HT;    ``When you start to root for a guy like Ripley,'' he adds, ``and
some people do, you've got to think to yourself, `Well, what does
that say about me?'
 &HT;    ``Hopefully, that question will stay with people after the
lights come back on in the theater,'' Damon says. ``Hopefully,
people will take away the feeling that they're implicated in it
all.
 &HT;    ``In that sense, `Ripley' is a cautionary tale.''
 &HT;    But, since Damon admits that even he started to root for Ripley,
what does that say about him?
 &HT;    ``Exactly,'' he says, breaking into a toothy grin. ``That's why
I had to do the movie. That's why I felt `Ripley' was important, in
terms of the way it goes against the grain of the way movies are
made nowadays.
 &HT;    ```Ripley' really says something,'' the actor adds, ``and its
tone is so original. It was exciting, because I hadn't seen
something like `Ripley' in a long time. Our hero is a very complex
antihero.''
 &HT;    And, it should be noted, Damon delivers a very complex
performance, a well-calibrated one that smartly plays off his
youthful good looks and aw-shucks charm. It's as if the Devil rose
from the pits of Hell and was reborn as the boy next door.
 &HT;    Damon doesn't consider Ripley a despicable character, however.
It's a subtle distinction, but he thinks of him as a guy who
commits despicable acts.
 &HT;    ``The whole challenge of the movie was to keep the audience with
Ripley, not in the sense that they're sympathetic, but in the sense
that they understand what he does,'' the actor says. ``They can
disagree with what he does, but they understand it because they
know where it's coming from, which is this deep loneliness that
this guy (feels).
 &HT;    ``He's so desperately trying not to be alone,'' Damon says,
``and you see that he has this incredible capacity for love, I
think, and sensitivity. He's really far more good to the people
around him than Dickie is.
 &HT;    ``Dickie is very careless, but he just has this incredible
charisma and can leave people totally gobsmacked,'' he adds. ``He's
like the sun, with everyone orbiting around him, but he's totally
oblivious to it. Tom would never treat people that way if he had
Dickie's life.''
 &HT;    Damon's own life has not been the same since ``Good Will
Hunting'' became an unexpected breakout hit a couple of years ago.
The actor, in fact, has spoken often of how he lives out of two
duffel bags that he's dragged from set to set.
 &HT;    After ``Good Will Hunting,'' Damon turned up in ``Rounders''
(1998), then the current ``Dogma'' _ in a role even darker than
Ripley, since he plays a casually murderous renegade angel. Several
other films are already shot, including ``All the Pretty Horses,''
directed by Billy Bob Thornton, and ``The Third Wheel,'' a romantic
comedy, starring Denise Richards and Luke Wilson, which is produced
by Damon and Affleck, who make cameos.
 &HT;    Just completed is ``The Legend of Bagger Vance,'' a Robert
Redford-directed ``fairy tale'' about a golfer (Damon) who has lost
his soul and must be redeemed by a mysterious caddie (Will Smith).
 &HT;    As the holidays approach, Damon is at last slowing down and
catching his breath. At home in his Manhattan apartment, he'll
unpack those well-traveled duffel bags and squeeze in some quality
time with his girlfriend, actress Winona Ryder.
 &HT;    And, despite the high price of fame _ most notably the loss of
anonymity _ Damon intends to count his blessings as the new year
begins. He has no film about to go into production, and he and
Affleck are only now beginning their next script.
 &HT;    ``I'm looking forward to getting a little time to reflect on
everything that's happened to me, because I haven't had that yet,''
he says softly. ``I'll have six months off, and all I'm planning on
doing is writing a script. I think it'll be a good time for me to
reflect and spend time with my family and friends.
 &HT;    ``But I can't think of anything I'd want to be different right
now.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
