<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIVER-STONE-DIRECTS-ANY-GIVEN-SUNDAY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLIVER STONE: THE SAME OLD GAME ON A WHOLE NEW FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Oliver Stone directing Al Pacino and
Cameron Diaz in a scene from ``Any Given Sunday.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The ball is in Oliver Stone's hands and the clock is ticking
down.
 &HT;    The people at Warner Bros. are rooting for a touchdown, and the
pressure is on.
 &HT;    ``There is such a level of intensity before I release a film
that I've actually had to develop a skin as tough as a football,''
Stone says.
 &HT;    The football metaphors come naturally to the director, taking
time out for an interview before diving back into the massive task
of getting his latest film edited in time for its Dec. 22 opening.
 &HT;    That film _ which, at $55 million and counting, has a bigger
budget than any he's ever made _ is the football drama ``Any Given
Sunday.'' Al Pacino, as a driven NFL coach, headlines an all-star
cast that includes Cameron Diaz, Jamie Foxx, Dennis Quaid, Charlton
Heston, James Woods and Ann-Margret, not to mention some real
gridiron veterans, led by recent Hall of Fame inductee Lawrence
Taylor.
 &HT;    Dressed in black pants and a matching T-shirt, his thick black
hair uncombed, Stone looks physically fit but more than a little
distracted.
 &HT;    ``I have over 1,000 digital effects to check before the night is
over,'' he says as he enters a room at Los Angeles' Century Plaza
Hotel. ``Tonight, no matter how late it goes, I will finish this
movie.''
 &HT;    If so, it will be a bright spot in a troubling year.
 &HT;    The 53-year-old director of ``Platoon'' (1986), ``Wall Street''
(1987) and ``JFK'' (1991) was arrested last summer for driving
erratically down a winding Los Angeles road in his black Ford
Mustang. Police found a small amount of hashish in the car, as well
as hydrocodine, a pain medication.
 &HT;    Stone pled guilty to charges of drug possession and received
three years of probation, as well as mandatory enrolment in a
drug-treatment program.
 &HT;    He's also involved in a court case alleging that his ``Natural
Born Killers'' (1994) sparked a real-life murder.
 &HT;    Given that, it probably wasn't too surprising that making his
film about the violent world of football actually led to a call to
the real-life cops. Apparently a shoving match between Jamie Foxx _
who plays an arrogant quarterback _ and co-star LL Cool J
degenerated into a fight, with Foxx ultimately filing and then
dropping assault charges against the rapper.
 &HT;    ``I still shake my head,'' Foxx says in a separate interview,
``because it turned into World Wrestling Federation time. And it
was necessary for the cops to be there.''
 &HT;    And what was the volatile Stone doing while all this was going
on?
 &HT;    Foxx breaks into a laugh.
 &HT;    ``Oliver screamed, `What the hell is going on?''' he says.
```And why aren't my cameras rolling?'''
 &HT;    In short, making an Oliver Stone movie is not for wimps.
Especially if it's about football, a passion since his days
attending Trinity Grammar School in New York.
 &HT;    ``I was a left halfback,'' he says. ``I ripped into people. I
was great, until we moved and I went to a different school. They
moved me to fullback, and I was terrible.
 &HT;    ``Then I stopped playing and took up cross country in protest.''
 &HT;    But football stayed with him all those years.
 &HT;    ``I honestly thought there was something mystical about the
sport,'' he says. ``It reminds me of Indian teachings. I loved how
you literally dig your hands into the earth to get the ball _ there
is something old and primeval about football.''
 &HT;    But the NFL, wary of Stone's penchant for puncturing America's
greatest icons, wasn't buying it.
 &HT;    ``We tried very hard to get their cooperation,'' Stone says. ``I
negotiated with them on and off for months. I went for three or
four meetings, but eventually it just didn't work out.
 &HT;    ``Listen,'' he adds. ``I've never had cooperation from any
official body. Would it be an Oliver Stone film if the Defense
Department had supported `Platoon?' Or `Born on the Fourth of July'
(1989)? Or `Heaven and Earth' (1993)? It's not like the State
Department greeted me warmly about `JFK.'
 &HT;    ``I count on those doors being closed,'' the director says.
``Most of the time I can't go to the real guys, because I want to
tell the truth. I need to be honest.''
 &HT;    And indeed the movie opens an unblinking lens onto the
behind-the-scenes world of professional football _ the greedy
agents, the violent players, the drug-dispensing team doctors, the
exploitative owners and more.
 &HT;    ``You go to the real guys who play and it is about hard hits,
cursing, playing hurt,'' Stone says, pacing the room as his
legendary temper flares. ``A lot of s--t goes down.
 &HT;    ``Of course the NFL doesn't want you to know about anything
behind the scenes,'' he adds, ``because this is supposed to be
family entertainment. They have this Disney image.''
 &HT;    Stone's intensity as a director is matched by Pacino's notorious
intensity as an actor, but he insists that the two had no special
problem working together.
 &HT;    ``I read some phony press account that Al and I were at each
other's throats,'' he says, ``but that is absolutely not true. Al
and I got along very well.''
 &HT;    In fact, he adds, the two have a longstanding relationship
dating back to ``Scarface'' (1983), a Pacino vehicle which Stone
scripted.
 &HT;    ``I wrote `Born on the Fourth of July' for him,'' the director
says. ``Al is a shy man with a sweet inner core. He is also one of
the most sensitive human beings I've ever met. He's one of the best
actors of his generation.''
 &HT;    In a separate interview, Pacino agrees that the two got on
famously.
 &HT;    ``I think what people misunderstand is that Oliver Stone likes
to create chaos on a movie set,'' Pacino says. ``Working with
Oliver is a bit like doing live TV _ it's happening for the first
time and it's happening there. This is it. You're not going to get
a chance to do it again.
 &HT;    ``So it's always good to be ready to meet the day,'' he says.
``You're going to have a lot of surprises.''
 &HT;    Stone also appears briefly in the film as a fashion-challenged
sportscaster _ his first onscreen appearance since a gag cameo as a
conspiracy theorist in ``Dave'' (1993).
 &HT;    ``I was actually planning my own future as a washed-up
sportscaster for when the movie career is done,'' Stone says,
laughing.
 &HT;    ``Any Given Sunday'' may rake its share of NFL muck, but chances
are it won't raise the hackles of the powers that be to the extent
that Stone's Vietnam trilogy and, especially, ``JFK'' and ``Nixon''
(1995) did. Collectively, these films have made the outspokenly
liberal director perhaps the most controversial filmmaker Hollywood
has ever known, and earned him more than his share of enemies in
politics and the media.
 &HT;    ``If you've had success, then you become a bigger target,''
Stone says matter-of-factly. ``It's always nicer to be the underdog
_ I long for the days when I was a younger director and nobody knew
me. Now they watch every move.''
 &HT;    Which doesn't mean he's getting any mellower.
 &HT;    ``Why do I push the envelope? Well, a lot of divorces. A lot of
children,'' he jokes. ``No, I love making movies.
 &HT;    ``Listen,'' Stone says, ``I make hard films, and that hasn't
changed. I still have the energy to make these movies. I am getting
older, so maybe I need to get these movies out of my system before
I make films about people sipping tea.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Any Given Sunday,'' consult
the official Website at www.anygivensunday.net. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
