<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4437 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-THE-RETURN-OF-FANTASI     12-20 1488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-RETURN-OF-FANTASIA-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICKEY MOUSE, MUSIC AND THE MILLENNIUM: `FANTASIA/2000' HITS THE
BIG, BIG SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of a woodland spirit in a scene from
``Fantasia/2000.'') 
 By JEANNE WOLF and SHEP MORGAN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Don't look for Mickey Mouse in the crowd cheering the drop of
the Times Square ball on Dec. 31, or hailing the dawn of a new
millennium on some distant Pacific island.
 &HT;    Instead, Walt Disney's beloved cartoon icon will be hard at
work, pushing a broom across a giant movie screen, accompanied by a
live orchestra, at the gala New Year's Eve premiere of
``Fantasia/2000.''
 &HT;    The new film, an IMAX sequel/revamp to Walt Disney's legendary
animation/classical music hybrid ``Fantasia'' (1940), introduces
seven new sequences _ featuring music by the Chicago Symphony under
conductor James Levine _ and adds star hosts for each sequence,
including Steve Martin, Bette Midler, James Earl Jones and Angela
Lansbury.
 &HT;    Donald Hahn _ who also worked on ``Beauty and the Beast''
(1991), ``The Lion King'' (1994) and ``The Hunchback of Notre
Dame'' (1997) _ clearly relished the opportunity to direct the
celebrity hosts.
 &HT;    ``Being given a chance to take `Fantasia' to a new level is like
being entrusted with the studio's crown jewels,'' he says with an
enthusiastic chuckle. ``What's funny is that Walt was ahead of his
time _ `Fantasia' got mixed reviews and didn't sell a lot of
tickets. Now it seems to end up on everyone's list of best films of
the century.
 &HT;    ``Walt's idea was, `What if we threw together some of the
greatest animation artists and greatest composers in a film without
dialogue?''' Hahn continues. ``Then he had a chat with the famous
conductor Leopold Stokowski, who loved the concept, and they became
a team, with Stokowski taking charge of the music and Disney
coordinating the artists.
 &HT;    ``They began with the sequence with Mickey Mouse, and it just
sort of grew into a feature.''
 &HT;    ``The Sorcerer's Apprentice,'' Mickey's memorable tussle with a
host of enchanted brooms, remains a centerpiece of
``Fantasia/2000.'' His longtime cartoon pal Donald Duck gets into
the act in a Noah's Ark sequence, and the film also introduces
myriad new characters, from animated whales who perform a soaring
aquatic ballet to Respighi's ``Pines of Rome'' to a flock of
flamingos with yo-yos who cavort to the strains of Saint-Saens'
``Carnival of the Animals.''
 &HT;    The choice of the still-new IMAX format was a natural, Hahn
says.
 &HT;    ``Why not?'' he says with a shrug. ``I think it's just breaking
new ground, which is part of the heritage that Walt left behind.
There's never been a feature-length IMAX film. We like to step out
and try things that have never been done before.
 &HT;    ``But there was a tremendous amount of fear in doing it,'' he
admits. ``You start out seeing the characters on a drawing board or
a computer screen, and suddenly they're three stories high _ Mickey
Mouse is as big as a cement truck. I must say that all the images
take on a life of their own when they're that big.''
 &HT;    The original film may be more than a half-century old, but Hahn
thinks its appeal to today's children may be greater than it was
back when.
 &HT;    ``I think kids are more visually literate now than they were in
1940,'' he says. ``Then there wasn't even television, not to
mention MTV. Now there're computers, the Internet and video games _
we have a whole new generation that will see this film with a
different eye.''
 &HT;    The celebrity hosts are more than window-dressing, he adds.
 &HT;    ``I decided to put together an eclectic group who would
represent the diversity of the arts and bring their own style and
personality,'' he says. ``We open `Fantasia/2000' with Steve
Martin, who makes it clear that you're in for more than serious
entertainment _ you're going to have some fun.
 &HT;    ``Steve and the other celebrities will, I think, make the work
of great composers more accessible to the audience.''
 &HT;    Nor are all the hosts clean-cut family entertainers. The honor
of introducing Mickey Mouse fell to the eccentric illusionists Penn
and Teller, known for black humor and offbeat antics.
 &HT;    ``I can tell you they didn't behave themselves,'' Hahn says,
laughing, ``but that made it fun. I knew they'd be irreverent, but
that was the perfect way for them to introduce `The Sorcerer's
Apprentice.'''
 &HT;    On the other hand, Hahn says he's still in awe of James Earl
Jones _ a Disney veteran since ``The Lion King'' _ who introduces
the flamingos with yo-yos.
 &HT;    ``When we had lunch,'' he recalls, ``it was just amazing. He was
ordering his meal in that booming voice of his, and we all felt
like we were at the table with Darth Vader.
 &HT;    ``I wanted to juxtapose that imposing presence of his with what
is a very nutty comical piece,'' Hahn adds. ``He had a great time
doing it.''
 &HT;    Eric Goldberg, a veteran of ``Aladdin'' (1992) and
``Pocahontas'' (1995) who directed the animated-flamingos sequence,
seconds the motion.
 &HT;    ``James Earl Jones could get your attention reading the
telephone book,'' he says. ``I ended up appearing with him in his
introduction. You see me drawing away in the background _ I'm the
short, bearded guy with the pencil. I have to interrupt him and
tell him to change the intro. So now I can say I've acted with
James Earl Jones.''
 &HT;    It was Goldberg who came up with the idea of equipping flamingos
with yo-yos, inspired by Michael Gabriel, his co-director on
``Pocahontas.''
 &HT;    ``Every time Mike would get bored,'' Goldberg recalls, ``he
would pull out his yo-yo and start playing with it. So I shot some
live-action footage of Mike and then turned his right arm into a
flamingo's foot.''
 &HT;    Goldberg also set Gershwin's ``Rhapsody in Blue'' to a story,
set in Jazz Age Manhattan and rendered in the style of the
legendary caricaturist Al Hirschfeld.
 &HT;    ``I was sweating bullets when I had to show the preliminary
drawings to Mr. Hirschfeld,'' he admits. ``He's 92, but as sharp as
ever. He's always been one of my heroes, and I had used his style
when I created the Genie for `Aladdin.' Fortunately he liked that,
and he loved what we did in `Fantasia/2000.'''
 &HT;    The driving force behind the new ``Fantasia,'' both Hahn and
Goldberg say, was Walt Disney's brother Roy, chairman of the
studio's feature-animation division, who was inspired by the
success of the film's early-1990s video release.
 &HT;    ``I always saw Walt's `Fantasia' as a work in progress,'' Disney
says. ``I kept thinking we should do a sequel, but it was always a
dream, not a real possibility. After the success of the video sale,
I asked Michael Eisner if we could fool around a little, and he
said, `Go ahead.'
 &HT;    ``Walt used to say that he felt like a bee that went around
pollinating the various talents at the studio,'' Disney adds. ``I
guess I felt like that's the part I played in `Fantasia/2000.'''
 &HT;    Walt Disney undertook ``Fantasia'' as an artistic statement, one
that he didn't expect to be particularly profitable. While the
studio expects ``Fantasia/2000'' to be successful, the same
aesthetic has driven the new version, and Hahn is confident that
Disney would approve.
 &HT;    ``Sure he would,'' he says. ``He was a great storyteller. In the
end, what really matters is that you go into a dark theater and are
told a tale that moves and engages you. It is what made Shakespeare
great, Dickens great or any storyteller from any generation.
 &HT;    ``That was Walt's genius, and it's reflected in `Fantasia' _ and
I think he'd be proud of the way we've carried on the tradition in
`Fantasia/2000.'''
 c.1999 Pentacom Productions  
<TEXT>
