<HEADER>
A4449 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-PLANT-DNA-NYT &LR;      12-20 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PLANT-DNA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENETICISTS TAP SECRETS OF `THE WEED' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Biologists have decoded a large part of the DNA of a plant,
affording the first glimpse of the genetic programming of the plant
world.
</P>
<P>
   The plant, known formally as Arabidopsis thaliana and informally
as ``the weed,'' is studied by nearly a thousand laboratories
around the world as a model plant.
</P>
<P>
   One immediate surprise is that Arabidopsis, which scientists
chose to decode because of its small and simple genome, turns out
to have some 25,000 genes, considerably more than the C. elegans
roundworm, whose full DNA or genome was decoded last year.
</P>
<P>
   This may give ``weed people,'' as those who study Arabidopsis
are sometimes known, unexpected bragging rights over worm people.
</P>
<P>
   Several large consortiums of scientists were formed to work on
Arabidopsis' five chromosomes, the units in which its DNA is
packaged. The first two of these chromosomes have now been decoded,
scientists reported last week in Nature.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute for Genomic Research in Rockville, Md., has
obtained the DNA sequence of Chromosome 2, and a consortium of
European and American groups has sequenced Chromosome 4.
</P>
<P>
   These two chromosomes, two of the smallest, represent about a
quarter of the plant's total genome. They show that large parts of
the genome consist of duplications, with the identical sequence of
DNA letters appearing twice over.
</P>
<P>
   The duplications, arising through errors in the copying process
when a cell divides, are thought to play a major innovative role in
evolution, since the new spare copy of a gene is free to evolve new
functions.
</P>
<P>
   This first glimpse ``shows a remarkably dynamic genome, one in
constant motion and undergoing constant rearrangement,'' Dr.
Elliott M. Meyerowitz of Caltech wrote in a commentary in Nature.
</P>
<P>
   On the basis of the sequenced chromosomes, Arabidopsis is
calculated to possess 25,000 genes. It is hard to see why it needs
so many, given that a mere 19,000 genes suffice to run the
roundworm, which has a brain and nervous system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should underestimate the complexities of
flowering plants,'' said Dr. Michael Bevan, a biologist at the John
Innes Center in Norwich, England, and a leader of a Chromosome 4
team. ``They have an enormous repertoire of genes for elaborating a
vast variety of chemicals from sunlight, air and water, and they
have very sophisticated defense mechanisms because they cannot
fight or run away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arabidopsis Genome Initiative, which oversees the decoding
work, hopes to complete much of the genome by the end of 2000.
Having the first complete plant genome in hand should make it much
easier to improve the genetics of crops. Bevan said genes from
Arabidopsis could be effective when transferred to crop plants
because ``a lot of these processes are conserved between different
plants.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the biologists who decoded the first human chromosome this
month, the Arabidopsis biologists were baffled by the part of the
chromosome known as the centromere. This region of DNA, important
in helping to distribute dividing chromosomes equally between two
daughter cells, is made of the same short run of DNA letters
repeated over and over again. The repetitions, like identical
pieces of a jigsaw, are very hard to reassemble correctly.
</P>
<P>
   The centromere has ``one part that we just do not technically
have the capability to sequence,'' said W. Richard McCombie, a
member of the Chromosome 4 team at the Cold Spring Harbor
Laboratory. The team sequenced as far into the centromere as it
could go and hopes to finish the rest when technology improves,
McCombie said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
