<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COMMAND THAT LETS YOU EAT YOUR INTERNET WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics. The words LESS THAN
and GREATER THAN in parentheses should be replaced by the
symbols.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Another damned, thick, square book!'' said the duke of
Gloucester in 1781 to a hard-working historian, Edward Gibbon,
whose ``Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire'' would ultimately run
to six damned, thick, square volumes. ``Always  &UR; scribble &LR; ,
 &UR; scribble &LR; ,  &UR; scribble &LR; , eh, Mr. Gibbon?''
</P>
<P>
   That was the most famous use of a word that means ``to write
hastily, often illegibly,'' rooted in the Latin  &UR; scribere &LR; , ``to
write.'' A  &UR; scrivener &LR;  is a public copyist, but that noun has
fallen into disuse except among notaries public; a  &UR; scribe &LR; , once
``a copyist of biblical texts,'' is now used jocularly to mean
``journalist,'' and a  &UR; scribbler &LR;  is a put-down of a writer. This
eye-strained wretch, in the millennial winter of his discontent,
can be found down in the subbasement of information architecture in
a cubicle labeled  &UR; content provider &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   But the noun and verb  &UR; scribble &LR;  has been resuscitated by the
Internet set and given a new command position. In ``Wired Style,''
by Constance Hale and Jessie Scanlon, the  &UR; scribble command &LR;  is a
boon to  &UR; flame-throwers &LR;  _ those intemperate types who post curses
on bulletin boards and otherwise abuse the civility of computer
intercourse: `` &UR; Scribbling &LR;  ... the saving grace of flame-throwers
on the Well, the  &UR; scribble &LR;  command lets posters delete their words
after the fact. The original post is replaced by a (LESS
THAN) &UR; scribbled &LR; (GREATER THAN) notice. It lets you eat your words,
but not without leaving some digital crumbs.''
</P>
<P>
   If you have second thoughts about some snarl you have posted on
the Well, a members-only Sausalito, Calif., ``online community,''
where this 1985 PicoSpan software was first used, you can delete it
with the  &UR; scribble &LR;  command. The post time, date and user name will
be listed, but the text of the heated message will be replaced by
the word  &UR; scribbled &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   What a great idea. Our civilization would neither decline nor
fall if only we could work out a mental eraser that would scratch
out insults we wish we had never hurled. Thanks to Internetese, at
last self-expurgation has a moniker _ eh, Mr. Gibbon?
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S PAST MUST NOT BE PRELUDE
</P>
<P>
   It is time to get right with the old millennium. In the course
of the last thousand years, and especially in 1999, I have made a
few mistakes that I want to get off my conscience so I can start
with a clean slate.
</P>
<P>
   In a jeremiad denouncing ``shoppertainment'' in factory-outlet
malls, I wrote: ``Standing here in the epicenter of
pre-Christmasism, laden with shopping bags of merchandise that
proves my worth both as a provider and conspicuous consumer, a
nagging thought intrudes: Is this the way I want to spend my
leisure time?''
</P>
<P>
   As Robert Peyser of Brookline, Mass., writes, ``Might you not
agree that the participial phrase beginning with the words
`Standing here' ought to modify `I'?'' I might. That was a double
dangling participle _ hard to do _ and it would be wrong to let it
slop over to 2000. Should have written: ``... consumer, I was
struck by the thought ....''
</P>
<P>
   In a factual lapse, I misinformed readers that Al Capone ``died
in jail _ `nutty as a fruitcake,' as a gangland visitor reported.''
A mob of his Chicago followers pointed out that their hero,
Scarface Al, died of cardiac arrest in 1947 at his Palm Island,
Fla., home after being released from jail (but _ as reported
accurately here _ nutty as a fruitcake).
</P>
<P>
   ``The 50 American states are not sovereign,'' I wrote in a
column that sought to explicate the exquisite difference between
 &UR; state &LR;  and  &UR; nation &LR; , ``no matter what they say in Texas and Hawaii
(the only states that were once sovereign nations).''
</P>
<P>
   An indignant troop of Ethan Allen's Green Mountain Boys came
after me on that one. ( &UR; Vermont &LR;  means ``green mountain.'') From
1777 to 1791, the settlers of the New Hampshire Grants, as Vermont
was first known, refused to consider themselves part of neighboring
New York and functioned as an independent nation, issuing their own
money and telling the 13 states forming a union to take a hike.
</P>
<P>
   Finally the feisty Vermonters paid greedy New York $30,000 to
drop its claim, which paved the way for it to become the 14th
state. Sen. James Jeffords, on behalf of his incensed constituents,
was especially worked up about my error, and I hope this does not
start a secession movement.
</P>
<P>
   The Gotcha! Gang follows me from these pages to television
appearances. I was heard to say  &UR; congratulate &LR;  and  &UR; accreditate &LR;  as
if those words had no  &UR; t &LR;  (except the one in  &UR; ate &LR; ), but only a
 &UR; d &LR; . Leslie Hill-Levitt Latham of West Redding, Conn., wondered if
this frequent mispronunciation would lead to a change in spelling
to  &UR; congradulate &LR;  and  &UR; accredidate &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Hats off to  &UR; congratulations &LR;  _ the word is impossible to
pronounce correctly. When a  &UR; d &LR;  or a  &UR; t &LR;  comes between two vowels,
what linguists call ``flapping'' takes place, and we hear the sound
of  &UR; d/t &LR;  or  &UR; t/d &LR; , an amalgam of the two.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, as Ellen Kaisse, professor of linguistics at the
University of Washington (Seattle), notes, ``The  &UR; y &LR;  sound before
the  &UR; u &LR;  makes the consonant  &UR; t/d &LR;  sound more like  &UR; ch/j &LR; , and
people pronounce this word in about three ways:  &UR; congradyulate, &LR; 
 &UR; congrachulate &LR;  or  &UR; congrajulate &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   What's a kudos-giver to do? I will adopt slang's shortened noun
form,  &UR; congrats &LR; , but will still struggle along with the word I
pronounce  &UR; congradulate &LR;  as a verb. However, I will not adopt that
spelling, preferring to stick with the  &UR; t &LR;  for old times' sake. (As
for the mispronounced and misspelled verb  &UR; accredidate &LR; , I'll
strike it from my mental set; the verb is ``to accredit.'')
</P>
<P>
   And as for those lifting a glass at the big hooh-hah in a few
days: a festive, neatly snipped-off, easily pronounceable and
correctly spellable  &UR; congrats &LR;  to one and all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 1556EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
