<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4461 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-FILIPINO-VET-HNS &LR;      12-20 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILIPINO-VET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILIPINO VETERANS WIN A BATTLE, BUT NOT THE WAR, FOR EQUITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Having lived for 85 years _ as an elementary
school teacher, a Filipino guerrilla fighter, a sharpshooter for
the U.S. Army and now a stooped, slow-moving man who only
occasionally wanders outside his San Francisco apartment _ Ernesto
Fajardo's thoughts have turned to his funeral arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   If he dies in his adopted homeland, where he has been living as
a U.S. citizen for eight years, ``we don't have the money to pay
for the transportation of my dead body back to the Philippines.''
</P>
<P>
   If death takes him in his hometown of Mayantoc, about 70 miles
from Manila, ``The whole town will be attending my funeral. I am a
bandleader, so the band will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sensing the end is near, Fajardo had his boxes packed and was
waiting for President Clinton to sign a bill that would allow him
to continue receiving benefits while spending the rest of his days
in his native country.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, he got the good news from a friend who dropped
by: Clinton had signed the Foster Care Independence Act, which
included a rider allowing Filipino veterans of World War II who
receive Supplemental Security income (SSI) to return to the
Philippines and still get 75 percent of those monthly payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the bottom of my heart, I am thanking the president for
his benevolence and his Christmas gift,'' he said, his words coming
out slowly, but each one loud and distinct.
</P>
<P>
   However, only a fraction of the 14,000 Filipino veterans
eligible under this provision are expected to take advantage of it.
The ever-declining number of aging Filipino veterans _ now
estimated at 50,000 to 70,000 _ have spent 53 years waiting for the
U.S. government to give them the same medical, pension and burial
benefits as American soldiers, which they believe the U.S.
government promised them when the war broke out in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   Such legislation has been proposed in Congress, but to date has
not been approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``This SSI is just a drop in the bucket,'' said Jon Melegrito,
executive director of the National Federation of Filipino American
Associations in Washington, D.C. ``It doesn't cost the United
States anything. In fact, it saves them money.''
</P>
<P>
   By taking the reduced SSI payments, which would be up to $380 a
month, and agreeing to give up Medicaid, the veterans would save
the U.S. government an estimated $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is pleased some veterans will benefit from the law,
Melegrito said he had misgivings.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is, by passing this legislation, it doesn't give
Congress any incentive to pursue the Filipino veterans equity
bill,'' he said. ``We've been fighting for that for 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Eric Lachica, executive director of the American
Coalition for Filipino Veterans, sees it, the SSI provision is just
the first step in the fight for equity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Round One,'' said Lachica, the Washington lobbyist
behind the provision. ``It inspires our supporters to get
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Philippines was still a U.S. commonwealth, about
200,000 Filipino soldiers were drafted into the war against the
Japanese. They say they were promised citizenship and benefits, but
Congress denied them those privileges in the Rescission Act of
1946, the same year the Philippines gained independence from the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Filipino groups have been fighting for equity ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, the cost of providing full veterans benefits to
Filipinos was estimated at $5 billion. The cost goes down each year
as the old soldiers die.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the money is not the issue here,'' Melegrito said. ``It's
the issue of being recognized. They want nothing else but to have
their honor and dignity restored. For the last 53 years, they have
not been paying these veterans, so you can argue the U.S.
government has been saving money.''
</P>
<P>
   Lourdes Tancinco, a San Francisco lawyer and president of the
board of the newly opened Veterans Equity Center in the city, said
the SSI benefit had nothing to do with equity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The SSI bill is financial assistance to needy U.S. citizens,''
she said. ``It's not at all an answer to what they've been
clamoring for. The fight for equity still continues.''
</P>
<P>
   The closest that Filipino veterans have come to equity is a 1990
law allowing them to become American citizens. About 24,000 of them
_ including 7,000 in the Philippines _ have been naturalized.
</P>
<P>
   About 7,000 veterans living in the United States, plus the 7,000
in the Philippines, are eligible for SSI. Lachica believes 2,000 of
the 7,000 U.S. residents will, like Fajardo, want to return to the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Fajardo's face lights up when talking about his hero's funeral.
But when asked about the equity bill for Filipino veterans, his
smile turns into a frown and furrows creep into his forehead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not interested anymore in the equity bill,'' he said.
``It's too hard. I believe they won't sign the equity bill. It
involves too much money.''
</P>
<P>
   That makes him no less adamant about the injustice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought side by side with the American soldiers,'' he said.
``We should also have the same benefit as Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 85, though, he is giving up his fight for equity. He will
probably not miss the tiny apartment he shares with his wife and
grown son. He sleeps in the walk-in closet, which he says is warmer
than the rest of the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   He is already thinking about how he will pass his days when he
goes back to the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will attend to my family,'' he said. ``Maybe I can still
direct my orchestra. I have many pieces I have collected _ tango,
rumba, waltz.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
