</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ I saw the winter's first robin this
weekend, a cheerful early omen of mild weather and good times in
the new century. What a difference a year makes. This time last
year the House had just voted to impeach the president, and the
country was in an uproar. Now his job approval rating is lower than
it was but still at 56 percent. And 58 percent still say the Senate
was correct to acquit him. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ The anticipation of the new
millennium has been building for months now, even though its
technical arrival, according to the way we number our calendar,
will be Jan. 1, 2001, still a year away. But technicalities aside,
the transition from 1999 to 2000 is a good time for reflection and
celebration. So, in the seasonal spirit, here are some of my
reflections. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 1620EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
