<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4499 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-EYE-CANCER-ART-NY     12-20 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-EYE-CANCER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING AN EARLY START ON TREATING EYE CANCER BY INDUCING LABOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada, Calif., Fla.)  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MARK BLOOM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Terry Hoddinot, 36, of London, Ontario, has been blind since the
age of 3. His son, Riley, 3{, lost his left eye a month ago. The
same rare eye cancer, retinoblastoma, was diagnosed in his baby
daughter, Katie, while she was still in the womb.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say there is a good chance that they may have saved
Katie's vision with a bold new procedure: delivering her
prematurely, then treating the affected eye before the cancer had a
chance to grow and blind her.
</P>
<P>
   The approach, described by Dr. Brenda L. Gallie, a University of
Toronto ophthalmologist, at the annual meeting of the American
Society of Human Genetics in San Francisco in October, has
important implications for the treatment of retinoblastoma, a
potentially fatal genetic disorder that afflicts 1 in 20,000 North
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Gallie's treatment has not been accepted everywhere, but
retinoblastoma researchers say it holds promise for the 10 percent
of victims who, like Katie Hoddinot, have a family history of the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us can point to a case or two where three weeks would
have made a difference,'' said Dr. Timothy Murray of the University
of Miami's Bascom Palmer Eye Institute. ``The size and the extent
of the tumor clearly is associated with whether we can preserve the
eye without losing vision. Everyone will tell you that the earlier
you deliver the child, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   When Patti Hoddinot was nearly eight months pregnant with Katie,
the doctors discovered by amniocentesis that the fetus had the same
genetic defect as her father. It meant that she was likely to
develop eye tumors, and that they might even start growing before
she was born.
</P>
<P>
   So Dr. Ants Toi, a radiologist who is a colleague of Gallie,
began checking Katie's eyes every week with ultrasound scans.
Gallie's hope, she said, was that if the scans found tumors, Katie
could be delivered three weeks early to jump-start anticancer
therapy and save as much sight as possible. Since the fetus tends
to move around, getting just the right view of its eyes requires
the patience of a baby photographer, Gallie said.
</P>
<P>
   No tumors were seen on the scans. But because of the family
history, labor was induced early, with the consent of Mrs. Hoddinot
and her obstetrician. Sure enough, when Katie was born on March 17,
there was a tumor in her left eye near the edge of the center of
vision. Katie became the second child to be delivered prematurely
for early retinoblastoma treatment. (The first, MacKenzie
Brinker-Winch, also a patient of Gallie, was born a month before
Katie, and a tumor was substantially reduced.) Before the tumor
could grow larger, it was burned away with a green laser beam.
</P>
<P>
   For Katie and other children who have a family history and whose
condition can be detected late in pregnancy, Gallie thinks the loss
of three weeks of maturity is a good trade-off for the likelihood
of improved vision, particularly if ultrasound shows that the tumor
may be impinging on the field of central vision. She has been
talking for years about inducing delivery to get early help to
these children. Now Gallie, a professor of ophthalmology and
molecular and medical genetics at Toronto's Princess Margaret
Hospital, has done it.
</P>
<P>
   While other retinoblastoma researchers praised her approach,
none have copied it so far. For some, the reason is that no baby
has come along who fits the needed criteria. ``I've never had a
child with retinoblastoma tumors I couldn't treat at birth after a
normal delivery,'' said Dr. Joan O'Brien of the University of
California at San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But others say retinoblastoma is too complex for the treatment
to do much good. Dr. David H. Abramson, director of ophthalmic
oncology at the Weill Cornell Center of New York Presbyterian
Hospital, says ultrasound scans are not sensitive enough to detect
many tumors; if the tumor is in the center of the eye, and big
enough to be seen on ultrasound, it will destroy vision anyway, he
says. If the tumor is big and on the periphery, it can be treated
by laser after a normal birth.
</P>
<P>
   More important, he says, treating the tumors that may develop in
the last three weeks of pregnancy are irrelevant to those that may
continue to develop unpredictably all the way through the age of 7;
some children may develop as many as two dozen, and the mean number
is five.
</P>
<P>
   ``We explored induced delivery with our group,'' he said, ``and
we don't think it's going to accomplish what Dr. Gallie wants to
accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Abramson says a more promising approach may be to give
chemotherapy to the mother in the last few weeks of pregnancy and
let the anticancer drugs pass from mother to fetus. Chemotherapy is
often given toward the end of pregnancy to mothers with cancer,
with no apparent harm to the child, but it has not been tried for a
fetus with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. A. Linn Murphree of the University of Southern California
School of Medicine's Doheny Eye Institute points out that the
genetic disorder in itself does not cause the tumors. What is
inherited, or develops spontaneously, is a single working copy of
the retinoblastoma gene on chromosome 13 in every cell, instead of
two copies, as is normal.
</P>
<P>
   With only one copy of this tumor suppressor gene, an accident in
cell division can lead to no copy _ and tumor growth. But that does
not guarantee that tumors will develop.
</P>
<P>
   Murphree described identical twins he treated who were born
about three weeks prematurely. One child had a large tumor in the
area of central vision, which had to be destroyed by laser. The
child will still have peripheral vision in the eye.
</P>
<P>
   The other twin had no tumor in either eye and has developed none
by the age of 4 months. ``That's chance alone,'' Murphree said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gallie says her first two patients retained considerably
more sight than they would have had they gone full term.
</P>
<P>
   Prenatal ultrasound at 34 weeks determined that MacKenzie
Brinker-Winch, her first patient, whose mother, Corinne Brinker,
was the carrier, had a large tumor in the middle of her left eye.
It doubled in size in a week when labor was induced. The tumor
responded well to chemotherapy. From that tumor, MacKenzie should
wind up with 20/400 sight in that eye. Her right eye had a small
peripheral tumor at birth that was treated with a laser, and
doctors hope her vision in that eye will be unimpaired.
</P>
<P>
   But early this month, she developed a new tumor near the optic
nerve of her good eye, her mother said, and stereotactic radiation
will be tried to destroy it. The prognosis is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Hoddinot, however, is still looking good, with normal
vision for her age in both eyes, even though eight small tumors
have developed and been treated by laser since birth. Her mother
says that if the doctors had waited for a full-term delivery, ``it
would have been a whole different story.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thrilled,'' Mrs. Hoddinot added. ``We think we're a huge
success story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
