<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4502 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-ODOM-CLIPPERS-2ND     12-20 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ODOM-CLIPPERS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 LOS ANGELES: ... a chance.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Was it any wonder, then, that his coming-out party turned into
such a free-for-all?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think he reluctantly put in for the draft,'' says
DeGregorio. ``He didn't do it until three or four hours before the
deadline. I think he thought he was doing the right thing for him
and his family. Two or three days later, he was expressing regrets
to his teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   But by then, he had no recourse, and all he succeeded in doing
was mystifying the evaluators who had him pegged as the top overall
pick in the draft. He attended a tryout in Vancouver, then stopped
auditioning, rejecting an offer to work out for the Bulls, who
owned the No. 1 choice, and skipping the predraft camp in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Not until the week of the draft did he showcase himself for a
handful of NBA representatives. Among them was Clippers scout Jim
Mitchell, who arrived a couple of hours before the trial run,
talked at length with Odom, and was impressed with what he heard.
But the Clippers, renowned for making unimaginable draft blunders,
had been on Odom's trail all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had him checked out thoroughly, just like we do with all
our top picks, and he knows that,'' says Baylor. ``A couple of
people whom he thought were close to him said some negative things,
and they proved to be absolutely untrue. I had an opportunity to
talk to him a long time on the phone. He said he was confused,
fighting with himself about whether to try to get back into
college. I was satisfied with what he had to say. He was very
honest. He said he'd done some things he regretted when he was 17 _
nothing illegal or anything like that _ just some mistakes he'd
made.''
</P>
<P>
   For once, the Clippers didn't regret their selection. Picking
fourth, behind the Bulls (Duke's Elton Brand), Grizzlies
(Maryland's Steve Francis), and Hornets (UCLA's Baron Davis), they
hit the jackpot _ as did Odom, who received a three-year, $7.8
million contract that is considered only the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally with a rookie, you say, `Oh, he's all right,' '' says
Clippers veteran guard Eric Piatkowski. ``With Lamar, after the
first week of camp, I said, `This kid is going to be something
special.' I'd seen him play (in college) and seen a couple of the
others, and I thought, `This guy is definitely going to be No. 1.'
There was no question in my mind. I couldn't believe it when he
fell to fourth. Man, what were these guys (picking ahead of the
Clippers) thinking? This is the type of thing that could cost a
couple of guys their jobs, these so-called gurus.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Growing up fast &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, it's evident that the only reason Odom's name
wasn't called first was his reluctance, which in turn created
doubts among those so-called gurus.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're making a decision with so much riding on it,''
says Odom, ``there's going to be some indecision. I just wanted
everything to be right. I found I couldn't go back, so I was going
to be a pro. When you're 19 years old, you want the right
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no division of opinion that Odom is in the ideal
situation on the court, which Baylor considers ``like therapy'' for
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like a flower opening up,'' says Harrick. ``When he steps
across that black line, you can't wipe the smile off his face.''
</P>
<P>
   Or the faces of those who watch him. Odom's sublime talents
never have been in question. ``He's as special a player as I've
seen join the NBA in quite a while,'' says Walton.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Odom, who left his teens behind only last month,
is that rarest of commodities _ a big man who can put the ball on
the floor, who can create his own shots off the dribble, who is
equally at home on the perimeter or under the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``His versatility is outstanding,'' says Clippers and former
Celtics coach Chris Ford. ``You can't define him as a positional
player. You just leave him on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   When the referees allow it. Nominally the starting small
forward, Odom has played every position except center with the
Clippers, for whom he debuted with a 30-point, 12-rebound effort at
Seattle, but lately has hit a rookie wall of sorts, thanks in no
small part to the fouls that seem automatically assigned to him.
</P>
<P>
   His attitude toward his successes and struggles is instructive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about that Seattle game is we lost,'' says Odom,
``so what good did Lamar Odom do? I can't find my rhythm at all
lately. I've been playing horribly. I'm not blaming anybody but
Lamar Odom. This is the most games I've ever played in my life so
fast. It's a matter of getting used to the schedule. I've got to
get in the gym, keep working, be a warrior, be a good teammate.
That's what basketball is all about to me _ being a good
teammate.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal thinks Odom is trying to be too good a teammate. ``He
seems to be trying to be a playmaker more than doing what he has to
do,'' says the Laker luminary. ``It's a learning process he has to
go through. But I know he's a good player. On any given night, he
can take over a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Of greater concern to his admirers is getting acclimated to the
pro lifestyle, fending off the sharks. Abdur-Rahim can speak from
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's loaded,'' says the Grizzlies small forward. ``I love his
game. He can do just about everything well. But there's an
adjustment. The way I look at it, most guys who go to college (for
four years) are really just getting into their jobs when they're 24
or 25. We're ahead of our time. We've got a lot of people depending
on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is why Odom seeks sanctuary with DeGregorio, a man
who never has asked anything of him, only for him. They became
friends during a summer league when Odom broke his nose and
DeGregorio _ who wasn't even his coach _ drove him to the hospital.
The bond became unbreakable when DeGregorio gave Odom a safe haven
to get his diploma. Even now, Odom calls DeGregorio twice a week,
if for no other reason than to say, ``This is your son, your only
son. I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He could've played at this level two years ago,'' says
DeGregorio. ``I think what he misses about college basketball is
the life, the sense of family. You practice, you study film, you go
to class, you eat as a team. In the NBA, it's two hours of practice
and the rest of the day is yours. Certainly if you're a single kid
alone for 22 hours a day, there's a lot of influences, none of them
good.''
</P>
<P>
   As if anticipating such pitfalls, Odom, who lives with Liza and
Destiny, places a premium on ``being a professional, learning how
to handle yourself off the court, being responsible with your
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Given his difficulty in making some decisions, that may seem
ironic. But DeGregorio believes ``he's done a remarkable job''
adjusting to enforced independence, and those around Odom daily
concur.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't find too many kids his age who are that mature,''
says Clippers assistant coach Jim Todd.
</P>
<P>
   To which Baylor amends, ``You don't find too many guys around
for 10 years who are that mature.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom really had no choice.
</P>
</TEXT>
