<P>
   RUSSIA-ELECT (Moscow) _ Prime Minister Vladimir Putin, already
acclaimed as Russia's latest political hero for his tough conduct
of the war in Chechnya, said Monday that he would use a mandate
from Sunday's Parliamentary election to meet the voters' demand for
new results, new ideas and new solutions, as well as new faces. By
Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-SUIT (Washington) _ Former nuclear weapons scientist Wen Ho
Lee on Monday sued the FBI and the Justice and Energy departments,
alleging they violated his privacy and wrongly portrayed him as a
Chinese spy. The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court, accuses the
agencies of violating the Privacy Act and selectively leaking
``misleading information designed to convince the public that Lee
had engaged in espionage activities for the People's Republic of
China.'' The suit, which was brought by Lee and his wife Sylvia,
does not specify monetary damages. But it opens a second front of
legal attack for the jailed scientist, who was charged earlier this
month with 59 felonies alleging he removed nuclear secrets from Los
Alamos. The indictment didn't allege he gave any information to
China. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   VT-GAY-MARRIAGE (Boston) _ The Vermont Supreme Court ruled on
Monday that the state must guarantee the very same protections and
benefits to committed gay couples as it does to heterosexual
spouses. The decision stopped short of legalizing gay marriage but
threw open the legal door to it and left up to the legislature
whether Vermont will become the first state to take that step. By
Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-VOUCHER-EDUC (Cleveland) _ A federal judge threw out the
state's taxpayer-funded school voucher program Monday, saying it
violated the constitutional separation of church and state.
(Summary from wires) By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-SNOW (Undated) _ Hank Snow, whose gaudy rhinestone suits
and million-selling hit song ``I'm Movin' On'' made him a country
music legend for more than 40 years, died on Monday in Nashville.
He was 85. (Summary from wires) By Neil Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-SEX-SHOPS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The state's highest court ruled on
Monday that the Giuliani administration had overstepped its bounds
in trying to shut down adult businesses, a decision that could
affect dozens of stores, and is by far the Mayor's worst setback in
his drive to restrict X-rated bookstores and theaters. By Richard
Perez-Pena.
