<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4506 &Cx1f; tth-z
r l BC-TIME-CAPSULE-SPI &LR;      12-20 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIME-CAPSULE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU'VE GOT THE TIME, PUT TOGETHER A CAPSULE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By M.L. LYKE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time turns the ordinary extraordinary _ even the $43.64 grocery
receipt Beth Evans-Ramos slips into a protective plastic sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   She pairs this oh-so-'99 cultural relic with advertising fliers
and a picture of the Safeway at her local minimall in Mill Creek,
Wash.
</P>
<P>
   It's all going to a place she's not. The far, far future.
</P>
<P>
   It's a future where a $2.25 gallon of milk, a $6.99 takeout
pizza or pre-HomeGrocer.com stores with four concrete walls may be
a thing of marvel. ``This tells people in the future, `Here is how
we got our food. We used to go to a store in a strip mall,''' says
Evans-Ramos, a local expert in making memory boxes and time
capsules.
</P>
<P>
   Time capsules in various forms are almost as old as
civilization, from the coffins of Egyptian mummies to the
torpedo-shaped time capsule Westinghouse Electric Co. sealed at the
New York World's Fair in 1939, not to be opened for 5,000 years.
The idea of making time stand still, of putting it in a bottle, has
endless appeal, especially in the waning days of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Store shelves and Internet sites are full of commercial capsules
of varying quality. ``Bury one for the millennium,'' boasts an ad
from 4TimeCapsules.com for a $99 capsule with industrial-grade
plastic pipe.
</P>
<P>
   Ads show a truck running over it.
</P>
<P>
   Time trippers can spend from $5 for a plastic capsule shaped
like a giant pill, at Packaging Specialties in Seattle, to $500 and
up for heavy-duty aluminum and stainless steel varieties. A myriad
of flimsy cookie-tin capsules are on the market, filled with reams
of paper to fill out: family trees and pop culture synopses and
letters to future generations.
</P>
<P>
   They don't impress Evans-Ramos. She believes in do-it-yourself
simplicity. ``People are sick of the commercialization of the
millennium,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Evans-Ramos makes a face as she weeds through the papers in two
commercial time-capsule packages: one is meant for kids (``I don't
see a child wanting to do all this writing''), one for adults.
(``Who has the time for another big project this time of year?'').
</P>
<P>
   She recommends keeping capsules simple, using objects to tell
stories and making up the rules as you go along. ``It's one of
those brand-new traditions,'' Evans-Ramos says. ``There's no right
or wrong way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   A sturdy box kept in a dark closet and opened every decade is as
effective as a $400 aluminum capsule buried in the back yard for
great-great-great-great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Evans-Ramos has made capsules using a house-paint can, a
stationery box, even an old film reel container, bought secondhand
and decorated with stick-on letters and tags: ``Do not open until
1-1-2010 '' and ``Review contents, add more and seal up until next
decade.''
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds like too much work, grab a shoebox, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone should do one _ even if you just take the box on Jan.
1, walk around the house, pick up newspapers and magazines and jam
them in. How hard is that?
</P>
<P>
   ``And there'll be somebody in future who will really appreciate
it _ even if it's a perfect stranger.''
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Meyers Gibbs, one of Evans-Ramos' time-capsule students,
used an Army ammunition box for a high-school millennium capsule,
to be opened at the 50th-year reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs is now busy making a boxed family version for the
millennium, with hardware fliers and computer fliers (``That's
going to change in a big way''), grocery receipts, grandma's
crochet, family writings and mementos, and pictures of the changing
view from her living-room window. ``I may put in my brother's
lists, too. He makes lists of how many televisions and phones
people have. He even went through his closet and counted all his
shirts and shoes,'' says Gibbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's kind of interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs has no intention of burying the past. At least not these
pieces of it. ``I'm afraid I would lose it _ or if we move out, I
might forget it's there,'' she says. ``I also want it to be
something you can grab if the house is burning down.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're set on burial, Evans-Ramos recommends using a simple
canning jar. Inside her quart jar, she put a photo of her suburban
Mill Creek chateau, a Garfield Pez dispenser, Yankee Diner matches,
costume jewelry and other pop culture artifacts, adding a little
packet of silica gel from a box of tennis shoes to cut down on
moisture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably bury it a foot down in the back yard. You want
someone to be able to find it,'' she says. ``Can you imagine what a
hoot that would be?''
</P>
<P>
   Evans-Ramos confesses to a Martha Stewart streak, evident in
capsule creations dolled up in bows and collages. Atop one
vintage-looking box is a picture frame with a family collage of
charms, coins, jewelry, a feather (``for tickling _ our family
likes humor'') and the Evans-Ramos surname spelled out in Scrabble
letters, scavenged at a garage sale. Two old belts are buckled
around the box.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to make it so it's not easy to peek,'' says
Evans-Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   Her boxes and capsules are filled with pieces of everyday life:
tickets stubs for Mariners' games and $7 movies, recipes for Mom's
Meat Loaf and Aunt Iris' Jell-O Cool Whip Salad, catalogs for
cookware and fashions. ``That's so your great-great-grandkids can
make fun of what you wore,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   There are In Style magazines and TV Guides. ``People may think,
`What a silly simplistic way to spend your time.'''
</P>
<P>
   And there are dumb videos (``Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles''),
and a Super Mario 3 video-game instruction booklet purloined from
her two boys. ``That's so they can tell their kids, `See, we used
to spend months of our lives doing this.'''
</P>
<P>
   She has high hopes for the Nine Inch Nails CD she slipped into
the mix: ``I'm just hoping the grandkids go, `Oh Dad! What were you
listening to?'''
</P>
<P>
   Evans-Ramos laughs. ``Of course, there may not be anything to
play these on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
