<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4508 &Cx1f; tth-z
r l BC-TIME-CAPSULE-TIPS-SPI     12-20 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIME-CAPSULE-TIPS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPS FOR PUTTING TOGETHER A TIME CAPSULE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ Paper (especially newsprint) may have high-acid content.
Separate pieces in acid-free plastic or glassine sleeves; look for
an ``archival safe'' notation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use acid-free glues and gluesticks. You may want to line your
box with acid-free tissue paper, and wrap each item in it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Remember that videotape may last only 10 years, while
traditional black-and-white photographs may last a century or more.
Color photos are suspectible to color change and fading.
</P>
<P>
   _ Think twice about burial. It is estimated that more than 90
percent of capsules in history have been lost or suffered damage
after being buried.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't put precious wedding pictures, birth certificates and
other prized documents in a capsule. Those go in a safe-deposit
box. Instead, photocopy them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Select a date when the capsule is to be opened, something with
personal or familial significance: the solstice, the new year, a
birthday or anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't put capsules in an insulated attic (too hot) or a
basement (too damp). Light can also cause damage. A dark closet is
best.
</P>
<P>
   _ Label and date everything. Mark the backs of photographs with
soft-lead pencil. Use full names of individuals.
</P>
<P>
   _Don't laminate and don't use self-adhesive tape. It sticks for
only five to 10 years, and leaves messy adhesive behind.
</P>
<P>
   _ Check these useful Web sites:
</P>
<P>
   www.creatingkeepsakes.com
</P>
<P>
   www.lib.cmich.edu/clarke/pres.htm
</P>
<P>
   www.geocities.com/heartland/flats/3081/
</P>
<P>
   acidfree.htm
</P>
<P>
   _ If you have waited till now to begin, don't panic. You can
collect all through the year 2000 and aim for next New Year's to
seal it.
</P>
<P>
   What to put in a capsule:
</P>
<P>
   Awards, certificates
</P>
<P>
   CDs
</P>
<P>
   Clothing catalogs
</P>
<P>
   Coins, bills
</P>
<P>
   Handprints
</P>
<P>
   House plans
</P>
<P>
   Letter to your great-great-grandchildren
</P>
<P>
   Letter to yourself
</P>
<P>
   Locks of hair
</P>
<P>
   Magazines
</P>
<P>
   Menus
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper clippings: headlines, stock market prices
</P>
<P>
   Real estate prices
</P>
<P>
   Paycheck stub
</P>
<P>
   Photographs
</P>
<P>
   Poems, prayers
</P>
<P>
   Political buttons (``Shut down Seatown'')
</P>
<P>
   Postcards
</P>
<P>
   Postage stamps
</P>
<P>
   Pressed flowers
</P>
<P>
   Recipes
</P>
<P>
   Report cards (the good ones)
</P>
<P>
   Ticket stubs
</P>
<P>
   Toys (think Beanie Babies)
</P>
<P>
   Vinyl record
</P>
<P>
   World map
</P>
</TEXT>
