<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4510 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      12-20 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON HEALTH AND FITNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PREVENTION: For Diabetics, a Sight-Saving Eye Test
</P>
<P>
   With relatively basic eye examination, vision loss among people
with diabetes can often be prevented.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the nation's 16 million diabetics develop at least
some retinopathy, which damages the small blood vessels in the
retina. But what frustrates experts in the field is that it cannot
be discerned through a regular eye exam; to see it, the examiner
must dilate the retina with drops. Retinopathy can be treated with
laser surgery, if detected early.
</P>
<P>
   Avoidable vision loss is particularly prevalent among diabetics
who are black, studies have shown; black diabetics suffer twice the
rate of blindness as white ones.
</P>
<P>
   But a new study finds that examination rates among blacks can be
greatly improved with an aggressive education program. About 90
percent of the patients who took part in the study ended up having
dilated-eye exams, which are crucial in avoiding vision loss, said
the report, published in the current issue of The American Journal
of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   The study, sponsored by the National Eye Institute, part of the
government's National Institutes of Health, focused on black
diabetics, 280 in all, because the disease occurs more often among
the black population and has a disproportionately severe effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a really important issue,'' said Dr. Charles E. Basch,
chairman of the department of health and behavioral studies at
Teachers College, Columbia University, who helped direct the study.
``This is an area where there's effective treatment, and it's an
area where people are just not getting diagnosed in a timely way.''
</P>
<P>
   BEHAVIOR: Antismoking Campaigns Elude Gay Men
</P>
<P>
   Gay men are almost twice as likely to smoke cigarettes as men
over all, a new study finds.
</P>
<P>
   The study, by researchers at the University of California at San
Francisco, looked at 2,600 men who described themselves as gay or
bisexual. About 48 percent reported smoking, compared with about 27
percent of all American men.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers said they were not sure how to account for the
disparity. They looked at a variety of factors, including heavy
drinking, frequenting gay bars and being personally affected by
AIDS, and found that this seemed to explain some of the higher
incidence of smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause, they said, the study suggests a need for
antismoking programs that are more effective with gays.
</P>
<P>
   The lead author, Dr. Ron Stall, pointed out that the smoking
rate was highest among younger gay men _ 50 percent for those 18 to
24. That, he said, suggests a health danger that could last for
years.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published in The American Journal of Public Health,
found that although higher educational level was associated with a
lower incidence of smoking, gay men at all educational levels
smoked more than the general male population. Among older gay men,
the smoking rate was lowest.
</P>
<P>
   NOSTRUMS: Recipe for Health: Shaken, Not Stirred
</P>
<P>
   The return of the martini, which with the cigar has become one
of the more dubious symbols of the go-go '90s, has found some
unusual defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian researchers report that after studying a variety of
alcoholic beverages, they found that the martini scored highest for
its antioxidant properties, which researchers believe may help the
body fight everything from cancer to cataracts.
</P>
<P>
   But simply stirring the gin and vermouth, the researchers say,
will not do. They must be shaken, in the manner of a certain
British secret agent.
</P>
<P>
   The study appears in The British Medical Journal's Christmas
issue, which traditionally devotes space to offbeat topics. (Other
articles in the same issue include one study of people who agreed
to have sex in MRI machines, and another of the most common first
names of women seeking treatment for venereal diseases.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, the motivation behind the research was serious, said Dr.
John Trevithick, a professor at the University of Western Ontario.
Alcohol has long been shown to have antioxidant properties, and
Trevithick and his colleagues were testing a variety of beverages.
</P>
<P>
   Why martinis scored so high was unclear, although researchers
believe that much of the antioxidant power comes from the plants
from which they are produced and even the wood casks in which the
beverages are stored.
</P>
<P>
   At some point in the study, Trevithick said, his daughter,
Colleen, who helped with the research before entering UCLA,
suggested comparing stirred martinis with shaken ones. ``We thought
probably the shaken would be just as good,'' he said. To the
researchers' surprise, the difference was significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really not able to explain this,'' Trevithick said.
</P>
<P>
   STAGES: When Specialists Err on Aging Voices
</P>
<P>
   Some elderly people who are given diagnoses of voice or speech
disorders may simply be showing ordinary signs of aging, scientists
say.
</P>
<P>
   A study of 44 men and women aged 70 to 80 detected numerous
changes in their speaking voices.
</P>
<P>
   But the study noted that speech pathologists trying to determine
whether a patient had a voice disorder often relied on tests based
on the voice patterns of young and middle-aged people.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, specialists can wrongly conclude that there is a
problem and prescribe speech therapy, said the report, which was
presented last month to the annual conference of the American
Speech-Language-Hearing Association in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chances are that it is just a part of the aging process,''
said Dr. Steve Xue, an assistant professor of hearing and speech
sciences Ohio University, who wrote the report.
</P>
<P>
   Xue and his colleagues found that among the elderly people they
studied, voices commonly changed. Men's voices, for example,
sometimes became higher, and women's, lower. Study participants
also found that their voices had become harsher or more hoarse, or
that it was harder to keep a stable tone.
</P>
<P>
   LINKS: An Online Aid for Surviving Cancer
</P>
<P>
   More people than ever are surviving cancer, health officials
say; by one estimate, about 8.4 million Americans who have had
cancer are alive today. But from this indisputable good news flows
a host of new challenges for doctors and patients alike, as the
survivors and their families face years of uncertainty and health
concerns that few people without cancer could imagine.
</P>
<P>
   A newly redesigned Web site aims to make these waters easier to
navigate.
</P>
<P>
   The site is an overhaul of one that has been maintained for some
years by the National Cancer Institute's Office of Cancer
Survivorship. It is designed to be of use not just to patients but
to researchers and practicing doctors. Its address is
http://dccps.nci.nih.gov; follow the link to ``Survivorship
Research.''
</P>
<P>
   Although much of the information there is not new, officials
say, it has been reorganized for simplicity. Different forms of
cancer, for example, are given their own sections. And visitors
seeking information about new treatments can read about 1,800
clinical trials. There are also numerous links to other information
sources.
</P>
<P>
   In its old version, the site drew about 5 million visits a
month, officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
