<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4536 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-ODOM-CLIPPERS-2TA     12-20 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ODOM-CLIPPERS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODOM HAS FINALLY FOUND HOME IN NBA 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It is about 15 minutes before tapoff to a
pre-holiday NBA drudgefest, the 4-16 Vancouver Grizzlies visiting
the 4-16 Clippers, and Lamar Odom is joining his Los Angeles
teammates in some final preparatory stretching. Supine on the
Staples Center court, he raises his left leg to its skyscraper
height as a trainer stands on tiptoe to apply pressure to his foot.
Suddenly, Odom shrieks _ not in unbearable pain but in euphoric
recognition. There, by the stanchion to the Clipper basket, he has
just spotted his past innocence.
</P>
<P>
   University of Rhode Island coach Jerry DeGregorio, whose team
has a game at the University of San Francisco the following night,
has made the hour flight, unannounced, to pay a surprise visit to
his 20-year-old protege, who considers him ``like a father to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom bounds to his feet, and with a couple of giant strides, he
leaps into DeGregorio's arms, a 6-foot-10-inch, 220-pound wraith
taking gleeful refuge in the embrace of the much smaller man. They
exchange greetings, Odom plants a quick kiss on DeGregorio's cheek,
and then it's back to business.
</P>
<P>
   DeGregorio does not see a vintage performance by the former Ram.
Odom endures the rookie's crucible of excessive scrutiny by the
referees, drawing foul calls for everything short of blinking, and
he is disqualified late in the game for the first time in his
infant pro career.
</P>
<P>
   But there are highlights. At halftime, DeGregorio applauds as
Odom receives the NBA Co-Rookie of the Month plaque for November,
emblematic of the impact already made by the man-child of promise
in this land. And in the fourth quarter, briefly unshackled, Odom
comes off the bench to offer a glimpse of his preternatural skills
_ fighting inside for a lefthanded bank shot, canning a jumper off
the glass from the right, drilling a cross-court laser pass that
Tyrone Nesby converts into a 3-pointer
</P>
<P>
   _ as the Clippers snap a nine-game losing streak, 102-90.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, it gets even better. Odom spends a precious hour with
his mentor. He presents him with the NBA hardware. ``He gives me
all his trophies,'' says DeGregorio.
</P>
<P>
   And the youngster, who has searched nearly a lifetime for a
father, shows his surrogate that that quest will skip at least a
generation. With the child's mother, Liza Morales, looking on, Odom
cradles his 16-month-old daughter, Destiny, an incandescent smile
creasing his serene features. ``I'll always be there for her,'' he
says. ``When it comes to family, I get serious.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a tableau that is all too brief, the closest Lamar Odom
will get to a college reunion. For one sweet respite, he is able to
satisfy both sides of his ambivalence. &QL; 
 &QL; 
School daze &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If only it were that easy. If only Odom could simultaneously
bestride the Kingston, R.I., campus where he spent two essentially
blissful years and the NBA arenas that have been considered his
inevitable destination since he was an adolescent.
</P>
<P>
   That is impossible, of course, but it didn't ease the conflict
for Odom last spring when first he declared he would leave school
early to become eligible for the draft, then changed his mind, only
to discover that according to NCAA rules, there was no turning back
because he already had retained an agent.
</P>
<P>
   So here he is, the key ingredient in the misbegotten Clippers'
rise to respectability. They are only 6-17after beating visiting
Golden State, 92-91, Friday _ a game Odom won when he banked in an
8-foot runner with 11.9 seconds to play. Odom has played in all 23
games, averaging a team-high 38.7 minutes. He is second on the team
in scoring (16.6 points a game) and assists (3.7), third in
rebounding (7.1) and blocks (1.2).
</P>
<P>
   More than that, he is being hailed as a cosmic prodigy by
virtually everyone who sees him: by his teammates and Clippers vice
president of basketball operations Elgin Baylor, the Hall of Fame
forward; by Clippers television analyst Bill Walton, the Hall of
Fame center and former Celtic; by the Grizzlies' Shareef
Abdur-Rahim, an established All-Star who also left college after
playing just one year; and by the King of LA himself, Lakers center
Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a grand entrance. And yet there is this other world .
. .
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss URI every day,'' Odom says softly. ``Every day when I
wake up, I think about it. But it's human. It's like when you get
divorced _ you don't stop thinking about the divorcee. The way I
look at it, it was a win-all situation. Either I'd still be on a
college campus _ another year of college wouldn't have hurt _ or
I'd be playing basketball at the best level and being well-paid for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The reality isn't as neat as the summation. His hesitant pro
arrival was merely the latest complication Odom has endured since
his parents separated when he was 6, his father left his life, his
mother died when he was 12, and he was raised in New York by his
grandmother, Mildred Mercer. Ever since he was a national schoolboy
prodigy who, because of academic difficulties, attended three high
schools _ in New York City, Troy, N.Y., and finally Milford, Conn.
Ever since he was accepted by the University of Nevada-Las Vegas,
only to be released from his grant-in-aid when Sports Illustrated
raised questions about the validity of his entrance exam scores.
Ever since he called DeGregorio, with whom he had shared a room for
six months while pursuing his high school diploma at St. Thomas
Aquinas in Milford and who had just been hired as new URI head
coach Jim Harrick's assistant, and said, ``Coach, I've got nowhere
to go.'' Ever since Harrick, who had recruited Odom before being
fired as UCLA's coach, and DeGregorio pleaded his case with the
school administration, which admirably disregarded the charges that
it was turning URI into a fleshpot athletic clearinghouse and
admitted him as a nonmatriculating student.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were tough times,'' recalls Odom, who resisted
six-figure pro offers from Europe and the CBA in order to gain
college eligibility. ``I couldn't practice or travel with the team.
I just studied and worked out on my own. It was the first time I
hadn't been part of a team.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was only natural that even when he became part of the URI
team the following year, even as he was becoming the Atlantic 10
Rookie of the Year and leading the Rams into the NCAA tournament,
where they lost in the first round of the Midwest Regional at
Milwaukee, he would be tugged at like a wad of taffy.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the NCAA game, I saw guys in that lobby I'd never seen in
my life,'' says Harrick, now the coach at the University of Georgia
after doing an impression of Odom in miniature, first taking the
job, then deciding to stay at URI, then opting to leave after all.
``It was disgusting. Lamar came up to me and said, `Coach, I've got
cousins here I've never seen before.' He never had a chance to stay
in school. People didn't give him a chance.'' &QL; 
 &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
