A4552 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-CONTACT-LENSES-NY     12-20 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CONTACT-LENSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE SALE OF CONTACT LENSES RAISES HEALTH CONCERNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Utah, Calif., Pa., Ill., Texas) (nk) 
 By SUSAN GILBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buying contact lenses has never been easier. Besides the
traditional outlets, like optometrists' offices and mail order
stores, they can be found on hundreds of Web sites and even at
beauty salons and local flea markets.
</P>
<P>
   But while this explosion of suppliers has held down prices, it
has created a problem, in the view of eye doctors, school nurses
and contact lens manufacturers: Growing numbers of people are
getting contact lenses illegally, without prescriptions, and they
are suffering from health problems as a result.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a number of cases of conjunctivitis in teen-agers
who had gotten contact lenses over the Internet without a
prescription,'' said Dr. Walter M. Fierson, a pediatric
ophthalmologist in Pasadena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Harold P. Koller, an ophthalmologist in suburban
Philadelphia, agreed. ``I'm seeing an increase in problems like
corneal infections,'' he said, adding that many of these patients
admitted that they had either bought their contact lenses without a
prescription or were wearing lenses they had borrowed from friends.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in such patients led Fierson to conduct his own
investigation. He had a part-time employee try to order contact
lenses online. While most of Web sites asked for prescription
information and the name of a doctor, he said, some did not contact
the doctor for verification.
</P>
<P>
   Fierson said the lack of verification was especially common when
his staff member tried to order cosmetic contact lenses, which have
become extremely popular in recent years, especially with
teen-agers. Such lenses change the color or appearance of the eyes
without necessarily correcting vision.
</P>
<P>
   Though the cosmetic lenses do not correct vision, they are still
considered prescription devices under federal law and cannot be
sold without a prescription indicating the size and shape of the
eyes. Lenses that fit improperly can deprive the cornea of oxygen
and cause corneal abrasions, leaving the eyes vulnerable to
infections that can cause permanent vision loss, doctors say.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers are at especially high risk for two reasons. Doctors
say they are more likely than adults to buy the lenses without a
prescription. And being teen-agers, they can be careless about
hygiene: wearing lenses for too long, neglecting to sterilize them,
even swapping them with friends.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how many outlets sell contact lenses without
verifying prescriptions. But isolated investigations have borne out
Fierson's findings. Last summer Keith Cole of Austin, an employee
of the Texas Optometry Board, clicked on 1-800 Contacts, a Web site
that sells lenses.
</P>
<P>
   He typed in his order, gave his name, address and billing
information and a doctor's name and phone number, and the lenses
arrived by mail five days later. Cole says he got the lenses
without being asked to provide a written prescription from a
licensed physician.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of Cole's accusations, the Texas Optometry Board
filed a lawsuit against 1-800 Contacts in October, saying it had
illegally sold contact lenses without a prescription. The Kansas
State Board of Examiners of Optometry has filed a similar lawsuit
against the company.
</P>
<P>
   The company denies these accusations. ``We call the doctor in
every case,'' said Jonathan Coon, the chief executive of 1-800
Contacts, based in Draper, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   The Wesley Jessen Corp., which makes Wild Eyes, a leading brand
of cosmetic lenses, hired a private investigator to order its
lenses from Web sites, beauty salons and flea markets. The company
says it has found dozens of outlets selling its lenses without
verifying prescription information.
</P>
<P>
   Companies found to be selling Wild Eyes illegally get a letter
from Wesley Jessen's lawyers. ``I send letters every week,'' said
Martha Brecher, a lawyer for the company, which is based in Des
Plaines, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, Wesley Jessen's lawyers wrote to two prominent
Internet companies, Yahoo and eBay, after finding that contact
lenses were being auctioned on their Web sites. Both companies
stopped the auctions when they learned that selling contact lenses
without a prescription was illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Now that doctors are seeing harmful consequences from the
illegal trade in contact lenses, health organizations are beginning
to take action. The Contact Lens Council, a trade association, is
about to propose legislation to Congress that would require a hard
copy of a prescription before contact lenses could be sold. And the
American Academy of Pediatrics is preparing guidelines for primary
care physicians to use in educating teen-agers about the safe use
of contact lenses, since they are the prime market for cosmetic
contact lenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The AAP wants to get the message to teen-agers not to share
contact lenses or get them without a prescription,'' Koller said.
``And if they have lenses that they got without a prescription, we
want to tell them to have them checked out by a doctor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
