<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY ANY OTHER NAME
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Note publishable editor's note at end.) 
(nk) 
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY 
 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What is the difference between dentists with D.D.S. after
their names and those with D.M.D.?
</P>
<P>
   A. There is no difference between the two degrees, according to
the education division of the American Dental Association in
Chicago. One stands for doctor of dental surgery and the other
means doctor of dental medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Each is a degree awarded upon graduation from a dental school
after studying to become a general dentist.
</P>
<P>
   The two kinds of dentists have the same education, but
universities have the prerogative to determine which degree is
awarded, much as a bachelor's degree in the arts can be a Bachelor
of Arts (B.A.), or in modern Latin, Artium Baccalaureus (A.B.).
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen institutions grant D.M.D. degrees and 36 grant D.D.S.
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, dental schools require three or more years of
undergraduate education plus four years of dental school to
graduate and become a general dentist.
</P>
<P>
   Additional postgraduate training is required to become a dental
specialist, like a periodontist or orthodontist. The training
generally requires two to four years, depending on the specialty.
</P>
<P>
   The specialists may be granted certificates or master's degrees,
again, depending on the institution they attend, but it is up to
the schools to decide what additional ``paper'' they provide, and
the degree or certificate is not mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   There are nine specialities recognized by the ADA: pediatric
dentistry, periodontics, prosthodontics, oral and maxillofacial
surgery, oral and maxillofacial pathology, dental public health,
orthodontics, and oral and maxillofacial radiology.
</P>
<P>
   The additional training can be quite extensive. For example,
programs for a combined specialty in prosthodontics (the
replacement of missing teeth) and maxillofacial prosthetics (the
use of artificial substitutes for missing jaw and facial
structures) generally take 45 months.
</P>
<P>
   The ADA maintains a Web site for more information on dental
careers and other oral health topics: www.ada.org. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Readers are invited to submit questions by mail to
Question, Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd Street,
New York, N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to question(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Questions of general interest will be answered in this column,
but requests for medical advice cannot be honored and unpublished
letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
