<HEADER>
A4558 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BREAST-CANCER-2TA     12-20 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BREAST-CANCER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAST CANCER RISKS CAN START IN THE WOMB 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Mass., Ala., Calif., N.C., Japan) (nk) 
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeking to better understand the origins of breast cancer,
researchers have begun to look as far back as the womb to identify
prenatal factors and childhood experiences, including birth weight,
diet and exercise patterns, that may affect a woman's risk of
developing breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Though the data are preliminary, the relationships complex and
the conclusions tentative, the emerging findings may help to
explain long-suspected influences on breast cancer risk like early
puberty, the age of a woman at the end of her first full-term
pregnancy and the amount of fat and calories in her diet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evidence is accumulating, though the research is still in its
very early phases, that the periods before and soon after birth,
childhood and early adolescence are much more important to breast
cancer risk than had been appreciated,'' said Dr. Karin B. Michels,
clinical epidemiologist at Harvard Medical School and Brigham and
Women's Hospital in Boston. ``Just as heart disease has its origins
in childhood, breast cancer is not just an adult disease.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, there is a strong link between high-fat diets in
the population and high rates of breast cancer, but at best a weak
relationship to the amount of fat an individual woman consumes as
an adult. But the effects of fat in a child's diet may explain why
Japanese women who emigrate to the United States maintain their low
risk of breast cancer, while the risk faced by their American-born
daughters and granddaughters approaches that of white American
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Migration studies reveal that racial factors play only a minor
role and that environmental or lifestyle factors, or both, are far
more important,'' Dr. Jaak Ph. Janssens, a Belgian expert on
hormonal factors in cancer wrote in an article in a recent issue of
the journal Nutrition Today.
</P>
<P>
   Janssens, who studies hormones and breast cancer at the L.
Willems Institute and Limburg University Center in Diepenbeek,
Belgium, suggested that breast cancer risk might in part be
determined by the kind of diet a woman consumed as a child and even
what her mother ate during pregnancy _ if the diets were high in
calories, and especially if they were rich in animal fat.
</P>
<P>
   Animal studies have also suggested that a prenatal diet rich in
polyunsaturated fats, which includes most vegetable oils, can
increase the susceptibility of fetal breast tissue to the
cancer-stimulating effects of estrogen. Several studies in adults
have indicated that monounsaturated fats like olive or canola oil
are protective.
</P>
<P>
   The high-calorie diet typically consumed by Americans fosters
the production of estrogens associated with early puberty and early
menarche, both of which are already linked to breast cancer risk.
</P>
<P>
   Exposure to protective or harmful substances soon after birth
may be particularly critical. Janssens said newborn rats treated
with genistein, an estrogen in soy, were less susceptible to
carcinogens that caused breast cancer and had a reduced rate of
mammary tumors throughout life. He suggested that part of this
protection might result from genistein's effects on the growth of
mammary tissue in newborns, resulting in structures that were less
susceptible to cancer. This finding may explain why the protective
effect of the Asian diet appears to occur early in a girl's life.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern is the exposure of newborns to environmental
chemicals that simulate the action of estrogens. For example,
polychlorinated biphenyls, or PCB's, are weak estrogens that can
accumulate in body fat and are passed to nursing newborns in breast
milk. These chemicals' effects on cancer risk are unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Walter Rogan, an epidemiologist at the National Institute of
Environmental Health Sciences in Research Triangle Park, N.C., said
studies of the effects of PCB's on breast cancer risk had produced
inconsistent findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese have high levels of PCB's in their bodies, but
they don't have high levels of breast cancer,'' Rogan said in an
interview. He added that DDE, a breakdown product of DDT, was a
more potent estrogen than PCB's and that high levels of DDE were
found in China, India and Mexico, where breast cancer rates are
low.
</P>
<P>
   The effects of diet on breast cancer risk may well start in the
womb. Based on data from the continuing Nurses' Health Study at
Harvard, Michels, the Harvard epidemiologist, and colleagues found
a clear link between birth weight and later risk of breast cancer:
The bigger the baby, the greater the risk. Since a baby's birth
weight is largely determined by how much weight a woman gains
during pregnancy, Michels said, she is concerned about the current
tendency to allow pregnant women to gain a great deal of weight.
</P>
<P>
   Also worrisome, for more reasons than a possible increase in
breast cancer risk, is the precipitous rise in childhood obesity
and a concurrent decline in physical activity in the United States.
Both body fat and inactivity can increase blood levels of estrogen.
Janssens explained that for estrogen to activate cell growth, it
must circulate freely in the blood serum or be bound to a blood
protein, albumin. Estrogens that are bound to a protein called sex
hormone binding globulin, or SHBG, are not biologically active.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nutrition can induce changes in the fraction of estrogens
bound to the serum proteins and, therefore, can enhance or decrease
the action of estrogens on highly susceptible target organs'' like
a woman's breasts, Janssens wrote. ``Fruits and vegetables, which
seem to increase SHBG binding, are protective with regard to
estrogen stimulation.'' Animal fat, he wrote, decreases this
binding, and thus increases the amount of estrogen available to
stimulate tissue growth.
</P>
<P>
   Janssens also noted that obese girls and women were less able to
bind estrogens and that extra estrogens were produced in their body
fat, resulting in more estrogen freely circulating in blood and
able to stimulate breast tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``High calorie diets that are low in fruits and vegetables can
induce puberty at an earlier age and facilitate estrogen action on
the highly susceptible target organ of the breast,'' he said. ``The
available data suggest that such a dietary pattern should be
avoided for many reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Vigorous activity not only promotes leanness and delays puberty,
it also slows the onset of menarche with its high levels of
estrogen and diminishes the frequency of ovulation in menstruating
girls, which also lowers exposure to hormones that stimulate the
breast. Delayed menarche has long been known to protect against
breast cancer by reducing exposure to estrogen.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There is evidence that regular exercise, especially in youth,
can reduce breast cancer risk. In 1985, Dr. Rose Frisch of Harvard
University published a tantalizing finding: Radcliffe graduates who
had been student athletes had significantly lower rates of breast
cancer as adults than did their less active classmates.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits to the breast of exercise in adult women are less
clear, although a study of more than 1,000 women by Dr. Leslie
Bernstein, preventive medicine specialist at the University of
Southern California in Los Angeles, found that premenopausal women
who engaged in just three hours of moderate exercise a week had a
30 percent lower risk of breast cancer and those who got four or
more hours of exercise each week had a 50 percent lower risk.
</P>
<P>
   Those who benefited most, experiencing 60 percent less breast
cancer than inactive women, had been active in their teens and
early 20s as well as later in life.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the less estrogen a woman is exposed to _ from fetal
life through childhood and adulthood _ the lower her risk of
developing breast cancer. Early menopause, which results from a
loss of estrogens produced by the ovaries, has long been known to
reduce breast cancer risk. Women whose ovaries are removed in their
30s and who take no hormone replacement have up to 75 percent less
breast cancer than women who undergo natural menopause at around
age 50, Janssens noted.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Malcolm Pike, a hormone researcher at the University of
Southern California in Los Angeles, said in an interview that
Japanese women on a traditional low-fat, high-fiber diet routinely
produced 25 percent less estradiol than American women did.
Estradiol is an estrogen that is considered an important promoter
of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Pike suggested that American women might be able to achieve the
Japanese pattern of estrogen production and low breast cancer risk
by adopting, from childhood on, a diet that derived less than 10
percent of its calories from fat and that was at least twice as
rich in fiber as the current American diet.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Americans derive about 34 percent of their calories
from fat, much of it animal fat, and few American women consume
less than 20 percent fat calories at any stage of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could get rid of 85 percent of American breast cancer by
starting with 10-year-olds,'' Pike said, ``keeping them on a
low-fat, high-fiber diet, exercising them heavily and keeping them
slim.''
</P>
<P>
   Some experts maintain that Asian women are protected by their
lifelong high intake of soy, which is rich in weak plant estrogens
_ isoflavones like genistein _ that may block the action of a
woman's own estrogen. Pike said the jury was still out on that
question.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark Messina and colleagues at the University of Alabama in
Birmingham suggested that soy might be protective in part because
it increased the length of a woman's menstrual cycle, which is
associated with a lower risk of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But in adults, Pike said, studies of soy's effects on breast
cancer had produced conflicting results, with some studies
suggesting that plant-based estrogens, especially in large
quantities, might promote, not prevent, breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he suggested: ``Soy in the Asian diet may just be a
marker substance for a diet that is very low in animal fat. At this
point, we just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Other factors that seem to reduce breast cancer risk are
pregnancy at an early age and prolonged nursing. But the experts
concede that the age of a woman at the end of her first pregnancy
(if indeed she gets pregnant), how long she can breast-feed and the
age at which she undergoes menopause are less amenable to
modification than eating and exercise habits.
</P>
<P>
   Until more conclusive data emerges, Michels and Pike suggested
that the best way for women to reduce their risk of breast cancer
might be to stay thin, eat a very low-fat diet and get plenty of
physical exercise _ from the womb to the grave.
</P>
<P>
   Janssens advised, ``Even small changes in overall intake of
estrogenic substances, decreases in animal fat consumption and
increases in fruit and vegetable fiber could result in dramatic
changes in breast cancer risk later in life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
