<HEADLINE>
WHAT 3 FAMOUS NONHUMANS WANT FOR CHRISTMAS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Wednesday, Dec. 22)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christmas wish list of some of America's most famous (nonhuman)
celebrities as told to the psychic who seems to be in a trance 24
hours a day, Madame Davida:
</P>
<P>
   Tony the Tiger
</P>
<P>
   _ Anything but Frosted Flakes. They may have been GREAT! the
first time, but now all they do is hurt my teeth. Besides, I'm a
carnivore. I eat meat, not sugary cereals. I watched ``Who Wants to
be a Millionaire'' the other night and I must say that Regis
Philbin looks mighty tasty. Final answer? Actually, no. Some people
might miss Regis. Give me Martha Stewart instead. Maybe with a
clove-studded baked apple in her mouth. That would add a nice,
festive touch.
</P>
<P>
   Lassie
</P>
<P>
   _ How about a new family to live with? You say that's a cold,
disloyal thing for a dog to ask for? I'll tell you what, pal. You
live with Timmy and the rest of the Martin family for 24 hours and
you'll be begging for adoption.
</P>
<P>
   That Timmy, I don't know. Maybe they dropped him on his head
when he was a baby or maybe it's a genetic thing, but the boy ain't
right. All he's got to do is walk out the door and _ BOOM! _ he
either falls down a mine shaft or gets cornered by a mountain lion.
Or both. You'd think his parents would take him aside and say,
``Son, you need to watch where the hell you're walking. This is
getting old.'' But that never happens. In fact, if it weren't for
me barking like crazy and pawing at their legs, I doubt they'd ever
realize Timmy was missing. These people are dense, I'm telling you.
</P>
<P>
   More than once I've had to type them a letter:
</P>
<P>
   Yo, Martins! Your doofus son, Timmy, has fallen down a mine
shaft. Again! There are currently six mountain lions, two grizzly
bears and a rather confused elk waiting in line to eat him. I
realize that you are very busy right now, watching the dust motes
float across the sunbeams and everything, so if it's OK with you, I
will go rescue him all by myself. Again!
</P>
<P>
   Love, Lassie
</P>
<P>
   P.S _ You people need counseling. Seriously.
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. _ I'm leaving you the first chance I get.
</P>
<P>
   Wile E. Coyote (Hard-Headipus ravenus)
</P>
<P>
   _ Money. Send me money. Lots of it. I'm drowning in debt. The
Acme Corp. sent me a letter the other day threatening legal action
if I don't pay up. Seems I owe them $76,304.87 for various products
I've bought from them over the years including the Giant Slingshot,
Rocket-Powered Sled, Rocket-Powered Roller Skates, Self-Guided
Aerial Bomb, ``Little Giant'' Firecracker, Spring-Loaded Shoes,
Giant Kite and various catapults, harpoons, robots and explosives.
</P>
<P>
   All of these products, as you surely know, not only failed to
perform as advertised but caused me grievous physical harm,
including but not limited to fractures; contusions; abrasions;
severe singeing of the hair of the head, neck and muzzle;
flattening of the cranium; spinal compression and a compound
fracture of the left ear, causing it to dangle with a creaking
noise.
</P>
<P>
   My medical bills, as of today, total $3,894,211, all of which
falls on me since I am self-employed and not eligible for Workers
Compensation.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the not-insignificant matter of my attorneys' fees
as I seek (thus far unsuccessfully) compensation from the Acme
Corp. for personal injuries, loss of business income and mental
suffering resulting from Acme's gross negligence.
</P>
<P>
   This bill, at present, totals roughly $800,000, give or take a
hundred-thousand, bringing the total bill to $4,770,515.87.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't send me any money, the head of the Road Runner
(Velocitus delectiblus) would also be nice.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
