<HEADER>
A4562 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-ANALY     12-20 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-ANALYSIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ANALYSIS: HOLD THE CHAMPAGNE, RUSSIA'S NOT OUT OF THE WOODS YET
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Charles W. Holmes 
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Kremlin on Monday called Sunday's parliamentary
elections ``a peaceful revolution.'' Analysts said that voters
opted for political stability. And international lenders said the
outcome means better times ahead for the country's crippled
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that the success of political moderates in the
elections has given fresh hope to Russia's long-stalled efforts to
improve its unstable market economy and corruption-riddled
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that while the atmosphere has changed, the
political landscape remains unpredictable and treacherous,
particularly as Russia gears up for a more momentous election next
summer _ the race to replace President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the new Duma and the prospects of political and
economic progress in Russia rest almost exclusively with Yeltsin's
chosen successor, Prime Minister Vladimir Putin, and the war he has
waged against separatists in the breakaway republic of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   At 47, Putin is Russia's most popular politician this decade and
the man most likely to succeed the highly unpopular Yeltsin as
president.
</P>
<P>
   Voters gave stronger-than-expected support to four moderate and
pro-reform parties who will control about half the seats in the
450-member Duma, the lower house. It was a clear victory for
Yeltsin and the Kremlin, whose new Unity Party finished a close
second to Russia's largest party, the Communists.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin's success came largely because Russians admire and
support Putin. His popular appeal has come, in turn, from his
leadership of the war against Islamic guerrillas in Chechnya, a
brutal conflict that large numbers of Russians view as a just fight
against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   With so much staked on Putin and the war, the possibilities of
what could happen between now and the presidential elections in
June are daunting. Consider what took place over the last half-year
in Russia to effect the parliamentary elections: Five months ago,
Putin was an unknown ex-spy and bureaucrat before Yeltsin appointed
him prime minister. Four months ago, the war in Chechnya was
dormant. And three months ago, the Unity party did not exist.
</P>
<P>
   Among the risks ahead for Russia's political stability:
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA. The popular war served as the key tool for the
Kremlin, building support for Unity and crippling opposition
efforts to focus the campaign on Russia's meager economy and
Yeltsin's ineffective leadership.
</P>
<P>
   . The three-month military campaign has been successful so far.
But Russian troops have yet to capture the capital, Grozny, and
they risk attacks from determined fighters dug in to positions in
the city and in Chechnya's southern mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the longer Russian forces remain in Chechnya, the
greater their risk of losses, and the chance that public opinion
could turn against the war and Putin.
</P>
<P>
   YELTSIN. Putin was appointed in August. He was Yeltsin's fifth
prime minister in 17 months, compounding at the time the political
uncertainty that had existed since Russia's economic collapse of
mid-1998. Analysts say Putin is safe from sacking while he remains
high in the polls. But many analysts believe he would be out should
the war turn for the worse, or should Kremlin insiders feel that he
would not look after their power and business interests as
president.
</P>
<P>
   Under the constitution, most power is in the hands of the
erratic and ailing Yeltsin, 68. He is surrounded and supported by a
group of influential business tycoons and close advisers _ known as
``the family'' _ who have bent and swayed policy to suit their
needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This vote concentrates an awful lot of power in the existing
elite. The issue is really what they do with that power _ whether
they are going to abuse it in the way they did from 1996 to
mid-1998 or whether they are going to be more responsible with
it,'' said Tom Adshead, political analyst at Troika Dialog
brokerage in Moscow
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS. Despite the election of Unity and other centrist
parties, the pro-reform groups may be unable to form a workable
union in the Duma. Or if they forge a pro-government coalition,
rivalries among personalities who have their own presidential
aspirations could hamper progress.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest chance for improvement, analysts say, again rests
with Putin. His endorsement of Unity was key to the new party's
election success. Using similar leverage, Putin could force the
Duma to action if parliament members felt they would incur the
wrath of the public for countering the widely admired prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, everything depends now on Putin's rating,'' said the
newspaper Izvestiya in a commentary Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
