r a BC-SF-MAYOR-HNS &LR;      12-20 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-MAYOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MAYOR SAYS HE WON'T SEEK ANOTHER POST WHILE IN OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ANASTASIA HENDRIX  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mayor Willie Brown, who was forced into a
run-off election against a write-in candidate last month, says he
will not run for higher office for as long as he is mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``My history has been one of staying put,'' Brown, 65, said.
``When I'm turned out, there may be an opportunity to do something
else. But I'm not one of those politicians who's constantly looking
for the next rung.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a Democrat who led the state Assembly before running for
mayor in 1995, said the law should be changed to force politicians
running for another office to first resign from the job they have.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, you would find most of us real restrained about
how we exercise our options,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's hour-long appearance Sunday at Grace Episcopal
Cathedral's Gresham Hall was part of a series of
cathedral-sponsored forums. About 200 people attended the event,
including many who stood in the back after the chairs were filled.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, dressed in a dapper chocolate-brown suit and sitting in
front of a crimson curtain, conversed briefly with the Very Rev.
Alan Jones before a handful of audience members were allowed to
pose polite inquiries into the mayor's plans for the city in his
second term. The questions largely revolved around Brown's plans to
address concerns such as housing costs and the plight of the
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   His biggest goal, the mayor said, is to ``have the city be
affordable for all people,'' whether it be access to housing,
medical care or the public education of their choice. If he can do
that, he said, he will have ``kept the faith'' of the people who
voted for him.
</P>
<P>
   Board of Supervisors President Tom Ammiano, also a Democrat,
surprised Brown and two other leading candidates by finishing
second in the general election last month, forcing Brown into a
run-off contest because no candidate won more than 50 percent of
the vote. But the incumbent rallied, beating Ammiano 60 percent to
40 percent in the Dec. 14 election.
</P>
<P>
   Brown also defended his pro-development positions to one woman
in the audience who complained that too many lofts and chain stores
are crowding her neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lofts would not exist in this city if there was not a loft
market,'' he said, explaining his support of such developments and
the ``dot.com kids'' who inhabit them.
</P>
<P>
   Technology workers and other newcomers pour millions of dollars
into the economy, Brown said, helping to fund dozens of improvement
projects. Besides, he said, not a single loft has replaced any
residential housing in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot roll up the drawbridge, seed the moat with piranhas
and go inside the castle and say that no one else should enter,''
he added. ``This is a city.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown received a standing ovation from nearly half the crowd at
the end of the event, and about a dozen people huddled around him
afterward to shake his hand, congratulate him on his mayoral
victory or have a personal conversation with him.
</P>
<P>
   David Campbell was one of those who approached Brown to tell him
of his concern that some longtime San Francisco families can no
longer afford to live in the city. Brown assured him that would be
a major focus of his administration in the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought of him as a very personable person, but
I'd never had the chance to speak with him one-on-one,'' said
Campbell, a 37-year-old San Francisco resident who works for a
nonprofit organization in Palo Alto.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 1738EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
