<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4564 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p BC-KEYES-PROFILE-2000(2T     12-20 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEYES-PROFILE-2000(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEYES SCORING IN DEBATES, NOT POLLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ For the rest of the presidential candidates
at the televised gathering, part of last week's Republican debate
was a discussion about the merits of ethanol.
</P>
<P>
   Not for Alan Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   No, the argument over subsidies for farmers who convert corn
into fuel, he said, ignores a much larger problem, one that strikes
at the very heart of America's moral courage and decency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Folks look at the family farming system like the only thing we
get from family farms is the food,'' said Keyes, his soft voice
belying the explosive oratory that followed.
</P>
<P>
   The other candidates, having grown accustomed to the eloquent
but piercing admonitions from the former Reagan administration
official, knew that fireworks were on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes' voice dripped with indignation: ``We lose the family
farm,'' he boomed, ``and we lose the nursery of America's moral
character.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where did we get the young men and women who were willing to
sacrifice themselves in battle, rise to the extraordinary tests of
war every time we asked them to, have the courage that used to be
restricted supposedly only to aristocrats?'' he asked, providing
the answer after hardly a breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found them in the fields of America, behind the plow,
nurtured in the family farms of this country. We cannot let that
die, any more than we can let America's heart and individuality and
courage die.''
</P>
<P>
   It was classic Keyes: taking an arcane subject and turning it
into an emotion-packed, crowd-pleasing pronouncement. Mesmerizing
speeches roll effortlessly from his tongue.
</P>
<P>
   That Keyes is an effective debater is hardly a subject for
debate. Even a senior adviser to Gov. George W. Bush, the GOP
presidential front-runner, acknowledges that the former radio
commentator blows his competition out of the water in contests such
as last week's debate in Des Moines.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were about how well you do in debates,'' the adviser
said afterward, ``he'd be 50 points ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes is not 50 points ahead, and winning presidential contests
entails more than scoring points in debates. Keyes barely registers
in many polls across the nation, and his last campaign finance
statement showed him with about $50,000 available to spend.
</P>
<P>
   But don't talk about polls to Keyes, or to his small but loyal
band of supporters. He calls opinion surveys ``fiction'' and said
the news media's fascination with them is ``dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in the end they (polls) can become an instrument for
turning our electoral system into a sham,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keyes was born in New York City into a family steeped in
military tradition and order. His father was an Army sergeant, and
the family moved around a lot. The future presidential candidate
grew up in segregationist Georgia and spent time in Italy and
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from Robert G. Coleman High School in San Antonio
while his father was stationed at Fort Sam Houston. Even then an
award-winning debater, Keyes said he was politically curious from
an early age, even though his parents were not active on that
front.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes briefly attended Cornell University but left, partially
because he opposed the Vietnam War protests and the forceful
takeover of a campus building by rifle-toting black students.
According to college pal Marlo Lewis, Keyes received death threats
for speaking out against his fellow black students.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, whose wife works for the Keyes 2000 campaign, recalls the
young Keyes as ``brilliant, original and funny, with sort of just a
great love of life.''
</P>
<P>
   He also remembers that Keyes, a talented singer and musician,
briefly considered a career as an opera singer and toyed with the
idea of following his father into the military. The elder Keyes
persuaded him not to.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes, who received student deferments and was not drafted into
service in Vietnam after receiving a high lottery number, never
served in the military.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lewis, Keyes' father told him, ``I fought in three
wars so you wouldn't have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes received his bachelor of arts degree from Harvard
University in 1972 and his doctorate from Harvard in 1979, then
joined the U.S. diplomatic service. He served a stint as U.S. vice
consul in Bombay, India, where he met Jocelyn Marcel. They married
and have three children.
</P>
<P>
   While in the diplomatic service, Keyes was noticed by Jeane
Kirkpatrick, then the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations. She
helped get him appointed U.S. ambassador to the U.N. Economic and
Social Council, on which he served from 1983 to 1985.
</P>
<P>
   He was then named assistant secretary of state for international
organizations; he clashed with a superior, whom he accused of
treating him in a racially demeaning fashion. The official denied
the allegation.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes also became a chief spokesman for the Reagan
administration's policy of ``constructive engagement'' with South
Africa, meaning that he opposed sanctions against the
white-minority government.
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   He remains unapologetic for that role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that it represents a very sound approach to those
societies that are open to our influence,'' he said, calling South
Africa ``relatively free.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were all kinds of bad disparities and oppressions for
blacks, but you did have access to people, you did have access to
newspapers, you did have access to labor unions, you did have an
ability to influence the society through its internal economic
workings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly added that the approach would not work in a place
such as China, where, he said, communist dictators deny basic
freedoms, ``play us for fools'' and repress their people with U.S.
complicity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keyes developed his first taste for election campaigns when he
was recruited by Maryland Republicans to run against Democratic
U.S. Sen. Paul Sarbanes in 1988. He garnered 40 percent of the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, he again won the GOP nomination, but this time
ran against Sen. Barbara Mikulski and got 29 percent of the vote.
He was harshly criticized that year for taking the unusual step of
paying himself a monthly salary of $8,500 from campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   He defended the practice but abandoned it in both of his
presidential races _ in 1996 and this year.
</P>
<P>
   A ferocious opponent of abortion, Keyes argues that the United
States is in a serious moral crisis, and he does not miss an
opportunity to cast political dialogue in those absolutist terms.
</P>
<P>
   During the exchange in Des Moines, for example, he took a shot
at Bush's ``leave no child behind,'' slogan, declaring: ``We are
not leaving unborn children behind. We are killing them.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes that abortion should be illegal in all cases except
to save the life of the mother.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes also favors abolishing the income tax, which he would
replace with a national sales tax that would provide exemptions for
certain basic items, such as food, medicine and clothing.
</P>
<P>
   That, he says, would allow people to gain control of the money
they earn by consuming less.
</P>
<P>
   His solution for campaign finance reform is similarly audacious:
allow only people who can vote to contribute _ meaning no money
from labor unions, corporations or political action committees _ at
any level they wish.
</P>
<P>
   But Keyes rejects the notion that he is calling for radical
reform, because ``in most cases they're simply a return to the
fundamental principles of this country.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A staunch foe of race-based affirmative action, Keyes said he
possibly benefited from such programs as a college student,
although he calls that point ``irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of people who benefited from segregation. Did
that mean that they should have supported its perpetuation? Once
you know that something is an injustice, you move to stop it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes has not hesitated to criticize the news media for what he
calls institutional prejudice, complaining that outlets have
repeatedly left his name out of news stories because they can't
adjust to a black politician who is a conservative Republican.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent appearance on Fox's ``Hannity and Colmes'' show,
Keyes accused host Alan Colmes of bias for applauding his
oratorical skills, comparing the compliment to saying, ``Oh, he
dances real well.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Keyes has often cited his stellar debate
performances _ including surveys showing that voters judged him the
winner _ as proof that he is the best candidate.
</P>
<P>
   After the Des Moines appearance, Keyes told reporters that his
strong showing has begun to affect the race. The other candidates
have begun appropriating his ideas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take great pleasure and pride in the fact that the other
candidates are, yes, learning how to talk about these serious
issues from me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But wouldn't you rather have the master as president of the
United States?'' Keyes asked. ``Wouldn't you rather have the
instructor as the leader rather than those who have followed his
lead?''
</P>
<P>
   That depends on whom you ask.
</P>
<P>
   As Keyes hurried out of the downtown Des Moines civic center to
an array of TV trucks, one of them waiting to beam live images of
him across the nation, a young college student stopped to pay him a
familiar compliment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alan Keyes!'' shrieked Liz Crokin, 20. ``You're an amazing
orator.'' Keyes quietly thanked her and stepped in front of the
camera.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whom she's voting for, Crokin said, ``Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think Keyes is a great speaker,'' she said. ``He's
just so extreme sometimes, it seems.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
