   And the professor's voice flutters when she speaks of e-mail and
her marriage. Andrews commutes between the Delaware campus and her
home in Maine. Her husband frequently travels. So for them, Andrews
says, the blinking cursor is the ``new hearth,'' with a ``seductive
pull,'' the place where the small details of life are passed back
and forth.
</P>
<P>
   ``E-mail is the tie that binds,'' Andrews says. ``We feel close
because we can send e-mail. My eyes light up when I look at my
index and there's a message from him.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, there's no real mystery to this communication
revolution. E-mail is cheap. It's easy, missives constructed in the
flash of a few keystrokes, and zipped away, all at the convenience
of the sender. Same for replies. No more untimely phone calls from
old friends who want to catch up, just when the third period of the
televised hockey game begins, or the latest episode of ``ER''
reaches its dramatic crescendo.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, through e-mail, latent letter writers are flexing
their literary muscles. Even those who don't write for a living are
finding new pleasure in the well-crafted sentence, or the thought
or feeling eloquently conveyed. The letter, once languishing on
societal life support, now seems as fit and vital as a yearling.
</P>
<P>
   Writer Adam Gopnik goes so far as to proclaim e-mail ``the
literary event of the late century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, even the most literate of us wrote maybe a half
dozen letters a year; the rest of our lives took place on the
telephone. ... Yet it seems a good bet that in 200 years people
will be reading someone's collected e-mail the way we read Edmund
Wilson's letters or Pepys' diaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``... multitudes have found a nearly forgotten friendship
suddenly made intimate again, because of e-mail, and are attentive
once more to their sentences.''
</P>
<P>
   But I submit that the real explanation behind e-mail's stunning
emergence is something more subtle than the cost of it, or ease, or
the bliss of self-discovered e-mail poets. Instead, the real
explanation for its popularity is e-mail's relative anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Admit it, for most of us, face-to-face communication remains one
of life's most chronically stressful endeavors. We are tyrannized
by our conversation partner's nonverbal cues _ the facial
expression, the body language, the tone of voice. We as a species
desperately aim to please, and if a furrowed brow indicates that's
not happening, well, you know the feeling.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail removes the threat of the furrowed brow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The anonymity thing; it's kind of like talking to someone in
the dark,'' says Amanda Hutchens, an e-mail devotee from Fort
Worth, Texas. ``You can share more honestly. I prefer doing it that
way. I don't see disdain in the face or in the eyes or anything
else. There's no judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 1744EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4571 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-EMAIL-REVOLUTION-2000     12-20 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMAIL-REVOLUTION-2000(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: no judgment. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gopnik concurs with the anonymity theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new appeal of e-mail is the old appeal of print,'' he
writes. ``It isn't instant; it isn't immediate; it isn't in your
face. Written language gives you a hat and a Groucho nose and
glasses; it's you there, but not quite you. E-mail has succeeded
brilliantly for the same reason that videophone failed miserably:
What we actually want from our exchanges is the minimum contact
commensurate with the need to connect with other people.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Which leads finally to e-mail's annoyances, pitfalls and
limitations.
</P>
<P>
   First, to get to the heartwarming personal message, we
invariably must wade through the electronic junk mail, called spam.
Between 15 and 30 percent of the e-mail received by Americans
online is spam, and the problem is likely to get worse, according
to a recent article in ``The Boston Globe.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a whole new set of etiquette questions generated by the
e-mail emergence, causing Judith Martin, aka Miss Manners, to
devote several columns to the topic. An e-mail message bears the
formal weight of a postcard, Miss Manners says, so if you wouldn't
deliver tragic or deeply unpleasant tidings by postcard, neither
should e-mail be put to that use. Nor are e-mail messages
substitutes for greeting cards.
</P>
<P>
   Nuance is often a casualty of e-mail. Many an ironic gibe,
delivered online, has been misinterpreted, with painful
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   And then this troubling notion: The only real antidote to human
loneliness is face-to-face, or at least voice-to-voice, human
interaction, however daunting those interactions might be. E-mail,
then, is ultimately left wanting _ appetizer before the main meal.
In a perfect world, e-mail is just the precursor to the moment when
we swallow hard and actually call another human, or visit in
person.
</P>
<P>
   Making up online with your wife is one thing, but warmth and
companionship when together at home is the whole point. Deep and
abiding friendships require more than keyboard greetings. Another
e-mailer, Leslye Rood, of Tulsa, says that a few weeks ago, she
reconnected via e-mail with a close friend in Paris. That reunion,
like millions of others these days, might never have occurred
without the blinking cursor, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two of us did reconnect and did a little catching up''
with e-mail,) Rood says. ``But once the connection was made, e-mail
didn't fulfill our needs. We needed to talk. I needed to hear her
laugh, which is low and deep and round, and that fantastic French
accent which you don't get on e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   At least not yet. In a few years, the way these things move,
maybe French accents will be part of the package. For now we get to
share the little details with friends and family near and far, with
only a few keystrokes and for almost no charge. That is more than
we had before, much more, come to think of it.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
