<HEADER>
A4572 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-Y2K-TERRORISM21-COX     12-20 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-TERRORISM21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STATE DEPARTMENT: Y2K MAY ATTRACT TERRORISTS
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Terrorists may strike during the millennium
rollover to take advantage of media attention focused on the
``Y2K'' computer problem, a top State Department official warned
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Pickering, undersecretary of state for political affairs,
also said some terrorist leaders may feel that victims will be more
vulnerable if computer problems hinder authorities' ability to
respond to an attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have individuals around the world and leaders of terrorist
groups. ... who would seek to exploit, in their view, a period when
they might feel world attention was focused either in the press on
events going on around the world or that there were weaknesses that
could be exploited,'' Pickering said at a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks came as other federal officials responded to last
week's arrest of an Algerian man trying to smuggle explosives into
Washington state from Canada:
</P>
<P>
   _ U.S. Customs Commissioner Raymond Kelly said he was putting an
extra 300 inspectors on duty at points of entry into the country,
with particular attention to ``remote ports.''
</P>
<P>
   _ President Clinton's press secretary, Joe Lockhart, said the
president had been briefed on counterterrorism efforts in the
pre-New Year's period. ``That work is something that the president
has closely involved himself in and has done a lot of work on,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clinton's national security adviser, Samuel Berger, said
officials know of no specific terror threats against targets in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Pickering, co-chair of an international working group that has
been meeting throughout 1999 to plan for the New Year's holidays,
noted that the State Department warned several months ago of
possible terrorist activity in the earliest hours of the new
century.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have the beginning, at least, of some information that
indicates that our foresight was uncannily correct,'' Pickering
said, referring to the arrest in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Other members of the working group said the government was
well-prepared to provide assistance to American citizens traveling
abroad during New Year's.
</P>
<P>
   However, the department has issued four country-specific travel
warnings, suggesting that Americans defer trips to Russia, Ukraine,
Moldova and Belarus until after Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Security at U.S. embassies and consular offices has been beefed
up, and the posts placed on a ``high state of alert and readiness
to respond to terrorism, civil disorder, disruptions of critical
local services and cyber-threats,'' said David Carpenter, assistant
secretary for diplomatic security.
</P>
<P>
   A 24-hour command-and-control center will be staffed at the
State Department's Washington office throughout the New Year's
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department's Internet site (www.state.gov) has been
receiving between 250,000 and 600,000 visits a day, and the number
is expected to increase during the holidays, said Kevin Herbert,
director of overseas citizen services.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
