<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4573 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SIDEWALK-BOOK-REVIEW-     12-20 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIDEWALK-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SIDEWALK': EMBRACING STREET LIFE, WITH CAMERA AND HEART 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By RICHARD EDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picture a scene common enough on New York's streets, especially
in the holiday season. Dodging panhandlers and improvised sidewalk
vendors, a mother threads her 5-year-old through the shopper
crowds. The mother fixes her gaze ahead; the child turns to gaze at
the slovenly figures displaying blanketsful of urban jetsam.
</P>
<P>
   As we get older, hyperopia takes us: a farsightedness of the
social as well as ophthalmological kind. It is hard to see what is
nearby. We are likely to know more about the homeless in Kosovo
than in New York. The imagination drifts to Samarkand and shuns the
street people of lower Sixth Avenue. It would rather conceive an
abstract errand than challenge us to do something _ borrow a
child's glance, perhaps _ or, worse, tell us we can't do much
besides drop a dollar. Dropping a dollar is easier than looking.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell Duneier has spent seven years looking, and to such
effect that ``Sidewalk,'' like a pair of reading glasses, makes the
blur of what is close up turn sharp. Frequenting one particular
street colony, mainly black, in the blocks around the Avenue of the
Americas and Eighth Street, he finds a world of weakness and
failure but also one of mutual support, frail dignity, ingenious
struggle and fluid hierarchies.
</P>
<P>
   Used-book and magazine sellers rank at the top, their wares
displayed on rickety tables and trundled away at night to a storage
locker or accommodating garage. Then come Dumpster scavengers,
ranking in the middle; and then down to a range of ancillary
service providers: part-time table-minders and all-night
place-holders for the limited places available. At the bottom are
the drifting panhandlers and, before a police crackdown, the
self-appointed greeters and doormen at ATMs. ``Until 1996 the local
bank had four doormen who divided among them a 24-hour shift,''
Duneier wryly writes.
</P>
<P>
   That he can be wry and in some instances condemnatory only makes
more striking the sympathetic understanding that runs through his
magnificent book, with luminous photographs by Ovie Carter, whose
camera eye, held steady, records the humanity that ours avoids.
Contrary to a periscope, ``Sidewalk'' refracts our vision downward,
breaking through to what, for freshness, seems unnervingly like
open sky underneath our feet.
</P>
<P>
   Duneier is a professor of sociology, but he has a superb
journalist's ear for quotes and the ability to limn character and
scene. He writes, that is, as very few sociologists do; he stays on
for years, immersed in his subjects, as virtually no journalist
will do.
</P>
<P>
   Year after year he visited his street people, interviewing,
taping their exchanges with passersby and customers, and eventually
having them tape one another. He minded tables, made sales,
accompanied them on scavenging errands. It was not so much that he
won their trust as that they got used to living with him around. On
the street you have to live your life with all manner of things you
may not trust.
</P>
<P>
   His way in was the bookseller Hakim, a self-made
African-American intellectual who left a job as a legal and
financial proofreader to set up his tables on the street and
become, eventually, the wise man of the driftwood community. He had
felt humiliated and confined, racially and mentally, by the
corporate world where he held a small but comfortable place. ``I
needed my longitude and latitude,'' he told Duneier.
</P>
<P>
   It took a number of conversations before Hakim would open up,
wary as he was of being patronized and exploited by a white
scholar, yet bursting to share his reflections on a level not
possible with his street fellows. Eventually he became a lucid and
thoughtful Virgil to Duneier's Dante.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, that is. A measure of the author's passion and the
richness of his work is that after writing a book based on what
Hakim showed him, he put it aside. He remained on the street
another four or five years for a more difficult task: getting down
the stories and daily lives of some 20 people, many half crippled
by drugs, drink, hardship and jail, but driven by a will to
survive. They were not nearly as fluent as Hakim, yet Duneier
stayed to bring up deep-buried veins of wit, humor and
reflectiveness. It is as if Dante had told Virgil, ``Thanks for
your help with the residents; now I will stay on for face time.''
</P>
<P>
   Here and there, as if to hold the franchise, are passages that
wrap Duneier's provocative ideas in a caul of academic reiteration,
making explicit what is already so wonderfully implicit in the
street scenes, the encounters, the flow of life and talk the author
records. ``Sidewalk'' is far more than sociology, although it is
that, too; it is the chronicle of a community, a ``Nanook'' of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   There is Angela, whose bookstand is not far from that of Hakim,
who was for a number of years her lover and counselor. (When a
bookstore owner swoops down and confiscates four copies of a book
she insists were stolen, Hakim quiets Angela's outrage: ``When a
white woman comes here and says something is hers, it's hers.''
There is a world of borne injustice there; and Duneier sharpens it
with an account of the gray market in books conducted in at least
one respectable bookstore.)
</P>
<P>
   There are, among a dozen others, Marvin, the self-styled
``overseer'' of the used-magazine vendors (he discourages
pornography); Ron, his unsteady but redoubtable protege, and
Mudrick, man of picaresque words and schemes. There is the
precarious Butteroll, who sleeps in a niche beside the subway
tracks. ``The trains come about two feet from you,'' he relates.
``But you put your body in a position like listening to music. You
tune yourself to the roar of the tracks and the making of the noise
and you go right to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Duneier recounts the origins, travails, fragility of the street
community, with periodic police crackdowns under the
``broken-window'' theory of criminology: removing street disorder
and dilapidation reduces crime. (Bible: The poor are always with
you. Mayor: Not with me they're not.) He spells out the antisocial
aspects of the street people, but his book is a vivid, patient and
moving account of those who have inched up from crime and despair
to take control, however precarious and scruffy, of their lives.
From behind the broken windows, human eyes peer out.
</P>
<P>
   Publication Notes:
</P>
<P>
   `SIDEWALK'
</P>
<P>
   By Mitchell Duneier
</P>
<P>
   Photographs by Ovie Carter
</P>
<P>
   383 pages. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $27.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 1747EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4574 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-INTERNET-FUTURE21-COX     12-20 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-FUTURE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AT&AMP;T CHALLENGED OVER INTERNET CONTROL
 &HT;    550&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal regulators should act to give a wide range
of Internet service providers access to AT&AMP;T Corp.'s high-speed
cable networks, consumer advocates and academic experts said at a
forum Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Many Internet providers nationwide want access to AT&AMP;T's
``broadband'' network in order to sell blazingly fast service that
would allow Internet users to use video and other cutting-edge
applications. The Federal Communications Commission, citing the
emergence of competitive broadband technologies, has refused to
intervene.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T is in a position to decide what kind of applications run
on the Internet,'' Lawrence Lessig, a Harvard Law School professor
who specializes in computer issues, said at a forum on the future
on the Internet in the coming era of high-speed access.
</P>
<P>
   Lessig said the company seeks to undermine the open,
decentralized and competitive nature of the Internet, which fosters
innovation because anyone can use it and anyone can communicate
with anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   He said the central ``end-to-end'' design principle of the
Internet requires that the ``intelligence'' be located where users
put data onto the network and take it out _ at its ``ends'' _ and
that the ``pipes'' through which the information flows be as simple
and neutral as possible.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, Lessig argued, wants to tie those pipelines to the content
and services they are selling and thereby control interconnection
to the world at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``Architecture matters,'' Lessig said.
</P>
<P>
   Lessig called upon FCC Chairman William Kennard to end his
hands-off policy.
</P>
<P>
   The independent agency, he said, should back local cable
regulators who are contesting AT&AMP;T policies in the courts in order
to ensure customers have a wide range of choices in the
fast-growing broadband market.
</P>
<P>
   The position taken by Lessig and consumer advocates at the forum
reflects the Clinton administration's policy, spelled out in a
57-page report Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers should have choice in both their content and their
Internet access provider,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T General Counsel James Cicconi rejected ``the faulty notion
that AT&AMP;T has a monopoly on cable modem access'' to the Internet.
He cited a Dec. 6 accord with Atlanta-based Mindspring Enterprises
Inc., a large Internet service provider, to offer high-speed access
over AT&AMP;T's cable lines after AT&AMP;T's current exclusive contract
with Excite(at)Home expires in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Chairman Michael Armstrong has told Kennard that the
company has ``begun discussions with a number of (service providers
and Internet portals) about offering their services on our fixed
wireless and cable systems, and were open to discussions with
others as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Another seminar speaker, Mark Cooper, research director of the
Consumer Federation of America, said Armstrong would be
``conducting private negotiations'' in Aspen, Colo., over the
Christmas holidays with Steve Case, chairman of America OnLine
Inc., which has 20 million Internet subscribers in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the right way to make public policy,'' Cooper
claimed. Jim McCann, an AT&AMP;T spokesman, declined to confirm that
such talks would take place.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In practice, the current debate revolves less over freely
displaying any and all content and more over such commercial issues
as which content will be featured and which data, if any, will get
preferred treatment through AT&AMP;T's fast ``pipes.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Cicconi cited legal and technical issues that he
said could oblige AT&AMP;T to act as more than a neutral mail carrier
in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is the company's obligation to preserve copyright
protection, a particularly sensitive issue in the music field at a
time when it has become simple for computers to make perfect
digital copies.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another unresolved issue: How to deal with ``bandwidth
hogs'' _ customers who, say, seek to download a movie at a time
when their neighbors are also on line, thereby slowing down their
speed of Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
