<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Dec. 21, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A voluminous shield of precipitation will spread northeast
across the Southeast and Middle Atlantic states on Tuesday as a
low-pressure system, which spawned moderate to heavy rains Monday
across parts of the western Gulf states, ripples along a front. The
low will weaken and accelerate, however, reducing the risk of heavy
rain in many areas in the Southeast and Middle Atlantic states.
</P>
<P>
   A narrow swath of snow or ice, the latter mainly in the form of
freezing rain, will develop on the western fringe of the
precipitation shield across the lower Mississippi and Tennessee
Valleys as moist Gulf air glides over cold air wedging
south-southwestward in concert with a cold high-pressure system
over Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   The swath of wintry precipitation will streak northeast across
parts of the Ohio Valley and then expand once it reaches the
central Appalachians in West Virginia and Pennsylvania later
Tuesday and Tuesday night. Some wintry precipitation may spread
east of the central Appalachians Tuesday night toward the northern
Middle Atlantic seaboard.
</P>
<P>
   An arctic front will slice across the Great Lakes on Tuesday. In
its wake, snow squalls and snow showers will stream off the
southern coast of Lake Superior and the eastern coast of Lake
Michigan, with some squalls producing snowfall rates of two inches
an hour or more.
</P>
<P>
   Winds from the east-northeast will average 20 to 30 mph hour,
with gusts over 40 mph, below canyons in parts of central and
southern California. Meanwhile, fog will shroud parts of the
Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Winter Begins
</P>
<P>
   At 2:44 a.m. EST on Wednesday, the sun's rays will be directly
overhead along the northeastern coast of Australia, marking the
winter solstice. The solstice is also the shortest day of the year
in the Northern Hemisphere. New York City will only receive nine
hours and 15 minutes of daylight. North of the Arctic Circle, the
sun will not rise at all. The long night will reach its midpoint at
the North Pole on Wednesday and, while the days begin slowly to
lengthen in this hemisphere, the cold air will continue to
strengthen for several weeks in the feeble sunlight of the northern
latitudes.
</P>
</TEXT>
