<SLUG> BC-BOMB-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BOMB-ITTY OF ERRORS:' RAP IS TO SHAKESPEARE AS BOMB IS TO COMEDY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes appear at end of review.) (DW) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The farcically disastrous performance of ``Taming of
the Shrew'' that is at the center of ``Kiss Me, Kate'' on Broadway
doesn't do half the damage to Shakespeare that is cheerfully
executed, in a garage-like space in the East Village, by the four
young creators of ``The Bomb-itty of Errors.'' Shakespeare can take
it; theatergoers who don't also appreciate a mosh pit may have a
harder time.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to dismiss, just advise. The show, an adaptation of
the slapstick mistaken-identity play that is arguably Shakespeare's
silliest work, all in rap verse and sketch-comedy staging, has the
kind of relentless exuberance, exhortatory fervor and enthusiasm
for all manner of sex acts that remind older people that youth is
wasted on the young. The full-house audience at the recent
performance I attended, evidently including a large contingent from
nearby New York University, was noisily responsive with delight,
and it wasn't because they could follow the plot.
</P>
<P>
   Those without Shakespearean background enough to know that the
source material is ``The Comedy of Errors'' can still enjoy this;
indeed they might be the ideal audience. Shakespeare's play _ which
concerns twin sets of twins, separated at birth, and their
accidental, convoluted reconciliation _ makes it tough enough to
follow the plot machinations, much less swallow them. Here the
story matters almost not at all.
</P>
<P>
   The action is set in a contemporary Manhattan-like place, and
the two sets of twins (in Shakespeare, two masters and their
servants) are here all four brothers born to the same parents, a
rap star and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   How they came to be separated has to do with the rapper being
arrested for selling drugs, an episode recounted in a prologue that
introduces the four performers and their hip-hop take on
Shakespearean verse:
</P>
<P>
   He started sellin' skunk, you know, cheeba? Weed?
</P>
<P>
   Just to try and get by and give his family what they need.
</P>
<P>
   OK, it's not iambic pentameter, which is, of course, the point:
the poetry of Shakespeare made modern (and not entirely
grammatical). There is an admirable zest in the persistent doggerel
in which the entire 90-minute text of the play is delivered. The
ambition of it, the gall, really, and the intermittent achievement
of genuine cleverness are the show's chief pleasures. The problem
is these guys aren't quite Shakespeare's equal when it comes to
wordplay (oh well), and though it's hard not to admire the number
of rhymes they come up with for the male sex organ _ Venus,
limousine is, Salinas, arenas, to name just a few _ there are
limited theatrical pleasures to be derived from this.
</P>
<P>
   The show would be hugely improved with more attention to
performance fundamentals. No one, including the director, Andy
Goldberg, seems to have thought of doing any real choreographing
aside from keeping the actors from bumping into each other while
horsing around. Perhaps that's because the performers, all of whom
play multiple roles and all of whom have taken hip-hop stage names
_ Rodan (Jordan Allen-Dutton), Gruff (Jason Catalano), G.Q.
(Gregory J. Qaiyum) and Red Dragon (Erik Weiner) _ don't seem to
dance particularly well in spite of their obvious athleticism.
Catalano (or would that be Gruff?) does nice bits as a hooker in a
platinum wig and a leopard-patterned satin teddy and as a
Rastafarian herb seller.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, as actors there is little to judge them by. Weiner is
particularly annoying as Luciana, the dim-witted husband-seeker of
the two Shakespearean sisters, not bothering to hide his goatee
(yuk yuk) and reciting all his lines in a falsetto.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's a generation gap at work here. The audience
seemed not to share any of my reservations and left the theater as
jazzed as any group of theatergoers I've seen in a long time.
</P>
<P>
   So, as I understand the phrase, word up.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE BOMB-ITTY OF ERRORS'
</P>
<P>
   Written and performed by Jordan Allen-Dutton, Jason Catalano,
G.Q. and Erik Weiner; music written and performed by J.A.Q.
Directed and developed by Andy Goldberg. Set by Scott Pask;
costumes by David C. Woolard; lighting by James Vermeulen; sound by
One Dream Sound and Sunil Rajan; production stage manager, Kate
Broderick; general management, RFP/Jo Porter and David W. Caldwell;
production manager, Joseph L. Robinson; associate producer, Andrew
Kato. Presented by Daryl Roth, Michael Lynne, Q Brothers and Hal
Luftig. At 45 Bleecker in Manhattan. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
