<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DON'T DISCRIMINATE' IS BETTER THAN `DON'T ASK'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK Z. SMITH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several years ago, a newspaper cartoonist outlined a proposed
compromise on the issue of whether gays and lesbians should be
allowed to serve in the military.
</P>
<P>
   The cartoonist's solution? Homosexuals could serve on Mondays,
Wednesdays and Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   That tongue-in-cheek proposal was good for a laugh. But it makes
about as much sense as the U.S. military's current ``don't ask,
don't tell'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   The policy should be scrapped. It's a simple matter of fairness.
Gay soldiers should be allowed to serve in the military under the
same rules of conduct that govern heterosexuals. It's way past time
for discrimination to end.
</P>
<P>
   This past week, Defense Secretary William Cohen ordered a 90-day
review of the ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy after President
Clinton complained that it was not working as intended. Clinton
cited the murder of a gay Army private as an example.
</P>
<P>
   Pfc. Barry Winchell was bludgeoned to death with a baseball bat
in July as he slept in his barracks at Fort Campbell, Ky., after
enduring months of cruel harassment supposedly forbidden by the
policy. Another private, Calvin Glover, recently was sentenced to
life in prison for the murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ask, don't tell'' forbids the military from inquiring
about a soldier's sex life unless there is clear evidence of
homosexual conduct. But the policy also requires soldiers to leave
the service if they volunteer that they are homosexual.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Pentagon, 1,145 people were discharged last
year for being gay. The majority of the discharges were due to
statements that violated the ``don't tell'' policy, rather than for
homosexual conduct. Although the policy was supposed to help
prevent discrimination against gays, last year's discharge total
far exceeded the 682 discharges of gays in 1993, the year the
policy took effect.
</P>
<P>
   First lady Hillary Clinton, as well as Democratic presidential
candidates Al Gore and Bill Bradley, has urged that the policy be
ended and that gays serve in the military under the same terms as
heterosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Commendably, Bradley has gone a major step further, urging that
discrimination against gays be barred under the historic Civil
Rights Act of 1964.
</P>
<P>
   The law forbids discrimination based on a person's race,
religion or gender. Discrimination is forbidden in employment,
housing, lending and public accommodations. Under Bradley's
proposal, the act would be expanded to ban discrimination based on
sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ``don't ask, don't tell'' is being increasingly
recognized for the abysmal failure that it is.
</P>
<P>
   Large U.S. newspapers editorializing in favor of ending the
policy include Newsday, The New York Times, the St. Louis
Post-Dispatch, the San Francisco Chronicle and The Arizona
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   As the Post-Dispatch put it: ``It is time for Mr. Clinton and
the military to dispense with `don't ask.' The best policy is the
one Americans claim to hold so dear _ don't discriminate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle said: ``As anecdote after anecdote shows, many
homosexual men and women are valiantly serving their country, often
in extraordinarily heroic ways. They should be subject to the same
rules and restrictions as all members of the armed services, no
more and no less ... they should not be penalized with a
hypocritical policy that says they may only fight for their country
if they live a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republic cited the case of gay Army Reservist Steve May, a
Republican state legislator in Arizona who was characterized as
``one of the finest young officers'' in an Army performance review.
May now faces discharge because he revealed that he is gay in
commenting on an anti-gay bill in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Congress should pass whatever legislation might be needed to bar
discrimination against gays in the military. Such action would echo
a long-occurring trend across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Britain announced this past week that it has decided to end its
ban on homosexuals in the armed forces. But Britain is a laggard.
Most other European nations have allowed gays in the military for
years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ending ``don't ask, don't tell,'' the U.S.
military should conduct markedly stronger training programs to
encourage more tolerance toward homosexuals and actively discourage
harassment.
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't take the violent death of a young Army private in
Kentucky to galvanize the nation into ending discrimination against
gays in the military. What's right is right, and discrimination is
clearly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
