<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS-ANALYSIS _ MOSCOW _ A senior Kremlin official
called Sunday's parliamentary election results a ``peaceful
revolution'' that offers new hope for Russia's long-stalled market
and democratic reforms. But nothing is a sure thing given Russia's
complex political system, the ongoing war in Chechnya and the
unpredictable President Boris Yeltsin. The results of Sunday's
election altered the political landscape in Russia more than anyone
could have imagined. But the pitfalls on the way to political unity
are many. (Holmes, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-TERRORISM _ WASHINGTON _ Undersecretary of State Thomas
Pickering and other officials discuss international preparations
for New Years in a 1 p.m. EST session expected to be dominated by
questions about a recent terrorism alert at U.S. borders. (Nesmith,
Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   PORK _ WASHINGTON _ A ``complete guide'' to pork in the
appropriations bill is released by Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla.
(Malone, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-FUTURE _ WASHINGTON _ Lawrence Lessig of Harvard Law
School and other nationally known Internet policy experts will
discuss the challenge of maintaining the Internet's uniquely open
qualities in the face of the emerging closed broadband cable
systems at a National Press Club forum. (Glass, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   TEX-TAX-DISCOUNT _ WASHINGTON _ For the owners of Austin's Texas
Discount Furniture, the cost of doing business could go up $2.4
million. That's how much the Internal Revenue Service is demanding
in back taxes and penalties from the owners, their son and his
wife, and their daughter and her husband. The IRS ruled they had
unreported gross receipts from Texas Discount and SDB Check
Cashing. (Moskal, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ABERNATHY _ ATLANTA _ Closing arguments, possible verdict in
Ralph D. Abernathy Jr. trial. TENTATIVE. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   VERMONT _ MONTPELIER, Vt. _ Going further than any other high
court in the nation, Vermont's Supreme Court ruled Monday that gay
couples are entitled to the same benefits and protections as
married couples. But the court said it is up to the Legislature to
decide whether gays can actually marry. Vermont had been gay
couples' last, best hope after Hawaii slammed the door on same-sex
marriages. (Croft, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-DISTURBANCE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ State prison guards lost
control of a cellblock early Monday at a Beeville prison after the
doors of about 80 prison cells unexplicably opened early Monday.
Control was regained after several hours but officials are
perplexed about why the doors would open. The disturbance occurred
at the McConnell Unit, where a prison guard was stabbed to death
late last week. (Ward, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   BIG-MOON _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In recognition of Western
civilization's frenzied quest to find a divine _ or, at least,
cosmic _ sign that the end of the millennium approaches, try this:
The Internet is alight with e-mails declaring that Wednesday
night's last full moon of the millennium will be the brightest
first night of winter in 133 years, perhaps portending disaster.
Most astronomers aren't impressed, saying the event isn't as big a
deal as millennium pundits claim. (O'Meilia, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
