<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-MEDIA21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Read of the week: Healthy cookbooks
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie and M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking for a gift book for someone who needs to change their
diet, or recipes for a healthier new year for your family? Three of
these are published by major national health organizations and the
fourth by Atlanta's Promina Health System.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``American Medical Association Family Health Cookbook'' by
Melanie Barnard and Brooke Dojny with Mindy Hermann,
</P>
<P>
   registered dietitian, and C. Wayne Callaway, M.D. (Pocket Pooks,
1997, $16 paperback, $30 hardback)
</P>
<P>
   Not just a cookbook, this begins with textbook-like information
about ``good food that's good for you.'' The diet-health connection
is covered in regard to heart disease, cancer, diabetes and
maintenance of a healthy weight. The book also gives a crash course
on nutrition basics, food labels and vitamins and sorts through the
confusing maze of fats and cholesterol. Foods to always have on
hand are described, along with how to keep your kitchen and food
free from contamination. The book is full of variety: penne pasta
with sausage and autumn vegetables; grilled salmon with dilled
cucumber yogurt sauce; baked potatoes with spicy chili bean
topping. There are helpful hints peppered throughout, such as how
to properly crush a garlic clove. A very healthful and helpful
512-page book, with 350 recipes listing per-serving calories and
nutritional information.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call 1-800-621-8335 or go to
</P>
<P>
   www.ama-assn.org/catalog.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The New American Heart Association Cookbook, 25th
Anniversary Edition'' (Random House, 1998, $30 hardback)
</P>
<P>
   Porcupine meatballs. Breakfast pizzas. Berries in rich vanilla
cream. Sound heart-healthy to you? They are, along with some 400
other dishes put together by the nation's top organization devoted
to preventing heart disease and strokes. Lowering or keeping
cholesterol levels low is the goal of these recipes, along with
proving that it's possible to eat both ``healthful and zestful''
food. Dishes are simple, and the book includes an appendix of which
recipes to combine for a complete meal or party appetizers. The new
edition of the book has 698 pages and 150 new recipes, which list
per-serving calories and other nutritional information.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call 1-800-242-8721 or go to
www.americanheart.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The New Family Cookbook for People With Diabetes'' by the
American Diabetes Association and the American Dietetic Association
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1999, $27.50 hardback)
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to have diabetes to find this cookbook helpful in
planning low-fat, delicious meals. And those living with diabetes
can learn how to make easy-to-prepare dishes that don't require
special ingredients or extra time or fuss in the kitchen. Recipes,
ranging from moussaka with lamb to avocado-and-grapefruit salad
with sherry vinaigrette to Georgia peach cooler, use lower-fat
ingredients whenever possible or unsaturated fats (olive or canola
oils) when needed. Sugar, not sugar substitutes, is used, because
people with diabetes can eat small amounts of sugar as long as
their overall daily carbohydrate intake does not exceed recommended
levels. Sodium (salt) is also tracked carefully and noted in
recipes when it gets above 400 milligrams, because eating too much
salt can contribute to high blood pressure. This 400-recipe,
542-page cookbook is perfect for those needing to know how to get
their insulin levels under control; each recipe has a nutritional
analysis and the latest diabetes exchange information.
</P>
<P>
   For information: American Diabetes Association,
</P>
<P>
   1-800-232-6733, or American Dietetic Association,
</P>
<P>
   1-800-366-1655 or www.eatright.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Promina Heart Healthy Recipes
</P>
<P>
   This small recipe book is published by Atlanta's Promina Health
System, which includes Piedmont and Kennestone hospitals and
Gwinnett and DeKalb medical centers. The introduction gives ``Fat
Facts'' and suggestions for lowering fat and sodium content in
diets, and there's a handy guide for replacing fatty ingredients
with heart-healthy alternatives. The 30 pages of recipes include
basics, such as baked potato skins and mock sour cream and a fruity
breakfast smoothie, and easy-to-prepare dinners such as grilled
salmon with lime butter and heart-healthy Texas chili.
</P>
<P>
   The booklet is free. To order, call Promina Healthcall at
404-541-1111 or go to www.promina.org.
</P>
<P>
   _Patricia Guthrie
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET SITE OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   You know why your doctor prescribed the drug. You know what's on
the list of warnings the pharmacist gave you. But reactions to
drugs can differ by individual. What can you actually expect when
you start taking it?
</P>
<P>
   No one can guarantee how you'll react to a drug, but the
Internet Drug Index (www.rxlist.com/) can help. Among the features
of this longstanding site is RxBoard, a set of bulletin boards
where people trade descriptions of their experiences with the 20
drugs most frequently prescribed in the United States, as well as
some alternative medications. Among the entries: arguments over
whether Prozac causes weight gain, testimonials to the new
painkiller Celebrex, and a report of fever and headache after
taking ginkgo biloba.
</P>
<P>
   The site was created as a public service by a pharmacist named
Neil Sandow. Recently it began being hosted by HealthCentral, a
medical-themed Internet portal that, like many medical gateways
these days, includes a link to an online pharmacy. As with all
sites on the Net, exercise caution and judgment.
</P>
<P>
   _M.A.J. McKenna
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie and M.A.J. McKenna write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
