<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Futurists foretell of life in the next century
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Newsweek ($3.95) bids farewell to Charlie Brown and the
``Peanuts'' crowd in a cover story this week, but the most
compelling reading is the magazine's predictions for the 21st
century. According to the experts Newsweek consulted, the brave new
world will feature toys designed by kids, dolls that will act as
baby monitors and automobiles that drive us instead of vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   In science, neuroplasticity will influence the way we use our
brains, better sex may be just a bodysuit and virtual-reality booth
away and 90 percent of all books will be published electronically
by 2020. In the entertainment world, TV shows and movies will be
viewed on demand.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, to illustrate just how wrong the seers can be, John
Leland writes about what the experts foresaw for America in 1899.
Most futurists missed the medical advances of the 20th century and
only one mentioned the automobile, or ``electrical carriage.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Amazon man: By now you probably know that Amazon.com founder
Jeff Bezos has been named Time's ($3.95) Person of the Year. But
the magazine also devotes a sizable chunk of this issue to others
who mattered in 1999 as well as providing an analysis of the impact
the Internet has had on society. One major trend is the explosion
of collectibles _ from yesteryear's treasures to yesterday's
garbage _ for sale or auction on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   As for other notables, Time's gallery includes Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright,
golfer Tiger Woods, Jordan's Queen Noor and ``Harry Potter'' author
J.K. Rowling.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Familiar face: U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($3.95) hedges its
bets by naming Uncle Sam as Person of the Century. In a look back
at the past 100 years, reporter Michael Barone explains how America
has left its mark on the world with everything from movies to
microchips. Included is an interesting lineup of 25 entrepreneurs,
entertainers and visionaries who shaped the modern era, from
shopping mall inventor Victor Gruen to the Big Mac himself, Ray
Kroc.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  People who made a difference: Looking at history in a
different light, American Heritage ($4.95) doesn't even include
Bezos on its list of the century's 20 greatest innovators. The top
10 are television inventor Philo T. Farnsworth, botanist George
Washington Carver, polio vaccine developer Jonas Salk, automotive
pioneer Henry Ford, aviation pioneers the Wright brothers,
physicist Albert Einstein, laser progenitor Charles Townes and
electrical engineer Charles Steinmetz.
</P>
<P>
   And in an article bound to stir debate, Victor Davis Hanson
argues that instead of being a ruthless act of revenge, Gen.
William T. Sherman's march through Georgia actually was ``a vast
moral crusade'' that saved lives on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Literature of the millennium: Some of the best writing in The
New Yorker's ($3) Millennial Fiction issue is not fiction at all,
but rather letters written by soldiers in the American wars of the
century. ``Sure, I was afraid _ as you or any other chap would be,
too,'' one World War I soldier writes from France, ``but what I
feared most was I would be yellow.'' By Vietnam, the tone of the
writing had changed. ``Every second I was expecting to die,'' one
man writes. ``I regretted everything I had done for the U.S.A. ...
Americans are ruthless and violent: I hate 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   The fictional contributions are excellent as well, with works by
Alice Munro, Robert Stone, Alec Wilkinson, Donald Antrim and James
Thurber.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: Julia Roberts tells In Style ($3.95) that she has
finally found some stability on her 82-acre Southwestern ranch _
and in her relationships. The Georgia actress lives on the ranch
with six horses, seven dogs and former ``Law &AMP; Order'' actor
Benjamin Bratt. Roberts also makes the cover of People ($3.99) as
one of the 25 most intriguing people of '99. ... Jezebel ($3.95)
chats with former Atlanta resident and ``Melrose Place'' actress
Jamie Luner about her new role in the ``Profiler'' TV series. The
magazine also visits Jim Borum and Quinn Brack, who have moved into
one of Margaret Mitchell's old apartments at the corner of South
Prado and Piedmont Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
