<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4592 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SECOND-CITY-1800-(2TA     12-20 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECOND-CITY-1800-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 40, SECOND CITY HAS GROWN FROM A COMEDY CLUB TO AN EMPIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Art is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ ``I feel like I was born here,'' Alan Arkin said.
</P>
<P>
   That would have been in 1960, when Arkin, the comic actor and
director, was 28 and starving for work (and to hear him tell it,
food) in New York. Out of desperation and with a sense of descent
into oblivion, he accepted an invitation to move to Chicago and
join a fledgling comedy troupe called the Second City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was the end of everything,'' he said. ``But it
was the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it was. The troupe that began here in 1959 (the name
comes from a disparaging remark about Chicago by A.J. Liebling),
forging a new art form from the disparate skills of classical
acting and comic improvisation, celebrated its 40th anniversary
last weekend, having by now peopled the world of television
sitcoms, filled the nation's cabarets with stand-up and spawned
nutty movies by the dozen.
</P>
<P>
   It has grown to become a company, in the corporate sense of the
word, whose business is the creation and distribution of comedy. It
includes a troupe in Toronto that in the 1970s created the
television show ``SCTV.'' For the last 20 years a second Chicago
troupe, the Second City e.t.c., has performed in a separate theater
around the corner from the company's building on North Wells
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago a troupe was started in Detroit, and another is
to make its debut in Cleveland in the spring. Three touring groups
serve as a sort of farm team for the franchise, and there are
training centers in New York and Los Angeles as well as in Chicago,
the nation's center for improvisation-based comedy, which alone has
800 students. Second City has even built a corporate division that
sends actors out as business consultants, teaching levity as a
management tool.
</P>
<P>
   Its list of alumni is, of course, legendary, a multigenerational
Who's Who of funny: Mike Nichols, Elaine May, Joan Rivers, Edward
Asner, Valerie Harper, John Belushi, Dan Aykroyd, Gilda Radner,
Martin Short, Bill Murray, Andrea Martin, George Wendt, Shelley
Long, Dan Castellaneta, Amy Sedaris and Tim Meadows, to name a
handful.
</P>
<P>
   Arkin was among dozens of them _ including Joe Flaherty, Robert
Klein, Avery Schreiber and Harold Ramis _ who returned for the
40th-anniversary weekend, three days of performances by current
members and reminiscences about the rise of an institution _ ``My
God, it's an empire!'' Klein exclaimed at one point _ that by now
is probably to blame if there is too much comedy in the world.
</P>
<P>
   It was also an opportunity to reflect on the changes wrought on
comedy by the world, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were committed to mischief,'' said Bernard Sahlins, who
started the company with Paul Sills and Howard Alk at a time when
the one-liners of Bob Hope and Henny Youngman defined popular wit,
before personal revelation and political mockery became comic
staples, when the stage irreverence of Mort Sahl, Dick Gregory and
Lenny Bruce was new and shocking.
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``We had a golden opportunity. McCarthyism had
chilled everything, and comedy was a lot of mother-in-law jokes.
There wasn't any political humor. All you had to do was go out on
stage and say `Eisenhower,' and everybody had an orgasm. It just
wasn't done.''
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst for the weekend's discussion was opening night of
the company's latest main-stage revue, its 85th. Like all of Second
City's core work, it was a series of sketches, some loosely
connected by overlapping characters, that were written by the six
performers and honed into polished routines with a director over
weeks of improvising sessions. Improvisations are built into the
program, but even they have a format, with specific places where a
suggestion for a song title, say, or a food, is solicited from the
audience to catalyze a comic riff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Improvisation is not a presentational form,'' Sahlins said,
``except in small doses or as a game. It's a tool.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a working method that is distinct to Second City, and it
existed from the start, a melding of the ideas of Viola Spolin, a
theater teacher who created an influential set of games for actor
training; her son, Sills, a director; David Shepherd, the founder
of the Compass Players, a theater troupe based on the European
tradition of commedia dell'arte; and Sahlins, a classical theater
producer and director.
</P>
<P>
   It is full-time work: daytime rehearsals, evening performances
and late-night improv sessions. Intended to bring discipline to the
fervid cultural observations of young performers, the method tends
to instill professionalism in the eager anarchists who are drawn to
comic theater. This helps explain why Second City, with performers
and audiences that stay the same age (18 to 35), has endured
through four decades of flux in culture and comedy. Its guiding
principle, which was invoked frequently during the weekend: Always
perform at the top of your intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``At its best, it is a comedy of behavior, not a comedy of
comment,'' Sahlins said.
</P>
<P>
   The anniversary show was exemplary. It began with a couple in a
doctor's office, getting bad news. The doctor has found a lump in
the woman's breast. Long, discomforting pause. Then the husband
speaks: ``But you're a dentist!''
</P>
<P>
   It was a characteristic moment: quick and rather spare,
resonantly topical, obviously, aggressively irreverent. The two
dozen or so other bits were similar. There was the folk singer
singing about how he picked up a homeless woman: ``I asked her, `My
place or mine?''' There the post-game interview with a football
star who thanks God for helping him score the winning touchdown:
``So why,'' the interviewer asks about his opponents, ``does God
hate the Kansas City Chiefs?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It was well received by the visiting alumni _ ``How about that
dentist?'' Klein said _ interesting to them as much for what wasn't
on stage as for what was. There was sexual humor, but no vulgarity
for the sake of outrage, not a single cheap clutch of the genitals.
There were no references to the culture of television. Most
surprising, there was no overt political satire. Subtle subversion,
if that's possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed that,'' said Klein, who spent 14 months at Second
City in 1965 and 1966. ``We were nonstop political,'' he said.
``Our Mayor Daley, I did him all the time. I was also the local
Lyndon Johnson.''
</P>
<P>
   Arkin said he had not been back to Second City since the 25th
anniversary, when the sense of anything goes, a hangover from the
John Belushi ``Animal House'' days _ Sahlins called the influence
of Belushi on less gifted performers ``pernicious'' _ dragged the
company into a kind of comedy gutter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen years ago I felt it was anarchic and vulgar, and I was
dismayed,'' Arkin said. ``But this tonight was very impressive,
literary in a way. There was a slight cynicism to it, I thought,
but that's just appropriate to the time. For us there was an
innocence to what we were doing. We thought we were going to change
the world. And there was no touching. Whatever sexuality we put
onstage was very timid.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985 Sahlins sold Second City to Andrew Alexander, who had
been running the Toronto troupe and who has presided over the
expansion, enlarging the training programs, opening the Detroit
branch and, in 1992, beginning the corporate division, which, given
the irreverent nature of the Second City product, was viewed by
some in the company with some skepticism. But it has served the
company well financially, bringing in $1.5 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was resistance in the very beginning,'' Alexander said.
``The attitude toward the corporate world was, `Isn't that selling
out?' It's still a balancing act. But it's become an important part
of our expansion. We have limited space for live shows. You can
only sell 350 seats so many times a week.''
</P>
<P>
   And for many of the young performers who are drawn to Second
City as a launching pad to television, Alexander said, the
corporate workshops are good practice for money-making gigs to
come. ``They're viewed now as live commercials,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's current projects include developing the means for
live Webcasting and diversifying its audience, which remains almost
entirely white. The Detroit troupe has introduced a handful of
black performers into the Second City pipeline; two of the e.t.c.
cast members are black, and one is Hispanic. But the company
acknowledges that it has been frustrated in its attempts to draw a
more racially mixed crowd. It has applied for city funds to build a
new theater on Chicago's largely black South Side, where the wish
is to attract a black business partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very community-based tradition,'' said Kelly Leonard,
the producer of Second City in Chicago. ``We speak a common
language, and it's a white language. For a young, funny black
person, going the stand-up route has been the route to success.
We've been cracking away at this for six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point we did three minority-based shows. They were
mostly well reviewed. But the audiences were mostly white. And
we've been going into a lot of black high schools, and they've
loved what we do. But that hasn't translated to more black students
in the training center. We've done better with women. Until a few
years ago the typical Second City cast was four men and two women.
Now most of them are three and three.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the changes, the talk over the weekend was mostly about
what has stayed the same. Older alumni and younger ones shared
reminiscences about their training, recalling stern taskmasters
Paul Sills, a noted curmudgeon (now a theater teacher and director
in Door County, Wis.) and Del Close.
</P>
<P>
   Close, who died last year, was a legendary influence on
generations of Second City performers, insisting on selflessness
onstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be cute in your work,'' Tina Fey, a 1990s alumna and now
a writer for ``Saturday Night Live,'' said, summarizing Close's
advice. ``He asked me, `What's this scene about?' And I said
something. He said, `This scene is about bad improv.'''
</P>
<P>
   Arkin, who is preparing to direct ``Taller Than a Dwarf,'' a new
play by Elaine May, on Broadway, said he relished Second City
particularly for what it has never yielded to the changing times.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only place in the country where you're allowed to
fail,'' he said. ``You're encouraged to fail, because that's how
you learn. Failure has become a moral issue in this country. You
fail at anything, you're a bad person. It's a disaster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
