A4596 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CAR-FRANCE-COX     12-20 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-FRANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR president France has cancer
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bill France Jr., who brought NASCAR into the national
limelight, faces a new challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The organization announced Monday that France, NASCAR's
president, has been diagnosed with cancer. Officials said France is
pursuing additional diagnosis and treatments but did not offer
details or identify the type of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors have told me that the illness is treatable,''
France said in a statement. ``I am anxious to begin treatment and
get on the road to recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My father is in good spirits,'' said France's son, Brian, who
serves as NASCAR's vice president. ``He is receiving expert medical
care, and we have the utmost respect and confidence in his medical
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The news about France surprised the stock-car-racing circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sorry to hear it,'' said Tom Beard, co-owner of the No.
36 Winston Cup team. ``I hope he treats it as aggressively as he
treats the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Motor Speedway general manager and president Ed Clark
was informed of the situation late Sunday night after getting a
call from NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a shock, and terrible timing by happening here
at Christmas,'' Clark said. ``We're going to put Bill France on our
prayer list and support him all we can. We hope he gets through
these treatments and whatever they else they can do, make a full
recovery and be active as long as he wants to be for a long, long
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill France is so important to so many people in this
business,'' Clark said. ``I'm sure he will fight this with the same
intensity he did to bring NASCAR to the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Felix Sabates, who owns the race teams of Sterling Marlin and
Kenny Irwin, said he talked to France on the telephone Sunday.
Sabates said France's health concerns were brought up during the
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bill) really didn't make that big of deal out of it,''
Sabates said. ``I had called him to talk about some issues with my
race teams. He just said he had undergone some treatments but
didn't go through a whole lot of details. But he didn't sound too
worried about it to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the doctors have said the illness is treatable, then I'm
sure he will recover. Bill is a fighter. He'll make it.''
</P>
<P>
   France, 66, owns NASCAR and International Speedway Corporation.
Last February, he turned over the day-to-day operation to Mike
Helton.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carvell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
