<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4597 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-20 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STUDYING THE EFFECTIVENESS OF A DUCK CALL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ We peered over the top of the duck blind,
largely concealed by eucalyptus branches spread across its top, and
watched Moto Duck do its thing.
</P>
<P>
   A low fog hung over the marsh. My partner, Bob Simms, and I were
dressed in camouflage, calling for mallards, sprig and wigeon. Moto
Duck, meanwhile, about 40 feet in front of the blind, set well
ahead of a spread of duck decoys, was near silent as it worked
away.
</P>
<P>
   At dawn, the fog seemed to break, we looked up and a flock of
seven spoonies came soaring in. We raised our shotguns, but
stopped, when right behind them came a flight of wigeon, then all
at once, a succession of mallards, sprig and buffleheads. For a few
minutes, the marsh came alive with so many ducks, at least 100,
that it was awe-inspiring for us to simply watch them fly over us.
</P>
<P>
   Did Moto Duck bring them in? Or was it the sudden break in the
fog? Simms' skilled calling? A light breeze that put a ripple on
the pond? Or the break of dawn when the entire world of nature
seems to come alive?
</P>
<P>
   On our right, a biologist from the University of California at
Davis, Josh Ackerman, was trying to determine the answer.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest controversy in wildlife in California, and spreading
quickly to the rest of North America, right now is the use of Moto
Duck, which attracts ducks by simulating the sound of flapping
wings, on waterfowl hunts _ and whether or not it gives hunters an
unfair advantage.
</P>
<P>
   That is why UC-Davis is undertaking a study in which hunters are
being logged for 100 days this season by scientists acting as
independent observers. The study is being funded by hunters with
the California Waterfowl Association.
</P>
<P>
   Under the biologists' supervision, Moto Duck is run for 30
minutes, and all activity is logged. Then, Moto Duck is turned off
for 30 minutes, and again, all activity is again logged. After this
winter's season, the results will be compiled to determine if Moto
Duck has resulted in a higher duck kill.
</P>
<P>
   The debate has become intense among some hunters. They have been
banned through a private agreement by some private duck clubs, such
as Capitol and several neighboring clubs in the Colusa Basin in
California's Sacramento Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A Moto Duck does not look a duck. It looks instead like a
strange mechanical device that was invented by a rocket scientist,
and it is posted three feet above the water. The key to the device
is a revolving blade, one side painted light, one side painted
dark, which is turned by a motor at a precise speed to simulate the
wingbeats of a landing mallard. There are now thousands of them in
use in California, having increased in large numbers suddenly in
the past year, now with many hunters using three and four of them
around their blinds. They cost from $180 to $250 each.
</P>
<P>
   Without knowing we were outdoors writers, Simms and I were
contacted as independent testers. A hunt was arranged through
UC-Davis at the Pioneer Duck Club east of Williams, a top club that
offers the opportunity to hunt a four-person blind for $160 total
for a day; unlike most duck clubs, there is no seasonal membership
fee. At 6:20 a.m., we pulled in, met club owner Jeanne Cave and
biologist Ackerman. Moments later, we fired up the outboard motor
on a small boat, and cruised through the fog across a pond that
looked like a Scottish moor, and reached a well-hidden platform
blind in tules, which included a hiding place for the boat.
</P>
<P>
   The experiment started at 6:41 a.m., when Ackerman started the
Moto Duck, timed for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing we noticed was the distant squawks of geese,
nowhere in sight, flying above the layer of fog.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen to the geese,'' Simms said. ``There must be thousand of
them up there.''
</P>
<P>
   A moment later, three teal sailed by, emerging so fast out of
the fog that we didn't even have a chance to say anything. Ackerman
immediately logged them on his study sheet. In the next five
minutes there arrived mallards, sprig, a single canvasback, and
more teal _ shadowed by the distant squawks of geese.
</P>
<P>
   When the first 30 minutes was up, Ackerman turned off Moto Duck.
At the time, a heavy fog again dropped down on the marsh. We then
sat there looking at each other, telling stories and eating a
strange breakfast/lunch. At one point, Simms was admiring a ham
sandwich, when four mallards suddenly divebombed us and continued
past. Our hearts pounded as we hoped for them to return, and Simms
grabbed his duck call and proceed to fill it with the partially
chewed bite of his ham sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the magic, fun and comradeship of a duck hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The test last three hours, and at 9:47 a.m., Ackerman called it
quits. We took 10 ducks, eight when the Moto Duck was running, and
passed on dozens of others because they arrived so fast out of the
fog that we found ourselves surprised.
</P>
<P>
   To this point in the season in California, using Moto Ducks has
been more productive than without, by generally a 5-to-2 ratio,
according to a well-connected insider, though these numbers are
unofficial.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman took wing samples from each of the birds in order to
age and classify them, and then left to assess his data.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Simms and I headed back to the blind, looked up at
the sky, now clearing, and watched the skeins of hundreds of Snow
geese, thousands in all, passing high overhead.
</P>
<P>
   We crouched down, watching them and Simms asked, ``Have you seen
the rest of my sandwich?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
