<HEADER>
A4606 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-WORLD-ACCESS21-COX     12-20 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-ACCESS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    World Access deals again
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ World Access on Monday announced a tentative deal for
a $650 million acquisition _ the second major purchase within days
for the rapidly growing, Atlanta-based telecom company.
</P>
<P>
   With a series of mergers, World Access is becoming an
increasingly high-profile provider of long-distance, data and other
services, mostly in Europe. Its latest target is Star
Telecommunications Inc. in a stock deal that will give World Access
the California-based company and its international long-distance
business, most of which is in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will give World Access annual revenue of more than $2.3
billion and will ``accelerate our plans to be a leading provider of
bundled voice, data and Internet services in key international
markets,'' said John D. Phillips, chairman and chief executive
officer of World Access.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, World Access announced an agreement to buy the assets
of Florida-based Long Distance International for more than $185
million in stock. That deal will give World Access about 20,000
corporate customers in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   World Access last year had revenues of just $152 million, but
has been on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this fall, World Access agreed to buy FaciliCom
International, a provider of long-distance services in Europe, for
$750 million. At the time, Phillips promised to ratchet up the
company's growth through more acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   FaciliCom had invested several hundred million dollars in
networks in 14 countries. By combining assets _ and continuing to
buy other companies _ World Access can make increasingly efficient
use of its long-distance network.
</P>
<P>
   That approach can let World Access handle each dollar of Star's
business more profitably, said analyst Stephen Shook of Wachovia
Securities. ``You can take a company losing money and make it very
profitable _ which is what I think is happening in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's rapid growth raises its profile in Europe, where
deregulation and growth are roiling telecom markets. That profile
also makes World Access itself a potential takeover target.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is, that from this point on, they will be a very
attractive,'' Shook said. ``Maybe MCI WorldCom, maybe Global
Crossing _ anyone who plays in the international market might be
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom, based in Jackson, Miss. , is already a substantial
minority stockholder.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, World Access announced plans to spin off its
$250 million-a-year equipment group in order to let management
concentrate on its European telecom business.
</P>
<P>
   After Monday's announcement, World Access stock was up 50 cents
a share to close at $20.875. Shares of Star jumped $2 to close at
$8.875.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
