<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Tuesday, Dec. 21 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-VOUCHER-EDUC (Cleveland) _ A federal judge threw out the
state's taxpayer-funded school voucher program Monday, saying it
violated the constitutional separation of church and state.
(Summary from wires) By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   VT-GAY-MARRIAGE (Boston) _ The Vermont Supreme Court ruled on
Monday that the state must guarantee the very same protections and
benefits to committed gay couples as it does to heterosexual
spouses. The decision stopped short of legalizing gay marriage but
threw open the legal door to it and left up to the legislature
whether Vermont will become the first state to take that step. By
Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   SC-REPUBS (Columbia, S.C.) _ Ever since Ronald Reagan's 1980
victory put South Carolina's primary on the map, it has had a
central place in Republican politics. Now, Sen. John McCain and
Gov. George W. Bush are campaigning as if South Carolina were
pivotal in their nomination fight. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SEX-SHOPS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The state's highest court ruled on
Monday that the Giuliani administration had overstepped its bounds
in trying to shut down adult businesses, a decision that could
affect dozens of stores, and is by far the Mayor's worst setback in
his drive to restrict X-rated bookstores and theaters. By Richard
Perez-Pena.
</P>
<P>
   INS-DEPORT (Rochester, N.Y.) _ The proposed deportation of an
Italian-born housewife and mother convicted of shoplifting, a woman
who has not lived in Italy since the age of five, is an example of
a common predicament that even sponsors of tough deportation laws
enacted by Congress in 1996 are now saying needs to be changed. By
Eric Lipton.
</P>
<P>
   EARNINGS-REPORTS (Undated) _ A penny is not worth much nowadays
except, oddly enough, on Wall Street. There, a penny a share in
company earnings can mean the difference between a stock that soars
and one that skids. The punishment that stocks regularly endure
from investors disappointed over the tiniest earnings misses has
put managements under pressure to deliver upbeat earnings
announcements even if the numbers do not support them. The result,
according to some Wall Street accounting experts, is a disturbing
trend. More and more companies, they say, are going to extremes to
paint a rosy picture of their operations _ so much so that the news
distributed by companies in news releases and conference calls with
analysts is increasingly suspect, they say. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ASSESS (Moscow) _ The West has long seen the development
of democracy in Russia as a check against the Kremlin's military
ambitions and a way to bridge the political divide between East and
West. But consider the results of Russia's Parliamentary election:
millions of Russians went to the polls and demonstrated their
support for the war in Chechnya by voting for candidates backed by
Vladimir Putin, Russia's hawkish prime minister. A news analysis by
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
</TEXT>
