<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BAD BEHAVIOR GIVING FOOTBALL ITS LUMPS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ I had a college professor who claimed sports
simply mirrors society at large. If so, the mirror in which we look
is cracked.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Charlotte, former Carolina Panther Rae Carruth is
accused of first-degree murder, the first active NFL player so
charged.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, running back Cecil Collins was arrested for burglary
after he broke into a couple's apartment. He had reportedly been
annoying the woman for two months before his 5 a.m. break-in on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Deep in the heart of Jerry Jones' Texas, the Cowboys have as
their starting defensive tackles Alonzo Spellman, who has a history
of mental problems, and Leon Lett, who has had several suspensions
for drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Former Ram Darryl Henley is in prison for drug trafficking and
threatening to kill a judge.
</P>
<P>
   New York Giants quarterback Kerry Collins nearly had his career
derailed by alcohol abuse before seeking treatment. Same thing with
teammate Christian Peter, who had incidents of violence against
women while at Nebraska That were fueled by alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco 49ers finally wised up and got rid of their
social blight from Nebraska, Lawrence Phillips, before he could do
more damage than insubordination.
</P>
<P>
   These are only some of the more recent abuses perpetuated by NFL
players. While these problems certainly exist in the larger
society, they are magnified when they occur in the over-hyped world
of sports. Furthermore, athletes seem to think they are immune from
the consequences of their actions. Sometimes they are. Money often
buys justice in our skewed society.
</P>
<P>
   While the Carruth case is truly tragic for the number of people
it affects, most of the offenses involving athletes are rather
tiresome and cliche, reflecting a class of young men who have a lot
of money and think they can get away with anything.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, NFL rosters generally have many more good guys than
bad guys. It's certainly newsworthy when an NFL player is accused
of a crime, but on a daily basis it's a pleasure dealing with the
league's solid citizens. On the 49ers that means guys like Bryant
Young, Junior Bryant, Tim McDonald, Steve Young and all the
offensive linemen, who are, almost by definition, solid guys.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it really doesn't matter what kind of a player a guy
is or was. What matters is the strength of his character and what
he stands for. The mirror may be cracked, but on either side the
view is still pretty good.
</P>
