<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY IS STILL OUT ON NEW BANK LAW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SHANNON BUGGS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congress caught up with the times last month and repealed the
Depression-era law that divided the banking, securities and
insurance industries.
</P>
<P>
   Banks had been getting around the law by setting up holding
companies that purchased brokerages and insurance companies, but
maintained the firewalls between the three businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But as the globalization of the economy forced U.S. financial
institutions into direct competition with foreign entities without
the same restraints, corporate leaders pushed Congress to pass a
new law.
</P>
<P>
   The result is the Gramm-Leach-Bliley law, which is named for
Texas Republican Sen. Phil Gramm and touted by him as the most
important banking bill in 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   It allows all sides of the financial services triangle to merge
and sell each other's products. Soon, you will be able to go to
your bank branch and talk to one person to apply for a loan, buy
stock and increase your life insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HOW WILL CONSUMERS BENEFIT? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What Big Business gets out of this is obvious: new ways to make
money.
</P>
<P>
   But what consumers get remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother used to be the idea about what government was,''
says Rob Schneider, staff attorney for the Austin, Texas, office of
the Consumers Union. ``More and more it's about the information
that corporations collect on us and that we have no oversight over
how it's used.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Travelers Group and Citicorp got approval last year
for their $72 billion merger, banks have been merging to keep up
and heralding the day when they will be one-stop financial shops.
</P>
<P>
   To compete, brokerages and insurance companies have rushed to
remake themselves into trusted financial advisers that do more than
sell stock and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Now that this new banking era has arrived, expect more corporate
marriages to produce financial giants that will dominate the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the new law say all the consolidating will save the
nation's consumers $15 billion annually in reduced fees and
charges. They point to the deregulation of the telephone industry
as an example of what is to come.
</P>
<P>
   But if you look at all the bank mergers in the past few years,
you'd be hard pressed to find a bank that significantly lowered its
fees after the marriage. Schneider says studies have shown you
still get your best interest rate deals on loans at credit unions
and small local banks.
</P>
<P>
   So, if the big banks don't turn out to be the convenient,
cost-effective option that you're looking for, you still have your
small home-grown banks.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens if your community bank decides it doesn't want
to lend you money?
</P>
<P>
   The new law relaxed enforcement of the Community Reinvestment
Act, which requires national and local banks to make loans in
neighborhoods the banks had neglected. Now any bank that receives a
satisfactory or higher CRA rating won't be audited again by federal
regulators for at least four years.
</P>
<P>
   Through meeting CRA requirements, banks learned that lending in
low-income and minority communities can be profitable. But the
inevitable economic downturn will come and someone needs to make
sure banks don't go back to ignoring some neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Find out how your bank plans to maintain its satisfactory or
excellent rating and hold them to those commitments.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PRIVACY NEEDS MORE PROTECTION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You also need to know that these new financial services
superstores don't have to ask your permission before passing on
your financial information to their subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   They just have to tell you what procedures they have in place to
to protect your privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Congress did give you the right to ask in writing that the
details of your financial life not be shared with telemarketers and
other companies outside the corporation. But it also gave
businesses a loophole. They can tell telemarketers and other third
parties all about you, as long as the outsider agrees not to pass
on the information.
</P>
<P>
   A last-minute amendment gave states the leeway to write stricter
privacy laws, but handling this issue in a piecemeal way could
leave some consumers unprotected. Count on the financial
institutions to battle more restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   As we wait to see how things shake out, we need to tell our
financial institutions what we want them to do. We are not
powerless in this brave new world of banking.
</P>
<P>
   We get a say every time we write a letter or a check.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
