<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GOOD TIME FOR REFLECTION AND CELEBRATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The anticipation of the new millennium _ spurred
on by countless publicists and marketing gurus _ has been building
for months now, even though its technical arrival, according to the
way we number our calendar, will be Jan. 1, 2001, still a year
away.
</P>
<P>
   But technicalities aside, the transition from 1999 to 2000 is a
good time for reflection and celebration. So, in the seasonal
spirit, here are some of my reflections:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; H  &LR; _ Historic. Let's hear it one more time for the previous
century, which took us from the horse and buggy to the space and
computer age in a mere 100 years. It produced an amazing collection
of advancements, tragedies and triumphs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A  &LR; _ Answers. Don't believe a political candidate in the new
year who claims that he or she has them all.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; P  &LR; _ Presidential race. This will certainly be the dominant
political story of 2000. Texas Gov. George W. Bush is still the
front-runner for the Republican nomination, but he will have to
fight to win it.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Arizona Sen. John McCain will be a tough
competitor in New Hampshire's key, early primary. The race for the
Democratic nomination is still a toss-up between Al Gore and Bill
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; P  &LR; _ Performance. Gov. Bush's mediocre performances in his
first two presidential debates raised questions about his readiness
for the Free World's top job. He did much better in his third
debate in Iowa, holding his own and maybe scoring a point or two
against chief rival John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The more ``free-flowing'' format of the latest candidate forum
may have been more suited to the governor's style. He also
benefited from the practice he received in his first two
encounters.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Y  &LR; _ Year (old). Gov. Bush's presidential plunge dominated the
political news so much in 1999 that it is easy to forget that the
Texas Legislature was in session for the first five months.
Lawmakers enacted some modest tax cuts and, more importantly for
the long term, increased funding for public education, cracked down
on social promotions in the schools, boosted health care for
low-income children and lowered the blood alcohol content limit for
drunken driving. For better or worse _ time will tell which _ they
also deregulated electric utilities.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; H  &LR; _ Health care. This will remain a burning issue. Political
candidates will promise reforms and improvements, but many people
will remain skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; O  &LR; _ Odd-numbered year. The new year will not be one. So state
legislators will be at home, trying to get re-elected, rather than
at the state Capitol, trying to make and kill laws.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; L  &LR; _ Losses. Many people lost someone in 1999. On a statewide
level, we marked the passing of Bob Bullock, a legendary figure who
had more influence over state government than any other single
individual in recent memory. On a personal note, we in the Houston
Chronicle's Austin Bureau mourned the death of Nadine Thompson, our
longtime secretary and receptionist and a kind and gentle friend.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; I  &LR; _ Ideas. Images. Political campaigns should be about ideas,
and many candidates actually offer some. Usually, however,
candidates spend more time and money fashioning or altering their
images, and image-conscious media consultants will make a ton of
money in the 2000 campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; D  &LR; _ Democrats. The Texas Democratic Party begins 2000 as it
began 1999 _ struggling. Democrats hold no statewide elected
offices in Texas. The party so far has been unable to recruit a
viable challenger for U.S. Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison. And if Gov.
Bush wins the Republican presidential nomination, the Democratic
nominee can forget about Texas, except for hitting up labor unions
and trial lawyers for campaign cash.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats will declare victory in 2000 if they can hold onto
their slim majority in the Texas House. If they can also reclaim a
majority in the state Senate, which is possible, they will be
beside themselves with glee.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A  &LR; _ Another year. The dispute over legal fees in Texas'
tobacco case didn't go away in 1999. The outside lawyers hired by
former Attorney General Dan Morales to fight the cigarette makers
told a federal judge that they will take huge payments from tobacco
companies and not from Texas taxpayers. That was a victory for
Morales' successor, John Cornyn, but Cornyn says he is still
investigating the lawyers' conduct. The lawyers deny any wrongdoing
and say the state should be grateful for the $17.3 billion
settlement they helped negotiate. How much longer will this soap
opera last? Another year? Another millennium?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Y  &LR; _ Y2K. The more advanced we become, the more helpless we are
without our advancements. Most people seem to be betting, though,
that predictions of Y2K disruptions will prove to be overblown.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; S  &LR; _ So long. Till 2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
