s t BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV26-NYT     12-20 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)  
(ms) 
 By PAUL FREIREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREGORIAN CHANT IN SPAIN
</P>
<P>
   Q. When in Madrid I would like to visit the Monastery of Santo
Domingo de Solis, renowned for concerts of Gregorian chants. Can
you tell me about trains or buses to the monastery, visiting hours
and how to arrange attending a concert? _ Victor M. Palacios,
Staten Island, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. The monastery, one of the oldest in Spain, is believed to
have been founded in the seventh century. Among the outstanding
elements of sculpture in the cloisters are biblical scenes, plants
and animals.
</P>
<P>
   Those considering mass transit from Madrid will find that
Saturday is the only day one can visit Santo Domingo de Silos,
which involves traveling by bus or train for three hours to Burgos
and then a 90-minute bus ride to Santo Domingo de Silos. On Monday
to Friday, the one bus a day from Burgos to Santo Domingo de Silos
arrives too late to catch the start of the 7 p.m. service, the last
one before visiting hours end at 9:30. On Sunday, there are no
buses. But on Saturday the bus from Burgos leaves at 2 p.m. (fare:
$3.80, based on 165 pesetas to the dollar).
</P>
<P>
   So you can take a train for Burgos from the Chamartin Station in
Madrid at 9:20 a.m. and arrive at 12:30 p.m. or the 10 a.m. and
arrive at 1:26 p.m. The fare is $43 first class, $31 second class.
Information: Rail Europe, (800) 438-7245. If you prefer a bus, take
Continental Auto, at Calle Alenza, 20, telephone (34) 91 533 0400.
The fare is $11.80 one way. To play it safe, you will want to leave
by 9. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bus line from Burgos to Santo Domingo de Silos is Autocares
Arceredillo. Telephone: (34) 947 48 52 66 or (34) 947 26 83 47. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the monastery, there are no Gregorian chant concerts as such.
Rather, the Gregorian chant is part of the service. The church is
open to visitors, with tours Monday through Friday from 6 a.m. to 2
p.m. and from 4 to 9:30 p.m. The hours at the cloister are Tuesday
through Saturday from 10 a.m. to 1 p.m. and 2:30 to 6 p.m., and
Sunday and Monday 2:30 to 6 p.m. A guided tour is $1.50. Entry is
free on Monday, but there is no guided tour.
</P>
<P>
   Services take place at 6 and 7:30 a.m. (8 on Sunday) and at
1:45, 7 and 9:40 p.m., with Mass at 9 a.m. (noon on Sundays and
holidays).
</P>
<P>
   Two alternatives to mass transit are renting a car in Madrid and
taking a 10-hour excursion such as one run by Ole Spain Tours in
Madrid, (34-91) 551 52 94, fax (34-91) 501 18 35;
www.olespaintours.com. The tour operates when visitors express an
interest in taking it. With a driver-guide, participants travel
across the Somosierra Mountains, stopping in Lerma and the historic
town of Covarrubias on the way to Santo Domingo de Silos. If there
are one to four passengers, the car is a Mercedes-Benz or the like;
for five or six, there's a minivan. Some sample per-person charges:
a total of two passengers, $181.50; four, $90.75; six, $69.75.
Meals are not included.
</P>
<P>
   To hear Gregorian chant on an Angel recording, as sung at the
monastery, visit
http://db2.-tunes.com/tunes-cgi2/tunes/release-/159072.
</P>
<P>
   STORAGE AT ZURICH AIRPORT
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does the Zurich Airport have storage lockers? We would like
to store luggage needed for a cruise, but not while we drive for a
week. _ Mary Grimes, Fairborn, Ohio
</P>
<P>
   A. The airport has lockers in both the arrival and departure
terminals. The cost per day is $3.15 a day per suitcase, based on
1.59 Swiss francs to the dollar. There is no discount for longer
storage. Should you need a luggage cart, you can get one free in
the baggage claim area, among other places.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK CONCERTS
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife, mother-in-law and I are looking for a company to
make arrangements for a New York trip in May or June for, say, four
or five classical music concerts but only one or two operas. _
Robert Jordan, Vancouver, British Columbia
</P>
<P>
   A. Though there are companies that can try to get concert
tickets _ and arrange for hotels, if you wish _ they do not have
concert tickets in stock, as they might for a Broadway show. So
there is no certainty that you will get what you want.
</P>
<P>
   In timing your trip, you might take note of the final
performances for the 1999-2000 season: the New York City Opera,
April 23; the Chamber Music Society of Lincoln Center, May 5; the
Metropolitan Opera, May 6, and the New York Philharmonic, June 3.
And at Carnegie Hall, once you get into May or June, the calendar
is not brimming with nationally known performers either.
</P>
<P>
   But those months are a fine time for dance, what with the
American Ballet Theater at the Met from May 8 to July 1 and the New
York City Ballet is at the New York State Theater from April 25 to
June 25.
</P>
<P>
   One company that can help plan your visit is Keith Prowse, 234
West 44th St., New York, N.Y. 10036; (800) 669-8687, fax (914)
644-8671. A five-night stay at the Roger Smith Hotel, on Lexington
Avenue near 48th Street, with four concerts will cost about $920 a
person, based on double occupancy, according to Jeremy Fenn-Smith
of the sales and marketing staff. Just what performances and dates
are ultimately selected will affect the price. If you just want
tickets, the cost of a seat at a New York Philharmonic concert will
typically range from $96.25 to $115, which reflects a 25 percent
charge for booking and handling.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is RMP Travel, 301 West 53rd St., New York,
N.Y. 10019; (212) 581-8051, fax (212) 956-8063. It tacks on a $25
service charge per ticket, according to Brigitta Haas,
international tour coordinator. Sample rates at two hotels RMP uses
are the following, per person, double occupancy: the Helmsley
Windsor Hotel, 100 West 58th St., is $470, and the Millennium
Broadway, 145 West 44th St., $620. Again, the dates will determine
the precise cost.
</P>
<P>
   You also might want to try Lincoln Center Visitors Services,
which designs packages that include a tour of Lincoln Center
theaters and concert halls; a beverage and dessert, or a full meal;
a concert and, perhaps, a preconcert lecture. Information: (212)
875-5370, fax (212) 875-5330.
</P>
<P>
   To cut costs, you might get in touch with the major halls
directly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For events at Lincoln Center, the number for information is
(212) 546-2656; for tickets, (212) 721-6500. The service and
handling charge is $5.75 a ticket. Events at Avery Fisher Hall and
Alice Tully Hall are listed on www.lincolncenter.org, those at the
Met are on www.metopera.org.
</P>
<P>
   Carnegie Hall, &UR;  &LR; (212) 247-7800; www.carnegiehall.org. A service
and handling charge of $4.75 a ticket applies to online, fax and
phone orders.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
