<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4629 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-INS-GAO-HNS &LR;      12-20 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INS-GAO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INS TO CONTINUE CAMPAIGN TO ADD MORE BORDER AGENTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Immigration and Naturalization Service said
Monday that it will press ahead with a $2.2 million effort to
recruit more Border Patrol agents and avoid a repeat of last year,
when INS fell well short of its goal of adding 1,000 officers.
</P>
<P>
   The INS' pledge to beef up its hiring of agents followed a
report that the Border Patrol gained only 369 officers in fiscal
year 1999, which ended Sept. 30. That increase raised to 8,351 the
number of patrol agents, 631 short of its goal, the General
Accounting Office reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 8,351 agents, 3,591 served along the Texas border with
Mexico. The 1999 Texas figure marked an increase from 3,460 agents
at the end of fiscal year 1998, the INS reported.
</P>
<P>
   The INS attributed its failure to meet the hiring goal to a
robust national economy and job market, which prompted many
would-be agents to opt for the more lucrative private sector.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the INS said it has generally hired about 4 percent
of its eligible Border Patrol applicants in past years. But, in the
tough 1999 labor market, it hired only 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To compete with private companies, the INS said it will consider
paying bonuses to new recruits and raising starting salaries, which
generally range from $30,451 to $42,531 per year with overtime. The
agency added that it will train more than 200 current Border Patrol
officers to help in the recruitment effort.
</P>
<P>
   In fiscal 1999, the INS suffered a four-year low in the number
of new Border Patrol hires. The 1,126 new agents failed to
compensate sufficiently for an uncommonly low attrition rate, 9
percent, in the patrol last year, reported GAO, an investigative
arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators placed much of the blame for the hiring shortage
on INS' failure to find enough qualified applicants and to retain
recruits through the employment process. The agency's recruitment
methods of media and billboard advertisements and campus hirings,
which had worked well in past fiscal years, failed in 1999, the GAO
said.
</P>
<P>
   One area where the INS fell short was in getting many of the
applicants who signed up for the Border Patrol's written
examination to actually take the test.
</P>
<P>
   Only 25 percent of the candidates who scheduled to sit for the
Border Patrol exam actually took it, the GAO said. The attendance
rate in prior years was a relatively high 40 percent, investigators
added.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO offered no explanation for the shortage of exam takers
and faulted the INS for failing to adequately survey applicants who
canceled their plans to join the Border Patrol. Information gleaned
from such inquiries of former candidates, especially those who had
quit late in the application process, could help the INS reverse
the reduction in new hires, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When faced with an impending hiring shortfall for fiscal year
1999, INS officials expanded their recruiting and hiring efforts in
an attempt to meet INS' hiring goal,'' the report stated.
``However, because INS had limited information on why applicants
withdrew from the hiring process, it may not be addressing all the
causes for the shortfall.''
</P>
<P>
   The INS declined to comment on whether the shortfall will
undermine the agency's ability to thwart illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are continuing to be vigilant along the borders,'' said INS
spokeswoman Nicole Chulick.
</P>
<P>
   INS chief Doris Meissner recently hailed the Border Patrol in
Texas as a model for law enforcement, saying that its forceful
presence has led to a 19 percent drop in crime near the border at
Brownsville since 1997. But Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, a leading
INS critic, has countered that illegal immigration remains a
problem in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to GAO's recommendation, the INS said it plans to
evaluate the feasibility of improving its system of surveying
applicants who withdraw from Border Patrol consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, in an effort to stem the flow of illegal immigration,
called on the INS in 1996 to increase the Border Patrol's ranks by
1,000 agents in fiscal years 1997 through 2001. The INS exceeded
the congressional goal in 1997 and 1998, raising the number of
agents by a total of 2,037.
</P>
<P>
   But fiscal year 1999 tarnished INS' earlier success, as the net
increase of 369 agents raised the three-year total to only 2,406
new officers, resulting in a shortfall of 594 agents from the
three-year goal of 3,000, the GAO reported.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
