<SLUG> BC-MACAU-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRATEFUL MACANESE WELCOME CHINESE TROOPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACAU _ China's troops streamed into this new Chinese territory
on Monday, in a joyful procession that revealed how deeply people
here yearn for law and order after the gangsterism that stained the
last years of Portuguese colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
   At high noon, 12 hours after the solemn ceremony in which China
gained sovereignty over Macau, a convoy of armored personnel
carriers, buses and trucks rumbled across the border from
neighboring Zhuhai, on the Chinese mainland. Less than an hour
later, the 500 troops secured their objective: a makeshift barracks
in a vacant apartment building in the center of Macau.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of people lined the route, cheering and waving
Chinese flags in a largely unscripted expression of hospitality. It
was a decided contrast to the handover of Hong Kong two and a half
years ago, when the arrival of the Chinese army was met with
ill-concealed dread.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am thrilled because the soldiers give me confidence,'' said
Lau Kit Leng, 34, a homemaker who waited outside on a bright but
chilly day. ``Security has been such a big problem in Macau. The
troops give me a reason to hope.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese army seems destined to play a very different role in
Macau than in Hong Kong. In well-policed Hong Kong, the troops have
kept a very low profile since the handover. They arrived in the
predawn darkness on July 1, 1997, and headed to their barracks,
where they have essentially remained since.
</P>
<P>
   In Macau, where the colonial administration could not stop a
gang war for control of the territory's lucrative casinos,
officials said the army would play a powerful symbolic role in
restoring law and order. On the streets Monday, several people said
that if the local police force was not up to the job, they would be
happy to see the army go after the gangsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course they should get involved in that,'' Mrs. Lau said as
she sheltered her 4-year-old daughter from the biting wind.
``That's why they're here.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmund Ho, the new chief executive of Macau, insisted that the
troops would not be used for police work. But he said they would
give people an overdue sense of safety. And he added that having a
garrison nearby would help him reform the Macau police force, which
has been plagued by corruption.
</P>
<P>
   The deployment of troops was a raw bone of contention between
China and Portugal in an otherwise smooth transfer of power.
Portugal, which withdrew its soldiers shortly after its revolution
in 1974, insisted that Macau was too small to require a military
garrison. And Portuguese officials said the joint declaration
governing the return of the colony did not provide for stationing
troops there.
</P>
<P>
   But early this year, China's deputy prime minister, Qian Qichen,
said the government planned to send an advance guard to the colony
even before the handover. His announcement came after other senior
Chinese leaders publicly chided the Portuguese for not doing more
to curb the gang wars.
</P>
<P>
   In March, President Jorge Sampaio of Portugal threatened to
boycott the handover ceremony if the Chinese did not explain why
they were not abiding by the agreement. After a visit to Lisbon by
China's president, Jiang Zemin, in October, Sampaio withdrew his
threat, saying he had been satisfied that the Chinese intended to
use the troops only for defense purposes.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview here on Sunday, Sampaio seemed eager to wash his
hands of the issue. ``China is China,'' he said. ``China has
sovereign rights. Macau is going to be a special region of China.''
By the time the Chinese troops arrived, the Portuguese president
and his entourage were long gone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
