<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4637 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-LEIBOVITZ-BOOK-4000(3     12-20 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEIBOVITZ-BOOK-4000(3TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTOGRAPHER'S BOOK SHOOTS DOWN FEMININE STEREOTYPES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW MARTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. _ Photographer Annie Leibovitz choreographs
her presence in the stark contrast of one of her black-and-white
shots. On this windy day in Miami Beach, the Atlantic's foamy
whitecaps paired with the egg-cream interior of the Tides Hotel to
form a pale backdrop to Leibovitz's brooding chic. With her
coal-black tails, turtleneck, pleated pants and watchband,
Leibovitz is a thundercloud of feral energy. It's a full Palm Pilot
day, and no lost hotel-room key, elevator breakdown or nagging cold
will derail her.
</P>
<P>
   No, the 5-foot-11-inch Leibovitz, who doesn't walk so much as
stride _ a predatory panther for space _ is not to be deterred. She
drowns her cold in a bath of chamomile tea spiked with Sue Bee
honey, satchels of pure vitamin C, and a room-service double
espresso _ hot milk on the side. It's her rocket fuel for a
promotional tour for ``Women'' ($75, Random House), Leibovitz's
latest collection of photographs, mixing her signature shots of the
notable and notorious with an assortment of perfectly obscure
women. A collaboration with writer Susan Sontag, who contributed
the book's introductory essay, Leibovitz's ``Women'' aims a
dispassionate, unpatronizing lens at the wide spectrum of women and
their pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theme for `Women' is who women are and what women look
like,'' Leibovitz says, raking her hands through tendrils of
blond-streaked hair. ``There were no big revelations from the work.
I didn't learn anything new about women, except that I really was
able to see women as a group of individuals. The book is less about
gender and more about individuality.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout her 30-year career, Annie Leibovitz has become the
f-stop Boswell to the infamously famous, the famously infamous, and
the garden-variety celebrity general, Olympic sprinter, Nobel Prize
winner, or Hollywood nymph du jour. At 50, she is arguably the most
recognized, if not the most accomplished, photographer of her
generation. Esteemed enough to have had several prints exhibited at
the National Portrait Gallery, Leibovitz is still insouciant enough
to mention a recent backstage photo session with Bruce Springsteen
as if it were a Kodak moment at a backyard barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   Leibovitz first made her name chronicling for ``Rolling Stone''
magazine the purple haze of rock 'n' roll's early days. When she
hitched a ride on the Rolling Stones' 1975 tour, Leibovitz not only
memorialized but sampled some of the pagan pleasures of the day.
With her subsequent work for ``Vogue'' and ``Vanity Fair'' plus her
advertising-as-art campaigns for American Express, The Gap and the
dairy industry (think: milk mustaches), Leibovitz carved out her
place as a distinctive portraitist.
</P>
<P>
   Her contemporary work is drenched in color, meticulously groomed
and glossy. Leibovitz plots her photos with a wise-cracking style.
Using witty props, she gently twits the personae in question while
revealing something poignant embedded in the air-brushed image.
This mix of deference and cheekiness has resulted in some of
contemporary photography's most hagiographic works. Consider Whoopi
Goldberg bathing in a tub of white milk, or John Lennon, coiled up
in a naked fetal position of devotion to Yoko Ono only hours before
he was killed. Remember the late John Belushi looking like a
forlorn hobo on his last hitchhiking jaunt? Most recently,
Leibovitz positioned the cast from ``The Sopranos'' in a modern-day
``Last Supper'' pose, playing on the show's penchant for betrayal
and gourmand eating. ``I really am not a glamour photographer,''
Leibovitz says. ``In all of my work, I humanize the celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Women,'' also the name of her splashy exhibition at
Washington, D.C.'s Corcoran Gallery of Art, breaks considerable new
territory by sending Leibovitz back to her reportage roots. It is a
throwback to on-the-fly production design. The project became a
hybrid of Leibovitz's ``Vogue'' and ``Vanity Fair'' work mixed with
her ramblings throughout America in search of women in all their
guises. The result is a Studs Terkel-on-celluloid gallery of female
farmers, bull riders, astronauts, socialites, maids, police
officers, carnival performers, doctors, corsaged debutantes and
factory workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wonderful truth of this book is that if Freud had seen it,
he couldn't possibly say what women really want because every
individual woman as portrayed by Annie wants something different,''
says feminist activist Gloria Steinem, herself a subject in the
book.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Women'' contains more than 120 images in a pastiche of
formats. They are divided roughly in half between black-and-white
and color pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was figuring this whole thing out as I did it,'' admits
Leibovitz. ``I was afraid that I would never be able to do the
project justice. It really could have gone on and on without end.
Frankly, when it comes down to it, I didn't want to let women
down.''
</P>
<P>
   The book's first photo makes Leibovitz's breaking-the-mold
intentions clear. Her unflinching black-and-white study of her
mother, Marilyn Leibovitz, is neither brutally critical nor treacly
sentimental. It is a maternal study done with the ripened affection
of an older daughter. ``The shot of my mother is the book's
dedication,'' says Leibovitz. ``After all, she is the first woman I
ever met.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the celebrity subjects, there is someone for everyone.
Actress Drew Barrymore lies supine on some California grass, her
diaphanous nightgown clinging to her downy skin. Martina
Navratilova, clad only in a Speedo swimsuit, hangs on with
Chaplinesque aplomb to an industrial gear-winch. Elizabeth Taylor,
accompanied by her faithful pooch, ``Sugar,'' is all Gloria Swanson
smile and vanity. And actress Christina Ricci is shot astride a
motel bed, clad only in a lacy camisole and sweater, exuding a
pouty Lolita-esque attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women'' does make some concessions to the powerful. In one of
the collection's most posed, and maybe least compelling shots,
Hillary Clinton peruses a document on a White House balcony, pen in
hand, a waxen study in gravitas.
</P>
<P>
   But these poised, camera-ready women are bit players in
``Women's'' drama, overshadowed by dozens of photos of women who
simply are. ``So this is what women are now _ as different, as
varied, as heroic, as forlorn, as conventional, as unconventional
as this,'' writes Sontag in the collection's preface.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Leibovitz's whole gallery of regular women radiates an
intrinsic beauty stripped of power-breakfast status or designer
fashions. There are the five female coal miners from Alabama's Jim
Walter No. 5 Mine, clothed in sooty thermal coveralls. There is
Lamis Srour, a teacher in Michigan whose coal-dark eyes stare out
from behind a black veil. And Shen Chu hunches over her sewing
machine, producing another garment for the Four Maples Ladies'
Blouse Co. in Manhattan's Chinatown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep in mind that Annie worked very hard to make the project
be a lot more than just well-known celebrities,'' says Paige
Turner, assistant curator of exhibitions at the Corcoran Gallery of
Art. ``She wanted women who wouldn't be the first choice of a
fashion-magazine editor.''
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding mawkish pity, Leibovitz's portraits of anonymous abused
women is the kind of sobering work worthy of a crime-scene photo.
The two women, one from Connecticut, the other from New York,
display all the swollen-eye marks of domestic violence, yet retain
a resilient dignity.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most of the photos, either the shots would be good or not
good, and if it wasn't good I wouldn't belabor it,'' says
Leibovitz. ``If it is good, frankly I probably didn't have so much
to do with it. I was simply a medium and it usually had more to do
with the sitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Annie Leibovitz spent her elementary-school years at Fort
Worth's Bruce Shulkey Elementary School (she can break out into the
school song on request), so it is no coincidence that she returned
to Texas often to photograph many of ``Women's'' subjects. Who best
to personify the Chanel-swathed ``ladies who lunch'' than the
troika of Pat Breen, Lynn Wyatt and Caroline Wiess Law caught in
mid-coffee, clucking at Tony's Restaurant in Houston? Then there's
former Texas Gov. Ann Richards, all aviators, khakis and pricey
shotgun, waiting to shoot the next lame duck. And no look at Texas
women would be complete without a shot of the Kilgore College
Rangerettes caught in a gravity-defying high kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas just has a great reservoir of subject matter,'' reflects
Leibovitz. ``Just a little visual statement on a Texas subject goes
a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   But no other series of photos crystallizes Leibovitz's theme of
the multifaceted roles women play than in her Las Vegas showgirl
series. In several ``before'' and ``after'' poses, four showgirls
are first displayed in their civies of halter tops and bluejeans.
Then, in vibrant color shots, the women disappear behind their
performing battle gear of rouge and rhinestone bustiers.
Leibovitz's shots transport the dancers from understated
embodiments of feminity to comic-book caricatures of pulchritude.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the most important pictures in the collection,'' says
Leibovitz. ``One of the dancers showed up looking a little like
Joyce Carol Oates before donning her Vegas costume and suddenly
becoming empowered by this armor. It just completely supported
Susan Sontag's line about women dressing up to look like `women.'
''
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   As the sun dips below Miami Beach's blushing horizon, Annie
Leibovitz awaits her room-service order (it has to be taken up
eight flights of stairs because of a conked-out elevator) and takes
some time to deconstruct her ``Women's'' work.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, making the final edits proved to be quite difficult,
knowing that it was completely up to me,'' says Leibovitz between
restorative sips of chamomile tea. ``But then it became a very
freeing experience. I became this monster, and there was no turning
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Thinking back to ``Women's'' origins in November 1995, Leibovitz
recounted her peripatetic cycle of photo sessions. In one frequent
flying odyssey, Leibovitz jetted to Taos, N.M., to shoot painter
Agnes Martin before hopping over to Los Angeles for a Courtney Love
session, only to red-eye it back to the East Coast for a 5 a.m.
bulb-garden photo-op with Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``In between her insanely busy schedule for `Vanity Fair' or
`Vogue,' she would make time to shoot cheerleaders in Texas,'' says
David Harris, design director at `Vanity Fair.' ``At the end, I
think Annie produced some of the best work she's ever done.''
</P>
<P>
   To achieve that level of perfection, Leibovitz would seek out
the most perfect locale. She reportedly drove around rural Oklahoma
for four hours to find the desolate area near the headquarters of
the Cherokee nation for the pickup truck shot of Gloria Steinem and
Wilma Mankiller.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that very Oklahoma moment, Annie caught us on the edge of
that truck, understanding that Wilma and I are very close
friends,'' recalls Steinem. ``Trying to show life, not artifice,
adding a bit of Diane Arbus realism _ it all says such good things
about Annie.''
</P>
<P>
   The operative mood Leibovitz created with most of her subjects
was one of ease, from the most inexperienced sitter to the most
savvy. When Hillary Clinton confessed that the White House's
sun-drenched balcony was one of the few places where she could seek
refuge, Leibovitz coaxed her into sitting at her desk there.
Stealthily, Leibovitz began to work, and before the first lady knew
it, the session was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``While doing these sessions, I didn't talk to the subjects
about pretending not to be there,'' Leibovitz says. ``I actually
talked about taking the picture, but tried not to put their lives
too far out of joint while photographing them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Women'' also provided Leibovitz that rare opportunity to work
with what she diplomatically terms ``unprofessional sitters,''
otherwise known as camera-shy mortals. The Alabama miners were
quite giddy at the prospect of an Annie Leibovitz photo shoot.
``Frankly, the celebrity subjects became less and less interesting
as I went along,'' admits Leibovitz. ``More and more celebrities
bit the dust because I realized that this project could not have 20
actors and one schoolteacher.''
</P>
<P>
   The shooting sessions for ``Women'' also occasioned wonderfully
unrehearsed moments of creativity. Wanting to capture newly buff
actress Sigourney Weaver in a slinky ``Cabaret'' style, Leibovitz
scheduled a massive two-day shoot. She ended up using the very
first Polaroid studies of Weaver.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone has been completely enamored of Leibovitz's latest
effort. Some feel that in trying to depart from her usual style,
Leibovitz succumbed to mimicking a consortium of other
photographers' work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Largely, the images we see are Annie Leibovitz copies of other
people's pictures,'' says Mary Panzer, curator of photographs at
the National Portrait Gallery. ``There is no organizing principle
behind this book other than that Annie Leibovitz has photographed
these women. As a viewer, I feel shortchanged, as I don't really
know what Annie Leibovitz really thinks about these people.''
</P>
<P>
   Leibovitz doesn't bridle at this criticism. She is the first to
admit that ``Women,'' while good, is flawed and that she could have
put in another year to iron out all its kinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize there are a variety of styles out there that I can't
help but be influenced by,'' says Leibovitz. ``But no matter how
much you are influenced by different photographers, you do end up
with your own look. Frankly, if there is any legitimate criticism
of my work, it is that I'm not hard-edged enough in my shots _ that
I'm a bit of a wimp. With `Women,' I'm trying to have a stronger
edge.''
</P>
<P>
   She will take issue with criticism that her celebrity actually
overshadows the actual subject matter, warping the final art. ``I
just don't see it getting in the way of the fundamental situation
of putting someone at ease and then just taking the picture,''
Leibovitz says, sounding more intrigued than irritated.
</P>
<P>
   Promoting ``Women'' has given Leibovitz the rare opportunity of
taking a reading of who is buying her book. She has been pleasantly
surprised by the number of male customers. ``Frankly, I was afraid
there might be nothing but girls in motorcycle jackets buying it,''
says Leibovitz. ``But I'm getting men buying books for their
mothers and sisters, wives and girlfriends. And I don't think
they're doing it just to score points.''
</P>
<P>
   She has also discovered that these photos, more than any others
in her illustrious catalog, have sparked an unexpected misty-eyed
response. ``Yesterday, a woman at a book signing just started
crying when talking about the battered-women photos,'' Leibovitz
says. ``The book seems to be a very emotional kind of breakthrough
for a lot of women.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, ``Women'' has gotten Leibovitz thinking about where she
would like her career to go next. ``Sure, I have mixed feelings
about what I'd like to do more of,'' she says. ``This book has the
more quiet work, the kind of nonconceptual things that my magazine
editors get nervous about. It's work that is very emotionally
moving to me. In the end, it's probably the best work I've ever
done.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be, but all the career fulfillment and accolades
showered on Leibovitz's recent work haven't shifted her priorities.
Scurrying to finish the interview, Leibovitz has to catch a plane
for her next assignment. It may be her year's most meaningful. It
will pay her zip. She is off to San Francisco to shoot her nephew's
bar mitzvah.
</P>
<P>
   (Star-Telegram researcher Shannon Canard contributed to this
report.) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
