<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)  
(ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCYTHIAN TREASURES TO TOUR U.S. MUSEUMS
</P>
<P>
   For 400 years the Scythians, a tribe of nomadic horsemen, ruled
over the European steppe stretching from the Danube, east across
what is now Ukraine and into Russia, with their reign reaching its
height more than 2,500 years ago. Among the legacies of their
culture is some of the most accomplished gold artwork ever
produced.
</P>
<P>
   Some 170 of these artifacts from the Museum of Historical
Treasures of Ukraine-Kiev, the Institute of Archaeology of the
Academy of Sciences of Ukraine-Kiev and the State Historical
Archaeological Preserve-Pereiaslav may now be seen at the San
Antonio Museum of Art, where the exhibition ``Gold of the Nomads:
Scythian Treasures From Ancient Ukraine'' will run through Jan. 30.
Over the next year, the objects will travel to the Walters Art
Gallery in Baltimore, the Los Angeles County Museum of Art, the
Brooklyn Museum of Art, the Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art in Kansas
City, Mo., and the Grand Palais in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the lavish gold jewelry, vessels and weaponry, which
were found in burial mounds known as kurhans in Ukraine, were
commissioned by the Scythians from Greek workshops along the
northern coast of the Black Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Among the objects on display are a gold helmet with combat
scenes depicted in relief, plaques decorated with images of winged
dragons, fourth-century Sphinx earrings, a fourth-century gold
headdress, swords, scabbards and daggers. Most of the objects were
only recently excavated and will be viewed for the first time
outside of Ukraine. These treasures probably represent only a
fraction of the Scythian legacy; experts say some 40,000 kurhans
await excavation.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio Museum of Art, 200 West Jones Street, is open
Tuesday to Sunday. General admission is $5, $1.75 ages 4 to 11, $4
ages 65 and up and for students; admission to the Scythian
exhibition is an additional $5 a person regardless of age.
Information: (210) 978-8100.
</P>
<P>
   A BIGGER BEAUBOURG FOR THE 21ST CENTURY
</P>
<P>
   At 11 a.m. on Jan. 1, the Georges Pompidou Center (or Beaubourg,
as Parisians call the museum, after the street that runs behind it)
reopens its doors after more than two years of renovation. About
5,000 square feet of exhibition space have been added to France's
most significant modern art collection, along with an expanded
library, a rooftop restaurant, a cafe and boutique on the mezzanine
overlooking the lobby and a series of auditoriums on the lower
level for film screenings and dance, theater and music
performances.
</P>
<P>
   The soaring entrance hall on the Piazza, or Place Georges
Pompidou, the heart of the Pompidou Center and now its sole
entrance, is marked by a large awning (visitors will no longer have
free access to the roof terraces via the exterior escalator). The
heating and air-conditioning were updated, handicap access was
improved and 370 computer stations with Internet connections were
added in the library. Renovations of the lower level and ground and
first floors were designed by Renzo Piano, one of the museum's
original architects (the other was Richard Rogers). Originally
conceived to receive 5,000 visitors a day, the Pompidou Center was
attracting a daily attendance of 25,000 following its 1977 opening,
requiring numerous face lifts since. The most recent and most
extensive has cost $88 million.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth and fifth floors of the Pompidou Center will be
dedicated to the permanent collection, which includes works by
Braque, Picasso, Matisse, Kandinsky and Dubuffet. Nearly 1,500
works will be on view at one time (they will be rotated every 18
months to show the entire collection), compared with 800 before the
renovation. The redesigned and enlarged sixth floor will be set
aside for temporary exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Le Temps, Vite'' (Jan. 18 to April 10) will be the major
inaugural exhibition, with artwork in different mediums reflecting
the changing perception of time. Another inaugural exhibition,
``Jour de Fete'' (Jan. 1 to Feb. 28), will present the work of nine
contemporary French artists, including Marie-Ange Guilleminot,
Pierrick Sorin and Xavier Veilhan.
</P>
<P>
   Admission is $4.75; $3.15 for students 18 and over and free for
those under 18, at 6.3 francs to dollar; between $4.75 and $7.95
for temporary exhibits (free for those under 13) and free for all
on the first Sunday of every month. The Center, at Place Georges
Pompidou in the fourth arrondissement, will be open Wednesday to
Monday 11 a.m. to 9 p.m. (until 10 p.m. weekends). For information
see the Pompidou Center Web site, www.centrepompidou.fr, or call
(33-1) 44.78.12.33.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON MONUMENT CLOSES (ONCE AGAIN)
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Monument has closed for the third time during its
renovation and should reopen well before its completion goal of
July 4. In this last stage, the observation levels at 490 and 500
feet will be refurbished, and the elevator cab upgraded.
</P>
<P>
   Since the renovation began two years ago, 36,000 exterior stones
have been inspected on the 555-foot obelisk, with 78 of them having
to be repaired. In addition, 62,304 linear feet of joints were
repointed, and its entire surface (94,060 square feet) was cleaned.
A lot of dirt had accumulated since the last cleaning, in the
1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Once the cleaning is finished, the scaffolding system designed
by the architect Michael Graves will be removed, and the monument's
surface will be visible again.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone will be happy when that happens. The scaffolding,
which is covered by a fabric that mimics the design of the stones,
turned out to be a popular attraction, especially at night when
lights make the monument look like a beacon.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED EXPANDS FLIGHTS FROM THE WEST COAST
</P>
<P>
   Since designating Los Angeles International Airport as a hub
last spring, United Airlines has been steadily expanding its West
Coast operations. In September the airline inaugurated direct
nonstop service between Sacramento and Washington and between Los
Angeles and Dallas, Houston and Atlanta. In addition, service from
Los Angeles to Miami and Orlando and from San Jose to Washington
was expanded. At the end of October shuttle service using 737s was
introduced from Los Angeles to Santa Barbara, Palm Springs and San
Diego, and _ outside the state _ to Reno and Medford, in southwest
Oregon. There are two round-trip shuttles to Medford every day,
three to Reno, four to Santa Barbara and Palm Springs, and seven to
San Diego.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Information and reservations: (800) 241-6522 or www.ual.com.
</P>
<P>
   A TRAIN CALLED BETSY DEBUTS IN BANGKOK
</P>
<P>
   Since Dec. 5, Bangkok's visitors and commuters have been
traveling faster along busy Sukhumvit and Silom Roads aboard the
Bangkok Elevated Train System, officially called the Skytrain and
unofficially dubbed Betsy.
</P>
<P>
   The 14.6-mile electric train line serves many hotels, such as
the Dusit Thani and Oriental, and several shopping centers, with a
central station at Siam Square. It extends far along Sukhumvit Road
past the Ekamai bus terminal, and in the other direction past
Victory Monument as far as the Chatuchak weekend market. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The elevated trains run 6 a.m. to midnight, with an expected
650,000 passengers daily. The trains will initially be three cars,
with 126 seats each, expanding to six cars as demand grows. Fares
are 10 to 40 baht (about 40 cents to $1, at 38.55 baht to $1),
depending on distance traveled. Tickets are sold at ticket counters
and vending machines at stations.
</P>
<P>
   The Skytrain is so far the most successful of three mass transit
projects planned for Bangkok, the other two being the financially
troubled Hopewell elevated train and highway system and a subway
due for completion in about two years. The Skytrain has had its own
troubles, including protests from those in wheelchairs about the
lack of elevators, a matter unresolved. Bangkok's governor, Bhichit
Rattakul, has promised 11 elevators to serve at least five main
stations in the 23-station network. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Traffic was light when the system made its debut Dec. 5 because
it was the 72nd birthday of Thailand's beloved monarch, King
Bhumibol Adulyadej, a national holiday. The elevated train posed
one protocol puzzle: would trains stop, as does everything and
everyone else in Thailand, when a royal motorcade passes by, or
even underneath?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have talked about this matter with the Secretarial Royal
Palace,'' a spokesperson for the transit system replied. ``The
palace allows the Skytrain to run normally with no stop on this
regard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Skytrain has an Internet site, with route map, fare finder
and links to maps of individual stations: www.bts.co.th/mapeng.htm.
</P>
</TEXT>
