<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4644 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-R-SCI-BETHLEHEM-COIN-     12-20 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SCI-BETHLEHEM-COIN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARK! A COIN LINKS BETHLEHEM'S STAR TO JUPITER RISING IN APRIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeats to add graphic note)  (Eds.: This story was budgeted earlier as SCI-BETHLEHEM-STAR) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Star of Bethlehem has been called many things by many
people: a comet, a conjunction of planets, a supernova, a miracle,
a myth. With just one biblical account, in the book of Matthew, of
the star and how it caused the wise men to come to Judea in search
of the newborn Jesus, exactly what it was, if it was anything at
all, remains an open question.
</P>
<P>
   That question has attracted yet another answer, one that is
gaining attention from historians of astronomy for its unusual
approach. Dr. Michael R. Molnar, an astronomer and physicist and
former teacher at Rutgers University, proposes that the star was
the planet Jupiter, seen in the constellation Aries the ram.
</P>
<P>
   Molnar even offers a date for its appearance: April 17, 6 B.C.
On that day, he argues in a new book, ``The Star of Bethlehem: The
Legacy of the Magi'' (Rutgers University Press), Jupiter reappeared
as a morning star (after days when it rose, invisibly, only during
daylight hours) and was also hidden briefly by the Moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jupiter was considered to be the regal star or regal planet,''
Molnar said in an interview. Thus the two events on the same day
would have been looked upon by the wise men, or magi, who were
astrologers, as strong portents of the birth of a great king. The
fact that Jupiter appeared in Aries, in the east, had further
significance, Molnar said, as Aries was considered the symbol of
Judea.
</P>
<P>
   Molnar studied many ancient astrological texts, including the
Tetrabiblos of Ptolemy from the second century A.D., to try to
understand how astrologers of the time would have interpreted
events in the sky. When looked at in this way, other theories about
the star are easily refuted, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Supernovas, for instance, are exciting events but were virtually
ignored by astrologers, not considered omens of anything. A comet
was an omen for bad, not good _ for war or civil unrest or death,
not for the birth of a king. It is the reliance on an ancient view
of things that has earned Molnar's book praise from some historians
of astronomy, including Dr. Owen Gingerich, a professor of
astronomy and the history of science at the Harvard-Smithsonian
Center for Astrophysics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one of the few works on this subject that is
historically sensitive to the era,'' Gingerich said. ``He's not
just trying to think from modern terms of how we'd look for a star
in the sky. He's painted a very plausible historical picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Molnar pored over numerous old texts and star charts to come to
his conclusions. But he first began formulating his idea while
looking at something else: a Roman coin. That coin, which Molnar
bought for $50 at a New York show for his collection, was minted in
Syria around A.D. 6. It showed Aries looking back over his shoulder
at a star. ``I thought, `Why did these people put Aries the ram on
there?''' he said. The Romans, he learned, annexed Judea in A.D. 6,
and Aries first appeared on Roman coins in that year. That told him
that Aries was a symbol for Judea, a fact confirmed by reading
Ptolemy.
</P>
<P>
   While stars occur often on Roman coins, the star on this coin,
combined with the symbolism of the ram, got him thinking that
something happened in Aries related to Judea. From there it was a
question of conducting research until he found out what that
something could have been.
</P>
<P>
   His date for the star's appearance is consistent with many
scholarly estimates of the year of Jesus' birth. It is generally
accepted that Jesus was born within two years of the death of the
Judean King Herod, which has commonly been put at 4 B.C. But that
date has been called into question in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jack Finegan, an emeritus professor at the Pacific School of
Religion in Berkeley, Calif., and author of ``The Handbook of
Biblical Chronology,'' a standard reference on the subject, now
puts Herod's death more likely at 1 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   John Mosley, program director at the Griffith Observatory in Los
Angeles and an expert on the Star of Bethlehem, said that while it
may never be possible to know what the star was, ``when Herod died
was an actual event and should be knowable.'' If Herod died in 1
B.C., he added, ``you can't stretch the birth of Jesus back to 6 or
7 B.C.''
</P>
<P>
   From a religious perspective, such questions of timing may not
matter, said Dr. Alan Altany, an associate professor of religion at
Marshall University in Huntington, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of biblical scholars would say that the truth of the
story is not dependent on whether there was a star,'' Altany said.
The book of Matthew was written some 50 years after the death of
Jesus, Altany said, and the writer may have been using a star
symbolically. ``Whenever a ruler was born, there usually was a star
connected with his birth,'' he said. By including a star in his
account, the writer of Matthew was ``putting Jesus up there with
the other heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   Molnar realizes as well that at some point, any discussion of
what the star might have been, particularly one that sets a
specific date, involves an act of faith. ``I cannot prove that
Jesus was born at that time,'' he said. ``The evidence is there for
other people to judge for themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
