<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'PORK' LIST SHOWS PATH OF POWER
 &HT;    Eds: Bullet items at end could run as graphic element.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional appropriators decided ``who was
naughty and who was nice enough'' for federal grants, according to
a report Monday that identifies 1,348 pet projects in the recently
passed federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., issued the ``Year 2000 Pork List'' of
earmarked projects that, he charged, have distorted the spending
process and funneled dollars into the states of the most powerful
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska was a big winner in the listing. The sparsely settled
state would receive $125 per capita in specially designated federal
grants. Alaska's senior senator, Ted Stevens, is a Republican who
chairs the Senate Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia, which ranks 35th among the states in population,
was among the top 10 in winning federal grants, averaging $33.60
per person. That state has the top-ranking Democrat, Robert C.
Byrd, on the appropriating panel.
</P>
<P>
   Other big winners were Mississippi, home of Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, a Republican. His state averaged $11.60 per
person. Alabama garnered $11 per person in earmarked projects and
Kentucky about $10.75.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, California's lawmakers obtained more total grants,
but the spending for that most populous state averages only about
$3.40. The per capita ``pork'' spending for Texas is only about
$1.40.
</P>
<P>
   So-called ``losers'' also include Georgia, averaging $2.15 per
person, North Carolina at $2.30, and Ohio at $2.05.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn's ``Year 2000 Pork List'' is taken from the $617 billion
that Congress recently approved for so-called discretionary
government spending, excluding programs such as Social Security,
Medicare and other mandatory spending.
</P>
<P>
   His office found that the number of projects ``earmarked'' by
lawmakers for their home districts had doubled since last year for
the Labor-Health and Human Services legislation, which has long
been considered prime pork territory.
</P>
<P>
   The practice of seeking special interest funding ``creates at
least the appearance of corruption,'' Coburn said. ``Some
politicians think they prove their worth by bringing home the bacon
to their constituents. The expected reward for doing so is support
in the next election.
</P>
<P>
   ``In essence, earmarking creates the appearance that incumbent
politicians are using public funds to help our their own
re-election. It may not be illegal, but this is the sort of thing
the old-time bosses meant by 'honest graft.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Coburn is far less harsh in his criticism than Sen.
John McCain of Arizona, the Republican presidential candidate who
has cited more than $14.6 billion in pet projects.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn's definition of pork is much narrower, limited to grants
that are clearly designated for particular recipients. His pork
list totals only about $1.5 billion. And he does not include
billions of dollars in military programs and weaponry that Congress
has required the Pentagon to spend, often to the benefit of their
home states.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of this kind of spending, including Stevens and Byrd,
have defended it as evidence of working hard for constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn argues that the job of Congress is to approve the general
outlines of programs, not to designate the details of the spending.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 1,348 items on his ``pork'' list:
</P>
<P>
   _ A package of $50,000 grants for computer aid for 20 school
systems in the district of Rep. Bob Riley, R-Ala. His spokesman
Pepper Bryars, said the schools needed special assistance, since
they are among the lowest in the nation in use of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _ $400,000 for construction in Springfield, Mass., of a national
memorial park honoring the late children's author Theodore Geisel,
known as Dr. Seuss.
</P>
<P>
   _ $1.2 million to renovate a gateway to historic downtown
Madison, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   _ $500,000 for development of a new facility for the Harriet
Tubman African American Museum in Macon, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   _ $200,000 to buy land for the Tool Town precision metal working
park in Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   _ $800,000 for technology for community policing in Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   _ $4 million to develop a ski area for the Special Olympics in
Anchorage, Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
