<HEADER>
A4649 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w CANSPRINGBEFARAWAY? &LR;      12-20 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 CAN SPRING BE FAR AWAY?  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ I saw the first robin of the winter season this
weekend, bob-bob-bobbing along, all fat and sassy. Its arrival is
so premature I longed to buy it a wool muffler. When I was growing
up in the Midwest, it was a major event to spot the first robin,
whose appearance sometime in April meant spring was coming at last.
</P>
<P>
   Now this unexpected holiday presence seems a good omen not just
for continued mild weather but for happy times in the new century.
</P>
<P>
   Some places will still have a white Christmas, but we here on
the East Coast head
</P>
<P>
   toward a fresh year with temperatures so balmy that the trees
and plants are as impatient for spring as the birds. In New York,
200 miles north of here, snowdrop bulb shoots are up and forsythia
is in bloom. Here in the nation's capital, the boldest trees
suddenly have that lime-colored feathery look that signifies infant
leaves aborning.
</P>
<P>
   Federal scientists say that in the contiguous 48 states 1999
will go down as one of the warmest years on record and the trend is
likely to continue.
</P>
<P>
   We are indeed a warm and contented nation these days, both
physically and emotionally. We are in a far better mood than last
year at this time. What a difference a year makes.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 19, 1998, the House of Representatives impeached
President Clinton for lying and assorted sins stemming from his
illicit affair with a White House intern. We were tormented by
disgust and divided by partisan rancor. Things were ugly. The
government was immobilized.
</P>
<P>
   The first momentous act of this year was the Senate acquittal of
the president, keeping him in office and avoiding the inevitable
chaos of a transfer of power that an overwhelming majority of
voters told pollsters they opposed. (To this day, 57 percent of
those surveyed still say the Senate action was correct, down 11
percentage points from the number who felt that way during the
trial but still a clear majority.) The acquittal did not wipe out
the stigma Clinton will forever bear of becoming the first elected
president to be impeached, but it did quiet the political uproar.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and Congress put up a facade of working
together, but tempers did not cool sufficiently for any major
legislative achievement. It will not be possible next year either
in the midst of the 2000 presidential campaign. We need a breather.
We need another voter referendum to demonstrate the popular will.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of House Speaker Newt Gingrich, that ``family
values'' champion recently discovered to have been a six-year
adulterer, and his almost-successor Rep. Bob Livingston, who quit
the House to avoid exposure of his own infidelity, took some of the
partisan sting out of Clinton's misbehavior. Republicans can be
scoundrels too. The GOP no longer has a political lock on moral
values.
</P>
<P>
   But as a country we are still uneasy about our ethical standards
_ or lack of them.
</P>
<P>
   For all their moralizing, politicians do not have the answers.
Instead, religious values have taken on new political importance.
</P>
<P>
   Violence, particularly in the schools, is deeply troubling.
Something in our culture needs fixing, and there is no consensus to
point the way. We will have to deal with it in the next century. A
democracy is a work in progress. There is always unfinished
business _ in education, in retirement security, in abusive
campaign practices.
</P>
<P>
   The key to our present overall satisfaction is peace and
prosperity, the two traditional pillars of political stability. We
are in an unprecedented period of economic growth, spread unevenly
but widely enough to touch most of us. American soldiers are not
dying on foreign soil in some dimly understood cause. There are
wars around the globe, but we are basically keeping our military
distance.
</P>
<P>
   Since welfare reform, the rolls have been cut in half. The
violent crime rate has also dropped dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 presidential campaign is already down to two
Republicans and two Democrats, all qualified, substantive men. No
matter which one wins, the republic will be in safe hands. (I'm
ignoring the Reform Party, which is a joke and hasn't a chance
anyway.)
</P>
<P>
   The debate over the issues is sometimes heavy going, more for
policy wonks than ordinary folk, but it may be useful to the future
of the country.
</P>
<P>
   It is a good time to be alive and an American. It may not yet be
springtime in this country, but the turn of the century is a
wonderful moment for robins.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
