<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARROLL, FACING PRESS, TALKS OF RESETTING GOALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Pete Carroll was sullen and humble Monday as
he faced the media horde for the first time since learning he would
not be going to the playoffs for the first time in his tenure with
the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke about winning the remaining two games and challenged
his players when he said, ``I'll take those who want to go with me.
It's very important that we need to reset our goals. We need to be
winners. We'll play guys that feel the same. This is a new time for
us since we've been here, since we've not been in a situation where
the playoffs weren't at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   He made his players rewatch the film and never called any of
them quitters, but he certainly implied that some played harder
than others. He said he was not ready to throw in the towel and
play Michael Bishop or certain other rookies. He felt very strongly
about ending the season on a winning note, and he's curious how his
team will respond to the knowledge that they're playing for pride.
</P>
<P>
   The players came and went without much to say.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Jefferson was still quite upset about missing the playoffs
for the first time as a member of the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't go out last night,'' said Jefferson. ``My wife is a
Lakers fan, and we were going to go to the (Celtics) game, but I'd
be embarrassed to show my face in public after a game like that. I
didn't even go out to eat. My wife asked me if I took this all too
personally, and I said to her, `This is how I am, and this is how I
respond to losing, especially losing like this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said he didn't see Larry Whigham celebrating after his
blocked punt, but the coach came down on Whigham Monday after
watching the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't sit with me,'' said Carroll. ``That's one of
those plays that it has to be your mindset that you finish the
play. It was a bad mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   After Whigham met with Carroll, he admitted his mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just very enthusiastic, but I learned something from
that play,'' said Whigham. ``You have to finish plays, and I'll do
that from now on.'' Asked if he could have made the subsequent
tackle considering the play was well away from him, ``I'm not sure,
but given a great effort, you never know what can happen,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Whigham also believes the players will ride Carroll's coattails
toward a strong finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing the competitive nature of this team, I know they'll
want to win the next two games more than anything to save
something,'' said Whigham.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson said Carroll warned them to stay focused against the
Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many times he warned us about Philadelphia,''
he said. ``He told us that we had to be at the top of our game.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Whigham, ``I think there was an acceptance of what was
going on. I'm not saying anybody quit, but everyone accepted it.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither player believes the Patriots need to start from scratch.
They both think minor tweaks will produce a very good team next
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speaking from a personal viewpoint, I don't think it's a
matter of rebuilding,'' said Whigham. ``I just think it's a matter
of guys getting their heads out of their behinds. From an owner's
perspective, he looks at trying to get better every year, so I'm
not sure how he feels about the situation. He pays a lot of money
to the guys to go out and win games, and we haven't been doing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll continued to defend offensive coordinator Ernie Zampese,
who will surely take the fall along with the head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have strong feelings about Ernie,'' said Carroll. ``In
Monday's game, we had plenty of shots, or we didn't throw the ball
where we should have. Ernie can't catch the ball for them, but he
gave them a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   It is in these tough times that veterans have to step up and
take control. And that's precisely what Terry Allen (two fumbles)
did not do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really disappointed,'' said Carroll. ``Putting the ball
on the ground two times. We had to sit him down and challenge him
and get him back out there. He didn't run the ball that well after
that, but Terry is one of the guys I've depended on as an
experienced guy in a tough situation who can handle it. He has been
that. But we didn't need that to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got away with his first fumble. On the second one, Heath
Irwin was trying to make a block and hit the ball with his foot.
He's an experienced guy who's been here before. He responded.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll believed there should have been more of a tempo of
urgency in his players as they strolled to the line of scrimmage
late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a case of not trying or being
disinterested,'' said Carroll. ``That's a rhythm dictated by the
quarterback. I wished it wasn't an issue. I think the urgency was
there. Yeah, it could have been done faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his personal situation, Carroll said firmly, ``What
you can expect is, I'll stay on course with how I've been. I'm
gonna do everything we can and think of everything I can think of
to get us back on track. It's important to win this game. Anything
that distracts me, I'd be letting our guys down.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll is pained by the slide in his record since taking over
for Bill Parcells _ from 10-6 (second round of the playoffs_ to 9-7
(first round of the playoffs) to 7-7 (out of the playoffs).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real disappointed,'' said Carroll. ``It looks like we're
sliding. You like to think you're getting better. It's
disappointing because we've had our guys available to us. We have
to get what we can out of it and make it a winning season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
