<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 1999 Chronicle Publishing Company 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE LAW SHE IS A TRICKY DEVIL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Civil Justice Association of California _ formerly, &LR;  the
Association for California Tort Reform, seemingly an anti-litigant
group _ has named California's Most Outrageous Lawsuits of the
Decade. Three pick hits:
</P>
<P>
   - A case in which a man sued beer vendors in a baseball stadium
for emotional distress incurred when he saw women using a men's
room during a rock concert. He blamed the beer vendor for sending
him on numerous trips to the rest room.
</P>
<P>
   - A case where a bank robber sued a bank, the police and a
California city, &LR;  after he got away from the bank with marked money
containing a tear gas device that caused him burns when he stuffed
it into his pants.
</P>
<P>
   - An Orange County city was sued for not maintaining its
property when an 11-year-old ran over his finger while
skateboarding.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Long live love: A San Francisco city employee, given a
sick-pay transfer form to donate hours to a colleague in need, was
fascinated by the form's Marital Status Declaration, an
encapsulation of the state of modern romance:
</P>
<P>
   Either the donor is married, in which case the donor's spouse
has to approve the gift, or 1) ``I am not married.'' 2) ``I do not
know, and I have taken all reasonable steps to determine, the
whereabouts of my current spouse.'' 3) ``I and my current spouse
have executed a marriage settlement agreement pursuant to Title II
of Part 5 of Division 4 of the California Civil Code (or a
predecessor statute, if applicable) which makes my earnings my
separate property.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Jodie Foster  &LR; is fighting with CBS over a $12,000 hair and
makeup bill incurred in preparation for her appearance on ``60
Minutes II'' last week, &LR;  to promote ``Anna and the King.'' The New
York Post says that NBC settled with Foster by sharing the costs of
her hair and makeup with the movie's studio.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Barbara  &LR; and  &UR; Dennis Kavanagh &LR;  of Mill Valley, sailing
through the Panama Canal alongside a vessel filled with crew
members for the movie ``The Perfect Storm,'' came face to face (bow
to bow) with the WWII battleship New Jersey. As the 57-year-old
ship passed, all hands on the two boats going in the other
direction saluted.
</P>
<P>
   - Organizers of the Miss America pageant are thinking about
moving the contest from September to October so as not to compete
for television viewers with the Olympics, which will be broadcast
from Australia between September 15 and October 1.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Muhammad Ali &LR;  will ring the opening bell at the New York
Stock Exchange on December 31.
</P>
<P>
   - Emcee  &UR; Jan Wahl &LR;  proclaimed  &UR; Tom Ammiano  &LR; ``Mayor of the
Emerald City'' last week, &LR;  when the defeated candidate escorted
 &UR; Lorna Luft &LR;  down the aisle of the Castro Theatre er  &LR; at  &UR; Marc &LR; 
 &UR; Huestis &LR; ' ``A  &UR; Judy Garland &LR;  Christmas.'' Luft, Garland's daughter,
revealed that  &UR; Judy Davis  &LR; will play her mother in a made-for-TV
movie based on her book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOMAGE TO A FRIEND &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pat Steger &LR; , The Chronicle's late social columnist, is to be
remembered with a circle of tiles in Pioneer Park, at the base of
Coit Tower.
</P>
<P>
   The Pat Steger circle will be located near an already existing
 &UR; Herb Caen &LR;  circle. Neighborhood preservationists have been raising
money for park restoration by selling tiles marked with donors'
names.
</P>
<P>
   An anonymous colleague bought the first tile; friends  &UR; Carole &LR; 
 &UR; Shorenstein  &LR; and  &UR; Jeff Hays  &LR; bought the second. Tile purchases are
$500, tax deductible. A flyer is available at (415) 398-5112.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Egg magazine names Coit Tower one of the best Lovers Lanes
_ not literally a lane but a place for necking in cars _ in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   And  &UR; Ken Maley  &LR; forwards Men's Fitness magazine, which says that
San Francisco is the fifth fittest city in the country. The city's
``cool weather is ideal for most fitness-minded outdoor pursuits,''
says the magazine. (The other four: San Diego, Minneapolis,
Seattle, Washington, D.C.)
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore,  &UR; Lynn Ferrin  &LR; forwards a story from Travel Holiday
magazine, which attempts to answer the question ``What is dressy
casual?'' In San Francisco, says the magazine, the answer is shorts
and sandals, ``even at the Grand Cafe, a popular post-opera venue
(501 Gary St.).'' The only kneecaps revealed in repeated visits to
the Grand Cafe, which is halfway across town from the Opera, on
Geary Street, are those left uncovered by short skirts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same inventiveness that resulted in the Salk
vaccine.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Carolyn Wyman, &LR;  author of ``The Kitchen Sink Cookbook''
(Birch Lane; $14.95), describing the imagination employed in
recipes such as salmon cooked in a dishwasher. Wyman was quoted by
the Wall Street Journal, which is cited by  &UR; Angela Weber &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
