<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-MUDSLIDES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASUALTY COUNTS FOUND TO BE UNRELIABLE AFTER MUDSLIDES IN
VENEZUELA 
</HEADLINE>
   ( ms) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO _ Overwhelmed by the damage that extensive
flooding and mudslides inflicted along its Caribbean coast late
last week, Venezuela struggled Monday to rescue survivors of the
tragedy and to calculate the loss of life.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of the number of dead in what authorities describe as
the worst natural disaster in modern times in Venezuela varied
wildly, reflecting the chaotic conditions in the devastated zone.
Military and civil defense units have been working around the clock
to remove victims. Thousands of families have been displaced or
separated and do not know whether their missing relatives are dead
or alive.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with foreign reporters on Sunday and early Monday,
Foreign Affairs Minister Jose Vicente Rangel variously estimated
that the floods and mudslides that accompanied three days of heavy
rains could have killed 5,000 to 20,000 people. But at a news
conference later Monday, he acknowledged that ``any figure that we
give is more in the realm of speculation than reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Military officials, in contrast, said more than 1,000 bodies had
been recovered, mostly from the hard-hit coastal states of Vargas
and Miranda. And in a television address to the nation Sunday,
President Hugo Chavez, a former Army paratrooper who has personally
taken command of relief efforts, put the death toll at less than
600, but added, ``I have good reason to think there are bodies that
we will never find.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the much lower figure initially cited by Chavez would make
the calamity the worst natural disaster in Venezuela in this
century. The previous most deadly disaster was an earthquake in
Caracas, the capital, in 1967, when 300 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 150,000 people, mostly residents of the shantytowns
that climb the mountains that ring Caracas and other large cities,
have been left homeless. They have taken refuge at any site that
can accommodate them like Simon Bolivar International Airport near
the capital, parks, schools and churches.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the uncertainty, Chavez urged news organizations
Monday to exercise added caution with casualty estimates. He
acknowledged that no reliable count was available, but said
speculation was merely contributing to the anguish and confusion.
``At times,'' he said, ``rumors get spread about, and that is
dangerous and delicate. Let's try to be as objective, calm and
patient as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Chavez pointed to the case of El Guapo, east of
the capital, where a dam overflowed last week, forcing the removal
of residents of several towns. He said the number of missing there
appeared to be 15 or 20, ``and not this horrifying figure of 2,000
dead that somebody announced on television.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, a daily in Caracas, El Universal, published a
front-page story in which Mayor Lenin Marcano of La Guaira, on the
coast, was quoted as having said he believed that 25,000 people had
died in his town. He has retracted that statement.
</P>
<P>
   As relief experts are well aware, confusion is customary in the
tumult that follows disasters, even in developed countries like the
United States. But uncertainties are magnified and relief efforts
hampered in poorer developing countries, including Venezuela and
other Latin American nations that lack strong communications and
transportation systems and well-organized and prepared civil
defense organizations.
</P>
<P>
   When a hurricane devastated Central America last year, initial
estimates of the dead in Honduras, both the poorest country in that
region and the one most severely affected, ranged up to 15,000. But
the Honduran government later backed away from that figure, and the
toll in Central America from the hurricane is now estimated at less
than 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The disaster in Venezuela has also played into politics. Chavez
took office in February, and his critics have seized on the
disaster to criticize him and his highly personalized style of
government. In a referendum last Wednesday, the day when the rains
began, Venezuelans overwhelmingly approved a Constitution that
grants the president and his allies in the military new and
expanded powers.
</P>
<P>
   A long article Sunday in another daily in Caracas, El Nacional,
maintained that the government was so busy preparing for the vote
that it ignored reports that unusually bad weather was on the way.
``It was a tragedy that could have been seen coming,'' the
newspaper wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's recent war of words with the Roman Catholic church,
including personal attacks on leading prelates, has also become a
factor. In a sermon Sunday that echoed remarks heard in the streets
since the calamity began, Archbishop Ignacio Velasco of Caracas
said it was the president's ``arrogance that attracted the wrath of
God'' and led to the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Rangel, the foreign minister, said Monday, ``It was nature, and
not God'' that has ravaged the country, adding that it is the
responsibility of all institutions to ``show restraint in their use
of language'' in the crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
