<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4665 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CHALUPA-HNS &LR;      12-20 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHALUPA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POP CULTURE CAN MAKE OR BREAK A CLICHE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It is worth remembering, says the president of
the Popular Culture Association, that there was a time _ precisely
three months ago _ when no one in the history of the planet had
heard the phrase, ``Drop the Chalupa.''
</P>
<P>
   Or knew what it meant.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it means anything at all.
</P>
<P>
   Now, spawned by the Taco Bell commercial featuring an officious
Chihuahua, the Chalupa is now part of the vocabulary, with the ad's
signature phrase being repeated by everyone from sports
commentators to students to business executives. Even when he is
trying to avoid it, Professor Robert Thompson says he hears it at
least three times a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's interesting is there is no context for it,'' said
Thompson, founding director of the Center for the Study of Popular
Television at Syracuse University in Syracuse, N.Y., and head of
the Popular Culture Association. ``There are virtually no places in
American life where it makes sense to say `Drop the Chalupa,' no
way to use Newtonian physics to figure out why it caught on. But
people are saying `Drop the Chalupa' and getting huge laughs. It's
almost a punch line without a setup.''
</P>
<P>
   As the cast of ``Friends'' would say _ in the vapid vocal
construction that has been emulated by the nation's youth _ he's SO
looking forward to never hearing it again.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not just Chalupalooza that is sending Thompson to the
edge. There's another monster catchphrase sweeping the country _
for this one, blame Regis Philbin and his ABC quiz show ``Who Wants
to Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hear the line `Is that your final answer?' one more time,
I'm going to hang myself,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Language is an elusive animal that doesn't evolve according to
what English professors teach in classrooms,'' he said. ``Instead,
it evolves according to real people. Walt Whitman was all about the
common people. And just the same, Regis Philbin can change our
language. Philbin and Whitman are kindred spirits.''
</P>
<P>
   These social slogans, and dozens more before them _ everything
from ``Make my day'' to ``Where's the beef?'' _ have rocketed into
the American lexicon. Like cultural viruses, they leap into the
vocabulary, spreading unpredictably, gaining unlikely footholds.
They have become our national glue, delivered direct by Hollywood
and Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a relative fluke, it was the right thing for the
</P>
<P>
   dog to say,'' said Chuck Bennett, the creative director behind
</P>
<P>
   the Chalupa commercial. An advertising veteran who works for the
TBWA/Chiat/Day agency, Bennett recently flew to Hawaii to film a
new commercial when he heard a fellow passenger use the Chalupa
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you set out to write one that would catch on, it probably
wouldn't,'' he said. ``We wanted the Chalupa line to be funny and
catchy but we never thought America would be saying it. Now there's
an expectation that everything the dog says will be repeated by
America. It's horrible, the pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some catchphrases serendipitously survive _ indeed, Philbin's
annoyingly repetitious game show query could endure for
generations, a sort of lowbrow Catch-22 of our time.
</P>
<P>
   Most catchphrases, however, have the staying power of an eye
blink. Virtually unanimously, prognosticators believe that ``Drop
the Chalupa'' will barely make it into the next millennium before
becoming an exhausted victim of its own fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sudden popularity kills it, it becomes not cool anymore,''
Bennett said. ``That's OK because we'll be onto something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Catchphrase lifespan depends on utility as well as an
increasingly brief hipness factor. Today what may be cool _ a word
enjoying renewed popularity after a long hiatus _ is passe
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``They go out as fast as they come in,'' said Professor Donna Jo
Napoli, head of the linguistics department at Swarthmore College in
Pennsylvania. ``What sticks is something that resonates, like
`Toto, we're not in Kansas anymore.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The older a catchphrase becomes, the more it comes to have
meaning. But it's really rare for a commercial to stick,'' Napoli
said.
</P>
<P>
   The television program ``Seinfeld,'' a catchphrase gold mine,
cannily captured self-absorbed life in the late 20th century,
giving rise to such memorable nuggets as ``master of my domain,''
meaning masturbation, and ``double-dipping'' to describe the
execrable practice of dipping one's chip, biting, then re-dipping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yada, yada, yada'' was a phrase used by a minor portion of the
population until adopted by Seinfeld and given the massive push of
a hit show to become wildly in vogue.
</P>
<P>
   In order to tickle that collective consciousness, catchphrases
must embody a certain novelty and resonance. ``Drop the Chalupa''
would scarcely have worked, experts agree, had the commercial said
instead ``Drop the burrito,'' or even worse, ``Drop the coq au
vin.''
</P>
<P>
   In this sound-bite world, it is not sufficient for a movie or
television show to be merely good _ it also needs a grabby slogan,
said Stephen Kraus, an Alameda resident who holds a doctorate in
social psychology from Harvard University and is a partner at
Yankelovich Partners, a marketing research firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't name half the presidents of the United States but I
could tell you ``Drop the Chalupa,''' he sighed. ``It tells you
something about the times in which we live doesn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Kraus has coined his own catchphrase, one that might sweep the
nation in coming months: ``That's so 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It means something outdated,'' he said. ``I use it a lot with
my sister. She's still using DOS applications on her computer.
That's technology from 1985, can you believe it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 1912EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
