<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4667 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MOBILE-HOME-RULES-NYT     12-20 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOBILE-HOME-RULES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL PLANS TO UPDATE MOBILE HOME RULES WORRY CONSUMERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ala., Colo.)   By CARL HULSE   NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress is poised to overhaul outdated federal
rules governing construction of manufactured housing, rules
patterned more after motor vehicle safety laws than building codes
when they were first adopted in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer groups worry that in their push to modernize
regulations designed when mobile homes were often attached to a
trailer hitch, lawmakers will put industry in the driver's seat.
</P>
<P>
   AARP and other advocates for owners of manufactured homes say
that legislation before the House and Senate would unfairly stack a
new ``consensus'' committee charged with overseeing quality
standards in favor of builders and retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really think you have a fox in the chicken coop here,''
complained Roy Green, an AARP lobbyist closely following the issue.
</P>
<P>
   AARP and a handful of state activists also criticized the
emerging legislation for its failure to include federal warranties
for either manufacture or installation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are at the mercy of the industry,'' the Federation
of Manufactured Home Owners of Florida wrote to the House Banking
Committee in an appeal for changes in its measure. ``A lack of
warranty is one of the greatest problems with manufactured
housing.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry representatives dismiss the complaints and say home
buyers would be the ultimate beneficiaries of the changes because
they would get a home built to the latest standards with the best
materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``In reality, both consumers and the industry favor
result-oriented, cost-effective regulation that ensures both safety
and sound construction at a reasonable price,'' said William Lear,
vice president of Fleetwood Enterprises, as he presented the
industry perspective to a Senate panel last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Though the House and Senate held hearings on the legislation,
neither chamber acted before adjourning for the year, however, it
is likely a revamped manufactured housing law will clear Congress
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is now widespread agreement that it is time to update
and improve this act,'' said Sen. Wayne Allard, a Colorado
Republican, who is chairman of the Senate Banking Subcommittee with
jurisdiction over the law. ``Manufactured housing has changed a
great deal in the past 25 years and we are dealing with outdated
laws and regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides in the policy dispute concede the law and Department
of Housing and Urban Development oversight of the industry have not
kept pace with the rise in popularity of the housing or changes in
available materials and building practices. A cumbersome process
for winning code changes keeps manufacturing behind the times and
adds to the cost of homes, industry allies say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the HUD code hasn't kept pace with many safety
innovations and technologies of today's marketplace,'' said Rep.
Robert Aderholt, an Alabama Republican whose district is a center
of the manufactured housing industry.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the likelihood of passage is that HUD, which has
fought past updates, now appears open to the congressional action.
</P>
<P>
   Two major trade groups, the Manufactured Housing Institute and
the Manufactured Housing Association for Regulatory Reform, sought
changes for years but have come up short. As a result, the industry
mobilized in recent elections to increase its visibility and clout
in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Responsive Politics, which tracks campaign
contributions, showed more than $61,000 in industry money going
directly to the parties since 1997 and more than $300,000 given to
congressional candidates, predominantly Republicans. The groups
also spent more than $350,000 on direct lobbying of Congress in
1998, according to the most recent reports.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, consumer groups are loosely organized and have no
national presence in Washington. AARP officials say their
organization stepped in because manufactured housing is popular
among its members, particularly those retiring to the Sun Belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Industry is well-organized and well-financed and these
individuals are not,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative fight centers mainly on the make-up of the
consensus committee, which would recommend changes in standards and
enforcement to HUD. The industry hopes creation of the committee
would expedite such reviews.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer groups take issue with the composition of the
25-member panel, which would have five builders, five from other
industry sectors such as retailing, five consumers, five public
officials and five other interested parties such as architects and
developers.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say industry would hold far too much sway over the
group, allowing consumers to be steamrolled.
</P>
<P>
   Authors of the legislation disagree but say they are willing to
consider revisions to build support for a measure that already has
solid bipartisan backing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe for the bill to move forward we are going to have to
change a few things,'' conceded Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., a main
Senate sponsor. ``We know this bill was a first draft, not the last
word.''
</P>
<P>
   The other main sticking point is warranties. AARP said its
survey of manufactured housing owners found widespread
dissatisfaction with new purchases. Data it collected from the top
destinations for manufactured housing _ predominantly Southeastern
states _ showed more than 7,000 consumer complaints in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   AARP's Green said the lack of a warranty results in what he
describes as the ``ping-pong problem'' _ buyers shuttling back and
forth between builder and installer as they try to get someone to
take responsibility for fixing problems. AARP would like a
five-year guarantee on construction and two years on installation,
with the requirement applied only to new homes and their first
installation.
</P>
<P>
   The industry and its congressional allies are dead-set against a
warranty requirement, saying warranties can already be purchased
and that requiring them would only drive up the cost of
manufactured housing for little return. Problems found in the AARP
survey were usually minor and cost less to fix than buying a
warranty, according to the Coalition to Improve the Manufactured
Housing Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many cases, mandatory federal warranties will actually be
more harmful to consumers,'' said Kami Watson, a spokeswoman for
that group.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials also oppose the warranty proposal, with U.S.
Housing Commissioner William Apgar terming them
``counterproductive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With many private companies already developing new warranty
products, I believe it is preferable to let the market drive
innovations in this area,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Green said AARP would continue to fight to enhance consumer
protections in any final legislation given the stake many
manufactured home buyers have in their new residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is their version of the American dream,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
