<HEADER>
A4674 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-GERMANY-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      12-20 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOHL'S SECRECY ON HUGE POLITICAL GIFTS THREATENS HIS LEGACY AND HIS
PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ During his 16 years as chancellor of
Germany, Helmut Kohl was famous for his Sitzfleisch _ which roughly
translates as the ability to weather problems by sitting them out.
</P>
<P>
   But now, one year after Germans voted him out of office, Kohl
appears bent on exceeding his own reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl stunned Germans earlier this month when he admitted, after
previous denials, that he had used a slew of illegal bank accounts
to accept secret political contributions and channel money to local
branches in his center-right party, the Christian Democratic Union.
</P>
<P>
   Now Kohl, 69, is invoking his personal honor in refusing to
reveal the names of people who he said contributed more than $1
million between 1993 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The donors had my word that they would remain anonymous,''
Kohl said in an interview published last weekend in the Bild
newspaper. ``I keep my promises, and I will not identify the
donors. But I can tell you this much: They are upstanding German
citizens who donated the money from their own wealth.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet as new details trickle out almost daily, the scandal
threatens to engulf both Kohl and the Christian Democratic Union.
It seems likely to shred Kohl's place in history as the man who
both re-unified Germany and led much of Europe toward a single
common currency.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl's image is becoming that of a small-time machine-politician
who accepted cash payments from shadowy business people and used an
off-the-books system of slush funds to shore up support within
party ranks.
</P>
<P>
   But the widening investigations could shake the Christian
Democratic Union itself. German newspaper and television reports
have charged that party officials in eastern Germany received large
sums of money from the French oil company Elf Aquitaine, which took
over a huge chemical complex in the eastern city of Leuna in 1992.
And this weekend, party officials admitted that documents related
to Elf's purchase had disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Other brush fires have broken out as well. The Christian
Democratic Union's official records note that a Hamburg businessman
named Karl Ehlerding contributed about $1.8 million shortly before
he won a big contract to manage the privatization of real estate
owned by the German national rail system.
</P>
<P>
   The contributions were properly disclosed, but have now been
re-examined because of the potential conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Last but not least, a top manager at the accounting firm that
kept track of the secret accounts admitted he had made scores of
trips to Zurich on party business, giving rise to allegations that
Kohl diverted money to Swiss bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   While creating turmoil within the Christian Democratic Union,
the relentless stream of disclosures has strengthened the hand of
Kohl's successor as party chairman, Wolfgang Schaeuble. Despite his
election ouster as chancellor, Kohl remains a member of parliament
and had until recently stayed active in party business. Now
Schaeuble, who had until the scandal been laboring in Kohl's
shadow, is trying to push his former mentor onto the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl has admitted he received 300,000 to 400,000 marks a year
over a five-year period and admitted that the donations came in
cash _ ``because donors wanted to remain anonymous.'' But he has
steadfastly denied using any of the money to enrich himself or
letting government decisions be swayed by the donations.
</P>
<P>
   But now he is under pressure from all sides to tell everything
he knows.
</P>
<P>
   Volker Neumann, chairman of a parliamentary committee
investigating the affair, threatened Kohl on Sunday with fines or
even imprisonment if he refuses to identify the secret donors.
</P>
<P>
   And although Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder has remained fairly
quiet about the issue, other leaders of the ruling Social Democrat
Party have vowed to force Kohl into cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not enough to tell us he took a vow of secrecy, like
some sort of Godfather,'' said Frank Hofmann, a Social Democratic
member on the investigating committee, in an interview in the
Sunday issue of Bild.
</P>
<P>
   Many Christian Democratic leaders are now begging Kohl open up
as well. Monday, he answered questions in a closed-door meeting
with Ernst &AMP; Young, the auditing firm hired by his successors in
the party leadership to investigate the secret accounts.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that the investigations will drag on for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in Bonn and elsewhere are still deciding whether to
open formal criminal investigations, but seem likely to do so.
Meanwhile, Neumann, head of the parliamentary investigation, has
said his work could take two years to complete.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
