<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 COMMENTARY: GORE-BRADLEY Vs. LINCOLN-DOUGLAS  
(jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most terrifying threat of the holiday season is not Y2K
computer failure. It's Al Gore's new idea that he and Bill Bradley
should have nonstop debates for the next four or five months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have two debates every single week and get rid of all
of the television and radio commercials,'' he proposed on ``Meet
the Press'' last weekend. ``I'm willing to do it right now if
you'll shake on it.'' He offered his hand to Bradley, who stared at
it as if it were a seven-day-old mackerel.
</P>
<P>
   We have had three Democratic debates so far, and three with all
the Republican candidates. They've been useful, but I think I am
speaking for us all when I say you can have too much of a fairly
good thing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Quick question:  &LR; Why is it that we get bored with these debates
so easily when people in the 1850s would stand in the sun for five
hours listening to Abraham Lincoln argue with Stephen Douglas?
</P>
<P>
   A. The politicians back then were better orators.
</P>
<P>
   B. The voters were better citizens.
</P>
<P>
   C. The only competing form of entertainment was watching the
rutabagas grow.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, while Lincoln was one great speaker, only the front of
the crowd could hear a word he was saying. And if the 19th-century
voters were all that enlightened, how do you explain President
Franklin Pierce? James Buchanan? Two terms worth of Ulysses Grant?
</P>
<P>
   The current debates can actually be very interesting, under the
proper circumstances. I recommend taping the Republican ones, so
you can fast-forward through all candidates who have never
succeeded in even getting elected to an office in their hometown
PTA. If you also skip over any speaker who has yet to break the 1
percent mark in the polls, you'll be pleasantly surprised by how
quickly the event flies by.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are a little harder to handle, since there are
only two of them, and the differences between their positions are
rather subtle. On the issue of Social Security entitlements, for
instance, as far as I can determine Gore would cut off both his
hands before he would allow anybody to raise the eligibility age,
whereas Bradley would probably only chop off one hand and a couple
of additional fingers.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, the famous battle over health insurance.
Gore and Bradley both want to see every American covered, but have
genuinely different views on how to get there. This is exactly the
sort of policy dispute we're always telling you to pay attention
to. I am therefore more than a little embarrassed to admit that
listening to the Democrats arguing about health care plans is only
slightly more fun than getting stuck in an elevator with somebody
who wants to explain why the new millennium does not begin until
2001.
</P>
<P>
   Let me give you an idea of how it goes. At one point in Sunday's
debate, Bradley asserted that under his approach, 30 million of the
45 million currently uninsured Americans would get coverage, while
Gore's plan would only reach an additional 7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gore: Can I tell you something, I disagree with that strongly.
Let me just say that independent analysis, including at the Emory
School of Public Health, Marty Feldstein, have showed that we get
just about the same amount of people.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley (incredulously): You're quoting  &UR; Marty Feldstein? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Gore: ... 88 percent, 89 percent, the difference is ...
</P>
<P>
   Bradley: That's incorrect.
</P>
<P>
   At which point, the faithful audience members go out to the
kitchen to hit themselves over the head with a skillet.
</P>
<P>
   But if you keep listening, letting all the rhetoric wash over
you, you will pick things up. For instance, you will eventually
notice that Al Gore is a tough but weaselly debater. (When Bradley
called his debate idea ``ridiculous,'' the vice president managed
to look as though his heart were broken. He also specializes in
sighing with deep exasperation whenever his opponent manages to get
three words in edgewise.) Bradley is more dignified, but tends to
fade into the scenery.
</P>
<P>
   We will resume our debate coverage in the new year. While it
probably won't live up to Lincoln-Douglas standards, I think we can
top Buchanan-Fremont or Grant-Greeley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
