<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4686 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-VERMONT-COX     12-20 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERMONT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgians react to same-sex marriage ruling
 &HT;    By Jay Croft
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In an unprecedented ruling that could lead gay
marriages, the Vermont Supreme Court said Monday that gay couples
must receive the same benefits and protections afforded straight
couples who marry.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ruling has no immediate effect in any other state,
Georgians on both sides of the issue reacted strongly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely plan on going to Vermont as soon as it gets
worked out,'' said Atlanta physician Ray Deeb. ``We want to get
married _ domestic partners, whatever they want to call it.''
</P>
<P>
   Deeb walked down a church aisle in a commitment ceremony last
year with his partner, Jerry Gonzalez, and consider themselves
married.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Knox, executive director of the Georgia Equality Project,
a gay rights organization, said, ``It's a very hopeful legal
precedent that we hope will be paid attention to by other
jurisdictions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed and, once again, it looks like judges are
trying to create law,'' said Ron Crews, a Gwinnett County pastor
and former state representative who authored the state marriage
bill. ``I'm grateful for what we've done in Georgia, anticipating
events like this.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., sponsored the federal marriage bill,
which President Clinton signed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly encourage Vermont to follow Hawaii's lead and take
legislative action to block this misguided decision by an activist
court,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   The court shopped short of ordering the Vermont to allow gay
marriage, but instead gave the Legislature the choice between that
and creating some form of state-sanctioned domestic partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hold that the state is constitutionally required to extend
to same-sex couples the common benefits and protections that flow
from marriage under Vermont law,'' the justices said. The
Legislature ``must conform with the constitutional imperative to
afford all Vermonters the common benefit, protection and security
of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous order came less than two weeks after Hawaii's
highest court shut down the possibility of gay marriage there, once
considered the state most likely to allow same-sex unions.
</P>
<P>
   Gay activists hope the Vermont decision could be the first step
in challenging a federal ban on same-sex marriages. The Defense of
Marriage Act allows states to ignore same-sex unions performed in
other states, which gay activists say is unconstitutional. Same-sex
marriages are not allowed in any state; at least 30 have explicitly
banned them. The Georgia ruling in 1996 defined marriage as between
a man and a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Obtaining legal recognition in Vermont issues could give gay
couples the legal standing to sue to overturn the federal law, said
Peg Byron of the Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't go the whole nine yards (and grant marriage), but
it's also the first time anywhere a government has declared that it
must protect gay couples as much as it protects straight couples _
basically, that gay couples are equal to non-gay couples,'' Byron
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Vermont ruling was highly anticipated by both sides of the
fight over letting gays marry, which was sparked by Hawaii's
Supreme Court in 1993. It found that the state's failure to
recognize gay marriages amounted to gender discrimination. Voters
there amended the Constitution last year to prohibit same-sex
unions.
</P>
<P>
   The Vermont ruling stemmed from a suit filed in July 1997 by
three same-sex couples denied marriage licenses by town clerks. A
judge threw out the suit, but the couples appealed to the state
Supreme Court, whose decision may not be appealed to the U.S.
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The couples said the state was denying them more than 300 state
benefits and 1,000 federal benefits. The court found those benefits
include access to insurance, hospital visitation and other power to
make medical decisions, inheritance rights ``and many other
statutory protections.''
</P>
<P>
   Vermont's Speaker of the House said the Legislature probably
will approve domestic partnership rather than marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the politically obtainable solution,'' said Michael J.
Obuchowski, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchowski praised the court decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in line with Vermont's appetite for tolerance and, to me,
it means very simply that people should be treated equally, period,
and our Legislature is going to engage in the process of making
that determination,'' he said. ``It's going to be very complex,
very heart-rending, conscience-jolting enterprise, but I think this
Legislature can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Obuchowski said he expects hearings to begin when the
Legislature convenes Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Croft writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga. Wire services contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
