<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4692 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r w BC-TERRORIST-CUSTOMS-HNS     12-20 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRORIST-CUSTOMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CUSTOMS AGENTS HONORED FOR STOPPING BOMB SUSPECT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (Refiling for those needing)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By Mark Helm  
 &HT;     c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers on Monday
honored the four U.S. Customs Service inspectors who arrested a
suspected terrorist last week after discovering bomb-making
materials in his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``These men and women are true heroes,'' Summers told a packed
auditorium at the Ronald Reagan Building here. ``Thank you on
behalf on all Americans for making our country safer and
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   The secretary then presented Inspectors Diana M. Dean, Mark
Johnson and Carmon Clem with the department's exceptional service
award. Inspector Mike Chapman, who was unable to attend the
ceremony, will be given the award in Port Angeles, Wash., where all
four inspectors work.
</P>
<P>
   After the final medal was awarded, the crowd of more than 1,000
people, most of whom were U.S. Customs Service employees, gave the
inspectors a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   According to the agents, the suspect, Ahmed Ressam, 32, arrived
at Port Angeles, about 60 miles northwest of Seattle, around 6 p.m.
last Tuesday (Dec. 14) on a ferry from Victoria, British Columbia,
driving a Chrysler that he had rented in Canada. His car was the
last one off the ferry.
</P>
<P>
   Dean said the Algerian-born Ressam was ``acting nervous'' while
she asked him routine questions about what was in his car and what
he would be doing in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``After working on this job awhile, you get a knack for knowing
when something isn't right,'' said the 19-year veteran agent.
</P>
<P>
   Dean asked Ressam to step out of his car. While she and Johnson
questioned him, Clem began looking through the car. According to
Dean, Ressam gave her false identification papers that said his
name was Benni Noris.
</P>
<P>
   Clem's examination of the car uncovered a number of
false-identity cards, including at least eight credit cards, a
passport and other material under the name Noris.
</P>
<P>
   Then Clem lifted a mat in the trunk of the car to inspect the
well where the spare tire is usually stored. There was no spare
tire. Instead, he found 10 plastic bags containing 118 pounds of a
fine white powder; two plastic containers with 14 pounds of a
crystalline powder; two 22-ounce jars, each about three-quarters
full of a yellowish liquid, and four small black boxes that each
contained a circuit board connected to a Casio watch and a 9-volt
battery. The materials in the black boxes could be used to time a
detonator.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I thought it was drugs, which is something we come
across much more often,'' Clem said.
</P>
<P>
   After discovering the explosive materials, Dean and Johnson led
the suspect away from the car, but Ressam ``squirmed'' free and
ran, Johnson said. ``One second I have a hold of him; the next, I'm
standing there with an empty coat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, Clem and Chapman chased Ressam for about six blocks,
then spotted him trying to open the door of a car that had slowed
at an intersection. The female driver sped away, and the suspect
was then tackled in the street, according to the Johnson and Clem.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam was arrested that day, and last Friday he was charged in
U.S. District Court in Seattle with smuggling explosives into the
United States from Canada and giving false information to U.S.
Customs agents.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam's real identity was determined through fingerprinting
with the help of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police, according to
customs officials. He had served a short term for stealing
computers and other equipment and was being sought for other
burglaries, the agents said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the FBI, the crystalline powder found in Ressam's
car was a sulfate used primarily to absorb water and keep things
dry, and the fine white powder was urea, used to manufacture
explosives and fertilizer. Urea was used in the 1993 World Trade
Center bombing in New York City, which killed six people and
injured 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   A massive search is under way for a possible accomplice or
accomplices because Ressam is suspected of acting as a courier for
an unknown terrorist group and because he did not have all of the
elements needed to make a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is trying to determine if Ressam was acting at
the behest of Osama Bin Laden, a wealthy Saudi radical who is
wanted for allegedly ordering the bombing of U.S. embassies in
Kenya and Tanzania last year.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden is believed to be in Afghanistan, and his main access
to the rest of the world is thought to be through supporters in
Pakistan. Officias here are concerned because the Muslim holy
season of Ramadan coincides with celebrations marking the turn of
the century and the second millennium of Christianity _ a
convergence that authorities fear could entice extremists to resort
to violence.Summers said the Customs Service will deploy extra
inspectors to ports of entry around the country to try to prevent
terrorists from smuggling explosives or weapons into the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although there are no guarantees when it comes to terrorists,
I firmly believe that with agents such as the ones on this stage,
we will be able to keep our country safe,'' Summers said.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 1945EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4695 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-Y2K-HEALTH21-COX     12-20 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-HEALTH21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Experts downplay potential for Y2K problems, prescribe steps to
avoid glitches
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roger ``Buster'' Sappenfield, a semi-retired professional
golfer, has stored enough water and food to take his family well
past those first iffy weeks of Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   But more importantly, Sappenfield, 70, has stockpiled his supply
of medications _ more than seven different prescriptions _ in
anticipation of potential computer glitches in the health care
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these mean life or death to me,'' said Sappenfield, a
Lawrenceville resident who has undergone a triple bypass. ``Why
would I take the chance?''
</P>
<P>
   As the new year looms, some metro Atlantans are not only copying
bank statements and hoarding camping supplies, but also gathering
health care records to make sure when the clock strikes midnight
that their medical safety net doesn't evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   Experts almost categorically say patients should be fine as they
plunge into the first weeks of 2000, pointing out that most
insurance companies, hospitals and drugstores have been working to
head off Y2K-related problems for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably going to be the biggest nonevent ever to
occur,'' said Arthur Levin, executive director of the Center for
Medical Consumers, a nonprofit group in New York. ``I'm betting
that there will be little glitches. But, hey, there are little
glitches all the time ... so I don't think it's going to be a big
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Aetna-US Healthcare, for example, has been preparing its systems
for the advent of the new century since 1997, spending close to
$200 million on upgrades. The American Medical Association started
updating doctors on Y2K in 1998 through brochures, its Web site and
its magazine, American Medical News. And Eckerd Drugs _ vigorously
advertising its Y2K readiness _ started its computer checks back in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working on this for almost four years. We've tested
and re-tested not only our internal systems, but our external
systems with vendors and distributors,'' said Tami Alderman, Eckerd
Drugs spokeswoman. ``We feel very comfortable with our readiness,
and for us, it will be business as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are also protected from the ravages of computer mayhem
simply because many doctors are not that wired. Most patient
records are still meticulously filed in folders stored on shelves _
not on hard drives or discs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A majority of our physicians don't have electronic records
right now,'' said Camilla Grayson, director of health policy at the
Georgia Medical Association. ``So I don't think there is anything
that could go wrong that would directly affect patients, except
maybe in accounts payable. And if anything, that will merely result
in giving them more wiggle room to pay the bills.''
</P>
<P>
   And even pharmacists often keep the handwritten prescriptions
for reference and a protection against liability, meaning there's
little chance of a patient's history disappearing in cyberspace.
But experts also admit that it's hard to anticipate exactly what
will happen. And, as a precaution at least, consumers do need to
take basic steps to prepare for any eventuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the most prudent thing to do is take some steps you
should take all year long,'' said Dan Nutkis, director of research
at the Odin Group, a health care research company that has
distributed 20 million consumer guides on Y2K that's also available
at www.healthcarey2kguide
</P>
<P>
   .com. ``Do the basics.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you rely on medication, like Sappenfield, you
should probably make sure you have enough refills to last you
through January _ or at least have handwritten prescriptions that
you can use until February. Also, if you have the same insurance
company in 2000 that you had this year, carry your insurance card
with you to your doctor's office or any medical center you visit
early in the new year _ even if it expires at midnight. It will
allow medical personnel to log, by hand if necessary, a policy
number that probably has not changed.
</P>
<P>
   Things are more dicey for those who have switched insurance
plans. Your old insurance card is worthless, so you need to get
confirmation before Jan. 1 of your new policy either through your
employer or your insurer.
</P>
<P>
   Carry the new information in your wallet or purse. And if a
medical facility cannot confirm insurance because of Y2K problems,
you may have to pay for services out-of-pocket. But hold on to all
receipts to file for reimbursement later with your insurer, said
Anna O'Neil, spokeswoman for Blue Cross &AMP; Blue Shield of Georgia.
``Make sure you have a paper trail to follow up on,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Patients should also try to squeeze in some face-to-face time
with any new family doctors before 2000. Doctors are unlikely to
write prescriptions for patients they have never met _ leaving you
vulnerable if there are glitches in the pharmaceutical system.
</P>
<P>
   ``So try make the time to meet them,'' said Dr. John Mersereau,
a family practitioner at the Emory Clinic. ``Or at least have your
old physicians write enough prescriptions to carry you over until
you become acquainted with the new practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Mersereau said between 1 percent and 2 percent of his patients
have requested he write extra prescriptions in response to Y2K.
``I'm trying to downplay it, because I feel comfortable that
there's not going to be any problems,'' he said. ``But I think it
makes them feel more secure.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
