<SLUG> BC-GOLDEN-GLOBE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No green light for `Mile'
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This movie season's Golden Globe nominations include all the big
names: Kevin Spacey, Matt Damon, Jim Carrey, Julia Roberts, Tom
Cruise, Denzel Washington, Meryl Streep, Robert De Niro. But not
Tom Hanks.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks and his newest drama, ``The Green Mile,'' considered by
many to be a shoo-in for annual award nominations such as the
Globes and the Oscars, was nearly shut out of the Globe
nominations, announced Monday by the Hollywood Foreign Press
Association. ``The Green Mile'' got only one nod: Michael Clarke
Duncan for best supporting actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty,'' which details the implosion of a modern
suburban family, led all movies with six nominations, including
best drama, actor (Spacey), actress (Annette Bening), director (Sam
Mendes), screenplay (former Mariettan Alan Ball) and original score
(Thomas Newman).
</P>
<P>
   Also scoring well were Michael Mann's ``The Insider'' and
Anthony Minghella's ``The Talented Mr. Ripley,'' which opens in
metro Atlanta on Christmas Day. Each got five nominations,
including best dramatic actor nods for Russell Crowe and Matt
Damon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man on the Moon'' (opening here Wednesday) and ``Being John
Malkovich,'' both associated with Michael Stipe and Athens-based
R.E.M., are up for best comedy or musical movie.
</P>
<P>
   Among other winners and losers:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where's Malkovich? John Malkovich (``Being John Malkovich'')
was bypassed in the supporting actor category. The main competitors
include ``Green Mile's'' Duncan, Cruise (``Magnolia'') and Haley
Joel Osment (``The Sixth Sense'').
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Double contender: Julianne Moore is up for best actress in
both drama (``The End of the Affair,'' which opens next month in
metro Atlanta) and comedy (``An Ideal Husband'').
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  New faces: They include Hilary Swank and Chloe Sevigny for
``Boys Don't Cry'' and theatrical star Janet McTeer for
``Tumbleweeds.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  And the familiar: Big stars receiving nominations included
Carrey (``Man on the Moon''), Roberts (``Notting Hill''),
Washington (``The Hurricane''), Streep (``Music of the Heart'') and
De Niro (``Analyze This'').
</P>
<P>
   Among the leading nominees in television categories are HBO's
``The Sopranos'' and several new series, including ABC's ``Once and
Again'' and NBC's ``The West Wing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Globes is a TV ratings bonanza, boasting 250 million
viewers worldwide. NBC recently signed a deal for exclusive rights
to the Globes' live star arrival interviews and will air this
season's ceremony Jan. 23. The rival Oscar nominations will be
announced Feb. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
