<HEADER>
A4702 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TURKEY-EU-NYT &LR;      12-20 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-EU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER CHANGE OF HEART, TURKEY VEERS TOWARD EUROPE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ The mood was jubilant on the night Prime
Minister Bulent Ecevit announced that Turkey would begin drawing
closer to the European Union, but one news reporter almost spoiled
it with an indiscreet question.
</P>
<P>
   ``You blocked this country's way to Europe once,'' he called
out. ``What made you decide not to do it again?''
</P>
<P>
   Ecevit ignored the question, but it reflected a remarkable
political transition whose effect is reverberating across Europe.
</P>
<P>
   During all of his more than 40 years in politics, Ecevit has
described himself as a leftist. When he was prime minister in the
1970s, he brusquely rejected the offer by the predecessor of
today's European Union to consider Turkey as a candidate, scorning
it as an imperialist plot.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of that decision, Turkey was left outside the
European family while its major rival, Greece, joined in 1981 and
rode quickly to prosperity and solid democracy.
</P>
<P>
   When Ecevit, now 75, returned to power this year, some voters
feared that he would again obstruct Turkey's progress toward
Europe. Instead he has done just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   For months Ecevit has been steadily steering Turkey on a
pro-European course, promising many reforms and even enacting some.
He has managed to squelch opposition not only in his own party, but
also among his right-wing coalition partners.
</P>
<P>
   Ecevit's quiet campaign was crowned with success in
mid-December, when the European Union named Turkey as a ``candidate
state.'' This onetime firebrand, still describing himself as a
leftist but now convinced that Turks belong in Europe, has the task
of leading them there.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt in my mind that he feels responsible and
guilty for what he did,'' said Ishak Alaton, a pro-European
businessman. ``This was a chance for him to change that bad
decision, and that's what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1970s, Greece's fragile new democracy applied for
membership. Leaders of the European group thought that to be fair,
they should also offer Turkey a chance to apply. But Ecevit refused
the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Ecevit was then trying to stake out an independent path for
Turkey, and he often denounced what he called the colonialist
designs of Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He was encouraged in his anti-Europe sentiment by owners of
subsidized businesses, who feared disaster if they were made to
compete with European companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They saw the European community as a capitalist
organization,'' said Cetin Altan, an author and social commentator
who is of Ecevit's generation. ``It was a time when concepts like
democracy, economy, state and nation were not very well understood
in Turkey. Now they are seen more clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   Ecevit has not spoken publicly about his actions of 20 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   When a recent interviewer asked him if he regretted rejecting
Europe then, he replied that he would leave the verdict to history.
</P>
<P>
   He may see the coming months as a period in which he can change
the way he is remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good that this candidacy came up while Ecevit, who is
known as a Euro-skeptic, was in office,'' said one European
diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really had no choice other than to accept it. When he did,
that reassured the establishment and made the whole idea more
convincing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
