A4703 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-LAWSUIT-COX     12-20 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-LAWSUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plaintiffs looking to add names to Coke lawsuit
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The plaintiffs in a racial discrimination lawsuit
against Coca-Cola want to add more employees and allegations to
their federal complaint seeking class-action status.
</P>
<P>
   In a motion filed Monday asking for court permission to amend
the suit, the plaintiffs claim Chairman and Chief Executive M.
Douglas Ivester and other senior managers have known about
``company-wide discrimination against African-Americans'' since at
least 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``This knowledge places full responsibility for current
violations of federal anti-discrimination law at the highest levels
of the company,'' the revised suit alleges. ``Despite
well-documented racial disparities, Ivester and other members of
Coca-Cola's senior management have consistently failed to take
their equal opportunity obligations seriously enough to correct
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, which strongly denied the allegations in the previous
version of the lawsuit, said Monday that it has not had time to
review the revised suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We received the plaintiffs' amended filing late this
afternoon, and it would be inappropriate to comment further until
we've had a chance to study it more closely,'' said company
spokesman Ben Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsch did say that the company was taking the allegations of
the four new plaintiffs in the revised suit ``very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs in the revised suit, which claims that
African-Americans have been discriminated against in pay,
promotions and performance evaluations, seek to represent more than
2,000 black salaried employees in the United States. That number is
up from 1,500 employees in the previous complaint.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Richard Story will eventually decide whether
to certify the case as a class-action, but that decision will not
be made for at least several months.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the plaintiffs are seeking Story's permission
to add four current or former employees to the four plaintiffs who
filed the previous version of the lawsuit in late April.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the new plaintiffs have worked for Coca-Cola in Atlanta:
</P>
<P>
   _ Ajibola Laosebikan, an information systems specialist, alleges
that he effectively went eight years without a promotion, while
white employees with less experience, education or seniority
advanced more rapidly than he did. He also alleges he was
wrongfully terminated last month in retaliation for making
complaints about race discrimination and after attending a hearing
in this case.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wanda Williams, an assistant scientist who has been working at
Coca-Cola for about 15 years, alleges that she has been denied
promotions because of her race. She also says she has been treated
differently than her white counterparts in performance evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   The other new plaintiffs have worked at the Minute Maid Co. in
Houston, which Coca-Cola owns:
</P>
<P>
   _ Elvenyia Barton-Gibson, who has worked at Minute Maid since
1996, is currently employed as an executive assistant to the chief
marketing officer. She alleges that she has been denied the chance
to compete for promotions. Barton-Gibson also alleges that eight
other African-American marketing professionals were terminated or
left in frustration over their inability to advance.
</P>
<P>
   _ George Eddings Jr. is a former Minute Maid employee who left
the company in 1997 after he said he was denied a long-promised
promotion. He had worked for the company for five years, most
recently as a category development manager.
</P>
<P>
   The revised suit claims that senior management has not corrected
discriminatory practices that have been brought to its attention
from inside and outside Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the suit cited a report by Carl Ware, the most
senior African-American executive at the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although Ivester received the Ware Report documenting. . .
barriers to the advancement of African-Americans at Coca-Cola in
1995, more than four years later, Coca-Cola admits that it has
failed to fully implement the report's recommendations,'' the suit
alleges. Those recommendations reportedly included executive
accountability for improved diversity results and increasing the
hiring of African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Ware, who heads the company's operations in Africa, now
co-chairs a Diversity Advisory Council set up by Ivester after the
previous version of the suit was filed in April. Ware, however,
plans to retire at the end of next year. That decision came in the
wake of a management restructuring in which Ware no longer reports
to Ivester. The revised suit also alleges the company has failed to
fulfill ``most of its obligations'' under an agreement it reached
with the government about certain violations of federal
affirmative-action regulations governing federal contractors, such
as Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   At Minute Maid, the suit claims, an internal consultant
concluded in 1997 that there were problems of racial discrimination
and that the company ``had a reputation as a poor place for
African-Americans to work.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time the plaintiffs have tried to amend the
suit.
</P>
<P>
   The initial suit was filed in December 1998 by Gregory Allen
Clark, who is employed as a security officer in Atlanta. He was
joined in April by three other current or former employees in
Atlanta: Motisola Malikha Abdallah, currently an administrative
assistant; Linda Ingram, currently an information systems analyst;
and Kimberly Gray Orton, a former director.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs are seeking monetary damages and a court order
preventing the company from engaging in the alleged discriminatory
practices.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
