<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SAKAMAKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAZUO SAKAMAKI,   PACIFIC POW NO. 1, DIES AT 81  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Japan, Brazil, Fla . , Texas)   By RICHARD GOLDSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kazuo Sakamaki, who became the first Japanese prisoner of war
captured by American forces in World War II when his midget
submarine ran aground during the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor,
died on Nov. 29. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
   His death, in Japan, was reported Monday by a Japanese veterans'
group.
</P>
<P>
   A midget submarine of the Japanese Imperial Navy carrying Ensign
Sakamaki and Chief Warrant Officer Kiyoshi Inagaki was launched
from a mother submarine 10 miles off Pearl Harbor, Hawaii, at 3:33
a.m. on Sunday, Dec. 7, 1941. About four and a half hours later,
Japanese bombers attacked the U.S. Pacific Fleet, plunging America
into World War II. But Sakamaki was frustrated by mechanical
misadventures.
</P>
<P>
   His 78.5-foot-long submarine, HA-19, and four other midget subs,
each armed with a pair of 1,000-pound torpedoes, were to attack
American destroyers or battleships.
</P>
<P>
   But Sakamaki's gyrocompass, which had given him trouble even
before the mission began, continued to malfunction, causing his
submarine to run in circles while at periscope depth. He struck
submerged coral reefs three times, then surfaced just after 8 a.m.
_ moments after the Japanese bombers' first wave _ and ran aground.
</P>
<P>
   The submarine was spotted by an American destroyer, the Helm,
which fired at it. The shots missed, but they blasted the submarine
off the reef and knocked Sakamaki unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   After he revived, Sakamaki tried to get his submarine going. It
managed to avoid American depth charges, but the firing mechanisms
for its torpedoes were damaged. The submarine became partially
flooded, it filled with smoke and fumes from its batteries, causing
the two crewmen to pass out.
</P>
<P>
   Sakamaki revived once again late Sunday night, opened the hatch,
noted that he was near land and tried to run his submarine onto a
stretch of beach, but the engines died, and the submarine grounded
on yet another coral reef.
</P>
<P>
   After ordering Inagaki to abandon the submarine, Sakamaki lit
the fuses of the self-destruct charges and leaped into the surf.
The charges did not explode, and the other crewman drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Sakamaki reached a stretch of beach, but fell unconscious once
more. When he awakened the next morning, an American soldier, Sgt.
David Akui, was standing over him. Sakamaki was the only crewman to
survive from the midget submarines. All five were lost, and none
were known to have caused damage to American ships.
</P>
<P>
   Sakamaki was questioned at nearby Fort Shafter, then sent to a
prisoner of war camp in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the war, he returned to Japan and wrote his
memoirs, ``Four Years as a Prisoner-of-War, No. 1,'' in which he
told of receiving mail from some Japanese denouncing him for not
having committed suicide when it appeared he could be taken
captive. His memoirs were published in the United States on the
eighth anniversary of the Pearl Harbor attack with the title, ``I
Attacked Pearl Harbor.''
</P>
<P>
   Sakamaki became a businessman, serving as president of a
Brazilian subsidiary of Toyota and then working for a
Toyota-affiliated company in Japan before retiring in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife and two children.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   His submarine was salvaged by American troops, shipped to the
United States in January 1942, and taken on a nationwide tour to
sell War Bonds. It was placed on display at a submarine base in Key
West, Fla., in 1947 and later transferred in 1990 to its current
site, the Admiral Nimitz Museum in Fredericksburg, Texas, in 1991,
Sakamaki paid a visit to his old sub during a symposium on the
Pearl Harbor attack.
</P>
<P>
   A fellow Japanese naval veteran, Sadaichi Fukui, said that
although Sakamaki wrote his memoirs, he did not speak much about
his war experiences. As Fukui put it, ``I think he had a lot of
feelings he could not put in words about becoming the first
prisoner of war at a time when falling into the hands of the enemy
was the biggest shame.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 1959EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4707 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BELL-UNIONS-BOS &LR;      12-20 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELL-UNIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC, UNIONS GIRD FOR UPCOMING TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ten years after a strike by 12,000 Nynex Corp. workers crippled
telephone service, Bell Atlantic's biggest unions say they are
bracing for a fight next year over the key issues of managed care
and organizing rights at the company's nonunion mobile wireless
units.
</P>
<P>
   The Communications Workers of America and the International
Brotherhood of Electrical Workers Local 2222 launched their
strategy sessions last week with a demonstration outside Bell
Altantic headquarters in Boston that drew some 700 union members.
Together, the two unions represent more than 14,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there is a possibility of a confrontation and we want
to be ready,'' said CWA representative Steve Early. ``The earlier
we mobilize, the more prepared we'll be.'' Talks are not scheduled
to begin until August.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic spokesman Steve Marcus said he could not discuss
upcoming talks. ``Our policy is we discuss issues like this at the
bargaining table,'' he said. ``At the appropriate time we will sit
down with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Although neither union mentioned the possibility of a strike,
Myles Calvey, business agent at IBEW Local 2222, said both unions
are preparing early for a possible job action. The unions chose
this month to begin mobilizing members because it marked the
10-year anniversary of the 1989 strike that disrupted service in
the region for 100 days. That strike, like upcoming talks, centered
around health benefits and job security.
</P>
<P>
   This time, a key issue among union officials is a company
proposal that would require workers switch from the current
indemnity health plan to a managed care plan now being used by
two-thirds of Bell Atlantic's workers. The indemnity plan had been
part of a negotiated agreement with the former Nynex Corp., which
merged with Bell Atlantic in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Union-represented employees in New England and New York have
an indemnity plan that allows you to go to any doctor and we pay
for that,'' confirmed Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   Such plans are now rare among corporations. A study of 1,020 US
firms by Hewitt Associates, a benefits consultancy based in
Lincolnshire, Ill., revealed that only three percent still carry
indemnity health plans.
</P>
<P>
   The IBEW's Calvey said another key concern is the expansion of
Bell Atlantic's mobile units. Currently, about 7,000 workers are
employed by Bell Atlantic mobile units. Of those, however, only 50
are unionized.
</P>
<P>
   The IBEW, responding to predictions of massive growth of the
wireless units in coming years, says it will seek the right to
organize the units without interference from the company.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, Bell Atlantic Mobile and Vodafone Group PLC of
Britain solidified a joint venture expected to make Bell Atlantic
the biggest wireless carrier in the country, with an estimated 20
million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Bell Atlantic is combined with the wireless subsidiaries
that are part of the Bell-GTE merger and when the wireless holdings
of a joint venture with Vodafone are added, we will see an even
larger wireless company and it will be nonunion,'' said Early.
</P>
<P>
   Added Calvey, ``These are future jobs. Our ability to continue
to negotiate good contracts will be undermined if the fastest
growing segment of the company _ the wireless segment _ remains
nonunion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
