<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FRANCE-KING-MYSTERY-(     12-20 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-KING-MYSTERY-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DNA TESTS MAY SOLVE 200-YEAR-OLD MYSTERY OF LOUIS XVII 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ At the height of the French Revolution, the little
prince was imprisoned with his parents, Louis XVI and Marie
Antoinette. Soon, however, the king and his brioche-loving queen
went to the guillotine. The 8-year-old prince, who became Louis
XVII, was left alone locked up in the Temple prison _ kept in the
dark for long stretches, uncared for and barely fed.
</P>
<P>
   On this much, historians agree. But there is much in dispute
after that.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional history has held that the little boy, his body
riddled with tumors and encrusted with scabies sores, finally died
of tuberculosis at the age of 10. But some have held that the dead
boy was an impostor. The real king, they say, was at some point
spirited out of the prison by supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has spawned more than 100 pretenders to the throne.
In 1845, one such man, Charles-Guillaume Naundorff, was buried in
the Netherlands, his tombstone reading: ``Here lies the king of
France.'' Experts on the royal family say there are still dozens
more claiming to be direct descendants, though few have been as
public with their claims.
</P>
<P>
   But now an answer to the mystery may be possible. Last week,
scientists began examining a heart kept in a crystal urn in the
royal crypt at the Basilica of St.-Denis north of Paris _
supposedly the heart of the young boy who died in 1795. Their aim
is to compare DNA from the heart with DNA in strands of Marie
Antoinette's hair.
</P>
<P>
   In a small but formal ceremony, the transparent urn was draped
with a purple cloth and taken across Paris to a laboratory where
scientists used a razor blade to slice two small pieces of the
heart. The pieces were then placed in sealed envelopes to be sent
to Germany and Belgium where two different laboratories will
attempt the same analysis. The results are expected by February.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had the heart for a while,'' said the Duke de
Beauffremont, who heads the Memorial of France at St.-Denis, the
private organization that oversees the royal graves. ``But the
techniques were not as good as they are today. To do these tests is
a very obvious thing to do. It is a very important issue for
France. There are so many hypotheses about what happened. Now,
maybe we will know, once and for all.''
</P>
<P>
   But getting the answer may not be easy. First, many questions
surround the authenticity of the heart, which was brought to the
royal crypt only in 1975. Before that, it had a long and
complicated odyssey, having been stolen, returned, refused, fought
over and passed on in various ways over the last two centuries.
</P>
<P>
   This tortuous journey means that getting enough DNA material
from the heart may be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been preserved under the best circumstances for
these sorts of tests, by any means,'' said Jean-Jacques Cassiman, a
scientist at the Center for Human Genetics at Louvain University in
Belgium, who will be supervising tests there. ``Whether we will be
able to do an analysis is hard to say. We will try. It's all we can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of how the heart was preserved is not a scientist's
dream. Those who say the heart is from the child who died in 1795
believe this version of events: When the child in the Temple died,
an autopsy was performed and one of the physicians present,
Philippe-Jean Pelletan, decided he wanted a souvenir: When the
others weren't looking he tucked the heart into his handkerchief
and took it home. There he put it in a glass vial filled with
alcohol. Unfortunately, the liquid evaporated and the heart dried
up. A few years later, one of the doctor's assistants stole it. But
when he died, his widow returned it to the doctor.
</P>
<P>
   When the monarchy was briefly returned to power in 1815, the
doctor apparently tried to return the heart to Louis XVIII, who
wanted nothing to do with it. So, just before he died, Pelletan
decided to entrust it to the archbishop of Paris. In 1831, however,
the archbishop's palace came under attack during civil disorders,
and a printer named Lescroart tried to save the relic and the
paperwork that proved its authenticity in the hopes of giving it
back to the doctor's son for safekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   He was caught in the mayhem, however, and as he tussled with a
national guardsman the crystal urn containing the heart was
smashed. Later, when all was quiet, Lescroart came back with
Pelletan's son and they found the heart lying among shards of
glass, some engraved with the royal fleurs de lys. The son kept the
heart until his death. In his will, he bequeathed it to members of
one of the branches of France's royal family, who kept it in their
chateau for more than eight decades. In 1975, was it put into the
custody of the Memorial for France at St.-Denis.
</P>
<P>
   Cassiman has already tried to solve another royal mystery, that
of the real identity of Naundorff. Last year, he published a paper
in the European Journal of Human Genetics saying that DNA analysis
showed that it was highly unlikely that Naundorff was related to
Marie Antoinette.
</P>
<P>
   Naundorff turned up in Berlin around 1810 claiming he was the
French heir, apparently providing enough details about the Court of
Versailles to be convincing. He came to France in 1833, was exiled
by the French, lived in London for a while and then died in the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Cassiman and his associates compared DNA material taken from
Naundorff's body with hair from the queen and two of her sisters
that was found in lockets that had belonged to their mother. They
found no matches.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The French Revolution, and its many aftershocks, wiped out a
great many royals and stripped most of them of their wealth. A
major split among them began in 1830, 16 years after the Bourbons
were restored to the throne: A crisis forced King Charles X to
abdicate, and his cousin the Duke of Orleans took over, ruling as
King Louis-Philippe until the revolution of 1848.
</P>
<P>
   When the last French Bourbon heir died in 1883, the Orleans
family, according to experts in such matters, could rightfully
claim the French crown if France ever decided to restore the
monarchy. But Bourbon loyalists counter with a claim for Prince
Louis of Spain, a descendant of the grandson of King Louis XIV of
France who founded the Spanish branch of the Bourbon family in the
18th century.
</P>
<P>
   The French are not all that interested in their royalty,
although there is enough interest to keep at least one
royal-watchers' magazine, Point de Vue, afloat.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the Duke de Beauffremont said, he has known
quite a few people who claimed to be direct descendants of Louis
XVII, most of them dead now. ``These people were not crazy,'' the
duke said. ``They made very convincing cases. One was a professor
at a university. One was an engineer. They were very, very sure of
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The duke said he would like the heart to be that of Louis XVII,
but he acknowledged that even if the DNA did not match, many people
could ``go on dreaming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very mysterious subject and one that invokes great
passions,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
