<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4710 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MEDIA-LATIMES-BOS &LR;      12-20 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-LATIMES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT CONDEMNS BUSINESS INFLUENCE ON L.A. TIMES NEWS PAGES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   With reputations _ and perhaps careers _ hanging in the balance,
the Los Angeles Times Monday published an extraordinarily detailed
37,000-word postmortem by staff media writer David Shaw on the
paper's credibility- and morale-sapping Staples Center episode.
</P>
<P>
   At a paper where Times-Mirror CEO Mark Willes has preached the
virtues of tearing down the ``wall'' between business and editorial
departments, Shaw blamed the fiasco on ``deadened sensibilities and
diminished standards.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy exploded in October, after several papers
reported that the Times had devoted an Oct. 10 issue of its
magazine to coverage of the new Staples Center sports arena, under
a deal to share revenues with the center. As word spread, there was
almost a newsroom revolt; about 300 staff members signed a petition
asking that publisher Kathryn Downing apologize and undertake a
review of Times policy.
</P>
<P>
   A newspaper becoming business partners with an institution that
is a subject of continuing news coverage is what Shaw described as
a ``flagrant . . . violation of the journalistic principle of
editorial independence.'' It is also emblematic of a newspaper
industry _ driven by stock prices and frightened by declining
circulation, aging readers and the Internet _ reaching out for new
revenue streams. One result may be near-toxic levels of distrust: a
recent survey by the American Society of Newspaper Editors found
that half the respondents believed papers allow advertisers to
influence news, and that almost 60 percent thought papers were more
concerned with profits than with the public good.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, a day before Shaw's story appeared, Downing and
editor Michael Parks apologized for the Staples Center episode, and
the paper published a list of Times principles. Included was the
statement that ``we will remain free of associations and activities
that might compromise our integrity or damage our credibility . . .
If the editorial mission and the commercial interests of the Times
conflict, editorial integrity will always come first.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, observers expressed relief that the paper had produced a
full and independent airing of the controversy. ``Finally, there's
a complete and exhaustive analysis of what took place,'' said the
Times senior projects editor, Kit Rachlis.
</P>
<P>
   Downing issued a statement saying, ``We believe we must be able
to shine as bright a light on ourselves as we do others.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly is a commendable first step,'' said the Nieman
Foundation curator, Bill Kovach. ``The question is `what's next?' I
never had any real doubt about the journalism inside the newsroom
of the LA Times. My doubt has always been about (the business
practices) since Mark Willes has come in and tried to change the
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   The Shaw reconstruction of events is critical of Downing's
judgment and of Parks's failure to act more decisively to protect
editorial integrity. But it lays the brunt of the blame on the
changes that Willes imposed on that culture with his bottom-line
orientation and his desire for closer cooperation between editorial
and business departments.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining how the Staples episode might have occurred, Shaw
wrote that ``so many in the newsroom had become so inured to
intrusions by business side considerations in the editorial process
that they were desensitized and demoralized.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why the largest single chapter in the piece is called
`The Wall,' '' Shaw said in an interview Monday. The Times culture
had ``created a climate in which people kind of shrugged their
shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's report suggested that Downing, the Willes protege who
became Times publisher this year, did not have the journalistic
experience to recognize the pitfalls of the Staples deal and was
``ill-served by her senior team.'' He quoted Times executives as
saying that ``without more experienced hands willing to challenge
her . . . a blunder like the Staples deal was inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Parks, Shaw asked the Watergate-era question: ``What did he
know and when did he know it?'' In the report, Parks acknowledged
first having heard about and having raised objections to the
Staples profit-sharing plan in mid-September, when the magazine was
at the printer. But Shaw pointed out that Parks and Downing still
had time to cancel the press run, or put some kind of public
disclaimer on the magazine, and failed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   In Shaw's story, Parks acknowledged: ``I underestimated the
impact of the Staples arrangement on our credibility, on the
journalistic ethos that we foster, on our standing in the community
and in the profession. And for all those things, I have profound
regret.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the report saves its most damning indictment for the
influence of the Willes philosophy at the paper. ``Increasingly,''
Shaw wrote, ``business concerns seemed to be influencing editorial
decisions in ways long forbidden at the Times.'' The report noted
that the agreement between the Times and Staples Center that led to
the revenue-sharing deal had been negotiated by the general manager
of the paper's sports section _ a position created as part of
Willes's plan to match business-side executives with editorial
sections.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we talked about bringing the walls down, what we should
have done . . . is to develop an explicit set of principles, rules
of engagement, whatever you want to call it,'' Willes told Shaw.
And along with publishing its principles, the Times also
distributed a list of guidelines to its employees on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   One relevant guideline notes that ``if the publisher decides to
enter into joint ventures, partnerships or sponsorships with other
organizations, the publisher will fully and promptly disclose the
nature of these relationships to the editor. Disclosure to readers
is always required when The Times covers stories that deal with
these organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview Monday, Shaw said: ``I deliberately, in this
piece, did not speculate on the future of anybody.'' But one
high-ranking Times editor said, ``Michael and Kathryn and Mark
Willes in very different ways, are being held accountable for what
happened.'' And there is open speculation about whether Downing,
and particularly Parks, will survive the fallout from the Staples
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some observers wondered whether Monday's report would
become a convenient closing chapter in the scandal, or a catalyst
for real reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue now is Shaw's piece and the articulation of
principles,'' said Tom Rosenstiel, a former Times staff member and
director of the Project for Excellence in Journalism. Is it ``an
attempt to put this behind them and forget about it? Or is it an
attempt to say, let's not forget about it, let's build on it?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Mark Jurkowitz is media reporter for The Boston Globe. The Shaw
report is available online at www.latimes.com/news/reports/line)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
