<SLUG> BC-EARNINGS-REPORTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSITIVE SPIN FOR ANALYSTS SOMETIMES VARIES WITH REAL DATA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A penny is not worth much nowadays except, oddly enough, on Wall
Street. There, a penny a share in company earnings can mean the
difference between a stock that soars and one that skids.
</P>
<P>
   The punishment that stocks regularly endure from investors
disappointed over the tiniest earnings misses has put managements
under pressure to deliver upbeat earnings announcements even if the
numbers do not support them. The result, according to some Wall
Street accounting experts, is a disturbing trend. More and more
companies, they say, are going to extremes to paint a rosy picture
of their operations.
</P>
<P>
   That picture tends to make stock prices jump. Only later does a
more accurate portrayal emerge in filings with regulators. By then,
though, investors usually have been swayed by analysts'
exhortations and are no longer paying close attention.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors say the trend and the pressures on companies to
perform well has made news distributed by companies in news
releases and conference calls with analysts increasingly suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Such pressure was evident recently as James H. Hance Jr., vice
chairman and chief financial officer of Bank of America, prepared
to deliver the bank's third-quarter results to Wall Street. The
bank's stock was under siege. In the week before the Oct. 18
earnings announcement, the shares lost 13.9 percent of their value,
falling to a 52-week low.
</P>
<P>
   Happily for Hance, he had positive news for investors that
Monday. For the third quarter of 1999, Bank of America's net income
more than doubled to $2.15 billion from the comparable period in
1998. Because the bank had for weeks been quietly advising analysts
to reduce their estimates, investors breathed a sigh of relief when
the company's results exceeded the reduced expectations. The shares
rose 22 percent by week's end.
</P>
<P>
   But little more than three weeks later, the bank's quarterly
earnings statement was filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, and it contained a surprise. A footnote to the
financial data contradicted a statement made by the bank's vice
chairman on that important October conference call and showed that
a one-time gain had helped the bank _ the nation's second largest
in terms of assets, after Citigroup _ meet Wall Street's earnings
estimates. Since one-time gains do not represent continuing
operations, investors view them as less compelling.
</P>
<P>
   The discrepancy between what was said on the conference call and
what came out in the regulatory filing has caused a stir among
analysts on Wall Street. Executives have always tried to put the
best face on their reports to analysts, investors and the public.
But some analysts feel that Bank of America went further,
misleading them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have always been companies willing to do this, but the
practice is now more widespread and is being seen at even the most
respected of firms,'' said Charles Peabody, a bank stock analyst
for 20 years, the last three at Mitchell Securities in New York.
``The actions are getting more desperate.''
</P>
<P>
   With so much of a typical corporate executive's pay tied up in
his company's shares, the power of positive spin on stock prices
has never been more important to managers.
</P>
<P>
   An increasingly common tactic is to publicize one set of numbers
in a quarterly news release and conference calls and file a
different, usually less positive, set with regulators weeks later.
Another maneuver is to be vague in a news release claiming
blockbuster results, leaving investors unsure about what
contributed to the company's gains until the quarterly statements
are filed.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn E. Turner, chief accountant at the Securities and Exchange
Commission, is not happy about the trend. ``I'm concerned about
people trying to put a better spin on their numbers that may be in
fact misleading,'' he said. ``If you're going to play games with
investors, you've got to understand you're going to lose your
credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Securities and Exchange Commission does not
regulate corporate news releases or conference calls, regulators do
say generally that companies must accurately portray the state of
their businesses to investors and the public. Companies that
distort their results could face regulatory action. Shareholder
lawsuits may also result.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bank of America conference call, Judah Kraushaar, a bank
analyst at Merrill Lynch, asked Hance whether any of the bank's
noninterest income designated as ``other'' included a material sale
of an asset or business that would not recur in coming quarters.
Hance replied, ``There is nothing in there but routine things.''
</P>
<P>
   But the bank's regulatory filing noted that fully 17 percent of
``other'' noninterest income, which totaled $515 million in the
quarter, was an $89 million nonrecurring gain on the ``sale of
certain businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked why Hance neglected to mention the $89 million,
Robert Stickler, Bank of America's spokesman, said, `` Hance was
focused on the line items that had significant extraordinary
aberrations in that quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   For a bank with $3.3 billion in income before taxes in the
quarter, $89 million may indeed seem like small change. But the
gain on the sale added 3 cents a share to the company's earnings in
the period. Without those 3 cents, analysts say, the bank would
have missed earnings estimates by a penny a share.
</P>
<P>
   Research organizations like First Call/Thomson Financial and
IBES compile analysts' earnings estimates daily to provide a
consensus of what Wall Street reckons a company will earn. With all
eyes on the magic earnings number, not meeting it can kill a stock.
</P>
<P>
   That is what happened to National City Corp. of Cleveland, the
nation's 10th-largest bank, when it announced third-quarter
earnings of 57 cents a share on Oct. 15. Even though the results
were 9.6 percent ahead of the comparable period a year earlier,
Wall Street had been forecasting 58 cents a share. Investors fled
the stock, lopping 5.1 percent off its value.
</P>
<P>
   It was not always thus. ``Thirty years ago, nobody cared if
IBM's business for a quarter or two was slowing down because it
didn't have any impact on the company's stock price,'' said Howard
Schilit, president of the Center for Financial Research and
Analysis, an accounting watchdog firm in Rockville, Md. That's all
different with stock prices are trading at such high levels. ``Now,
because a company having a period of decline in their business will
have a very, very severe impact on the stock price, these companies
will do almost anything legally to prevent that from occurring,''
Schilit said.  &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
