<HEADER>
A4712 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-NORWITH-INDONESIA-BOS     12-20 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORWITH-INDONESIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERMONT SCHOOL SEVERS TIES TO INDONESIAN GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an about-face, the president of Norwich University, a private
military college in Vermont, announced Monday that he would ``sever
all formal ties with the Indonesian government.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision dismantles a two-year-old program for Indonesian
students that came under fire this fall, against the backdrop of a
brutal Jakarta-backed crackdown on civilians in East Timor. The
students were selected and their tuition was paid by the Indonesian
government through its military attache in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In October, when the Globe first reported the connection,
Norwich's president, Richard Schneider, maintained that excluding
the Indonesian students would amount to discrimination. But
Schneider last weekend changed his mind, decreeing that the school
would no longer accept payments from the Indonesian military.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 undergraduates who are currently funded by the Indonesian
government will remain on campus, but their tuition will be paid
through ``alternative sources of funding,'' Schneider said. Norwich
will also establish scholarships for two students from East Timor,
``to demonstrate our commitment to helping the world's newest
nation as it sets about the onerous task of nation building.''
</P>
<P>
   Word spread quickly Monday among the small group of faculty who
have been trying to draw the administration's attention to human
rights abuses in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great. I feel stunned,'' said Mitch Hall, who is
director of the school's International Student Office and has been
one of the most vocal opponents of the cooperative program. ``I
think it's a tremendous leap forward and I think it's right.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the coming months, a university commission will lay new
ground rules for international students _ with a focus on when and
how a government's human rights record should affect a foreign
student's application. Some faculty members want the university to
invite outside human rights groups such as Amnesty International or
Human Rights Watch to consult on the school's admissions process.
</P>
<P>
   Until spring, when the panel delivers a report on international
admissions, the school will not accept any more students from the
Indonesian military. However, university spokesman Tom Greene said
there was ``unanimous support'' on campus for the continued
attendance of the undergraduates currently enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they applied again, we'd accept them again,'' he said.
``They've been great students.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Byrnes, one of the professors who argued for the changes,
said he and his colleagues never objected to Indonesian students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our criticism was never that there are Indonesian students
here,'' said Byrnes, who teaches in Norwich's history department.
``We objected to the fact that there seemed to be this
institutional relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The Norwich-Indonesia program was set up in 1997 after an
exchange of visits between Norwich officials and two Indonesian
generals. The generals were members of Kopassus, the Indonesian
Army's elite special forces.
</P>
<P>
   After the East Timorese independence vote Aug. 30 triggered a
brutal military crackdown in the capital, Dili, President Bill
Clinton issued a ban on U.S. support for the Indonesian military.
Because the students were civilians, and because Norwich is a
private institution, the university was not bound by that ban, said
Greene.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, though, Schneider decided to discontinue the
program after months of dismay over the growing split between the
Indonesian military and the civilian government, said Greene.
Schneider had ``wanted to see how the Indonesian military would
react'' after the referendum, and became discouraged by what he
saw, Greene said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 2014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4713 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-EARNINGS-REPORTS-ART-     12-20 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARNINGS-REPORTS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: Schilit said.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some companies try to shift the focus away from the bad news in
their results by trumpeting what's good in the earnings release and
conference call, leaving the darker side to the less-well-read SEC
filing.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the third-quarter results contained in a news release
on Oct. 25 by Trump Hotels &AMP; Casino Resorts. The company exulted
that its earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and
amortization had risen 18 percent from the third quarter of 1998.
Net income more than doubled, and earnings came in 9 cents a share
above the consensus estimate.
</P>
<P>
   The stock rose more than 8 percent on the day of the statement.
Clearly, it was a good quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Or was it? What Trump failed to note in its release was that it
had counted as revenue certain assets of an Official All-Star Cafe
in the Taj Mahal Casino. Because Planet Hollywood International
Inc., the troubled company that owned the cafe, had closed it and
ended its lease with Trump, the restaurant's fixtures, logos and
memorabilia were available for use by the Taj Mahal for four
months. The value of these assets was set by an ``independent''
consultant at $17.2 million, the company said. It was listed under
revenue as other income.
</P>
<P>
   Because Trump's news release lumped all the company's revenue
together, nothing was said about the $17.2 million in restaurant
assets. Investors assumed that the company's 1.4 percent increase
in revenue from a year earlier reflected an improvement in its
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Only in footnotes in the quarterly statement filed with the SEC
did the company specify that more than half of the $31 million in
other income for the quarter resulted inexplicably from the
restaurant's assets.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas L. Ribis, president of Trump, did not return a phone
call seeking comment about the accounting maneuver. The stock has
since fallen back to its level before the upbeat earnings release.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just footnotes that can contain land mines. Some
companies actually change their bottom lines from the time of the
news release to the regulatory filing.
</P>
<P>
   IDT Corp., a telecommunications services provider in Hackensack,
N.J., put out a release on Oct. 14 gushing about its ``record''
fourth-quarter revenues and those for the full year ended July 31.
The stock rose 3.6 percent on the news.
</P>
<P>
   When IDT filed its SEC report on Nov. 4, several of the
company's expenses were greater than they had been in the earnings
news release. As a result, the company reported a much wider loss.
While the company's news release said it lost 15 cents a share in
the fourth quarter, the SEC filings indicated a loss of 18 cents a
share. The discrepancy between the documents was reported by The
Street.com.
</P>
<P>
   Why did the reports differ? Norman Rosenberg, an IDT spokesman,
said an error was found in figures supplied by a subsidiary,
Net2Phone, after the first release. ``It was not an intentional
mistake,'' Rosenberg said, adding, ``these are complex accounting
issues.'' When it was discovered, the discrepancy was corrected,
and the subsequent SEC filing contained the new numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, IDT did not issue a corrected news release. ``We
were going to,'' Rosenberg said. ``But Net2Phone did not, so our
position was we can't put out a press release about it if they
don't put out a press release about it.'' Since IDT controls the
voting shares in Net2Phone, it is unclear why the parent company
did not influence its subsidiary to publish such a release.
``Technically, we could have done it,'' Rosenberg said. ``Nobody
here felt like forcing them to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone can make a mistake, of course, but investors suspect
that some errors may not be inadvertent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies are taking advantage of the fact that attention to
performance is increasingly concentrated in a small slice of time
surrounding the earnings release,'' said Martin S. Fridson, chief
high-yield debt strategist at Merrill Lynch. ``In principle, bad
news should have just as much impact if it's disclosed later on, in
the 10-Q,'' the quarterly SEC filings, he said. ``But companies are
betting that it won't and they may be right.''
</P>
<P>
   IDT's stock rose the day of its earnings release, but the shares
barely moved when it made its SEC filing.
</P>
<P>
   One result of the corporate dissembling is that investors should
be far more skeptical about news releases. Schilit, the accounting
watchdog, said that corporate earnings releases have become such a
good source of misinformation that his researchers use them to
identify companies that may be playing accounting games.
``Companies can dress up whatever they want to dress up in a
conference call, but SEC regulations require certain disclosure in
company filings,'' he said. ``Investors should absolutely wait
until the SEC filing comes out before making any decisions which
come from a preliminary announcement, press release or conference
call.''
</P>
<P>
   This kind of patience is increasingly difficult for investors to
practice when they see others giddy over an earnings announcement.
But the reality check that SEC filings represent are becoming more
and more valuable, accounting experts say.
</P>
<P>
   The practice of obscuring bad news while talking up the good is
at odds with the increasing candor in financial disclosures that
regulators have been calling for in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech before the American Bankers Association in October,
Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve Board chairman, urged
commercial bankers to improve their disclosures. ``The scale and
clarity of disclosures is better at some institutions than at
others and, on average, could be considerably improved,'' Greenspan
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
