<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ALA-BOWL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Burnell plays Santa; Fulmer speaks on inspiration
 &HT;    By Alan Wooten
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOBILE, Ala. _ David Burnell took the joy stick as he sat down
and looked right at home playing the Nintendo game.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours later, he was at practice zipping upfield on a post
pattern and firmly catching a laser of a pass from David Garrard as
he stepped into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Both actions brought smiles. The difference was the first one
was, in so many ways, more important than the second for the 5-5,
145-pound East Carolina wide receiver during Mobile Alabama Bowl
week.
</P>
<P>
   Burnell's Nintendo abilities were tested as he played with some
youngsters at the University of South Alabama Children and Women's
Hospital. He was one of 11 East Carolina players who, along with 11
from Texas Christian, made a few rounds along with the toy-bearing
soldiers from the Navy Marine Corps Reserve Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines make the visit during the Senior Bowl, and with the
new bowl in town, get to do it twice this holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said I related to the kids real good,'' Burnell said.
``It's really that they look at me, and laugh really, and they're
amused at how short I am and play football. That comes as an
advantage that I can relate to the kids. But it's fun to see the
kids having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnell was joined by Jeff Kerr, Brantley Rivers, Nick Crabtree,
Andrew Bayes, Tomha McMillan, Eric Reyes, Carlos Ochoa, LaMont
Chappell, Kevin Monroe and Forrest Foster. TCU sent J.W. Wilson,
Royce Huffman, Chris Kaylakie, Patrick Batteaux, LaDainian
Tomlinson, Shannon Brazzell, Reggie Hunt, Cedric James, Curtis
Fuller, Mike Scarborough and Michael Keathley.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the children at the hospital suffer from sickle
cell, cystic fibrosis, asthma or respiratory synticial virus (RSV).
</P>
<P>
   As the players moved about from room to room, one young girl got
away with something offensive linemen can't _ she grabbed the arm
of Kerr and wouldn't let him go.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an experience,'' Kerr said. ``She grabbed a hold of
me, wouldn't let go, and it was a good thing because you don't
really get a chance to have that experience very often. I think it
was real rewarding for me, and I hope it gave her a sense of
reward, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Ochoa arrived Saturday with a steadfast goal in mind similar to
all the Pirates _ beat TCU Wednesday night. But he liked having a
big part in making a child's day Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what it's all about,'' Ochoa said. ``Me personally,
this is the greatest reward you can give me, watching little kids
smile. This is when playing football becomes worth it to me, coming
here and seeing the kids _ this is the real world. This is what
really happens out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a part of that, to be a part of making a kid smile, you
can't give me anything better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspirational morning
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning's Fellowship of Christian Athletes breakfast,
featuring guest speaker Tennessee head coach Phillip Fulmer, was a
voluntary event for the Pirates. But several were in attendance and
inspired by his speech.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer spoke with relation to his years in coaching and
encouraged his listeners through some testimony of his faith,
including the most special moment of last year's national
championship season which ended with the Volunteers' win over Bobby
Bowden and the Florida State Seminoles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost my dad 10 years ago,'' Fulmer said. ``A few seconds
after I shook Coach Bowden's hand and turned to see the Tennessee
fans, I felt my dad's presence and knew that the Lord's presence
was there, too. I thanked God immediately that he allowed by dad to
come back and touch me.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer assured that the Vols go through their routines with
faith as a key ingredient, and they are unashamed in letting people
know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is not a rehearsal,'' Fulmer said. ``It's a one-shot
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Good workout
</P>
<P>
   Pirates head coach Steve Logan said his team enjoyed another
solid outing Monday afternoon. Skies were still overcast, but
finally began to clear and allow sun to shine by the time the team
made its way back to Ladd-Peebles Stadium to shower and change.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came out today again and had a really good practice,''
Logan said. ``We'll come out tomorrow (Tuesday) in just helmets
only, run through a few assignments, break a light sweat and be
ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Logan said with open practices, no new wrinkles were being
shown. But he also said those new wrinkles were put in before the
team left Greenville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back home, we put in a lot of stuff,'' Logan said. ``You've
got to. I mean, I'm convinced defensive coordinators watch film,
too. We've added some stuff and deleted some stuff to hopefully
we've got a fresh enough approach to where we can get in the end
zone a time or two.''
</P>
<P>
   Curfew tonight
</P>
<P>
   For the third consecutive night, East Carolina remained without
a curfew for its players _ normal operating procedure, according to
the staff. The Pirates will have one tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players back home live off campus, and the night before a
game we got to a hotel and have a curfew,'' Logan said. ``But this
(Monday night) to me is like Thursday night, two days away from a
game. They can go out and do whatever they want to do. We'll get
them up in the morning and do our routine but tomorrow night we'll
have the curfew and the whole bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Wooten writes for The Greenville Daily Reflector,
Greenville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
