</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-TEMPLE-MOUNT-ART-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCAVATING ANCIENT ARCHES IN JERUSALEM LEADS TO MODERN
CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeats to add photo note)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT23 is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In the southeastern corner of the great stone plaza
surrounding the two ancient mosques, a lone bulldozer methodically
scraped away a millennium's worth of dust and rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian and Israeli policemen stood guard tensely nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Behind them, freshly exposed to the Jerusalem sun, two
long-buried arches formed a new vaulted entryway to a vast
subterranean chamber. It is a chamber that Christians associate
with the 12th-century Crusaders who were once encamped there, and
that some Jews say could abut unexcavated ruins of the Second
Temple, built by the last Jewish kingdom more than 2,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   To the Muslim worshipers who fill the underground hall every
Friday during the holy month of Ramadan, the pillared chamber is
the seventh-century Marwani mosque, and its history and
architectural integrity are nobody's business but their own. The
Muslim clerics who are the custodians of the site angrily reject
demands by rightist Israeli politicians that they halt the digging
until Israeli archaeologists ascertain that they are not causing
archaeological damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't wait for permission from anybody,'' said Sheik
Muhammad Hussein, the director of the Haram al-Sharif mosque
complex, surveying the plaza from the desk of his Ottoman-era
office. ``This is an Islamic site.''
</P>
<P>
   In a project originally urged and authorized by the Israeli
police, the old arched walls were unearthed to provide an emergency
exit for the underground mosque. Only one narrow stairway led down
to the chamber, which was refurbished three years ago to handle
overflow crowds arriving to pray at the above-ground mosques here,
al-Aksa and the Dome of the Rock.
</P>
<P>
   This last Friday a record 400,000 worshipers filled the mosques
and the plaza. As many as a half million are expected for the final
Friday of Ramadan _ which, by coincidence, falls on New Year's Eve,
when thousands of Christians are expected to congregate in the
storied hillsides and ravines immediately outside the immense
plaza.
</P>
<P>
   In a city where theology and archaeology are explosively
entwined, it was inevitable that the excavation would not be seen
as a simple doorway project.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had work begun than Jerusalem's mayor, Israel's
attorney general, and the chief of the state antiquities commission
said it could endanger artifacts in the interior of the platform
that supported the Second Temple before the Romans knocked it down.
</P>
<P>
   Far-right Jewish protesters marched through the Old City streets
below, burning Palestinian flags and vowing one day to demolish the
mosques above. Prime Minister Ehud Barak convened a cabinet-level
review of the project. The archways would remain open, he ordered _
but not without trepidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about a very sensitive, volatile place, and one
must refrain from doing anything hasty that we will regret
afterwards,'' the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli courts have so far refused to issue a requested
injunction against the project _ to the relief of the Barak
administration, which does not want to impose its authority on
Muslim worshipers who have never recognized Israeli sovereignty in
Jerusalem's Old City. But Israeli television has kept the issue
alive, broadcasting scenes of Palestinian trucks hauling loads of
soil rich with pottery shards to a city dump.
</P>
<P>
   Sheik Hussein professed to be unconcerned by the criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pay it no mind,'' he said, dismissing the debate with a wave
of his hand. ``This is just a lot of noise stirred up by the
Israelis for their own internal reasons. It is a fight between
Israeli factions.''
</P>
<P>
   Some respected Israeli archaeologists also say the controversy
is overblown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where they are digging is all late medieval landfill,'' said
Dan Bahat, a former chief government archaeologist for Jerusalem.
``If it were up to me, I would not have used bulldozers. But there
is nothing of value there. There is certainly nothing from the
Second Temple period. That is nonsense.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Built by Herod the Great in one of the biggest construction jobs
of the Roman era, the mammoth structure Muslims know as Haram
al-Sharif and Israelis call the Temple Mount is ground zero for
Jerusalem's religious wars. It is crowned by the mosques that are
the third holiest site in Islam, after Mecca and Medina.
</P>
<P>
   The Western Wall of the great stone platform is the single most
sacred place of worship for observant Jews. A blocked-off portal in
its eastern wall is the fabled Golden Door, believed by some
fundamentalist Christians to be the divinely designated entryway
for the Second Coming of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   To tamper physically with any of this is to play a highly
dangerous game of three-dimensional chess. In 1996, violent riots
followed Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's authorization of the
opening of a tunnel along the platform's deeply buried base.
Fifty-four Palestinians and fourteen Israelis died.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the tunnel,'' said Jamal Joulani, a leader of the
Islamic Boy Scouts, whose young troops supervise crowds here during
Ramadan. ``The Israelis just want to prove they have sovereignty
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Ehud Olmert, a right-wing opposition leader, emphatically
agrees. By permitting Muslims to excavate with no oversight by
state archaeologists, the Barak administration is undermining
Israel's legal and moral claim to this crucial piece of Jerusalem
real estate, he charged. With Israeli and Palestinian negotiators
just beginning to try to reconcile their mutually exclusive
territorial demands here, this is a politically potent accusation.
</P>
<P>
   When Israeli forces occupied the Old City of Jerusalem in the
1967 Middle East War, Moshe Dayan, their commander, promised that
Muslim leaders would retain administrative autonomy at Islamic holy
sites. The Waqf, an Islamic religious foundation that holds title
to the mosques, has overseen public works there ever since, without
ever formally recognizing Israel's authority.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Jerusalem Waqf answers to Yasser Arafat's Palestinian
Authority, but on a practical level, it acknowledges Israel's de
facto control. The Waqf bulldozer was beginning to clear away a
third archway when Barak reiterated his decision to permit the
opening of two portals, but only two. The work abruptly stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment the Waqf acted beyond the authorization that we
gave them, we informed it immediately that it had to seal that
which had been opened _ and so it was,'' said Haim Ramon, the
Israeli government minister for Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   For Bahat, this archaeological spat is literally wide of the
mark. Where Second Temple remains might be found, he said, is about
200 yards to the west of the archways, directly beneath al-Aksa
mosque. But excavation there is considered unthinkable for both
diplomatic and religious reasons, he concedes.
</P>
<P>
   What would happen if the Temple were found?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what happens when politics is harnessed to
archaeology,'' Bahat said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 2016EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
