<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4718 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-COWBOYS21-COX     12-20 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two wins away from January play for Cowboys
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Two wins and they're in.
</P>
<P>
   That's the motto of the Dallas Cowboys, who are assured a berth
in the NFL playoffs if they close the regular season with victories
over New Orleans and the New York Giants. Of course, the Cowboys
have not won consecutive games since September.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the gloom of Sunday's 22-21 loss to the New York Jets is a
ray of optimism. The Cowboys are among 10 NFC teams with a chance
to play in the postseason, an indication of how close the race has
become.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cowboys finish the season 9-7, they are in the playoffs.
Here's why:
</P>
<P>
   In case of a tie in the standings, Dallas owns tiebreaker edges
over Tampa Bay, Carolina, Green Bay and Washington. According to
the NFL, Minnesota needed to tie its last two games to knock Dallas
out. (Minnesota played host to Green Bay in Monday Night Football;
the outcome was not available at presstime.)
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, Dallas beat the other playoff contenders in most
tie-breakers, such as head-to-head competition and winning
percentage in the division. The NFC playoffs include three division
champions and three wild-card teams. Dallas will win the NFC East,
by the way, if it sweeps its last two and Washington loses one of
its last two.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that's looking ahead, something the Cowboys cannot
afford to do.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas coach Chan Gailey said his team will keeps its focus on
New Orleans, a 2-12 team coming off a 31-8 loss in Baltimore. After
opening the season with a victory, New Orleans has lost 12 of 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``The objective now is to fight through this game, win it, and
then come back and beat the Giants at home (Jan. 2),'' Gailey said
Monday. ``That's the way to approach this.''
</P>
<P>
   The schedule favors Dallas in the final two weeks, even though
the Cowboys have not proved they can win on the road consistently.
They should be heavy betting favorites against the Saints and
Giants. Nevertheless, Dallas has not won consecutive games since it
opened the season with three straight victories.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey spent much of his time Monday explaining his inconsistent
offense. The most disturbing part of Sunday's loss was quarterback
Troy Aikman's inability to connect with his receivers. In the
second half, Aikman completed only four of 13 passes for 37 yards.
He threw four straight incomplete passes on the Cowboys' final
drive to close the game.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman is only part of the problem, Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all held accountable,'' the coach said. ``Everybody is
on the offensive side. Everybody has their share.''
</P>
<P>
   And the pain of losing so many close games is starting to show.
The team's seven losses have been by an average of 5.4 points a
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we are again after seven losses, saying what we could do
and how good we can be,'' Emmitt Smith said in a frustrated tone.
``Who are we kidding?''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys were victims of their own mistakes Sunday. The
league's most penalized team had eight penalties for 92 yards.
Aikman threw two interceptions, including a poorly thrown pass in
the end zone that was intended for Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get deep when (defensive backs) are running out
there,'' Sanders said. ``I can't catch them and the ball, too.
Don't blame me for that mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders has played offense for two games, and the experiment has
not worked. He caught two of 14 passes against Philadelphia nine
days ago and was held without a reception against the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said he did not expect Sanders to produce much on
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was expecting him to to have an impact because of his
presence on the field,'' Gailey said. ``But considering he only
practiced one week _ and then was sick most of last week _ you
can't expect all the timing to be there. Even great athletes have
to have a certain amount of timing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Cantu writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: rcantu(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
