<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4725 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-VT-GAY-MARRIAGE-970(2     12-20 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VT-GAY-MARRIAGE-970(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERMONT COURT RULES GAYS MUST BE PROVIDED SAME RIGHTS AS
HETEROSEXUAL COUPLES
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Vermont Supreme Court ruled on Monday that the
state must guarantee the very same protections and benefits to
committed gay and lesbian couples as it does to heterosexual
spouses. The court ordered the Legislature to either make Vermont
the first state to legalize gay marriage or to adopt a domestic
partnership law that would be the most sweeping in the country.
</P>
<P>
   To extend equal rights to homosexual couples ``who seek nothing
more, nor less, than legal protection and security for their avowed
commitment to an intimate and lasting relationship is simply, when
all is said and done, a recognition of our common humanity,'' the
ruling said.
</P>
<P>
   The court found that it was unconstitutionally discriminatory to
deny marriage licenses to three homosexual couples, thus depriving
them of the myriad benefits, from inheritance rights to health
insurance to tax breaks, that accrue to heterosexual married
couples.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling gave legislators an unspecified ``reasonable period
of time'' to consider whether the remedy lay in some sort of
``domestic partnership'' system or in simply including homosexual
partners in the state's marriage laws.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Shumlin, the president pro tempore of the Vermont Senate,
said on Monday that the state's predominantly Democratic lawmakers
may decide in the coming session, which begins next month, how to
respond. He expects it will be much easier to get votes for a
domestic partnership law than one creating full-fledged gay
marriages, but ``both are strong possibilities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the court says, `You have a class of people whose civil
rights are being trampled upon, Vermonters want to remedy that,'''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Piecemeal systems of protections and benefits for gay and
lesbian couples have been enacted in recent years in places around
the country, but advocates for gay rights said on Monday that the
Vermont ruling would put the state far ahead of anywhere else.
California and Hawaii have statewide domestic partnership systems,
they said, but they pale next to what is likely to come about in
Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   If Vermont opts for full-fledged gay marriage and homosexual
couples begin flocking to the state to wed, their legal status in
their home states will prove a very tangled issue, experts said on
Monday. Since the prospect of legalized gay marriage arose in a
Hawaii case in 1991, nearly 30 states have passed laws against it.
But gay rights advocates say it is not clear whether those laws
would stand up against challenges. Most likely, legal experts say,
there would be state-by-state battles over recognizing same-sex
marriages performed in Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's decision, written by Chief Justice Jeffrey L. Amestoy,
exhilarated the three couples suing the state, their lawyers and
the many gay and civil rights groups supporting them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We celebrated our 27th anniversary together in October,'' said
one of the plaintiff couples, Holly Puterbaugh and Lois Farnham, in
a joint statement. ``We look forward to the time when we can
finally make it official.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Levi, a lawyer for Gay and Lesbian Advocates and
Defenders who worked on the case, said, ``It's unbelievable. The
scope and the magnitude of it are really tremendous.'' Never
before, she said, has a state supreme court guaranteed ``the full
range of benefits, in both public and private employment'' to
same-sex couples.
</P>
<P>
   But the ruling brought expressions of dismay from the religious,
conservative and other groups who oppose gay marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision is not only troubling but it is tremendously
disappointing,'' said Jay Sekulow, chief counsel of the American
Center for Law and Justice, a national conservative group, in a
statement. ``This is the first court in the country that has
mandated same-sex marriage. And while this legal decision is
designed to elevate the status of same-sex couples, it really
represents a slap in the face for marriage between a man and a
woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, the Republican presidential candidate, declared:
``If I were living in Vermont, and had three women I was living
with, I would immediately file suite for benefits for my female
live-ins. Once a court says the benefit of marriage is not limited
to a man and a woman, then everything is up for grabs. Why not four
men living together, why not every possible combination you can
imagine?''
</P>
<P>
   In Vermont, Craig Bensen, an evangelical pastor and vice
president of a coalition that opposes gay marriage, said the group,
Take it to the People, was considering a strategy like that used in
Hawaii and Alaska, where opponents of gay marriage put the idea to
a referendum and got enough votes to block it. Earlier this month,
tTe Hawaii Supreme Court dismissed a gay marriage case there as
moot because a ballot measure in 1998 had authorized lawmakers to
restrict the definition of marriage to heterosexual unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suspect there will be momentum for a constitutional
amendment to clarify the nature of marriage,'' he said. ``The
difficulty is, we've got the toughest constitution to amend in the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the ruling went against them, Mr. Bensen and others on
his side said they were happy to see the question now go to the
legislature.
</P>
<P>
   William Sorrell, the state's attorney general, noted that
because the court's decision was based on the state's constitution
rather than the federal one, the ruling cannot be appealed to the
U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Other courts have ruled in favor of certain
spousal benefits for gay couples in a limited way. But, he said,
``Where this case goes further than any court has gone thus far is
that the whole panoply, if you will, of benefits and protections
that flow from traditional marriages are guaranteed under the
Vermont Constitution to same-sex couples.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although the court's ruling focused on benefits rather than
marriage itself, lawyers for the same-sex couples said on Monday
that they believed that the Legislature would ultimately choose
full-fledged marriage for same-sex couples. A domestic partnership
system would not go far enough to secure gay couples the same exact
privileges as heterosexual ones, such as access to benefits from
the federal government and private employers, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legal status of marriage carries with it a lot of
baggage,'' said Beth Robinson, a lead lawyer for the couples. ``The
Legislature will come to understand that as a practical matter, you
can't call it something different and have it be truly equal.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Monday's ruling was not a total victory for gay rights
advocates, it still left some marveling at what they described as
tremendously rapid social progress.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Coles, director of the Lesbian and Gay Rights Project of
the American Civil Liberties Union, noted that the phrase
``domestic partnership'' was only invented about 19 years ago, back
when there was virtually no recognition of gay and lesbian
relationships and the whole idea was so far out that when the San
Francisco City Council passed a domestic partnership law, the mayor
then, Dianne Feinstein, vetoed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think about the way law and society move,'' he said,
``to go from San Francisco considering domestic partnerships too
far out there in 1981, to all five justices of the Vermont Supreme
Court taking equal treatment for granted in 1999 _ it's
astonishing, it really is.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the justices, who are appointed by the governor and can
be removed by the Legislature, all concurred that gay couples
should be protected from discrimination, they were not in such
simple agreement about other parts of the ruling. Three of the
court's five justices disagreed with some of Amestoy's reasoning,
and one, Denise R. Johnson, wrote that the court should order the
state to let the couples marry, rather than consigning them to ``an
uncertain fate in the political cauldron'' of a debate in the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The case began in 1997 when the three couples _ Holly Puterbaugh
and Lois Farnham, Stan Baker and Peter Harrigan, and Nina Beck and
Stacy Jolles _ filed suit after their local town clerks denied them
marriage licenses. A Superior Court judge turned them down, but
they appealed to the state Supreme Court, which heard their oral
arguments last November.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, Ms. Puterbaugh told reporters on Monday, will make
this a special Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's going to be a little extra feeling of family
now,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
