<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABERNATHY21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Abernathy case in jury's hands
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Former Georgia state Sen. Ralph David Abernathy III's
attorney told a jury in final arguments Monday that the state's own
witnesses testified Abernathy had paid them for their work _ but
the prosecution pointed out that those witnesses said they hadn't
been fully paid.
</P>
<P>
   The jury began deliberating just before 2 p.m. on the 28 counts
against Abernathy, based on eight expense vouchers he turned in to
the state. The jury continued deliberations into the night Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It is Abernathy's second trial on the charges, which involve
theft, false swearing, violation of his oath, forgery and
influencing a witness. His first trial, in September, ended in a
hung jury. Some jurors said it was caused by a single woman who
refused to consider convicting Abernathy.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorney General Stacey Hydrich, in the first of her
two final arguments, told the jury that Abernathy ``used his office
to defraud the people of the state and to line his own pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the state, Abernathy filled out vouchers while he
was a state senator, had various aides and helpers swear he had
paid them, collected the money and kept all or most of it.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Lackland, Abernathy's lead attorney, said he offered no
witnesses for the defense ``because their witnesses were our
witnesses. They came in here and told the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the witnesses for whom Abernathy turned in state expense
vouchers all testified they were paid. Some said they were paid in
part, but never saw all the money that Abernathy had them swear
they had been paid.
</P>
<P>
   Because the defense unaccountably submitted a single piece of
evidence _ a copy of the Georgia code concerning notaries public _
the state had the privilege of making the opening and closing final
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   In her closing argument, Hydrich proposed to play excerpts from
the state's strongest evidence, tape recordings of telephone
conversations in which Abernathy asks his former public relations
adviser, Zee Bradford, to tell the GBI he had paid her the $2,700
for which he had signed her name to vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   The defense objected to playing excerpts, so Judge L.A.
McConnell allowed her to play the tapes in their entirety.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Warner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
