<SLUG> BC-BURLINGTON-CANADIAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$6 BILLION MERGER WOULD CREATE LARGEST NORTH AMERICAN RAILROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map and graphic are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Burlington Northern Santa Fe Corp. and Canadian National Railway
Co. announced a $6 billion merger Monday that would create the
largest railroad in North America.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company would have 50,000 miles of track stretching
from Nova Scotia to Los Angeles and the Gulf of Mexico, connecting
every state west of the Mississippi and every major city across the
length of Canada. Burlington Northern, a longtime advocate of a
transcontinental railroad, would vault ahead of Union Pacific as
the biggest railroad and solidify its position as the largest
carrier of coal and grain.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed combination will face regulatory scrutiny in the
United States and in Canada, but it is only the latest step in
fulfilling every rail tycoon's dream for the last 150 years of
establishing a transcontinental railroad in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Robert D. Krebs, the chairman of Burlington Northern, and other
proponents have contended that such a railroad would provide
shippers with seamless, coast-to-coast service that is cheaper and
more predictable, despite the disruptions that have accompanied
virtually every recent merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposed merger positions this company as the front-runner
in any potential transcontinental mergers in the United States,''
said Carole M. Neely, a transportation analyst with Brown Brothers
Harriman. ``I'm confident this will be good for both railroads as
well as the industry. The new franchise will be the largest in
terms of market capitalization and geographic presence within North
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors did not immediately embrace the deal, as shares
of Burlington Northern fell $3.5625 or 13 percent Monday to
$24.8125 on the New York Stock Exchange. Canadian National shares
fell 2.8 percent to $42.95 (Canadian) or $29.20 on the Toronto
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a reaction to past merger problems with investors
saying, I don't want to be around for this one,'' said Michael H.
Lloyd, a transportation analyst with Merrill Lynch. ``But I think
it'll calm down tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the proposed deal, Burlington Northern would
own about two-thirds of a new company, North American Railways Inc.
The deal consists of a stock swap in which Canadian National
shareholders will get 1.05 shares of North American Railways, while
Burlington Northern shareholders will get a share of the new
company for each of their shares.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company would employ 67,000 people and have annual
revenue of about $12.5 billion. It would be based in Montreal,
although the headquarters for Burlington Northern would remain in
Fort Worth, Texas. Paul Tellier, chief executive of Canadian
National, would serve as chief executive of North American
Railways.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination uses a new model for railroad consolidation,''
said Krebs, who would become the non-executive chairman of the new
company, ``one that will enable the partners to effectively
integrate with maximum efficiency and without sacrificing quality
customer service. The model carefully preserves and protects the
existing identities and efficient rail networks of each company.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the New York market still eludes him, Krebs will get
the transcontinental link he has long sought and connections to a
major, deep water port on the East Coast, Halifax. Both companies
expect that most of the growth in rail traffic will be north-south,
rather than east-west.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that the latest announcement could spur another
round of consolidation that has already put more than 90 percent of
North American rail revenue into the coffers of a half dozen
companies. Canadian Pacific, Canada's other major railroad, would
almost certainly become a target, especially since it has a route
into the lucrative New York market, they said.
</P>
<P>
   But Paul Clark, vice president of Canadian Pacific in Calgary,
said his company would not rush into anything. He described the
latest deal as a ``financial merger'' and acknowledged that
alliances with American railroads are ``necessary to improve the
financial performance'' of major carriers. He said he preferred the
cooperative arrangements Canadian Pacific had with Union Pacific,
Norfolk Southern and CSX to a merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a large railway like Burlington Northern shows up on your
doorstep,'' Clark said, ``they want to move traffic away as much as
grow traffic in your neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger will almost certainly face opposition from rival
railroads, Canadian nationalists and rail freight customers, who
have been battered by delays and tie-ups caused by recent mergers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be rough sailing,'' Robert L. Banks, a longtime
transportation consultant in Washington, predicted. ``There'll be
opponents coming from many different quarters, here and in
Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Shippers are still grumbling about widespread delays and freight
snarls in the West during 1997 and 1998 as Union Pacific struggled
to absorb Southern Pacific Rail Corp., in a $5.4 billion deal. In
the East, Norfolk Southern Corp. and CSX Corp. have split up
Conrail in a $10.2 billion transaction, and faced similar, albeit
less dramatic, problems in integrating those assets into their rail
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the logistical nightmares, shippers have complained
that they are increasingly at the mercy of a single railroad
serving a particular city or area of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Emmett, president of the National Industrial
Transportation League, said that the rail, truck and ocean-shipping
customers who make up his trade association are almost universally
opposed to the alliance between Burlington Northern and Canadian
National.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rail shippers are still waiting for the railroads to
deliver on the better service promised by the earlier mergers,''
Emmett said. ``They haven't got that right yet. And the thought of
yet another megamerger is a kick in the gut to shippers.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda J. Morgan, chairman of the Surface Transportation Board,
the regulatory agency that would have to approve the deal, said
Monday that the announcement took her by surprise. ``Railroads,
together with their customers and employees, have not yet fully
adjusted to recent mergers, and this proposal may represent the
beginning of another round of major rail mergers,'' Ms. Morgan said
in a statement. ``The Board will have to review carefully all of
the ramifications of any such application.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Neely was optimistic about the prospects for the deal,
because, she said, there is little overlap between the companies'
rail networks, which use the same computerized information systems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
