<SLUG> BC-GOLDEN-GLOBES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AMERICAN BEAUTY' LEADS GOLDEN GLOBE PICKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With six nominations, including those for best film and best
director, the dark satire ``American Beauty'' led the way Monday
among this year's dramatic films in contention for Golden Globe
Awards. The film also earned a nomination for its director, Sam
Mendes, as did the four other films nominated as best: ``The End of
the Affair,'' directed by Neil Jordan; ``The Hurricane,'' directed
by Norman Jewison; ``The Insider,'' directed by Michael Mann and
``The Talented Mr. Ripley,'' directed by Anthony Minghella.
</P>
<P>
   Nominations for best actress in a drama went to Annette Bening
for ``American Beauty,'' Julianne Moore for ``The End of the
Affair,'' Meryl Streep for ``Music of the Heart,'' Hilary Swank for
``Boys Don't Cry'' and Sigourney Weaver for ``A Map of the World.''
</P>
<P>
   Nominations for best dramatic actor went to Russell Crowe for
``The Insider,'' Matt Damon for ``The Talented Mr. Ripley,''
Richard Farnsworth for ``The Straight Story,'' Kevin Spacey for
``American Beauty'' and Denzel Washington for ``The Hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   The award ceremonies will be broadcast on NBC on Jan. 23. The
Golden Globe Awards are conferred by the Hollywood Foreign Press
Association, an organization of roughly 100 foreign journalists,
many of them free-lance and some of whom seldom see their work in
print.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
