<HEADER>
A4737 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-PRISON-DISTURBANCE-CO     12-20 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-DISTURBANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inmates at Texas prison go on rampage, damage cellblock
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEEVILLE, Texas _ Dozens of rampaging convicts, freed from their
cells by a security breach, looted and heavily damaged their
cellblock early Monday at a maximum-security prison where a guard
was stabbed to death three days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the uprising involving 80 convicts at the
McConnell Unit lasted just over three hours before specially
trained riot-suppression squads, firing pepper spray and tear gas,
regained control of the administrative segregation building about
7:15 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Three guards were injured, one for a severe gash on her arm and
two for exposure to the eye-watering gas. Officials said no
convicts were seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   By late Monday, an uneasy calm remained at the 2,900-man prison.
All convicts remained locked in their cells as guards conducted a
cell-by-cell search for weapons and contraband.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we don't think this was the result any organized
effort, but rather one inmate who was able to get out of his cell,
seize control of a security post and then let the others out,''
said Gary Johnson, director of the prisons division of the Texas
Department of Criminal Justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no indication of negligence up to this point, but we
want to know how this inmate got into that (security) post.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the riot, the first in a Texas prison since
100 convicts heavily damaged the Briscoe Unit in Dilley in March
1995, began about 3:45 a.m. when convict William Steed Kelley, 31,
jimmied his cell door open and forced his way into the cellblock's
security post, located at the center of the building and surrounded
by cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a shank (a sharpened piece of metal),'' Johnson said.
``In order to get in that post he had to come through two doors
that should have been locked. How he got through those two doors is
something that's part of our investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Other officials said the guards who electronically opened at
least one of the doors for Kelley has worked at the prison only
since July. She was being interviewed by investigators, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and other officials confirmed that the cell doors at the
McConnell Unit are like those that have been prone to being jimmied
open at other prisons in the past. By late Monday, a team of prison
security specialists were at McConnell to review damage and
recommend immediate modifications at 10 other prisons with the same
type of cell doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want this to happen again,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   After Kelley slashed one officer, and started ``punching all the
buttons'' to open the 84 cell doors, both inmate and officer fled
the control room, said Larry Todd, a spokesman for the prison
agency. One of the cells was vacant and three inmates did not take
part in the riots, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A third guard escaped into an adjacent exercise yard and scaled
the fence. Todd said co-workers used wire cutters to allow him an
escape route a few moments late, as the riot began.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were breaking all the windows, smashing the equipment in
the control room, pulling their mattresses out _ trying to destroy
everything they could,'' Todd said. ``Then they tore the rails off
their bunks and used them as battering rams. Vandalism is too
understated for what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, a general alarm had been sounded throughout the
prison. Steel riot doors were locked across a hallway to keep the
rioters inside their cellblock. Initial efforts to quell the melee
with pepper spray failed, officials said, and within two hours more
than 100 guards and riot specialists had been assembled at the
prison to retake the cellblock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inmates used towels under the doors to keep out the gas
and a number were running around with wet towels across their faces
for the same reason,'' Todd said. ``It took some time, but control
was re-established.''
</P>
<P>
   That came about 7:15 a.m., Johnson said, when riot teams wearing
gas masks stormed the cellblock behind a cloud of eye-irritating
gas and quickly took custody of the rioters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inmates offered little resistance,'' Johnson said. ``At no
point were we in any danger of losing the unit as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Todd said that throughout the morning _ as guards
stripped the rioters to their boxer shorts and led them in
handcuffs to a gymnasium for interrogation and medical checks _
some rioters continued trying to fight. ``We have some who remain
very belligerent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday afternoon, a line of white prison busses and vans were
lined up outside the prison to begin transferring the rioters to
other maximum-security prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Damage to the cellblock was still being tallied, but Johnson
said he hopes it can be back in service within a month. The 84
cells affected by Monday's riot are among 504 in the high-security
building at the prison, which was opened in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Todd said officials plan to seek charges of attempted capital
murder and inciting a riot against Kelley. He is already serving a
99-year term from Houston for attempted murder and aggravated
sexual assault with a deadly weapon. The attempted murder charge
involved a 1991 attack on another inmate at the Coffield unit near
Palestine, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the ongoing investigation into the riot, officials would
not identify the injured guards but said two were treated at a
hospital and one was treated at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The uprising was the latest violence at the prison. Daniel
Nagle, 37, a correctional officer since June 1996, was found
stabbed to death Friday in a hallway.
</P>
<P>
   Nagle _ a local union official who has been working for a pay
raise for guards, citing the dangerousness of the work _ was the
first prison guard killed in the line of duty since 1982, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Correctional officers and family members complained Monday that
the riot highlights that danger, heightened by a staffing shortage
of more than 1,000 prison guards short statewide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prisons are a powderkeg waiting to explode,'' said Lidia
Torres, 37, who said her brother is a McConnell employee. ``How
many more people have to be killed before something is done.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ward writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
