<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `A madhouse' as shoppers spend billions
 &HT;    By Renee DeGross
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Metro Atlanta retailers are all smiles going into the
last four shopping days before Christmas. Sales are up 5.8 percent
through Dec. 19, compared with 2.8 percent at this time last year,
according to First Data Corp.'s TeleCheck index. TeleCheck tracks
check writing, which accounts for about one-third of retail
spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Saturday) was the busiest I've seen it yet,'' said Lenox
Square spokesman Jeff Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   At Arbor Place in Douglasville, Ga., the mall has room for 6,000
vehicles at one time, but more than 30,000 vehicles packed its
parking lot throughout the day, equaling about 51,000 shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   But what could really keep storefront retailers smiling over the
next few days is this: As of Dec. 15, more than 75 percent of
Americans still had not finished their gift buying, according to a
holiday survey conducted by International Mass Retail Association
in Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   With Christmas about over for Internet retailers because of
delivery constraints, the evergreen procrastinators are showing up
at retailers' doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This week is going to be a madhouse because the Internet is no
longer an option,'' said David Herskovits, a partner in the Atlanta
office of Deloitte &AMP; Touche accounting and consulting firm.
Internet holiday sales are expected to reach $8 billion to $10
billion this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw earlier holiday buying to be more e-commere-based and
the later buying frenzy is going to be more store-based,''
Herskovits said.
</P>
<P>
   What's really giving the holiday season a kick is that consumers
are splurging on everything from digital cameras to diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   Music, video and home entertainment purchases topped the list
with the biggest increases in sales over last year _ at 13.7
percent _ for Dec. 13-19, according to the latest International
Council of Shopping Centers survey. The survey covered 70 regional
malls around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hottest items are digital cameras, without question,''
said Wayne Freedman, a spokesman for Alpharetta, Ga.-based Wolf
Camera, a chain of 720 stores in 30 states.
</P>
<P>
   Jewelry sales also sparkled, with an increase of 9.7 percent.
``People are buying diamonds, bigger than ever before,'' said Ken
Gassman Jr., an analyst with Davenport &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Other categories that showed increases include footwear, with a
6.8 percent increase, followed by apparel at 4.7 percent over last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, retail sales growth for the past week topped 6.8
percent nationally from a year ago, the ICSC found. Holiday sales
could be up anywhere from 5 percent to 7 percent for the entire
season, analysts predict.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Vitner, a First Union economist in Charlotte, N.C.,
predicts overall sales will be up around 12 percent for metro
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strong enough,'' Vitner said, ``that we're going to have
the best holiday season since 1992.''
</P>
<P>
   Renee DeGross writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
