<SLUG> BC-OHIO-VOUCHER-EDUC-720(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL VOUCHER PROGRAM IN CLEVELAND IS UNCONSTITUTIONAL, FEDERAL
JUDGE RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge ruled on Monday that a program giving thousands
of Cleveland children taxpayer-financed vouchers to attend
parochial schools violates the Constitution's separation of church
and state.
</P>
<P>
   The closely watched case, which concerns one of the most
contentious issues in education, has been the subject of debate in
the presidential campaign and is widely expected to be reviewed by
the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Solomon Oliver Jr. of Federal District Court in Cleveland
wrote that the voucher program, enacted by the Ohio Legislature in
1995, ``has the effect of advancing religion through
government-sponsored religious indoctrination.'' Noting that nearly
all the students receiving vouchers attend parochial schools, he
added, ``A program that is so skewed toward religion necessarily
results in indoctrination attributable to the government and
provides financial incentives to attend religious schools.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling is the latest in a series of legal victories for
those opposing vouchers, but proponents have nonetheless gathered
political steam as states continue to fashion new voucher programs.
The governor and attorney general of Ohio vowed immediately to
appeal the decision, and all parties to the case agreed to let
children continue attending schools under the voucher program until
the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals considers the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very disappointed with today's ruling because I believe
it takes away a valuable option for Cleveland parents and
students,'' Gov. Bob Taft of Ohio, a Republican, said in a
statement. ``It interrupts an experiment that can shed light on how
best to move forward with education reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The case was filed by a coalition of civil liberties groups and
teachers unions, which contended that the vouchers violated the
First Amendment's prohibition on government establishment of
religion and presented a major threat to the public school system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taxpayer dollars should be put to work in the public schools,
where they belong, and not be used to subsidize someone's
religion,'' said Carole Shields, president of People for the
American Way, a Washington group that was among those supporting
the plaintiffs. ``The country would be wise to support proven
education reforms, such as smaller classes, and not this voucher
gimmick that's leaving children, parents and taxpayers high and
dry.''
</P>
<P>
   But Christine Suma, a Cleveland mother of 12 who has three
children attending Our Lady of Counsel under the voucher program,
called Oliver ``the Grinch who stole Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision ``leaves a lot of parents on a yo-yo,'' said Mrs.
Suma, who was among the defendants named in the lawsuit. ``I won't
risk my children's lives and future in education. If I had my
children in the Cleveland public schools, I wouldn't have much
say-so.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Cleveland program, 3,761 elementary schoolchildren
receive up to $2,500 in state money toward tuition at one of 56
approved private schools, more than 80 percent of which are
religious. Currently, 96 percent of the students receiving vouchers
attend one of the parochial schools, a point emphasized throughout
Oliver's ruling. Most of those receiving the vouchers are poor.
</P>
<P>
   The 63-page court decision opens with a litany of examples of
the schools' religious nature.
</P>
<P>
   At St. Patrick, one of several Catholic schools involved in the
program, the student handbook says the No. 1 objective of education
is ``to communicate the gospel message of Jesus.'' Parents are
warned that ``religious truths and values'' permeate the whole
atmosphere of the school at St. Rocco, another Catholic
institution, and that even non-Catholic students must attend
religion classes and prayers. St. John Nottingham, a Lutheran
school, promises to teach ``reading, mathematics, spelling,
language, social studies and handwriting with a Christ-centered
approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike programs using taxpayer money to defray the costs of
parochial school education that have been upheld by the Supreme
Court, Oliver said that in the Cleveland voucher program, ``it can
generally be said that a central part of each school's program is
instruction in the theology or doctrine of a particular faith and
that religion and religious doctrines are an integral part of the
entire school experience.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The ruling quoted Thomas Jefferson and James Madison, framers of
the constitutional prohibition against mingling church and state,
and suggested that the core values of the country are at stake.
Oliver rested his decision largely on a 1973 case known as
Community for Public Education and Religious Liberty vs. Nyquist,
in which the Supreme Court rejected a New York state program that
gave parents $50 or $100 toward tuition at private and parochial
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like the program in Nyquist, there `has been no endeavor to
guarantee the separation between secular and religious educational
functions and to ensure the state financial aid supports only the
former,''' Oliver wrote. ``The effect of the aid is unmistakably to
provide desired financial support for nonpublic, sectarian
institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver also reviewed in detail several Supreme Court cases that
have allowed taxpayer money to be funneled to parochial schools,
but said each was far narrower and thus less problematic than the
Cleveland program.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's was the first program to allow vouchers to be used
for religious schools, though there is now a similar program in
Milwaukee upheld by the Wisconsin Supreme Court. The U.S. Supreme
Court declined to review the Wisconsin ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver's decision comes after state supreme courts in Maine and
Vermont have ruled that voucher programs there may exclude
parochial schools, and as Florida begins the first statewide
voucher program. In August, the day before school was to start,
Oliver temporarily blocked students from attending school using the
vouchers, then backtracked several days later amid parental
protest.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court took the unusual step of intervening in the
Cleveland case in November to guarantee the program's survival
until the appeals court rules. That, combined with the clarity of
the issues in the Cleveland case, is one of many reasons why
lawyers and advocates on both sides believe it is likely to gain
Supreme Court review.
</P>
<P>
   Though litigation typically centers on the church-state
question, vouchers are also controversial because of their
potential impact on public education. Liberals fear that vouchers
will drain badly needed resources and motivated children away from
already struggling public schools; conservatives see vouchers as a
competitive market force that will push public schools to improve
or die.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has figured prominently in the presidential campaign.
Republicans have lined up behind vouchers, while Vice President Al
Gore has attacked his Democratic challenger, Bill Bradley, for
voting in favor of vouchers while he was in the Senate. Bradley
said in a televised debate Sunday that he had supported programs
like Cleveland's only as experiments, adding, ``I do not believe
that vouchers are the answers to the problems of public
education.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, who was appointed by President Clinton in 1994, is
widely considered to be a staunch opponent of vouchers. He was once
on the board of the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People, which later was part of a coalition opposing
vouchers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 2100EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
