<HEADLINE>
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 BC - SC-REPUBS-2TAKES -NYT 
 BUSH AND McCAIN SEE SOUTH CAROLINA AS A MUST WIN   By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Ever since Ronald Reagan's victory here in 1980
put it on the map, the South Carolina primary has had a central
place in Republican politics. Sen. John McCain and Gov. George W.
Bush are certainly campaigning as if the state is pivotal in their
fight for the party's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he surges in New Hampshire, McCain is citing South
Carolina's ``transcendent importance'' to his candidacy, stopping
just short of declaring that a loss here would end his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very complicated strategy we have,'' he said the
other day in Charleston, where he conjured up images of D-Day.
``It's very similar to that of the landing at Normandy: win South
Carolina. Every page says, `Win South Carolina.' ''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, whose record as a Navy aviator plays well among the
state's many veterans and active military personnel, pledged to be
here ``literally every day'' between the New Hampshire primary on
Feb. 1 and South Carolina's own balloting 18 days later. Shortly
after South Carolina come the multiple-primary days in far-flung
states where Bush's advantage in organization and resources could
prove overwhelming if he is not weakened by then.
</P>
<P>
   Bush showed up in South Carolina a day after McCain and
similarly emphasized its importance. Promoting his tax-cut proposal
in the town of Camden, he reminded the state's voters of their
legacy of restoring Republican front-runners who have stumbled, as
if he himself might need rescue after New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Carolina's had a tradition,'' he said, ``of when
somebody thinks the door is open, of slamming it shut. It's been an
important state regardless of what happens in the early states.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush should know. His father dashed the hopes of Bob Dole and
Pat Robertson here in 1988, beginning the Southern sweep that
cemented the nomination. Four years later President Bush used South
Carolina as a firewall to stop Pat Buchanan, who had made an
unexpectedly strong showing in New Hampshire. South Carolina also
helped revive Dole in 1996 after New Hampshire had gone to
Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Now, once again, much of the state's Republican establishment
has rallied to the side of a front-runner, and of a member of the
Bush clan. Bush has endorsements from leaders including Sen. Strom
Thurmond, former Gov. Carroll Campbell, former Gov. David Beasley,
Lt. Gov. Bob Peeler, State Attorney General Charlie Condon and
David H. Wilkins, speaker of the South Carolina House.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say Bush not only has inherited his father's South
Carolina political machine but also is benefiting from the
affection in which his parents are still held by voters here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps him a lot, his mother and father,'' said Henry
McMaster, the Republican state chairman, who is remaining neutral.
``Governor Campbell had them down so much that people thought they
lived here.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 2103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4750 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-SC-REPUBS-2NDTAKE-NYT     12-20 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-REPUBS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
COLUMBIA, S.C.: lived here.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Then there are the general electoral inclinations of the state's
Republican voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think we have a much different electorate down here,''
said Heath Thompson, the state director of the Bush campaign.
``Besides being more contrarian, the voters in New Hampshire are
considered more independent. While we may like to think of
ourselves as independent, the independents among us are still very
conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans tend to be far less insurgent than institutional
here, in a state that reveres institutions (witness the Confederate
battle flag that still flies over the Capitol or the new statue
nearby of Strom Thurmond, erected in testimony to his stature at
age 97 as the longest serving U.S. senator in history.
</P>
<P>
   Evangelical Christians also make up a high proportion of the
electorate. McCain, however, hopes to make inroads though his
personal history as a prisoner of war in a state that has the
highest proportion in the nation of veterans and active duty
military personnel. McCain's supporters argue that the support of
the Republican establishment does not mean what it once did before
Republicans lost the governor's seat to Jim Hodges, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, McCain's advisers have their own South Carolina model
to point to: Ronald Reagan's 1980 primary victory here over the
former governor of Texas, John Connally, who campaigned intensively
in South Carolina and was the favorite of the local Republican
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Quinn, a lanky, soft-spoken political strategist, worked
in Reagan's South Carolina campaign then and is McCain's local
strategist now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an interesting comparison between 1980 and 1999,'' he
said. ``It was kind of a Who's Who of the Republican leadership
structure who was for Connally.''
</P>
<P>
   Drawing a comparison to Bush, he added that Connally ``was
leading Reagan in the polls. He was raising far more money than
Reagan. He had the endorsements and the money behind him and he was
from Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinn also argued that Buchanan had not been able to capitalize
on his New Hampshire showings here in part because he had never
built an organization or media presence in the state. But McCain
has, with chairmen and veterans chairmen in all 46 counties.
</P>
<P>
   The senator has also picked up endorsements from his own share
of party officials including Terry Haskins, the house speaker pro
tem, and two members of Congress, Reps. Lindsey Graham and Mark
Sanford, both young Turks from the Republican class of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago you would have had two congressmen going against
the machine and it wouldn't matter,'' said Graham, who has achieved
folk hero status in his state for his high-profile role in
President Clinton's impeachment trial. ``It matters now. Things are
up for grabs now.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes too has been organizing here, reaching out in
particular to anti-tax activists and Christian conservatives.
Friday, on the first day of a bus tour across the state, he
emphasized his stand against abortion. But Republican state
officials say that as of yet, he is not posing a threat to Bush and
McCain. The three other candidates _ Gary Bauer, Sen. Orrin Hatch
and Alan Keyes _ are not given much of a chance.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Bush is still the heavy favorite. A CNN/Time poll in
late November found that 62 percent of likely primary voters
favored Bush versus 15 percent for McCain. Forbes was third with 6
percent. Even Bush's aides expect the race to tighten and McMaster,
the Republican chairman, calls the race fluid. ``I just see it as a
wide open contest that's almost unpredictable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain believes he has some natural advantages to build on in
South Carolina, starting with the 450,000 veterans and active duty
military personnel here. In addition, independents and Democrats
are allowed to vote in the Republican primary and might be attuned
to his stance as a maverick fighting special interests, although
the state has not had much history of such cross-party voting.
</P>
<P>
   At The Flight Deck restaurant in Lexington, the senator on
Wednesday went out of his way to portray himself as the man
fighting the establishment, as he looked at a giant three-D figure
of King Kong protruding from a wall and gripping an Empire State
Building in one fist and a World War I era plane in another.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's almost like our campaign,'' McCain said. ``Really.
We've got a big King Kong up there on the top of the building with
all the money and all the establishment and I'm the guy in the
airplane there strafing them,'' he said. Then with Borscht-belt
timing he added, eyeing the ape, ``in fact it looks a lot like
Governor Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   As the audience laughed, he added, under his breath, ``We're
running a positive campaign here.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham, who was accompanying him, also sought to use the
Lewinsky scandal to help the senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the first president post-Clinton,'' the
congressman reminded the breakfast crowd. ``We're going to have to
elect a man that's ready to clean that place up.'' Introducing
McCain, he said, ``Wouldn't it be nice to have a commander-in-chief
that actually understood how the military worked? Wouldn't it be
proud to have someone that when they came on the news you didn't
have to take the kids out of the room?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has worked hard to neutralize McCain's potential strengths.
The governor has stressed military and veterans issues here and he
chose to deliver his speech this fall on national security at the
Citadel, South Carolina's revered military academy. One of the two
television commercials the governor has on the air here showcases
his stance on military matters and support of an anti-ballistic
missile system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not conceding any political turf to anyone,'' said
Thompson. ``We feel like we're not going to concede veterans to
Senator McCain any more than we did the women's vote to Elizabeth
Dole.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain now has two television commercials in rotation here and
three 60-second radio spots, and two of the radio commercials
feature a fellow Vietnam prisoner of war, Col. Bud Day.
</P>
<P>
   For now, rank-and-file Republicans showing uat McCain's events
seem far from decided. After McCain unveiled a health care plan at
a Rotary Club lunch in Charleston, Betty Dronen, 71, said she was
leaning his way. But she added, ``If Bush would approach some of
these same issues and explain what he would do, that might make a
difference.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
