<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4751 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-SEX-SHOPS-2TAKES-N     12-20 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SEX-SHOPS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK MAYOR WENT TOO FAR IN TRYING TO CLOSE SEX SHOPS, COURT
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New York state's highest court ruled Monday that
the administration of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani overstepped its bounds
in trying to shut down pornography businesses, a decision that
affects dozens of stores and is by far the mayor's worst setback in
his campaign to restrict X-rated bookstores and theaters.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the plaintiffs said the ruling by the Court of
Appeals could keep the doors open at as many as 80 pornography
businesses that the city had ordered shuttered, but a city lawyer
put the number at 25 to 30. City officials said they would look for
ways around the ruling, so that they could continue to reduce the
number of X-rated businesses. But the decision raises the
possibility that new businesses could crop up to take advantage of
the court's edict, reversing some of the success Giuliani has had
in driving them out of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision did not address the 1995 city zoning law,
championed by Giuliani and upheld by the Court of Appeals, that
sharply restricted where in the city peep shows, strip clubs and
hard-core book and video stores could be operated. Instead, it
dealt with a regulation the city had adopted, defining what is an
``adult'' business.
</P>
<P>
   In a unanimous ruling, the court said that the administration's
interpretation was overly broad, and that it had tried to close
down a business that was actually complying with the law _ in this
case, an Upper West Side video store catering to gay men. That
reversed decisions by a Manhattan trial court and the Appellate
Division of state Supreme Court, which had supported the city's
stand.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday in Union Square, the mayor said the
Court of Appeals' decision ``will have some effect on'' the
campaign against sex-related book and video stores, but he noted
that it would not hinder efforts to close strip clubs ``that were a
key problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But Herald Price Fahringer, the lawyer for the X-rated store
that had sued the city, said that Monday's decision was another in
a long string of setbacks in court for Giuliani, as judges have
concluded that his administration was overzealous in pursuit of his
policies _ cases varying from questions of free speech to welfare
policy. In recent weeks, a federal court blocked the mayor's
attempt to cut off city financing for the Brooklyn Museum over a
controversial exhibition, a state Supreme Court justice blocked his
plan to require the homeless to work in return for shelter, and the
Court of Appeals found that his administration had illegally taxed
thousands of its employees.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani has been notably more successful in chasing
sex-related businesses out of neighborhoods and tourist-heavy
sections like Times Square, winning a long string of court
victories. By the city's count, since enforcement of the law began
in August 1998, 62 of 144 sex-related businesses have either been
forcibly closed by the police or, under that threat, have
voluntarily gone out of business.
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 law banned any business where a ``substantial portion''
of it was devoted to X-rated material or nude performances, and was
within 500 feet of a school, church or residential area, or of
another pornography business. That relegated the businesses mostly
to industrial zones, far from the eyes of most city residents and
tourists. The restrictions were welcomed in many neighborhoods _
particularly in Queens, where strip clubs had cropped up in several
residential areas _ and by businesses in the newly sanitized,
tourist-friendly Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   When the law was challenged on First Amendment grounds as a
violation of free speech rights, the city was careful to insist
that it was not trying to restrict the content of what was sold in
the stores _ an approach that state and federal courts had made
clear they would not accept. Instead, the city argued that the law
was meant to curb dangerous activity that it said X-rated
businesses attracted, like prostitution and drug dealing.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In response to complaints that the ``substantial portion''
standard was too vague, the administration adopted a rule defining
that phrase to mean that 40 percent or more of a business' floor
space, or of the merchandise on display, was adults-only. That
satisfied the Court of Appeals, which unanimously upheld the law in
February 1998. In July 1998, the U.S. Supreme Court declined to
hear an appeal, clearing the way for enforcement of the law to
begin.
</P>
<P>
   Many businesses, particularly book and video stores, tried to
stay open by making sure that 60 percent or more of their display
stock was not pornographic, which often meant lining their stores
with videos of cartoons, wrestling and karate movies that sold
scantly, if at all. The case decided Monday dealt with Les Hommes,
a store at 217 W. 80th St., where, a trial court concluded, 24
percent of the material on display was X-rated.
</P>
<P>
   The city, calling this ``sham compliance,'' moved to close Les
Hommes and similar businesses, noting that their new, more
pedestrian stock did not sell anywhere nearly as briskly as the
salacious material they had all along. Les Hommes sells videos of
all kinds, but only the X-rated videos are offered for rent, a fact
that the city cited as evidence that the sexually explicit material
was the real business and the rest was a front.
</P>
<P>
   But in the city regulation, ``the focus is solely on the
appropriate percentages of stock and floor and cellar space, and
the city drew these at 40 percent,'' Judge Carmen Beauchamp
Ciparick wrote for the court. ``The city's guidelines provide no
support for the view that profitability or stability of the
nonadult stock need be considered.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end,'' she wrote, ``we must enforce the city's
administrative guidelines as written.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Connolly, special counsel to Corporation Counsel Michael
Hess, the city's chief lawyer, said the court's treatment of the 40
percent rule ``has taken a small loophole and made it a gaping hole
for people who have no intention of complying with the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he warned against ``interpreting this too broadly.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fahringer, the lawyer for Les Hommes, the plaintiff, and
Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil Liberties
Union, both said the decision could not only save many existing
businesses, it could clear the way for new ones to open outside the
areas permitted by the 1995 law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court has said 40 percent means 40 percent, and the city
can't go interpreting that as it pleases,'' Fahringer said.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of Les Hommes, which has operated for two decades,
declined to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly pointed to one cryptic sentence in Monday's ruling, in
which the court said there might be instances ``where what a store
is selling or renting cannot be considered stock'' for the purposes
of the 40 percent rule, but did not elaborate. He said city lawyers
were trying to determine whether that line opened the door to
continued enforcement of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly said that the city was studying several options,
including the adoption of a new regulation that would give it
greater leeway in interpreting the 40 percent rule. But Fahringer
and Siegel, who had vigorously opposed the law, said it would be
difficult to do so without having the city explicitly judging the
content of the material on sale, which a court would be likely to
judge unconstitutional.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
