<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4753 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-HOLBROOKE-U.N.-450(2T     12-20 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLBROOKE-U.N.-450(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S CHIEF U.N. DELEGATE CHARTS HIS COURSE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Richard Holbrooke's moment has come, and he
intends to make the most of it.
</P>
<P>
   With a long and bedeviled nomination process and the battle to
pay American dues to the United Nations now behind him, he has one
year left as chief American representative here, one year to put
his imprint on Washington's relations with the world and perhaps to
emerge again as a leading candidate for secretary of state after
the next election.
</P>
<P>
   Almost four months after taking office here and picking up a
cabinet seat at the White House, Holbrooke called his first major
news conference Monday to talk about his plans for January, when he
takes on the rotating presidency of the Security Council and can
frame much of its agenda. In a word, it will be Africa. Not Iraq,
not Kosovo or Bosnia, not North Korea or East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just a gimmick,'' said Holbrooke, who is an expert on
Europe and Asia. Back from his first extended tour of sub-Saharan
Africa, he was shaken by what he saw: the endless implosion of
Angola, a pointless war in Congo and the social and economic
devastation of .
</P>
<P>
   With Secretary of State Madeleine Albright now focused on the
Middle East, and with events in the Balkans and East Timor largely
under U.N. or NATO control, Africa looms as the great unfinished
business at the century's end. Holbrooke plans public Security
Council sessions on Burundi, Congo and Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Many diplomats are skeptical. Council debates on Africa have
often turned into speechfests that change nothing.
</P>
<P>
   But Africans and envoys from other developing nations are
welcoming the attention. At the Center for the Global South at
American University in Washington, the director, Clovis Maksoud,
said that Holbrooke might strike the right chord with poorer
nations, finding a way to line up their support, much of which has
been lost in recent years because of fears of unrestrained American
power.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke is more willing than most diplomats to be openly
critical of African leadership and the slow-motion responses to
crises of the Organization of African Unity. To underline the folly
of neglecting AIDS in many countries, he said he would set aside a
day for AIDS in Africa, particularly southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people wonder, why hold a Security Council meeting on a
health issue?'' he said. ``There has never been a Security Council
meeting on a health issue. The reason is simple. In Africa, in
southern Africa, in countries like Namibia and South Africa,
Zimbabwe and other countries, AIDS is far more than a health issue.
It is jeopardizing the advances that these countries have made.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke will be a relative newcomer to the Security Council,
where he is seen only sporadically, and some diplomats wonder if he
will have the patience to live by its peculiar rhythms for a month.
He is a fierce critic of U.N. procedure, accusing the organization
and many of the diplomats assigned to it with being more fascinated
with process than principle.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference Monday, he took aim at the organization,
which he said still needed a lot of reform _ words congressional
Republicans always like to hear. He is impatient with the chain of
command and the complex relationships among U.N. agencies.
</P>
<P>
   In the last American presidency of the Security Council of the
Clinton era, there will also be some performance diplomacy. Sen.
Jesse Helms, R-N.C., who is one of the U.N.'s most intractable
critics will be invited to sit in on the Security Council, and the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee, of which he is chairman, will
hold a hearing in New York, Holbrooke said. Half a dozen senators
and about 30 representatives have already been his guests.
</P>
<P>
   Politically motivated stunts? Well, maybe, a European said. But
if this is what it takes to get a better hearing on Capitol Hill,
then everybody might enjoy a little American politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps we didn't do a good enough job on bringing Congress
aboard on policy in the past,'' Holbrooke said in one of several
careful asides hinting that he was not always in line with
administration's handling of foreign issues. He was also asked
Monday why so many war criminals in Bosnia were still at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not share my thoughts with you on why they're at
large,'' he said. ``I find it very, very difficult. I've long taken
the view that they must be brought to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   At the sort of shabby, '50s-style American mission to the United
Nations, a monument to congressional stinginess toward diplomacy,
Holbrooke has assembled his own team of trusted colleagues from the
past. A tough taskmaster with a gargantuan appetite for work, he
provokes either winces and wounded feelings or a loyalty often
couched in black humor. One of his tops diplomats recalled at his
swearing in that he had worked for Holbrooke ``for 10 years,
between 1994 and 1995.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke plunged into U.N. activity playing from his own
strengths. After checking in at the U.S. mission here only long
enough to claim his new office in August, he left for the Balkans.
There, he is well known. Holbrooke, who was ambassador to Germany
in the early years of the first Clinton administration, later wrote
the 1995 Dayton peace agreement for Bosnia, and then browbeat and
cajoled three distrustful parties - Croats, Serbs and Bosnian
Muslims - into accepting it.
</P>
<P>
   He is also remembered for having secured a celebrated cease-fire
agreement from President Slobodan Milosevic of Serbia last October,
only to have it violated, leading to an American-led bombing
campaign this year. Under criticism himself in June in the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee for having negotiated with Milosevic,
an indicted war criminal and recipient of much vitriol from
Washington, Holbrooke was characteristically blunt.
</P>
<P>
   He criticized the limits of his instructions _ the Clinton
administration did not want to commit itself to ground troops to
ensure peace in Kosovo _ and added for good measure that his talks
with Milosevic were hardly fun. ``This isn't bridge or tennis,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Back from the Balkans on Labor Day weekend, he stepped off the
plane into the maelstrom of the crisis in East Timor following the
region's voter for independence. A former assistant secretary of
state for East Asia, Holbrooke was no stranger to the region.
Within hours, he renewed as many contacts as he could muster on a
holiday, from human rights experts to diplomats in the region. Then
he turned his sights on the White House as well as the Security
Council to plead for more of an outcry.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, the Indonesians had agreed to international
intervention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
