<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4755 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-CARRUTH-LIFESTYLE     12-20 1591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARRUTH-LIFESTYLE-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY HISTORY, TRAPPINGS OF PRO SPORTS CONTRIBUTED TO CARRUTH'S
DOWNFALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ The day after gunmen mortally wounded his
pregnant girlfriend, and the police treated him like a suspect, Rae
Carruth took shelter at another girlfriend's apartment here and
spoke in soft tones on the telephone to his stepfather in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Carruth's stepfather, Samuel Carruth, had always been the moral
compass in his life, helping him successfully navigate the
dangerous neighborhood in Sacramento where he had grown up and
where many of his cousins had ended up in jail, friends said. When
Carruth, a wide receiver for the Carolina Panthers, laid down the
telephone, he wept.
</P>
<P>
   ``He broke down into tears,'' Nakish Stewart, the girlfriend,
recalled. ``He said, `I don't believe what's happened to me.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was only the beginning of Carruth's fall from grace. Last
week, his pregnant girlfriend, Cherica L. Adams, who was 24, died,
a month after she was struck in the chest and neck by four bullets.
Carruth was charged along with three other men with first-degree
murder; the police said he had masterminded the drive-by attack to
avoid responsibility for the pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Carruth, who had been free on bond, fled Charlotte and was
captured the following day, hiding in the trunk of a car outside a
motel in western Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Adams' infant son, Chancellor, has defied the odds and survived
after being delivered 10 weeks premature.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional material)
</P>
<P>
   The violent end to Carruth's relationship with Adams surprised
almost everyone who knew them. ``Rae, he's not a conflict guy, if
anything, I think he avoids conflict,'' said Maurice Henriques, a
former college teammate. ``The Rae I know would never be involved
in something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the relationship between Adams and Carruth was never a
story-book love affair. Rather it was a combustible sort of
liaison, not uncommon in professional sports these days, between
young men propelled into sudden fame and fortune and women of
modest means who are intensely attracted not just to them, but to
their stature and wealth.
</P>
<P>
   (End optional material)
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, Adams and Carruth seemed a good match. Carruth
was a good-looking, millionaire athlete with a spotless record who
liked children and aspired to write screenplays someday. He did not
drink or smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Adams appeared to be a lovely and eloquent young woman pursuing
a career in real estate, who had also started her own
music-production company. ``She was a classy person, real nice, a
smart girl, very ambitious,'' Portia Welch, a friend from high
school, said.
</P>
<P>
   But their lives were much more complicated, friends said.
Plagued by injuries, Carruth, who is 25, was worried about money.
He was nearing the end of his contract with the Panthers and was
saddled with child-support payments for a son he had fathered in
California. His social life was also spinning out of control. He
was seeing at least three women at once, including erotic dancers,
and had befriended some local men with criminal records.
</P>
<P>
   Adams had been dating professional athletes since high school,
her friends said, and traveled frequently to parties and games in
other cities. Last year, she began working as a stripper at The
Diamond Club, a topless bar frequented by professional athletes, a
manager and several employees at the club said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She only quit dancing because she got pregnant,'' said a
dancer at the club, who identified herself as Angel Smith. ``She
really wanted that baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Dancers at The Diamond Club said Carruth had been a regular
there and met Adams while she was dancing about a year ago. But
Adams' mother, Saundra Adams, told The Associated Press that her
daughter met Carruth at a party thrown by another Panther player.
</P>
<P>
   After Adams became pregnant last spring, Carruth urged her to
have an abortion, but she refused because it was against her
principles, her friends said. Still, they say Adams had few
illusions that Carruth would settle down and marry her. She was
aware that he was dating other women.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knew where she stood with Rae,'' said one close friend,
who like many of the people interviewed for this article insisted
on anonymity. ``She didn't have any false hopes of getting
married.''
</P>
<P>
   Carruth appeared to become increasingly worried about money as
the pregnancy progressed, Adams' friends said. Though he was a
first-round draft choice out of the University of Colorado in 1997
and led all rookies with 44 receptions, he broke his foot during
the season-opener in 1998, ruining his season. Then this season he
sprained an ankle on Oct. 17 after five games, sidelining him for
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   With only one year left on a 4-year, $3.7 million contract, his
financial future was hardly secure. He had lost money in a
nationwide pyramid scheme involving car title loans and was sued by
a couple claiming he had backed out on a house purchase. In
addition, Carruth was paying $5,500 a month to support his child in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Adams complained to friends that Carruth quarreled with her
often about money. ``If she would ask him for something, like for
her bills, he would always get mad,'' Welch said. ``She said it was
always like a money issue with him.''
</P>
<P>
   There was another change in Carruth's life besides the injury.
In early September, he met Stewart, a 23-year-old administrator
with the AAA, at a comedy club. By November, they were going out at
least three times a week and their relationship was deepening,
Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   In late October, after attending a Panthers game with the
injured Carruth, Stewart learned through a mutual friend that Adams
was carrying Carruth's baby. She confronted him over dinner that
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `She's telling a lot of people that,''' Stewart
recalled. ``So I asked him, `Rae, are you all going to have a
baby?' You know, I said it with a smile on my face. And he said,
`Well, I don't know.'''
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, after a long argument, Stewart said Carruth
had confided in her that he was not comfortable with his lifestyle
and wanted to settle down with one woman. He led her to believe,
Stewart said, that she was the one.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Adams' friends said, Carruth continued to go
out with Adams regularly and had been telling her that he wanted
her to bear his child.
</P>
<P>
   For a man who made millions playing football, Carruth kept
strange company in Charlotte. He had only one close friend on the
Panthers, Hannibal Navies, a linebacker who had also played with
him at Colorado, Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   But there were a few Charlotte men who also came by Carruth's
house often to play pool and hang out, Stewart said. One was
Michael Eugene Kennedy, a 24-year-old street hustler with an arrest
record that included charges of cocaine possession, car theft,
carrying a concealed gun and assault with intent to kill.
</P>
<P>
   Another new friend was William Edward Watkins, a 44-year-old New
Yorker who, prosecutors say, has a record in New York dating to
1983, including charges of assault, larceny and attempted
possession of a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   The police said Carruth had met Watkins when he hired him to do
detail work on his Mercedes Benz, and Watkins introduced him to
Kennedy. Kennedy then introduced Carruth to Stanley Abraham, a
19-year-old with no criminal record who had grown up in Kennedy's
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, Watkins and Abraham have all been arrested and accused
of conspiring with Carruth to kill Adams. The police said they were
riding in a rented car from which the shots were fired.
</P>
<P>
   The police declined to say where Carruth was at the time of the
shooting, about 12:20 a.m. on Nov. 16. He had gone to the movies
earlier that night with Adams, the police say. Adams' statements to
the police the night of the attack and Carruth's cell phone records
led investigators to the other three men, who have since made
statements implicating Carruth in the plot.
</P>
<P>
   James Exum, a lawyer for Kennedy, has said Kennedy was driving
the rented car with Watkins and Abraham as passengers, while
Carruth was driving his car in front of Adams' black BMW and
talking with them by cell phone. Carruth slowed down, and Watkins
opened fire on Adams, Exum said.
</P>
<P>
   Carruth has not made a statement to the police, but Stewart said
he told her he was innocent. In several conversations after the
shooting, he told Stewart that he had left the movie theater in his
own car and went his own way. He told her he had not known about
the shooting until several hours later, when Adams' mother,
Saundra, paged him.
</P>
<P>
   Carruth's willingness to let Kennedy and Watkins into his circle
may have stemmed from his upbringing, Stewart said. He grew up in
the tough Oak Park neighborhood of Sacramento, where drugs and
crime were constant threats and some of his friends and relatives
ended up in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Carruth's biological father, a man named Wiggins, abandoned him
when he was born. His legal name is Raelamar Theotis Wiggins, but
he started using the name Carruth when his mother married Samuel
Carruth. He has a sister, Samel.
</P>
<P>
   At Valley High School in Sacramento, Carruth was a poor student,
but his athletic prowess attracted the attention of the football
coach, Dave Haskins. Haskins urged the young man to retake several
classes and boost his grade point average so he could qualify to
play college football. He did.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The coach said Carruth's home life was chaotic. His mother and
stepfather divorced when Carruth was 14. During his high school
years, he bounced around from house to house, living on and off
with various cousins and other relatives, according to Haskins and
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   But Haskins said Carruth did not openly associate with gang
members or troublemakers in high school, and he seemed to distrust
people who might have befriended him solely because of his athletic
ability. ``He didn't trust a lot of people,'' the coach said. ``He
was always evaluating people.''
</P>
<P>
   A good sprinter with soft hands, the 5-foot-11, 195-pound
Carruth was given a scholarship by the University of Colorado in
1992 to play wide receiver. He thrived in Boulder, both on the
field and in class.
</P>
<P>
   Among his teammates, Carruth was known as a fun-loving
prankster. In 1995, he caught 53 passes for 1,008 yards and nine
touchdowns. His senior year, he had 54 catches for 1,116 yards.
</P>
<P>
   He also majored in English and education, maintaining a B
average. ``He didn't go to bars, didn't go to parties, he kept his
nose pretty clean,'' a teammate, Matt Russell, said. ``He was
probably one of the more well-behaved guys in my class.''
</P>
<P>
   But on a visit home in 1994, Carruth had a short affair with a
high school friend, Michelle Wright, who became pregnant and later
gave birth to a boy. In 1997, just as Carruth was entering the
National Football League draft, Wright filed a paternity suit
against him. Carruth fought the suit, but after a blood test proved
he was the father, he settled the case, agreeing to pay her $5,500
a month in child support.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers drafted him in the first round, gave him a $1
million signing bonus and made him a starting wide receiver. But he
had a hard time adjusting to life in North Carolina and missed the
camaraderie of college football. ``Here, I'm kind of alienated from
the guys,'' he once told the Charlotte Observer. ``Once players
leave for the day, they like to do their own thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Off the field, Carruth seemed to have a special fondness for
children. In Boulder, he befriended a young deaf boy. In Charlotte,
he coached a baseball team and mentored a 6-year-old boy named
Jacobi as part of the Big Brother program.
</P>
<P>
   Carruth told Stewart he wished he had a relationship with his
own son in California, and sometimes felt his desire to help other
children stemmed from guilt over his son. ``He told me `I get
emotional about Jacobi,''' Stewart said. ```I feel like that should
be my son.'''
</P>
<P>
   Known as Cookie to her family because she liked sweets, Adams
graduated from West Charlotte High School in 1993 with high grades
and a reputation as a smart, outgoing and beautiful young woman.
She modeled professionally while still in high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone kind of looked up to her,'' recalled Douglas
Blackmon, a high school classmate. ``She was a very pretty girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams had shown a strong interest in professional athletes from
an early age. She babysat for the children of players on the
Charlotte Hornets, and worked as an intern for the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   After high school, she went to Winston-Salem State University,
where she studied communications for two years. But she dropped out
in 1995 and began pursuing a career in real estate in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional material)
</P>
<P>
   ``She sold homes to families and made them feel like they were
happy for the opportunity,'' her manager at Torrey Homes, Denis
Ane-McManus, recalled at Adams' funeral on Saturday. ``I used to
tell her she could sell ice to eskimos.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams also continued dabbling in modeling and started her own
company to promote rap musicians and rhythm and blues bands, her
friends said. A statuesque woman, she attracted attention in
Charlotte's nightclubs; she dated athletes from local pro teams and
also had friends on visiting teams, her friends said.
</P>
<P>
   She traveled extensively at the invitation of friends in sports
and the music business. Lakia Quick, a close friend, told the
Charlotte Observer that she had attended an NBA All-Star game in
New York in 1998 with Adams. Shaquille O'Neal stopped to say hello
to her. Adams also dated Larry Johnson of the Knicks when he played
in Charlotte, her friends said. Johnson acknowledged that he knew
Adams, but declined to discuss their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   (End optional material)
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in 1998, Adams appears to have run into financial
trouble, friends said. She began working in the boutique at the
Men's Club, a cavernous restaurant with erotic dancers in
Charlotte, according to several club employees. Later last year,
she began dancing herself at The Diamond Club, a seedier topless
bar nearby, employees at the club said.
</P>
<P>
   Dancers at the Diamond Club said Adams met Carruth while she was
dancing there and became infatuated with him. They began dating and
she learned last spring that she was pregnant. She quit dancing and
took a job as a sales representative for a mortgage company.
</P>
<P>
   Several friends said Adams had been ecstatic about having a
baby. Her friends said she loved children and often volunteered to
babysit for their kids for free. Wayne K. Brown, the president of a
local radio station, said Adams had often taken care of his two
sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will miss her radiant smile,'' Brown said at her funeral.
``I have a whole pocketful of pictures of Christmas days when she
visited my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
