<HEADLINE>
COLUMBINE PARENTS ASK SHERIFF TO RESIGN OVER TAPES OF GUNMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Adding their voices to growing criticism,
parents of students who were shot to death at Columbine High School
called Monday on the Jefferson County sheriff, John Stone, to
resign over the release of videotapes made by the two teen-age
gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I applaud him for saying the buck stops here,'' Darrell Scott,
whose daughter, Rachel, was killed, said on Monday at an informal
new conference by at least five families. ``But Sheriff Stone needs
to take one more step. He has wounded deeply the victims of the
Columbine tragedy over and over, and he needs to resign.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone had apologized for what he conceded was a mistake in
allowing Time magazine and, later, other news organizations to see
the tapes, which had not been shown to families of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   But he has refused to resign, saying Time had broken a promise
not to quote anything that the killers said on the tapes. Time has
said no such deal was struck.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Davis, a spokesman for the sheriff, who was elected to a
four-year term 13 months ago, said Stone was out of town on Monday.
Davis said he knew of no plans by the sheriff to resign.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the showing of the tapes has created new tension
throughout the Columbine High area. Families of the victims say
they are still grieving over the massacre last April 20.
</P>
<P>
   The two gunmen, Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold, had planned to
kill hundreds, but after some of their bombs failed to detonate,
they used guns to shoot and kill 12 students and a teacher before
killing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In more than two hours of tapes that they made in the weeks
before the killings, the two teen-agers expressed their hatred of
humanity and showed off an arsenal of weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the parents said on Monday that Stone, who had
acknowledged that he never watched the tapes, misled them by
promising not to show the tapes to anyone before the families of
victims had an opportunity to view them.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Mauser, whose son, Daniel, was killed, said he did not
believe the sheriff's contention that he was misled by Time
magazine and called Stone ``extremely naive or extremely
incompetent.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of the tapes and questions over who gets to see them
are not likely to go away. Stone has said that the tapes could be
included in his department's final report on the killings, which is
expected to be made public next month. And families of the students
who were killed or injured might seek the tapes as evidence in
civil lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Others are fighting to limit viewing. Klebold's parents, Thomas
and Susan Klebold, asked a county district court last week to give
custody of the tapes to a judge, complaining that allowing the
sheriff's department to keep them might compromise evidence.
</P>
<P>
   And lawyers for the Jefferson County School District said they
are investigating whether they can block the release of the tapes
to the general public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
