<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: D'ALEMA TO TRY AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   Acting Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema, who resigned when his
center-left majority unraveled, was asked by President Carlo
Azeglio Ciampi to try to cobble together a new one. He agreed to
try. If he fails, and no other center-left leader succeeds, Italy
could be plunged into early elections.
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN: POPES ON WAY TO SAINTHOOD
</P>
<P>
   John Paul II put two predecessors on the road to sainthood. The
pope signed a decree recognizing the ``heroic virtues'' (the first
step toward beatification) of John XXIII, who revolutionalized the
church by calling the second Vatican Council in 1962. He also
recognized a miracle attributed to Pius IX, the last pope with
temporal powers, who declared papal infallibility in the 19th
century.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: SPY, 87, ESCAPES PROSECUTION
</P>
<P>
   Britain will not prosecute Melita Norwood, an 87-year-old
suburban London woman who admitted spying for the Soviet Union
while working in Britain's atomic weapons program after World War
II. The government told Parliament it would not pursue her or four
other Britons named in papers published by a KGB defector, Vasily
Mitrokhin, last fall because the evidence would probably not be
admissable in court.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: 70's BOMBINGS REVISITED
</P>
<P>
   The government is beginning a new investigation of simultaneous
car bombings in Dublin and the border town of Monaghan 25 years ago
that killed 33 people and wounded more than 300 in one day.
Inquiries in the 1970s and '80s proved inconclusive, and no one has
ever been charged in the attacks, which were thought to be the work
of Northern Ireland Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: FIRED TORY JOINS LABOR
</P>
<P>
   Shaun Woodward, whom the Conservative leader William Hague fired
this month as shadow minister for London for his refusal to support
the party's hard-line stance on gay rights, has joined the Labor
Party Woodward, 41, said the party had swung too far to the right
in its social policies and opposition to Europe, and he said other
liberal Tories were thinking of defecting.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: REBELS' CHRISTMAS TRUCE
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in a decade, the largest left-wing rebel
army, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, has declared a
cease-fire. The holiday truce, scheduled to last through Jan. 10,
followed a week of heavy fighting and fell short of the monthlong
cessation sought by President Andres Pastrana. Rebel leaders said
it was a ``personal gesture to the Colombian people.''
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN: SEXUAL HARASSMENT SUIT
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors raided the offices of Gov. Knock Yokoyama of Osaka
in connection with a criminal complaint of sexual harassment filed
by a university student and former campaign worker. Yokoyama, a
former comedian turned politician, was ordered to pay $107,000 to
the student in a civil suit. Sexual harassment complaints are
booming in Japan as women assert their rights in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: MUGABE'S NEW THREAT
</P>
<P>
   President Robert Mugabe threatened to seize land owned by whites
without providing compensation, as required by the Constitution.
Mugabe told his Zimbabwe African National Union Patriotic Front
that Zimbabwe's 12.5 million blacks could not make economic gains
while 60,000 whites controlled large tracts of land and dominated
industry and commerce. About 4,000 white farmers own about
one-third of the nation's land.
</P>
<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE: VOTE RESULTS DELAYED
</P>
<P>
   The National Electoral Commission delayed the release of the
results of this month's presidential and parliamentary elections.
Officials said contested votes were still being counted in Nampula
Province, a stronghold of the opposition. Preliminary results show
President Joaquim Chissano narrowly leading his opponent, Afonso
Dhlakama, but the opposition has questioned those figures. Official
results will be issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: MILLION BELOW POVERTY LINE
</P>
<P>
   More than a million Israelis, of whom some 40 percent are
children, live below the poverty line, according to official
figures issued by the National Insurance Institute. The two cities
with the highest poverty levels are Bnei Brak, dominated by
strictly religious Jews, and Jerusalem, whose mixed population
includes religious Jews and Palestinians. The poverty line was set
at $345 a month for an individual and $886 for a family of four.
</P>
</TEXT>
