<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   High Bond Yields Hurt Dow, But Technology Shares Rise
</P>
<P>
   Rising long-term interest rates hurt some segments of the stock
market as concerns mounted about what Federal Reserve policy makers
might do about interest rates at a meeting today. The yield on the
30-year Treasury rose to 6.44 percent from 6.37 percent on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks seen as sensitive to rising interest rates, like
financial-services companies, helped helped to pull down the Dow
Jones industrial average by 113.16 points, or 1 percent, to
11,144.27. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 2.94 points,
to 1,418.09, but demand for technology stocks remained intense, and
the Nasdaq composite index rose 30.81 points, or 0.8 percent, to
3,783.87, a record.
</P>
<P>
   Putting a Good Face on Profits
</P>
<P>
   The punishment that stocks regularly endure when profits come in
shy of forecasts, even by the tiniest amount, has put managements
under pressure to deliver upbeat earnings announcements even if the
numbers do not support them. The result, according to some Wall
Street accounting experts, is that more and more companies are
going to extremes to paint a rosy picture of their operations.
</P>
<P>
   49 Percent Stake Sold in Virgin Airlines
</P>
<P>
   Richard Branson sold 49 percent of Virgin Airlines to Singapore
Airlines for $965 million, giving the airline a global reach and
highly profitable partner at a time when his airline is in a heated
competitive battle with British Airways for trans-Atlantic
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Profit Rises 86 Percent
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter posted an 86 percent increase in
quarterly income, well ahead of analysts' estimates. The investment
bank is riding two powerful trends: a boom in new stock offerings,
especially by Internet-based companies, and a wave of mergers and
acquisitions involving European companies.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel to Change Toy Materials
</P>
<P>
   Mattel plans to eliminate petroleum-based plastics, which have
been linked to an assortment of environmental and health problems,
from Barbie and many of its other toys.
</P>
<P>
   IRS Official Accused of Favoritism
</P>
<P>
   The top Internal Revenue Service official in Northern California
repeatedly gave wealthy and politically connected taxpayers
unwarranted breaks including reduced tax bills, a refund, and
deferred payments in 1996 and 1997, the government's former chief
tax collector for the district testified. Peter W. Coons, tax
collection chief for Northern California from 1995 until he was
removed in February 1998, testified at a hearing where he is trying
to get his job back under a federal law that protects
whistle-blowers. The Internal Revenue Service contends that Coons
was fired for looking at 253 Web sites on his government computer,
five of them featuring images of naked women. Coons says the
allegations are a smoke screen to obscure the real reason for his
removal.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Times Examines Deal
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times published a 14-page special section
detailing its ill-fated profit-sharing deal on a Sunday magazine
section with the Staples Center sports arena. The erosion of
traditional lines between the editorial and advertising departments
raised questions about a possible conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   TV Networks to Share News Video
</P>
<P>
   The news operations of CBS, ABC and Fox agreed to form a
cooperative service to supply video pictures of news events to the
affiliated stations of each network. NBC News was excluded. It was
the first time that the three news organizations, which normally
compete in news coverage, had gotten together on a formal basis to
create a joint enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Bias Suit May Grow
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for four former and current employees who have brought a
racial discrimination lawsuit against Coca-Cola filed a request to
add four new plaintiffs and contended that M. Douglas Ivester, the
company's outgoing chief executive, was directly involved in the
company's employment policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
