<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4770 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-BRADLEY-NYT &LR;      12-20 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUSING NO-AD IDEA PUTS BRADLEY ON THE DEFENSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (A Political Memo) 
(ms) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a certain level, it sounded like an act of unalloyed civic
virtue: have the two Democratic presidential candidates swear off
all campaign commercials, and in their place stage face-to-face
debates throughout the primary season. As Vice President Al Gore
explained on ``Meet the Press'' to his rival, Bill Bradley, the
offer was meant to satisfy Bradley's oft-stated appeal to get
so-called soft money out of the political process and, in Gore's
words, ``accomplish one of the best reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   The surprising overture on Sunday morning television not only
seemed to momentarily unsettle Bradley _ ``He looked like a Rhodes
scholar caught in the headlights,'' said Alex Castellanos, a
Republican media consultant _ but it also incited one of the most
dramatic exchanges of the campaign, one that revealed the growing
intensity _ even the palpable antipathy _ between them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no matter how public-spirited Gore's gesture might have
appeared, it had little to offer a contender like Bradley, whose
only means of competing effectively is to spread his message
through paid political advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   ``If 30 to 40 percent of the people in the country don't know
who you are,'' Bradley said Monday as he campaigned in Iowa, ``not
using the television to communicate with them seems to me to be a
little bit contrary to our interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley acknowledged that in states like Iowa and New Hampshire,
which hold the first two presidential primaries, he can deliver his
message ``by looking at people in the eye in town hall meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you get to a national forum,'' he added ``the only
way you can do that is doing the same thing, looking at people in
the television, in their living rooms, telling them what you
believe, where you want to take the country, who you are and why
you believe what you believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Gore campaign has identified a soft spot in
Bradley's firm embracmpaign finance reform. That Bradley has
been compelled to defend his reliance on television advertisements
undermines his condemnations of the money raised by other,
better-financed candidates like Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly they dreamed that up as a response to the
Bradley-McCain event of last week,'' observed David Gergen, a
former White House communications adviser in both Democratic and
Republican administrations. He was referring to Bradley's
appearance in New Hampshire last Thursday with a Republican
presidential candidate, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, in which they
pledged to ban soft money from their campaigns if they won their
parties' nominations. But Bradley added that he would only
participate if the eventual Republican nominee also agreed to
eschew soft money.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Gore seized on this point Monday, suggesting that
Bradley was an advocate of reform in name only. ``Senator Bradley
has talked about campaign finance reform,'' said Chris Lehane, a
Gore campaign spokesman. ``But if you're going to talk the talk,
you better be able to walk the walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehane added that it was unclear which of the Democrats would
benefit most from a moratorium on commercials. But he said, ``My
guess is most people would agree that the Lincoln-Douglas debate
model would be better than the current 30-second TV commercials and
9-second sound bites.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, however, said that voters would interpret Gore's gambit
as strategy more than sincerity. ``What it says is that this is
another example of some tactic, as opposed to just saying what he
believes,'' he said. ``I mean, process tactics are not what the
people I think care about. What they care about is substance and
vision.''
</P>
<P>
   The former senator from New Jersey has tried in recent weeks to
reinforce this idea in the commercials he has been running in New
Hampshire and Iowa. The advertisements include issue-oriented
pieces concerning Bradley's views on health care and campaign
finance reform, and testimonials featuring former Senate colleagues
like Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York and Bob Kerrey of
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's offer was the dominant theme in the coverage of the
``Meet the Press'' debate, which drew a larger audience than usual
for the Sunday morning show.
</P>
<P>
   The morning-after analysis in print and online seemed to side
largely with Bradley: in USA Today, for instance, the columnist
Walter Shapiro dismissed Gore's action as ``a transparent
gimmick.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, tactical strikes are a mainstay of television debates.
Gergen, now a professor of public service at Harvard's John F.
Kennedy School of Government, said that although Gore's move was
transparent, it had political appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a smart tactical ploy, but it was a ploy,'' he said.
``Gore is the front-runner; of course he wants to find ways to
muffle Bradley's voice. And advertising is going to be crucial to
Bradley's closing the gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Stevens, who produces McCain's political commercials,
thinks that in the end, the issue doesn't resonate with anyone but
the ``insiders and activists who watch all that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had a debate in a classroom with 30 good government
students,'' he said, ``they would probably agree that there
shouldn't be any paid advertising. But (a) that's not going to
happen, and (b) I don't think it's anything that the average voter
thinks about at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 2133EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
