<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0351 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4779 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-GREENHILL- &LR;      12-20 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-GREENHILL- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT GREENHILL, THE NAME-BRAND DEALMAKER ADVISING U.S . ON
MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
 ART- NYT 
(ATTN: M aine , Mass., Conn., Mass., Ala.)  (ART ADV: A photo NYT18 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 10 minutes with Robert F. Greenhill, a longtime Wall
Street dealmaker, it is clear why the Justice Department hired him
to advise it on its negotiations with Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Ask about his 20-year friendship with Sanford I. Weill, chairman
of Citigroup and frequent dinner companion, and his answer is a
firm ``No comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Question his role in some of this decade's largest corporate
takeovers, like Viacom's bid for Paramount Communications or the
restructuring of IBM, and he says, ``I won't talk about that.''
When queried about what it was like to run not one, but two, Wall
Street firms, he dodges the question: ``You don't really want to
know, do you?''
</P>
<P>
   After 37 years on Wall Street, Greenhill has joined the rarefied
group of investment bankers who command the ear of America's
corporate elite. Not only does he have a knack for wooing the most
stubborn executives, but he has the drive to get them to the
bargaining table. Still, while he delights in his role as
matchmaker, he prefers to negotiate far from the eyes of a curious
press and public. So it comes as no surprise to those who know him
that the Justice Department sought his discretion in studying the
financial impact of various proposals to resolve the antitrust case
against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, not many people on Wall Street have the stature to give
counsel on the most important antitrust action in recent history.
Joel Klein, head of the Justice Department's antitrust division,
needs help sifting through the technological and financial
implications of each proposal.
</P>
<P>
   If Microsoft is fractured into pieces, Klein wants a name-brand
executive to defend that decision before Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But of the handful of eligible candidates Klein approached, who
would be willing to do it?
</P>
<P>
   Almost every leading investment bank with any technology prowess
has either worked with Microsoft or does not want to risk making
such a powerful enemy. Smaller boutiques could not afford the task.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever comes forward has to be credible,'' said Charles Koob,
an antitrust attorney at Simpson Thacher &AMP; Bartlett in New York.
``Greenhill is credible.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenhill, who now owns a small investment firm, was attracted
to the Microsoft assignment, in part, because it was an unusual
challenge. That is in keeping with his driven personality.
Greenhill's recent interest in technology companies comes at an
age, 63, when most executives are considering retirement. When he's
not piloting one of his three airplanes, including a
top-of-the-line jet, between homes in Greenwich, Conn., Maine and
Nantucket, Mass., he can be found on his satellite phone with
clients. (His wife pilots her own single-engine plane.) He took up
golf in his late 50s and now boasts a solid 14 handicap. On
vacation, he pushes the limits, too, taking his family canoeing
near the Arctic Circle or skiing in untainted wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   But his true passion is negotiating deals. Sumner Redstone,
Viacom's chairman, knows that firsthand. In the spring of 1993,
Greenhill called Redstone and suggested that they and Martin Davis,
then Paramount's chairman, have dinner. Greenhill knew Redstone
coveted Paramount's assets but after three years of trying had
failed to strike a pact with Davis. Greenhill knew Davis well
because he had advised on Paramount's unsuccessful $12 billion
hostile bid for Time Inc. in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `If you are asking what I think you are, it's not
going to happen,''' Redstone said in a recent interview. ``I didn't
want to get involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the two chairmen agreed to meet and, as Redstone
predicted, the ensuing months' negotiations were tortuous. More
than once Greenhill dragged Redstone to the bargaining table
against his will.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob was absolutely persistent,'' Redstone said. ``A couple of
times I said, `Leave it alone. It's not going to happen.' I even
sent a telegram that said, `Bob, back off.''' But he never did
until the deal was done.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 2141EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4780 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-GREENHILL- &LR;      12-20 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-GREENHILL- </SLUG>
 ART- 2NDTAKE-NYT 
UNDATED: was done.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Such forcefulness engenders enemies too. Wall Street executives
are loath to criticize Greenhill publicly, but privately warn that
he can wreak havoc. When he left Morgan Stanley in 1993 to become
chairman of Smith Barney Shearson, as it was then named, he
relentlessly pursued talented financiers at Morgan, angering old
colleagues. His abrupt manner has bruised more than a few egos. His
zeal to win at any cost offends even his most avid supporters. ``He
can be like a bull in a china shop,'' said one banker who worked
with him.
</P>
<P>
   Greenhill attended Yale University, graduating in 1958. At first
he thought of majoring in physics, then philosophy and finally,
painting. His senior thesis, he said, was on Van Gogh's theory of
color. In perhaps his first ``hostile takeover,'' he met his wife,
Gayle, when she was on a blind date with his college roommate.
</P>
<P>
   After two years in the Navy, he abandoned his paint brushes and
headed for Harvard Business School. In 1962, MBA in hand, he moved
to New York and joined Morgan Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, his career was blessed. In 1970 he became a
partner and set to work creating a mergers and acquisitions
department that would become a powerhouse. He later ran investment
banking and, in 1989, was made a vice chairman. Two years later he
was named president.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenhill's intensity was not suited for the corner office.
In March 1993, after a weekend retreat in Utah with clients,
Greenhill was ousted as president. He left the firm soon after,
ending a 31-year career, and found refuge with his good friend
Weill, who named him chairman of Smith Barney Shearson, then part
of Travelers Corp.. That job lasted only three years before
Greenhill _ pocketing tens of millions of dollars in the process _
was again asked to step down, former colleagues said, in a
management tussle over how the firm was being run. In 1996, he
started the boutique Greenhill &AMP; Co..
</P>
<P>
   Greenhill is hard pressed to reflect on his undistinguished
career as a manager. But former colleagues say he lacks an innate
ability to lead. When asked about it, he becomes unusually still,
his hearty laugh silenced. ``One of the pleasures of being in a
small firm is you can focus on working with clients,'' he said,
noting that he has only six partners now. ``Helping clients is the
thing I've liked doing all my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenhill got a call from Klein the week before Thanksgiving
asking if he was interested in the Microsoft assignment. Executives
from Greenhill &AMP; Co. then met with Justice Department officials to
understand exactly what was expected. They were told, said an
executive involved in those discussions, that it would be Greenhill
&AMP; Co.'s job to analyze the financial impact if Microsoft were ever
split up.
</P>
<P>
   Greenhill has a limited background in technology, although he
advised IBM on its restructuring in 1993 and includes Compaq
Computer in his stable of clients. ``He doesn't necessarily
understand all the technology he is dealing with,'' said one banker
who has worked with him.
</P>
<P>
   Greenhill, too, wanted a well-defined role, which he accepted on
Nov. 28. He will not say what his firm is being paid by the Justice
Department, but industry executives say it is a flat fee that is
``substantially less'' than the millions his firm usually commands.
So far he has assigned six bankers to the task.
</P>
<P>
   One is Jeffrey Williams, a long-time colleague of Greenhill's
who once headed Morgan Stanley's telecommunications and media group
and counseled AT&AMP;T. Colleagues describe Williams, a former
architect, as technologically savvy and detail-oriented, a perfect
foil to Greenhill, whose strength is distilling mountains of
research by subordinates into a coherent action plan.
</P>
<P>
   Greenhill is not shy about worming his way into the action.
Michael Levitt, a partner at the leveraged buyout firm Hicks, Muse,
Tate &AMP; Furst and a close friend who worked for Greenhill at Morgan
Stanley and later Smith Barney, recalled the summer of 1997 when
Hicks, Muse announced it was buying Lin Television for $1.4
billion. A banker from Morgan Stanley had brought Levitt the idea,
which Greenhill later asked about. ``He didn't call up and say
`What role can we play?''' Levitt said. ``He called up and said he
wanted to understand the broadcasting industry and why we were
interested in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Few bankers can get much mileage from a phone call like that.
But Greenhill called Levitt later and said Hicks, Muse should line
up a partner, like NBC, in case another bidder emerged. Levitt
agreed. So Greenhill called his Nantucket neighbor, Jack Welch, the
chief executive of General Electric, which owns NBC, and set up a
lunch at his summer home there for Robert Wright, NBC's chief
executive, as well as executives for Hicks, Muse.
</P>
<P>
   It was timely. Raycom Media, an Alabama-based company, offered
to pay $1.7 billion for Lin. The lunch meeting at Greenhill's led
to a partnership between Hicks, Muse and NBC that topped Raycom
with its own $1.9 billion offer. ``That was Bob using his network
of relationships to create opportunities for both of us,'' Levitt
said.
</P>
<P>
   He is doing the same thing for his firm by advising the Justice
Department. Greenhill &AMP; Co. is increasingly interested in
representing Internet companies, having helped counsel Compaq this
year on the sale of its 83 percent stake in Alta Vista, a Web
search engine, to CMGI, a publicly-traded company that invests in
Internet ventures. His involvement in the Microsoft assignment
suggests that Greenhill doesn't want to lose his edge in the new
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob wants to make sure the world knows he's not out of the
game,'' said one executive who has worked with him. But don't ask
about it; his answer is predictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll play golf with you,'' Greenhill said, laughing. ``But I
won't talk about Microsoft.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
