<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4784 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-McHALE-COLUMN-LAD     12-20 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-McHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REELING KINGS NEED A QUICK START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 30 games everything seemed fine. The Kings might not have
been as good as their 39 points in the standings, but they had
played through injuries and certainly looked capable of a good seed
in April when the playoffs begin.
</P>
<P>
   Three grotesque losses later, the Kings don't know who they are.
Thirteen of the 23 goals they allowed came in the first period and
disintegrated their confidence. They started getting their stars
back and it only made them play worse.
</P>
<P>
   There is no magic wand for turning this around, but a good first
period Wednesday night at San Jose certainly would help.
</P>
<P>
   It would help the team breathe for the first time since losing
7-1 a week ago in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   When the Rangers beat them 8-3 the next night, the Kings' spirit
was broken by a couple of early saves from goaltender Mike Richter.
At the same time New York was walking in on Jamie Storr.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the third period of last Saturday's 8-4 loss to
Chicago, Rob Blake landed a crushing check on Jean Pierre Dumont.
The Blackhawks responded by hitting Ziggy Palffy, but Sean
O'Donnell whacked Alexei Zhamnov.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd roared, but it was two periods too late. The score was
5-1 Chicago. The game was over. The message was wasted.
</P>
<P>
   Although top players were returning, even the best need a few
games to get all the way back. Young defenseman Aki Berg played
maybe his best two games as a King when Blake was out. When Blake
returned, Berg wilted.
</P>
<P>
   Fragile? Extremely.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings virtually have no postseason experience to get them
through the tough spots. That includes coach Andy Murray, who is in
his first season and captain Blake, who has played four playoff
games since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   When the Kings acquired Palffy and Bryan Smolinski last summer
from the New York Islanders, they got two top offensive players.
They also got two guys who hadn't been in a playoff game in four
years.
</P>
<P>
   When you're trying to find your legs for the long season ahead,
that isn't a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey is a two-way sport and the offense has abandoned the
defense. The Kings' early-season success was based in part on the
forwards getting back to help out. But Wednesday night, while
Palffy and Luc Robitaille were hanging out at the red line, the
defense was getting battered in the Kings' end.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of response got winger Donald Audette bumped to the
fourth line and wondering how he became the scapegoat for this
mess. It had nothing to do with what he did with the puck. It's
what he did when he didn't have it that helped caus the freefall.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the team was among the top teams in the Western
Conference, Murray was obsessing about the standings. He has given
the team structure that was needed for the post-Larry Robinson era,
but the next game was not the biggest game. If you doubt that, look
at the Ducks, who are tied with the Kings and Dallas Stars in the
Pacific Division after beating mighty Detroit 3-1 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   They trailed the Kings by 10 points just two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jozef Stumpel, who has missed six weeks after undergoing
abdominal surgery, could be back Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that two points here or two points there could decide
whether the team finishes fifth in the conference or eighth or out
of the playoffs all together.
</P>
<P>
   But one confident first period could mean a lot more in deciding
a season.
</P>
<P>
   What's up? Anyone who expects a lot from Stumpel right away
might want to know that Colorado's Peter Forsberg has produced one
assist and is a minus-4 in the six games since that five-point
performance against Calgary in last month's season debut.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old star missed all of training camp and the
Avalanche's first 23 games while recovering from offseason shoulder
surgery, and he had predicted there would be some hard times for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly doesn't help that captain Joe Sakic remains out
with what the team is calling a rib cartilage injury. He has been
skating for brief periods on his own, but never when anyone is
around.
</P>
<P>
   Sakic, stuck at 999 NHL points, missed his 11th consecutive game
Monday. He came back Nov. 23 against the Kings and scored a goal
but last played three days later and isn't expected back until
after Christmas. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 2143EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
