<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Tuesday, Dec. 21. you have
any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
GENDERGAP (Phoenix) _ Sen. John McCain's call to arms for political
reform has rallied men to his cause, but the very intensity that is
making his campaign effective in New Hampshire may also have a
downside with Republican women, polls show. So far, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush is attracting female GOP voters by a significant
margin. Poll results comparing the preferences of men and women in
early primary states show that, although many women respect McCain,
they express a clear preference for Bush. Aware of this gender gap,
McCain is turning increasingly in his policy addresses to domestic
issues that are of concern to both sexes but traditionally of more
interest to women, including education, the environment and Social
Security _ all issues Bush has been speaking to for months. By KRIS
MAYES. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   BOMB (Phoenix) _ Explosives similar to those stolen last week
from a quarry near Drake are stored at scores of mines around
Arizona, state officials said Monday, and they're often unguarded
in isolated areas. In fact, neither the state mine inspector nor
the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms know the
quantity and type of explosives stored by the 87 Arizona mines that
use them. State officials, who say they are ``on pins and needles''
in the wake of the theft, said that all they know for sure is there
are plenty of explosives out there. Last week, thieves stole 750
pounds of fuel oil mixed with ammonium nitrate _ a fertilizer _, as
well as 250 pounds of dynamite from a relatively small flagstone
quarry owned by 3 Wins Mining Co. south of Ash Fork. By KERRY
FEHR-SNYDER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
