<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Monday, 12/20/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Phot
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) SOUTHINGTON, Conn. -- Dec. 20, 1999 --
DRIVE-IN-NATIVITY-2 -- A spectator viewing the drive-through,
live-action Nativity scene at the Christian Tabernacle Church in
Southington. ``In this country, and certainly in New England, we
tend to be very fast-food-oriented and this kind of meets people
where they're at,'' says John Muldoon, a church member doubling as
a Roman centurion. (George Ruhe/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) SOUTHINGTON, Conn. -- Dec. 20, 1999 --
DRIVE-IN-NATIVITY-1 -- Two camels, Bill and Eli, tied up in front
of the Christian Tabernacle Church in Southington. A few feet away,
spectators in hundreds of cars await a four-minute glimpse of the
birth of Jesus Christ, as seen through their car windows. This is
among the latest, and oddest, wrinkles in late-20th-century
Christmas revelry: the drive-through, live-action Nativity scene.
(George Ruhe/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) LITTLETON, Colo. - Dec. 20, 1999 -- COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING
-- Dave Todd, father of Evan Todd, a student murdered at Columbine
High School, addresses the media next to memorial crosses placed at
the foot of the altar at the Trinity Christian Center in Littleton
on Monday. Adding their voices to growing criticism, parents of
students who were killed at Columbine High School called on the
Jefferson County sheriff to resign over the release of videotapes
made by the two teenage gunmen. (Kevin Moloney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) JERUSALEM - Dec. 20, 1999 -- TEMPLE-MOUNT -- Muslims
during prayer at the Marwani mosque earlier this month. The great
underground vault, known by Jews as Solomon's Stables and by
Muslims as the Marwani mosque, has touched off a war of words in
Jerusalem's Old City. At issue is the opening of an emergency exit.
(Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Dec. 20, 1999 -- GATSBY-FASHION-3 -- In both
the book and the opera, Jay Gatsby wears a pink suit, symbolic of
his parvenu status. Jerry Hadley sings the title role in John
Harbison's opera of ``The Great Gatsy,'' which opened Monday night
at the Metropolitan Opera House. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Dec. 20, 1999 -- GATSBY-FASHION-2 -- For the
flapper dresses worn in the party scenes in John Harbison's opera
of ``The Great Gatsy,'' Jane Greenwood, the costume designer, used
hot colors inspired by the dust jacket for ``The Great Gatsby,''
published in 1925. ``You always associate pastels with the 1920s,
but I didn't want to do that,'' she says. (Marilynn K. Yee/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Dec. 20, 1999 -- GATSBY-FASHION-1 -- A
frenetic moment in the pivotal party scene at Gatsby's mansion in
John Harbison's opera of ``The Great Gatsy,'' which opened Monday
night at the Metropolitan Opera House. Giving voice to F. Scott
Fitzgerald's novel of wealth and reckless yearning presents
challenges that go well beyond the ``right'' shoe or the correct
display of ladies' knees. (Marilynn K. Yee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) UNDATED -- Dec. 20, 1999 -- OBIT-MOSER-B&AMP;W -- Jurgen
Moser, one of the world's leading mathematicians who helped develop
an influential theory for analyzing the orbits of planets,
asteroids and other celestial bodies, died of prostate cancer on
Friday in a hospital in Schwerzenbach, Switzerland. He was 71.
Moser is seen in a 1979 file photo. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK - Dec. 20, 1999 -- MICROSOFT-GREENHILL --
Robert Greenhill, a longtime Wall Street deal-maker, was hired by
the Justice Department to advise it on its negotiations with
Microsoft. After 37 years on Wall Street, Greenhill has joined the
rarefied group of investment bankers who command the ear of
America's corporate elite. Not only does he have a knack for wooing
the most stubborn executives, but he has the drive to get them to
the bargaining table. (Nina Barnett/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Dec. 20, 1999 -- COSMETOLOGY-FASHION --
Diane Heras, 17, a student at the Jane Adams Vocational High School
in the Bronx, plucks the eyebrows of Fay Rosen, 78. Every year at
this time, students of cosmetology display their skills here by
making up older women. (Joyce Dopkeen/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) SAN DIEGO, Calif. - Dec. 20, 1999 --
PERSONAL-GENOMICS-B&AMP;W -- A technician with Orchid Biocomputer holds
a microfluidics chip made up of a complex network of tiny valves
and capillaries that allow researchers to move liquids on and off a
microchip. The biotechnology industry, which has long lived in the
shadow of Silicon Valley and envied its many overnight successes,
is now tapping into that same technology in a bid to speed up its
own growth significantly. (Orchid Biotcomputer/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW ORLEANS, La. -- Dec. 20, 1999 -- NORLEANS-VENDOR-COX
-- ``I'm quite sad that people can't live in harmony and peace,''
says Mystic Goddess, a psychic who sets up her table in front of
the St. Louis Cathedral doors. Residents of New Orleans' French
Quarter, one of the nation's oldest and best-preserved residential
districts, say it is being turned into a Disneyland entertainment
center catering to the 11 million annual tourists and the
businesses that feed off them. (Anne Rochell Konigsmark/Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Dec. 20, 1999 -- BOMB-THEATER-REVIEW --
Jason Catalano, left, Erik Weiner and Jordan Allen-Dutton do
Shakespeare, in a manner of speaking. Shakespeare can take it;
theatergoers who don't also appreciate a mosh pit may have a harder
time. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) ATLANTA -- Dec. 20, 1999 -- SAMS-SONG-COX -- Sam Taylor
makes his way over to a pay phone to straighten its cord. Taylor
suffers from autism, an incurable neurological disorder
characterized by extreme withdrawal, impaired communication and
emotional detachment. It affects between 1 and 2 of every 1,000
newborns. (Kimberly Smith/Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- Dec. 20, 1999 -- SCI-BARBIE-ENVIRON -- Mattel
Inc., the world's largest toy maker, announced this month that it
would begin an effort to eliminate petroleum-based plastics from
many of its toys and dolls. Tests by the National Environmental
Trust showed Pony Luv, made by the Tara Toy Corp., had a 24.4
percent content of DEHP, a suspected carcinogen; the Pooh Bathtub
Pal from Mattel was among those made with high concentrations of
DINP, as were the Teletubbies, a product of Ritvik Toys. (Tony
Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) MAMMOTH LAKES, Calif. -- Dec. 20, 1999 --
TRAVEL-MAMMOTH-2-LADN -- A skier glides down one of the many
downhill slopes at Mammoth Mountain in California. The popular ski
area is now in the midst of a resort makeover. (Eric Noland/Los
Angeles Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MAMMOTH LAKES, Calif. -- Dec. 20, 1999 --
TRAVEL-MAMMOTH-1-LADN -- Among the new looks at Mammoth Mountain
this winter is Panorama Station. The mountain, with 3500 skiable
acres, offers plenty of wide-open terrain. (Eric Noland/Los Angeles
Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Dec. 20, 1999 -- SCI-ANCIENT-FLOWERS -- The
Clusia gaudichadii flower produces a sticky resin that is collected
by a specialized group of bees, known as meliponine bees. The bees
use the resins to defend themselves by globbing the sticky
substance, for example, on attacking ants. They also use it for
building nests. (Michael Rothman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) LOS ANGELES -- Dec. 20, 1999 -- FOOD-DESSERTS-2-LADN --
The classic chocolate truffle cake is a frequently requested recipe
at the Spago Restaurant in Los Angeles. This sinful dessert couples
bittersweet chocolate with Grand Marnier. (Los Angeles Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Dec. 20, 1999 -- FOOD-DESSERTS-1-LADN --
Chocolate orbit cake is easily prepared and served with creme
anglaise, if desired. This treat will launch chocolate lovers into
ecstasy. (Los Angeles Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK - Dec. 20, 1999 - TIMES-SQUARE-BALL-2 -- Alberto
Ibanez, left, and Charles Sperazza, screw in the light bulbs on the
New Year ball atop 1 Times Square on Monday. The 1,070 pound ball
will have 168 newly-designed bulbs on its exterior, while the
interior will be illuminated by over 400 other bulbs. The ball will
usher in the year 2000 over Times Square in just over a week.
(Angel Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK - Dec. 20, 1999 - TIMES-SQUARE-BALL -- Alberto
Ibanez, left, and Charles Sperazza, screw in the light bulbs on the
New Year ball atop 1 Times Square on Monday. The 1,070 pound ball
will have 168 newly-designed bulbs on its exterior, while the
interior will be illuminated by over 400 other bulbs. The ball will
usher in the year 2000 over Times Square in just over a week.
(Angel Franco/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON - Dec. 20, 1999 - CLINTON-CHRISTMAS --
President Clinton, along with his wife Hillary Rodham Clinton, show
illustrations from ``The Night Before Christmas,'' to children
gathered for a reading of the holiday classic on Monday in the East
Room of the White House. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- Dec. 20, 1999 -- SCI-BETHLEHEM-STAR -- Dr.
Michael Molnar with a photograph of a Roman coin depicting Aries,
which helped shape his theory. It is the reliance on an ancient
view of things that has earned Molnar's book, ``The Star of
Bethlehem: The Legacy of the Magi,'' praise from some historians of
astronomy. (Nancy Wegard/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WORCESTER, Mass. -- Dec. 20, 1999 -- SCI-GENES-PATENT-BOS
-- Sherri Epstein holds her 14-month-old daughter, Rachel, who
suffers from a genetic disorder called Canavan disease. Canavan
disease ravages the brain and nervous system and usually leads to
death in the first few years of life. The disease affects about 1
in 6,500 births to couples of Ashkenazi Jewish background, like the
Epsteins. (Tom Landers/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CHICAGO - Dec. 20, 1999 -- SECOND-CITY -- Former Second
City actors, from left, Harold Ramis, Tim Kazurinsky and Peter
Murietta, during a panel discussion on Saturday. Forging a new art
form from the disparate skills of classical acting and comic
improvisation, Second City celebrated its 40th anniversary over the
weekend. (Steve Kagan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times
</P>
