<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS LOOK FOR A LIFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Kings survived injuries to Luc Robitaille,
Ziggy Palffy and Stephane Fiset, so coach Andy Murray won't say the
return of first-line Jozef Stumpel will ignite the sputtering club.
</P>
<P>
   But after allowing 23 goals in a three embarrassing losses,
there's a reason the Kings are excited about Stumpel's expected
return Wednesday at San Jose. The Kings need rejuvenation, and
Stumpel can provide a jolt.
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel's return means the reuniting of the Kings' top line _
Stumpel flanked by Palffy and Robitaille. It also means the rest of
the lines can get back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He handles the puck really well and he's going to create that
much more room for us,'' Robitaille said. ``Sure, we need him. A
guy like that, he's talented. We need him.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray has a few reasons for downplaying Stumpel's return.
Murray wants to take pressure off the 23-year-old, and Stumpel
isn't in game condition. In addition, Robitaille is trying to find
his pre-broken-foot form and Palffy is fighting back problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone over how we want him to play that first game
back,'' Murray said. ``We have to get him in sometime. We know it's
a big game and we're putting a guy in that hasn't played in a long
time, but we have to get him in. He's got to play hard, but he's
got play a basic game and play strong defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Kings add toughness: As expected, the Kings added tough forward
Bill Huard to their 23-man roster _ and it comes with a message.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were pushed around in Saturday's 8-4 loss to Chicago.
Tough guy Steve McKenna was a coach's decision scratch and the
addition of Huard, who may not play during this promotion, is to
give the Kings some toughness in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Huard had 63 minutes in penalties in 11 games for Lowell (Mass.)
of the AHL and was impressive in a Monday night fight.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings also made a few other expected moves because of the
quasi-roster freeze. Jason Blake and Garry Galley, both suffering
post-concussion syndrome, were put on injured reserve. Defenseman
Jere Karalahti and winger Dan Bylsma, demoted to Long Beach on
Sunday morning, both practiced Monday with the Kings. One of those
players can be sent back to Long Beach to make room for Stumpel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
