<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REWARDED FOR CHECHNYA WAR, RUSSIAN PREMIER VOWS TO TURN TO DOMESTIC
ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With RUSSIA-ASSESS, RUSSIA-AID) 
(ms) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Prime Minister Vladimir Putin, newly confirmed in the
parliamentary elections as Russia's current political hero for his
tough conduct of the war in Chechnya, signaled Monday that he was
now prepared to put his stamp on domestic issues _ to meet voters'
demands, as he said, for ``new results, new ideas and new
solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   In effect, Putin, 47, opened up the second stage of a Kremlin
campaign that has already made him a clear favorite _ at least for
now _ to succeed President Boris Yeltsin in elections set for June.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was not a candidate, Putin, who was named prime
minister just four months ago, emerged as the political winner in
the parliamentary vote on Sunday when two parties he endorsed _
both brand-new political concoctions _swept into parliament on his
coattails, together collecting more than 30 percent of the votes
cast along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   The surprisingly strong showing by the pair _ an obscure
coalition known as Unity, or Medved, which means Bear, and the
Union of Right Forces, a party of liberal economic reformers _ put
Putin within reach of a working majority in the 450-seat
parliament, depending on shifting alliances with other parties and
the more than 100 deputies elected independently.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics, however, were skeptical of the cohesiveness and
goals of Unity in particular, a party that was slapped together by
the Kremlin in October as a late-hour entry in a vicious and often
ugly campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the first time we have a virtual party in parliament,''
said Vyacheslav Nikonov, a political analyst with the anti-Kremlin
center-left opposition. ``Unity has no organization, no program, no
nothing, not even people you can name.''
</P>
<P>
   With 84 percent of the vote counted, Unity, headed by
Emergencies Minister Sergei Shoigu, polled 23.4 percent of the
national vote _ just behind the Communist Party's showing of 24.2
percent. The Union of Right Forces, headed by former Prime Minister
Sergei Kiriyenko, won 8.7 percent of the national vote.
</P>
<P>
   Kremlin officials Monday hailed the results as a breakthrough in
the decade-long stalemate between Yeltsin and successive
parliaments that for most of his tenure has been dominated by a
Communist-led opposition. ``In Russia, a revolution has taken
place, a peaceful one but a revolution all the same,'' said Igor
Shabdurasulov, a top Kremlin aide.
</P>
<P>
   Western experts said the strong showing by pro-government
parties could give the Kremlin the backing it needs to pass
long-awaited reform legislation, including a new tax law, and a law
allowing the buying and selling of land, which until now has been
blocked by the Communists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This opens a lot of possibilities that no one had expected,''
said Anders Aslund, a senior associate of the Carnegie Endowment
for International Peace. ``Putin can now change the political stage
by having a reformist parliament.''
</P>
<P>
   But in some minds, the Kremlin's use of hard-ball tactics in the
campaign left doubts about its commitments to genuine economic and
democratic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``What shocks me about the Western reaction is this is seen as a
triumph for democracy in Russia while in my mind, it is completely
the opposite,'' said Nikonov. ``In my mind, it is a defeat of civic
society and a victory for the Family, which I consider the most
anti-democratic force in Russia.'' The Family is a term for the
Yeltsin entourage.
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Gorbachev, the former Soviet president, was also
dubious. ``Expectations that we will have a national policy
supporting the interests of all Russian and not clans and groups _
I do not think we will get this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, a former KGB officer who was a political unknown when he
was appointed prime minister in August, has already signaled that
he would endorse parts of an economic platform put forward by the
Union of Right Forces.
</P>
<P>
   But Putin's political views remain something of a mystery,
although his links to Yeltsin's democratic reform movement date to
the early 1990's, when he joined the administration of Anatoly
Sobchak, a democratic reformer who was then mayor of St.
Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Russian news agencies Monday, Putin said
his cabinet would do its best to work with the new Duma, the lower
house of parliament, ``not only on economic legislation, but also
on other decisions important to the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We must and will work with everybody in the new Duma no matter
what party, group or coalition he or she belongs to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist Party, still in first place as Russia's largest
party, will continue to be a major player in parliament. They will
have a minimum of 111 seats of their own, but may command a bloc of
up to 150 votes, according to some experts. In the last parliament,
the Communists drew on support from small left-wing parties and
independent deputies, to garner more than 200 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those parties have since split, or even vanished. A new
anti- Kremlin electoral bloc, Fatherland _ All Russia, headed by
former Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, polled only 12.6 percent.
That was a poor showing for an electoral bloc that as recently as
last summer was expected to sweep the parliamentary elections as
the favorite of the political establishment.
</P>
<P>
   The final makeup of parliament will be determined by the outcome
in 224 individual districts where candidates run in local races,
similar to American Congressional elections. In those elections,
candidates can run with party affiliation or as independents.
</P>
<P>
   In an election widely seen as a trial run for next summer's
presidential contest, attention was fixed on the contest between
political parties, which fill the parliament's remaining 225 seats
in proportion to the national vote for party lists.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Russian system, a party must get at least 5 percent of
the national vote to qualify for seats in parliament; votes cast
for parties that fail to make the threshold are distributed to the
winners.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's elections, six parties cleared the 5 percent hurdle,
including Yabloko, a liberal opposition party, with 6.1 percent,
and the party led by Vladimir V. Zhirinovsky, a nationalist
maverick, which got 6.1 percent. Both Zhirinovsky and Grigory A.
Yavlinsky, leader of Yabloko, are regarded as potential allies for
the government on certain issues.
</P>
<P>
   According to results so far, Fatherland _ All Russia already
claims 63 seats, with 76 for Unity, 30 for the Union of Right
Forces, 25 for Yabloko and 18 for Zhirinovsky's party. Still to
come are results from many individual districts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
