<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-AID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. ASKS DELAY ON $500 MILLION FOR RUSSIAN OIL COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (With RUSSIA-ASSESS and RUSSIA-ELECT) 
(ms) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration asked the Export-Import
Bank of the United States Monday to delay $500 million in aid to a
Russian oil company as a protest over continued resistance to
economic reforms and, more obliquely, to step up pressure to end
the military campaign in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   But the chairman of the bank, James A. Harmon, said Monday night
that he expected the board of the independent agency would probably
reject the request, which he argued was based on an extremely loose
reading of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secretary of state has the right to instruct the board to
deny the loan on the basis of `national interest,''' Harmon said in
an interview Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   That is a step that Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright has
apparently been unwilling to take, at least so far, in hope that a
delay would be enough to send a warning signal to the Russians and,
perhaps, might effectively kill the loan.
</P>
<P>
   But delay itself, Harmon said, ``is not one of the state
department's options, as we understand the law.''
</P>
<P>
   The request to the bank was made Monday night after considerable
debate in the administration, caught between its desire to remain
economically engaged in Russia and its fear that it will be seen as
underwriting companies that have resisted Western-style economic
reforms. Complicating the politics has been the military action in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Chechnya,'' a senior administration official said
Monday, ``I suspect that this would have gone through already.''
</P>
<P>
   The transaction is the kind that in other times would hardly
garner much notice. The bank is scheduled to meet Tuesday to decide
on loan guarantees to Tyumen Oil Co., a business in Siberia. The
Russian government owns nearly half the company.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year Tyumen has been involved in a dispute
involving another oil company whose assets it has been trying to
acquire. Along the way, Tyumen has been accused by BP Amoco and
George Soros, the international investor, of using unscrupulous
tactics to acquire the business and its huge oil field. Both the
company and Soros are investors in the target company.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, lobbying in the case has been fierce. BP Amoco and
Soros are pressing to have the Export-Import Bank loan killed,
perhaps hoping that would give them leverage in negotiating with
Tyumen. BP Amoco has been negotiating with Tyumen over a compromise
deal that could be completed soon.
</P>
<P>
   But the opponents of the deal have found that they have allies
in the White House, including officials who a year or two ago were
advocating more help for Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, President Clinton's economic adviser, has made it
clear that he believes Tyumen ``may have abused the rule of law.''
Sperling was part of a White House group that forwarded a Central
Intelligence Agency study of the company's actions to Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence H. Summers called Harmon from Europe
last week, saying there were ``significant questions'' about the
company and its efforts to manipulate the Russian legal system to
its advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say they are a bit mystified by
Harmon's resistance to their calls for a delay. But Harmon argues
that he is doing what the law calls for him to do, to make loan
decisions based on commercial, not political, considerations.
</P>
<P>
   The bank has two primary criteria, whether an export would
create American jobs _ in this case jobs that would produce
oil-drilling and environmental equipment _ and whether the foreign
company is creditworthy. ``We believe this meets those standards,''
Harmon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
