 &UR; GRASS _  &LR; Michael Neff was out mowing his lawn in Southern
California when inspiration struck. It occurred to him that this
tiresome chore could be virtually eliminated by creating
genetically engineered ``dwarf grass'' that would grow much more
slowly than ordinary grass.
</P>
<P>
   Now, more than a year later, Neff and other scientists have
succeeded in isolating a gene that limits stem growth in plants.
This ``dwarf gene'' may allow growers to restrict the height of
grass, trees and other plants. By David Lazarus
</P>
