 &UR; ECON &LR;  _ The California economy is expected to slow slightly in 2000
as a labor shortage and housing crunch dampen growth _ particularly
in the technology-driven Bay Area. Tom Lieser, director of the UCLA
Anderson Forecast, is projecting a 2.7 percent increase in nonfarm
employment in the state next year, compared with the 2.8 percent
rise expected in 1999. By Carol Emert
