<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEYBAG/ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Retirement Is a Risk But It's a Good One 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: I am 70 years old but still earning about $70,000 per year as a
real-estate broker. My wife and I would like to move to Carmel
Valley, where I might continue to work _ but very little, because I
want to spend most days playing golf. We would have $1,700 per
month from Social Security and could meet the rest of our expenses
by liquidating 5 percent of our securities portfolio each year. (It
is worth $925,000.) We also own a home with about $725,000 worth of
equity and would sell it and buy another in the $450,000 range. Do
you think we can pull this off?
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: Probably.
</P>
<P>
   If you could tell me exactly how long you and your wife are
going to live, exactly how the stock market will perform during
that period, and what the inflation rate will be each year, then it
would be possible to give you a definite answer.
</P>
<P>
   Barring that, we have to fall back on the averages. The average
annual stock-market performance over many decades is about an 11
percent gain, including dividends. The average rate of inflation is
about 3 percent. If the market were to go up 11 percent every year
and your expenses were to increase by 3 percent every year, then
you could liquidate 5 percent of your portfolio every year forever.
</P>
<P>
   However, the stock market and inflation don't always behave in a
neat, orderly fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you retire, and stocks suddenly begin a long, severe
bear market. Let's say the principal market averages decline by
more than 40 percent, while inflation shoots above 10 percent
annually. As paranoid as that scenario seems, you can't rule it
out, because it happened in 1973 and 1974. If it happened again, it
might put a notable crimp in your standard of living.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, that kind of economic havoc might never occur
again during the remainder of your lifetime. If you let worst-case
scenarios intimidate you, then you'll never retire. Almost
everybody who retires has to be a bit of a risk taker.
</P>
<P>
   If I were in your shoes, I would take the risk. However, I would
set aside a little time each evening to pray for continued economic
stability.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
IRA Contributions
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Suppose I report $3,000 in salary on line 7 of tax Form
1040, &LR;  and a $3,000 capital loss from stock sales on line 13,
netting out to total taxable income of zero. Would I be eligible to
contribute to an individual retirement account that year?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that you report more than $2,000 in wages entitles you
to contribute up to the $2,000 annual maximum to an IRA, says
Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse Weller. You won't lose
this right because you report an offsetting capital loss. Losing
the money is penalty enough. (And, by the way, how did you lose
money in this one-way stock market?)
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with an IRA ought to obtain a copy of IRS Publication
590, entitled `'Individual Retirement Arrangements,'' which spells
out just about every rule you need to know. You can download it
from the IRS Web site at www.irs.gov, or telephone for a copy at
(800) 829-3676.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Pay Debt or Invest?
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it better to pay off debt before investing in mutual funds
or stocks? I have approximately $7,000 in credit-card debt at 16
percent interest and am also making payments on a car and school
loans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: It depends on how good an investor you think you are.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you have $7,000 in cash available today to either invest
or pay off all your credit-card debt. If you don't pay off the
debt, it will grow by 16 percent per year.
</P>
<P>
   So, your goal as an investor would be to make your $7,000 in
cash grow by more than 16 percent per year after taxes. &UR;  &LR; I say
after taxes, because you would be paying your credit-card debt with
after-tax dollars.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know which tax bracket you are in, but to accomplish
your goal you probably would have to produce a pretax investment
return of more than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That is way above the stock market's historical average return
of 11 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, you probably could have earned a 20-plus
return in almost any of the past five years, when the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was gaining an average of more than 27 percent
annually.
</P>
<P>
   You don't say what interest rate you are paying on your car and
school loans; probably less than 16 percent. But the logic is the
same: You compare the interest you are paying with your expected
payoff from investing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag &LR; sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
