<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-ECON </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Rising Housing Costs, Labor Shortages May Cause
California's  Growth to Slow 
 &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The California economy is expected to slow slightly in 2000 as a
labor shortage and housing crunch dampen growth _ particularly in
the technology-driven Bay Area.
<P>
   Tom Lieser, director of the UCLA Anderson Forecast, is
projecting a 2.7 percent increase in nonfarm employment in the
state next year, compared with the 2.8 percent rise expected in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   But on the cusp of the new millennium, the California economy is
already showing signs of deceleration. Lieser's 2.8 percent
projection for this year is significantly lower than his original
estimate of 3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And in the San Francisco metropolitan area, which includes the
counties of San Francisco, San Mateo and Marin, the number of jobs
created dropped precipitously to 2 percent this year from 3 percent
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is great demand for what the Bay Area is producing and I
don't see any near-term end to it,'' Lieser said. ``The question is
whether it will be too costly for (those jobs) to stay there.''
</P>
<P>
   One dramatic example of the Bay Area employment dilemma is the
Transamerica Corp., the venerable insurance company whose
pyramid-shaped headquarters defines the San Francisco skyline.
</P>
<P>
   Only 150 top executives and their staff were left in the
Transamerica Pyramid when the company was sold to Aegon NV earlier
this year _ down from 2,400 people working there in the mid-1980s.
Most employees were transferred to cheaper areas like Chicago,
Dallas and Los Angeles. Offices in the Pyramid, meanwhile, were
rented at sky-high rates to other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Many other San Francisco corporate pillars, from Chevron Corp.
to Gap Inc., also maintain sizable offices outside of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, San Francisco's jobless rate hit a rock-bottom 2.4
percent in November _ strong evidence that there aren't enough
workers to go around, Lieser said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, November unemployment was 5.4 percent in the Los
Angeles area and 4.1 percent nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, local construction is slowing and Bay Area home
prices are rising 12 percent a year, with no relief in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Area home prices are now more than double the national
average _ a median price of $305,000 for a single-family dwelling,
compared with about $140,000 nationally, according to
Acxiom/Dataquick. The California median is $197,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly in the Bay Area, the housing problem must now be
viewed as a major constraint to growth,'' said Ted Gibson, chief
economist with the state Department of Finance.
</P>
<P>
   Although exports are starting to pick up, ``under these
circumstances, I'm not sure companies will want to expand in the
Bay Area since they won't be able to find housing for their
workers,'' Gibson said. ``That's a big problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as job creation slows, sky-high compensation among the
ranks of the employed is keeping the state economy barreling along.
That's especially true in the Bay Area, with its generous salaries,
bonuses and stock options, Lieser said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer spending is accelerating at a blistering pace. Lieser
forecasts a jump of 8.9 percent this year and 5.8 percent in 2000,
up from 5.2 percent in 1998. Since the housing market is so tight,
much of the money is being spent on remodeling and furniture
upgrades in existing homes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Incomes, meanwhile, are forecast to rise 6.4 percent in 1999 and
6.1 percent in 2000, increases that are robust but short of last
year's 6.9 percent jump.
</P>
<P>
   California's export sector, which had suffered from low
worldwide demand, particularly among struggling Asian countries, is
another area of optimism for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   State exports rebounded with a 10.2 percent increase in the
third quarter after falling 4.2 percent in 1998 and the same amount
in the first half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Economies throughout most of the world, from Italy to Thailand
to Mexico, are strengthening _ and so is the demand for California
products, particularly electronic equipment, according to Lieser.
</P>
<P>
   Still, much of the state's future growth will be generated
outside of the Bay Area, since impediments to living and doing
business here are so great, economists predict.
</P>
<P>
   New construction, as measured by residential and commercial
building permits, is booming in much of the state. For the first 10
months of the year, new permits in Los Angeles were up 21.6 percent
over the same period of 1998; statewide, permits jumped 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the issuance of building permits in Alameda and
Contra Costa counties declined 6.2 percent. Permits were also down
in San Jose and Sonoma, although they rose 3.9 percent in San
Francisco, San Mateo and Marin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic; you have an economy that wants to grow and local
governments that won't let it,'' said Gibson, who blames the local
housing shortage on an antigrowth mind-set among municipalities. He
forecast ``static'' employment in the Bay Area for the foreseeable
future.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area squeeze is good news for outlying areas. The number
of construction permits issued in the Salinas/Monterey region more
than doubled in the first 10 months of 1999 against the comparable
1998 period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even out in Martinez, there are houses starting in the
mid-500s,'' said Gibson. ``That's very illustrative of the
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Sacramento area, companies like Intel and Hewlett-Packard
are expanding their facilities, Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern in the longer term is that even places like
Sacramento won't be an option,'' Lieser said. ``California is
uniformly expensive. We'll be fortunate if the state can hold onto
new job opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
