<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4821 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-GATSBY-FASHION-ART-NY     12-20 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATSBY-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MET OPERA'S CHALLENGE IN DRESSING `GATSBY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photes, NYT20,22 and 22, have been sent. Non-subscribers
can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Harbison's ``Great Gatsy,'' which opened Monday
night at the Metropolitan Opera with Dawn Upshaw and Jerry Hadley
in the roles of the Long Island lovebirds, will probably not do for
shirt sales what the Robert Redford film version did in 1974. In
the famous scene when Gatsby nonchalantly tosses his many-colored
shirts in the air, Hadley has a mere handful, while Redford had a
heap.
</P>
<P>
   But then, as Jane Greenwood, the costume designer for the Met's
production, noted dryly of not the least of the differences between
the leading men, ``Redford cannot sing opera.''
</P>
<P>
   Giving voice to F. Scott Fitzgerald's novel of wealth and
reckless yearning presents challenges that go well beyond the
``right'' shoe or the correct display of women's knees. Yet,
because of the movie's extravagant costumes, which generated enough
buzz to make the covers of both Time and Newsweek and to land a
number of commercial tie-ins, from shirts and ice-cream-colored
suits to white Teflon pants, lots of people know what Gatsby looked
like even if his personality remained in shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Lauren, then at the beginning of his ultra-dreamy career,
designed the clothes for Redford, as well as for the other male
actors. Although Theoni V. Aldredge ultimately won the Academy
Award for the film's costumes, it was Lauren's designs that created
the most stir, partly because fashion editors around the country
immediately picked up on the look for their magazine and newspaper
columns, and partly because Lauren, ne Lifshitz, seemed to have the
same longings that had transformed the young roughneck Jimmy Gatz
into Jay Gatsby.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the movie, which Paramount made for $6.4 million,
was so high, in fact, that when the studio held its gala premiere,
on March 27, 1974, people came dressed in flapper beads and
feathers. Fitzgerald's daughter, Scottie Lanahan Smith, brought 28
friends and relatives from Montgomery, Ala. As for Lauren, he felt
both elated and frustrated by what would turn out to be his only
Hollywood costume job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so thrilled, because it was everything that I believed
in, and I was unknown at the time,'' he said last week. But it
rankled Lauren that he didn't receive equal billing with Ms.
Aldredge, a veteran costume designer. He added, ``It was not a
great experience in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, it was Lauren whom the Met first approached to
design the costumes for the ``Gatsby'' opera. ``I talked to him a
lot, and we had some marvelous discussions,'' said Mark Lamos, the
production's director. Flattered by the offer, Lauren said he
almost accepted, but declined because of business demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been an amazing amount of work, and I felt like
I did `Gatsby' in the movie,'' he said. ``For the opera, you have
to be very concerned with the period, so there wasn't a lot of room
for originality.''
</P>
<P>
   In a quirk of fate, one of those who joined Mrs. Smith's
contingent for the film premiere was Jane Greenwood, who last April
began designing costumes for the latest ``Gatsby.''
</P>
<P>
   A lanky Englishwoman with deadpan delivery, Ms. Greenwood
remembered staying with Mrs. Smith in Montgomery, where Ms.
Greenwood's husband had relatives, and being knocked out when she
was browsing through a bookcase. ``I thought, My goodness _ here's
every first edition of F. Scott Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   It is Ms. Greenwood's inspired use of the same hot colors that
appeared on Francis Cugat's dust-jacket design for the first
edition of ``The Great Gatsby,'' in 1925, that give the opera's
riotous party scenes their sinful look. ``You always associate
pastels with the 1920s, but I didn't want to do that,'' Ms.
Greenwood said. Cavorting against Michael Yeargan's minimalist
backdrop, the dancers and chorus, in acid tones of orange, blue,
fuchsia and yellow, look electric.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting halfway back in the house during rehearsal, Ms.
Greenwood pointed to a pudgy chorus member in a
preposterous-looking blue panier skirt. ``That's a copy of a 1925
Lanvin,'' said Ms. Greenwood, whose film, stage and opera credits
include ``Glengarry Glen Ross,'' ``Master Class'' and ``Dialogues
of the Carmelites.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's wearing her stole wrong,'' Michael Zecher, an assistant,
whispered.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Greenwood made a note to fix that. During an earlier break,
Lamos had come over to Ms. Greenwood and asked whether the silk
wrapper worn by Lorraine Hunt Lieberson, who plays Myrtle Wilson,
the garage mechanic's floozy wife, should be shortened to show more
leg. Ms. Greenwood said she thought so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Myrtle's a little bit more available,'' Lamos said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a little,'' Ms. Greenwood agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Although she saw the movie version of ``The Great Gatsby,''
which starred Mia Farrow as Daisy Buchanan, Ms. Greenwood said she
avoided watching it again. In any case, the costume concerns of
opera are vastly different. ``In a movie, you can come in for a
close-up on a clasp of pearls,'' she said. ``But on the stage all
that detail is lost.'' She concentrated on color, mixing
contrasting textures like velvet and satin to bring out more depth,
and on period silhouettes, like the flowing, kimono-sleeved pink
jacket with pale blue ribbons that Ms. Upshaw wears as Daisy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the silhouette doesn't read all the way to the back row,''
Ms. Greenwood said, ``then the icing doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   She also replicated foundation garments for the female singers,
to heighten their sense of reality while flattening their chests in
the boyish style of the era. In all, there are about 150 costumes,
made either by Angel in London or by Eric Winterling Ltd. in New
York. The millinery came from Lynne Mackey, and the shoes from
Pompei in Rome. ``He made all the shoes, and they nearly all fit,''
Ms. Greenwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Given his association with the movie, and his ability to exploit
and market such old-sport notions as taste and class, Lauren was
asked to give his opinion of the new ``Gatsby'' costumes. Looking
at some photographs from the flashy party scene, with its
rebellious hues and arching plumes, Lauren said, ``What I'm seeing
is that the women's clothes are beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   But he wondered about Gatsby, whose style and well-worn tales of
collecting rubies and hunting big game could by turns provoke
incredulity and fascination in his listeners. ``He was really a
mysterious guy,'' Lauren said, ``and a lot of what he was about
came through the clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, little of the character's complexity and verve come across
in the opera's costumes. The opera's Gatsby wears the flamboyant
pink suit that appeared in both the novel and the movie, now in a
shade close to strawberry soda, and he duly sports a light
caramel-colored suit (another sartorial reference from the book)
for his first afternoon with Daisy.
</P>
<P>
   But he doesn't look remarkably different from the other peacocks
on the stage, and when he begins throwing around his shirts _ no
significantly bold stripes, no plaids in coral or lavender, no
monograms in Indian blue _ it's hard to imagine what Daisy is
bawling about. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
