<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MOSER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUERGEN MOSER, WHO PROVED CELESTIAL THEORY, DIES AT 71 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By SYLVIA NASAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Juergen Moser, one of the world's leading mathematicians who
helped develop an influential theory for analyzing the orbits of
planets, asteroids and other celestial bodies, died of prostate
cancer Dec. 17 in a hospital in Schwerzenbach, Switzerland. He was
71.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other talented young Germans who came of age after
Germany's glittering scientific establishment was gutted by the
Nazis, Moser emigrated to the United States in the mid-1950s, soon
after completing his doctorate. He spent most of his career at the
New York University Courant Institute, where he served for three
years as director.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly 25 years in this country, Moser returned to Europe
in 1980 to rebuild the once-stellar Mathematics Research Institute
at the Federal Institute of Technology, Switzerland's equivalent of
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Moser's research was inspired by problems that arose in
physics. A lifelong astronomy enthusiast who as a boy built model
gliders and as a father made boats for his children, Moser was
fascinated by problems involving the stability of motion, or lack
of it. He is best known for a fundamental contribution to celestial
mechanics, the Kolmogorov-Arnold-Moser theory, that he published,
in an article that appeared in a German journal in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   The problem that Moser tackled, the stability of the solar
system, was one that had tantalized scientists for centuries. Will
the solar system remain as it is for all eternity, or will Jupiter
one day collide with Mars and Venus drift into the Sun? Isaac
Newton made his contribution to the invention of calculus while
trying to prove that celestial bodies always travel in elliptical
orbits.
</P>
<P>
   But Newton's proof applied only to systems that consisted of two
bodies, say Earth and the Sun. Nearly every leading 18th-century
mathematician took up the problem of systems with more elements, a
problem that involved both stable movements and unpredictable,
chaotic ones, but by the end of the 19th century, the celebrated
French mathematician Poincare had concluded that the problem was
essentially insoluble.
</P>
<P>
   The KAM theory addresses the following question: What happens to
well-behaved elliptical orbits if one tries to take into account
the small perturbations resulting from the gravitational pull of
smaller or more distant planets? In 1954, the Russian
mathematician, Andrei N. Kolmogorov, announced that he had found
the answer, arguing that if the disturbance was sufficiently small,
many but not all of the orderly motions would survive, with orderly
orbits coexisting alongside chaotic ones. But Kolmogorov outlined a
general theory without supplying complete proof. His student, V.I.
Arnold, proved one case; Moser proved another.
</P>
<P>
   Moser was just 27 and completely unknown when he was asked to
summarize Kolmogorov's argument for a mathematics journal and
discovered a critical gap in the Russian's argument. It took him
several years to produce the result that filled that gap. The
result created an immediate sensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wonderful thing is that KAM theory also applies to
airplane dynamics, submarine dynamics, automobile dynamics; in
fact, practically any dynamical system described by Newton's
laws.'' said Philip Holmes, an applied mathematician at Princeton
University, who with Florin Diacu wrote the book ``Celestial
Encounters,'' (Princeton University Press, 1996), a history of
dynamical systems theory.
</P>
<P>
   Though he went on to make other important contributions in
dynamical systems, Moser also worked in the field of partial
differential equations, the sorts of equations in which many of the
laws of physics, not to mention those of financial derivatives, are
formulated.
</P>
<P>
   Juergen Moser was born on July 4, 1928, in the East Prussian
city of Koenigsberg. He grew up in an intellectual family that
spent summers at an aunt's country estate and evenings playing
Haydn and Bach. His mother played the piano, his father, a
psychiatrist, the violin, and young Juergen , the cello.
</P>
<P>
   At 15, he was drafted, along with his entire high school class,
into a military auxiliary force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trained to man antiaircraft guns against the bombers
attacking our town,'' he recalled in a letter to a grandson.
</P>
<P>
   Too slight to lift the heavy explosives, he was assigned to
compute their trajectories. Many horrors, including the death of
his older brother and most of his classmates, followed. For more
than two years, he was always hungry, surviving by will and wit.
Once, after he had crossed into Russian territory, he was captured
briefly, held in a basement half-filled with water and starved for
a week. Afterward, he said, ``I succeeded in snatching a frozen
turnip which I believe may have saved my life.''
</P>
<P>
   What saved his mind was a habit of seeking refuge in mathematics
that he first developed in the barracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I forgot about the outside world and thought about a
mathematical problem which I made up and tried to solve in my
head,'' he recalled. ``That was very soothing; the officers could
yell at me as much as they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   After the war, he spent two years finishing high school in what
later became East Germany. He fled to the west in 1947 to study at
Goettingen. Most of the luminaries, including Richard Courant and
Carl Ludwig Siegel, had been driven out or left voluntarily before
the war. Moser came under Siegel's influence after he returned from
the United States in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   A Fulbright Scholarship allowed Moser to spend a year in New
York with the assemblage of emigres and young New Yorkers at the
institute established by Richard Courant. Before long, he was
spending weekends in the Courant house in New Rochelle, N.Y., with
its heavy Biedermeier furniture, grand piano and musical evenings
reminiscent of home, and was falling in love with Courant's eldest
daughter, Gertrude, a biologist.
</P>
<P>
   Moser returned briefly to Goettingen to work as Siegel's
assistant, writing a book on celestial mechanics with his mentor.
By September 1955, he was back at NYU and had married Gertrude
Courant. Two years later, he accepted a position at MIT. He became
an American citizen in 1959, and one year later accepted an offer
to return to the Courant Institute as a professor. In 1967, Moser
took over the directorship of the institute, serving three years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, he accepted the position in Zurich. He retired in 1995,
the year he received the Wolf Prize for mathematics. He also served
as president of the International Mathematical Union from 1983 to
1986..
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, a son, Richard D. Emery of New York;
two daughters, Nina S. Moser of Seattle and Lucy I. Moser of Dijon,
France; a brother, Klaus Moser-Maync of New York, and seven
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Nirenberg, a mathematician at Courant, said of Moser's
work, ``His mathematics was beautiful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
