<SLUG> BC-BROKER-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORGAN STANLEY EXCEEDS EXPECTATIONS WITH RECORD OPERATING PROFIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. reported record quarterly
income of $1.63 billion Monday, up 86 percent from its operating
profit a year earlier and well ahead of analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   In the first look at fourth quarter results from a major Wall
Street securities firm, the company said it earned $2.84 a diluted
share. The profit was up from $1.49 a share a year earlier, when
its operating income totaled $879 million, and was well ahead of
the $1.96 a share expected by analysts surveyed by First
Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to argue with anything that they posted,'' said
Richard Strauss, an analyst at Goldman Sachs Group. ``It's a
blowout quarter.'' Strauss raised his estimate of Morgan Stanley's
earnings 20 percent last month, to $2.10 a share, only to be topped
by 35 percent. Monday, he raised his estimate for the firm's 2000
earnings to $9.10 from $8.15 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley also announced that in January it would split its
shares two for one and increase its dividend, before the split, by
67 percent, to 40 cents a share. The firm said it planned to spend
up to $1 billion buying back its stock. Its shares rose $1.4375, to
$129.50.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley, like rival investment bank Goldman Sachs, which
reports its earnings Tuesday, is riding atop two powerful trends: a
boom in new stock offerings, especially by Internet-based
companies, and a wave of mergers and acquisitions involving
European companies. Morgan Stanley ranks just behind Goldman this
year in money raised through initial public offerings and in the
value of announced mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IPO boom certainly plays an important role in the results
of the quarter,'' said Robert Scott, Morgan Stanley's chief
financial officer. ``We also had a record quarter in M&AMP;A with lots
of activity in the U.S. and in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott said high levels of trading, especially stock trading, led
to a 36 percent increase in commission revenue, to $786 million
from $579 million in a depressed quarter a year earlier. Over all,
the firm's profit from its securities businesses more than doubled
to $1.39 billion in the quarter that ended Nov. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's 43 percent jump in revenue, to $5.66 billion for the
quarter, surprised even the firm's management, analysts said. That
was clear, they said, from how much the firm's compensation
expenses shrunk.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley set aside almost $1 billion less in employee
compensation and benefits last quarter than the quarter before.
Scott said the decrease was a result of the firm's practice of
accruing money through the year to pay year-end bonuses. Those
bonuses, which account for the bulk of annual pay for investment
bankers and traders, will be paid in early January.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, Morgan Stanley and its competitors pay about half
of their revenues to their employees as salaries, bonuses and
benefits. But, Scott said, Morgan Stanley had such a big year that
it needed only 23 percent of this quarter's revenue _ 40 percent of
the full year's revenue _ to pay competitive bonuses this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had such a stupendous year, if they had paid out 49
percent of this year's revenue, it would clearly argue that the
business doesn't have economies of scale,'' said Joan Solotar, an
analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Solotar said the markets gained strength well into December,
confounding most industry insiders, who thought investors would
pull back in fear of Year 2000-related problems. ``Even those who
weren't bearish thought it would be significantly slower,'' she
said. ``But money is still flowing into the markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley's expenses aside from compensation were higher
last quarter, Strauss said. He said some of the increase went
toward technology and marketing for the firm's new iChoice online
trading operation.
</P>
<P>
   Scott said it was too soon to gauge the success of iChoice, but
he said the firm was pleased that of the online accounts opened
since the October introduction, 70 percent were for new customers
and only 30 percent were transfers from the firm's traditional
brokerage operation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
