<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-TIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LA TIMES PUBLISHES PROFIT-SHARING DEAL WITH STAPLES CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times published an unsparing account on Monday
of its ill-fated profit-sharing deal on a Sunday magazine section
with a local sports arena, the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which was written by David Shaw, media reporter for
The newspaper, and published in a 14-page special section, detailed
the deal's incremental evolution, the haphazard way editors
realized what was happening and the failure of the newsroom's
leadership to quash it.
</P>
<P>
   The extensive coverage, which was edited by a former managing
editor of the paper but not reviewed by the paper's current top
editors before publication, reveals some moments of high drama at
the height of the controversy in late October and early November.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the drama and the detail, and the light the report
shines on some of the murkiest moments of the affair, ``There is no
smoking gun in this piece,'' said Narda Zacchino, an associate
editor at The Times. ``I'm not sure people really expected a
smoking gun.''
</P>
<P>
   The firestorm that erupted in The Times' newsroom after it was
disclosed that The Times and the Staples Center had split the
profits from the magazine _ $600,000, acccording to Shaw _ was
borne of the traditional tension between the newspaper's two roles.
</P>
<P>
   As a business enterprise, a newspaper is supposed to make a
profit. As a journalistic enterprise, it is suppose to report the
facts regardless of who is offended. Its journalistic independence
and the trust that inspires are vital.
</P>
<P>
   The journalists who rebelled over the deal argued _ and the
publisher and many protesting readers agreed _ that to share the
profits of its journalism with the subject of that journalism gave
readers reason to doubt the newspaper's objectivity and integrity,
even though the journalists involved had not known of the deal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shaw documented cultural changes that were a byproduct of the
desire of Mark H. Willes, the chief executive of the Times Mirror
Co., the newspaper's parent and for more than 18 months the
publisher of the newspaper, to reinvent the newspaper, eliminating
traditional barriers between business executives and journalists _
barriers designed to protect the integrity of the news product from
advertiser influence.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, The Times published a front-page apology for the
Staples Center deal, along with a statement of the ``Principles of
The Los Angeles Times,'' including one reading, ``We will show no
favoritism. Our newsroom will operate free of influence from public
and private institutions, political officials and advertisers.''
</P>
<P>
   That, Shaw's report said, had not always been the case in recent
months. In some other arrangements advertising executives tried to
guarantee coverage of certain events, or suggested that the books
of publishers with large advertising budgets be given special
attention in the newspaper's book review.
</P>
<P>
   ``This story shows in great detail that when people had concerns
about breaking down a wall (between advertising and editorial
content), this was not just a theory, there was reality to this
fear,'' said Henry Weinstein, a legal affairs reporter who was one
of the most outspoken critics of the Staples Center deal.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to some of the report's revelations about other deals,
he said it presented ``a distressing picture of a situation where
business considerations had improperly encroached on journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   The Staples Center deal, in its embryonic phase, had little to
do with journalism. On Dec. 17, 1998, after months of negotiation,
The Times agreed to be one of the ``founding partners'' of the
center. The agreement, Shaw wrote, committed the newspaper ``to pay
Staples Center about $1.6 million a year for five years _ $800,000
of that in cash, $500,000 in free advertising and an estimated
$300,000 in profits'' from what the contract described as ``joint
revenue opportunities'' _ such as a special magazine to be
published when the center opened.
</P>
<P>
   Although two managing editors, at meetings in March, objected to
devoting the magazine to the arena's opening, Michael Parks, the
paper's editor, later overruled them _ although, he said, he was
never told by the publisher, Kathryn M. Downing, that the magazine
would be used as a ``joint revenue opportunity.'' Ms. Downing has
consistently agreed with his recollection.
</P>
<P>
   Parks said that he became aware of the deal at a Sept. 14
meeting, as final preparations were being made to print the
magazine, which was issued.
</P>
<P>
   His account is confirmed by Ms. Downing but not by several other
participants. (Parks' account of what he said during an interview
with The New York Times is also contradicted by this reporter in
the Shaw report.)
</P>
<P>
   Neither he nor Ms. Downing, however, took steps to not publish
the magazine or give readers notice of the profit-sharing
arrangement with the subject of the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am happy that we've had this'' special section, Ms. Zacchino
said. ``I'm not sure that this is closure. I'm not sure when
closure will come. But I do feel this is a very, very important
step toward closure.'' The Shaw report, she said, was ``very
thorough and exhaustive and tough.''
</P>
<P>
   In late November and early December, however, Ms. Downing has
made two costly decisions to shred sections of the newspaper
containing unlabeled advertising material. The statement of
principles published Sunday, which was being prepared at the time,
says, ``We hold that journalistic excellence is the soundest
foundation for our success and that the editorial integrity of The
Los Angeles Times is its most precious asset.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
