<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRGIN-SINGAPORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGAPORE AIRLINES BUYS 49 PERCENT STAKE IN VIRGIN AIRLINES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Richard Branson, the British entrepreneur who started
Virgin Airlines 15 years ago with a single jumbo jet flight across
the Atlantic, sold nearly half his business Monday to Singapore
Airlines for $965 million.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of a 49 percent stake gives Branson a highly profitable
partner at a time when his airline is in a heated battle with
British Airways for trans-Atlantic passengers, Virgin's most
important business.
</P>
<P>
   It also will greatly expand the European reach of Singapore
Airlines, which is known for the quality of its service. In effect,
the deal gives Branson's airline an instant global reach.
</P>
<P>
   Branson said the airlines had ``sort of courted each other'' for
12 years. Virgin's London-New York service started with a lone
jumbo jet in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal has avoided leaving us out in the cold,'' he said,
referring to the new alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant benefit for the Asian airline is access to
Heathrow in London, Europe's busiest airport, which will allow it
to fly trans-Atlantic routes.
</P>
<P>
   While Singapore Airlines will not be able to fly directly
between Britain and the United States with its own planes, it will
be able to book the routes as Singapore flights in a code-sharing
program with Virgin.
</P>
<P>
   The deal means that Virgin and Singapore will control 2.5
percent of Heathrow's available slots, or available daily takeoff
and landing opportunities. By law, an airline cannot sell a stake
of more than 49 percent without forfeiting its nationality and its
rights under international route agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The sale is the latest in a series of international alliances in
the airline industry that give participating carriers integrated
route schedules and timetables.
</P>
<P>
   Branson said, however, that Virgin would not enter the much
broader Star Alliance, which Singapore is expected to enter in the
spring. That arrangement, led by United Airlines and Lufthansa,
enables several international carriers to coordinate schedules and
ticketing.
</P>
<P>
   Branson and Cheong Choong Kong, chief executive of Singapore
Airlines, said at a news conference here Monday that the deal came
together during lunch on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   After morning negotiations, Branson and Cheong both adjourned
for lunch at the same restaurant in the Four Seasons Hotel. As
Choong told it, he was eating when Branson walked over and passed
him a handwritten note on scrap paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were two sentences on it,'' Choong said. ``The first
indicated strongly that we could strike a deal; the second was a
question: Who is paying for lunch?''
</P>
<P>
   Choong added, ``I was so excited about the first sentence that I
forgot the question.'' He said he owes Branson lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the deal would benefit both companies. ``It puts
Singapore Airlines in a great position and is a tremendous price
for Virgin to get,'' said Chris Tarry, an analyst at Commerzbank in
London.
</P>
<P>
   Singapore Airlines has been trying to make an acquisition since
it unwound an alliance with Swissair and Delta Air Lines by selling
its stakes in the two carriers for $526.1 million. Even though it
has $3.07 billion in cash, it made two unsuccessful attempts to
take stakes in South African Airways and Ansett Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Singapore Airlines also recently expressed interest in buying a
stake in Thai Airways International.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Virgin's domestic rival, British Airways, fell 4.8
percent Monday, as investors worried that the deal would mean an
increase in competition on North Atlantic routes, which industry
executives already say have too many planes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
