u l BC-COSMETOLOGY-FASHION-A     12-20 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSMETOLOGY-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH SCHOOL GIVES BEAUTY LESSONS TO SENIOR CITIZENS IN THE SOUTH
BRONX  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In her 1992 book, ``The Change,'' Germaine Greer
famously counseled women against Cher-like acts of age defiance.
Women should use their later years, she maintained, finally to
break free from the ``fretful struggle'' always to look good.
</P>
<P>
   This is just the kind of feminist thinking that probably doesn't
sit well with Joyce Cox, who spent Friday morning in a crushed
velvet jacket getting silver feathers etched onto her pearlized,
paper-clip-length nails and talking about her recent turn as a sort
of advanced-age Gisele.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cox, a retired mail-room worker, had modeled a handkerchief
skirt at a fashion show held at the Hope of Israel social center in
the Bronx a few weeks earlier. ``Guess how old I am?'' she asked.
``Guess,'' she prodded, before pre-empting with the answer.
``Sixty-nine.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cox, along with about 58 other women, were getting
manicured, pedicured and plucked in the classrooms of the Jane
Addams Vocational High School in the South Bronx, whose cosmetology
students each year offer makeovers to neighbors who generally
exceed the age of the average ``Dawson's Creek'' viewer by about 55
years.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Addams, which was founded in 1934, has 1,600 teen-agers
enrolled. About 300 wear white smocks every day, balancing course
work called Beauty 3 or Beauty 4 with course work called English or
algebra. They hunch over plastic heads with penned grids on the
scalps, learning to layer hair and finger wave and box braid it in
classrooms that make few concessions to modernity, save for a
Christy Turlington photo on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Proving that male vanity is not the sole province of Maxim
magazine's readership, Charles Estridge, the only male client at
the event, said he has been coming to Jane Addams for beauty
treatments for years. While getting a manicure on Friday, he said
he was most looking forward to his facial. Estridge had just turned
80.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use two creams, an emollient, a mask and an astringent,''
said a student who was tending to Estridge's nail filing and was
about to begin his skin care. ``People come out with a glow.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Isabel, another student, said, ``I like better blow-drying
and hair coloring,'' referring to the beauty curriculum. Ms. Isabel
came to the United States from the Dominican Republic in 1992.
Until two years ago she spoke no English; now, she is a member of
the National Honor Society and plans to apply to college next year.
</P>
<P>
   However dramatically money and celebrity have attached
themselves to some in the business of making people look more
attractive, Ms. Isabel and her friends generally aspire to jobs
traditionally accorded more status, rather than becoming the next
Frederic Fekkai.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a manager in any type of business,'' Tenisha
Artis, a 12th grader, said. ``I just wanted something to fall back
on after I go to college,'' she said of styling.
</P>
<P>
   Another senior said, ``It's nothing to make a future with.'' An
11th grader, Valene Benjamin, said she did think of opening a salon
one day, but her more immediate goals included getting into the
University of Connecticut, studying accounting and playing
professional basketball.
</P>
<P>
   This is not welcome news to the beauty industry, which is
suffering from a labor shortage that Ray Testa, president of the
American Association of Cosmetology Schools, described as brutal.
Testa estimated that there are about 1,000 beauty schools in the
country, half the number that existed in the 1980's. In Manhattan,
Testa said, there are just two beauty schools left.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Coniglio, head of the International Chain Salon Association,
a trade group, conceded that ``a lot of people don't look at
cosmetology as a viable profession,'' despite the fact that the
number of Americans getting their hair cut in salons is at an
all-time high, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Some graduates of Jane Addams go to work in places like Vidal
Sassoon and Tear Drops of Elegance, a beauty parlor in Harlem.
Upscale salons like John Barrett and Stephen Knoll in Manhattan
have not tapped into the talent pool there. Their graduates, they
say, come mostly from the Long Island Beauty School. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 2229EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0391 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4850 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-NYT &LR;      12-20 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A HANDSHAKE REFUSED 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Tuesday, Dec. 21: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore may have won the battle of the headlines
by offering to debate former Sen. Bill Bradley twice a week and
refrain from television ads during the primary season. But Bradley,
who responded to Gore's offer of an on-air handshake with amused
disdain on ``Meet the Press'' on Sunday, had sound tactical reasons
for rejecting the suggestion. Debates are healthy and enlightening,
and the Democratic contenders' two televised encounters over the
weekend showed the strengths and weaknesses of both. But there is
no reason to insist that Bradley, a challenger who is much less
well known than Gore, give up a crucial avenue to communicate with
voters.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Meet the Press'' encounter was by far the liveliest of all
the presidential candidates' exchanges so far. But even Tim Russert
found it hard to keep the candidates from confusing viewers with
their intense squabbling over the arcane history of school vouchers
and the fiscal details of health care policy. Perhaps more
memorable than any particular points scored was the barrage of
comments like ``No! No! No!'' ``That's false!'' and ``Give me a
break!'' In his closing statement, Bradley said aptly that he and
the vice president represented ``different styles of leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   They also bring very different strategic plans to their
confrontations. Bradley clearly believes he gains by casting
himself as a big-picture visionary who resists political games. For
his part, Gore seems convinced that he wins by pressing Bradley on
policy details and outpointing him on the debate scorecard.
Controlling the content has become a battle of wills between the
two. Bradley seems to have the upper hand when the exchanges are
thematic, Gore when they are about the history and funding of
specific programs.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and Bradley have been thrown on the defensive more
than once in their debates. The former New Jersey senator is
probably going to have to do better than swat away challenges about
how his budget numbers add up, particularly on health care. Gore
looks weakest when called upon to defend the fund-raising abuses of
the 1996 Clinton-Gore campaign and his assertion that Clinton would
be remembered as one of the nation's greatest presidents. Both are
going to have to do better in candidly discussing reforms in Social
Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   With the holidays approaching, it is possible now to assess the
debate performances of all Republican and Democratic candidates. It
must be said that for all their differences, Gore and Bradley gave
intense demonstrations of their knowledge and interest in
education, health care and budget issues, whereas the Republicans
have drifted off too often into generalities over reducing
government and abortion. Unlike Gore and Bradley, Sen. John McCain
and Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican front-runners, have yet to
get into any serious arguments except for campaign finance reform.
They may find themselves ill prepared when it comes time for them
to face either of the two Democrats in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout this season there have been two types of debates
among the candidates. In one popular setting, the so-called
town-meeting format, the questions are asked by regular voters who
sometimes cut through the policy verbiage but sometimes digress
into self-indulgent tangents. The other format has been to turn the
debate over to a star network correspondent like Russert, Ted
Koppel or Tom Brokaw, creating the odd effect of the politicians
competing with someone who is a bigger star than they.
</P>
<P>
   More experimentation might be in order when the campaign resumes
next year. Why not try something like the old-fashioned debate,
with the format left up to the candidates themselves, volleying
back and forth with statements and questions? Gore was right to say
that more debates would be better for the public. It would also
facilitate understanding to make the television time available
free. There is a role for television ads and stump speeches, but
there is no substitute for give-and-take among candidates
emphasizing their differences with each other. That is what a
political campaign is supposed to be. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 2232EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0392 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4852 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-IRS-FAVORITISM-1STLD-     12-20 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRS-FAVORITISM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER IRS OFFICIAL ALLEGES FAVORITISM FOR THE WELL-CONNECTED
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Adds comments from Al Davis' spokesman and tax attorney.) 
(jw) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The top Internal Revenue Service official here
repeatedly gave wealthy and politically connected taxpayers
unwarranted breaks including reduced tax bills, a refund and
deferred payments in 1996 and 1997, the government's former chief
tax collector for the district testified Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Coons, tax collection chief for Northern California from
1995 until he was removed in February 1998, testified at a hearing
where he is trying to get his job back under a federal law that
protects whistle-blowers.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS contends that Coons was dismissed for looking at 253 Web
sites on his government computer, most of them travel or stock
market sites, but five of them featuring images of naked women. It
also says he initially lied to investigators about this.
</P>
<P>
   Coons, 55, has acknowledged some ``stupid'' misuse of the
computer, but says the charges are a smoke screen to obscure the
real reason for his removal. He says he stood in the way of a
pattern of favoritism for the wealthy, especially those represented
by former IRS executives and federal prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   No names of taxpayers were mentioned in Monday's testimony
before an administrative law judge for the Merit Systems Protection
Board, Phillip Reed. But records in the case show that the
taxpayers to whom Coons is referring include Al Davis, owner of the
Oakland Raiders football team; members of the Alioto family, whose
patriarch was mayor here in the 1960s; and a diamond company,
Golden ADA, which the federal government says was a Russian
diamond-for-cash money-laundering operation.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Alioto Jr. said that his family had a years-long dispute
with the IRS that included the sale of one brother's home and the
seizure of his mother's car, but that ``we never sought any special
treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Davis, Amy Trask, said ``neither Mr. Davis or
the Oakland Raiders received or sought special treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We only asked for fairness and civility,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Lipton, Davis' tax lawyer, said he could not imagine any
reason to remove Coons from his post over the tax dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Coons said that in the Russian money-laundering case, he was
repeatedly urged to back off both by representatives of the company
and by federal prosecutors, the State Department and Russian
officials.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he complained repeatedly to Robert Ah Nee, the IRS
district director here, about these and other actions he considered
improper, but that Ah Nee just shrugged and said nothing. Coons
said one taxpayer who owed millions of dollars and had substantial
income received a major tax break, over his objections, to Ah Nee _
partly by threatening to go to the Senate Finance Committee, which
at the time was investigating the IRS. Public records show that the
testimony concerned Davis' tax case.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview earlier, Coons said that Ah Nee and his deputy,
Peggy Rule, told him not to enforce collections in another case
because seizing a mansion and selling it would ``create bad
publicity for the IRS, and we don't need that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them it would make every working stiff see that we
treated the rich the same way we treat them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that after this, the two officials cooled toward him.
</P>
<P>
   Coons said subordinates, in another case, brought him two years
of tax returns and a refund check for nearly $100,000, saying that
Ah Nee had personally ordered the check be issued. The subordinates
told Coons that they regarded the returns as fraudulent. Coons said
he went to Ah Nee to complain, but was told that his opinion did
not matter and that the issuing of the check would be delegated to
another official.
</P>
<P>
   An IRS lawyer, Richard Slizeski, through questioning of
witnesses Monday and Friday, sought to portray Coons as an
opportunist who, only after he was caught misusing his computer,
tried to refashion a series of routine disagreements into something
more.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Jensen, the IRS executive who demoted Coons in August,
testified that he regarded him as a whistle-blower, but that the
misuse of his computer and his denials were so serious that it left
him with no other choice.
</P>
<P>
   Reed refused to allow testimony by Frank Miceli, the IRS
compliance chief in the Western region. Mary Dryovage, Coons'
lawyer, wanted Miceli to testify that any punishment greater than a
two-week suspension was unwarranted and to discuss Coons' track
record as one of the most highly regarded executives in the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   Although Coons has been dismissed as chief tax collector in
Northern California, he still collects money for the IRS _ for the
federal charity drive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
