<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4855 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CELLPHONE-COMPETE-2TA     12-20 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELLPHONE-COMPETE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING THE FIELD FOR THE BEST CELLPHONE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Imelda Marcos picking out yet another pair of shoes.
Patricia Duff running through five teams of divorce lawyers. Donald
Trump and his succession of leggy blondes. In the annals of the
fickle, some people are giants.
</P>
<P>
   But alas, even among ordinary mortals, there has never been a
shortage of caprice, whether in matters of the heart or the head,
or in these modern times, matters close to the ear and the lips.
That is to say, telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, countless people jilt their phone companies and then
embrace another in a kind of mating ritual that makes marketing
executives stare at their ceilings at night. There are usually few
warning signs before the split. It's not as if most callers can
complain of egregious lapses like being cut off in midsentence.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, after years of being stuck with one or two choices,
telephone customers have suddenly become the belles of the ball.
They are courted by dozens of phone companies, each dangling
enticements like free calling time, frequent-flier miles and $100
checks that come unsolicited in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a kind of game that you play,'' said Ninon Rogers, 27, an
actress in Greenwich Village who has switched phone companies five
times in five years. ``It is worth it because you get the same
service for less money _ and sometimes outright cash.''
</P>
<P>
   A quick glance at Ms. Rogers' dance card: She signed up with
Sprint in 1995, but was lured away by a $100 check from AT&AMP;T. In
1997, she bit at MCI's offer of 3,000 frequent-flier miles on
Continental Airlines, but then settled again for Sprint because the
international rates were lower. Last year, she was wooed back to
AT&AMP;T with the 10 cents-a-minute plan for domestic calls.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rogers is just the sort of disloyal customer who has helped
stimulate a fierce competition in the telecommunications industry
and drive the cost of phone calls down to just a few pennies per
minute. A recent marketing survey of 12,185 households by J.D.
Power &AMP; Associates showed that 31 percent switched their
long-distance service at least once this year compared with 26
percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the industry has created its own monster because
companies keep topping each other,'' said Kirk Parsons, director of
telecommunications accounts at J.D. Power. ``Brand loyalty doesn't
matter any more; what drives the consumer is cost. The way the rate
is going down, in a couple of years, long distance is going to be
free.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite. But in this freewheeling buyer's market for
telephone service, New Yorkers seeking to play the field have never
had so many suitors _ or so many tangled offers that seem to
promise one thing and turn out to be quite another.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, AT&AMP;T, MCI Worldcom, Sprint and a host of
upstart companies have leased local lines from Bell Atlantic and
started offering what is basically the same service. They have
dangled sign-up bonuses like two free hours every month for six
months (AT&AMP;T), a three-hour phone card picturing two cuddly polar
bears (MCI Worldcom), frequent-flier miles and a $10 credit at
Radio Shack stores (Sprint).
</P>
<P>
   They have pursued new customers in unlikely places. At the New
York City Marathon last month, Sprint banners heralded an unlimited
local calling plan while workers passed out cellular phones for
runners to make free calls. A local competitor, Z-Line, gave out
key chains and glossy cards that read, ``Rudy. Hillary. Z-Line. New
Yorkers love a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web site Priceline.com, after letting customers name a price
for airline tickets, hotel rooms and groceries, plans to do the
same thing early next year for long-distance rates. Customers will
be able to buy blocks of time from companies willing to match their
bids.
</P>
<P>
   But all these options leave some consumers simply flustered.
They complain that calling plans are convoluted and seem to benefit
those who scramble for the best deal rather than those who stand by
their plan. Slick advertising campaigns leave out crucial details
like monthly fees and restrictions on calling times.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are busy, and the phone companies take advantage,''
said Cindy McIntyre, publisher of The Frugal Gazette in Newtown,
Conn., who advises her readers to call the phone companies every
six months for the latest offers.
</P>
<P>
   Even Jules Polonetsky, the commissioner of consumer affairs for
New York City, seemed baffled by it all. He spent 45 minutes last
month comparing his phone plan with half a dozen others before
throwing up his hands. ``It's more complicated than applying for a
mortgage,'' Polonetsky declared, after ending up where he started:
with his current company, Excel.
</P>
<P>
   Some people are just looking for a down-to-earth relationship
with their phone company, but that is increasingly hard to find.
Lawrence Whiteside, 63, a building consultant in Clinton Hill,
Brooklyn, was nearly persuaded to switch by a letter from AT&AMP;T that
promised 75 hours of local calling and 7 cents a minute for
long-distance calls, all for $24.90 a month. He had to call the
company to find out that phone charges were rounded up to the next
minute and that his fax line would cost extra. ``I don't want to
spend half an hour going through a bill,'' Whiteside said. ``That's
too much like work.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Like Whiteside, most phone customers stay faithful to the
company they know, if only because switching seems like too much
trouble. For instance, Judy Langer, 58, a focus-group moderator in
Manhattan, routinely ducks calls from telemarketers. ``I'm not a
comparison shopper,'' said Ms. Langer, who spends about $50 a month
with MCI Worldcom. ``It's a relatively minor expense, and we've
been satisfied with the quality of service.
</P>
<P>
   But an increasing number of people, either because they have
more time, or less money, or both, are on the prowl for better
deals. They scour the mail for the latest offers and compare notes
with their friends. Several self-styled phone experts have even set
up Web sites comparing pricing plans.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Sayers, an advertising sales manager from Martinez, Calif.,
runs 10-10phonerates.com _ a Web site he created last May to
compare 10-10 dial-in numbers that charge by the call without
requiring a monthly fee.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some bargain hunters can be downright bashful about their
obsession. John Williams, 32, switched from AT&AMP;T to MCI Worldcom in
October after calculating that he would save $10 a month, or $120 a
year. But he hesitates to brag about it for fear that he will sound
like a ``cheap date.''
</P>
<P>
   Others offer no apologies for their love-'em-and-leave-'em
attitude toward phone service. Arlene Burgos, 27, a lawyer in
Manhattan, said she saved hundreds of dollars by switching phone
companies every six months in law school, raking in $100 checks and
ever-lower rates.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Ms. Rogers, the actress, has been quarreling with AT&AMP;T
over the $4.95 monthly fee for her discount rate. When she
complains, the company removes it from her bill to keep her from
leaving. Several months later, the fee will quietly reappear. Then
she picks up the phone again.
</P>
<P>
   When the day comes that AT&AMP;T refuses to drop the charge, she
knows she will have to make good on her threat. ``Ultimately, the
reason I'd be switching is to switch back to AT&AMP;T at a later
date,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Spurned companies, Ms. Rogers confided, always offer the best
deals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
