<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREY-FIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE DESTROYS PALATIAL HOME ONCE OWNED BY MARIAH CAREY  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEDFORD, N.Y. _ When the singer Mariah Carey and Tommy Mottola,
the chairman of Sony Music Entertainment, moved into their
22,000-square-foot house that was built here in 1993, it was
described with nothing but superlatives.
</P>
<P>
   It was the biggest house imaginable, people in town said, with
the fanciest recording studio, the prettiest ballroom, the deepest
man-made pond and the oddest indoor shooting range. When the couple
divorced and sold the house to a neighbor in 1997, the red brick
Georgian mansion set a new record: at $20 million, it became the
most expensive house sale in Westchester County history. Now the
house has set its last record. It burned to the ground early
Saturday morning, leaving rubble and debris in place of luxury, and
became what is believed to be the most expensive private house fire
on record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only in the past few years would you even have homes that
would approach $20 million,'' said Steven Goldstein, a spokesman
for the Insurance Information Institute, an industry association.
``There have always been manor houses, but only recently have we
seen the drastic increase in land value and the building of these
gargantuan homes. It appears to be the most expensive single family
home fire ever.''
</P>
<P>
   The next most expensive private home fire was in 1998, when a $7
million, 9,000-square-foot home burned to the ground in California,
Goldstein said.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the fire on Saturday has not been determined, said
Richard T. Hooker, second assistant chief of the Mount Kisco
Volunteer Fire Department. The house was under renovation and
vacant when two security guards in a separate house on the 50-acre
estate smelled smoke, heard an alarm and saw flames shooting out of
a second-story window. They called the Fire Department about 1:15
a.m. on Saturday, but flames had already engulfed the house when
the first engines got to the wooded hilltop estate, Chief Hooker
said. More than 125 firefighters from six departments fought the
blaze for the next several hours, but piles of debris were all that
remained of the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to have to go through layer and layer of debris
before they can determine the cause of the fire,'' Hooker said.
``Nothing has been ruled out.''
</P>
<P>
   The home's new owners, Nelson and Claudia Peltz, had not planned
to move in until next year, their lawyer, Neale M. Albert, said.
Peltz, the chairman and chief executive of Triarc Cos., which owns
Snapple Beverages, the Arby's fast-food chain and Royal Crown Cola,
and his wife live in a home that sits on a 106-acre estate next to
the house that burned down.
</P>
<P>
   ``They poured a lot of their thinking and emotion and energy
into that house,'' Albert said of the Peltzes. ``They are extremely
sad. When they bought the house, it was built for a couple, and the
Peltzes have six children, so they needed to do extensive
renovations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Peltzes have wrangled with town officials in the past over
their private helicopter, which Peltz uses to commute to Manhattan,
40 miles away. The Town of Bedford is suing the couple in State
Supreme Court saying they are violating an ordinance banning
landings and takeoffs of private aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The Peltzes say they should be allowed to use their Sikorsky
six-seater helicopter because private airplanes were used on the
property by its previous owners, and there was a hangar on the
property when they bought it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 2242EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
