<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0396 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4859 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-RAPTORS-CARTER-2T     12-20 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RAPTORS-CARTER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAPTORS' CARTER IS AN NBA ACROBAT WITH FEET ON THE GROUND
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Dell Curry rifled the inbound pass from halfcourt, a
bullet that careered off the right side of the backboard. The ball
looked awfully misguided until Vince Carter, the Toronto Raptors'
spectacular forward, came streaking in from the right wing,
perfectly timing and catching the ricochet. Spectators in the Air
Canada Center looked on in awe as he tried to cradle it between his
right palm and wrist _ before losing the ball, and his most recent
chance at video immortality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince is making stuff up in midair,''' Kobe Bryant said
Sunday. ``I asked him afterward what he was thinking. He just
laughed. Catching a halfcourt pass off the glass and dunking?
That's crazy stuff. I haven't even tried that one yet.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a new prince in the National Basketball Association's
young acrobats club. He is 22 years old and 6 feet 6 inches tall
and spends much of his work life above the rim. He pirouetted 360
degrees last season and helicopter-dunked, but that's almost passe
now, outmoded by an assortment of windmills and lean-ins. As the
hyperbole and the highlights grow, so, too, do Carter's chances of
making the United States team for next year's Olympic Games as a
12th man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' inquired John Salley, the veteran Lakers forward.
``He's already one of the top five talents in the league. Everyone
knows it. They just don't want to tell him yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter managed a rueful smile when he heard of the compliments,
moments after the Raptors lost their third straight game and as
Toronto prepared to play host to the Nets on Tuesday night before
traveling to Madison Square Garden on Wednesday to face the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   He had just got caught up in a little egocentric game of
one-on-one with Bryant, another young flier who the National
Basketball Association is hoping will fill the post-Jordan void.
After the game ended, the two hugged as if they had just finished a
soft-drink commercial rather than a one-sided contest won by the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it is easy to forget that Carter's main job is seeing
that Toronto keeps winning and functioning as a team rather than
operating as a vehicle to market this young, improvisational player
whose misses are often as breathtaking as his makes. He is
averaging 23 points, seventh in the league, for a team that is
13-11.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets to me sometimes, but I have a lot of people around me
to keep me grounded,'' Carter said. ``I've got guys on this team
that let me know if we don't win, all that other stuff doesn't
matter. I'm learning.''
</P>
<P>
   He took several ill-advised shots and was 11 of 28 from the
field, but Carter also provided some of the best theater on Sunday.
Going past Glen Rice and Shaquille O'Neal in the fourth quarter, he
converted a wild, twisting reverse layup. Last season, when he was
named rookie of the year and rejuvenated an expansion franchise
known more for its cornball mascot than its play, he force-fed
Alonzo Mourning a dunk in his face.
</P>
<P>
   Against San Antonio earlier this month, Carter erupted for 39
points and one of the most scintillating moves of the season.
Blowing by Mario Elie on the left baseline, Carter rose up and
appeared to be challenging Tim Duncan's reach. Just as Duncan was
about to meet him, Carter contorted his body until he slithered
underneath the center and put the ball in softly off the glass.
</P>
<P>
   Though it came from a different angle, it vaguely resembled a
play in the 1990 NBA finals, when another 6-6 player who had left
North Carolina after his junior year appeared as if he were going
to dunk over the top of the Lakers, but instead switched to his
left hand for a layup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Michael Jordan comparison is something he's been dealing
with since high school,'' said Carter's mother and full-time
business manager, Michelle Carter-Robinson. ``On one hand, it's
very flattering. You can't overlook the similarities. By the same
token, it gets a little old, too. Vince gets tired of hearing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean Smith was often said to be the only coach who could contain
Jordan, with a structured program at North Carolina that
de-emphasized individual theatrics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just look at all the guys that have been through Carolina,''
Carter said in reference to Smith's influence. ``Myself, Jerry
Stackhouse, we all didn't score many points.'' Carter, in fact,
never averaged more than 15.6 points a game at North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we blossomed later,'' he said. ``We're prepared to blossom
by the time we get to the NBA. I think when you get here, you
realize, hey, what you were taught and what you were so-called held
back from, here's what he was teaching you.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter sees the game with amazing clarity for such an
inexperienced player, understanding the nuances of angles, the arc
on his shot, the spin of the ball. In fact, as evidenced by his
catnaps during games, it is almost as if the game is coming too
easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the time I've been around great players, at times they get
so bored they'll just try things,'' said Butch Carter, Toronto's
third-year coach and a veteran of NBA six seasons as a player. ``It
happened when I was around Magic and Isiah at different parts of my
career. And I just have to go through that with Vince. The great
thing about him is he'll let me bring him back to earth. I was
around Magic and Isiah at different parts of my career. And I just
have to go through that with Vince. The great thing about him is
he'll let me bring him back to earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince listens to Oak,'' Butch Carter said, referring to the
veteran power forward Charles Oakley, Vince Carter's on-court
protector and off-court counselor. ``If Oak tells him something was
wrong and he handled it wrong, he listens to him. He doesn't tell
Oak, `You're crazy' or `Get away from me; I don't care how many
years you played in the league.' He's a young person that respects
information.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammate Antonio Davis said: ``You fight the bad decisions
with him. In some instances, what can you say? It's like you're
yelling at him not to take the shot and then he hits it and you're
giving him a high-five. What do you do?''
</P>
<P>
   Vince Carter admitted: ``Sometimes I think I don't play hard for
four quarters or I kind of get lost out there sometimes. I know
that. I just have to continue to play through what's going on out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   He takes criticism from elders constructively rather than
imagining some challenge against his manhood. Carter spent time
Sunday giving a motivational talk to 14 teen-agers after a tough
loss. He moves home to Florida during the summer, makes his bed and
takes out the garbage, ``just little things like that that reminds
the player that you're still a young man, that you still have
responsibilities, that you're not bigger than life or bigger than
basketball,'' his mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter-Robinson was a 21-year teaching veteran of Florida's
public schools before she retired two years ago to concentrate on
her son's career. ``You've got parents here who are not intimidated
by the NBA,'' she said. ``He's my son first and an NBA player
second. I'm still Mama. And I've been around the block a few times
more than he has, so he still listens to me.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Carter has also become the center of a strictly monitored
business and marketing enterprise. Among his diverse interests,
Carter owns a company called Business in Flight.
</P>
<P>
   His mother said Carter had more than 20 people employed to
nurture and market his image, including three publicists whose main
job is to coordinate a master schedule with the Raptors.
</P>
<P>
   He just finished a two-week stretch that included more than five
dozen interviews, a Gatorade commercial shoot and a homecoming in
Orlando, Fla., in which he and members of his foundation passed out
food baskets to needy families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Night in and out, I can't get caught up in all that,'' he
said. ``Of course, you know you're going to disappoint some people.
I just try to give to as many people as I can. I'm a human, also. I
need time to rest, time to myself. I can't be everywhere at once.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his whirlwind schedule, Carter is well grounded, his
coach said. ``He doesn't have 20 friends from his old
neighborhood,'' said Butch Carter, who is not related to his star
player. ``Everyone working for him is a specialist in certain
areas. Team Carter is unbelievable. I call Mrs. Robinson `Canada's
First Mother.'''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said: ``Some of the time I hear him talking and some of
the things he had to do after practice or something he had to
before practice, it's like, wow. And you still made it to practice
on time, you got your work in after practice? That's tough, trying
to lift your team and sell the league at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to help the league by being himself. He's doing a
great job of it. Michael Jordan is the perfect example. He didn't
start winning championships until he started depending upon the
guys around him, making the guys around him better to make him
better. Vince is going to understand that. It's just going to take
some time. ``
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
