<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4861 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHANGES-AD-COLUMN-NYT     12-20 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHANGES-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: THREE WEDDINGS AND A FUNERAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three acquisitions and an agency's closing are making news.
</P>
<P>
   In the largest of the acquisitions, Interpublic Group of Cos. in
New York, which owns agencies like Draft Worldwide, Lowe Group and
McCann-Erickson World Group, agreed Monday to buy NFO Worldwide
Inc. in Stamford, Conn., a leading market research company.
</P>
<P>
   The stock deal is valued at about $580 million.
</P>
<P>
   Interpublic is the world's No. 2 agency company in revenue, at
$4.3 billion behind Omnicom Group, according to the trade
publication Advertising Age, and is No. 1 in billings at $37.7
billion. NFO is to operate as a stand-alone autonomous unit of
Interpublic, perhaps as part of its Allied Communications Group
division.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition vaults Interpublic into the front ranks of the
market research field, which is booming because of the demand for
data related to interactive advertising. In fact, NFO describes
itself as the single largest provider of Internet-based marketing
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider market research an area of opportunity,'' said
Sean Orr, executive vice president and chief financial officer at
Interpublic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arguably, it was a bit of a hole in our portfolio of service
offerings. We're delighted to have that hole closed.''
</P>
<P>
   While Interpublic owns some small market research companies, it
has not been as large a force in that field as the WPP Group in
London, which has assiduously assembled an array of such
operations, primarily through acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted a significantly larger presence, ideally globally,''
said Barry Linsky, senior vice president for planning and business
development at Interpublic. ``With NFO, we're gaining the size and
scope and a terrific brand.''
</P>
<P>
   NFO was originally known as National Family Opinion, after a
unit that polls consumers through surveys sent out under the name
Carol Adams _ an imaginary woman who could be considered the Betty
Crocker of market research. NFO, founded in 1946, has about 4,000
employees in 35 countries providing custom and syndicated marketing
information to more than 3,000 clients; annual revenue is estimated
at more than $425 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great strategic fit between two global leaders,'' said
William Lipner, chairman, chief executive and president at NFO,
``reaffirming the convergence of advertising agencies and market
research firms.''
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal call for NFO shareholders to receive $26 worth
of Interpublic stock for each NFO share they own. On the New York
Stock Exchange, NFO stock closed Friday at $14 and closed Monday at
$22.25, up $8.25. Interpublic shares, traded on the same exchange,
fell $2.3125 Monday, to $55.75.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition was announced as NFO warned that it expected a
significant shortfall in earnings during the current quarter, far
below the predictions of Wall Street analysts, and would take
fourth-quarter after-tax charges of $15 million to $20 million.
Interpublic was aware of those developments before making the deal,
Linsky and Orr said.
</P>
<P>
   The second acquisition involves Modem Media.Poppe Tyson in
Norwalk, Conn., an Internet advertising agency and Web site
creator, which agreed to buy Vivid Studios in San Francisco, a Web
site creator and consultant, for $64 million in cash and stock.
Modem Media.Poppe Tyson is partly owned by True North
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Vivid, which has about 100 employees, is
meant to help Modem Media.Poppe Tyson develop e-commerce sites more
efficiently and effectively. It will be the third deal in recent
months for Modem Media.Poppe Tyson, whose shares closed Monday at
$64.375, down $1.375, in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   The third acquisition involves Powers &AMP; Associates in
Cincinnati, which agreed to buy another agency there, Sive/Young &AMP;
Rubicam. Terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Sive/Y&AMP;R has 24 employees working on accounts with billings
estimated at $42 million from clients like Frisch's Restaurants,
Mercy Health Partners and the U.S. Playing Card Co. Powers has
about 26 employees and clients like American Savings and Loan and
Progressive Insurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   The merged agency will operate under the Powers name, with
Charles Powers, 62, continuing as president. Michael Kitei, 62,
president and chief executive at Sive/Y&AMP;R, will serve as a
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new agency will be a long-held dream come true,'' Powers
said, referring to his attempt in 1977 to acquire the old Sive
agency, only to be outbid by Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. in New York.
Sive/Y&AMP;R remained part of Y&AMP;R until 1994, when five managers bought
90 percent of the agency. Sive/Y&AMP;R is being acquired from current
management and Y&AMP;R, which is selling its 10 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the agency that is closing, effective immediately, is
Mulryan/Nash, a small New York shop specializing in campaigns aimed
at gay and lesbian consumers. Clients included Agouron
Pharmaceuticals, part of Warner-Lambert Co., and Subaru of America,
a unit of Fuji Heavy Industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no one thing'' that led to the decision, said Dave
Mulryan, president at Mulryan/Nash, adding that he could not
comment further.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter addressed to ``valued customers, vendors and
friends,'' Mulryan wrote that ``harsh financial circumstances
beyond our control'' led to the closing. Inquiries were referred to
Geron &AMP; Corsano, a New York law firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it's a bad situation not typical of other agencies
specializing in the gay market,'' said Sean Strub, chairman of Poz
Publishing LLC in New York, `it's a black mark on the gay market.''
He estimated that his company was owed about $125,000 for ad space
that Mulryan/Nash bought for clients in Poz and Poz en Espanol
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Agouron, which extensively advertises an AIDS drug, Viracept, in
publications read by gay men, sent letters to those magazines and
newspapers expressing regret over ``the unfortunate circumstances
of the agency closing.'' The letter notified the publications that
Rivendell Marketing in New York and Westfield, N.J., would take
over media duties from Mulryan/Nash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sorry to see Mulryan/Nash go,'' said Todd Evans, chief
executive at Rivendell, adding that he did not think the agency's
difficulties were indicative of the health of the overall market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies have a commitment to the gay market,'' said Evans,
who sells ad space in gay and lesbian publications in local markets
nationwide. ``Our business was up 30 percent this year, and we
expect another banner year next year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
