r a BC-BURLINGTON-MERGER-1ST     12-20 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURLINGTON-MERGER-1STLD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURLINGTON NORTHERN, CANADIAN NATIONAL AGREE TO MERGER
</HEADLINE>
 
(ADDS overline) (DUPLICATION ALERT: Story also moving in ``f'' financial news
category) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MITCHELL SCHNURMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ In a move intended to provide seamless
service along growing trade corridors, Burlington Northern Santa Fe
and the Canadian National Railway said Monday that they have agreed
to combine operations.
</P>
<P>
   The deal creates the largest rail company in North America, with
its headquarters and leadership to be based in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   The companies said there will be little disruption for employees
or shippers because the rail networks do not overlap.
</P>
<P>
   Burlington Northern, which moved to Fort Worth from St. Paul,
Minn., in 1984, employs about 3,200 in Fort Worth, including 2,500
at its corporate headquarters. Executives said the combined company
will maintain a major presence in North Texas, including its
dispatch center.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the structuring of the deal, which gives a
majority of top management posts to Canadian National officials,
satisfies protectionist laws in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the rail companies employ about 67,000 in two
countries, and executives said that only a few thousand jobs will
be lost, probably through attrition.
</P>
<P>
   The merger requires approval from regulators and shareholders in
the United States and Canada, and executives said they do not
expect to complete the transaction until mid-2001.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, a new holding company will be created, to be called
North American Railways. It would generate more than $12.5 billion
in annual revenue, and its 50,000 miles of track would cover much
of the continent.
</P>
<P>
   The system would stretch from Los Angeles to Halifax, Nova
Scotia, and from Vancouver to the Texas Gulf Coast. It would be
especially strong, analysts said, along the north-south corridors
that connect Mexico, Canada and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   That has become a busy route since the North American Free Trade
Agreement was approved early this decade, and traffic is expected
to grow sharply.
</P>
<P>
   ``A map of this new railroad is truly incredible,'' said Robert
Krebs, Burlington's chief executive, during a news conference in
Montreal. ``This is a perfect time for us to get together.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies did not put a value on the deal, saying it was a
tax-free stock swap that does not pay a premium to shareholders of
either company.
</P>
<P>
   Burlington investors will receive one share in North American
Railways for each share in BNSF, while Canadian investors will get
1.05 shares. Burlington shareholders will control about two-thirds
of the stock in the new company.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the companies have a total market value topping $18
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street reacted negatively to the deal, however, pushing
down the stock prices of both rail operators. In late trading at
4:15 p.m. Monday, Burlington's stock was down $3.5625, to $24.8125.
Canadian's stock fell $1.35 (Canadian) to $42.85 (Canadian) on the
Toronto exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the deal does not provide enough of a premium to
Burlington investors. And they noted that Canadian's top executive,
Paul Tellier, will be at the helm of the holding company, with his
associates making up most of the staff.
</P>
<P>
   When the deal closes, Krebs said he will become non-executive
chairman of the new company. Matthew Rose, currently president of
Burlington, will add the title of chief executive of Burlington
Northern Santa Fe, and is expected to remain at the Fort Worth
office.
</P>
<P>
   Another Burlington official, chief financial officer Thomas
Hund, will become CFO of North American.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-member board of directors will include six members from
each company, plus three appointees.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of the rail companies said that the merger
willbenefit shareholders over the long-term by providing more
growth opportunities and lower operating costs.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts, noting the long regulatory process, said the gains
will be far down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``In three to five years, this will be the premier freight
railroad in North America,'' Terry Gardner, an analyst at Deutsche
Banc Alex Brown, told TheStreet.com. ``But the issue here is
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies plan to submit their business plans to regulators
within 90 days. The U.S. Surface Transportation Board may review
the plans for as long as a year, officials said. A Canadian court,
which considers both the payout to shareholders and regulatory
laws, also must approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian National was a state railway until the government sold
it to the public in a 1995 stock offering. Executives acknowledged
that this deal was structured to meet Canadian rules that still
govern the business.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the new company's headquarters will be in Montreal;
a majority of its directors will be Canadian citizens; and no
single company will control 15 percent of the stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many Canadians, there's always a concern about `sleeping
with the elephant,' '' said Tony Hine, managing director of
National Bank Financial in Toronto. ``Economic nationalism is still
a big factor in Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, one reporter asked whether a Canadian
company is being ``Americanized.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the Americanization of CN,'' said Tellier,
Canadian National's chief executive. ``This is transforming CN into
a true North American company, while retaining a very strong
Canadian identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Krebs quickly cited the Montreal headquarters, the makeup of the
board, and the fact that Tellier, a Canadian, will be CEO.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been extremely sensitive to that very issue,'' Krebs
said.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter added that Canadian law required those
concessions, Krebs added: ``It's the right thing to do, and we're
very happy to do it. Or we wouldn't be involved in this deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The rail industry has always been marked by mergers, as
companies sought to expand their markets, offer better service and
boost profits.
</P>
<P>
   The Burlington-Canadian deal was driven by similar factors,
Krebs and Tellier said. In the first three years as a combined
company, they expect to generate as much as $600 million in
additional operating income by pulling in new business and cutting
costs.
</P>
<P>
   They talked about offering automakers a single rail line to
reach from Ontario and Detroit into California and Mexico. Other
routes would entice chemical makers from the Gulf Coast and lumber
companies in Canada, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What shippers want is seamless service with a single line,''
Tellier said. ``They want to deal with one bill, one invoice, one
account manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trucking's already there,'' he added. ``Now we want to be
fully integrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Shippers signalled some skepticism. Major mergers have rocked
the rail industry in this decade, often disrupting traffic as
companies tried to blend their computer systems and far-flung rail
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Union Pacific and Southern Pacific, along with Norfolk
Southern and CSX, have struggled to integrate lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do we need another mega-merger when the industry is
already having trouble providing reliable service?'' said Ed
Emmett, president of the National Industrial Transportation League,
a trade group that represents shippers. ``We don't need it now.''
</P>
<P>
   (Star-Telegram writer Dan Reed contributed to this report. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
