<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4864 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-GENDERGAP-AZR &LR;      12-20 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENDERGAP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN WOOING WOMEN VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John McCain's call to arms for political reform has rallied men
to his cause, but the very intensity that is making his campaign
effective in New Hampshire may also have a downside with Republican
women, polls show.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Texas Gov. George W. Bush is attracting female GOP
voters by a significant margin. Poll results comparing the
preferences of men and women in early primary states show that,
although many women respect McCain, they express a clear preference
for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of this gender gap, McCain is turning increasingly in his
policy addresses to domestic issues that are of concern to both
sexes but traditionally of more interest to women, including
education, the environment and Social Security _ all issues Bush
has been speaking to for months.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, McCain interrupted a swing through veteran-haven
South Carolina to make his pitch on a women's Web site,
iVillage.com, and on Monday he outlined an environmental agenda in
a speech in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Personality also appears to play a role in the perception of
women voters.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Eaton, a Bush supporter and small-business owner from
Phoenix, said Bush is probably ``a little bit smoother'' than
McCain. And he focuses on the issues that are near and dear to
women, such as education.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's some kind of a softness,'' Eaton said. ``He isn't trying
to show off or be cute, he's just an appealing kind of a person.''
</P>
<P>
   She said McCain appeals to different priorities.
</P>
<P>
   `McCain is a little bit more of a rough and tumble man's man,''
Eaton said. `He's been in the service . . . and he's very vocal
about that.`
</P>
<P>
   In most key primary states, Bush retains a considerable lead
among women.
</P>
<P>
   A ``Washington Post'' survey conducted Dec. 12-15 in New
Hampshire showed Bush leading McCain 49 to 32 percent among women,
while McCain led Bush among men 46 to 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A mid-November CNN/Time poll in South Carolina indicated that
among men, Bush led McCain among women 66 to 11 percent, and he
also led McCain among men, 59 to 19 percent. &QL; 
Bush focuses on education &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with ``The Arizona Republic,'' Bush pinned his
advantage among women voters on his focus on education and his
unwillingness to take the usual hard-line stand on illegal
immigration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's probably because I've got a record on education
that is substantiated by results, that people know I'm passionate
for education,'' Bush said. ``And I think people recognize I'm
someone who has resisted bashing immigrants; that while I believe
in enforcing the border, I understand the motivations of why people
come to America to put food on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush aides are quick to note that they employ more women in top
positions than almost any other campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Among Bush's top advisers are his foreign policy guru Condoleeza
Rice, national political director Maria Cino, communications
director Karen Hughes, and by Bush's count, his wife, Laura. &QL; 
MCCAIN HAS FEW WOMEN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   y contrast, McCain employs few women in top spots. Among them
is Deb Gullett, a deputy campaign aide who works in McCain's
Phoenix office but who is considered one of his closest advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, McCain's aides are confident that he is making up the
difference with women.
</P>
<P>
   ``As voters learn more about John McCain, those gender numbers
tend to even out,'' said Dan Schnur, McCain's communications
director, noting that in recent weeks, polls in New Hampshire have
shown dramatic increases in female support for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing that voters found out about John McCain was
his war record and his time in Vietnam, and that tended to move
male voters more than females, in particular older voters who may
have served themselves,'' Schnur said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second thing that voters are learning about John McCain is
his support for campaign-finance reform, and that tends to appeal
to female voters more than male.''
</P>
<P>
   The contrasts extend to the way the two candidates campaign.
Bush has loaded up the airwaves with ads that show him surrounded
with children. McCain has ads featuring his time as a prisoner of
war in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has mastered the art of the gentle shoulder shrug and
occasionally winks at those around him. McCain campaigns
frenetically and sometimes punches the air with his fist when his
speech becomes animated. &QL; 
`PASSION ISN'T THERE' &QL; 
Campaign observers say that for McCain to begin closing the
distance with women, he must be able to sell them on his commitment
to their issues.
</P>
<P>
   So far, in the presidential debates, McCain has appeared less
than gung-ho on domestic concerns, according to Sherry Bebitch
Jeffe, a political scientist at the Claremont University in
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``The passion isn't there,'' Bebitch Jeffe said of McCain. ``It
is with Bush. He may be rote on many other issues, but he's not on
education.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's near singular focus on campaign finance reform and
national defense and national security to the exclusion of other
issue bucks ``the history of polling on women's attitudes, which is
that women tend to be doves,'' Jeffe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't like aggression, they don't like war, they don't
like change, and they don't like risk,'' Bebitch Jeffe said. &QL; 
SINKHOLE FOR GOP &QL; 
The gender gap turned into a sinkhole for Republicans in 1996, as
they watched women desert the party's standard bearer, Bob Dole, in
droves to vote for Bill Clinton. That year, Clinton held an
11-point advantage over Dole with women. In 1992, Bush's father
lost out to Clinton in part due to a four-point gender advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he believes the 1996 loss was due in large part to the
gender gap, and the ``generational'' gap between Dole and the baby
boomers who have come to dominate American elections. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
