<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-XMAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEVER MIND SANTA CLAUS, WHO BELIEVES IN VIRGINIA THESE DAYS?  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Curiosity led to a row house at 115 West 95th Street,
where one of the best-known sentiments of this holiday season was
born. The idea was to see if anyone knew that Virginia O'Hanlon
once lived there, or even had a clue who she was.
</P>
<P>
   It was a foolish mission. Inquiries produced polite shrugs or
don't-bother-me clicks of the intercom from the few people living
at No. 115. Their reaction should have been anticipated. After all,
this is a city of impermanence; collective memory often lasts about
as long as sand castles at high tide.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one thought that there just might be a plaque or some
other indication that, in this house 102 years ago, an 8-year-old
girl wrote a letter that produced perhaps this country's most
enduring secular affirmation of hope and faith.
</P>
<P>
   Some of her ``little friends'' at school had said there was no
Santa Claus, Virginia O'Hanlon wrote to the editor of The New York
Sun. Could they conceivably be right? In what would become
America's most famous newspaper editorial, Francis Pharcellus
Church of The Sun replied:
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, Virginia, there is a Santa Claus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He exists,'' the editorial continued, ``as certainly as love
and generosity and devotion exist, and you know that they abound
and give to your life its highest beauty and joy.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornball? You bet. Irresistible? That, too.
</P>
<P>
   Generations of open-hearted Americans have thought so (their
numbers including countless newspaper writers who have taken ``Yes,
Virginia'' and pounded it silly, often on the misguided assumption
that they were the first to play with that locution).
</P>
<P>
   You would think that a piece of New York writing of such grace
and durability deserved formal acknowledgment. Surely, something
creative could be figured out by city officials, whose taste in
tributes leans more to renaming streets Senor Wences Way and the
like.
</P>
<P>
   Given the absence of any public recognition, you can hardly
blame the present occupants of No. 115 for drawing a blank. ``Yes,
Virginia'' doesn't always ring a bell with Claus, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never heard of her, to tell you the truth, and I've been
doing this a long time,'' said Bob Williams, a sidewalk Santa for
14 years with Volunteers of America, the helping hand to some of
New York's neediest.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 66, was at his regular post during the weekend, on
Fifth Avenue, facing the Rockefeller Center Christmas tree. He is
something of an expert, he said, on little children and their need
to believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I tell them right up front that I'm not Santa,'' he said.
``I'm Santa's helper, and if they tell me something, I'll pass it
on to the big guy. I don't make promises I can't keep.''
</P>
<P>
   There is wizardry in that red suit, whether you believe it or
not, Williams added. ``When I'm in street clothes, I'm nobody,'' he
said. ``But the minute I put on that suit, I'm somebody. It changes
everything. Even when I go take a break, I can't really take a
break. I get mobbed.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not all magic. To steal from Barbara Basler, formerly
of The New York Times, being Santa can be a tough row to ho.
</P>
<P>
   Children today are more jaded than their older brothers and
sisters, Williams finds. The grown-ups who stuff cash in Santa's
chimney are usually tourists, not New Yorkers, who are too busy
rushing through the canyons of Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones that work in those office buildings there, they don't
give,'' he said. ``The ones that don't have it, give it. The ones
that have it, they walk right by you.''
</P>
<P>
   Sad but true, agreed Linda McNeil, Volunteers of America's
director of development and communications. Altogether, the
Volunteers' eight sidewalk Santas are likely to collect about
$45,000 by Christmas Eve. Even though these are heady days on Wall
Street, the figure has held steady for several years, Ms. McNeil
said.
</P>
<P>
   In general, she said, ``the boom in the economy is not impacting
on our fund-raising at all. There are maybe a few donors who find
it advantageous to unload some stock on us.''
</P>
<P>
   What about all the cyber-generated money floating out there?
``The new wealth,'' Ms. McNeil said, ``has not necessarily been
trained in philanthropy.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Santa is about more than money and gifts. Church of
The Sun knew that, and said so to Virginia O'Hanlon, who died in
1971.
</P>
<P>
   ``How dreary would be the world if there were no Santa Claus!''
he wrote. ``It would be as dreary as if there were no Virginias.
There would be no childlike faith then, no poetry, no romance to
make tolerable this existence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
