<SLUG> BC-JUDGES-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR VOWS TO STALL ACTION ON JUDGESHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A long-running dispute over executive appointments
flared again Monday as a Republican senator said he would block
every one of President Clinton's nominees for federal judgeships
until the president left office.
</P>
<P>
   The senator, James Inhofe of Oklahoma, said he would put
personal ``holds'' on every judicial nominee submitted to the
Senate for confirmation and urge other senators to do the same. The
senator said he was angry because the president recently made a
surprise reappointment to the National Labor Relations Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has broken his word, yet again,'' Inhofe said in
reaction to Clinton's renaming of Sara M. Fox to another five-year
term on the labor board.
</P>
<P>
   The senator said that he had nothing against Ms. Fox, but that
she was not on a list of 13 appointments the White House planned to
make while Congress was in recess.
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman, Jake Siewert, said Monday night that
there was no subterfuge, and that the White House had conferred
with Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the Republican leader. As for
the list cited by Inhofe, Siewert said, ``It doesn't necessarily
correspond to our list.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Senate rules, any senator can put an indefinite hold on a
nominee. A dispute between Democratic and Republican lawmakers
delayed confirmation of dozens of judicial nominees for months
until it was apparently resolved in November. With dozens of
nominations still pending, Inhofe can delay the process again, if
he chooses.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution allows the president to bypass the Senate
confirmation process temporarily by making appointments during a
Congressional recess, with appointees allowed to serve without
confirmation until the end of the following year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
