<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HOLLYWOOD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINCAY'S TITLE ONE FOR THE AGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Nobody should be surprised by anything Laffit Pincay
does anymore. But he was surprised by what he did Monday at
Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the meeting, if you'd have asked me if I
had a chance to be leading rider, I'd have told you `No way,'''
Pincay told the fans in a winner's circle ceremony between races on
the track's closing day.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay, 52, became the oldest man to capture the jockey title at
a major U.S. track, riding winners Ruff Ruckus in the fifth race
and Fantasy Leap in the ninth-race nightcap to finish with a 32-28
edge over Pat Valenzuela.
</P>
<P>
   The victory aboard front-running Ruff Ruckus clinched at least a
tie for the championship. Pincay pumped his right fist as he
crossed the finish in the $12,500 claiming event, a gesture not
unlike the one that accompanied his record 8,834th career win Dec.
10 at Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   Half an hour later, when Valenzuela failed to win the sixth
aboard Montjoy, Pincay had the title outright, marking the 38th
time he'd led the standings at a U.S. track and the first since the
1991 Hollywood Park spring-summer season.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Shoemaker was 44 when he won his last title at the 1975 Oak
Tree meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I won't have too many more chances,'' said Pincay, who
began the day with a 30-28 lead over Valenzuela. ``I'm thinking
about retiring in three or four more years....
</P>
<P>
   ``Breaking the record was the ultimate for me. But this is the
icing on the cake.''
</P>
<P>
   Pincay acknowledged he was helped by the absence of some other
top riders for much of the six-week meet. Still, he was delighted
to have proved he's still one of the circuit's best when he rides
competitive horses. He won with 22.1 percent of his mounts.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy Leap was career win No.8,844.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he would break the record after a while,'' said Mike
Mitchell, who trains Ruff Ruckus. ``But to be the leading rider at
52, that says a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   When Pincay broke Shoemaker's record 11 days ago, Mitchell was
disappointed the momentous winner wasn't one of his horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I got cheated,'' said Mitchell, describing how Pincay's
agent Bob Meldahl had begged out of an agreement to ride one of his
horses (who won) in an earlier race so he could switch to a Bill
Spawr-trained horse (who lost). ``I told Bob before the race, `If
I'd looked the horse up (and read his past performances), I never
would have let you off.' I was kinda semi-mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Pincay's record-setting winner, Irish Nip, was trained by
Richard Mandella.
</P>
<P>
   But Mitchell, who describes himself as ``Laffit's biggest fan,''
got his consolation prize by saddling the title-clincher Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The achievement is his dieting all his life to maintain his
weight, when you know 90 percent of the riders couldn't have done
it. He's muscle on top of muscle,'' Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a weight problem all my life, and I've tried all
sorts of diets, so I know what kind of willpower it takes. I've had
dinner with Laffit and seen him chew a piece of meat and spit it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Pincay, feeling the best he has in years, said he ate an entire
bagel one night recently and was ``scared'' to step on the scale
the next day. But he hadn't gained a pound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing something right,'' he said with a laugh. ``I can't
wait to get home and have another bagel.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottom lines: Hollywood Park reported on-site increases of 2
percent in attendance (7,443 a day) and 11 percent in betting at
its first meet under Churchill Downs management.
</P>
<P>
   ``We caught every break,'' admitted track president Rick
Baedeker, referring to Pincay's record run, plentiful pick-six
carryovers and good weather during the season that opened Nov. 10.
</P>
<P>
   He described a two- to three-year plan to give the 62-year-old
facility's grandstand ``an overdue facelift,'' and a stepped-up
marketing effort.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Corey Nakatani, third in the standings with 27 wins,
rallied New Zealand-bred Accomplice ($10.20) to a 2{-length win
over favored Howbaddouwantit in the Dayjur Handicap turf sprint....
Bob Baffert won the training title, his first at Hollywood Park,
with a 14-11 edge over Richard Mandella.... Bob Ike of the Daily
News led the newspaper handicappers by selecting 80 winners (29.9
percent). &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
