<SLUG> BC-NY-LIBEL-RULING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING IN LIBEL CASE HAILED BY NEW YORK MEDIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a decision that could broaden protection from libel suits,
New York state's highest court issued a ruling Monday making it
more difficult for people to sue news organizations over articles
that disclose details of their private lives provided the articles
raise issues of ``legitimate public concern.''
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous ruling by the state Court of Appeals involved a
libel lawsuit filed by Charles Huggins, the former husband of the
singer Melba Moore, over a series of articles published in The (New
York) Daily News in 1993. The articles chronicled the couple's
bitter divorce and Ms. Moore's accusation that her husband, who was
her manager, had committed ``economic spousal abuse'' by ruining
her career and bankrupting her.
</P>
<P>
   Huggins sued The Daily News and Ms. Moore for $90 million,
asserting that her statements were false, his reputation had been
destroyed and their divorce was a private matter. Monday's ruling
focused on what standard Huggins would have to prove in court to
win his libel case.
</P>
<P>
   The case sets a precedent because lower courts had ruled that
while Ms. Moore was a public figure, her former husband was not.
Under New York law, people deemed public figures must prove that a
news organization's account was malicious before a libel suit can
proceed, but others must prove only that a news organization was
negligent, a lower standard.
</P>
<P>
   In an initial victory for Huggins, the Appellate Division of the
state Supreme Court ruled in April that the couple's divorce was a
private matter and that to win he only needed to prove that The
Daily News had been negligent in printing the articles.
</P>
<P>
   But in its unanimous opinion Monday, the Court of Appeals
reversed that ruling. Judge Howard Levine wrote that because the
articles raised an issue of public concern _ what Ms. Moore called
``the black-on-black crime of economic spousal abuse'' _ Huggins
would have to prove in court that the newspaper was ``grossly
irresponsible'' in printing the articles, a far higher standard.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for The Daily News and other New York news organizations
hailed the decision Monday. ``The net effect of this opinion is
that the flow of information in the state will be protected,'' said
Eve Burton, deputy general counsel for The Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen news organizations, including The New York Times, The
Associated Press, Dow Jones Co., ABC, NBC and CBS filed legal
papers urging the state's highest court to overturn the lower court
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley Rosen, the lawyer representing Huggins, said the ruling
would give the news media free reign to report on people's private
lives and then claim that the articles raised important social
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means that the most private aspects of a person's life
can be reported on and arguably declared a matter of public
concern,'' he said. ``Whether it is a private person's very private
divorce or a person getting a jaywalking ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosen said that Huggins would still go to trial in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Under the state constitution and a series of rulings by the
Court of Appeals, news media in New York generally enjoy far more
protection from libel suits than news organizations in other
states. Richard Winfield, a lawyer for The Associated Press who
drafted the joint legal papers filed by the 16 media organizations,
said there was concern that the appeals court could have eroded
those protections.
</P>
<P>
   But in his opinion, Levine criticized the lower court with
strong language. ``Absent clear abuse, the courts will not
second-guess editorial decisions as to what constitutes matters of
genuine public concern,'' Levine wrote. ``The Appellate Division
did not accord the deference to editorial judgment our decisions
require.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 2310EST &QL; 
