<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETSBIDDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A JETS' BIDDER, WITH NO FANFARE, MAY HAVE AN EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If public renown were a prerequisite to owning a
sports team, Robert Wood Johnson IV would be excluded. But Johnson
is a Jets bidder, competing for the team against better-known
rivals like Charles F. Dolan and Sam Grossman.
</P>
<P>
   Dolan is not a headline grabber, but his company, Cablevision,
controls Madison Square Garden and Radio City Music Hall, tried to
buy the Yankees and is trying to buy the Mets. Grossman is a
garrulous former senatorial candidate in Arizona and game-show
announcer who made his fortune by developing shopping malls. He
tried to buy the Washington Redskins earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Woody Johnson has done none of that. A great-great-grandson
of the founder of Johnson &AMP; Johnson, his name has never come up in
connection with buying a sports franchise, but he is Dolan's most
serious rival to acquire the Jets, for as much as $600 million. His
low profile may prove beguiling to the Leon Hess estate _ the late
owner defined quiet ownership _ especially if he offers the most
cash.
</P>
<P>
   The race for the Jets may end by Jan. 18 when National Football
League owners meet in Manhattan to discuss the sale of the Jets and
49 percent of the Baltimore Ravens, a deal announced Sunday. By
then, Goldman, Sachs, which is handling the Jets sale, is expected
to have picked a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is the chairman of the Johnson Co., a Manhattan
investment firm and philanthropy that serves as his base of
operations. Although a stranger in the sports world, Johnson is
well known in the health care and Republican Party worlds. He is
the chairman of the Juvenile Diabetes Foundation International and
a board member of Robert Wood Johnson University Foundation in
Princeton, N.J., one of the country's largest philanthropies. He
has also given more than $1 million to the Wildlife Conservation
Society, the parent of the Bronx Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   The few news stories that mention Johnson cite his GOP
activities or his attendance at local benefits for the diabetes
foundation, the Bronx Zoo, the Mounted Unit of the New York City
Police Department and Brazilian rain forests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being part of the Johnson family, it behooves him to be
interested in health care,'' said Harvey Holzberg, president of
Robert Wood Johnson University Hospital in New Brunswick, N.J. ``He
was one of the people who interviewed me for this job, and
afterward, I never thought I'd see him again, but he calls me
regularly, with advice and suggestions.'' Johnson has underwritten
the hospital's nurse scholarship program for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   One of Johnson's three daughters, Casey, 20, has diabetes, and
his desire to raise money for a cure animates his work. ``When you
see what your daughter has to do to live, and when you see other
kids less well off losing eyesight, limbs or kidneys, you can't get
any more passionate,'' said Ross Cooley, head of the diabetes
foundation's finance committee.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``He's the best one-on-one fund-raiser I've ever seen.
He has contributed $12 million to the foundation, but you have to
double or triple it to see what he has done around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Johnson testified before Congress in favor of
research to clone pancreatic beta cells to provide a cure that
insulin cannot. The cloned cells ``would not be as susceptible to
attack by her immune system,'' he said of his daughter. ``Creating
these replacement beta cells for Casey would not require cloning a
new Casey, but they would give her a new lease on life.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Johnson, his daughter, and his wife, Sale, wrote a book
called ``Managing Your Child's Diabetes.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooley said he was not surprised to learn that the trim,
bespectacled Johnson, a sports fan and squash player, chose to bid
for the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes to his competitive nature,'' he added. ``His
management style is conducive to that; he can screen and select
leaders, which I think would wear well in that world.''
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, Johnson's net worth is enough to keep him in the
hunt. ``And he has access to a lot more money,'' Cooley added.
Johnson may choose to add a limited partner, like Stephen M. Ross,
a New York real estate developer.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, Johnson is a key Republican fund-raiser. He gave
$130,000 to the Republican Party between 1997 and 1998, held a
fund-raiser for New York Gov. George E. Pataki's 1998 re-election
campaign and gave $22,583 to Texas Gov. George W. Bush's
re-election campaign last year.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 52, who is one of Bush's top New York fund-raisers for
his presidential run, played a part in Team 100, a group of major
backers of former President George Bush, the governor's father.
</P>
<P>
   Besides a political passion shared by Johnson and Bush the
younger, Johnson would like to add sports ownership to his resume,
as it was for Bush when he owned a part of the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, buythejets.com, an on-line group that wants to buy
the team, is appealing its exclusion from the sale process by the
NFL. It is asking fan-investors to e-mail Eliot Spitzer, the New
York State attorney general, to demand an investigation of the
league's ``anticompetitive practices'' and an injunction against
the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Members of buythejets.com have met with Harry First, head of the
attorney general's antitrust division. But yesterday, a spokesman
for Spitzer said he did not know on what grounds the attorney
general's office could intervene.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
