<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4984 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NATIVITY-DRIVETHRU-AR     12-20 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIVITY-DRIVETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DRIVE-THROUGH LIVE NATIVITY SCENE THRIVES AT A CONNECTICUT
CHURCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By CLAUDIA ROWE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHINGTON, Conn. _ The first hint that something different was
going on at the Christian Tabernacle Church was the sight of two
camels, Bill and Eli, tied up in front, beside the main road of
this Hartford suburb. A few feet away, hundreds of minivans and
sport utility vehicles snaked through neighboring parking lots as
the families inside waited for a four-minute glimpse of the birth
of Jesus Christ, as seen through their car windows.
</P>
<P>
   This is among the latest, and oddest, wrinkles in
late-20th-century Christmas revelry: the drive-through, live-action
Nativity scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this country, and certainly in New England, we tend to be
very fast-food-oriented and this kind of meets people where they're
at,'' said John Muldoon, a church member dressed as a Roman
centurion. He held a walkie-talkie, continually muttering
directions to the shepherds milling about.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the crowd, Muldoon's assessment was on the mark.
About 275 cars came through on the first night, and 400 on the
second. With an average of four people per car, about 2,700 people
wheeled past the depiction of the birth of Christ over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Tabernacle's is only the newest drive-through Nativity
scene in Connecticut. At the United Methodist Church in nearby
Cheshire, the congregation has been holding live-action
drive-throughs for the last 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   The tradition is evidently taking hold around the country;
Cheshire got the idea when a how-to pamphlet detailing such
pageants arrived from the United Methodist headquarters in
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very popular,'' said Sue Dougherty, who helps sew
costumes at the Cheshire church. ``People even come from New York
and Massachusetts. It's pretty much a continual steam of cars.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nativity at Christian Tabernacle last weekend, featuring 23
live animals, began with a centurion handing motorists a Christmas
tape to play in their cars as they drove along. First stop: the
``back through time'' tunnel, with fog and eerie lighting, courtesy
of an old disco ball. Motorists entered the deep past through a
plastic car-wash curtain. The church was aiming for a ``creation of
the world'' feeling, ``kind of like going through the cosmos,''
said Muldoon, who masterminded this attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Once on the other side, visitors watched Mary and Joseph
knocking at the innkeeper's door as the tape sang of Jesus' birth
and Mary rubbed her belly and moaned. Donkeys brayed at the
minivans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone says: `Where did Christmas go? The spirit of
Christmas has been so watered down,'' said Jay Leroux, a church
member dressed as a centurion. ``People are really feeling this.''
</P>
<P>
   A few feet along, another Mary and Joseph couple rocked their
baby (a doll) in a manger next to a pen full of sheep. And just
beyond that, Ryan Maringola, a high school student, sat atop a
throne, playing King Herod. The king held court as two camels,
rented from a petting zoo in Goshen, tugged on their lead lines in
front of him. Motorists finished their tour by cruising past a
half-dozen carolers.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few first-timers' glitches, naturally; helpers
sometimes did not rewind the tapes properly and since so many cars
have built-in CD players, the centurions had to hustle portable
tape decks back to the front of the line as each family finished.
There was also the inescapable fact that it was sometimes quicker
to simply park and order your Big Mac, instead of waiting on line
at the drive-through. So, too, at the Nativity. The Tabernacle's
journey took only 4 minutes. The wait on line was closer to 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're bumping and grinding a bit with this being the first
year,'' Muldoon cheerfully admitted. ``But we kind of wanted to do
something a little more special than the rest of the cardboard
cutout nativities.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, anyone familiar with drive-through windows knows that
the real advantage is not speed or convenience, but privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that people are a lot more comfortable in their own
cars,'' Muldoon said. ``And they're a lot more likely to go to a
drive-through than a church service.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention that most people do not get to see live animals
in church. ``People really like their kids experiencing the
realness of it,'' said Michael Chevalier, a data processing manager
turned Roman centurion, who was stationed in front of Bill and Eli,
the camels. ``I didn't expect that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great!'' said 10-year-old Erica Lachat, bouncing up and
down in the back of her parents' minivan. The carolers had
impressed Erica. But her 7-year-old sister, Elizabeth, said she
would always remember the camels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
