<HEADLINE>
BARNES HAS NEW START WITH BRUINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAHUKU, Hawaii _ At approximately 4 p.m. Monday, UCLA forward
Matt Barnes gave up. He had waited three days for an English grade
that would lift his academic suspension and enable him to join the
Bruins this week for the three-game Pearl Harbor Classic. When it
wasn't posted by 4, Barnes packed his bags and headed to LAX for a
flight home, to Sacramento, for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   The grade arrived with Barnes somewhere on the 405. UCLA placed
a hold on his ticket, tracked him down at the Southwest terminal
and sent him to a Delta flight bound for Honolulu. He was scheduled
to arrive here late Monday night, and he'll be in uniform for the
first-round game today against Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proud of the effort he put forth in allowing himself to
be reinstated,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said. ``Hopefully, this
was a valuable lesson in terms of priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, a 6-foot-8 sophomore, failed a summer school class and
had to pass four classes in the fall quarter to meet NCAA progress
standards.
</P>
<P>
   His return bolsters a frontline depleted by JaRon Rush's
suspension. The Bruins (4-1) now have four experienced big men _
starters Dan Gadzuric and Jerome Moiso, reserve Sean Farnham and
Barnes _ for the most demanding week of their season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It couldn't have come at a better time, with three games in
three days,'' Lavin said. ``Matt's had a couple of pretty good
weeks of practice. I think the question for him will be less
conditioning and more about timing and the growing pains that come
with not playing in game situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavin's other challenge is to motivate the No.18 Bruins. The
Pearl Harbor Classic is not exactly loaded with marquee names:
Maine, Colorado State, San Jose State, Florida A&AMP;M, South Florida,
The Citadel and the host, BYU-Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   On reputation and talent, UCLA is heavily favored to return home
with a 7-1 pre-Christmas record.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Bruins never play well in these early-season
tournaments, even against teams they're supposed to overpower. They
lost to Santa Clara and Vanderbilt in the 1995 Maui Invitational.
They lost to Tulsa in the 1996 preseason NIT. They were humiliated
by North Carolina in the 1997 Great Alaska Shootout, and they lost
to Maryland and Kentucky last year in the Puerto Rico Shootout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be wary with every team,'' Farnham said. ``DePaul
was a big win for us, especially coming off that loss to Gonzaga.
We needed something to lift our spirits. Now, if we get on a roll,
we can go home 7-1. But we know from what's happened in the past
that we can't take anyone for granted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
