u f BC-TV-NEWS-VIDEOS-NYT &LR;      12-20 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEWS-VIDEOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 TV NEWS OPERATIONS UNITE TO PROVIDE VIDEO TO AFFILIATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The news operations of CBS, ABC and Fox agreed Monday
to form a cooperative service to supply video pictures of news
events to the affiliated stations of each network. NBC News was
expressly excluded.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time that the three news organizations, which
normally compete in news coverage, had formally united to create a
joint enterprise. The shared coverage, to be called Network News
Service, will mainly involve video from news scenes. Only rarely
will the coverage include any voices of reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The three news organizations emphasized that they would still
provide any exclusive or enterprise reporting to their affiliates
on an individual basis. And no affiliate will be able to use
coverage being provided by a competing station in that city.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose, said Andrew Heyward, the president of CBS News, is
to provide local stations with the best pictures of news events as
fast as possible, while ``freeing resources for unilateral
reporting.'' He added, ``This is not joint news gathering.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC News executives expressed some surprise about the
arrangement Monday, saying that joining the group had not been
discussed with them. ``We find it curious that we were not included
in these discussions,'' said Alexandra Constantinople, the
spokeswoman for NBC News, a unit of the General Electric Co.
</P>
<P>
   One possible goal of the combined coverage is to counter the
widespread use of video collected by the Cable News Network. Many
affiliates of the broadcast networks routinely use pictures from
CNN on their newscasts, always including an identifying logo of CNN
on the bottom right corner of the screen. As one senior network
news executive put it, ``We'd be happy to see a lot less of that
logo on our stations.''
</P>
<P>
   But CNN executives said they were confident that their
longstanding relationship with more than 600 local stations wouldd
continue.
</P>
<P>
   Neither CBS nor ABC, a unit of the Walt Disney Co., has an
all-news cable channel so they have a natural interest in making
this kind of cooperative arrangement. Fox does have an all-news
channel, but it competes directly with MSNBC, the one owned by NBC.
That possibly accounts for NBC's exclusion.
</P>
<P>
   As for NBC, Heyward said only, ``We did not approach them.''
</P>
<P>
   Heyward said the plan for the joint news service grew out of
regular conversations he was having with David Westin, the
president of ABC News, and Roger Ailes, the chairman of Fox News, a
unit of the News Corp. ``We have a relationship,'' Heyward said.
``We all know each other.'' He added that each network had
consulted with its lawyers to ensure there was no question of any
antitrust violation in such a cooperative arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   The news organizations have cooperated ad hoc in the past.
During the coverage of the crash of the plane owned by the golfer
Payne Stewart, for example, a crew from a CBS-affiliated station in
Des Moines reached the scene of the crash first, but its satellite
truck was not there. A truck from Fox soon arrived, however, and
the two organizations cooperated to send out the first pictures of
the crash.
</P>
<P>
   During the coverage of the funeral of John F. Kennedy Jr., ABC's
helicopter supplied pictures to CBS when that crew had to fly back
for refueling and CBS did the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 2323EST &QL; 
