<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4993 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-HORNETS-NY     12-20 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HORNETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREWELL AND CAMBY HELP KNICKS MEASURE UP TO HORNETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Knicks muddled through a schedule full of teams
searching for crawl space at the bottom of the league in the last
two weeks, and had no real read on how they measured up against the
league's elite teams.
</P>
<P>
   They discovered they were right with them after taking the
Eastern Conference's best team into overtime and defeating the
Charlotte Hornets, 112-109, in an intense, playoff-like game Monday
night at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   After Coach Jeff Van Gundy played a shell game with his
personnel _ even changing the starters _ to find the right match
against the versatile Hornets, it came down to a familiar
combination of aggression and energy: Latrell Sprewell and Marcus
Camby.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell scored 6 of the Knicks' first 8 points in overtime and
provided the pass to Camby for a dunk that put his team in position
to win. Camby not only left with a highlight on offense, but came
through with a key block on a Derrick Coleman shot with 37 seconds
left in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell finished with 30 points, Allan Houston added 31 and
Patrick Ewing came away with 18 rebounds. Finally, the rebounding
the Knicks had been waiting for arrived on cue as the Knicks ended
the Hornets' winning streak at eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Going into overtime could have been a letdown for the Knicks
considering how they had surged ahead in the fourth quarter. The
Knicks went on an 18-0 run early in the quarter and held a 10-point
lead with four minutes to play, but the Hornets came back and tie
the score with 12.2 seconds left when Eddie Jones hit two free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had a chance to win the game in regulation, but
Houston missed a jumper over Anthony Mason with three seconds left
and Ewing missed a putback jumper at the buzzer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy has sarcastically called the Houston-Sprewell
backcourt _ a tandem so popular with fans _ the ``panacea'' for the
Knicks. Monday night, he stopped mocking the notion and benched
Charlie Ward to start the game with a big lineup against a
streaking Hornets team that travels on a bulk rate.
</P>
<P>
   In ending Ward's regular-season streak of 157 games as a
starter, Van Gundy wanted size on size and started a front court of
Larry Johnson, Camby and Ewing against Mason, Coleman and Elden
Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the move only led the Knicks into a
first-quarter calamity.
</P>
<P>
   Out of sync and disorganized, the Knicks started 1 for 17 from
the field and quickly fell behind, 17-5. Once Ward was inserted
into the game late in the first quarter, some balance was restored
and the Knicks were able to pull to 51-46 at the half. The score
was only that close because Ward hit a long 3-pointer at the buzzer
and the Knicks were outrebounding an opponent for only the second
time in six games.
</P>
<P>
   Once in the locker room, the Knicks regrouped and Van Gundy
tried the big lineup again to start the second half. And this time,
there was some success.
</P>
<P>
   Much more focused and aggressive, the Knicks used a 3-pointer by
Johnson as part of a 7-2 run to tie the score early in the third.
After a steal by Johnson that led to a layup by Sprewell, the
Knicks took the lead for the first time in the game three minutes
into the second half.
</P>
<P>
   From there, it was a furious back-and-forth in a third quarter
that contained 12 lead changes and a handful of high-energy plays
by Sprewell, who took off after a steal for a one-handed dunk that
pumped up the decibel level of the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets remained calm amid the Knicks' rush and combated
every highlight play with some assertive moves that put them at the
free-throw line 12 times in the quarter. After a free throw by
Mason with 2.6 seconds left, the Hornets held a 74-73 lead entering
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   At least the Knicks were close. Before Ward came into the game
in the first quarter, there was nothing but misery for the Knicks,
particularly for a slow-footed, languid Ewing. He missed his first
six shots and allowed Campbell to slip by him on a succession of
layups.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing was also the unwitting culprit to a Camby injury. After
missing a putback and slipping down, Ewing was in the way of a
backpedaling Camby. The spindly forward tripped over Ewing and
sprained his left wrist on the hard landing with 9:51 left in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, nothing was going right for the Knicks. Mason was
bludgeoning Johnson in the post and the Knicks were missing
everything on the offensive end. With 4:35 left in the first
quarter, Ward replaced Houston. With Ward on the bench, the Knicks
were a minus-10. With Ward on the court, they were a plus-5.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as he entered, a sense of calm was restored. Although
the Hornets kept beating the Knicks down court on fast-break
attempts and threatened to blow the game open, it was Ward who kept
pulling the Knicks back. He hit a 3-pointer with four minutes left
in the half to put the Knicks within 2, 38-36. On the Hornets' next
possession, an energized Sprewell swiped the ball and drove for a
fast-break layup to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets, boosted by a 3-pointer by David Wesley, took a
45-40 lead with two minutes left. Ward helped close that gap at the
end of the half with a 3-pointer from 46 feet against one of the
elite teams in the East. The Hornets came in on an eight-game
winning streak and the high of having embarrassed the Miami Heat
over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what you try to do is you try to play every game hard
because they all count the same toward getting to the playoffs,''
Van Gundy said before the game. ``When you do play good teams, you
do have a sense of what you need to work on to improve.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-20-99 2330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991220.0412 </DOCNO>
