<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-20 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5009 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-BOMB-AZR &LR;      12-20 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMB-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLOSIVES THEFT PROBE FOCUSES ON CREW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 and KERRY FEHR-SNYDER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF _ State and federal investigators are focusing on the
12-man crew of a remote flagstone quarry where a half-ton of
explosives were stolen last week.
</P>
<P>
   Although no conclusions can be drawn yet, authorities say
mounting evidence suggest that the theft of 750 pounds of
fuel-soaked ammonium nitrate, 250 pounds of dynamite, blasting caps
and detonator cord was an inside job.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, investigators want to know why the theft went
unreported until 9:30 a.m. Thursday, more than 36 hours after the
materials were taken from two 4-by-5-foot steel-plated magazines at
the 3 Wins Mining Co. quarry near Drake, about 20 miles southwest
of Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   State mining officials, meanwhile, say similar explosives are
stored at scores of mines around Arizona, and they're often
unguarded in isolated areas.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, neither the state mine inspector nor the federal Bureau
of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms knows the quantity and type of
explosives stored by the 87 Arizona mines that use them.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday afternoon, Coconino County Sheriff Joe Richards showed
reporters photos of the magazines, neither of which had signs of
obvious damage. That weakens or eliminates one working theory of
mine experts: that thieves used acetylene cutting torches.
</P>
<P>
   Each magazine has two locks inside deep cylinders in the doors.
Owners of other flagstone operations in the area say that keys
generally are given to the top two or three company officials in
each operation.
</P>
<P>
   Richards refused to comment on whether keys had opened the
locks.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for the company that supplied explosives to the
3 Wins quarry said the locks were cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is quite unusual for someone to go in and tip over
magazines and snip the locks and take everything that was in
there,'' said Jay Anderson of Dyno Nobel Americas in Salt Lake
City.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff said deputies found tracks of a vehicle believed to
have been used in the theft. The tracks were about a mile from the
magazines and went around a locked gate at the entrance to the
quarry.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities are offering a reward of up to $10,000 for
information to help crack the case. Richards said the investigation
includes 25 officers from sheriff's departments in Coconino,
Yavapai and Mohave counties, along with ATF agents.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have fanned out to Chino Valley, Paulden, Ash Fork
and surrounding areas, circulating fliers with reward information
in both English and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Richards said officers had received a number of tips that
militia members living in the Paulden and Chino Valley areas could
have been involved in the theft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the militia cells are there, but we have nothing
substantive to suggest that they were involved in this,'' Richards
said. ``We certainly don't want to cause any panic by leading
anyone to believe that organized militias have anything to do with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   State mining officials say they aren't sure how much explosives
are stored around the state, but they know there's plenty of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very common products that they're using for earth
removal with rock,'' said Phil Howard, the state's assistant mine
inspector.
</P>
<P>
   Although mines must pass yearly safety inspections, smaller
operations are more likely than big players to be vulnerable to
theft.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of mining, that's a small amount,'' Howard said of
the amount stolen last week. ``But in terms of what it can do,
that's a lot of damage.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, such materials are good for only one thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any other use for it than to use it as
an explosive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got us all on pins and needles. We don't know if people
know how to use this energy right, and that's very worrisome.''
</P>
<P>
   About 350 mines are active in Arizona, and 87 of them use
explosives. But Howard said it's unclear how many of those store
explosives on site or how many of them employ guards to thwart
would-be thieves.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal laws require that explosives be stored in
padlocked metal magazines that are resistant to weather erosion,
fire, bullets and theft.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, a state mine inspector cited 3 Wins for four
violations. The citation, which did not carry a fine, included two
safety infractions dealing with the explosives magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The violations were quickly corrected and the quarry has not
been cited since.
</P>
<P>
   Howard agreed that the theft seems like an inside job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody knew it was out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be crazy to steal that stuff because you do not
want the ATF after you, I guarantee that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was some good ol' boys that wanted to make a big blowup
for New Year's, man, they're going to be behind bars by the time
this thing is through.''
</P>
<P>
   Mine operators are responsible for maintaining an inventory of
their explosives, with permits to store them coming from the state
mine inspector.
</P>
<P>
   The federal ATF issues licenses to detonate the explosives. The
ATF on Monday could not provide a list of mines that store
explosives on site or the quantity they keep on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Although explosives suppliers generally run background checks on
customers who buy their explosives, Arizona is more lax about mine
operations than other states. For example, no state agency is
responsible for licensing blasters, and all that's required to buy
explosives is a driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   California, by contrast, oversees blasters through its state
worker safety agency. Those who detonate explosives must have three
years of experience, 20 to 40 hours of training and pass both
written and oral tests.
</P>
<P>
   Howard, of the state Mine Inspectors Office, said he and others
pushed for similar requirements in Arizona during the past
legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never even made it to committee,'' he said, adding, that
critics ``tended to say we were just bureaucrats generating more
work for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the recent theft, Howard said his office plans to lobby
for tighter rules again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like this may be the opportunity,'' he said. &QL; 
Mark Shaffer can be reached at &QL; 
mark.shaffer(at)arizonarepublic.com &QL; 
or at (602) 444-8057. &QL; 
Kerry Fehr-Snyder can be reached at &QL; 
kerry.fehr-snyder(at)arizonarepublic.com or at (602) 444-8975. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
